<HEADLINE>
ERSTAD WILL HIT LEADOFF, PERIOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. _ Darin Erstad has spent his career bouncing
around in the lineup, hitting leadoff one night, third the next,
fifth or sixth the next. But manager Mike Scioscia made it clear
from the beginning of camp that Erstad, despite his struggles last
season, would be his leadoff hitter in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad has been viewed as a No.3-type hitter in the past, but he
looks more like a leadoff hitter now, bunting and stealing bases.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's 6-2 loss to the Colorado Rockies, Erstad had two
hits, including a bunt single, and a stolen base. His four steals
this spring lead the team. He's hitting .400 (26 for 65) and his
on-base percentage is .414.
</P>
<P>
   ``It benefits me as a player all-around to be able to do those
things,'' Erstad said. ``It widens the range of what I can do.
During times you're not swinging the bat well, you need to find
ways to get on base.''
</P>
<P>
   ORTIZ IMPRESSIVE: Ramon Ortiz threw three scoreless innings _
allowing only one hit _ in a minor-league game at Mesa. Pitching
for Triple-A Edmonton against Tacoma, Ortiz struck out four, did
not walk a batter and was clocked between 90-94 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz made 30 pitches in the game, then pitched more in the
bullpen afterward. Diagnosed with a small tear in the tissue of his
right shoulder two weeks ago, Ortiz will pitch Saturday in Mesa in
another minor-league game and go four or five innings. Then on
April 6, he'll pitch the season opener for the Single-A Lake
Elsinore Storm, which will put him on schedule to make his season
debut April 11 in Anaheim. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
