</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MICHIGANST-FLINT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHIGAN STATE TRIO THE PRIDE OF FLINT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLINT, Mich. _ In the foreground of the barren Buick plant in
this town that prosperity forgot, weeds cover asphalt basketball
courts like cobwebs and the bare rims rise like wraiths. To stare
at the starkness is to get no sense of the assembly-line efficiency
with which Flint has been cranking out sleek, high-powered,
reliable basketball players.
</P>
<P>
   Hope abandoned the auto factory years ago, but it didn't go far,
taking up residence at Berston Fieldhouse just a couple blocks over
and a few miles up the road. It is there, inside a Chuck Taylor
shoebox of a gym, that Glen Rice honed his basketball skills. And
Mateen Cleaves, Morris Peterson and Charlie Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves, Peterson and Bell are known around the Michigan State
campus as The Flintstones because this is their home. It is by no
means a fashionable place to be from any more, not since General
Motors moved out and despair swooped in to fill the yawning void.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vehicle City'' is known more for crime than chrome these days.
Last month the city was back leading the national news, not for any
cutting edge feat of industry and engineering but because one of
its first graders cut short a classmate's life with the blast of a
handgun.
</P>
<P>
   The city of 132,000 is routinely dismissed by outsiders as so
dangerous and downtrodden as to be unlivable. The John Rockers of
this world probably would place it a notch below Beirut.
</P>
<P>
   And yet the Spartans from Flint wear their roots proudly, on
their sleeveless arms and strong shoulders but mostly on their blue
collars.
</P>
<P>
   This past Saturday, with time winding down in the NCAA
Tournament Midwest Regional Final at Auburn Hills, The Flintstones
formed the bedrock of Michigan State's 75-64 win over Iowa State.
</P>
<P>
   With a little over two minutes to play, Cleaves lobbed the
basketball to Peterson for a rim-and-roof-rattling dunk that gave
the No.1-seeded Spartans the first bit of breathing room they had
enjoyed all night against the Cyclones.
</P>
<P>
   The alley-oop jam was the silver hood ornament in a 12-0 run
engineered by Cleaves, Peterson and Bell. A run that effectively
delivered Michigan State, which had trailed by as many as eight
points in the second half, to the Final Four this week in
Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   The city that spawned the United Autoworkers' Union could
appreciate more than most the Spartans' comeback under Cleaves'
foremanship. Because in Michigan State's toughness and camaraderie
and unselfishness in its second half against Iowa State the people
of Flint saw themselves.
</P>
<P>
   You can take the boys out of Flint but you can't take Flint out
of the boys. That's what the The Flintstones' tattoos suggest,
that's what people here say and that's why this city is deriving no
small satisfaction from seeing Michigan State take its place among
college basketball's elite just as Flint once did among the world's
automakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of Flint has become their village because they are a
team,'' said Cleaves' mother, Frances, referring to Michigan State.
``There's no big I's or little U's on this team. We learned that
from being union people.''
</P>
<P>
   Frances Cleaves worked for General Motors for 22 years before
retiring in 1998, as the company was embarking on the final phase
of its massive downsizing.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to be a doddering town elder to remember a day
when General Motors utilized a transition break with shimmering
success. The automaker ran workers in and out of its plants here in
waves so there was never a lull in production.
</P>
<P>
   Such was the demand for bodies, both parents were likely to be
working, more likely than not a swing shift and quite possibly
alongside cousins and aunts and uncles. So early on, year-round
community sports programs became another link in the chain, their
formation driven by the need to occupy the children whose guardians
were otherwise engaged making cars.
</P>
<P>
   Berston Fieldhouse is a clean and compact case in point. A
historical marker planted just outside the entrance proclaims that
the recreation center was opened in 1923 and was the first of its
kind in the city to admit African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   There was talk recently of tearing down the building, which also
houses an auditorium and a swimming pool. But the community rushed
to the rescue of a place that has saved an awful lot of kids over
the years.
</P>
<P>
   On a morning last weekend, the gym stood empty. A worn leather
basketball sat on one baseline, waiting patiently for a pick-up
game. A kind of hush had settled over the room, the quiet broken
only by the strains of laughter and music wafting from a children's
dance class taking place across the hall.
</P>
<P>
   During the summers the gym is a hub for hoops. Everybody from
Flint who is anybody in basketball has at one time graced its court
(just as many now grace the center's picture-lined walls).
</P>
<P>
   Kids can learn the fundamentals and play in organized leagues,
starting in grade school. The Lakers' Rice was a scrawny seventh
grader when his raw skills came to the attention of longtime
Northwestern High coach Grover Kirkland.
</P>
<P>
   As a high school senior, Rice averaged 28 points despite playing
little more than a half most nights for a Northwestern team that
went 28-0 and beat all its opponents save one by at least 30
points. The point guard who fed Rice was Andre Rison, the All-Pro
NFL receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Pendelton, who would go on to play at USC, was a junior
on that unbeaten team. Other prominent Northwestern products
include Jeff Grayer, who played at Iowa State and in the NBA for
nine years, and Desmon Farmer, who will attend USC this fall. Then
there's Kelvin Torbert, a junior, who is going to make some college
coach a very happy man in the fall of 2001 (unless he decides to
jump straight to the NBA).
</P>
<P>
   The kids who take part in the city programs are drilled in
everything from how to make a bounce pass in the lane to how to
make a passing grade in school. Coaches go one-on-one with the
players in the classrooms, trying to impress upon them from an
early age the need for good habits on and off the court.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, some of Flint's finest players fall through cracks as
ugly as the ones sprouting weeds on the courts in front of the
abandoned Buick plant. Kirkland, in an interview the other day on
the Northwestern High campus, recalled a kid who was Cleaves' equal
on the court but who couldn't get through high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of kids like that,'' Kirkland said. ``It's an
ongoing battle.''
</P>
<P>
   The ones, like Cleaves, who make it tend to be tougher for
having survived. Their resolve is reinforced on the playgrounds, in
the downtown YMCA, at Berston; wherever players gather to see who
gets next.
</P>
<P>
   The coaches are constantly on their kids to defend their turf.
``We're really tough on them,'' said Kirkland. He will admonish his
players not to let the wino with the sweet jumper make a few shots
off them, explaining, ``Then he'll come back and bring along his
buddies and suddenly you'll have lost the court to a leader going
the wrong direction.''
</P>
<P>
   He lectures them to surround themselves with positive
influences, to steer clear of good friends with bad intentions.
Kirkland's day is made whenever he hears of kids picking their ball
up and going home when troublemakers come looking for a game and
possibly a lot more.
</P>
<P>
   For a city that has been slowly bleeding to death, the success
of Cleaves, Peterson and Bell at Michigan State on the court and in
the classroom has been as good as a tourniquet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're losing a lot of our industry and all the other things
that come along with losing jobs,'' Frances Cleaves said. ``The
Flintstones send to Flint the message that we have a respectable
place in the United States of America.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
