<SLUG> BC-LA-OVERTAX-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. OWES TAXPAYERS MILLIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Mayor Richard Riordan announced Monday that the
city overcharged taxpayers as much as $17 million for a 1988 bond
issue and must pay back the money _ an unprecedented step that
escalated his struggle over power and policy with the City Council.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan cited the goof in stepping up pressure to make the
Finance Department created by the new voter-approved City Charter
responsible for virtually all money matters.
</P>
<P>
   But shortly after Riordan announced how various agencies with
divided responsibility had fouled up the bond issue charges, the
City Council panel implementing the new charter rejected his
proposal to consolidate revenue projections, debt management and
related matters in the Finance Department.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the threat of a mayoral veto, the council's Ad Hoc
Committee on Charter Implementation recommended that the City
Administrative Office retain that authority and report to both the
mayor and the City Council when the new charter takes effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue here is one of providing information,'' Councilwoman
Jackie Goldberg said. ``And I have no confidence that this mayor or
any mayor would share information with the council.''
</P>
<P>
   Council members Laura Chick and Mike Feuer, both seeking
citywide office, supported keeping financial management in various
departments for now but said they would consider changes after the
new charter takes effect in July.
</P>
<P>
   About all the mayor and the council members could agree on was
that property owners had been overcharged by $12 million to $18
million for the $65 million bond issue and that refunds _ which
officials called an unprecedented act _ would need to be made to
taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   While the final figures will be determined through an
independent audit, officials estimated residents will get a $12 to
$18 credit on their property tax bills.
</P>
<P>
   The bond issue was for fire and paramedic services and was paid
off last September.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan and City Controller Rick Tuttle said the mistake _ in
which the amount needed to cover the cost of the bond's repayment
was miscalculated _ demonstrated the need for a strong Finance
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan initially blamed the City Administrative Office for the
foul-up, but later broadened that to include a number of city
agencies, which he said should have discovered the mistake earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the problem with the current system,'' Riordan said at
a news conference. ``There is no accountability. That's why we need
a new system. Something like this is intolerable and we have to get
away from the status quo.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuttle said keeping the current system will go against voters'
wishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the committee keeps the status quo, it will eviscerate all
the efforts that are being made to strengthen our ability to
efficiently pursue financial functions,'' Tuttle said.
</P>
<P>
   However, City Administrative Officer Bill Fujioka differed with
Riordan and Tuttle and said it was his office that discovered the
mistake and initially proposed the taxpayer refund.
</P>
<P>
   ``We identified this problem in late December and we brought it
to the attention of the Mayor's Office,'' Fujioka said. ``We also
went to the City Attorney's Office, who advised us we had to refund
the money. We went back to the Mayor's Office and they wanted us to
look at ways to keep the money and use it to balance the budget.''
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Mayor Kelly Martin disputed Fujioka's account.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did ask if we could use the money, but we only got the
legal opinion last Friday telling us we needed to refund it,''
Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We only recently learned about all this. Last year, the CAO
was telling us we had this money we could use for the budget. Now,
they say we have to return it. This whole debate goes to the issue
of the quality of information we are getting.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin said Riordan wants the authority over revenue projections
and debt management to make the city more efficient and place
accountability over the decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Los Angeles is one of the most expensively run cities and one
of the least efficient,'' Martin said. ``That was part of the
reason for charter reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Riordan and Fujioka have been at odds for several months, with
Riordan asking him to step down from the job. Since then, Fujioka
has shown a strong independent streak, clashing frequently with the
Mayor's Office on policy issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
