 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
 (sw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For TUESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Tuesday, March 28.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GUYANA-HAMMOCK-WEAVERS (Lethem, Guyana) _ This village in the
remote southern savannah could easily be taken for one of those
places untouched by the digital revolution. But it was here that an
organization formed by indigenous women of two tribes revived the
ancient art of hand-weaving large hammocks from locally grown
cotton _ and then took their exquisite wares online. They hired a
young member to create a Web site. And last year, they sold 17
hammocks to people around the world for as much as $1,000 apiece.
But threatened by the women's success, regional leaders moved in
and took control of the weavers' organization. The woman who
created the Web site quit in a fury, and the group has been
struggling since then to get by. By Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   MONTENEGRO (Podgorica, Yugoslavia) _ A situationer, including an
interview with Montenegro's president, on the junior partner in the
Yugoslav federation, which is increasingly under pressure from
Serbia. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ISHIHARA (Tokyo) _ If any politician was ever going to try
to break the central government's hold over almost every aspect of
Japanese life, it seemed most likely to be the ever-crusading
shoot-from-the-lip governor of Tokyo, Shintaro Ishihara. By Howard
French.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-FOSTER-CARE (New York) _ Thousands of young adults in New
York City's foster care system, many of whom were neglected or
abandoned during the height of the city's crack epidemic a decade
ago, have been ``aging out'' of the system in recent years, left at
age 18 to fend for themselves, often with little in the way of
education or financial resources. By Somini Sengupta.
</P>
<P>
   DISABLED-FARMERS (Ackley, Iowa) _ Rising before dawn for Sunday
chores, Darwin Hoffmeister fed the pigs, checked the cows and
mended a trampled fence. But he could not tie his shoes.
Hoffmeister, a 50-year-old Iowa farmer, lost four fingers and the
use of his left arm in a combine accident five years ago, the kind
of dreadful mishap that makes farming one of the nation's most
dangerous professions. He is one of thousands of farmers in America
with disabilities who have triumphed over physical adversities, a
survival made possible by technological advances and the changed
nature of farming, which today relies more on brain power and
computer skills than mere brute strength. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT23,24) have been sent to NYT photo
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GORE-REACT (Washington) _ Political donors and fund-raisers
approached Vice President Al Gore's latest campaign finance
proposal warily, concerned that it would diminish their influence
with candidates and create an unwieldy new government bureaucracy.
By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   NJ-SENATE-CAMPAIGN (Trenton, N.J.) _ With much of New Jersey
awash in prosperity, running against the boom seems like an odd
strategy. But in New Jersey's U.S. Senate contest, unusual
circumstances have transformed the Democratic primary into a race
that has put the economic boom on trial. Jon Corzine, the former
co-chairman of Goldman Sachs, has said that his work on Wall Street
helped New Jersey companies create hundreds of thousands of jobs.
Those arguments have prompted his opponent, former Gov. Jim Florio,
to warn voters that a dark cloud has been obscured by the economic
silver lining, and Florio has hammered his opponent with the kind
of class-based attacks Democrats usually aim at Republicans. By
David Kocieniewski.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HOUSING-SHORTAGE _ Sometimes it seems that the nation has all
the money in the world, but the poor are finding it harder and
harder to rent affordable housing. By Irvin Molotsky.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BIOTECH-PATENT (Boston) _ A legal showdown began here Monday
that could determine whether some of the biotechnology industry's
most lucrative drugs will be vulnerable to lower-priced
competition. On one side is Transkaryotic Therapies Inc., a tiny
company with technology that could allow it to circumvent patents
on drugs produced by genetic engineering. In partnership with
Aventis, the big European drug company, it wants to sell its own
version of Amgen Inc.'s Epogen, the biotechnology industry's
biggest drug with worldwide sales of about $4 billion. Amgen has
filed a patent infringement lawsuit aiming to protect its product.
By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphics have been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   OIL-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ As the oil ministers met in Vienna,
Austria, there was great concern about whether OPEC would give the
rest of the world a break and do something to restrain soaring oil
prices. So it was nearly 20 years ago, when OPEC met in the fall of
1980. But there are important differences between then and now. By
Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   LEESON-AD-COLUMN (London) _ Nicholas Leeson, the rogue stock
trader who caused the collapse of Britain's oldest merchant bank,
Barings PLC, is appearing in a campaign that promotes a Swedish
dot-com stock trading company. It may sound bizarre, but the
commercial's creators said bizarre was very much the point.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WEST-THEATER (New York) _ The two leads of Sam Shepard's ``True
West'' on their alternating roles. By Robin Pogrebin.
</P>
<P>
   TV-OSCARS (Undated) _ A critic's notebook on the Oscar telecast.
By Caryn James.
</P>
<P>
   TITO-OPERA-REVIEW (New York) _ ``La Clemenza di Tito,'' the
opera Mozart wrote for a coronation in Prague a few months before
he died, was long undervalued but now seems absolutely immediate.
Not only is it filled with great and glorious music _ strongly
presented in this New York City Opera production _ but it speaks to
concerns that are ours. Reviewed by Paul Griffiths.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-POET-FRANCE (Les Maquignons, France) _ With the publication
of his third novel, ``The Fly-Truffler,'' wider recognition has
suddenly come to Gustaf Sobin, a poet and novelist who left Boston
for France 40 years ago. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   BOHEMIAN-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ In ``Weird Like Us: My Bohemian
America,'' Ann Powers argues that bohemianism is not only alive and
well, it is thriving, and whatever inroads it makes into the
mainstream only provide evidence of its power and vibrancy.
Reviewed by Jenny Lyn Bader
</P>
<P>
   TV-GOODTIMES-REVIEW (Undated) _ On PBS, A Moyers Report:
``Surviving the Good Times.'' Reviewed by Walter Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COLLINS-COLUMN (Undated) _ Gail Collins looks at the vice
presidential prospects.
</P>
<P>
   FRIEDMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Thomas L. Friedman examines union
opposition to a bill in Congress aimed at aiding African economies.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBO-BASEBALL-ABROAD (Undated) _ As baseball prepares to open its
season for the first time outside North America, its international
aspirations begin to come clear: a desire to increase its
visibility worldwide, enhance marketing and retailing opportunities
and lure talent to the U.S. But there won't be any Asian franchises
anytime soon. By Murray Chass.
</P>
<P>
   BKC-NCCA-FINALFOUR (Undated) _ The Final Four of the men's
basketball tournament features on favorite and three unexpected
teams that have lent an atmosphere of freshness, and unfamiliarity,
to the final weekend. By Joe Lapointe.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE TIMES (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HEISENBERG-BOMB (New York) _ Physicists and historians
gathered in Manhattan today to discuss the issues raised by Michael
Frayn's play, Copenhagen, which deals with the relationship between
quantum theorists Niels Bohr and Werner Heisenberg and the German
atomic bomb project. By James Glanz.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AURORA (Undated) _ Shimmering waves of color and brilliance
may soon be visible around the globe as the Sun approaches the peak
of its 11-year cycle of storms, sunspots and flares. The resulting
heavy rain of particles, interacting with Earth's magnetic field,
will light up the skies with heavenly fire known in the Northern
Hemisphere as the aurora borealis. The solar disturbances produce
auroras in places where most people never expect to see them. By
William J. Broad.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphics have been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HOPKINS-GENES (Undated) _ Dr. Nancy Hopkins, the MIT
professor who convinced her bosses that sex discrimination was
rampant on campus, now is making her mark in genetics. In her lab
she has developed a technique that uses retroviruses to induce
mutations of single genes in zebra fish. The technique allows for
quick isolation and cloning of the mutated genes and could
ultimately help define a kind of ``construction kit'' of the genes
necessary to make, say, a heart, or a brain, or a whole baby fish.
By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CORAL-REEFS (Undated) _ The federal government has issued a
long-term plan to save coral reefs along the coast of the United
States and its territories, setting aside many sites as ecological
preserves over the next 10 years. The plan calls for 20 percent of
all coral reefs in American-controlled waters to be designated
ecological preserves by 2010, protecting them from pollution,
fishing and other activity that could harm the reefs. By John
Files. (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GAMMA-RAYS (Undated) _ Even as NASA bureaucrats were
ordering up its demise, the Compton Gamma Ray Observatory
discovered a new class of mysterious sources of celestial gamma
rays scattered along the Milky Way. Bu John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BLACK-HOLES (Undated) _ Astronomers at Ohio State University
have photographed feeding frenzies at the hearts of a score of
galaxies, images of gas and dust draining into what may be black
holes like water spiraling down a bathtub drain.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NANOTUBES (Undated) _ A research team at Rensselaer
Polytechnic Institute has created tiny ``trees'' using flashes of
extreme heat to deposit carbon atoms in piles on a graphite
surface. The structures average about one one-hundredth of an inch
in height and can be as narrow as five- millionths of an inch in
diameter. By Henry Fountain.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MOAS-EXTINCTION (Undated) _ An entire class of large
flightless birds called moas, 11 species and an estimated 160,000
individuals in all, lived in New Zealand until the 13th or 14th
century when Polynesians colonized the island and began what
biologists call a blitzkrieg. New evidence now suggests that it may
have been the most rapid extinction ever brought about by primitive
people. The bird probably was so naive that that is just allowed
hunters to walk up and kill it. By William K. Stevens. (1325 words)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ News and notes on science: Items on the
vibrations of earth, toxins in puffer fish and Lake Vostok's water
movements. By Henry Fountain.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CHILDREN-GRIEVE (Undated) _ A new book based on findings of
a large-scale study by researchers at Memorial Sloan Kettering
Cancer Center of families coping with the illness and death of a
parent, offers new understanding of children's ability to come to
terms with loss. In ``Healing Children's Grief: Surviving a
Parent's Death From Cancer'' (Oxford; 2000), Dr. Grace Hyslop
Christ makes it clear that children, even very young children, do
grieve, though their grieving differs at different ages, and often
bears little resemblance to the mourning reactions of adults. By
Erica Goode. (1850 words)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DIABETES-DRUG (Undated) _ Patients react to FDA's pulling of
rezulin off market. For some, the drug has helped tremendously, and
the news took them by surprise. But others died from it, their
families said. By Holcomb B. Noble.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ Personal Health: An important
documentary ``Cancer: Evolution to Revolution'' to be shown
Thursday offers extraordinary segments of people living and dying
with the disease, and they share hopes, goals and expectations. By
Jane E. Brody.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DINING-TOGETHER (Undated) _ A large Harvard study shows that
children who eat with their parents frequently may have healthier
eating habits than those who rarely do. By Randi Hutter Epstein.
(825 words)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PARALYSIS-CHIP (Undated) _ An electronic microchip implanted
in the back of a 38-year-old paralyzed man is enabling him to move
his legs for the first time in 10 years. By Holcomb B. Noble. (250
words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ A science question answered: Why don't you
sneeze when you are asleep? By C. Claiborne Ray.
