u s BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      03-28 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRACTICE-FLOOR FIGHT PUTS FLOODLIGHT ON SONICS LACK OF LEADERSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ What happened at Sonics practice Sunday was not, in
terms of team-building morale, Wally Walker's worst nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   But that could have been only because just before bed the team
president ate a lot of pizza slathered with jalapenos and
anchovies.
</P>
<P>
   When a sagging team's volatile superstar and a volatile reserve
get into such a locker-room fracas that the starting center is
injured breaking it up, it is time to search out a new job or a new
team. Especially if everyone was pulling for the volatile reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Walker, besides the WNBA entry, there is no
new team in town. And so far, Walker has evinced no desire for a
new job.
</P>
<P>
   That means the only alternative for him and the Sonics is to sit
helplessly for the next five weeks until the Lakers put them out of
their misery in the playoffs' first round.
</P>
<P>
   Which will provide the answer to an unusual question:
</P>
<P>
   How many implosions can one sports market stand?
</P>
<P>
   Oh, I suppose the Sonics have another option: Let Payton lead
the team out of the mess.
</P>
<P>
   Good luck.
</P>
<P>
   Payton had an opportunity to lead his team Sunday. Instead, he
let a fairly common practice-court trash-talk session with Maxwell
unravel into a locker-room melee.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a shoulder injury to Horace Grant, which
contributed to a loss to San Antonio Monday night _ the Sonics'
fourth in a row _ which contributed to the steep plunge down the
playoff ladder, as well as to an impression that the Sonics are in
chaos because maybe only Maxwell (who earned well his nickname Mad
Max) in the entire organization has the guts to stand up to Payton.
</P>
<P>
   Although team sources said Walker fined Payton and Maxwell,
Walker reiterated Monday night that he never discloses fines. But
he did indirectly acknowledge that the fight, regardless of its
origins and responsibility, was and is a potentially dangerous
moment because of its long-term impact on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't have teammates watching out of the corner of their
eyes to see if everything's OK,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the immediacy of Grant's injury, the loss of trust in
the team's leader is the primary casualty of the latest episode.
His teammates don't know when Payton is going to go off, the
identity of the target, or whether to ignore or take on the
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   The lame excuse, ``That's just Gary being Gary,'' no longer cuts
it.
</P>
<P>
   Walker and coach Paul Westphal had a chance to lay down some law
by suspending both players for a game for conduct detrimental.
Grant's injury, and his noble if misguided attempts to hide the
truth from many in the media Monday night, was the physical proof
that matters were so far out of hand that serious action is
required.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how Payton and his defenders spin it, and no matter
the degree of Maxwell's provocation, Payton has to know the line
between his ego and the team's best interests.
</P>
<P>
   A real leader averts foolishness. A real leader leaves the
argument on the court. A real leader breaks up the fight.
</P>
<P>
   Payton did none of that.
</P>
<P>
   Chronicling Payton's mercurial moods has been a sports section
staple for much of his decade in Seattle. So has chronicling his
superb skills and toughness that make him one of the game's elite.
The conventional wisdom has been that a lot of superstars are the
same way, and anyway, the good Gary always outweighed the bad Gary.
</P>
<P>
   This season is different.
</P>
<P>
   The team was built around and for good Gary and took his input
that, ``We need more ghetto.'' It was Payton who advocated for
Maxwell. Walker even filled a roster spot with a veteran, Chuck
Person, whose primary job was to help Payton develop a little touch
on his emotional throttle.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, Payton had to be more than he had been. He had to
not only take charge, but be supportive of teammates and coaches.
No longer could he defer the job to older players such as Nate
McMillan, Sam Perkins, Detlef Schrempf or even Shawn Kemp.
</P>
<P>
   The good Gary had to be so much more prominent than the bad Gary
that it would be a mismatch.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, there were positive signs. But these days, the
Sonics are in a death spiral. They have fallen to the eighth and
final playoff spot and are 13-17 since the seasonal high point, a
27-13 record on Jan. 20. They have not beaten a club with a winning
record since Charlotte Feb. 28, a game the outplayed Sonics
admitted was a mystery as to how they won.
</P>
<P>
   Now is when Payton's leadership is needed most. Instead, he
abdicated.
</P>
<P>
   If Payton will not lead, Walker and Westphal had the chance to
show that they will lead by finally taking the risk of challenging
their star with a one-game suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Really, what is the risk? That Payton will be mad? He is
already.
</P>
<P>
   That they will play worse? Not likely.
</P>
<P>
   That they will lose his energy and spirit? As if they were going
to beat the Lakers in a first-round match up with him anyway.
</P>
<P>
   It's a hard question for any sports franchise: How to punish a
star without blunting the edginess that made him great.
</P>
<P>
   But at this point for this team, they had little to lose.
Excusing and coddling Payton's excesses only embarrasses the
franchise and creates resentments in the other players.
</P>
<P>
   A comeback from a suspension also would have given Payton, at
31, an opportunity to show that he is a bigger player than his
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
