r a BC-OSCAR-TV-LADN     03-28 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCAR-TV-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OSCAR SHOW TOO LONG? BLAME THE STAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDITORS: Television critic David Kronke contributed to this
story.) 
By VALERIE KUKLENSKI 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Maybe Sunday's record-long Academy Awards show
would have been shorter had winners taken a cue from last year's
Best Actor winner Roberto Benigni and climbed over seats to get to
stage.
</P>
<P>
   The cavernous Shrine Auditorium stage was blamed as one of the
reasons the scheduled three-hour show became the longest Oscar
telecast ever at four hours, eight or nine minutes, depending on
who you believe.
</P>
<P>
   Academy President Robert Rehme said Monday that it took more
time for presenters and winners to make their entrances and exits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a huge stage. That may have made the show longer
because the walks were longer,'' Rehme said. ``I think it was the
most use of that stage in its history. It's the largest stage in
North America and we showed all of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Any concern Rehme, a film producer, felt about the length of the
broadcast was overshadowed by the pleasure he took in counting the
academy's income from it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year the show grossed the highest ever, international and
domestic,'' Rehme said. He declined to reveal that sum, which pays
the academy's operating costs for the year, but the figure for the
1999 awards was $26.5 million, according to the academy's annual
report.
</P>
<P>
   ABC, which has the Oscar telecast contract through 2008, was
also celebrating. The show brought in the second-highest ratings in
the past five years, outdone only by the year ``Titanic'' swept the
awards.
</P>
<P>
   The network said some 46.3 million Americans were tuned in for
Sunday's entire show, and 79 million saw at least part of it, up
from 77.6 million the year before. Across the country it averaged a
29.2 rating and a 48 share, up from a 28.6 rating and a 46 share
last year. In Los Angeles, the No. 1 market for Oscar ratings, it
averaged a 42.7 rating and a 61 share. Chicago was the
second-largest market, despite the later broadcast in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Viewership peaked in the 10-10:30 p.m. Eastern Standard Time
block with 50.3million viewers nationwide, then plummeted to 39.2
million just after midnight when the last network commercial aired.
(Because no spots aired in the final 23 minutes, there is no rating
reported for when ``American Beauty'' finally was announced as Best
Picture).
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get 79 million people to watch, we're not
complaining,'' ABC spokesman Dan Doran said. ``One of our research
executives said if we get a third of the country watching our
commercials at one time, we have nothing to complain about.''
</P>
<P>
   Which means we are unlikely to see any remedies soon.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly at the Oscar nominees' luncheon earlier this month,
producer Richard Zanuck said the show's theme was ``keep it
short.''
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday, his wife and co-producer, Lili Fini Zanuck, said,
``When we took this on we had to open up our big mouths and say we
were going to make it shorter. And before we even aired we knew we
were going to run long.
</P>
<P>
   ``The run-throughs were really long. We tried to tighten it up
but only saved about a minute. It's just a long show,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Rehme agreed. ``The show's a long show. We're aware of it but
there's not a heck of a lot we can do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   He defended the film montage sequences dealing with the history
of the world according to Hollywood and the salute to child actors,
saying if those had been cut altogether it would have spared only
seven minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are, after all, about film, and we want to have film
packages.''
</P>
<P>
   Rehme also praised Burt Bacharach's star-studded medley of past
Oscar-winning songs, which went on long enough for everybody at a
typical home Oscar party to take a bathroom break.
</P>
<P>
   Lili Zanuck said she and her husband won't be repeating the
assignment next year. ``I wouldn't do it unless we could outdo what
we did, and right now I don't have those ideas in my head.''
</P>
<P>
   She reflected on the show at the Governors Ball less than an
hour after its conclusion. Asked about the length, she asked the
reporter, ``Did it feel long to you?''
</P>
<P>
   It felt plenty long to some. Best Director winner Sam Mendes
(``American Beauty'') told the Guardian in London that ``it felt
like a week'' before his category, the second to last of the
evening, came up.
</P>
<P>
   Elvis Mitchell, film critic for The New York Times, suggested
that the back-loading of the most interesting categories later in
the show than usual actually made it seem longer than it was.
</P>
<P>
   If they had offered up Best Supporting Actor earlier, he said,
``it would have been a little bit of meat to help you sit through
the rest of the vegetables that are bad for you to get to the rest
of the meat. It was like getting a Snickers with just one peanut.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he believes the length of the telecast will drive
viewers away in droves, Mitchell said, ``No. That's the classic
thing about pain. You forget about it until you experience it
again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
