A9907 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-PONCIANO-NORTHRID     03-28 0434
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-PONCIANO-NORTHRIDGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-NORTHRIDGE COACH GOES ON OFFENSIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTHRIDGE, Calif. _ Ron Ponciano, the Cal State Northridge
football coach fired eight months ago for violating NCAA and
university policies, finally is being heard.
</P>
<P>
   Ponciano, in his official response to the investigation that led
to his firing, accuses CSUN of distorting evidence and contends he
was a ``sacrificial lamb'' for the athletic department's lack of
control of the football program. He is seeking a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The Daily News has obtained a copy of the response to the
investigative report, which was written by internal auditor Peter
Dinauer and Tom Shannon, Northridge's faculty athletic
representative.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Football Audit misrepresents witness statements,
mischracterizes (sic) facts, reaches unsupportable conclusions,
slanders Coach Ponciano, and foists blame on Coach Ponciano for
which he bears no responsibility,'' writes Ponciano's lawyer, Scott
Campbell, in the 208-page document's introduction.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, who works for the Santa Barbara firm of Rogers,
Sheffield and Herman, sent Ponciano's response to CSU legal counsel
Pat Carroll in January. Campbell accuses CSUN of ineptitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems likely that no one with significant NCAA Division I
football experience reviewed the Football Audit and that no such
person was consulted prior to CSUN's decision to terminate Coach
Ponciano.''
</P>
<P>
   The report goes on to contest each of Dinauer's findings against
Ponciano that led to Ponciano's July 16, 1999 termination, and says
Dinauer's investigation was ``clearly ... prosecutorial.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell promises civil action if the CSU system doesn't settle
Ponciano's claim of wrongful termination, and said he and Ponciano,
now an assistant at Valley College, will attend the NCAA's April 14
hearing to determine sanctions against CSUN.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Football Audit and the NCAA investigation it spawned has
destroyed Coach Ponciano and his career,'' Campbell writes. ``He is
an `untouchable' in Division I ranks, and may well be tainted for
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Northridge is imposing its own penalties for the NCAA
infractions described in Dinauer's report, including a reduction of
two scholarships in each of the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   The CSU system is also in the final stage of settling a $6
million claim filed by football assistants Keith Borges and Craig
Wall. Borges and Wall say they have been blackballed from coaching
by CSUN for their cooperation in Dinauer's investigation. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
