<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-TENSION-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHT AT SONICS PRACTICE LEAVES TWO PLAYERS INJURED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Sonics guards Gary Payton and Vernon Maxwell were
involved in a fierce altercation Sunday that ended practice,
injured at least two teammates and threatened to fracture the
team's already fragile morale.
</P>
<P>
   Starting center Horace Grant did not play against the San
Antonio Spurs Monday night after bruising his left shoulder while
helping separate Maxwell and Payton. Swingman Chuck Person, already
on the injured list, aggravated his surgically repaired left knee
while trying to play peacemaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that shouldn't have happened, but it
happened,'' said Grant, who will undergo an MRI exam Tuedsday if
his shoulder does not improve. ``Things happen in the heat of
battle. ... We just need a win. We get a win and everything will be
OK.''
</P>
<P>
   The incident boiled over after a heated scrimmage during which
Maxwell and Payton continuously exchanged barbs. Sources said the
scene became so intense in the locker room afterward that Payton
picked up a chair, at which point Maxwell stormed into the training
room looking to grab a free weight. Both players were restrained
before making physical contact.
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell eventually got dressed in an office and was escorted out
of the team's practice facility by forward Vin Baker. Later, Baker,
apparently acting as mediator, spoke with Payton in the parking
lot.
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell declined comment Monday night when asked about the
incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an argument,'' Payton said. ``That's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sonics president Wally Walker said he talked to Maxwell on
Sunday night and to Payton early Monday. Walker refused to discuss
whether Payton and Maxwell would be fined, suspended or both.
Walker would say only that he encouraged both players to work out
their differences.
</P>
<P>
   However, club sources said Maxwell and Payton were fined
undisclosed amounts.
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell had a new locker location in KeyArena Monday night. He
had been situated directly to the left of Payton. Instead, Maxwell
used a locker that Lazaro Borrell occupied across the room.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute apparently did nothing to disrupt Maxwell and
Payton's chemistry on the court. The pair exchanged high fives and
patted each other's backside at times throughout the game Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both were wrong, and I told them that,'' Walker said. ``They
have to work it out between the two of them so it doesn't affect
the team and staff. If they put the onus on the team to settle
this, they won't like what could happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both assured me that it was over,'' Walker said. ``They said
they want to put the problem behind them. We'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell and Payton went hard at each other throughout the team's
workout Sunday. When it became obvious both players were driven by
more than competitive spirit, coach Paul Westphal ended practice.
What was scheduled to be a lengthy workout ended after about 90
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said Payton walked into the locker room while teammates
encouraged Maxwell to apologize. Maxwell is said to have entered
the locker room ready to resolve the matter.
</P>
<P>
   But Payton, still seething, reportedly threw a remote control at
Maxwell.
</P>
<P>
   As the two again became enraged, sources said Person restrained
Payton. Grant hurt himself when he subdued Maxwell in the training
room.
</P>
<P>
   Grant received treatment before the game but was unable to play.
Greg Foster started in his place.
</P>
<P>
   This was the second time a Maxwell-Payton exchange became
public. The two had to be separated earlier this season after
arguing during a timeout in a game in KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
