<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER LATE MELTDOWN DOOMS SONICS AGAINST SPURS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ While this would seem like the time most playoff-bound
NBA teams find ways to solidify their foundation, the Sonics
suddenly are discovering nothing but cracks.
</P>
<P>
   Their shooting? Broke. Defensive intensity? Inconsistent.
Health? Delicate. Fourth-quarter moxie? Deteriorating. Confidence?
Vanishing like the days in a week.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics' 90-82 loss to the San Antonio Spurs in KeyArena
Monday night went like a bad television re-run. For three quarters,
the Sonics played well enough to win. But once again they
relinquished a lead in the fourth quarter, and what followed was
predictable.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics fell apart as if someone hit a detonator. Their
offense sputtered, the defense yielded and the fight slowly seeped
from of their sagging bodies.
</P>
<P>
   The result was the Sonics' fourth consecutive home loss, and an
admission that it is becoming more difficult to keep the team
together.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're frustrated. I mean there's no keeping us from being
frustrated,'' Sonics coach Paul Westphal said. ``But we have to
keep in mind the big picture. We're going to make the playoffs so
we're fighting for positioning in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our record is such that we have a good chance to move up,'' he
said. ``We're like everybody else, we'd rather not play the
(top-seeded Los Angeles) Lakers.''
</P>
<P>
   The magic number for the Sonics to clinch a playoff spot is
essentially irrelevant. A Sonic victory combined with a Dallas loss
will ensure the postseason berth.
</P>
<P>
   However, the team's direction has taken a swift turn from a
route that was impressive to this disappointing stretch. It was
less than two months ago that the Sonics were sitting pretty with
the fourth seed.
</P>
<P>
   They are now in the eighth spot, a half-game behind the
seventh-seeded Sacramento Kings. Still, the Sonics must face a
streaking New York Knicks team Wednesday, and the Kings visit on
Friday. Then, the Sonics travel to Portland on Sunday. They are 0-2
against Sacramento this season and haven't beaten a playoff team
since Charlotte on Feb. 28.
</P>
<P>
   More pressing is the Sonics lost Monday for the fifth time in
their past six games in KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know it's not going to get any easier,'' backup center Greg
Foster said. ``But it's as simple as this: Either you're going to
be a man about it and stay and work hard, or you're going to run
and hide and quit. It's not too late. We can still get things
clicking and get things back together for the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   On top of finding ways to string together several wins, the
Sonics must get healthy. Foster started at center because Horace
Grant is suffering from a bruised left shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics may not have Vin Baker in the lineup Wednesday after
he left the game Monday with a left ankle sprain. Baker crashed to
the floor with 2:21 left in the game when he turned his ankle while
attempting a move in the post against San Antonio's Tim Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   Baker didn't get his shot off and did not return. He fell, and
the ball rolled out of bounds. There was at least a reason for the
turnover. Otherwise, the Sonics simply froze down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   They led 69-55 with 2:15 to play in the third quarter. San
Antonio stormed in front behind a 22-12 run that bridged the third
and fourth periods. An Antonio Daniels' layup put the Spurs ahead
77-76.
</P>
<P>
   From there, the Sonics had little ball movement, rushed shots or
were turned away by the Spurs front line of Duncan and David
Robinson. With 1:22 left in the game, Robinson's dunk capped an
11-2 run that buried the Sonics under a 88-78 deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's demoralizing to look at the body language when we lose a
lead,'' Foster said. ``This is the NBA. That's going to happen. But
you've got to be abrasive enough to handle that.''
</P>
<P>
   Without Grant, the team's best interior defender, the Sonics
struggled to contain Duncan (30 points, 18 rebounds) and Robinson
(23 points, 16 rebounds and four blocks).
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics, who shot 36-for-89 (40 percent), encountered the
best defensive team in the league. San Antonio entered the game
allowing opponents a league-low 89.9 points per game.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio held the Sonics to 16 points and 6-for-20 shooting
in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys are playing hard, but for some reason or another, we're
not making baskets down the stretch,'' Baker said. ``We've got to
get to the bottom of it before the playoffs start.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant said the team must first cement its psyche.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some confidence here, but it's slowly fading,'' Grant
said. ``We have to believe in each other and play like we trust
each other. ... Guys need to look at themselves and see what's more
important _ winning or individual goals. Where I come from, the
team comes first. Other things you have going on should be
secondary.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
