<SLUG> BC-RAYART-EXPAND-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAY-ART ADDS SOUND STAGE NO. 6
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARLA MATZER ROSE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  LOS ANGELES _ Sidestepping the effect of ``runaway
production'' by focusing on episodic television production, Ray-Art
Studios is adding a sixth sound stage to its Warner Center complex.
</P>
<P>
   Ray-Art converted a warehouse formerly owned by Boeing Aircraft
and Redken Laboratories to sound stages two years ago and will have
about 120,000 square feet of space by July.
</P>
<P>
   Paramount Television has already signed a lease for the new
sound stage and will use it for two shows.
</P>
<P>
   Ray-Art co-owner Robert Papazian declined to name the specific
shows, and Paramount did not return calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Previous shows that have used Ray-Art include ``Nothing
Sacred,'' ``The Love Boat: The Next Wave'' and the feature film
``Blade.''
</P>
<P>
   The growth in TV production has been fueled by the explosion in
the number of new networks, and it has created great local demand
for sound stage space in the past several years.
</P>
<P>
   Papazian said television series are more likely than feature
films and television movies to stay in Los Angeles because of the
quick turnaround time.
</P>
<P>
   Papazian said his location in suburban Woodland Hills was
especially attractive to television producers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're close to the buyers ... We're close to the talent,''
said Papazian, a veteran television producer himself with partner
and Ray-Art co-owner James Hirsch.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of Los Angeles-area sound stages are still on the
lots of the major studios. But in recent years, the studios have
moved more toward leasing property and equipment rather than
investing in it. This has fueled a mini-building boom in sound
stage space, stretching from Toluca Lake to downtown Los Angeles to
Manhattan Beach to Santa Clarita.
</P>
<P>
   In all, there are roughly 300 sound stages in Southern
California now.
</P>
<P>
   Papazian said location is an important factor to producers,
along with the physical facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We approached the facility as producers, so when people come
in, we already know their problems,'' Papazian said.
</P>
<P>
   Papazian, who currently is a co-executive producer of the Don
Johnson series ``Nash Bridges,'' said such things as the layout of
the production offices, the communications systems, the arrangement
of parking and even the presence of an on-site commissary are
considered critical by time-strapped TV producers.
</P>
<P>
   Sound stages often sign contracts with production firms to use
the space for a set number of months or years. If they're not using
the space at a certain time, they're often free to sublet it to
other productions. In this fairly tight market, sound stages often
rent for several thousand dollars a day.
</P>
<P>
   Ray-Art's sixth stage will be the only one to have an
audience-rated stage, meaning a show can tape there in front of an
audience. Papazian said it will be the only such stage in the West
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Ray-Art's stages are on the small side for feature
films. They are ideal, though, for both television and commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Papazian said he is looking to woo more commercials to Ray-Art
by converting one stage to be used strictly for commercials. TV
spots tend to be effects-heavy, so the studio will be equipped with
a ``green screen'' against which live action can be filmed and
effects put in later.
</P>
<P>
   This seems a smart move: Commercial production has been
especially resilient even during recent L.A. filming downturns.
According to Los Angeles' Entertainment Industry Development
Council, the number of commercial production days for the first two
months of 2000 was up more than 20 percent over the same months in
1999. During the same period, the number of TV production days was
up less than 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   More growth is likely: Papazian hinted at more stages being
planned, and said Ray-Art's staff of eight will surely grow along
with the studios.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
