<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VITESSE-ACQUIRE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VITESSE BUYS SILICON CHIP MAKER OROLOGIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JASON Z. COHEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  CAMARILLO, Calif. _ Moving to expand its chip product line,
Vitesse Semiconductor Inc. on Monday purchased chip maker Orologic
Inc. for $450 million.
</P>
<P>
   Orologic, based in Research Triangle Park, N.C., makes
semiconductors that Vitesse wants to offer in conjunction with its
existing chips.
</P>
<P>
   Vitesse, which makes semiconductors for telecommunications
equipment using gallium arsenide rather than silicon, is responding
to customer demands, chief executive officer Lou Tomasetta said.
</P>
<P>
   Tomasetta said Orologic's silicon chips add capabilities to the
complete package Vitesse plans to offer its customers.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition, along with Vitesse's May 1999 purchase of
network chip maker XaQti (pronounced ``shockti''), creates a more
complete offering, Tomasetta said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vitesse has been focusing on trying to bring complete
solutions to the high-performance communications market. A number
of (our customers) have been asking for this capability in the next
generation,'' Tomasetta said. ``We think this is a potentially very
big area.''
</P>
<P>
   The company projects the combined products will generate $50
million in revenue during fiscal 2001. Market forecasts for 2003
approach $1 billion, Tomasetta said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big market for us to go after,'' he said. ``We're
pretty certain that this is going to make a significant difference
in our revenue stream in 2001. The market is really ready now for a
chip supplier to go in with a complete solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Semiconductor analyst Arun Veerappan of Robertson Stephens
Securities said Vitesse's recent acquisitions move its chips beyond
the physical layer _ network switching, where the physical
connection to the user is made _ and closer to the infrastructure
of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will provide them with a fuller product portfolio that
encompasses an end-to-end solution,'' Veerappan said.
</P>
<P>
   To complete the purchase, Vitesse will issue 5.5 million shares
of stock, adding to its present base of 170 million shares, chief
financial officer Eugene Hovanek said.
</P>
<P>
   The company hopes to close the transaction by the end of the
week, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hovanek said the purchase will have a slight negative effect on
the company's earnings for 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
