<SLUG> BC-ASSAD-CLINTON-WAR-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAR IN MIDEAST THIS SUMMER? CLINTON, ASSAD MEET TO DISCUSS  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This 650-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By ROBERT FISK  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. President Bill Clinton and President Assad of Syria met in
Geneva Sunday in what may be a last attempt to avoid war in
southern Lebanon this summer.
</P>
<P>
   What was advertised as an attempt to restart Syrian-Israeli
peace talks _ with Clinton trying to accommodate Assad's demand
that a total Israeli withdrawal from the occupied Golan Heights
should be based on U.N. Security Council Resolution 242 _ has now
become a race to prevent a unilateral Israeli withdrawal under fire
from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   For three hours, the two men talked through interpreters at a
meeting in the Intercontinental Hotel in Geneva _ Assad has been
known to exhaust many foreign leaders with up to six hours of
discussions _ as the Syrian leader patiently explained that he was
not going to fall into the same ``peace'' trap as PLO leader Yassir
Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   He will not make peace with Israel before guaranteeing the
return of all of the occupied Golan, captured by Israel in the 1967
Middle East war.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat signed a peace settlement with Israel, then failed to
gain a majority of the occupied West Bank or a capital in
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis and Americans know that Syria will never allow the
Israelis to withdraw from their hopeless war in southern Lebanon
without the return of the Golan.
</P>
<P>
   With a Syrian peace still unsigned, Hezbollah guerrillas in
Lebanon _ supported by Syria _ will continue to attack withdrawing
Israeli occupation troops and Palestinian guerrillas may then be
permitted to attack Israel across the international frontier _ just
as they did before 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Israel wants its soldiers out of their occupation zone by July.
</P>
<P>
   Syria has already indicated that it would accept an
international presence on the Golan after an Israeli retreat;
sources in Beirut suggest that U.S. and French troops may be
permitted to man an early warning station on the Heights.
</P>
<P>
   And the Syrians seem resigned to the opening of diplomatic
missions in each other's countries if the Israelis do withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   Assad is even said to be prepared to compromise on the exact
line of withdrawal, perhaps accepting continued Israeli control of
the entire shore of Galilee while negotiating on joint water
rights.
</P>
<P>
   But he wants the whole of the Golan back before a full peace.
For this reason, the American administration, playing the Israeli
card as usual, has been lambasting Assad as an ``obstacle to
peace'' _ as if the Syrian desire to implement the U.N. Security
Council Resolution upon which the whole ``peace process'' is based
is somehow designed to obstruct a final settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Assad believes that the Palestinians were conned into signing
the Oslo agreement in the belief that this would give them Gaza and
the West Bank and a Palestinian capital in Jerusalem and end all
Jewish settlements on their land. It did nothing of the kind.
</P>
<P>
   But Assad's south Lebanon card is a powerful one. If Israel
withdraws, only to find that its northern border is as vulnerable
as it was more than two decades ago _ and this after two Israeli
invasions of Lebanon which cost the lives of at least 19,000
Lebanese and Palestinian civilians _ then Israeli prime minister
Ehud Barak will be seen to have failed in his attempt to cut the
Israeli army's losses in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   The Lebanese, of course, would bear the cost of such a war.
</P>
<P>
   The Syrian daily ``Ath-Thawra'' put it quite bluntly just before
Assad left for Geneva: ``President Assad will make no compromise...
on Syria's basic principles'' of exchanging land for peace, its
editor wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But Syrian radio _ as much a mouthpiece for Assad as the
Damascus press _ insisted that ``Syria wants to reach decisive and
clear results in Geneva to bring the peace process through to a
conclusion.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this timely 650-word article from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London, it must be purchased from the New York Times
Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or
fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
