<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASSAD-`NO'-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LION OF DAMASCUS ROARS `NO WAY' TO CLINTON  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This excellent 675-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By ROBERT FISK  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Syrian President Hafez Assad claims to like U.S. President Bill
Clinton but it would be difficult to find two more different men.
</P>
<P>
   Assad is a stickler for detail, inexhaustible in his search for
the exact words which will ensure a cease-fire or a peace
agreement, ruthless in pursuit of his political aims _ be it the
return of the occupied Golan Heights or the suppression of an
Islamic insurrection in his own country.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton doesn't like detail, he prefers emotion, ``trust'' _
always a sticky quality in high politics _ and will invariably give
way, like all American presidents, under Israeli pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Assad knows all about that pressure; he has fought it ever since
1967 when, as Syrian defense minister, he lost the Golan.
</P>
<P>
   That's why, in 1991, he demanded _ and got _ a confidential
letter from then-U.S. Secretary of State James Baker that an
Arab-Israeli peace would be constructed upon U.N. Security Council
Resolution 242.
</P>
<P>
   That historic resolution demands the return of all Arab land
occupied in the 1967 war in return for the security of all states _
including Israel _ in the area.
</P>
<P>
   It is upon that letter that Assad has based his entire
``strategic decision'' for peace. And in return, the Lion of
Damascus _ even the Israelis call him that _ as been called
inflexible, frightened, sick, desperate and brutal. It is a big
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those people who believe that Assad is negotiating out of
weakness _ or because he is desperate to bequeath a peace to his
son Bashar _ do not know the president of Syria,'' one of his close
acquaintances remarked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have told the Americans to be careful. The Israelis say all
these things but they are making a big mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assad is determined to get Golan back under the terms of the
U.N. Security Council resolution. He will stick to the letter of
the resolution. He is not going to be another Yassir Arafat.''
</P>
<P>
   True, Assad at 69 looks his age. His voice is gravelly, his
heart condition in 1982 proved his own mortality, his family feud
with his brother Rifaat remains unsettled.
</P>
<P>
   Syria is a police state and Assad's enemies rot in the darkest
of prisons. But his suspicions are almost always well-founded, his
fear of entrapment as real as his ability to lock up the Israelis
in their own adventures in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   If the Israelis want to leave Lebanon, they must give back
Golan. If they leave without handing back Syria's territory, then
there will be no peace on Israel's northern border with Lebanon.
Abide by the U.N. resolution, Assad says. Again and again and
again.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy, of course, to make the old man look uncompromising.
The U.S. State Department and the American media and all the usual
third-rate opinion-makers map out an easy story to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Assad is dying. He must be forced to accept ``reality'' (i.e.,
American and Israeli power). He is uncompromising. He wants Golan
back before making peace with Israel; so why should he throw a
``spanner in the works'' by demanding land first and peace later?
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Assad has seen what happened to Arafat _ who
accepted peace first and got precious little land, no capital in
Jerusalem, no end to Jewish settlements and no return of refugees _
is quietly erased from this scenario.
</P>
<P>
   Assad must be painted black. But his refusal to compromise on
the Baker letter and America's promise of a peace based on U.N.
resolutions is his sticking point.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton was reminded of that again Sunday when he met
with Assad. So was Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Assad may be prepared to bargain over foreign troops in early
warning stations and the sources of water, but he wants the land
that was Syrian up to that fateful month of 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Of all Middle East potentates, Assad is perhaps the only one who
believes that words mean what they say. Land for peace means just
that. All the land. And total peace. And in that order. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
