<HEADER>
A9929 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     03-28 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERA, PUT A CLOCK NEAR THE PHONE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ My gown? It's Vera Wang, of course.
<P>
   Vera phoned me one morning at 3 o'clock, so excited, said the
idea came to her in a dream, nobody could wear it but me, and by
the time we both realized she had a wrong number, there was no way
for her to withdraw the offer gracefully, nor for me to tactfully
decline.
</P>
<P>
   THE OAKLAND A's have a billboard campaign, ``While they're
building a stadium, we're building a team.''
</P>
<P>
   In the spirit of the Pope, it's good to see the A's publicly
admitting their mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   SUE ME, I even like the monstrous Coke bottle at the Giants' new
park. Yes, that stuff is swill, but at least it's not bottled by
Third World slave labor.
</P>
<P>
   AN ALGORITHM is a mathematical rule or procedure for solving a
problem.
</P>
<P>
   For example, an algorithm for the problem of sagging campaign
contributions might be something like ``Hit up some Buddhists.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Kales wonders if there is such thing as a
GeorgeWBushrithm.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, Richard, I don't think there's much chance George W. has
any kind of rithm.cq &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  SADDEST SIGHT on Oscar night was the news shot of Darva (The
Diva) Conger trying to crash the Vanity Fair apres-Oscars party.
</P>
<P>
   Darva does not want media attention, and she'll do whatever is
necessary, go wherever she must, to spread that message.
</P>
<P>
   Next, a photo spread in Playboy, titled, ``Hey, What're  &UR; You &LR; 
Lookin' At?''
</P>
<P>
   WISCONSIN is in the basketball Final Four, and hoopswatcher
Lotta Dotz has an explanation for the team's big, plodding style,
more Clydesdale than racehorse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's simple: A steady Wisconsin diet of beer, bratwurst and
cheese. Remember Lombardi and his power sweep? Same deal. Go to any
small-town Wisconsin bar, and you'll see eight bar stools occupied
by four women.''
</P>
<P>
   WHAT WOULD John Steinbeck say, wonders Daryl Glen, if he knew
there was a Grapes of Wrath Catering in the shadow of the public
library in Pacific Grove, where Steinbeck lived much of his life?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they cater field-worker strikes.
</P>
<P>
   BLUNDER YOUR WAY to billions! It's the latest craze.
</P>
<P>
   David Coulter was fired by BofA, got a $100 mil pink slip. The
BankOf Hugh McColl is in decline, so Hugh's bonus for '99 was only
$76 million.
</P>
<P>
   Now Mark Willes, the CEO who presided over the downfall of the
L.A. Times, gets $9.2 million to not let the door hit him in the
butt.
</P>
<P>
   Steer a monstrous corporation onto the rocks, cash big check.
It's called a Joseph Hazelwood Bonus.
</P>
<P>
   LAST SEEN, North Beach legend Enrico Banducci was heading north
to the wine country, having abandoned plans to open a restaurant in
North Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Next seen he's lunching at Moose's and telling Carole Vernier
he's back in San Francisco for good, planning to open a cooking
school.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, Enrico, tell 'em to go easy on the garlic. Garlic abuse is
running rampant in the city's restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   ONE MORE ROUND of American's favorite game, What Would Jesus
Drive?
</P>
<P>
   Donna Ernston says it might be a Silver Cloud, but thinks it's
more interesting to speculate on what the devil would drive, since
he'd get all the hot cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Infiniti,'' says Ann Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Moses, according to an anonymous caller, would ride an old
British motorcycle, because the Bible says, ``The roar of Moses'
triumph is heard in the hills.''
</P>
<P>
   Wandering way off course, Jamie Keller asks, ``How about the
first mention of tennis in the Bible? When Moses served in
Pharaoh's court.''
</P>
<P>
   Pastor Jim Stickney of St. Alban's in Albany says that whatever
Jesus drives, he would use his turn signals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wonder,'' says Mike Sullivan, ``what statue Jesus would
put on his dashboard.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Nader?
</P>
<P>
   HANG UP or get out: That's the rule in some of the hipper Bay
Area restaurants. Flying Saucer might be the first local spot that
instituted an official no-cell policy.
</P>
<P>
   Others now include Dine in SF, the St. Francis Yacht Club (``No
hats. No cell phones.''), Chapeau (Yes hats. No cell phones.),
L'Amie Donia in Palo Alto and Chez Panisse in Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Further afield: The Carmel Bay Co. gift shop, ``No food, drink,
or cell phones.''
</P>
<P>
   And Mo Stevens was in Zimbabwe at the hugely cool Victoria Falls
Hotel, where an ornately scripted sign in the lobby says: ``The use
of cellular phones in public places is not permitted in the
Victoria Falls Hotel.''
</P>
<P>
   HOT BIZ opportunity waiting to be exploited: A restaurant that
caters to the cell-phone junkie.
</P>
<P>
   Call it Chez Obnoxique.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
