<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 03:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9930 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-MAKEUP-POLLUTION-SFCH     03-28 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAKEUP-POLLUTION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKEUP, MEDICATION MAY POLLUTE WATERWAYS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARL T. HALL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ Exotic chemicals in drugs and cosmetics may
wind up polluting the nation's waterways and harming fish, experts
warned Monday.
<P>
   Not much is known about the potential dangers of pharmaceuticals
and other designer chemicals in the environment. Although the issue
has been under study for several years in Europe, research is still
in the very early stages and virtually no work has been done in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   An international panel of experts on the subject convened Monday
as part of the national meeting of the American Chemical Society,
under way this week in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers said it was the first time scientists have gathered
to address the topic in North America _ itself a sign of just how
little attention has been paid to the emerging environmental
concerns posed by products such as antibiotics, psychiatric drugs,
hormones, animal-feed additives and synthetic fragrances.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something federal agencies are just now getting into,''
said Christian Daughton of the U.S. Environmental Protection
Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Industrial pollutants with ominous-sounding chemical names tend
to garner far more regulatory and scientific attention. But
thousands of everyday products that most people take for granted
are being manufactured _ and, ultimately, flushed or thrown away
after use _ in huge quantities often comparable to agrochemical
production.
</P>
<P>
   Ecological monitoring in Germany and Switzerland confirm that
traces of commonly used painkillers and other prescription drugs
can be found in natural groundwaters and aquifers. Municipal
wastewater-treatment plants are unable to screen out some of the
more hardy compounds.
</P>
<P>
   Residues of cholesterol-lowering drugs and the analgesic
diclofenac have even been found in the city of Berlin's drinking
water, albeit in extremely low concentrations. German scientists
offered assurances that the city's tap water is in no danger of
becoming a prescription-only product anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a real problem for human health,'' said Thomas
Heberer of the Institute of Food Chemistry at the University of
Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; `An Uncomfortable Feeling'
</P>
<P>
   But his findings have been the cause of some squeamishness. Even
if the Berlin water meets health standards, Heberer said, ``it can
give you an uncomfortable feeling knowing you are drinking
something that has made it through someone else's kidneys.''
</P>
<P>
   The more critical concern is the impact on aquatic species,
which can build up surprisingly high concentrations of chemical
pollutants from barely detectable levels.
</P>
<P>
   David Epel, a biologist at Stanford University, said he is
planning studies of whether calcium-channel blockers and
immunosuppressant drugs might be capable of overwhelming natural
toxin-filtering systems common in nearly all multicelled animals.
</P>
<P>
   For therapeutic reasons, certain new drugs are being developed
that are specifically designed to block ``efflux transporters,''
molecules on the surface of cells that shuttle out troublemaking
substances.
</P>
<P>
   These transporters have a limited capacity to deal with a
multitude of chemicals, Epel said, raising the possibility that
fish and other aquatic species in drug-polluted waters may become
vulnerable to toxic overload.
</P>
<P>
   Other emerging issues include the possibility of endocrine
disruption and reproductive problems following exposure to
hormone-like drugs, small amounts of which can have big effects in
some species. At the same time, scientists are debating whether
antibiotics in the environment, either from human-drug residues or
farm runoff, could breed drug-resistant microbes.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists noted that nobody has established any clear
evidence of environmental damage yet. But they said the evidence so
far clearly warrants some close scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really haven't focused on this very much at all,'' Daughton
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
