<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 10:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9982 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l BC-ORGANS-DONATION-KANSA     03-28 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORGANS-DONATION-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVING SO OTHERS CAN LIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LISA GUTIERREZ  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Scottish researchers this month (March) introduced the
world to five piglets they'd cloned, they hailed the achievement as
a solution to the worldwide shortage of human organs for
transplantation.
</P>
<P>
   More than 68,000 people in this country alone are on a waiting
list, waiting for new hearts, kidneys, livers, lungs, corneas and
bone marrow.
</P>
<P>
   They wait and wait. Five thousand Americans died waiting last
year because there weren't enough organs and tissue available.
</P>
<P>
   Whether animal-to-human transplants are a viable, not to mention
ethical, solution remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   And the waiting continues.
</P>
<P>
   Next month the United Network for Organ Sharing, which maintains
the country's organ transplant waiting list, will run nationwide
public service announcements designed to dispel the myths and
address the fears that keep more Americans from donating organs or
tissue.
</P>
<P>
   Polls have shown that more than 80 percent of Americans support
the concept of organ donations. Yet every year, from the more than
15,000 potential donors who die in hospitals, only a third of their
families consent to donate their loved one's organs.
</P>
<P>
   The donation process starts with a signature on the back of a
driver's license or donor card, on which you can specify the organs
you want to donate. But because many people forget to take the
critical second step, their wishes are not always carried out after
they die.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem is, they don't tell their family. Most
people don't realize that the family has the last word,'' says Bob
Spieldenner, spokesman for the United Network for Organ Sharing in
Richmond, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ``So when families are asked about donating their loved one's
organs, they say, `I don't know what they wanted. I'm not sure.'
And even though it might be indicated on their driver's license,
they never talked about it with their family. And the family is
afraid to make a mistake, so they go with what they feel
comfortable with.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we tell people, `Make your decision now. But tell
your family about it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Organ procurement groups like Midwest Transplant Network in
Westwood, which covers all of Kansas and the western two-thirds of
Missouri, will not go against the wishes of the family, even if the
deceased had signed a donor card or driver's license.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your husband or brother and sisters say no, we would go
with their decision, because they are the survivors,'' says Midwest
spokeswoman Kim Francis. ``Flip it around. If your loved one died
and I said, `Too bad; he wanted to donate, and we're going to take
him off to surgery now,' how would you feel?''
</P>
<P>
   Having family members witness you signing your donor card or
driver's license can show them how committed you are to your
decision, Francis says. ``It's a good idea to say to your family
that this would make me really happy to know that I've saved
someone else's life, and this is really, really important to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Death, though, is a topic many would rather avoid. ``We've done
some focus group research that shows that people are afraid to talk
about it, or they are superstitious because they think if they talk
about it, it will somehow happen,'' Spieldenner says.
</P>
<P>
   Fear keeps most people from donating, say those trying to
encourage people to do just that. What will organ donation cost my
family? (Nothing.) Will my body be disfigured when they remove the
organs? (No.) Will doctors still work hard to save my life if they
see I carry a donor card? (Yes.) Does my religion allow this? (Most
do.)
</P>
<P>
   Everyone, regardless of age or health, is a potential donor.
Ninety-year-olds have donated livers; 80-year-olds have donated
kidneys. Though the oldest heart donors have been in their late
'50s, ``more and more they're willing to use older donors, partly
because of the shortage,'' Spieldenner says. ``And medical
advancements show that they can be used.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We tell everyone not to rule themselves out. If you have AIDS,
that's probably going to rule you out, although there is some
experimenting going on using organs from AIDS patients in other
AIDS patients.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the procurement agency receives consent from the family to
proceed, each organ is evaluated. Though the donor has been
declared brain dead, doctors use a ventilator to keep oxygenated
blood pumping through the organs to keep them healthy during the
process, Francis says.
</P>
<P>
   The matchmaking ensues when the organs are deemed useful. The
local procurement agency contacts the United Network for Organ
Sharing in Virginia, which by computer matches the organ to
transplant centers awaiting similar organs. Ultimately a recipient
is found.
</P>
<P>
   The entire testing and procurement process typically takes eight
to 12 hours at the hospital. Procurement workers, trained to assist
grieving family members, work closely with the relatives on the
timing, Francis says. ``Donation is not going to help anyone if we
have complicated their funeral plans.''
</P>
<P>
   For more information on organ donation contact:
</P>
<P>
   - Midwest Transplant Network, 1900 W. 47th Place, Suite 400,
Westwood, Kan. 66205. (913) 262-1668.
</P>
<P>
   - United Network for Organ Sharing (www.unos.org) and the
Coalition on Donation (www.shareyourlife.org), 1100 Boulders
Parkway, Suite 500, Richmond, Va. 23225-8770. (800) 355-7427.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-00 1004EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000328.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0001 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-BOOKS-MERKLE-KANSAS-K     03-28 1485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MERKLE-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS BASEBALL SEASON BEGINS, KC AUTHOR LINES ONE RIGHT OUT OF PARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN MARK EBERHART  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   More Than Merkle, by David W. Anderson (271 pages; University of
Nebraska Press; $29.95)
</P>
<P>
   Books and baseball are a natural fit. Of all the major-league
sports, baseball is the most cerebral, the slowest-paced, the one
that lends itself as easily to a writer's flights of fancy as the
flight of a home-run ball.
</P>
<P>
   So it's OK that David W. Anderson of Leawood took five years to
write his baseball book, following an arc that led back to 1908. In
doing so, he crafted an excellent new entry in the baseball
literary canon _ and rediscovered the greatest season baseball ever
had.
</P>
<P>
   More Than Merkle, in fact, boasts this audacious subtitle: A
History of the Best and Most Exciting Baseball Season in Human
History.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson chuckles; it was his publisher's idea. ``That's
hyperbole from the University of Nebraska Press. I wanted 1908:
Baseball's Most Exciting Year. But book publishing is a series of
compromises, at least at my level. Hey, I'm not Stephen King.''
</P>
<P>
   But Anderson does believe there has never been a season like
1908, and while one might be inclined to argue with a first-time
author, Anderson has also umpired high school baseball _ and you
should never argue with umpires.
</P>
<P>
   1908 was the last year the Chicago Cubs won a World Series. It
was the year pennant races in the American and National leagues
were tighter than nuts on a new bridge. It was the year the diamond
was ruled by future Hall of Famers _ Walter Johnson, Christy
Mathewson, Cy Young, Ty Cobb, Honus Wagner.
</P>
<P>
   And 1908 was the year New York Giants rookie Fred Merkle made a
mistake that cost his team a crucial game and gave the Cubs the NL
pennant. Largely forgotten now, the play was remembered for decades
by fans as ``Merkle's Boner.''
</P>
<P>
   Ninety-two years later, the 2000 baseball season looms; it
starts Wednesday with another cycle of glory and shame. Will it be
great? Will Sammy Sosa slug the Cubs back to the Series after nine
decades? Well, all seasons are great for baseball fans, if not for
Cubs fans.
</P>
<P>
   But there'll never be another 1908.
</P>
<P>
   Merkle's defender
</P>
<P>
   Fred Merkle was not an idiot.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson believes this. The Sprint executive, who relocated
earlier this year to Leawood from Indiana, grew up in South Bend
and followed Chicago baseball. He was more a White Sox fan than a
Cubbie, but at any rate he has no love for New York teams.
</P>
<P>
   But he champions Merkle, the New York Giants' rookie first
baseman that fateful year.
</P>
<P>
   The story in a peanut shell: The Giants and Cubs were fighting
for a World Series berth as the season drew to a close. On Sept. 23
they faced each other at the Polo Grounds, New York's home field
(this was long before the Giants moved to San Francisco).
</P>
<P>
   It was a low-scoring game, a pitchers' duel between the Cubs'
Jack ``The Giant Killer'' Pfiester and New York's Christy
Mathewson.
</P>
<P>
   Cubs shortstop Joe Tinker hit a homer, but the Giants came back
and tied the game, 1-1. Then, in the ninth, with two out and Giants
left fielder Moose McCormick on base, Fred Merkle singled.
Infielder Al Bridwell came to the plate and smacked another single.
McCormick scored the winning run.
</P>
<P>
   Except that it wasn't the winning run. According to an arcane
rule, Merkle was supposed to touch second base before he headed for
the clubhouse. He didn't. Nobody was in the habit of doing it. But
in 1908, umpires were just starting to enforce the rule.
</P>
<P>
   Merkle trotted off. Cubs' second baseman Johnny Evers ``screamed
for the ball,'' according to Anderson's book. Umpire Hank O'Day
ruled that Fred Merkle was the third out, that McCormick's run
didn't count, that the game was over.
</P>
<P>
   O'Day declared the game a tie. The National League ordered the
game to be replayed. It was _ and the Giants lost.
</P>
<P>
   They lost the game. They lost the pennant race, finishing behind
the Cubs by one game. And Fred Merkle lost the respect of fans and
journalists; the latter nicknamed him ``Bonehead.''
</P>
<P>
   But Anderson insists Merkle was made a goat for a mistake that
other players would have made that year, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a tragic figure because in that age, the press would go
after the players and not the managers _ and really, John McGraw
was at fault there.''
</P>
<P>
   Giants manager McGraw was ``a control freak,'' Anderson says.
Earlier in the season, another player on another team had made a
similar mistake against the Cubs and had been called out by the
same umpire. McGraw should have given Merkle a heads-up to touch
second, Anderson says.
</P>
<P>
   But as Anderson says: ``If ifs and buts were candy and nuts
...''
</P>
<P>
   On the Dead Ball
</P>
<P>
   The Merkle story is a classic, and Anderson's telling of it is
masterful. But the book is called More Than Merkle for good reason:
It's a wonderful portrait of a game that no longer exists.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, we have baseball. But More Than Merkle is about players as
opposed to millionaires, ballparks instead of stadiums, a game and
not a business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a different time and a time that I think we need to
exalt,'' Anderson says. ``What I was trying to do with this book
was give people an idea of what baseball was like in the Dead Ball
Era.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dead Ball Era? It doesn't sound glamorous, and maybe it
wasn't by today's standards. We're used to Mark McGwire and Sosa
and Ken Griffey Jr. blasting the ball out of the park, but the
balls they hit are literally corked _ they have cork centers, which
make them livelier. In 1908 the balls didn't carry as well. Hence,
``Dead Ball.'' Other aspects of the game also favored defense.
Pitchers dominated. Games had scores like 1-0 and 2-1, not 15-6.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson thinks it was more exciting. But if the game was purer,
fans were not.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was gambling and hard liquor in the stands. The owners
voted down a ban on glass containers in 1908 because they would
lose profits on beverage sales. There were no paper cups back then,
so you had fans in the ballpark with bottles. If you look at some
of the old crowd shots you can see how close the fans are to the
players ... and sometimes there's a look of terror in the players'
eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the situation after the replayed Giants-Cubs game got
ugly. The Cubs had won the decisive game of the season on Giant
turf. And Giants fans were on the edge of violence, as Anderson
recounts in the book through the eyes of Cubs pitcher Mordecai
``Three Finger'' Brown:
</P>
<P>
   ``We made it to the dressing room and barricaded the door.
Outside, wild men were yelling for our blood _ really. As the mob
got bigger, the police came up and formed a line across the door.
We read the next day that the cops had to pull their revolvers to
hold them back. I couldn't say as to that. We weren't sticking our
heads out to see.''
</P>
<P>
   As Anderson writes, ``The Cubs had to celebrate their
unprecedented third straight pennant on the train for Detroit. They
left town with a police escort.''
</P>
<P>
   Redemption and curses
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs won the battle that year. After that game with the
Giants, they went on to an anticlimactic World Series, defeating
the Detroit Tigers handily.
</P>
<P>
   But they lost the war: No Cubs team has won a World Series
since.
</P>
<P>
   Is there a Merkle curse?
</P>
<P>
   Anderson laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Merkle never uttered a curse. But there is kind of a cosmic
thing going there. Why wouldn't the Cubs ever win another World
Series? Of course, when you look at some of the teams they've
fielded, that answers that question.''
</P>
<P>
   And Merkle redeemed himself with 17 seasons of solid play and a
subsequent career as a minor-league manager. The jeers never
stopped, but Merkle never gave up, either.
</P>
<P>
   The big winners of 1908, though, were the owners. Total
attendance for both leagues was just over 7 million, a record
(compare that to today, when one team can draw 3 million in a
single season). It can be claimed that 1908 was the year baseball
became ``the national pastime.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That season gave the owners the confidence to realize that
baseball was a viable business and that they needed to build
permanent stadiums, of which three still stand _ Wrigley (in
Chicago), Fenway (in Boston) and Tiger Stadium (in Detroit). The
stature of the game became very important.''
</P>
<P>
   And now 1908 has given us a new baseball book that falls just
short of a classic. I say that only because at times the narrative
drive isn't as strong as it should be; digressions or statistics
sometimes intrude.
</P>
<P>
   But those are quibbles. Anderson has scored three runs with More
Than Merkle: He has vindicated Fred Merkle, a player whose
respectable career has been overshadowed by one play. He has told a
tale worth telling: how the Chicago Cubs edged the Giants in a
thriller season. And best, he has brought the Dead Ball Era back to
life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
