<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 10:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0002 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-BOOKS-BASEBALL-KANSAS     03-28 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-BASEBALL-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WRITES OF SPRING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN MARK EBERHART  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They do it every spring: They swagger out into the soft
sunshine, cocky, prideful, ready to play the game.
</P>
<P>
   But we're talking about authors and publishers, not baseball
players. The baseball book has become as much a rite of spring as
Opening Day itself.
</P>
<P>
   And we keep buying them. And why not? Just as each new season
brings hope (even to Royals fans), it brings a crop of writers,
some veterans and some rookies, who try to leave their literary
imprint on the game. One of those rookies this year is Leawood's
own David W. Anderson; the review of Anderson's fabulous More Than
Merkle starts on today's Arts cover.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball isn't really ``the national pastime'' anymore; the
audience for football is bigger now. But a spring without baseball
or the books it inspires would still be unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   Here's this year's lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Retro Redbirds
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake: I am a Royals fan and have been since my family
left St. Louis in 1970. But I grew up in St. Louis with the great
Cardinal teams of the 1960s; they played in three World Series and
won two, including a 1964 triumph over those damned Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Bob Gibson, base thief Lou Brock and outfielder Curt
Flood were my boyhood heroes, and they're all here, with plenty of
other company, in Peter Golenbock's The Spirit of St. Louis: A
History of the St. Louis Cardinals and Browns (651 pages;
Spike//Avon Books; $27.50).
</P>
<P>
   The Browns?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, they were St. Louis' other team, a sometimes goofy,
sometimes good American League franchise that eventually became the
Baltimore Orioles. Owner Bill Veeck Jr. was an oddball who once
promoted the team by having a midget come to bat.
</P>
<P>
   In 1944, though, the Browns actually sampled glory for once,
winning the American League pennant and advancing to the World
Series. Their opponent?
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   The Browns lost, of course; the Cards were mighty in 1944. For
that one year, though, St. Louis owned baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Golenbock's book is as beefy as Mark McGwire's forearms, and he
does a fine job of balancing his story between the legendary
Cardinals and the usually woeful Browns. This is a great read.
</P>
<P>
   Goosed
</P>
<P>
   ``Between the massive home run Brett hit off me in the 1980
playoffs ... and the Pine Tar Incident in 1983, George and I became
linked in baseball history.''
</P>
<P>
   That's former Yankees pitcher Goose Gossage, who tormented
Royals fans in the late 1970s and early '80s with his hated,
mustachioed face and, worse yet, that ray-gun heater that other
people modestly referred to as a fastball. And Gossage blathers on
a lot more in The Goose Is Loose (342 pages; Ballantine Books;
$25).
</P>
<P>
   More on his competition with Royals hitter George Brett: ``(W)e
had many duels during the bitter years of the Yankees-Royals
rivalry, and I probably won the vast majority. Pitchers always do.
... (But) let's give the devil his due: I never saw Ted Williams
hit, but I can't imagine that he could have been any better than
George Brett.''
</P>
<P>
   Gee, thanks, Goose. You know, all those years ago, KC fans
wished Gossage would just stop pitching. Now I wish he would just
stop ...
</P>
<P>
   You get the idea.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, I grudgingly concede that Gossage's
``autobiography'' is interesting. But then it should be; he had
Russ Pate help him write it.
</P>
<P>
   Guess Goose's pen isn't as mighty as his fastball.
</P>
<P>
   Or his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Base hits
</P>
<P>
   - Red Smith on Baseball: The Game's Greatest Writer on the
Game's Greatest Years, by Red Smith (363 pages; Ivan R. Dee;
$24.95). Nobody, but nobody, wrote or writes about baseball like
the great Walter W. ``Red'' Smith. He has won some of journalism's
most prestigious awards, including the Polk and the Pulitzer. This
book collects writings from 1941 to 1981, from Jackie Robinson's
breaking the color barrier to Bobby Thomson's ``Shot Heard 'Round
the World'' and modern players like Carl Yastrzemski.
</P>
<P>
   - The Sporting News Selects 50 Greatest Sluggers, by Tony
DeMarco (175 pages; The Sporting News; $29.95). I'm sorry, but this
thing looks like a Time-Life book about fixing your sink. Still,
it's not bad. The author has the sense to put the mighty Babe Ruth
at No. 1, right above that upstart McGwire. There are no Royals on
the list, but then George was always more a triple threat than a
dinger man. Come to think of it, when did the Royals ever have a
home-run king? Steve Balboni? Puh-leeze.
</P>
<P>
   - Batter Up! The Ultimate Baseball Scorekeeper, by Benjamin Eli
Smith (128 pages; Chronicle Books; $14.95). Take this one to the
ballpark with you. It has information to help fans learn how to
score a game, as well as scorecards and even a pouch on the back
cover to hold your pencils.
</P>
<P>
   - Baseball's Most Wanted: The Top 10 Book of the National
Pastime's Outrageous Offenders, Lucky Bounces, and Other Oddities,
by Floyd Connor (388 pages; Brassey's; $12.95). A title that long
should be self-explanatory. It is. Weird book. Good book, though.
By the way, did you know that Ken Brett, George's brother, pitched
for 10 teams between 1971 and 1980? You do now.
</P>
<P>
   - The National Game: Baseball and American Culture, by John P.
Rossi (243 pages; Ivan R. Dee; $25). There are plenty of histories
of baseball; Rossi strives for something different: a look at how
the game has affected American culture and vice versa. Ambitious
and worth an afternoon's perusing if there's not a home game on the
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Other voices, other leagues
</P>
<P>
   Josh Gibson: A Life in the Negro Leagues, by William Brashler
(200 pages; Ivan R. Dee; $14.95). In the first half of the 20th
century, Major League Baseball had the power to bar black players
from ``the big show,'' but MLB didn't have the power to keep black
players from being great. Gibson was known as ``the black Babe
Ruth.'' Unfortunately, he died at 35 in 1947, just as Jackie
Robinson broke that color barrier.
</P>
<P>
   - Joy in Mudville: A Little League Memoir, by Greg Mitchell (256
pages; Pocket Books; $19.95). Mitchell is one of those tireless (or
maybe crazy) dads who has spent time managing kids' ball teams. The
multiple roles as parent, coach and sports enthusiast sometimes
clash in gut-wrenching ways. His memoir covers two years in the
trenches _ er, dugouts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-00 1041EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
