<DOCNO> NYT20000328.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 10:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0008 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-POL-LATENIGHT-JOKES29     03-28 1515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-LATENIGHT-JOKES29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The mocking of the Presidency, 2000
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Letterman calls George W. Bush ``a colossal boob.'' Jay
Leno makes fun of the number of executions under Bush's watch. And
Bill Maher insists he hates both Al ``Bore'' and George W.
``Gush.''
</P>
<P>
   Late-night political humor is rampant this campaign season. It
may have been funnier and more exciting during the primaries,
before Bush and Gore wrapped up their respective party nominations,
but it likely will get meaner and nastier as we head toward the
general election.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Bush needed a kidney transplant, he could call Quayle and
not even have to do a blood test.'' Bill Maher on ABC's
``Politically Incorrect''
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's how stiff this guy Gore is: While campaigning in New
York City, he went up to Grant's Tom-- . They wouldn't let him
out.'' David Letterman on CBS's ``The Late Show''
</P>
<P>
   Political humor has been around as long as there have been
politicians, and late-night TV has been a major player since Steve
Allen hosted ``The Tonight Show.'' But over the years, the
monologists have multiplied. Besides Leno and Letterman, we now
have Conan O'Brien, Craig Kilborn, Bill Maher and cable's Jon
Stewart. Maher's entire show is devoted to ripping politicians in a
round-table forum.
</P>
<P>
   Not only are there more late-night political jokesters today,
but they are having more of an impact. According to a recent Pew
Research Center poll, nearly half of the under-30 crowd get most of
their campaign information from late-night talk shows, with 37
percent citing ``Saturday Night Live'' and ``Politically
Incorrect'' as major sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's new in contemporary political humor is how the media,
especially television, has made politicians into celebrities and
how many people get more of their political news from Letterman,
Leno and other humor shows than from the mainstream news
services,'' says David Schultz, professor of political science at
Hamline University in St. Paul, Minn., and author of the
just-published ``It's Show Time! Media, Politics and Popular
Culture.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result, the impression people have of politicians is
framed by the jokes and less by a stance on the issues. Thus, Bush
is seen as an intellectual lightweight and a fratboy, and Gore is
seen as wooden. And because they are treated more like movie stars,
politics is now thought of as entertainment, campaigning is like
acting and politicians are like actors. This clearly leads to a
loss of substance in politics.''
</P>
<P>
   As the campaign shifts into high gear in the fall, we can expect
the arrows to bear more poison. So far, Bush has taken the worst
drubbing, perhaps because he's fresh meat, while Gore has been vice
president for eight years. And perhaps it's just easier to poke fun
at someone portrayed as dumb than someone portrayed as boring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore proposed that he and Bush drop all TV ads for the
remainder of the race and instead hold twice weekly debates on the
issues. Bush responded, `Any time, any place _ as long as you give
me directions.''' Colin Quinn on ``Saturday Night Live.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore e-mailed Bush and then Bush tried to e-mail him back, but
he couldn't get the stamps to stick to the screen.'' Bill Maher on
``Politically Incorrect.''
</P>
<P>
   Night-owl jokesters have found soft spots they like to hit Bush
on _ his alleged stupidity, his youthful drinking days and the high
number of executions since he became governor. Maher has even gone
after Bush's wildly popular mother, claiming Barbara Bush is ``not
a nice old lady ... she's after vengeance.''
</P>
<P>
   The humor seems harsher than previous political seasons but
sedate compared to the field day comics had during Monicagate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton is the gift that keeps on giving,'' says Mark Russell,
the Washington-based humorist who has been lampooning politicians
since the '50s and is celebrating his 25th anniversary of comedy
specials on PBS.
</P>
<P>
   Russell concedes he's torn about the legacy of the Clinton mess.
On the one hand, the comedian considers himself patriotic and hated
to see his country go through such embarrassment. On the other
hand, the Clinton White House provided endless fodder for political
humorists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The impact of the Clinton scandals is we've really lost all
respect for the presidency and the city of Washington,'' Russell
says. ``You mention the Oval Office, and people go, 'Oh, yeah. We
know what goes on in there.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Gone are the days when political jokes were subtle or even
slightly sophisticated _ at least on late-night TV. The high-water
mark of modern political scandals was Watergate, when the
government seemed to collapse and Richard Nixon, sweat pouring off
his face, insisted he wasn't a crook. The way Johnny Carson handled
it, with gentle zingers and an impish lift of the eyebrow, is a far
cry from Leno relishing the X-rated details of the Clinton-Lewinsky
affair.
</P>
<P>
   The mark of Clinton scandal humor was extreme vulgarity, and the
late-night hosts wallowed in every juicy tidbit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those details coming out about what happened in the Oval
Office were vulgar,'' concedes Gerard Mulligan, who has written for
Letterman since 1977. ``But we didn't make any of that up. The
vulgarity didn't come from people putting a spin on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mulligan says the digs on politicos this season aren't any
better or worse than they were 20 years ago, but he thinks the
humor is more personal and cynical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the assumption is every candidate has some kind of sexual
scandal in the closet,'' Mulligan says. ``Everybody assumes it's
just a matter of time before photos of George W., naked and dancing
on a bar, show up. Some cynicism is healthy, but it also can be
corrosive. If you assume everything is a lie, that is bad.''
</P>
<P>
   So, don't these popular shows feel some responsibility for
contributing to the cynicism and the general lack of respect for
our politicians?
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we do contribute to the disrespect, but not to the
extent that the politicians do,'' Mulligan says. ``They shoot
themselves in the foot all the time. I guess if there's a constant
drumbeat that George W. is stupid, that gradually becomes accepted.
But as far as we're concerned, he's obviously not stupid. This is
our cartoon version of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, the comics do consider some areas off limits.
For the most part, the families of the candidates are left alone,
especially children. ``Saturday Night Live'' overstepped its
boundaries a few years ago and did a skit about Chelsea Clinton.
The executive producer later apologized to the first family. As a
rule, network censors don't get involved in late-night monologues,
so the weeknight comics have a good deal of freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tend to make jokes about the person who does the most
colorful stuff,'' Mulligan says. ``There's no ideological
balancing. If there were, we'd have to do two percent of our jokes
about Alan Keyes. It would be insane.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all political humorists are impressed with the late-night
comics. Much of the lampooning is seen as crude and superficial.
</P>
<P>
   ``These flat-out statements, like `George Bush is a colossal
boob,' aren't terribly rewarding,'' says Russell, whose heroes are
Mort Sahl, Fred Allen and Mark Twain. ``Humor is supposed to be
subtle, the turning of a phrase. But late-night people are talking
to a bigger audience, so it has to be a little less subtle ... I
know Leno and Letterman are intelligent guys, and they're smart
enough to know they have to talk down to their audience.''
</P>
<P>
   The razor-sharp barbs reached their peak during primary season
but have fallen into a temporary lull as Gore and Bush gear up for
the general election. During the primaries, comedians had more
variety to work with, tackling independent-minded bulldog John
McCain and sleepy-looking intellectual Bill Bradley. Now that's
over. And the good ol' days with Ross Perot clucking, ``Now that's
just sad '' are but a memory. With two alleged dullards (one of
them a party-boy-turned-alleged-dullard) left now, how much fun can
be had?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, boring and stiff is good!'' Russell says. ``But Bob Jones
v-- . Buddha? They almost cancel each other out. By the time we
reach the general election, I'm usually sick of it. This was a very
lively primary season, especially with McCain in there. I hated to
see it end. We're going to have to contrive excitement for the next
eight months and endure the travesty of the conventions, where
there's never any suspense. Our only hope is Pat Robertson.
Whenever Robertson gets in there, it's good material.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bush and Gore go at it during the 2000 election season,
Leno, Letterman and Maher will, too. We may laugh at all of them
from time to time, a guilty pleasure at best. Cynicism on the tube
and in the nation is rampant, and late-night TV is feeding the
beast.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Holloway writes for the Austin American-Statesman. She can
be reached at dholloway(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
