<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 10:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0009 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-BLACKS-TAXIS-COMMENT2     03-28 1184
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKS-TAXIS-COMMENT29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Race matters, even when asking a simple question
 &HT;    (With illustration and mugshot.)
 &HT;    By Marcus Franklin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The question, by most accounts, is mundane. Unless, of course,
the person posing the query is a black man trying to get to a dance
club in Southeast Washington, D.C., at 1 o'clock in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can I get a cab?'' I asked the man at the front desk of the
downtown hotel where I stayed Valentine's Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be very difficult,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   I'll flag one myself, I told the man. He looked at me as if I
were a fool.
</P>
<P>
   What a fool I was.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't know about the recent rash of robberies, assaults and a
murder of D.C. cab drivers. I didn't know the suspects were black
men. At the time, I had no reason to remind myself of one of the
nearly unbearable burdens of being a black man in the United
States: Each black man pays, in ways big and small, for any
misdeeds of the other 16,562,999 black men in this nation.
</P>
<P>
   No black man is exonerated from this socio-political liability.
Actor Danny Glover, who filed a complaint last year with New York
City because taxis whizzed by him, can attest to this fact. Amadou
Diallo could, too, had he survived the hail of bullets fired at him
by four recently acquitted New York police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Ready to brave the winter elements in a black waist-length
leather jacket, a fleece skully of the same color, dark baggy jeans
and a pair of Timberlands, I stepped inside the hotel's revolving
glass door and out into the freezing air.
</P>
<P>
   Unbeknownst to me, D.C. Taxi Cab Commissioner Sandra Seegars,
three weeks earlier, had urged the district's mostly black 6,500
cabbies to pass up ``dangerous-looking'' individuals. Seegars, who
is black and lives in Southeast, later defined
``dangerous-looking'' in The Washington Post as a ``young black guy
with his hat on backwards, shirttail hanging down longer than his
coat, baggy pants down below his underwear and unlaced tennis
shoes. ... Late at night, if I saw young black men dressed in a
slovenly way, I wouldn't pick them up, either. Drivers are afraid
of gangs of young black males. In all my life, I have never seen a
gang of young white males in this city.''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, my pursuit of a cab began in front of the hotel. For
more than two hours, I walked along the four major streets
surrounding the hotel. I hailed until my arms ached. I yelled,
``Yo, taxi!'' until my mouth dried and my voice grew raspy. My
resolve to get a cab intensified as I watched a white couple and
then a black woman successfully hail taxis. It no longer mattered
if a cab took me to the club or for a spin around the block. I just
wanted a cab.
</P>
<P>
   Only two cabs stopped for me. A uniformed D.C. police officer,
who happened to be going to a nearby 24-hour drug store, hailed one
of them at my request. The other cabbie stopped after I got
desperate and put my hands together, prayerlike, and extended them
toward oncoming traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Both cabbies demanded to know where I was going before I got in
their cars. Both sped off after I gave them the club's address. I
don't think the cabbies heard any part of the address except
``Southeast,'' which is a largely black section of the District
disproportionately plagued by poverty and black-on-black crime.
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't have been as indignant about the slights had they
been tied exclusively to the cabbies' fear of going to Southeast.
But the more than 100 taxi drivers who passed me up didn't even
know my destination. For all they knew, I was going to the upscale
Georgetown neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I took my last shot at getting a cab. A taxi carrying
three people _ all white, all men _ pulled in front of the drug
store. I jogged toward the cab, careful not to run too fast lest I
induce panic attacks among the emerging passengers and the driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to go to ... Southeast,'' I told the driver as he shook
his head horizontally. He wouldn't even let down his window.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, I don't want to rob you,'' I snapped.
</P>
<P>
   As I walked back to the hotel, I began to wonder: This possibly
cannot be the real nature of God's universe. Would I be justified
if I presuppose I am going to be dragged to my death every time I
see three or more white men in a pickup truck? Would it be rational
of me to think I am going to be showered with bullets (possibly 41
of them) every time I see four white police officers because they
may believe I'm a rapist and that the keys or wallet I reach for is
a gun?
</P>
<P>
   At the hotel, another concierge, Kwaku, called me a cab. He
wasn't optimistic. The dispatcher wanted to know where I was going
and, upon learning the destination was in Southeast, wanted
assurance from hotel management that I was a guest. ``This is
crazy,'' I screamed at the men. ``These cab drivers are men of
color, and they're all afraid to pick up a black man. Their
mind-set is no different from a racist white person's.''
</P>
<P>
   Questions spewed from my anger. ``Why am I being discriminated
against because of the actions of some man I don't even know?'' I
asked. ``Why is the entire Southeast community being redlined? I
had nothing to do with any of those robberies or assaults or the
murder, nor did most of the people who live in Southeast.
Nothing!''
</P>
<P>
   The men shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   The cab never showed.
</P>
<P>
   As I headed to my room, I considered my first night in D.C.
</P>
<P>
   For sure, my intense hunt for a cab nearly forced me to buckle
over at times; the experience compelled me to laugh aloud as
strangers gawked at me. The tragicomic ordeal angered me to the
point of wanting to do harm to the cabbies or their cabs because
they, black men, had bought into the stereotypes by associating
blackness with criminality.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, blacks accounted for more than half the robbery arrests in
America in 1998, as well as most of the murder arrests that year,
according to FBI statistics.
</P>
<P>
   But only one-half of 1 percent of all U.S. blacks were arrested
on charges of committing a violent crime in 1998. Moreover, nearly
seven out of every 10 people arrested for any crime in 1998 were
white, according to the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   As the elevator climbed the shaft, I remembered Toni Morrison's
simple but profound take on the absurdity of race as defined by
so-called skin color:
</P>
<P>
   ``When I know that you're white, I only know stereotypical
information about you,'' Morrison told PBS's Charlie Rose in 1998.
``I only know assumptions about you. That's like knowing you have
two ears on your head. But as an individual, I don't know anything
about you.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, it doesn't mean that race doesn't matter; it matters
a great deal. But that's because we've made it matter. We have made
it matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, it can matter even when a black man asks a question as
simple as, Can I get a cab?
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Franklin is a reporter for the Dayton Daily News. The
Detroit native joined the newspaper in 1997. You can e-mail him at
marcusfranklin(at)coxohio.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
