<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0329-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Story of one's life toldin automobiles
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ ``A purple Cadillac is the last thing I've
ever dreamed of owning,'' Gail assures me in her recent e-mail,
``but lately I've been having these funny daydreams.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry about it,'' I answer, ``it's a mild delusion
brought on by Social Security anxiety.'' I punch SEND and get back
to work _ but not for long. Another message from Gail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I blame the whole thing on going out for chowder with Arthur.
He got to droning on about some client of his and pretty soon my
focus wandered. Suddenly, there I was in a purple Cadillac.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see myself stepping out of the house one morning on my way
to pick up another load of manure for the vegetable garden only to
discover my green SUV (which remarkably resembles Toad of Toad
Hall) has turned into a lavishly-finned, iridescent land yacht.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly, I've forgotten all about carrots and kale, and I'm
cruising off into the sunset in this purple atrocity, with a long
scarf like the one that strangled Isadora Duncan billowing behind
me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please send help, or Tom Cruise _ whichever you can manage.
Love, G.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cruise is too young for you. Love, E.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Who cares,'' she answers. ``It's my daydream. Okay, how about
Robert Redford? Love, G.''
</P>
<P>
   For almost a week, I heard nothing more about movie stars or
Cadillacs. But this morning she writes that she's figured out her
recent pre-occupation with wheeled things. ``The entire story of
one's life can be told in automobiles. Did you ever think of
that?'' Admittedly, I hadn't, but as I read on, I could see what
she meant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first car in my life was a used Rambler that my
father-in-law bought for us while my husband was still in college.
It was big enough to hold the portable crib in the back seat when
we drove up to Maine in a blizzard for a grad school interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the second baby came, he gave us a tan VW beetle. It was
brand new but it had no radio _ $1500 in the late '60s. That's the
car we were driving on our way to Penn State when I jokingly
suggested since we had a Bachelor's baby, and a Master's baby,
maybe we should have a Ph.D. baby. My husband flinched and there
was no more talking the rest of the drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the third baby came a yellow Subaru station wagon. It had
a radio. I wrecked it while my husband was at a turkey convention
in Houston. He got it in the divorce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next came the blue Dodge station wagon that lasted long enough
to become my son's first car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then Aunt Alice's inheritance kicked in and I went a little
nuts. Bought two cars _ a navy-blue Toyota sedan and a TR-7. They
lasted about as long as my second marriage. Tourists in a truck
totaled the Toyota so I got rid of the wreck and the husband at the
same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traded the TR-7 for a white hatch-back Toyota that I kept
until 1990, when I swapped it for a wine-red station wagon that
hauled yard debris, recycling, kids, dogs, cats, and groceries for
nine years and 160,000 miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one point there were four Toyotas, all in varying stages of
decrepitude lining the driveway. Then one day they were gone _
first away to college and then just away. One to Florida, one to
California, and another to Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toad and I are alone now. He takes me to the gym (not as often
as he should), and occasionally to a nearby high school where I sub
(not as often as I'd like). He takes me to the Post Office with
boxes of storybooks for the grandchildren, but he knows little of
the life I've lived _ carpooling, or rushing three kids with sore
throats to the doctor. He's never even had ice cream smeared on his
back seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Understandably,'' my old friend philosophizes, ``my
transportation has shifted with my priorities, but WHAT does the
purple Cadillac mean? Love, G.''
</P>
<P>
   I send the only answer I can. ``Chowder bad. Don't eat there any
more. Love, E.''
</P>
<P>
   (Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
