<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Big-bucks candidates could foot their own security tabs
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ George W. Bush has spent a third of an elementary
school running for president. By November, he'll have consumed a
whole school, from bike racks to soap dispensers.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Department of Public Safety reported that Texas spent
$1.3 million last year protecting presidential candidate Bush, four
times what it spent the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   It's only money, unless we consider what it can purchase. The
going rate for an elementary school is about $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   A cost we must bear? Security is serious business. Candidate Al
Gore gets taxpayer-footed security, too. Do Bush and Gore really
need our help? No.
</P>
<P>
   Are they fully capable of rustling up protection for themselves?
Yes.
</P>
<P>
   Have they both used millions of dollars in soft-money
contributions to obliterate spending controls on presidential
campaigns? Yes.
</P>
<P>
   What do they intend to do with those funds? Enlighten voters?
Draw out the finer points of their plans for America? No. They'll
buy air time to show each other on television in unflattering
poses.
</P>
<P>
   There's got to be a better use for this money. The security we
now provide could be one.
</P>
<P>
   Until we as a nation come to a grips with the excesses of
campaign finance, here's what we do with some of the excess: No
more taxpayer-financed security for office-holders running for
president. Pay your own way, boys.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, the campaign-finance nut is a tough one to crack.
Both major parties are as dependent as dialysis patients. They not
only have sold their souls, they've donated their kidneys.
</P>
<P>
   Since it appears we're a long way from real campaign finance
reform, we as taxpayers should tell Bush and Gore to relieve us of
campaign security detail. They're so good at raising donations, let
them buy their own goons. They'd come cheap.
</P>
<P>
   Consider it privatizing away a government service, something
near to Bush's heart. The candidates could borrow from the Rolling
Stones, who in 1969 hired Hell's Angels for security at a concert
at California's Altamont Speedway. They were effective. A
concert-goer got fatally stomped, yes. But the Stones were safe
</P>
<P>
   The opportunities of privatized security for the candidates are
numerous. Bush, for instance, could tell the National Rifle
Association that its protection is needed against Gore and the
anti-gunners. True, unlicensed NRA bodyguards wouldn't be able to
pack pistols in every state like they can in Texas and Florida. But
you can fake a lot of liberals out with an NRA patch and a Tootsie
Roll Pop in your pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Bush could rely on Big Oil or Big Tobacco to fulfill his every
security fantasy. The latter is always making dreams come true.
Last year tobacco political action committees gave $2.2 million to
Republicans _ for off-year elections.
</P>
<P>
   As for Big Oil, Bush has his personal reservoir. It's the $5
billion holdings of Fort Worth drilling giant Richard Rainwater,
whom the Houston Chronicle calls ``largely responsible for Bush's
wealth.''
</P>
<P>
   Lest one worry that this approach would give an unnecessary
advantage to Republicans, consider the opportunities for the
Democrats. For his bodyguards, Gore could have his choice of
Teamsters with forearms like thunderheads, or animal-rights
activists armed with flasks of calves' blood.
</P>
<P>
   As taxpayers we should accept as our business the protection of
office-holders as they fulfill their official duties. But when they
go campaigning, they ought to be able to handle the load _ at least
until they face up to the legalized corruption of campaign
financing and accept real restraints.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, why should Texas spend elementary schools to get
George Bush elected?
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
