r k BC-KABAT-COLUMN29-COX     03-28 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KABAT-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: The lines are blurring
 &HT;    By Vicki Marsh Kabat
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ I do not live in a 20/20 world. I haven't for
quite a long time.
</P>
<P>
   My lifelong struggle with vision problems is my cross to carry,
I suppose. Certainly it could be much worse. Nothing seems worse,
though, when you're 7 and have to wear glasses.
</P>
<P>
   That was just the beginning of my eyewear nightmares. Fashion
glasses did not exist in those days. They basically took old-lady
glasses and scaled them down for little girls. I rebelled at one
point and chose stark black frames, a jarring contrast to my fair
color. My mother hated them. I was making a statement, although I
have no idea what.
</P>
<P>
   I am, then, quite used to not seeing things clearly. As I have
grown older, though, there are many more things that I don't see
clearly: newspapers and telephone directories as well as right and
wrong, truth and untruth. A lot of lines are blurring for me and
bifocals are addressing only a few of them.
</P>
<P>
   A 6-year-old girl is killed by her classmate with a
semiautomatic weapon. And there still are those who declare ``Guns
don't kill, people do.'' I can't see my way clear on that at all.
</P>
<P>
   More than 30 years after Martin Luther King Jr.'s assassination,
hate crimes against people of color still are occuring. I can't see
my way clear on that, either.
</P>
<P>
   One young woman chooses to keep her baby and another chooses to
abort it. And while there are plenty of folks who claim 20/20
vision on that issue, I still can't see my way clear on it.
</P>
<P>
   One country is tired of dealing with a race of people and so it
decides to ``cleanse'' itself by murdering thousands upon thousands
of people. Did we really think that kind of atrocity ended with
Hitler? I definitely can't see my way clear on that.
</P>
<P>
   A mother wakes up one morning in her one-room apartment and
discovers that her husband has taken all their savings and left. As
she picks up her crying baby and tends to her hungry toddler, she
wonders ``What will we do? Where will we go when I can't pay this
month's rent?'' I can't see my way clear on that one.
</P>
<P>
   Aging has peculiar properties. I used to see everything so
clearly. Every issue had a definitive answer. When you're 7 years
old, these things are right: being kind, sharing, helping others,
obeying your elders, showing respect. These things are wrong:
lying, stealing, hurting others, cheating, calling names, hitting.
We lived by a simple code of conduct: Do nothing that harms
yourself or others.
</P>
<P>
   There is a lot of blurring, though, in that clear-cut world.
People aren't playing by the same rules I learned when I was young.
A lot of people aren't playing by any rules at all, it seems.
</P>
<P>
   A recent story in Newsweek addresses that point. It states that
in our legal system, children have ``the requisite moral sense _
the ability to tell right from wrong'' by age 7 to 15, depending on
the state. The Roman Catholic Church pins it to the ``age of
reason'' _ 7. A psychologist is quoted as saying it's closer to 12
and perhaps up to 15. And, as the story concludes, sometimes that
sense of morality fails to develop at all.
</P>
<P>
   So I find myself living in an increasingly blurry world. I no
longer can see the third line on the eye chart no matter how many
lens options the ophthalmologist gives me.
</P>
<P>
   On certain days, though, like when I read about a 6-year-old
shooting another 6-year-old, I am oddly grateful for my blurred
vision. There is much in this world I cannot, and no longer want
to, see clearly.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Marsh Kabat writes for the Waco Tribune-Herald. She can be
reached online at VMKabat(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
