<DOCNO> NYT20000328.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 11:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0014 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-MONEYTALK29-COX     03-28 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    When it comes to investing, women do it better
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Women live longer and have less money than men, so
they need to be better investors.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that women are better investors.
</P>
<P>
   Recent surveys support both those propositions, and financial
counselors confirm it from their day-to-day experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women invest as though their lives depend on it, and they
do,'' said Deena B. Katz, a certified financial planner in Coral
Gables, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   She pointed out that the average age of widowhood is 56 and that
a high percentage of marriages, first and second, end in divorce.
``If you are not taking care of yourself now, you probably will
be,'' said Katz, who is writing a book on the subject. ``You really
can't afford to make a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I see lots of young women investing now,'' added Elaine D.
Mobley, a Sautee resident who is 65, retired and divorced. ``They
are not marrying so early, and many of them are better educated
now. They see they have to look after their own welfare.''
</P>
<P>
   Mobley began managing her family finances more than 30 years
ago, following an early retirement. ``I had no pension, and I knew
we had to prepare for our future,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A Gallup Poll released last week reflects increasing levels of
financial apprehension among women. Asked to name the biggest
challenge in their daily lives, 26 percent said money mattters.
Less common worries included family, 22 percent; health, 15
percent; time and stress, 14 percent; or career issues, 8 percent.
Education and equality got the remaining votes.
</P>
<P>
   There are good reasons for those worries. Women live longer,
receive lower salaries and get less money from pensions and Social
Security. They also suffer more financial damage following divorce,
and older women tend to know less about money management.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, women have certainly been successful is
managing their investments. That shows in the returns of single-sex
investment clubs surveyed by the National Association of Investors
Corp. Over the clubs' lifetimes, women-only clubs racked up average
annual returns of 23.8 percent. Men's clubs averaged noticeably
less, 19.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A massive study of trading among 35,000 households comes to a
similar conclusion. The authors, economists Terrance Odean and Brad
M. Barber of the University of California at Davis, found that men
buy and sell stocks much more frequently than women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men lower their returns more than women because they trade
more, not because their security selections are worse,'' the
economists reported.
</P>
<P>
   Experts have pointed out a number of reasons that women become
better investors than men. Each of them could be a lesson for the
rest of us _ males and beginners of both genders.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hot tips. Women are cool to them. ``I think maybe this
reflects the makeup of women, their thinking process,'' said Katz.
``Women are looking for something good and solid that they can
depend on. They are usually very goal-oriented: I'm making this
investment for my retirement or for raising my children. Men are
likely to buy a story.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Research. Mobley said she reads investment publications
weekly, to keep up with the companies she already owns as well as
to look for new investments.
</P>
<P>
   Women also are more willing to call on experts and to grill
them, said Katz. ``Society doesn't expect them to know anything, so
they can't be too embarrassed to ask questions. Men are expected to
know financial things, and they feel they can embarrass
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Patience. The California study disclosed that women sell and
replace 53 percent of their investments each year. That may sound
high, but men turned over 77 percent.
</P>
<P>
   High turnover increases transaction costs, and it reflects an
unhealthy concern with short-term results. ``The people who have
done well are those who can buy and hold on for a number of
years,'' said Ellen O. Keller, a certified financial planner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in the long-term philosophy,'' said Mobley, who has
achieved annual total returns of better than 15 percent over her
decades of investing. She tends to maintain her confidence in
stocks she has selected, even when the companies have bad years.
``Companies are like human beings: Our lives are not always happy
and easy and great, and companies are the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Price consciousness. ``Women are careful shoppers,'' said Mark
Robertson, a spokesman for the National Association of Investors
Corp. ``They are the ones buying Cisco when it drops down to $18 a
share, rather than when it's $80.''
</P>
<P>
   A related factor is an awareness of the cost of investing.
Mobley canned her first stockbroker. ``I realized this guy was
churning my accounts, and I fired him real fast,'' she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   _ Diversification. It's a basic principle for successful
investors: Distribute your money among different kinds of
investments, and you lower your risk. ``Women like the idea of
spreading it around,'' Katz observed. ``Men may like to take more
of a risk. They aren't afraid to slap it all into one pot.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Rational decision making. Women are less likely to buy and
sell on whims or to let their judgment be clouded by comparing
their returns with those of other people, according to Katz. ``It
all revolves around the fact that women are more likely to be
goal-oriented,'' she said. ``They don't have pride in their
investments, other than that they have been able to succeed in
their goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's good advice,'' she added. ``It keeps you from buying
and selling on impulse if you know where you're going and you know
you've got to make it work.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
