<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sport Trac creates its own niche
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Just when it seemed automakers had filled every
available niche in the pickup and sport utility vehicle classes,
here comes Ford with exactly what you didn't know you needed: the
half-SUV, half-truck Explorer Sport Trac.
</P>
<P>
   It's got the cabin of a Ford Explorer and a truncated cargo
cage. Its direct ancestors include the Ranchero, trotted out by
Ford in the late '60s to compete with Chevrolet's equally sleek El
Camino.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, Ford is early on challenging the hybrid
vehicles coming from other manufacturers, including Subaru. The
acronym, obviously, is SUT, for sport-utility truck.
</P>
<P>
   The base price is $23,050 in two-wheel mode, plus options, which
can include a dash-mounted six-disc CD changer, power driver's
seat, overhead console with compass and temperature display,
running boards, leather interior and a tonneau cover for the
4.2-foot cargo area. The only engine initially available is a
4.0-liter V-6 rated at 205 horsepower and 240 pounds-feet of
torque. The basic transmission is an automatic five-speed that, in
the $25,820 four-wheel-drive version, can be switched anytime from
two-wheel drive to four-wheel drive with high- or low-range
capability.
</P>
<P>
   The Sport Trac, about 16 feet long with seating for five, drives
and rides like the Explorer on which it's based, rather than, say,
the F-150 pickup. The interior, too, is Explorer-like,
distinguished by white-face gauges and _ this is a gee-whiz item _
a power rear window. So while the Sport Trac won't pass the pickup
cargo test of taking a standard size sheet of plywood, it will take
skis, if you don't mind running them into the cabin.
</P>
<P>
   Other wrinkles include a removable soft bag akin to a backpack
in lieu of a center console and the Sport Trac's all-plastic bed,
intended to resist the dings and dents that come with hauling loads
in a pickup.
</P>
<P>
   To its credit, Ford has done a good job of integrating the
disparate elements of the Sport Trac. The sculpted body panels
cleanly link the cabin and cargo bed, and the optional plastic
running boards are more than decorative because there's a step-up
of nearly 2 feet to the cabin.
</P>
<P>
   Once there, it's easy enough to think you're tooling along in an
Explorer. It's only when you look over your shoulder that you
realize there's a pickup rear _ of sorts _ behind you.
</P>
<P>
   Then it's only natural to think the Sport Trac, perhaps
redundant in view of other Ford offerings, could represent a useful
and logical evolution toward multipurpose vehicles that fill
general needs as well as niches.
</P>
<P>
   FORD EXPLORER SPORT TRAC
</P>
<P>
   Test vehicle: 2001 Ford Explorer two-wheel drive Sport Trac
</P>
<P>
   Base price: $23,050 (four-wheel drive: $25,820)
</P>
<P>
   Drivetrain: 4.0-liter V-6 engine (205 horsepower), five-speed
automatic transmission
</P>
<P>
   Safety features: dual air bags, height-adjustable shoulder
belts, power anti-lock brakes
</P>
<P>
   EPA figures: 15 mpg premium unleaded city, 19 mpg highway
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
