<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMBECK-PAPERS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Erma Bombeck's papers given to her alma mater
 &HT;    By Laura Dempsey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ From all appearances, the late humor columnist
Erma Bombeck kept just about everything, and the University of
Dayton is ready to give it all a new, permanent, climate-controlled
home.
</P>
<P>
   Erma Bombeck, who died in 1996 of a kidney disease, left her
papers _ original manuscripts, correspondence, photographs, awards
and the like _ to the University of Dayton, where she was a member
of the 1949 graduating class.
</P>
<P>
   A sneak preview of boxes to come arrived about 2 1/2 weeks ago
from Bombeck's Arizona home, where Bill Bombeck has been faced with
the daunting task of organizing his late wife's papers into a state
suitable for their donation to her alma mater.
</P>
<P>
   Kerrie Moore, UD's archivist, is thrilled with what Mr. Bombeck
sent.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I've seen so far, I can't wait to see the rest,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Moore asked for a select sampling of Bombeck memorabilia to
display during the university's Erma Bombeck Conference on Popular
American Humor this week. Mr. Bombeck responded with cartons of
documents representing the life and times of one of America's
favorite humorists, whose career began in her Centerville garage.
</P>
<P>
   Moore has separated everything into three categories:
professional, personal and philanthropic. There are photos from
Erma's tap-dancing days; snapshots of family vacations; a
hand-written note from George Bush; and copies of the New York
Times list of best sellers, upon which Erma's name appeared with
each book she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   There's a letter from Bennet Cerf, publisher at Random House,
dated Oct. 28, 1952. ``A smart girl like you should sit down and
write a book,'' he advised, telling Bombeck to go ahead and send
him her manuscript when she did.
</P>
<P>
   There's a letter from an editor at a syndicate, dated Jan. 29,
1965, informing Erma that Glenn Thompson, then-editor at the Dayton
Journal Herald, had sent along some of her columns. The syndicate
was impressed. They wanted more.
</P>
<P>
   There's a July 2, 1984, Time cover featuring Erma's
by-then-famous face; copies of books in various translations,
including Japanese; and, weighing in at about 8 pounds, the
original, typed copy of The Grass is Always Greener Over the Septic
Tank.
</P>
<P>
   That original manuscript, typed on carbon paper and tied with
twine, will symbolically represent the entire collection of Erma
Bombeck papers at Friday's lunchtime ceremony, during which Bill
Bombeck will make the presentation to the university.
</P>
<P>
   Moore said Bombeck's papers are a great and welcome addition to
the university archives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone of her fame, and as well-loved in our popular culture,
it really brings a lot of notoriety to the university,'' said
Moore. ``She was a great friend to UD.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the safekeeping of the documents, the UD archives
can be studied by anyone needing information for biographical
purposes or research projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the fun things about archives,'' said Moore,
whose job it will be to organize and cross-reference Bombeck's
papers. ``The research projects people come up with are
fascinating.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked when she thinks she'll have the documents in manageable
shape, Moore laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot possibly answer that question,'' she said. ``It's
going to take a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
