<SLUG> BC-THE-MECHANIC29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Amid rising gas prices, quality fuel remains your best bargain
 &HT;    By Nora Carter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As the escalating price of fuel continues to chisel
its way deeper into our wallets, the natural reaction of many
motorists is to find the cheapest gasoline available.
</P>
<P>
   Six months ago, you may have patronized a ``name brand'' gas
station, but today you are filling your tank with whatever is a few
cents less per gallon. This penny-wise/pound-foolish solution could
end up costing you more in the long run. In spite of its price, I
still adhere to the rule that quality fuel is the best bargain in
the long run.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, all gasoline, no matter where it comes from, must
go through the same process to get it from crude oil source to a
combustible fuel. Further refinement of this fuel produces either
regular or premium gasoline, which is only a rating of the fuel's
ability to resist knock.
</P>
<P>
   Either the refiner or the retailer determines the differences
between the qualities of fuel. Fuel quality depends on the special
chemicals that are added to the base fuel. Additives include
detergents for the control of deposits, corrosion inhibitors and
antioxidants.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say the fictitious Fish Oil Co. is a large refiner and
retailer of gasoline. The gasoline in its storage tanks is
basically the same as the equally fictitious Olive Oil Co. When the
tanker truck fills up with Fish Oil fuel, a special ``won't clog
fuel injectors _ keeps the inside of your engine sparkling clean''
additive package is mixed with the fuel in the truck before it is
delivered to Fish Oil retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Olive Oil distributors use a similar ``clean and healthy
engine'' additive package for their Olive Oil service stations.
</P>
<P>
   Zoom Co. has a large chain of quickie marts/gas stations. It
buys its fuel from the lowest bidder and adds it own ``we guarantee
our gas'' package to the gas it sells. Snake Oil Co., a small
independent specializing in cheap gas and greasy tacos, also buys
the least expensive fuel. However, to keep prices low to the
consumer, this company doesn't use an additive package.
</P>
<P>
   Snake Oil gas is 10 cents a gallon less than Fish or Olive Oil
gas and 5 cents less than Zoom, but that savings will be
short-lived. Without the benefit of the fuel additives, his car,
especially if it is fuel-injected, is more likely to develop the
driveability problems all of those chemicals were designed to
eliminate. Combustion chamber deposits, varnish buildup on fuel
injectors, fuel system component corrosion and PCV valve gook are
the most common.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, when a person is experiencing poor engine performance,
the first question I ask is ``Where are you buying your gas?''
</P>
<P>
   The pat reply I hear is, ``With the money I save in gas, I can
buy those bottles of gas cleaner stuff they sell at auto parts
stores.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. How much should you use, and how often? Excessive use of
these products can damage fuel systems. Not enough, and you're back
in the cheap gas syndrome. If you are a chemical engineer, you may
be able to arrive at the right formula, but I don't want to think
that hard.
</P>
<P>
   Quality gasoline contains an additive package. It is sold at
reputable, high-volume retailers. Their names are too numerous to
mention, but you hear their ads on the radio and TV all of the
time. Some will even supply you with printed information on the
additives and their benefits if you ask.
</P>
<P>
   I know it is tempting to feed your vehicle the lowest-priced gas
you can find, but the consequences could far outweigh the immediate
monetary benefit. Don't take chances with your car's fuel system.
Buy good gas. If you insist on buying cheap gas, invest that money
you save in a good interest-bearing account. The extra cash will be
needed come repair time.
</P>
<P>
   Nora Carter, who has 27 years of experience in the auto repair
industry, writes for Cox News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
