A0025 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-HOUSES-INSULATION29-C     03-28 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSES-INSULATION29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Adding insulation saves on energy bills
 &HT;    By Christine Moran
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKY MOUNT, N.C. _ Look at adding more insulation to a home as
an investment, not as a cost, three contractors agree.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Weaver of W.C. Weaver Insulation summed it up best when he
said, ``We've saved thousands of people thousands of dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   With the rising cost of energy, it makes sense to save money
whenever possible. The problem is, most people don't think about
cutting corners until its too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just like most people don't think about fixing their roof
until it leaks,'' said David Burris, manager of Tri-City
Insulation. ``Most people don't think about fixing their insulation
until they see their utility bill either in the dead of winter or
the middle of summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Prior to 1974, there was no insulation code for homes built in
North Carolina. Most homes built between 1974 and 1980 were
insulated, but not all of them were insulated properly, Burris
said.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 5 percent of Burris' business stems from insulating
older homes. It's just too hard to get behind the walls, underneath
the floorboards and in the ceiling. And, as the difficultly level
increases, so does the price, Burris said.
</P>
<P>
   It's not uncommon for homeowners to insulate their attics,
though. The attic is where most homes experience the greatest
amount of energy loss, up to 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The three most common insulating materials are Fiberglas,
cellulose and rock wool. Fiberglas is made out of sand. Cellulose
is made out of recycled papers. And rock wool, the oldest known
insulation, is made out of melted rock.
</P>
<P>
   Clete Kiper, owner of Spray Tech Insulation in Nashville, Tenn.,
only insulates homes with rock or mineral wool.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all-natural. It doesn't burn. And it has no chemical
additives,'' he said. ``We're really trying to push the health
aspect here.''
</P>
<P>
   Weaver insulates with Fiberglas because of its low cost, high
availability and efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   There are a couple of ways to insulate. Kiper uses the spray
method, in which insulation is funneled from a work truck to inside
the home through a long hose. Air pressure forces the insulation
through the hose, where it's directed to the desired site.
</P>
<P>
   The spray method isn't cheap. Aboard one of Kiper's work trucks
is $80,000 worth of insulating equipment. He prefers the spray
method, he said, because it takes less time and effort than laying
batt.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver and Burris don't have a preference. They spray insulation
and lay batt, depending on the application. Batt comes in preformed
pieces. Insulating contractors cut it down to size to fit into the
appropriate cavities.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the monetary gains, properly insulated homes offer
health benefits and enhance comfort.
</P>
<P>
   Insulation helps keep molds, spores, mildews and carpet mites
from making their way into homes, Kiper said.
</P>
<P>
   It also creates a more uniform temperature throughout the house,
thus increasing comfort.
</P>
<P>
   Burris reminds homeowners that an insulated home is also a
quieter home.
</P>
<P>
   Insulation is something people can add to a house that
eventually will pay them back. In two years, because of the money
they will have saved on utility bills, most homeowners will get
back every dollar they invested in insulation.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of adding insulation depends on the size of the house,
the material used and the method of insulation. Weaver, Burris and
Kiper offer estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
