A0026 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-PSYCHOLOGY-TODAY29-CO     03-28 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PSYCHOLOGY-TODAY29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Looking for ways to keep mind sharp
 &HT;    By Hap LeCrone
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ A great deal of research is being conducted to
establish the variables that enhance and preserve mental sharpness
and acuity. Some have been demonstrated to be more effective than
others, and further research will eventually help establish the
things that are effective as opposed to those that are valueless or
even harmful.
</P>
<P>
   Following is a list of things that at the present time are being
considered for their effectiveness in helping individuals achieve
and maintain mental sharpness:
</P>
<P>
   _ The interaction of certain medications that can produce
confusion and cause memory problems.
</P>
<P>
   _ Estrogen replacement therapy in women, which boosts the
production of certain chemicals essential in effective brain
chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   _ Regular exercise, giving rise to both physical and
psychological benefits.
</P>
<P>
   _ Healthy sleep patterns, both getting enough sleep and the
avoidance of problems such as obstructive sleep apnea.
</P>
<P>
   _ Effective methods of dealing with stress. Some studies are
pointing to the possibility that prolonged stress can actually
cause changes in brain chemistry and therefore brain structure.
</P>
<P>
   _ Avoidance of chronic depression and anxiety. Both of these
emotional problems can definitely impair healthy mental
functioning. Short-term memory is especially sensitive to the
effects of prolonged impaired mood states.
</P>
<P>
   _ Staying mentally stimulated. Although the net effect of
``brain exercises'' is still being studied, working crossword
puzzles, playing games that involve memory exercises, etc., are
considered by some experts to be helpful in retaining mental
sharpness.
</P>
<P>
   _ Eliminating poor indoor ventilation. Some authorities believe
that regular breathing in poorly ventilated work or living areas
can be harmful to brain cells.
</P>
<P>
   _ Herbal derivatives such as Gingko Biloba are promoted as being
effective in opening blood vessels in the brain and aiding in
circulation.
</P>
<P>
   _ Multivitamins are being studied as possible ways to decrease
the rate of aging at the cellular level and thus impacting memory
functions.
</P>
<P>
   _ Decrease the ingestion of food or beverages prepared in
aluminum cookware.
</P>
<P>
   _ Provide better protection for children and adults
participating in athletic events where head trauma is frequent. For
example, some experts caution about the potential damage from
frequent ``headers'' in soccer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Educate parents about the potential damage done to infants
when shaking or rapidly changing head position.
</P>
<P>
   Further research will assist in determining the relative
importance of each of these variables in attaining and maintaining
mental sharpness and acuity.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Hap LeCrone is a Waco clinical psychologist. His column
appears Sunday in the Waco Tribune-Herald. If you have questions or
topics you would like Dr. LeCrone to discuss, write him 4555 Lake
Shore Drive, Waco, TX 76710 or e-mail him at hlecrone(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
