<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 11:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0028 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-R-SOFT-MONEY-REVIEW-N     03-28 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-SOFT-MONEY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HARD BUSINESS OF SOFT MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By JILL ABRAMSON   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``They call us the fathers of soft money,'' Bob
Farmer says, and he's not preening. Neither is Bob Mosbacher, the
other hangdog dad.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Farmer, the top money man for Michael Dukakis and the
Democratic Party, and Mosbacher, finance chairman for George Bush
and the Republicans, were the kings of campaign fund-raising. More
than that, they earned a place in political history by starting the
first national programs to raise soft money, the large,
unrestricted gifts to the two parties by wealthy individuals,
corporations and labor unions.
</P>
<P>
   Both of them have lived to feel some regret over their fiscal
ingenuity (though not, it must be said, the victories it
contributed to). Today, Farmer says it's high time Washington
passed campaign finance reform legislation. ``Obviously, money in
politics is totally out of control,'' he says. Mosbacher agrees
that ``it's gotten totally out of hand.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's about to get worse, predicts Jeffrey Birnbaum, author
of ``The Money Men'' (Crown Books), a forthcoming book about
political fund raising. ``There will be far more soft money than
ever before,'' he says. Experts on campaign finance agree, some
estimating that during the 2000 elections the two parties could
collect as much as $500 million in soft money contributions. That's
up from $262 million four years ago, when there were widespread
fund-raising abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Birnbaum says that the Clinton-Gore money team has taken soft
money to a new level. ``At one time in the Democratic Party, it was
time to celebrate if they got a $50,000 check,'' he says. ``Now a
host of wealthy Democrats are expected to fork over $100,000 or
more every year.'' The Republicans, Birnbaum adds, ``are hungry for
victory, having been out of the White House for eight long years.''
More than 50 wealthy Republicans have joined the Regents, which
costs them $250,000 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Watching from the sidelines, Farmer and Mosbacher sound a little
like those physicists who came to regret having invented nuclear
weapons, which set off the arms race.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1988, Farmer says, he feared that the Republicans, who
held the White House, would raise so much money they would swamp
the Democrats. So he came up with the idea of asking wealthy
supporters to write $100,000 checks to the Democratic Party. They
got a fancy name, the Democratic Trustees, and although the money
they gave went into party coffers, most of it was spent to help the
Democratic ticket.
</P>
<P>
   When he learned about the Democrats' program, Mosbacher says, he
worried about being outpaced, so he promptly copied their idea,
calling the Republican version Team 100. Mosbacher says Vice
President George Bush didn't like the idea. ``He moaned and
groaned,'' Mosbacher recalls. ``He foresaw it as something that
would be perceived as someone getting clout for making a big
contribution.'' But he went along with Mosbacher's argument that
the Republicans would be ``left in the lurch'' if they left the
soft money field to Farmer. That year, Farmer recruited 130
Democratic Trustees, while Mosbacher drew 267 members to Team 100.
</P>
<P>
   Before 1988, soft money played an insignificant role, though it
was permitted by a loophole in the post-Watergate federal election
laws passed in 1974, which allowed unrestricted donations to
political parties for party-building activities, like voter
registration drives. Legal challenges to close the loophole have
failed, much to the benefit of presidential candidates, to whom
direct contributions from individuals are limited by law to $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   The soft money reaped by the two parties in 1988 was a pittance
compared with today, when almost every political leader, from
President Clinton on down, reserves large blocks of time for wooing
big contributors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's outrageous,'' Farmer says. ``They are all spending all
their time on the phone asking for money.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Gore has challenged Gov. George W. Bush not to
accept soft money, but even as he issued his proposal, his party's
largest benefactors were invited to a series of lunches. In
Manhattan last Wednesday, for example, Gore raised more than
$700,000 for his party from about 75 donors at two lunches. The
Republican Party will also raise huge amounts of soft money to
support Bush, who has already raised more than $70 million in hard
money for his presidential campaign, an unprecedented sum.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, $100,000 donations have become commonplace. And some
of the high rollers from 1988 are rolling higher today. Richard T.
Farmer, an Ohio executive who was one of the original Team 100
members, gave $445,000 to the Republican Party last year. Carl
Lindner, another Ohio executive who was one of Farmer's big
supporters, gave the Democratic Party $270,000 last year, according
to Federal Election Commission records.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bob Farmer and Mosbacher, now that they no longer spend
their days raising money, favor campaign finance reform. But they
doubt that Sen. John McCain's bill to ban soft money or the other
proposals now debated in Congress would work. Farmer, who served as
President Clinton's consul general to Bermuda and now runs a
high-tech company in Miami, would like legislation mandating free
or discounted television time for presidential candidates.
Mosbacher, chairman of a Texas energy company, thinks that if
corporate soft money is banned, independent spending by labor
unions must be constrained.
</P>
<P>
   But neither option, Farmer says, will shut the door on soft
money. ``The problem with campaign finance reform,'' he says, ``is
that every time you close one loophole, you open others.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-03-27-00 1217EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
