<HEADER>
A0029 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BBO-ERON-FIELD-29-COX     03-28 2097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ERON-FIELD-29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eron Field a `world attraction'
 &HT;    By Kirk Bohls
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Tal Smith was hooked on baseball long before he walked
wide-eyed into a major-league ballpark for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   It took a lot of badgering to persuade his parents to allow him
the biggest treat of his young life. And so it was that his mother
dropped off the biggest 7-year-old fan of the Boston Red Sox at
Fenway Park that summer afternoon in 1940 while she shopped for
groceries.
</P>
<P>
   As much as he was taken by the grace of the game's consummate
hitter, Ted Williams, Smith was just as overwhelmed by the giant
outfield fence known as the Green Monster and the meandering quirks
and cozy charm of the stadium where he could almost reach out and
touch Dom DiMaggio or Bobby Doerr.
</P>
<P>
   In the 60 years since, Smith has watched thousands of ballgames
in dozens of ballparks as a scout for the Cincinnati Reds, farm
director of the Colt .45s in Houston and vice president for the New
York Yankees and Houston Astros.
</P>
<P>
   ``I maintain that part of the appeal of baseball is the
distinctive features of each ballpark,'' Smith said. ``Every
basketball court and football field measures the same, but baseball
can provide something different.''
</P>
<P>
   Now as president of the Astros, Smith brought his love of
ballpark nuances and idiosyncrasies to the design of the new Enron
Field, a $250 million palace in downtown Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ballpark is so unique and such a world attraction that
it's great from the fans' standpoint,'' said Smith, who also had a
hand in the construction of Houston's Colt Stadium and the
Astrodome.''This is baseball at its best.''
</P>
<P>
   Or soon will be. Somewhere amid the dust and the wheelbarrows
lies a gem of a baseball diamond just waiting to be discovered.
That time will come Thursday night when the world-champion New York
Yankees play the Astros in the first of two exhibitions in the
plush, 42,000-seat ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it'll be one of the most exciting and memorable events
in Houston's sports history,'' said Astros owner Drayton McLane.
``It looks like an old-timey ballpark and looks a lot like the
storefronts that we all grew up knowing.''
</P>
<P>
   Definitely not the Astrodome
</P>
<P>
   The brick-and-limestone stadium bathed in an aqua color blends
the distinctive feel of old-fashioned ballparks and the latest in
modern technology. It offers the brick facade of Wrigley Field and
the rounded arches and a pronounced railroad motif as well. Even
the retractable roof resembles an old train shed. Fourteen
railroads once owned major terminals in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Historic Union Station, with its majestic marble columns and a
47-foot-high lobby ceiling, abuts Enron Field. The building served
as the main railroad terminal for passengers and World War II
soldiers from 1911 until the early 1970s and was designed by the
same architect who drew up the master plans for Grand Central
Station.
</P>
<P>
   Once restored, the ornate building with the neoclassical revival
style will serve as the main entrance to the ballpark off Crawford
Street for an expected 3 million fans this season. It also will
house a retail store, a cafe and the Astros' corporate offices.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake. Enron Field will be everything the Astrodome
was not: open air, when that air isn't too hot or humid; natural
grass, not AstroTurf, although the team already has had to resod
the infield with a hardy Tifway 419 bermuda; and a much smaller
facility than the 55,000-seat Dome. Enron Field offers further
confirmation that baseball is distancing itself from the
cookie-cutter, bowl-shaped dome stadiums and embracing more
intimate, open-air, downtown stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't anything architecturally replicated from the
Astrodome,'' said Earl Santee, Enron Field's lead architect from
the HOK Sport architecture firm in Kansas City, Mo. ``There's not
one thing they wanted us to carry over.''
</P>
<P>
   All the serious work has been completed in time for the home
opener against Philadelphia on April 7 as major-league baseball,
for the first time, will unveil three new stadiums in the same
season. The other two are in Detroit (Comerica Park) and San
Francisco (Pacific Bell Park).
</P>
<P>
   Enron Field is, by far, the least expensive and, in fact, came
in $1.8 million under budget. Arizona's Bank One Ballpark, for
instance, cost $465 million, and Seattle's Safeco Field topped $500
million and doesn't even require air conditioning. For 30 years,
the Astros will pay $7.2 million in annual rent, counting $2.5
million as a maintenance fund. The team also chipped in 36 percent
of the stadium's total cost. Bonds will be retired through user
fees, a hotel-motel tax and a tax on rental cars.
</P>
<P>
   Befitting the sport's trend toward downsizing, which heightens
ticket demand and brings fans closer to the action, Enron Field
will be among baseball's smallest ballparks with its 42,000-seating
capacity although Detroit's will accommodate only 40,000 fans and
San Francisco's only 40,800. Like the others, Houston's new home is
an urban ballpark, cut out of a tiny sliver of land northeast of
downtown and tucked inside Highway 59.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, HOK Sport had to tailormake Enron according to the
constraints of the 25 acres available. That explains one of the
shortest left-field porches in baseball at a Jeff Bagwell-friendly
315 feet, although it comes with a Fenway-like, 21-foot-high wall.
Conversely, no center fielders will stretch their legs more than
new Astro Roger Cedeno, who can retreat 435 feet to straightaway
center and still make a catch.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, to do so, Cedeno also will have to be wary of a
flagpole that's in the field of play some three feet away from the
wall. And to add to the degree of difficulty, he will have to
battle a 20-degree incline on the last patch of grass between the
warning track and the center-field wall. Astros employees lovingly
call it ``Tal's Hill'' because it's the brainchild of Smith, a
student of the game who loves ``wrinkles'' and was well aware that
Detroit's old Tiger Stadium had a flagpole in the field and that
Yankee Stadium, before it was renovated, had its monuments honoring
players such as Babe Ruth and Lou Gehrig in the field of play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why, old Forbes Field was so deep that they stored the batting
cage right there in center field,'' Smith said. ``There was no
other place to put it.''
</P>
<P>
   With the deepest center field in baseball, coupled with the
flagpole and the incline, fans should expect more triples and even
inside-the-park home runs. Pitchers can only hope for more deep
outs.
</P>
<P>
   All of those features are firsts for HOK, which has built or
renovated more than 500 sports facilities, including Jacobs Field,
Coors Field and Oriole Park at Camden Yards and has had a hand in
most of the 12 new ballparks built since 1990. Enron offers
countless other innovations, like the closed captioning for the
hearing impaired on the 131-foot-wide scoreboard as well as the
day's stock-market quotes. But it scratched the dirt trail leading
from the mound to home plate, maybe because the Arizona
Diamondbacks noticed it on Enron's artist renderings and
incorporated the idea in its park.
</P>
<P>
   McLane's pride and joy, though, is the 24-ton replica of a 1927
Wild West steam locomotive that will huff and puff with every
Astros home run and zip down an 800-foot track from center field to
left. The 57-foot-long engine was built in Minnesota and has
arrived in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows? McLane might don a conductor's cap and take the first
ride on Thursday night. ``There's definitely a place for somebody
to drive it,'' Santee quipped.
</P>
<P>
   `You'd better bring gloves'
</P>
<P>
   Promoted as one of the most intimate stadiums in baseball, the
first-row seats are three feet closer to the diamond than at
Wrigley Field, the benchmark for cozy ballparks. ``You'd better
bring gloves,'' McLane advised fans.
</P>
<P>
   Those farther away in the upper deck will be treated to a
dazzling view of the downtown Houston skyline. Even when the roof
is closed, those down the right-field line will not have their
sight line obstructed because the architects saw fit to build a
sliding-glass wall running from left field to center field, making
it the world's largest sliding-glass patio door.
</P>
<P>
   More than 20,500 season tickets have been sold, a club record
shattering last year's high of 15,500. Ninety-five percent of those
renewed, said John Sorrentino, vice president for ticket sales. The
Astros will cap sales at about 23,000 to allow for single-game
ticket-buyers, but the first seven games of the season, including
three exhibitions with the Yankees and Texas Rangers, have been
sold out. The average ticket price is $18 with a high of $29 for
dugout box seats and a low of $5 for outfield upper-deck seats, but
kids under 14 can sit in the upper deck for a buck. To assure
yourself of the option to keep your seat for up to 30 years, you
had to shell out up to $20,000 for a Permanent Seat License.
</P>
<P>
   Some longtime fans will miss the vast parking lot of the
Astrodome, not to mention its cushioned seats and
climate-controlled air conditioning. Only the club seats and seats
in the 63 luxury suites are padded. McLane notes there are 14,000
parking spots in the same radius of Enron Field as that which
included 24,000 slots surrounding the Astrodome. Enron includes 96
on-site parking spots, 2,040 reserved spots nearby and room for
more than 25,000 cars within a half-mile radius.
</P>
<P>
   He'd like to think many in the crowd will be among the 160,000
people who work downtown and will already have parked their cars.
For those who don't, 35 city-run trolleys cover the immediate area
_ the city plans to buy six more _ and will run 45 minutes after
games end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked the Astrodome,'' said Ward Adkins, a 53-year-old
oil-and-gas attorney who saw the first and last games played in
that stadium and has held season tickets since 1986. ``I think
we'll be closer to the action at Enron, and the concourses around
the concession stands are wider, but I'll miss the cushioned seats.
Plus, if you go outside in Houston in the middle of August, it's
like a fever. I don't want to spend $100 to go to an event and
sweat.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a $50 million retractable roof, Adkins and his friends
shouldn't have to. Enron's three-paneled roof weighing 5,000 tons
can close in approximately 12 minutes, and the 17 custom air
handling units can cool down Enron Field in four hours. The roof on
Arizona's Bank One Ballpark can close in 4 1/2 minutes, ``if she's
in a good mood,'' said the facility's senior inspector, David
Brown. ``It's four minutes, 35 seconds if she's cranky.''
</P>
<P>
   Santee, who has worked on 50 of HOK's stadiums and currently is
at work for ballparks for the Pirates, Yankees and Red Sox, claims
Bank One Ballpark's roof casts shadows on the playing field unlike
Enron's movable roof, which disappears behind the right-field wall.
</P>
<P>
   According to research over the last five years, McLane argues
that the roof will be open for almost all of April and May games
and between 65 and 70 percent of all the innings for the Astros' 81
home games. It needs to stay open to provide up to six hours of
daylight for groundskeeper Luke Jenkins' precious grass. Everyone
remembers that the natural grass in the Dome died because of a lack
of sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros have received approval from major-league baseball to
open the roof one time during the game if the weather conditions
allows, but only with umpires' approval. ``We can't open and close
it to suit the Astros,'' McLane said.
</P>
<P>
   But it's as much about the fans as the players. Enron has more
women's restrooms than men's and is above the city code
requirements by 44 percent for women and 165 percent for men. Fans
can frequent up to 35 concession stands to eat and will have every
imaginable food item from grilled (not boiled) Star Dogs to sushi.
Enron will even offer food found in the visiting team's city,
starting with Philly cheesesteaks for the opening series with the
Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   It's all part of making the customer feel wanted. Why, there's
even a small balcony jutting out over left-center field for
bystanders who don't want to sit.
</P>
<P>
   Like Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to stand during games,'' Smith said. ``Judge Roy
Hofheinz (Astrodome founder) did, too. He even had a stand-up desk.
We'll see how it works. It's just another wrinkle.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Bohls may be reached at kbohls(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
