<SLUG> BC-NUTSNBOLTS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Foundation cracks don't mean house is ready to fall down
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ You'd think that if your house foundation starts
to crack you've got big problems.
</P>
<P>
   But, to quote from ``Porgy and Bess,'' it ain't necessarily so.
</P>
<P>
   Small cracks in foundations are perfectly normal, and ignoring
superficial cracks won't lead to your kitchen sliding off into the
back yard.
</P>
<P>
   When the cracks are large enough to stick a finger through, or
when your basement walls bow inward or lean, then you've got cause
for concern. But it's not time to panic.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Glacken, owner of Hydra-Lift System of Dayton, said he's
been in the foundation-repair business about 16 years, and ``over
the years I've only seen five or six houses that were in danger of
falling down.''
</P>
<P>
   The Miami Valley is in the midst of a period of low rainfall
that has lasted at least five years, and Glacken and other
foundation specialists say the drought has contributed to
foundation problems in houses that have never had them before.
</P>
<P>
   As soils under houses contract, the support under foundations
shifts, and that puts stresses on the concrete. Concrete is
incredibly resistant to crushing, but it can crack if stretched or
twisted. The same goes for bricks and the mortar between bricks.
</P>
<P>
   Cracks develop at natural stress points: between bricks and
concrete blocks, at corners around windows and doors, where
concrete steps meet the foundation and so on.
</P>
<P>
   If you notice a hairline crack that wasn't there before, you
should keep an eye on it to be sure it isn't expanding or moving.
</P>
<P>
   One way to check a crack is to put a piece of tape across it.
Check back in a couple of days; if the tape is twisted, that
indicates the wall is continuing to shift.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, though, cracks expand and contract slowly as
temperatures change. In the heat of summer, the walls swell,
squeezing cracks closed. When the walls cool off in the winter they
contract, and the cracks may get a bit wider.
</P>
<P>
   This is a good time of year to apply a little silicone and latex
caulk to visible cracks in concrete. Because the weather is fairly
mild, the cracks are at about the midpoint of their expansion and
contraction cycle. Caulk applied now should be able to stretch to
keep covering the cracks when they are at their widest.
</P>
<P>
   At hardware and home-improvement stores, you can find caulk
colored to match concrete approximately, but don't expect an
invisible repair.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Sowder, vice president of W.T. Sowder Construction of
Centerville, said if cracks develop between bricks and the crack
hasn't changed in years, the problem can be fixed by tuckpointing
the bricks.
</P>
<P>
   Tuckpointing involves removing some of the deteriorating mortar
between the bricks and replacing it with fresh mortar. You can get
tips on tuckpointing from places where bricks and mortar are sold.
It's a process that will keep you hunched over in front of a brick
wall for hours at a time, but it's a job the average
do-it-yourselfer can handle with a little instruction.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a basement, apply caulk on both inside and outside
cracks above ground level. The cracks can be a path for air to
escape from the house, and patching them may improve energy
efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   If you have cracks or holes below ground level, you can deal
with them from inside the basement in most cases.
</P>
<P>
   To fix a hole of less than about two inches, you can use a
cement-hole plugging compound from a hardware store. Plugging
compounds usually come in two parts that are kneaded together to
make a claylike plug.
</P>
<P>
   You have to use a chisel to remove crumbly material from the
edges of the hole. Also use the chisel to slope the sides of the
hole so the hole is wider on the inside than at the surface.
</P>
<P>
   After cleaning the hole, force the plugging compound into the
hole. The rim formed by angling the sides of the hole will help
hold the plug in place.
</P>
<P>
   Narrow cracks are fixed in much the same way.
</P>
<P>
   You may need to add a latex bonding agent and cement to fix
larger holes and cracks. Cement comes in powder form and is mixed
with water to form a heavy paste. Spreading a latex bonding agent
in the hole or crack will help hold the cement plug in place.
Bonding agents are sold where cement is sold.
</P>
<P>
   While cracks and holes are common, serious foundation problems
are rare. And serious foundation problems require professional
intervention and can be quite expensive to repair.
</P>
<P>
   One indication of serious foundation problems is a basement wall
that bows inward. That indicates tremendous pressure in the soil
behind the wall trying to burst through. The same goes for a
leaning wall or a door that won't close.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no hundred-dollar fix for a bad foundation,'' Glacken
said. ``You're usually talking about several thousand instead of
several hundred'' dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Have an idea, question or concern? Contact James Cummings by
e-mail at jamescummings(at)coxohio.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
