<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Wednesday, March 29, 2000 are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-TAXIS-COMMENT _ The question, by most accounts, is
mundane. Unless, of course, the person posing the query is a black
man trying to get to a dance club in Southeast Washington, D.C., at
1 o'clock in the morning. ``Can I get a cab?'' I asked the man at
the front desk of the downtown hotel where I stayed Valentine's Day
weekend. ``It's going to be very difficult,'' he replied.
(Franklin, Dayton Daily News) MOVED. WITH ILLUSTRATION, MUG SHOT.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ No pope can travel without making political
waves, least of all this one, who has had active political and
human rights agendas. So it was in Israel and in the West Bank.
(Teepen, Cox News Service.) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ William Jefferson Clinton is embracing an
almost quixotic quest for a legacy that would put Monica Lewinsky
out of our minds. It won't happen. This not only is a lame-duck
president but one with baggage so heavy that other world leaders
see no reason to genuflect before him. (Kleinberg, Cox News
Service.) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ ``A purple Cadillac is the
last thing I've ever dreamed of owning,'' Gail assures me in her
recent e-mail, ``but lately I've been having these funny
daydreams.'' ``Don't worry about it,'' I answer, ``it's a mild
delusion brought on by Social Security anxiety.'' I punch SEND and
get back to work _ but not for long. Another message from Gail. ``I
blame the whole thing on going out for chowder with Arthur. He got
to droning on about some client of his and pretty soon my focus
wandered. Suddenly, there I was in a purple Cadillac. (Schuett, Cox
News Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   KABAT-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ As I have grown older, though,
there are many more things that I don't see clearly: newspapers and
telephone directories as well as right and wrong, truth and
untruth. A lot of lines are blurring for me and bifocals are
addressing only a few of them. (Kabat, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ Until we as a nation come to a
grips with the excesses of campaign finance, here's what we do with
some of the excess: No more taxpayer-financed security for
office-holders running for president. Pay your own way, boys.
</P>
<P>
   (Young, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
