women are better investors. (Ezell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   BOMBECK-PAPERS _ DAYTON, Ohio _ From all appearances, the late
humor columnist Erma Bombeck kept just about everything, and the
University of Dayton is ready to give it all a new, permanent,
climate-controlled home. Erma Bombeck, who died in 1996 of a kidney
disease, left her papers _ original manuscripts, correspondence,
photographs, awards and the like _ to the University of Dayton,
where she was a member of the 1949 graduating class. (Dempsey,
Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-FESTIVALS _ Pollen isn't the only thing blanketing the
South now that spring has sprung. Festivals of all types are
popping up all across the region. Keeping track of it all is the
Atlanta-based Southeast Tourism Society, which judges more than
1,000 entries each year to come up with quarterly lists of the best
events in 10 Southeastern states. We list its ``Top 20 Events''
lists for the months of April, May, June, with a bulleted sentence
or two on each. (Thrasher, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   PSYCHOLOGY-TODAY _ Dr. Hap LeCrone's weekly psychology column.
This week: a list of things that at the present time are being
considered for their effectiveness in helping individuals achieve
and maintain mental sharpness. (LeCrone, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   HOME AND GARDEN
</P>
<P>
   GARDENING-LIFE _ Lee May's gardening column is not available
this week.
</P>
<P>
   NUTSNBOLTS _ DAYTON, Ohio _ You'd think that if your house
foundation starts to crack you've got big problems. But, to quote
from ``Porgy and Bess,'' it ain't necessarily so. Small cracks in
foundations are perfectly normal, and ignoring superficial cracks
won't lead to your kitchen sliding off into the back yard.
(Cummings, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   HOUSES-INSULATION _ Older homes have their faults as well as
their charms. One of the former sometimes includes lacking
insulation. Homeowners can add insulation, facing varying degrees
of difficulty based on where in the house it has to be installed.
(Moran, Rocky Mount Telegram). 20. WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BLOOMSIDE _ A lot of gardening involves timing. By knowing what
blooms when you can combine plants according to when they flower
and in a sequence that will extend your garden's show throughout
the seasons. To help sort through the options, we provide 50 trees,
shrubs, perennials and bulbs and chart them on a seven-month
calendar according to when they bloom (Annuals weren't included
because their summer show is easy for most to plan). This pull-out
chart also should help you plan your beds so that they have
continuous color, or at least when you want it. Keep in mind,
however, that like the weather, gardening holds no absolutes.
(Flanders, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, March 30.
</P>
