<P>
   &UR; Tuesday, March 28, 2000 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Wednesday.
If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (``HNS'' appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   YOSEMITE-CROWDS (San Francisco) _ The Clinton administration has
unveiled a radical relief plan for crowded Yosemite National Park,
designed to unpave paradise and wipe out some parking lots. By
VICKI HADDOCK.
</P>
<P>
   CASINO-BRIBE (Baton Rouge, La.) _ After four hours of punishing
cross-examination by the attorney for former Louisiana Gov. Edwin
W. Edwards, Eddie DeBartolo lost his cool. After first denying,
then conceding that his office made 11 phone calls trying to locate
Edwards in Vail, Colo., and Baton Rouge one day before he was to
deliver a $400,000 payoff, DeBartolo said he was only trying to
find out where Edwards was. By ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   COMETS-LIFE (San Francisco) _ Experiments with high-speed guns
show that comets could have delivered the building blocks of life
to Earth billions of years ago, scientists say. Like microscopic
Evel Knievels, an unexpectedly large percentage of organic
molecules survived being shot from a large gun and slammed into a
wall of felt at several miles per second, one researcher reported
to the American Chemical Society. By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   SMOKING-VERDICT (San Francisco) _ The jury verdict awarding $20
million in punitive damages to an ex-smoker who is now dying of
lung cancer is the latest in a handful of significant courtroom
defeats for the tobacco industry in recent years. By EMILY GURNON.
</P>
<P>
   GENE-DATBASE (Troy, N.Y.) _ This is what Michael Fortun saw on
his recent trip: A country in which nearly every resident's genetic
information is filed with a giant corporation. Residents don't
volunteer to give their genetic data away; it happens
automatically. It may sound like science fiction, but the
Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute bioethicist was actually in
Iceland, where the future already is happening. By ANDREW
BROWNSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   MTBE-WATER (San Francisco) _ Decades after they approved the use
of MTBE in gasoline to clean the air, U.S. Environmental Protection
Agency scientists still don't know what it does to people who drink
it or how to effectively remove it from soil and ground water. By
JANE KAY.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   REGIS-PHILBIN (San Francisco) _ The reason for the immense
popularity of Regis Philbin, the host of the game-show hit ``Who
Wants to be a Millionaire,'' are tough to nail down. The appeal
seems to lie purely in his Regisness, if you ask his fans _ his
common touch, sense of humor, graciousness and ability to think on
the fly. But the appeal may also be that he is just a nice guy. By
CRAIG MARINE.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-REVIEW-MYSTERIES (Undated) _ Chris Larsgaard's thriller,
``The Heir Hunter'' (Delacorte Press, $23.95, 356 pages), is a
fast-paced debut that points to a bright future for this local
writer. Like the author, Larsgaard's protagonist specializes in a
very lucrative field of private investigations. Nick Merchant and
his partner, Alex Moreno, hunt for the heirs of people who die
leaving no will and no known relatives. If they find the heirs,
they get a percentage of the estate. By BOBBIE HESS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-PROFILE-SMITS (San Francisco) _ Diners at the other tables
in Le Charm on Fifth Street were trying to be cool, glancing
smoothly from the corner of their eyes, dipping a spoon into the
soup and laughing, ho. But that was, after all, Jimmy Smits sitting
over there. He was in San Francisco to talk about ``Price of
Glory,'' a new film about a Latino father from an Arizona border
town fighting to get his three sons shots at a boxing title. By
EDVINS BEITIKS.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COLON-CANCER (Undated) _ Studies have shown that fewer than 41
percent of Americans over 50 have ever been tested for colon
cancer. Even more disturbing is a recent government report that
only 9 percent of Medicare beneficiaries get the annual recommended
fecal occult blood test, one of the most basic screening tools.
``Women know about mammography, men know about prostate
screening,'' says Dr. Moshe Shaike of Memorial Sloan-Kettering in
New York. ``People are a little bit squeamish about intestines,
stool and having an examination in this area.'' By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   FREDERICK'S (Hollwood) _Today's Frederick's of Hollywood is
about flirtation, not sleaze. By CYNTHIA ROBINS.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   EXAMINER-SALE (San Francisco) _ The fight over the future of San
Francisco's daily newspapers intensified as former mayoral
candidate Clint Reilly asked a federal judge to issue an emergency
order barring Hearst Corp.'s imminent purchase of the San Francisco
Chronicle. By SETH ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-NINERS-SEASON (Palm Beach, Fla.) _ If only the San Francisco
49ers had had Steve Young and Garrison Hearst healthy for the
entire season, they might have been a playoff team once again.
That's the opinion of the man who lost a bid to become club
president and fled to Cleveland, Dwight Clark, now vice president
and general manager of the Cleveland Browns. By JOHN CRUMPACKER.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ I'm sorry. If the pope can do it,
I can do it. I'm saying I'm sorry. One thing, though. I'm not
making the mistake of saying what I'm sorry for. If I've wronged
you, you know who you are. Yes, I'm sorry for what I wrote about
you, but on the advice of counsel I can't get more specific than
that. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ I celebrated my 30th and 40th
birthdays there, and chose it as the site for a post-Mass reception
when I converted to Catholicism. To us, the women and men for whom
the Washington Square Bar and Grill was more second home than
saloon, it was _ and always will be _ ``the Square.'' After 27
years in business under three separate owners, the Square closed
its doors forever this week. The times and people's eating and
drinking habits have changed, said the final owner, Peter Osborne.
By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   NRA-POLITICS (San Francisco) _ Charlton Heston and his
gunslinging pals in the National Rifle Association have done
something no body else could do, not even pit bull Democratic
strategist James Carville. They've made President Clinton smell
like a rose. By SCOTT WINOKUR.
</P>
