<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 12:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0108 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-NETANYAHU-610&AMP;     03-28 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-NETANYAHU-610&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI POLICE PROPOSE CHARGING NETANYAHU WITH CORRUPTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
(js) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ After a seven-month investigation, Israeli police on
Tuesday recommended that former Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
and his wife, Sara, face criminal prosecution on charges of
bribery, fraud and the theft of $100,000 worth of gifts meant for
the state.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu, who quit politics when he was defeated by Prime
Minister Ehud Barak in May, said the charges were ``baselesq'' and
tendentiously inspired by political enemies. His lawyer, Yaakov
Weinrnth, said he was ``itching for a trial'' to demonstrate a
police vendetta against the former prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   If justice officials decide to put Netanyahu on trial, it could
thwart his ability to make a political comeback. While he has not
publicly expressed interest in doing so, the right-wing opposition
to Barak has been lackluster, and many here assumed that Netanyahu
would eventually be tempted back into politics.
</P>
<P>
   A police recommendation does not always lead to prosecution, as
Netanyahu well knows. In 1997, while he was prime minister, the
police suggested that he stand trial on corruption charges. But the
attorney general declined, saying there was insufficient evidence.
That attorney general, Elyakim Rubenstein, remains in office.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the police said the Netanyahus ``illegally
removed'' 700 gifts to the state of Israel when they left the prime
minister's residence. Netanyahu said last fall, when the police
investigation included well-publicized searches, that he was in the
midst of moving back into private life and had been planning to
``settle up'' with the state after unpacking.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday the police said some of the objects, which included
silver candelabras and paintings, had been altered to remove
inscriptions that clearly marked them as gifts to Israel. Some were
found in the Netanyahus' Jerusalem apartment and some in a
warehouse. Other gifts simply disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   The police also said that the Netanyahus had accepted some
$50,000 worth of free services from a contractor, Avner Amedi, over
nine years. They described it as an illegal ``give-and-take
relationship'' _ a relationship of bribery. It began when Netanyahu
was a legislator and continued through his three-year tenure as a
charismatic right-wing prime minister who eventually lost the
confidence of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The police would not specify Tuesday what the contractor
received in return. The police discovered ``a number of cases'' in
which, they said, ``Netanyahu did, in fact, act on Amedi's
behalf.'' But the police report indicated that the relationship
broke down when Amedi did not get everything he requested and
submitted a bill to Netanyahu, which went unpaid.
</P>
<P>
   After Netanyahu lost the election, the contractor, with the
knowledge of the Netanyahus, submitted a bill for $110,000 of
moving expenses to the prime minister's office, the police said.
They said that the bill was ``very high,'' and that it ``raised
suspicions about criminal acts,'' prompting government officials to
suspect that the Netanyahus were trying to have the government pay
for their private expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The police investigation began after a newspaper, Yedioth
Ahronoth, reported on the suspicions of government officials.
According to the newspaper, the private work included ``four floor
polishings in a single month,'' a crane used to install bars on the
windows of the Netanyahus' private apartment and the repair of an
exercise machine.
</P>
<P>
   Amedi, the contractor, is the state's chief witness, and most of
the case outlined by the police is believed to be based on
information he provided. But about 100 other people were also
questioned by the police.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Netanyahu's political allies suggested foul play by the police.
``The police have been behaving as if they were on a chase mission
to find Netanyahu guilty of something,'' said Uzi Landau, a
legislator from Netanyahu's Likud Party.
</P>
<P>
   But the Israeli police have numerous investigations before them,
targeting figures across the political spectrum. President Ezer
Weizman is under investigation for accepting a large cash gift from
a French businessman. The campaign fundraising practices of Barak
are under investigation. And on Monday, the police began an inquiry
into whether a leading rabbi, Ovadia Yosef, should be prosecuted
for incitement after a blistering sermon against the education
minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very dark day for Israeli politics,'' said Ophir
Pines-Paz, who is the chairman of Barak's governing coalition.
``The whole spate of investigations looks bad and is bad. We all
have to be very careful. We have to understand that we are not
above the law.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-00 1259EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000328.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 13:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0111 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-COLON-CANCER-HNS &LR;      03-28 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLON-CANCER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DOCTORS, OLDER AMERICANS URGED NOT TO OVERLOOK THE COLON 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SYLVIA WOOD  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Richard Farrell had always been good about going to the doctor
for regular checkups. And four years ago, at the age of 62, he had
no reason to believe anything was wrong, until he started getting
stomach spasms and vomiting.
</P>
<P>
   By then, his colon was riddled with cancer and Farrell was
flirting with death.
</P>
<P>
   ``The major symptom of colon cancer is no symptom at all,'' said
Farrell, who lives in Amsterdam, N.Y. ``It's one of those diseases
that creep up on you.''
</P>
<P>
   Farrell has since learned, after four major surgeries to remove
tumors and a third of his colon, that he never should have become
so sick.
</P>
<P>
   Simple screening tests could have tipped off doctors to his
condition a lot earlier, when colon cancer is much easier to treat.
The problem was that nobody ever mentioned them during all those
routine checkups.
</P>
<P>
   ``With early screening, you can reduce the death rate by 90
percent,'' Farrell said. ``But the average person doesn't know
about screening. Most primary care physicians don't talk about it.
None of my doctors said anything to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Studies have shown that fewer than 41 percent of Americans over
age 50 have ever been tested for the disease. Even more disturbing
is a recent report from the Department of Health and Human Services
indicating that only 9 percent of Medicare beneficiaries get the
annual recommended fecal occult blood test, one of the most basic
screening tools.
</P>
<P>
   Even fewer, 2 percent, get the flexible sigmoidoscopy, another
screening test recommended every five years. A more thorough
colonoscopy is recommended at least every 10 years, and more
frequently if problems are found.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women know about mammography, men know about prostate
screening,'' said Dr. Moshe Shaike, director of the Cancer
Prevention and Wellness Program at Memorial Sloan-Kettering in New
York City. ``People are a little bit squeamish about intestines,
stool and having an examination in this area.''
</P>
<P>
   Farrell, now 66, is part of a national campaign to change those
attitudes and a founding member of the Colon Cancer Alliance,
established last year in New York City to offer support services
and educational materials to people touched by the disease.
</P>
<P>
   This year, more than 56,600 people are expected to die in the
United States from colorectal cancer, making it the second leading
cause of cancer death among men and women in North America after
lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really frustrating,'' Dr. Edward Lee, assistant professor
of surgery at the Albany Medical Center in Albany, N.Y., said about
the lack of screening. ``With the 60- to 70-year-old patients I
see, the saddest thing is they've been going to their physician
every six months or year. They feel they've been cheated because
they've been doing the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   During the past month, a coalition of agencies, including the
Colon Cancer Alliance, has been trying to raise awareness of the
disease and get people talking about it. Katie Couric, the
co-anchor of NBC's ``Today,'' spearheaded a five-part series on the
disease after losing her husband, Jay Monahan, to colon cancer in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   The message seems to be getting out, especially to primary care
doctors who are in the best position to recommend screening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd have to say I'm better this month at remembering to ask my
50-year-olds about it,'' said Dr. Laura Pica of Delmar, N.Y. But
like many physicians and colon cancer advocates, Pica believes the
medical community needs to be more aggressive about talking with
patients, despite the time constraints under managed care.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, patients need to be more willing to talk with
their doctors about any problems or symptoms they might be
experiencing with their intestines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you've been toilet trained, most people don't like to
talk about their bowel movements,'' Pica said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Farrell, a father of four, retired in 1996 from his job with the
New York state Division of Food Safety and Inspection. These days,
in between talking to other colon cancer victims and survivors, he
spends his time talking with policy-makers and journalists to
advocate early screening.
</P>
<P>
   His last surgery was in October 1999 and he's optimistic his
cancer has been cured. Yet Farrell's life is far from normal.
Because he lost so much of his colon, he tends to have 10 to 15
bowel movements a day. And he lives with the uncertainty that his
cancer could return.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't go through the hell I've been through,'' Farrell said.
``Get yourself screened. It's been a terrible journey.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Sylvia Wood can be reached at 518-454-5445 or by electronic
mail at swood(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
