<P>
   YOSEMITE-CROWDS (San Francisco) _ The Clinton administration has
unveiled a radical relief plan for crowded Yosemite National Park,
designed to unpave paradise and wipe out some parking lots. By
VICKI HADDOCK.
</P>
<P>
   CASINO-BRIBE (Baton Rouge, La.) _ After four hours of punishing
cross-examination by the attorney for former Louisiana Gov. Edwin
W. Edwards, Eddie DeBartolo lost his cool. After first denying,
then conceding that his office made 11 phone calls trying to locate
Edwards in Vail, Colo., and Baton Rouge one day before he was to
deliver a $400,000 payoff, DeBartolo said he was only trying to
find out where Edwards was. By ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   COMETS-LIFE (San Francisco) _ Experiments with high-speed guns
show that comets could have delivered the building blocks of life
to Earth billions of years ago, scientists say. Like microscopic
Evel Knievels, an unexpectedly large percentage of organic
molecules survived being shot from a large gun and slammed into a
wall of felt at several miles per second, one researcher reported
to the American Chemical Society. By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   SMOKING-VERDICT (San Francisco) _ The jury verdict awarding $20
million in punitive damages to an ex-smoker who is now dying of
lung cancer is the latest in a handful of significant courtroom
defeats for the tobacco industry in recent years. By EMILY GURNON.
</P>
<P>
   GENE-DATBASE (Troy, N.Y.) _ This is what Michael Fortun saw on
his recent trip: A country in which nearly every resident's genetic
information is filed with a giant corporation. Residents don't
volunteer to give their genetic data away; it happens
automatically. It may sound like science fiction, but the
Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute bioethicist was actually in
Iceland, where the future already is happening. By ANDREW
BROWNSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   MTBE-WATER (San Francisco) _ Decades after they approved the use
of MTBE in gasoline to clean the air, U.S. Environmental Protection
Agency scientists still don't know what it does to people who drink
it or how to effectively remove it from soil and ground water. By
JANE KAY.
</P>
