<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 13:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0113 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-GENE-DATABASE-HNS &LR;      03-28 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENE-DATABASE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TINY ICELAND RAISES HUGE QUESTIONS ABOUT THE SECRETS OF LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ANDREW BROWNSTEIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TROY, N.Y. _ This is what Michael Fortun saw on his recent trip:
</P>
<P>
   A country in which nearly every resident's genetic information
is filed with a giant corporation. Residents don't volunteer to
give their genetic data away; it happens automatically, unless
objectors opt out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've become a nation of guinea pigs,'' the natives are known
to grumble.
</P>
<P>
   It may sound like Fortun stumbled into the nightmarish future of
a science fiction novel, but the Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute
bioethicist was actually in Iceland, a five-hour plane trip away.
As U.S. and British scientists battle over whether genes can be
patented, the future already is happening at deCode, in its labs at
a restored Kodak plant in the capital city of Reykjavik, lined with
rows of robotic genetic sequencers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can learn a lot by paying attention to Iceland,'' said
Fortun, 41, an assistant professor and historian of science. ``Even
though people's genetic information is being databased now, no one
knows, given the pace of scientific change, what it's going to be
used for 10 years from now.''
</P>
<P>
   The nation that was populated by Vikings 1,100 years ago and
which claims to be Europe's oldest democracy also is a treasury of
genetic material. The alleged homogeneity of Iceland's population,
which some researchers dispute, may give scientists a prized
opportunity to study genetic anomalies that lead to disease.
</P>
<P>
   Some families on the island can trace their family trees back a
millennium, and Iceland's state-run health care system has been
keeping detailed patient records since 1915.
</P>
<P>
   Add to the genealogies and medical records the DNA samples of
some 10,000 volunteers, and deCode could have one of the most
valuable, and controversial, genetic databases in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which has several U.S. board members and is
incorporated in Delaware, filed for an initial stock offering with
the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission earlier this month. In
exchange for $200 million, it won a monopoly on access to the
medical records of almost all of the Iceland's 270,000 residents.
</P>
<P>
   But at what cost? In an upcoming book that traces recent
advances in genetics, Fortun argues the company bought politicians
through political contributions, trampled on individual rights and
brazenly stifled dissent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was presumed to be in the database unless they opted
out,'' said Fortun, whose book is currently titled ``Promising
Genomics.'' ``It's a complete reversal of what's usually considered
to be informed consent.''
</P>
<P>
   In one of the book's more disturbing episodes, Iceland's
National Bioethics Committee, which regulates genetic research in
the country, was disbanded after one of its members publicly
criticized deCode.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very clear conflicts of interest,'' he said. ``It's
a very cozy arrangement.''
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of Iceland's population supports the project.
After all, the company has brought cutting-edge scientists back to
Iceland and could make the country a leader in fighting genetically
based ailments. The company claims it already has made progress
toward finding the genes associated with multiple sclerosis,
schizophrenia, arthritis and manic depression.
</P>
<P>
   The company also is trying to maintain residents' privacy.
DeCode said it will remove people's names from the database and
encrypt the data three times.
</P>
<P>
   But some Icelanders worry what will happen when deCode markets
its results to pharmaceutical and insurance companies around the
world. For example, could a person be rejected for a job or be
forced to pay higher insurance premiums if he was known to have the
gene that causes multiple sclerosis?
</P>
<P>
   Fortun, who was initially hopeful about the Icelandic venture,
insists he is not a critic of genetic testing per se. Rather, he
views it as critical in these early days of genetic experimentation
that ethics not be lost in the euphoria of science and money.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you think DNA is the secret of life, you should treat it
pretty damn seriously,'' he said. ``Everyone should be in on that
secret.''
</P>
</TEXT>
