<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 13:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0114 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-YOSEMITE-CROWDS-HNS &LR;      03-28 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOSEMITE-CROWDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GOVERNMENT OFFERS PLAN TO LIMIT YOSEMITE TRAFFIC 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By VICKI HADDOCK  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Clinton administration has unveiled a
radical relief plan for crowded Yosemite National Park, designed to
unpave paradise and wipe out some parking lots.
</P>
<P>
   The long-anticipated Yosemite Valley Plan presented Monday calls
for letting nature reclaim some 180 acres of the Yosemite Valley,
eliminating two-thirds of the valley's 1,600 day-use parking spaces
and funneling visitors in on shuttle buses during the high season.
</P>
<P>
   Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt touted the plan as a way to cut
traffic by up to 60 percent on peak days, when about 7,000 cars
clog the park.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing you can argue about is that we ought to be
going further,'' Babbitt said, an oblique reference to some
environmentalists who want to limit the number of people admitted
to Yosemite and ban cars altogether. ``You don't manage the
national parks by taking the easy step of saying, `Stay home.'''
</P>
<P>
   The public will have 90 days to comment on Babbitt's preferred
proposal and four alternatives before the National Park Service
makes its decision. Federal officials hope to adopt a proposal
before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the San Francisco Commonwealth Club on Monday,
Babbitt admitted suffering vexation during seven years of trying to
forge an agreement from competing interests with different visions
of what Yosemite should be.
</P>
<P>
   He noted the dueling passions of Californians: An infatuation
with both Yosemite and the automobile. But he predicted the latest
proposal would flourish, because ``everyone's exhausted.''
</P>
<P>
   Many prominent environmental groups flanked Babbitt to
enthusiastically endorse his proposal. Jay Watson, California
regional director of the Wilderness Society, hailed it as historic,
``an elegant balance between park protection and visitor use and
enjoyment.''
</P>
<P>
   A few, notably the Sierra Club, withheld their support and vowed
to fight for still more stringent environmental protection in what
they consider the crown jewel of the national parks.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal also faces opposition from some vacationers who
would resent the restrictions using a shuttle bus would impose on
their ability to freely wander the Yosemite Valley from the privacy
of their cars.
</P>
<P>
   Defenders of unrestricted Yosemite access contend
environmentalists overstate the dangers to the valley's ecosystem,
and that there are other methods of accommodating more park
visitors _ an underground garage, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Park attendance has dropped a bit in recent years, following a
quadrupling of the entrance fee to $20.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Babbitt maintained that with 3.8 million people
visiting Yosemite last year, overcrowding still was so bad that
something had to give.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't go so far as to compare it with Coney Island, but
yeah, why not?'' Babbitt said. ``You're not going to see majestic
Yosemite through a cloud of diesel fumes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Babbitt proposal would cost an estimated $343 million over
10 years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The proposal includes the following elements:
</P>
<P>
   _ Constructing parking lots near park entrances at El Portal on
Highway 140, Badger Pass on Highway 41 and Crane Flat on Highway
120 as feeder lots for shuttle buses into top valley attractions.
The shuttles would not run on slow winter days, when visitors could
find space among the 550 valley parking slots.
</P>
<P>
   _ Removing three bridges and the Cascades Dam on the Merced
River, requiring development be set back 150 feet from the
riverbank upstream and 100 feet downstream, and restoring riparian,
meadow and black oak landscape along the banks.
</P>
<P>
   _ Restoring about 180 acres, including the Ahwahnee and Stoneman
meadows to their natural, development-free state by removing roads
and parking lots.
</P>
<P>
   _ Abolishing a 3.2-mile section of Northside Drive so that the
river no longer would be bracketed by asphalt along Yosemite
Valley. Instead, it would become a bike and foot path.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reducing the number of valley rooms from 1,260 to 981 by
removing cabins at Curry Village and Housekeeping Camp, but
allowing Yosemite Lodge to replace more than 100 units destroyed in
the floods of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   _ Moving the park superintendent's home, concessionaires,
stables and staff headquarters out of Yosemite Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't been loving Yosemite to death; from my perspective
we've been disrespecting our national parks . . . paving over them
and polluting them,'' said Tom Kiernan, president of the National
Park and Conservation Association, an organization that supports
the national parks. ``This plan is our best hope for turning things
around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
