<DOCNO> NYT20000328.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0128 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-REGIS-PHILBIN-HNS &LR;      03-28 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REGIS-PHILBIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     REGIS PHILBIN, THE MAN WITH A MIDAS TOUCH, IS JUST A `REGULAR
GUY' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CRAIG MARINE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALY CITY, Calif. _ For Regis Philbin, one good thing about his
``overnight success'' after more than three decades in show
business is that he's not about to lose his grip on reality.
</P>
<P>
   With his ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' soaring as the most
popular television show perhaps of all time, considering how
frequently ABC airs it, Philbin, while enjoying the ride, can also
take a step back.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to keep it in perspective,'' said the dapper and
meticulously dressed game show host, who also has a rabid following
from his morning show with the soon-to-be-departing Kathie Lee
Gifford. ``This is all transitory, I know that. For now, we're
riding high. In time, people will get tired of the show, or I'll
get tired of the show, or something else will come along. I'll
still be the same person. That much I know.''
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for Philbin's immense popularity are tough to nail
down. The appeal seems to lie purely in his Regisness, if you ask
his fans _ his common touch, sense of humor, graciousness and
ability to think on the fly.
</P>
<P>
   Philbin recently was in Northern California handing out a $1
million check at the Wards store in Daly City to a contest winner.
Deanne Miletich, a 30-year-old farm land appraiser from Salinas,
snagged the check after buying some curtains. As strait-laced as
they come, the thrilled Miletich was the perfect winner for the
department store, which will give out four more million-dollars
checks around the country. With her fresh face and ``aw-shucks''
manner, the Wards honchos were no doubt grateful that Miletich
seemed far from the type of person who might spend her winnings on
a Vegas vacation package.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to take my family on a cruise,'' she said. ``Maybe take
my mom shopping in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's why Philbin is the man: His contract with Wards (they
lost the ``Montgomery'' after restructuring) says that he shows up,
hands out the big check, waves to the great unwashed and hits the
road. Instead, Philbin personally requested that he be allowed to
spend almost two hours sitting at a table signing autographs for
anyone who cared to wait in line. Nice guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big deal,'' he shrugged when it was brought up. ``I just said
I'd love to sign some things for awhile. These are the people who
have put food on my family's table for all this time. I'm not doing
them a favor, they're doing me a favor.''
</P>
<P>
   And he means it. He's really like that. A kind word here, a joke
there, a snapshot, a joke _ lots of show biz types can pull this
off in public and reveal a darker side when the lights are off, but
everyone _ the publicity people, the security guards, his driver,
everybody _ says that he is like this all the time. It's enough for
hundreds of fans to line up to meet the man they all call by his
first name, as though he's a family friend.
</P>
<P>
   The Reinosos _ 24-year-old Marvin, his 23-year-old wife Janet
and their 10-month old son Anthony _ waited and explained why.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regis crosses generations,'' said Janet. ``It's not just old
ladies who watch him. We love him, he's real, he can relate and
he's funny.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a regular guy,'' her husband agreed. ``And Anthony just
loves him. He'll sit there and stare when Regis is on, whether it's
the morning or at night.''
</P>
<P>
   Regis signed until he realized time wouldn't allow him to
accommodate everyone in line. Instead of hitting the back door,
Philbin signed a bunch of photographs that he had brought and spent
his remaining time walking the line of fans. He shook hands and
distributed pictures, making sure he didn't miss anyone, seeming
too good to be true.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he thinks about now that he's on top, Philbin
replied, ``I think about how lucky I am. I'm always aware of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   And that would have been his final answer, except someone asked
him whether the morning show would go on post-Gifford.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
