<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0143 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-PROFILE-SMITS-HN     03-28 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PROFILE-SMITS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SMITS TAKES ON A FATHERLY ROLE IN `PRICE OF GLORY' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Diners at the other tables in Le Charm on Fifth
Street were trying to be cool, glancing smoothly from the corner of
their eyes, dipping a spoon into the soup and laughing, ho. But
that was, after all, Jimmy Smits sitting over there.
</P>
<P>
   Smits, tree-top tall and gaspingly handsome, made a name for
himself with a supporting-actor Emmy on ``L.A. Law,'' added a
best-actor Emmy and Golden Globe in ``NYPD Blue,'' and has never
looked back. He was in San Francisco to talk about ``Price of
Glory,'' a new film about an Hispanic father from an Arizona border
town fighting to get his three sons shots at a boxing title.
</P>
<P>
   Smits was unfailingly gracious to the waitress and busboy (``I
appreciate it. Thank you so much.'') and nodded once or twice in
the direction of the other tables. By now Smits, 44, is used to
having people snatch glances at him in cafes, but there was a time
when the look on peoples' faces was altogether different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in New York, wearing a fatigue jacket, with this same
goatee, and they'd cross the street if they saw me,'' said Smits,
who grew up in Brooklyn and now lives in Santa Monica, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Smits remembered the hardscrabble days of trying to find acting
jobs in the early 1980s, ``especially one day when my daughter was
little and I was going out for a big audition, and I didn't have
any money. We kept a big change jar just for her, and I had to
break into her piggy bank. A guilt-laden day, I'll tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   Smits' daughter, Taina, is a teacher in Virginia, and his
17-year-old son, Joauquin, is getting a taste for the silver
screen. ``We were at a movie not long ago, and he puts his hands
up, frames the screen, and says, `Cool shot, Dad.' I thought, `Oh,
man, I'm in trouble now.'''
</P>
<P>
   It's the way his father and mother must have felt, said Smits,
when their son opted to major in theater at Brooklyn College and
went on to get a master's degree in fine arts at Cornell University
in 1982. Smits says his father, Cornelis, a former merchant seaman
from the South American nation of Suriname, ``used to tell me, `If
this acting doesn't work, you can teach, right? You can make a
living if acting doesn't work out for you?' Now, both my mom and
dad have these big Kool-Aid smiles about it.''
</P>
<P>
   In high school, Smits' acting class routinely would go to
Broadway performances by Raul Julia, a Puerto Rican actor who took
on dozens of roles.
</P>
<P>
   ```Mac the Knife,' Shakespeare, Pinter, Brecht, Shaw _ he did
them all,'' Smits said. ``He was not going to be defined by his
outward looks, by doing only Latino roles. Looking at it, watching
him work, it was like he gave me . . . permission, you know, like
he was saying to me, `You go ahead and dream your dreams.'''
</P>
<P>
   Smits hopes he's giving Hispanics the same sense of ``dreaming
your dreams.'' In between ``L.A. Law'' and ``NYPD Blue,'' he has
kept close to his roots, narrating a PBS documentary on illegal
immigration, hosting a television show on Hispanics in the United
States with Ricardo Montalban, starring with Edward James Olmos and
Esai Morales in Gregory Nava's ``My Family, Mi Familia.''
</P>
<P>
   Estimating that half his fan mail comes from Hispanics, Smits
said, ``I got one letter from a Latino kid who wrote to say he'd
seen me on `L.A. Law' and it boosted him a little, made him think
he could be a lawyer, too, and he got his degree. I'm not saying it
always happens that way, but it's nice to know it happens
sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't tell the kids in acting classes, `If you stay with
it you're going to wind up being Tom Cruise.' But you can point to
your own experience and say, `It can be done.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Smits would like to see Hispanics take heart from ``Price of
Glory,'' in which he plays a father reliving his boxing life
through his sons. The movie has largely an Hispanic cast, with Jon
Seda of ``Homicide,'' Maria Del Mar, former fighter Carlos
Palomino, and newcomers Clifton Collins Jr. and Ernesto Hernandez.
Shooting was done in Nogales, Ariz., and Huntington Park in
southeast Los Angeles, with Hispanics coming to the set on a daily
basis to see Smits and the others at work.
</P>
<P>
   It felt odd to star as the father of three grown sons, said
Smits. ``I have a beautiful wife in the movie, but I told my
agents, `Huh-uh. No more daddy roles for now.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a definite break from what he's been doing, said Smits _
``the idealistic lawyer and sensitive-cop kind of roles. This was
such a juicy part, a father who is American in so many ways,
aspiring to have his kids be better than he was.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie, directed by Carlos Avila, is essentially an American
saga, said Smits, the kind of boxing movie American audiences have
turned out for, time and again. ``We don't want a family that
resides in Iowa saying, `We're going to see a Latino movie. Are we
going to need subtitles?' I like to think of this as an American
movie that has a Latino heart to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Smits, whose mother, Emelina, is from Puerto Rico, has stayed
close to his roots since he started in 1982-83 with Off-Broadway
roles in ``Hamlet'' and ``Little Victories.'' He moved to TV with
his debut on ``Miami Vice'' in 1984, and then found the spotlight
with ``L.A. Law.'' The family in ``Price of Glory'' reminds Smits
of his growing-up years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ortega family has higher ideals, it wants the kids to be
better, to do only what is best for them,'' he explained. ``My
father was a major disciplinarian. `You will go to school. You will
stay in your room three hours to do your homework. You will make
yourself better.' Hey, that's as American as apple pie.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-00 1336EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
