<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000328.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0154 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-28 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LIVING BY THE POPE'S EXAMPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ I'm sorry. If the pope can do it, I can do it.
I'm saying I'm sorry.
</P>
<P>
   One thing, though. I'm not making the mistake of saying what I'm
sorry for. If I've wronged you, you know who you are.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I'm sorry for what I wrote about you, but on the advice of
counsel I can't get more specific than that.
</P>
<P>
   I'm even sorry about some of the things I haven't written
recently. But I'm sorry, some things are just too close to the
office.
</P>
<P>
   Getting specific about your apologies can get you in trouble, as
the pope has learned. It can even get columnists in trouble, and
we're draped in the mantle of pundit infallibility.
</P>
<P>
   Just look at what the remarkable John Paul II has been doing.
First he apologized for past actions of the Catholic Church, but
that wasn't enough. Sure, he's sorry about the Inquisition, said
some people, but what about Pope Pius XII's unwillingness to
intervene in the Holocaust?
</P>
<P>
   Then John Paul went to the Western Wall and left a note to God
expressing sadness about the oppression of Jews through the ages,
with a commitment to genuine brotherhood.
</P>
<P>
   His powerful gesture was appreciated by many, but there were
Orthodox Jews who objected to his presence at the wall and Muslims
who objected to his presence in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   And orthodox American liberals objected to the Church's attitude
toward women, abortion and gays. Being pope means having to say
you're sorry about everything.
</P>
<P>
   I say look at the example the pope has set. It took physical and
intellectual courage for this infirm man to go to the Middle East
and ask forgiveness for sins committed by other Christians on other
popes' watches.
</P>
<P>
   God can grant forgiveness. People tend not to.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is that people don't know how to apologize
anymore. Or their lawyers advise them to hedge their words.
</P>
<P>
   You hear a lot of passive sentences like ``I regret if anyone
was offended.'' You read sentences like ``Due to a production
error, the word `idiot' was inserted before Congressman Zeppelin's
name. The Daily Afterblat regrets the error.''
</P>
<P>
   A friend of mine once asked a boyfriend if he was having sex
with another woman. He told her, ``It occurred.''
</P>
<P>
   That's almost as ripe as President Clinton's redefinition of
``is.''
</P>
<P>
   It took Clinton months to get around to a full-fledged apology
for messing around with a young intern in the Oval Office. Before
that we heard Clinton saying he did not have ``inappropriate
relations'' with the young woman.
</P>
<P>
   We live in the age of lies and lawyers, and no wonder people are
cynical about apologies. And no wonder Clinton was much more
interested in apologizing for slavery than the sins he committed.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he got a lot of guff for that, too.
</P>
<P>
   Apologies, even genuine ones, are taken as signs of weakness.
When you do something regrettable, you should express some regret.
It makes you stronger.
</P>
<P>
   But don't be too specific, and don't apologize too much or
you'll never stop.
</P>
<P>
   Even the pope can't apologize without someone carping about it.
But we have to thank him for setting an example.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
