<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0170 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-NRA-POLITICS-HNS &LR;      03-28 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NRA-POLITICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NRA: THE SERPENT ON THE MOUNT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SCOTT WINOKUR  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Charlton Heston and his gunslinging pals in the
National Rifle Association have done something nobody else could
do, not even pit bull Democratic strategist James Carville. They've
made President Clinton smell like a rose.
</P>
<P>
   Heston, the NRA president remembered for his movie role as
Moses, called Clinton a liar; his partner in vilification, NRA
Executive Vice President Wayne LaPierre, all but accused Clinton of
rejoicing in the deaths of children in schools and on playgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   I felt sorry for Bubba. No more White House sexual
misadventures. Soon, no more White House power. Now Moishe the
Magnificent and his sidekick are calling the prez names with more
than the usual venom.
</P>
<P>
   With temperatures rising in the never-ending firearms debate, I
find myself wanting to cut out all the baloney and get back to the
question of law.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, many Americans believe it's not an open question.
In fact, among the biggest things the NRA has going for it is the
public's assumption that the Second Amendment is gospel, for good
or ill.
</P>
<P>
   These same people want gun control, polls show. They want
licensing, registration, child safety devices and bans on automatic
firearms that amount to weapons of mass destruction in the hands of
a lone gunman.
</P>
<P>
   They want it so badly, the mothers of America are planning a
march in Washington on May 14, Mother's Day, to tell the NRA where
to get off and Congress that now's the time to move on.
</P>
<P>
   But many Americans, moms and dads alike, don't think the nation
can make much progress in holstering its weapons as long as the
Second Amendment stands as written _ and they don't want to rewrite
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NRA has created a sense of futility, or inertia, among
people who support gun laws but also love the Constitution,'' said
Barrie Becker, executive director of San Francisco's Legal
Community Against Violence.
</P>
<P>
   According to advocates of gun control, strict regulation of
firearms _ like the regulation of automobiles, drugs and other
consumer products _ is not barred by the Constitution, and no
reasonable court has ever disagreed with that proposition.
</P>
<P>
   Becker added: ``What we want to say to the NRA is, `Stop hiding
your extremist rhetoric behind the Constitution. Everything on the
table today is completely consistent with the Constitution.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The NRA knows their policy agenda is unpopular, so they cloak
it in a very popular document. When people feel that what they want
is not constitutional, they throw their hands up. The average
person bows out of the debate. That's a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   To address it, the advocates of gun control held a
teleconference Monday, inviting reporters to pepper them with
questions about the Second Amendment's actual reach. Becker
participated, as did Harvard's Laurence Tribe, Yale's Akhil Amar
and other legal luminaries.
</P>
<P>
   The teleconference coincided with the delivery of an open letter
signed by 45 scholars and historians to Heston.
</P>
<P>
   The letter, complemented by an advertisement in the New York
Times, called the organization's stand on the Second Amendment ``a
distortion of legal precedent and a disservice to all Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanging over the discussion, and any discussion about gun
control, is a federal case that arose in Texas, Emerson vs. the
United States, that could go to the Supreme Court. In the case, a
trial court dismissed a criminal indictment on Second Amendment
grounds.
</P>
<P>
   The first ruling of its kind in 60 years, the Emerson decision
disregarded more than 100 other related decisions. If it stands,
look out: Even the government's currently limited ability to
regulate firearms will be subject to challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever else it does,'' said Tribe, who has acknowledged a
limited right to bear arms under the 14th Amendment that would
still be subject to strict regulation, ``the Second Amendment does
not guarantee a supply of cheap handguns available to all . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing about the language of the Second Amendment remotely
suggests the licentious, absolutist interpretation that everybody
is entitled to have guns.''
</P>
<P>
   The teleconference over, I had an insight: Moishe is confusing
the Second Amendment with the Second Commandment. There's a big
difference. The first was written on parchment, the second in
stone. And the authorial provenance of each is somewhat different.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem with Moishe is the fact that he thinks he's
still up on the mountain. He needs to come off it. The nation is
desperate for disarmament.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
