<HEADER>
A0201 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-28 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     A TOAST TO AN OLD WATERING HOLE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ I celebrated my 30th and 40th birthdays there,
and chose it as the site for a post-Mass reception when I converted
to Catholicism.
</P>
<P>
   Over long lunches, I fell in love there with baseball legend
Hank Greenberg, discussed the timeless appeal of big band swing
with Woody Herman and learned how baritone Sherrill Milnes went
from singing radio jingles in Chicago to starring on the stage of
the Metropolitan Opera in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Over a dinner there, a Dutch television journalist and I once
took turns picking the fertile, facile, funny brain of Studs
Terkel, who _ then in his mid-70s _ drank us both under the table.
</P>
<P>
   And on one perfect, sunny Sunday afternoon, I levitated along
with about 150 other jazz lovers as Stan Getz filled the air with
the most beautiful and sensuous tenor sax music I have ever heard.
</P>
<P>
   Some people called it ``the Washbag, but they were not among us
regulars. To us, the women and men for whom the Washington Square
Bar and Grill was more second home than saloon, it was _ and always
will be _ ``the Square.''
</P>
<P>
   After 27 years in business under three separate owners, the
Square closed its doors forever this week. The times and people's
eating and drinking habits have changed, said the final owner,
Peter Osborne.
</P>
<P>
   Almost nobody (including me) takes long, cocktail-laden lunches
anymore. And the folks who have the energy and livers to drink late
into the night belong to a younger generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this is hard on a lot of people and some of them see me
as `the villain,''' Osborne said during an all-day wake that marked
the Square's last day.
</P>
<P>
   I don't see Osborne, who also owns the wildly successful MoMo,
as a villain. Although I spent hundreds _ no, thousands _ of hours
in the Square during the 1970s, '80s and early '90s, my visits had
dwindled to a few a year.
</P>
<P>
   Meals out these days tend to be someplace near my office or home
where it's easy to find parking. A night of ``drinking'' is a
couple of glasses of wine at a bar near my newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, drinking.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Washington Square Bar and Grill managed to serve
very good food for nearly three decades, alcohol was unmistakably
at the core of the Square experience.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially a public club for journalists, novelists, movie
moguls, lawyers, real estate agents, investment types, visiting
celebrities and jocks and their fans, the joint attracted and
catered to people who tended to check ``three or more drinks per
day'' on those medical profile sheets you fill out at the doctor's
office.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not saying it was an admirable (let alone healthy)
lifestyle; I'm just saying it was what it was. And part of what it
was was the sort of booze-fueled fun and camaraderie that made the
Roaring '20s a decade that still fascinates as much as it appalls.
</P>
<P>
   Once, for example, in the mid-1980s, my friend Sally Jenkins and
I sat eating, drinking and entertaining visitors at the same table
in the Square for 11 1/2 straight hours.
</P>
<P>
   We'd just planned to have lunch but somehow never left. Over
cognacs (or maybe stingers), I calculated our time spent in the
same chairs and announced, ``We could have flown to Greece by
now.''
</P>
<P>
   That memory and scores of others wafted into my consciousness
when I read that the Square was closing and knew I wanted to pay my
last respects. Foremost in the nostalgia bin are the nascent days
of the globe-trotting softball team, Les Lapins Sauvages.
</P>
<P>
   The brainchild of Sports Illustrated writer Ron Fimrite and the
Square's original co-owner, Ed Moose, the team played games in
Paris, London, Ireland, New York and L.A., before I gave up the
mantle of official scorekeeper. Later squads traveled to Hawaii and
Moscow and finagled permission to play in such hallowed baseball
shrines as Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   It was Fimrite, the Square's official biographer, who literally
opened the doors of the place for me. On the night I arrived in San
Francisco to begin life as a Californian _ Sept. 23, 1975 _ he had
made dinner reservations for us at ``this terrific bar.''
</P>
<P>
   For the next 15 or 16 years, the dual-room restaurant at 1707
Powell St. was my venue of choice for lunch, dinner, brunch,
birthdays, New Year's Eve, out-of-town guests, St. Anthony's
penny-pitching contests, celebrations of good fortune and escapes
from the pain of a broken heart.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to an always high-quality, protective staff of
bartenders, servers and hosts, a woman could walk into the Square
solo and enjoy the same freedom that men traditionally took for
granted: to be left alone in peace if she wanted, even while
sitting at the bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cheers'' turned the concept into a TV cliche, but, if you were
a Square regular, everybody really did know your name and much of
what was going on in your life. For decades, we were all part of a
wacky, sometimes dysfunctional, but affectionate extended family.
</P>
<P>
   And now the family home has been sold.
</P>
<P>
   So, here's to the Washington Square Bar and Grill. I consider
myself fabulously fortunate to have known the best times there _
and to have survived to tell the story.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
