index down 48 points. Treasury prices were slightly higher. Abby
Joseph Cohen, Goldman Sachs' market strategist, recommended that
investors reduce exposure to stocks and to long-dated Treasury
securities, but increase weighting in intermediate bonds. Crude oil
was at $27.77 a barrel in early New York trading. European stock
markets were mixed: London was down 0.44 percent and Frankfurt was
up 0.50 percent. The Nikkei in Tokyo closed up 0.46 percent and
Hong Kong's Hang Seng ended up 0.05 percent. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The business travel column. By Nancy
Sharkey.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-SHAREHOLDERS (Tokyo) _ Yoshiaki Murakami, a former
government official turned shareholder activist, has failed in his
efforts to get the Shoei Company to raise its dividend and install
him as an outside director. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MANAGEMENT PAGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HORIZONLIVE (Undated) _ Bob Clyatt, chief executive of
HorizonLive.com.
</P>
<P>
   EMPLOYEE-TRAINING (Undated) _ Nanette Solow remembers the day
she stood in a row with 10 co-workers, tucked an orange under her
chin and transferred it to the space beneath a colleague's chin.
The goal was to move the orange down the entire line in less than
five minutes. But there was a deeper purpose: to build teamwork,
enhance communication and promote problem solving. And, oh yes: to
have a hoot in the process. But after the fun ended, employees
returned to their desks, submerged themselves in their daily chores
and forgot all about the great fruit exchange. More and more
corporations _ at least 70 percent, according to some estimates _
are relying on external training programs to foster leadership
skills and companywide bonding. Trouble is, many of these programs
have no practical value whatsoever. By Abby Ellin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Paul Krugman's ``Reckonings'' and Maureen Dowd's ``Liberties.''
