<DOCNO> NYT20000328.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0239 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-FREDERICK'S-HNS &LR;      03-28 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREDERICK'S-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AT RACY FREDERICK'S, IT'S ALL ABOUT LINGERIE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CYNTHIA ROBINS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ The sound of giggling erupted from behind the
louvered dressing-room door. I could hear it through the walls. A
very slender, dark and beautiful young woman was changing into a
red lace-up-corset, matching thong bikini and sheer, see-through
red nylon and ostrich-feather confection to parade (quickly, mind
you) past a waiting TV crew. Telemundo was at Frederick's of
Hollywood for a shoot and the on-air reporter was living the part,
not just observing it.
</P>
<P>
   She stepped quickly out of the dressing room and coyly pranced
by the camera and its two-man crew. Speaking quickly in Spanish,
she displayed a slim leg and flipped a boa at the camera, showing
just enough skin to make the point: Today's Frederick's of
Hollywood is about flirtation, not sleaze.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot of giggling that goes on at Frederick's, mainly
because of the filmy little nothings that gave it such a racy
reputation in days gone by. Crotchless panties; backless-sideless
and nearly frontless bras; maribou-kissed mules and fluffy feather
boas. The stuff of Vargas pin-ups and naughty Playboy shoots. But
if you look elsewhere at the Rio thongs (4 for $14), the ``Kiss''
bras (click the little gizmo between the cups and watch your
cleavage increase) and the H2O Water Bra, which weighs a ton but
looks great under a jacket, you realize that what Frederick's
really sells is simply . . . lingerie.
</P>
<P>
   You can find Frederick's of Hollywood in shopping malls and on
the Net (www.fredericks.com). You can send away for the catalog and
buy bridal trousseaux, bathing suits, garter belts, Superman robes
and boxer shorts for the boyfriend, wigs, body glitter and perfume,
lace-trimmed camisoles with matching briefs, cotton undies and yes,
selections from the section named ``Show-off,'' which includes
stretch lace body stockings and what they coyly call ``birdcage''
bra styles.
</P>
<P>
   Just from looking at him, you wouldn't have thought that the
Frederick of Frederick's, a dapper gent named Frederick Mellinger,
had it in him to invent such lascivious lingerie. Mr. Mellinger
(which is what the staff still calls him 10 years after his death)
spoke about women with a hushed reverence. Suave and debonair, he
was always the perfect gentleman. One only wonders about his
fantasy life.
</P>
<P>
   When Mellinger mustered out of the Army after World War II, he
opened a lingerie store on lower Fifth Avenue in New York and the
factory to supply it in New York's Chinatown. Frederick's of New
York specialized in French-style undies _ black, lacy, frilly
``unmentionables'' that no one talked about in polite society, but
behind bedroom doors _ ooo la la. Women who had worked in the
factories while their men were away fighting in Europe and the
South Pacific found themselves relegated to the kitchen and bedroom
again. Mellinger thought that it was the perfect time for a little
sex and sizzle. His undies were (and in some way still are)
scandalous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Mellinger was clever. He understood the American
mentality.'' So says Amanda Diaz, Frederick's spokeswoman, an
ebullient blonde with a generous figure and striking bangs. ``He
advertised in the back of women's magazines like Harper's Bazaar,
Good Housekeeping and Vogue _ usually about fixing a specific
figure problem. From there, he built a mailing list and a
catalog.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mellinger wasn't sure his business belonged in New York.
Glamour and sensuality meant one thing to him: Hollywood. And so
Frederick's of New York became Frederick's of Hollywood in 1947
when Mellinger moved his business to the West Coast and onto
Hollywood Boulevard across the street from Mann's Chinese Theater.
By then the formula was perfected. It was time to grow the
mystique: Frederick's of Hollywood was about one thing and one
thing only _ the secrets of the Hollywood stars.
</P>
<P>
   There was only one problem, and that came along with the sexual
revolution of the 1960s. Frederick's of Hollywood became synonymous
with naughty lingerie. If you wanted to dress like a dominatrix for
Halloween, you went to Frederick's. If you were having a bridal
shower and you wanted to give the bride something that would make
her blush for a week, you'd go to Frederick's. If it had feathers
on it but bared the nipples or the rear end, you bought it at
Frederick's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got that stripper-porn magazine reputation in the early
'70s,'' Diaz said, ``when everything was so loosey-goosey.
Frederick's, which was already in touch with female sexuality, went
more so with the crotchless panties. . . . They sell them at
Nordstrom's,'' she huffed. (FYI: I called Nordstrom to ask if they
had crotchless panties and the saleswoman who answered the phone
said, ``No we don't. You're going to have to go to Frederick's for
those.'')
</P>
<P>
   Seated at the desk in her office, upstairs from the retail
store, Diaz is surrounded by original catalog art from the '50s and
'60s. Then, the catalog was mostly drawings and sketches of pin-up
girls with the faces of movie stars, particularly Brigitte Bardot
and her charming Gallic pout (not to mention her daring derriere,
dressed-up satins and laces).
</P>
<P>
   If there was once a bit of back-room sexual mystery attached to
Frederick's, Diaz dismisses the idea that the company got a new
lease on life with the success of the Victoria's Secret franchise.
``We've always looked like ourselves,'' she said. ``We hear all the
time from our vendor base that they're going more sexy because of
us. There is plenty of market share for both of us. We have
200-plus stores and an Internet site which was up three or four
years before theirs. Victoria's Secret has a lot of wonderful
things, but they're never going to be 54 years old.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
