<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0256 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-EXAMINER-SALE-HNS &LR;      03-28 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXAMINER-SALE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEW EFFORT LAUNCHED TO BLOCK SAN FRANCISCO NEWSPAPER DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SETH ROSENFELD  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The fight over the future of San Francisco's
daily newspapers intensified as former mayoral candidate Clint
Reilly asked a federal judge to issue an emergency order barring
Hearst Corp.'s imminent purchase of the San Francisco Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   In a motion filed late Monday, Reilly asked U.S. District Judge
Vaughn Walker to issue a temporary restraining order blocking
Hearst's purchase of the Chronicle for 10 days, or until Walker can
hold a full hearing on Reilly's contention that Hearst's
acquisition of the newspaper would create a monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an important case of great moment and interest in this
community,'' said the motion by Joseph M. Alioto, Reilly's lawyer.
``Hearst should not be able to end competition in the daily
newspaper business in San Francisco by rushing to complete its
purchase of the San Francisco Chronicle before this court has had a
full and deliberate hearing.''
</P>
<P>
   A full hearing already was set for April 13, but Hearst
announced March 17 it would complete its purchase of the Chronicle
by March 30 for a reported $660 million. Hearst also said it would
sell its San Francisco Examiner to the publisher of the free,
thrice-weekly San Francisco Independent, by the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst has denied Reilly's antitrust claims.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly presented declarations from newspaper industry veterans,
including three formerly involved in the business operations of the
Examiner and Chronicle, asserting that Hearst's plan to give the
buyer of the Examiner an annual subsidy of up to $25 million for
three years was insufficient to publish a competitive newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Halling, a lawyer for Hearst, replied, ``The thrust of Mr.
Reilly's case is that Hearst is not providing a large enough
subsidy for the continued publication of the Examiner. To suggest
that the antitrust laws require any level of subsidy is absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   Reilly's motion is the latest shot in his suit seeking to
prevent Hearst, the New York-based company that publishes the
smaller afternoon Examiner, from buying the larger Chronicle, which
is published in the mornings. Alioto said the motion was delivered
to the federal court clerk's office after regular hours Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The court papers amplify Reilly's contentions that Hearst's
purchase of the Chronicle would lead to Hearst owning San
Francisco's only metropolitan daily newspaper, resulting in higher
advertising and subscription rates and fewer editorial voices.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst has said the sales of the Examiner and the Chronicle
would create economic competition between daily papers in San
Francisco for the first time in 35 years and promote a diversity of
editorial voices.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Fang, publisher of The Independent, has said the Examiner
would publish as a daily paper sold through home subscriptions and
newsracks.
</P>
<P>
   The Fang family has agreed to purchase the Examiner name,
archives, subscriber list, Web site, computers, office furniture,
delivery trucks and newsracks. The staff, buildings and printing
presses were not included. Hearst has said the Examiner employees
would be offered jobs at the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   In the court papers filed Monday, Alioto argued that Hearst's
sale of the Examiner to the Fangs was ``a sham.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The transaction . . . does not provide sufficient assets,
resources, or subsidy from Hearst to permit the continuation of the
Examiner . . . in competition with the San Francisco Chronicle,''
Alioto said. ``The result will be a monopoly by Hearst, just as if
Hearst had shut down the Examiner itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Alioto filed declarations from six industry veterans, who said
putting out a competitive paper would present the Fangs with
obstacles and costs far beyond the subsidy to be provided by the
Hearst Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Five of them said a competitive paper would require an annual
subsidy of $50 million for five years, or a one-time payment of
$250 million. The sixth estimated a $50 million subsidy would be
needed for three years.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the veterans are former executives with the San
Francisco Newspaper Agency, which manages the business operations
of the Examiner and the Chronicle under a joint operating
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly, who ran unsuccessfully for mayor last year, argued that
Hearst's purchase of the Chronicle would violate federal antitrust
laws that outlaw monopolies, and the Newspaper Preservation Act,
which allows joint operating agreements to preserve newspapers with
competing editorial voices.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1965, the Examiner and Chronicle have been in a joint
operating agreement, an exception to the federal antitrust laws
that allows them to share business operations while maintaining
independent editorial staffs.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, set to expire in 2005, the Chronicle and
Examiner split profits.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto alleged that Hearst, on one hand, had misused its
position in the agreement to discourage other potential Chronicle
buyers by insisting that they honor the duration of the
profit-splitting agreement with Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   That gave Hearst an unfair advantage, the lawyer claimed,
because only Hearst could buy the Chronicle, simply stop publishing
the Examiner and avoid its costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because Hearst insisted on continuing the joint operating
agreement, competition was foreclosed in the sale of the San
Francisco Chronicle, other bidders were excluded, and Hearst forced
the sale of the paper to itself at a below-market price,'' Alioto
said.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto further contends that Hearst on the other hand has
refused to offer potential Examiner buyers its cut of the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The court should permanently bar Hearst from buying the
Chronicle for ``abusing'' the agreement, Alioto said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
