<SLUG> BC-COLUMN-POP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIP AFRO-ASIAN FILMS REINVENT A GENRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To no one's surprise, ``Erin Brockovich,'' starring Julia
Roberts and her gravity-defying breasts, spent its second week at
the top of the box office, earning about $19 million. But to the
shock and amazement of most observers, ``Romeo Must Die'' came in a
close second with $18.6 million for its opening weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Despite middling-to-negative reviews, little of the attention
and publicity afforded big-name releases, and no ``stars'' in the
Hollywood sense of the word, the action film, which opened
Wednesday, has earned $25 million in less than a week. Compare
that, say, to Madonna and Rupert Everett's excessively hyped flop
``The Next Best Thing,'' which only earned $5.8 million during its
opening weekend earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Rest assured, Hollywood types are still shaking off their
Oscar-party hangovers and scratching their heads in wonderment at
how a film starring an R&AMP;B singer and a Hong Kong action icon most
Americans have never heard of could register one of the biggest
openings this year.
</P>
<P>
   So loosely based on William Shakespeare's ``Romeo and Juliet''
that it might as well have been inspired by a ``Flintstones''
episode, ``Romeo Must Die'' has Jet Li (perhaps best known for his
turn as a villain in ``Lethal Weapon 4'') as an ex-cop and son of
an Asian kingpin who comes to Oakland (that's Verona for you
English-lit fans) to avenge the death of his brother. Along the
way, he falls for the daughter of an African-American ganglord
(played by Delroy Lindo, who yet again is so much better than the
roles he is offered), who is his father's rival. Making her film
debut as the daughter is singerAaliyah, who, as an actress, is a
hell of a singer, and there's also rapper DMX in a small role. But
the film's best moments come when Li, who became a superstar in
hundreds of martial-arts films, flashes his fists and feet of fury
at anyone who vexes him.
</P>
<P>
   Is it a great movie? Not at all. For an action film, there's far
too little action, and the acting often is clunky and creaky. But
in months to come, ``Romeo Must Die'' may be remembered as the film
which ushered in the new era of ``blaxploitation'' movies.
</P>
<P>
   Surely you remember this film genre of the early '70s, which
made stars of Pam Grier, Ron O'Neal, Richard Roundtree, and Melvin
Van Peebles in such films as ``Coffy,'' ``Superfly,'' ``Shaft,''
and ``Sweet Sweetback's Baadasssss Song,'' respectively. These were
those cheaply made films that boasted a distinctly urban
sensibility sharpened by crime, violence, sex, and music. All of
the films _ whether the hero was a cop or a hustler _ featured an
iconoclastic character with a headstrong me-against-the-world
attitude. Think Clint Eastwood's spaghetti-western Man With No Name
crossed with Ruy Ray Moore's Dolemite, and you get the picture.
</P>
<P>
   Quentin Tarantino did his part in reviving the genre back in
1997, when he refashioned Elmore Leonard's crime novel ``Rum
Punch'' into an underrated blaxploitation homage, ``Jackie Brown,''
with Grier as the title character. While Tarantino made a typically
stylish film, it pretty much followed the blueprint of those 1970s
films he grew up watching.
</P>
<P>
   But films like ``Romeo Must Die,'' are as much informed by
hip-hop as by ``Cleopatra Jones'' and ``Shaft's Big Score'' _ which
seems appropriate given that since so many rap artists from Ol'
Dirty Bastard to Snoop Dogg to Foxy Brown _ have been clearly
influenced by blaxploitation flicks. Instead of blaxploitation call
it the ``new-blax-swing.''
</P>
<P>
   Also falling into this category is Jim Jarmusch's
recentlyreleased ``Ghost Dog: The Way of the Samurai,'' starring
Forest Whitaker as a hit man bound by codes of honor and loyalty,
as dictated by the wisdom of the ``Hagakure.'' At turns funny and
elegiac, it's a smarter and far superior film to ``Romeo Must
Die.'' But the two share the tenets of the modern blaxploitation
film _ a combination of hip-hop cool and Asian marital-arts
culture, which has been an underground staple of urban hipness
since Bruce Lee wandered through that hall of mirrors in ``Enter
the Dragon.'' (In 1973, there wasn't a self-respecting inner-city
kid who didn't have a Bruce Lee poster on the wall and a pair of
homemade nunchucks under the bed.)
</P>
<P>
   While it's unlikely such films will proliferate as they did in
the 1970s, the stunning success of ``Romeo Must Die'' and the
critical acceptance of ``Ghost Dog'' (already on its way to
worshipful cult status) cannot be ignored. ``Rush Hour II,''
starring Jackie Chan and Chris Tucker in the sequel to the 1998
hit, is already on the way. And as sure as Hollywood can run a new
idea in the ground, there will be more films capitalizing on this
new Afro-Asian combination platter which is proving that, after
nearly a quarter-century, blaxploitation is back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-00 1519EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
