<DOCNO> NYT20000328.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0263 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-FOOD-TECH-SCHOOLS-ART     03-28 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-TECH-SCHOOLS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 SUDDENLY, COOKING IS HOT AT VOCATIONAL TECH SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOREEN IUDICA VIGUE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FALL RIVER, Mass. _ It's lunchtime at Diman Regional Vocational
Technical High School here, but there are no scowling lunch ladies,
no mystery meats, no Formica tables reeking of bleach.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, paying patrons at the cozy Diman Tea Room restaurant
are served pan-seared salmon with spinach, baby shrimp, and New
Zealand mussels by teens in toques who dream of becoming star
chefs.
</P>
<P>
   And their passion is no flash in the pan.
</P>
<P>
   Culinary arts programs at vocational technical schools are
booming and a big part of the reason _ particularly at Diman, where
a whopping 140 students are wielding whisks _ can be summarized in
one word: ``Bam!''
</P>
<P>
   That is the culinary call of the wild television chef Emeril
Lagasse, a Fall River native and a Diman graduate, who sizzles on
the five-year-old Food Network, a national cable TV station
showcasing celebrity chefs from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Voc-tech students and administrators say that the influence of
television chefs who entertain as much as teach has filled their
cooking classes to the brim and has encouraged students who
otherwise might have passed over the program _ or dropped out of
school entirely _ to find a niche in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been here for 24 years and this is the largest class
we've ever had, and it's all kinds of kids. I know it's Food
Network and Emeril,'' said Ed Kerr, who heads the culinary program
at Diman and taught Lagasse for three years. ``The kids know all
the shows. They come in here and ask if we can make what they see
on TV, and it's really made them see how exciting cooking can be.''
</P>
<P>
   There are 51 culinary arts programs at vocational schools across
Massachusetts, although the programs have always been popular,
administrators say there has been a renewed interest over the past
five years, with some schools reporting 25 percent to 40 percent
increases in enrollment, and others, such as Assabet Regional in
Marlborough, renovating their aging kitchens to meet demands.
</P>
<P>
   Once dominated by boys, the programs are now evenly split, the
schools say, due, in part, to the soaring economy and thriving job
market in the restaurant field, and because the
cooking-as-entertainment phenomenon cultivates students' creative
and artistic sides.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, what Julia Child did for Baby Boomers by showing them on
television how to concoct coq au vin and other French fare, Food
Network chefs like grilling king Bobby Flay and Asian guru Ming
Tsai are turning the next generation on to catfish, quail eggs, and
key lime pie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love watching those chefs because it inspires me to do
something different,'' said April Smeaton, 17, a senior in the
Diman program who has won awards for her creative wedding cakes.
``I will see a recipe that interests me and then run out to get the
ingredients to try it at home. I just did a banana loaf with banana
leaves that I saw on `Yan Can Cook,' and it came out awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   At Blue Hills Regional Vocational Technical School in Canton,
Mass., culinary arts department head Jim Hanrahan said the quality
of his students has improved over the years and attributes that to
youths getting excited by what they see on television and entering
the program with a positive attitude and a burning desire to get
cooking.
</P>
<P>
   And, he said, because the students are so diverse, they are
preparing more ethnic foods than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that the kids who came to this program had
trouble with geometry or thought this would be an easy ride through
high school,'' Hanrahan said. ``But these kids are now
sophisticated about food, they are serious about cooking, and they
want to be challenged.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanrahan said he lets students choose a recipe they like from
any Food Network show and make it for their final project.
</P>
<P>
   ``These chefs they see on TV have great personalities. They
aren't stiffs like you used to see, and that really gets the kids
going,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At Tri-County Regional Vocational Technical High School in
Franklin, Mass., students are cooking at such a high level that
they can enter the culinary program at Johnson and Wales College in
Providence as sophomores, bypassing freshman year, said Tri-County
pastry instructor Bernard Osborne.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think students coming out of voc-tech programs are at the
greatest sophistication levels,'' said Thomas L. Wright, vice
president of culinary education at Johnson and Wales. ``Whether
it's Emeril or Martin Yan or Paul Prudhomme . . . kids see chefs,
they see the ice sculptures and they want to be that. The media
plays a huge role in inspiring young culinarians in many ways, and
kids come here ready to succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, celebrity chefs like Tsai, who owns the
critically acclaimed Blue Ginger restaurant in Wellesley, say that
while they are thrilled to be sources of inspiration for future
chefs, they warn that the road to TV chef stardom is paved with
dirty dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Tsai said students have to be realistic about their goals and
about the restaurant industry, which requires hard work, long
hours, dedication, talent, and the right breaks to make it big.
</P>
<P>
   ``If their goal is to be artistic and to create food, then they
will get instant gratification,'' said Tsai. ``If the plate comes
back full or empty, that's how you know you are doing the job every
night. But being a star chef is about timing and luck and they
should put their hearts into cooking because they love it, not
because they want to be on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason Lantagne, 17, of Norfolk, Mass., will happily take that
advice. The Tri-County junior is a fan of Tsai's and Lagasse's (he
is often heard yelling ``Bam!'' in the Tri-County kichen or ``Let's
kick it up a notch!'' another Lagasse-ism), but his dreams are set
on the high seas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be a chef for a cruise line, so I can see the world
and do what I love,'' said Lantagne. ``I mean, it would be cool to
have my own TV show, but it would have to be different than
everyone else's. I can think about it as I cruise the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
