<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BAHAMAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CHILD-FRIENDLY GETAWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STAN GROSSFELD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASSAU, Bahamas _ Last year my 1-year-old son threw up on me on
an American Airlines flight from San Juan. I didn't have a change
of clothes so my wife followed me to the lavatory and gave me her
frilly shirt. None of the passengers saw me sprint to the toilet
but they all saw me leave and I know what they were whispering:
``Who is that blushing transvestite?''
</P>
<P>
   I learned an important lesson that day. Although an infant is
entitled to fly for free, forget trying to save the money. Pay the
piper and buy the extra seat.
</P>
<P>
   This year would be different. Besides paying for Samuel we
decided to pick a destination that had more activities than any
2-year-old could dream about but would also offer fun things for
adults. With a skim of the Internet we chose Nassau, just a quick
50-minute flight from Miami. Here we could see dancing flamingos,
swim with dolphins, and ride on an inner tube that plunged straight
through shark-infested waters.
</P>
<P>
   The great thing about big resorts like the Day-Glo-colored
Nassau Marriott Resort &AMP; Crystal Palace Casino is that they are
kid-friendly. Children under 12 eat free and there is a Kids Club
and a playground right on the beach. From our balcony overlooking
the massive pool and powder blue ocean, we saw 12 stingrays
floating like butterflies in the sea. Inside, there is a parrot
named Pistachio who likes to be fed grapes, and a video game room
that parents can see from tables in the Goombay Mama restaurant.
This allows parents to actually be able to chew their food while
the kids play nearby. Samuel loves the video driving games but
doesn't like the ones with guns. ``Too many boo-boos,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Our first outing was to the Ardastra Gardens Zoo and
Conservation Centre to see what are billed as the world's only
dancing flamingos. Dancing flamingos?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a secret how we get them to do it but they've been
dancing here since the 1950s and they do it for the applause,''
said trainer Dario Higgs. Kids are free but adults pay $10 each for
a mostly Third World zoo. But it is not without charm. A Bahamian
boa constrictor emerges from a white pillowcase and poses for
pictures around your neck, an anteater just wants to be hugged, and
peacocks stroll the pathways always looking over their feathers for
2-year-olds seeking to add another feather to their cap.
</P>
<P>
   The dancing takes place in a small open-air ampitheater where
the flamingos run in and parade left, right, and run on command.
This time of year is breeding season so some of the flamingos are
thinking about other things besides being pink Rockettes. The
birds, the announcer explained, are pink because of
keto-carotenoids, found naturally in microorganisms in their food.
None of the flamingos have names but all are banded with numbers.
Samuel immediately bonded with number nine. That was the flamingo
that refused to take orders.
</P>
<P>
   Later, we took a boat ride to Dolphin Encounters on Blue Lagoon
Island to swim with the dolphins. Samuel was able to feed a dolphin
and proclaimed himself ``Dolphin Boy.'' The only problem was that
Dolphin Boy didn't want his mother to get in the water with a
well-trained, well-bribed dolphin named Dot. The ``Swim with the
Dolphins'' encounter, which includes an educational lecture, then a
half-hour swim with the majestic mammals was the highlight of some
people's lives, let alone vacations. For $129 you get kissed by a
dolphin, dance with a dolphin, get splashed by a dolphin, and have
a dolphin leap 10 feet over your head. For the grand finale, Dot
the dolphin pushes you across the lagoon at motorboat speed. Samuel
cried the whole time, worried what Dot would do to his mom.
</P>
<P>
   Dolphin Encounters is a photo opportunity paradise. But if you
are too busy with your 2-year-old to shoot much film, don't worry.
Somebody at Dolphin Encounters is videotaping the experience ($49)
or shooting the dolphin kiss ($30 for 8x10 framed or on a key chain
for $5. For those on a tighter budget, a shorter dolphin encounter
is offered for $49. Here, conservation is preached but capitalism
is practiced. The boat for the 20-minute return to Nassau doesn't
come until everybody has a good half hour in the gift shop.
</P>
<P>
   Next stop on the Anti-Terrible-Two Tour was the Atlantis Hotel,
across a bridge from Nassau at Paradise Island. This mammoth
sand-castle-shaped hotel boasts the world's largest marine habitat,
second only to Mother Nature's.
</P>
<P>
   It also is the solution to dining with the 2-year-old. At the
cafe, which has huge picture windows lining the giant lagoons, we
ordered our waiter's recommendations _ Bahamian lobster lightly
battered and then fried to lock in the juices, and tender lamb
chops. We then went to The Dig.
</P>
<P>
   The Dig is an underwater replica of what life could have been
like 11,000 years ago on the lost continent of Atlantis. The Dig is
the antithesis of Boston's Big Dig; it is soothing and relaxing.
You walk through dark stone tunnels with nautical noises piped in
and marvel at some of the 40,000 live fish. The only traffic is a
group of lobsters crawling on a grating over your head.
</P>
<P>
   We returned to find dinner being kept warm. Bahamians may be the
politest, warmest people on earth. The waiter played with Samuel
and entertained us with stories about waiting on Michael Jackson,
Michael Jordan, Shaquille O'Neil, and John Starks. The biggest
tipper, he said, was the Shaq, Jordan autographed a Bahamian
dollar, and only Starks ordered desert. The food was excellent, and
there were 38 restaurants and lounges to try.
</P>
<P>
   We loved this hotel and came back the next day.
</P>
<P>
   For the big kids, there is a 100-step-high water slide that
takes you from the cliff of a replica Mayan Temple virtually
straight down at more than 30 miles per hour. Just when you feel
your stomach in your throat, you splash into a clear tunnel that
whisks you in a tube insulated by plexiglass through a lagoon of
sharks and then spits you out into a swimming pool. All this in a
couple of heart-throbbing seconds. You must be 48 inches tall or
have the IQ of a starfish to attempt this. ``I got water in places
I never had water before,'' said a laughing Jessica Stone, a
teenager from Buzzards Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Less spectacular but more popular is a similar waterslide ride
on an inner tube through the shark tank. After one or two Bahama
Mamas (the local rum drink specialty), some people thought the
sharks started looking strangely similar to people they worked
with.
</P>
<P>
   Although the 2-year-old is smart enough not to want to go on
these death-defying rides, there are plenty of other options.
Atlantis has 40 waterfalls and five fresh-water swimming areas,
including wading pools with tiny waterslides, to satisfy every
toddler. There also is a slow inner tube river ride, perfect for
mother and child to relax.
</P>
<P>
   Don't miss the walk-through predator lagoon where you are the
lowest part of the food chain. In the all-glass tunnel, the fish
are either next to you or above you. There is a saw tooth ray that
looks as if he went to the chainsaw section of Home Depot for
Christmas, and tons of sharks, sting rays, and 200 other species of
sea creatures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
