<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
750,000 WORDS AT YOUR FINGERTIPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Oxford English Dictionary went on line earlier this month,
putting its contents _ 750,000 or so words, with etymologies,
pronunciations, timelines, and illustrative quotations from a
millennium's worth of sources _ at the fingertips of Netizens
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   This should be big news: The OED is more widely known than ever
before, thanks to two recent books about its creation. Simon
Winchester's ``The Professor and the Madman'' and K.M. Elisabeth
Murray's ``Caught in the Web of Words,'' a biography of her
grandfather, founding editor James A.H. Murray, brought the romance
and excitement of the enterprise's early years to an enormous
audience. So why has the hoopla been so restrained?
</P>
<P>
   Money is the likely answer. For all the OED's attractions,
there's not yet any cheap way to access it from your home computer.
The OED simply lacked the resources, spokeswoman Royalynn O'Connor
said, to fine-tune a consumer-friendly pricing structure _
pay-per-download, say _ so for now, the cost of an individual
subscription is a flat $550 per year. (Network subscribers
negotiate their own contracts, which start at $795 a year.)
</P>
<P>
   It's not a truly prohibitive price, given where so much of our
money goes; it's a movie ticket and a latte per week, say, or a
Tiffany trifle for Valentine's Day (and some of us would rather
have the dictionary than the Tiffany trifle). As the Wall Street
Journal calculated, you're paying only .0008593 cents per word _
hard to begrudge when the dictionary, for all its fame, has never
made a profit for Oxford University Press.
</P>
<P>
   Still, so many reference works are free online _ and so many
more allow subscribers to pay only for what they download _ that
$10.58 a week may sound steep to the recreational user. The OED
people seem confident, though, that most people will eventually be
able to get access, either free, through local library networks, or
through a refined subscription plan, as the online version evolves.
And one of the nicest proposals bouncing around the organization is
to offer free access on Sundays: If this world-circling
organization can decide on the boundaries of ``Sunday,'' crossword
addicts may find their lives much simplified.
</P>
<P>
   You can take a free tour of the site at www.oed.com, and see
what it might be worth to you. The experience is not likely to make
you nostalgic for the print version, unless book-lifting is part of
your training regimen. Here, if you turn to set (the plastering
term) and you're referred to rendering, you don't have to haul down
another six-pound volume _ you just click on the link, and there
you are. For bed, bath, and bus commuting, there is nothing like a
book, but for reference works, this is obviously the way to go.
</P>
<P>
   And the Internet version will be far easier to keep current _
for better or worse. Already it has Quentin Tarantino's ``I'm gonna
git Medieval on your ass,'' from ``Pulp Fiction'' _ though it seems
that the colloquial use of medieval to mean ``cruel, barbarous,''
was already a century old.
</P>
<P>
   Revisions will be posted quarterly, as the editors (who began
with M to Mah) work their way through the text, and around 2010 the
``finished'' product will be declared the third edition. But of
course, it won't stop there; when they finish with lyyn (an
obsolete form of the verb lie), it will be time to start all over
again with M, ``1. The letter, and the sound it represents.''
</P>
<P>
   Down for the count
</P>
<P>
   When the 2000 Census form arrived, I promptly filled it out _
excluding my college-age daughter, because the instructions on
answering Question 1 say ``DO NOT INCLUDE in this number: College
students living away while attending college.''
</P>
<P>
   But when I phoned to ask if she and her housemates had filled
out their form, she said no, they'd thrown it away. ``It came, but
it said not to list `college students living away while attending
college' '' _ which is what they are, of course.
</P>
<P>
   The census instructions on the Web site (if you can get there)
are far more detailed: They say clearly that you do list ``a
college student living at this residence during the school year.''
But someone condensed the thought one step too far _ and now, who
knows how many census forms are clogging the landfills of college
towns across the nation?
</P>
<P>
   (What's the word? Write or e-mail yours to Jan Freeman at The
Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107-2378; freeman(at)globe.com.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
