<HEADER>
A0267 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SCI-GENOME-BOS &LR;      03-28 1512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GENOME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLIC JOCKEYING INTENSIFIES ON GENE MAPPING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Talk about March Madness.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few weeks, biologists have traded accusations,
inflammatory documents have been leaked to the media, and the
seemingly abstruse question, ``Who owns the human genome?'' became
front page news across the country and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Even President Bill Clinton and British Prime Minister Tony
Blair were swept into the peculiar controversy over whether private
companies should be allowed to ``own'' pieces of the genetic
blueprint for an entire human being.
</P>
<P>
   But the debate is less futuristic than it sounds. By the end of
this year, competing public and private researchers predict they
will have read the full endowment of coded DNA instructions inside
every human cell _ in effect, the operating manual for a human
being.
</P>
<P>
   Now, just as science stands on the brink of what a U.S.-British
scientific declaration calls ``one of the most significant
intellectual achievements of all time,'' the researchers,
government officials and financial backers alike have begun
publicly jockeying for position.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the California Gold Rush, where (companies) are
offensively patenting genes as quickly as possible,'' even if they
don't know exactly what the genes do, in an effort to preempt other
companies, said C. Frank Bennett, a vice president at Isis
Pharmaceuticals Inc. in Carlsbad, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The complete set of human DNA will reveal what goes wrong in
thousands of rare diseases _ and will show how genes contribute to
common killers like cancer, heart disease and Alzheimer's. The
potential profits, as this newly found information gets translated
into safer and more effective drugs and treatments, are vast.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, both fortune and fame are at stake as the race for
the human genome enters the home stretch, pitting the decade-old,
public Human Genome Project against a two-year-old private upstart,
Celera Genomics. Negotiations aimed at combining their efforts
collapsed this month amid bitter disagreements over how their
genetic data would be released. The public program is releasing the
information daily, while Celera is providing it initially only to
subscribers, who pay millions of dollars for the privilege.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, companies that aren't gathering the DNA
sequences but want to use it ``are cheering on the Human Genome
Project'' in its race against Celera, said Roy Whitfield, chief
executive officer of Incyte Genomics Inc. of Palo Alto, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Many people suddenly seem baffled and outraged at how the
essence of humanity _ the DNA blueprint _ has become the genetic
equivalent of the Yukon Territory, with private biotech prospectors
staking patent claims right and left. One voice in opposition, the
Cambridge-based advocacy group, the Council for Responsible
Genetics, has been circulating a ``No Patents On Life!'' petition
denouncing the conversion of cells, genes and organisms ``into
corporate property.''
</P>
<P>
   The biotech companies lost $30 billion in value two weeks ago
when a call for free sharing of the basic DNA data by Clinton and
Blair was widely misunderstood. Many investors panicked because
they thought the statement meant that genes couldn't be patented _
and companies, as a result, would be unable to make money from
them. In fact, nothing had changed: Genes remain patentable.
</P>
<P>
   ``For patients awaiting therapies and cures for deadly disease,
there is hardly a more important issue than patents, because
without patents, private-sector research'' leading to gene-based
medicines ``will be very, very limited,'' said Chuck Ludlam, vice
president for government relations for the Biotechnology Industrial
Organization, or BIO.
</P>
<P>
   Patents allow their holders a 20-year monopoly on developing
commercial applications from their ``invention,'' but patents do
not confer ownership on it. That distinction is little comfort to
those who oppose gene patents in principle.
</P>
<P>
   The DNA in the genes, argued BobFranza, a biologist at
Washington University in St. Louis, is a product of evolution, not
of man. To patent it, he said, ``is an act of arrogance beyond
anything I can imagine.'' Lanza agreed that the tools and computer
software used in analysis should be patentable _ but not the DNA
itself.
</P>
<P>
   While this feeling may be widespread, US patent policy has been
that even living things can be patented, ever since the US Supreme
Court upheld a company's patent application for a genetically
modified bacterium in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   A major cause of the present controversy and confusion is that
the genetic information being decoded in the genome project can
exist in two different forms, only one of which can be protected by
patents.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called ``raw sequence'' is the genome's entire string of
3.2 million chemical units, or base pairs, that encode genetic
instructions. Ninety percent of this sequence is nonsense code: The
genes, each of which carries the code to make a single protein, are
interspersed among the nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   Patent policy says this genomic raw sequence is not an invention
but a purely natural substance, and can't be patented.
</P>
<P>
   So the answer to ``Whose genome is it?'' is ``The genome belongs
to everbody,'' said John Doll, head of biotechnology patenting at
the US Patent and Trademark Office.
</P>
<P>
   The genes, however, once isolated and purified and removed from
their natural context, can be patented. In the public debate, this
distinction often has been lost, leading to confusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people now believe that human genes are not
patentable,'' Doll said. ``That's simply not true.'' And, he said,
the Patent and Trademark Office has issued hundreds of patents for
human genes, and there are thousands of applications pending.
</P>
<P>
   But the gene-patent controversy is not so easily quenched. If
genes can be patented, biotech prospectors want to know, what about
pieces of genes?
</P>
<P>
   A patented invention has to show ``utility' _ that is, its
purpose. And companies and universities have filed for patents on
fragments of genes whose function they don't know, or they have
made an educated guess of the function based on computer algorithms
that search for similarity to known gene functions.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, leaders of US and British scientific organizations
warned that allowing patents at such an early stage of knowledge
``does not serve society well.'' Bruce Alberts, president of the
National Academy of Sciences, and Aaron Klug, president of the
Royal Society of London, said in a statement that such patent
applications shouldn't be allowed because they are, ``in effect,
laying claim to a function of use that does not yet exist,'' and
benefits only the companies' shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   The US Patent Office already has taken steps to ``raise the
bar'' on gene patents. It has proposed a set of guidelines
requiring that patent-seekers show ``real-world utility'' of the
gene sequences on which they seek protection. The public comment
period on the guidelines ended last week: The biotech industry
filed comments generally supporting the rules but is having some
differences, said Ludlam.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the war of words between Celera and the government
genome project continued _ with a polite interlude when Celera and
a consortium of university scientists announced they had jointly
read out the entire DNA sequence of the fruit fly, Drosophila
melanogaster. That collaboration was successful, and showed that
Celera's aggressive system of DNA sequencing _ called ``whole
genome shotgun'' _ was powerful and accurate.
</P>
<P>
   Celera, armed with hundreds of supercomputers, is using that
same method as it speed-reads the human genome: By the end of last
week, the company claimed to have read about 95 percent of the
genome. The entire genome has to be sequenced several times,
though, for best accuracy. Some of Celera's data was taken from the
public database after it was sequenced by the public Human Genome
Project.
</P>
<P>
   Celera president J. Craig Venter, in an opinion essay in the
Wall Street Journal, reiterated his position that the company won't
release genomic raw sequence data publicly until it has completed
the project. The company's business plan, he said, was to recoup
some of its ``hundreds of millions of dollars'' of investment by
charging for access to the sequence information.
</P>
<P>
   But, unlike some other companies, Celera is not going to try to
patent large numbers of genes, said J. Paul Gilman, director of
policy planning. It will concentrate on only 200 to 300 genes it
believes will be medically valuable, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ludlam, of the BIO trade organization, said that it will take
decades or even hundreds of years to turn all the insights from the
human genome project into health benefits. Given this viewpoint, he
said, the current acrimony seems trivial.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have people standing at the starting line and squabbling
about a two-step lead in a 90-mile race,'' he said. ``It's
ridiculous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-00 1524EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000328.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 15:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0268 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-BELIZE-BOS &LR;      03-28 1826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BELIZE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPTIONS ABOUND IN BELIZE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   POINT PLACENCIA, Belize _ From eagles in Alaska to emus in
Australia, my wife and I have crossed the globe to see animals in
their natural habitats. Which is why we were deep in the Monkey
River rain forest, listening to the harsh barks of howler monkeys
in the trees.
</P>
<P>
   Our guide, a burly Belizian named Terry, slapped the sides of
those trees with the flat side of a Guatemalan machete, all the
while shouting, ``HOO! HOO! HOO!'' The noise did it: He had
``charmed'' the monkeys out of the trees.
</P>
<P>
   Howling and scattering, the large, long-tailed, bearded
creatures moved from branch to branch, sometimes in groups of a
half-dozen or more, sometimes with babies among them.
</P>
<P>
   Watching the monkeys (and hearing their seal-like voices) was a
highlight of our animal-viewing, but hardly the only one. During
our four-day stay on the Placencia peninsula, located on the
Caribbean coast of southern Belize, we also saw: brightly colored
fish, pelicans, sea eagles, parrots, heron, toucans, iguanas, a
snoozing crocodile, and even a glimpse of a manatee.
</P>
<P>
   And along with the creatures came creature comforts, at a deluxe
20-room beachfront resort called the Inn at Robert's Grove, built
in 1997 by a couple of New Yorkers who thought it was time for a
change in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Belize, the only English-speaking country in Central America,
has long been known for its excellent snorkeling and scuba-diving.
But, as we discovered, it is also a haven for ecotourism and other
``soft'' adventures, with its rain forests, preserves, trails, and
acres of unspoiled land. And Placencia is probably the most
unspoiled section of this nation of 216,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   But adventures aren't for everyone. If you're averse to the
possibility of getting wet, dirty, or muddy, if you dislike wearing
sunscreen and bug spray (sometimes lots of it), and if you're not
up for sometimes strenuous excursions and bumpy rides on land and
sea, you may be happier with a different kind of vacation. My wife,
for instance, concluded that although she enjoyed the animals and
the inn, all the excursions were not for her. I, on the other hand,
participated in every adventure, feeling hardy _ or is that
foolhardy?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I had something to prove. We were in Belize celebrating
both our 33d anniversary and my rapidly approaching birthday, which
would take me into the last year of my 50s. Damned if I was going
to let the passing of time slow me down!
</P>
<P>
   This was a resort-centered vacation, in that all of our
excursions began from the resort and most were conducted by Roberts
Grove boat captain Herman Pollard. In our four days there, we had
three adventures. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Adventure one: snorkeling &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Our destination was Laughing Bird Caye National Park, one of the
best snorkeling areas in Belize. Getting there involved a
rip-roaring, 12-mile motorboat ride, with Herman at the helm.
</P>
<P>
   Despite clouds overhead, the snorkeling was fine, with
blue-and-yellow fish predominating and bright coral formations
waving beneath us. In addition, pelicans and sea eagles flew about
as we walked through the small park, stopping to admire an
accumulation of sea shells on a picnic table. (A sign asks you to
take only memories.)
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of picnics, we had a tasty one, packed by Herman and
accompanied by the local brew, Belikin Beer. Afterward, he took his
group to inspect a haven for dozens of hermit crabs of all sizes,
some walking around naked while searching for a new shell. One wag
labeled the creatures Herman's Hermits.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily, the inn's snorkeling trips include two other stops,
and one of them can be the largest barrier reef in the Western
Hemisphere. But the weather was iffy this November afternoon. So
after an extended stay at the national park, we headed back,
stopping at a waterfront village that is typical of what you'll
find in Placencia: a laid-back town with dirt roads and a few shops
and restaurants. You'll also find, here and elsewhere in the
nation, some of the friendliest residents anywhere, whose lilt and
attitude are decidedly Caribbean-flavored. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Adventure two: the rain forest &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The next day's trip began with a boat ride up the winding Monkey
River, surrounded by forest. Once we were on land, Herman turned us
over to local guides Terry and Brian, who led us along a precut
trail in the rain forest.
</P>
<P>
   It was raining in the rain forest, which to me seemed more like
a jungle, what with the thick vegetation and monkey howls. If
Tarzan had swung by on a vine, I wouldn't have been overly
surprised.
</P>
<P>
   We walked along the trail, made muddy by the rain, past bright
orange mushrooms, strangler figs, bamboo, gumbo limbo, and
tearcoats _ prickly plants that are so named because if you walk
too close to them they'll tear your coat or anything else you're
wearing. Toucans hopped in the trees, and the spiny-backed iguanas
(known locally as bamboo chicken) looked positively prehistoric. On
the ground was a jaguar print, but its owner wasn't present.
</P>
<P>
   Following the walk, we stopped in the tiny town of Monkey River
for a local lunch, which means that in addition to such dishes as
fresh fish or stewed chicken, it included Belize's national staple,
beans and rice, and Marie Sharp's Habanero Pepper Sauce was always
within reach.
</P>
<P>
   The boat ride back brought more animal sightings, including a
crocodile who appeared to be sleeping blissfully by the river bank.
In open water, Herman stopped the boat until we caught a glimpse of
a manatee surfacing. It was about this time that those who had
shunned bug spray began to regret their decision. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Adventure three: the jaguar preserve &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Our final trip was conducted by David Vernon, who runs an outfit
called Toadal Adventure. And for me, this was the trip's most
exciting episode.
</P>
<P>
   The destination was the Cockscomb Jaguar Preserve, a ride of
more than an hour in a four-wheel-drive vehicle over unpaved,
rose-colored dirt roads, with a drive by a banana plantation. And
while we hadn't expected to see jaguars strolling about, we did
enjoy the story of how they were caught. Originally, a pig was
placed in a wooden cage. But after dining on the pig, the jaguars
would munch on the cage to free themselves. So metal cages were
substituted, with a barrier inside that also preserved the pig.
</P>
<P>
   The Cockscomb Basin Wildlife Sanctuary (the official name of the
jaguar preserve) is also home to more than 250 species of birds and
other creatures, so a walk in the forest is part of the trip. Our
guide showed us plants that, when touched, close up and sway away
from you.
</P>
<P>
   But the real attractions were yet to come. After a picnic lunch
(and another good one at that), most of the group headed to the
river for a tube float. This consists of sitting semi-upright in a
small, inflated tube and paddling your way down the river. For me,
the float began smoothly _ I felt as if I were on a theme-park
ride. But on a theme-park ride, when you head for an obstacle it
miraculously moves away at the last second. Not so here. Despite my
paddling, the current introduced me to a number of branches hanging
over into the river.
</P>
<P>
   The ride was fun, and so was the next part of our adventure . .
. when it was over, that is. This portion consisted of a 1 1/2-mile
walk to a glorious natural waterfall. For an initiation, our guide
instructed us to swim beneath the 20-foot-high waterfall and let
the water beat on our backs.
</P>
<P>
   And so we did. But the next part involved sliding down smooth
boulders, with water rushing over them, into different sections of
the river. For me, this was a strenuous, sometimes heart-thumping
exercise, with some deep drops into the next water level. At least
three times, I thought we were done, only to find another drop
looming. One of them required a leap that sent me far underwater.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, I was wet and bug-bitten, apparently from not using
enough spray. But I was also exhilarated and proud. Take that, time
in thy flight! &QL; 
 &QL; 
Back at the inn &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After such adventures, there was nothing nicer than changing
into dry clothes and relaxing at the inn. Relaxation, after all, is
what inspired the inn in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   For Robert and Risa Frackman of New York City, opening the
resort was a major lifestyle change. He was a land developer and
she was a public relations executive. But, says Risa Frackman, ``It
was time for something new.'' In 1994, they visited Belize for the
first time and decided they (and their two springer spaniels)
preferred peaceful Placencia over other areas. Originally, they had
planned to build just a beach house for themselves, but in 1997
decided to construct a two-room inn. From there, plans mushroomed.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Inn at Roberts Grove sits on eight acres of land and
contains three white-stucco, red-roofed hacienda-style buildings
housing 20 beachfront or beachview rooms, which have a mix of
colonial and Central American decor, terraces, full baths,
king-sized beds, and both air conditioning and ceiling fans. Among
amenities are a 50-foot beachfront pool, the beach itself, a tennis
court, bicycles, boats, and _ ahh! _ rooftop Jacuzzis from which
you can watch the sun set. A new addition is an on-site dive
center. The price, starting from $100 a night for two in summer and
$150 in winter, is perhaps half of what comparable luxury lodging
would cost at more ``mainstream'' Caribbean destinations. And in
addition to snorkeling, trekking, and diving adventures, there are
fishing excursions and visits to Mayan ruins.
</P>
<P>
   Night life doesn't glitter in Placencia, although the bar scene
is reportedly lively on Friday nights. So I was content to unwind
at the inn's lounge, where bartender Franz Ramirez mixed perfect
pina coladas and rousing rum punches while letting us in on the
local goings-on. I thought the strips of flour tortillas used as
bar snacks were so delicious that they should be sold in bags.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant, meanwhile, consists of a 50-seat dining room and
a variety of international and Caribbean dishes, including fresh
seafood, steak, and conch fritters. The Caribbean lobster was
tasty, but for me it will never top the New England variety.
</P>
<P>
   The Placencia area is dotted with inns and resorts _ some
simple, some stylish _ for people seeking this kind of unspoiled
vacation. (The irony, of course, is that the more buildings that go
up, the less unspoiled the destination becomes.) Near the Inn at
Roberts Grove, we dined one night at another nice resort, Luba
Hati, whose restaurant specializes in Mediterranean cuisine with a
Caribbean touch. My favorite: the calaloo soup, a kind of
black-bean concoction.
</P>
<P>
   When we returned home, I found that because of those insidious
insects, I was still itching. But I was also itching for more
Belize-style adventures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
