<HEADLINE>
GLOW, LITTLE GLOWWORMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Their lovemaking has a special glow. Would you like to watch?
</P>
<P>
   Relax _ we're talking about marine glowworms. When the wee
creatures mate, they light up the waters of the Turks and Caicos
Islands. Theirs is an elaborate ritual, lasting 15 minutes and
involving a zig-zag dance by the male as he searches for the eggs,
which pulsate with a great green luminescence.
</P>
<P>
   This natural light show takes place every month, around three to
six nights after the full moon and 50 minutes after sunset. The
romantic rendezvous, which involves hundreds of the glowing
critters, occurs off the shores of Providenciales, or Provo for
short, the main visitors' island of the Turks and Caicos.
</P>
<P>
   A Glow Worm Cruise, which includes a beverage and conch
fritters, costs $49 a person. For information or reservations, call
Sail Provo at 649-946-4783. For more information about the Turks
and Caicos, call 800-241-0824 or visit
www.interknowledge.com/turks-caicos. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: Name the five principal Virgin Islands and their
nationalities. That is, are they American or English? (Answer at
end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``What do they call Pokemon in Jamaica? Would he be
Pokemon, mon?'' _ Jay Leno. &QL; 
 &QL; 
How's that again? Seen on a restaurant menu in Aruba: ``Chicken
Tenders . . . 7 pieces of delicious chicken served with sweat and
sour sauce.'' (With thanks to Mary Dawson of Quincy.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
The doctor is outside: Guests of the Jalousie Hilton Resort and Spa
on St. Lucia can make appointments to see the island's bush doctor,
Daniel ``Menziel'' Cherubin, who dispenses hands-on healing and
herbal medicine from his garden or the island's rain forest. His
remedies include boiling japanah with pea leaves to cure a cold;
making a tea of tichimai and salt to ease headaches; boiling glory
cedar with epson salts to help you relax; boiling dried sour soup
leaves with water to combat insomnia; and combining braden and
logwood leaves to encourage blood clotting. For more information
about the 114-room Jalousie Hilton, call 800-HILTONS or visit
www.jalousie-hilton.com. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sign of the times: A sign on the grounds of the Atlantis Resort on
Paradise Island in the Bahamas: ``Please Do Not Drop Your Cigarette
Butts on the Ground. The Fish Crawl Out at Night to Smoke Them and
We Are Trying to Get Them to Quit.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Snappy slogan: ``Yachts, Not Slots,'' proclaim the British Virgin
Islands, which eschew gambling and encourage sailing. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Colorful and shapely: Last week's trivia answer, sent to us by
Stuart Cohen of Marblehead, Mass., mentioned that Libya's flag is
monochromatic and Nepal's is non-rectangular. For those who have
asked, Libya's flag is green and Nepal's is shaped roughly like two
sideways triangles, one atop the other. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? The five principal Virgin Islands are St. John,
St. Thomas and St. Croix, all American, and Tortola and Virgin
Gorda, both British. (Water Island recently became part of the US
Virgins.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Compiled from wire service reports, news releases, books,
magazines, Web sites, and the deepest recesses of the author's
mind. Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpenter(at)globe.com. Include
your name and community.)
</P>
</TEXT>
