<DOCNO> NYT20000328.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0271 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-MAHO-BAY-BOS &LR;      03-28 1227
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MAHO-BAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOW-KEY HOLIDAY AT ENVIRONMENTALLY CONSCIOUS CAMPGROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD PENNINGTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. JOHN, Virgin Islands _ When I learned that E27 was my cabin
assignment, I laughed. Carrying my bags up 200 stairs should not be
considered a hardship, I thought, in light of the fact that I was
on one of the most indisputably beautiful islands in the world.
From experience _ this was my fourth visit to the camp _ I knew
that I'd be refreshed and in the water by noon the next day.
</P>
<P>
   The environmentally conscious Maho Bay Campground, established
in 1976, is built on the side of a tall hill within the confines of
the Virgin Islands National Park.
</P>
<P>
   The 114 tent-cabins are made of heavy canvas and mosquito
netting, and sit on stilts _ some people call them ``tree houses.''
Each 16-foot-square unit has a small deck that usually affords a
good view of the blue-green bays below the camp. Jungle separates
one cabin from another. Stairs and wooden walkways connect the
cabins _ there are no roads to your front door.
</P>
<P>
   To get to E27, I followed a route that says something about the
fauna found on the island: I walked along the Crab Ramble,
proceeded to Lizard Lane, then Pea Hen Parkway and Morning Dove
Pass, finishing at the Lost Donkey Highway.
</P>
<P>
   Soon I fell asleep as I listened to two women in the next tent
sing a lovely pop song _ I had been up all the night before
worrying that a nor'easter would cause cancellation of my flight
from Boston.
</P>
<P>
   My wife, Mary, joined me later. We like to call the camp
``Cambridge in the Jungle'' because it tends to attract a somewhat
bookish crowd. Almost every night a lecture is offered at the
pavilion, but that doesn't stop college-educated people from
playing ``Go Fish.''
</P>
<P>
   Guests are instructed to listen to their music with headphones,
and the only live music permitted is an occasional night concert.
As a result, quiet prevails much of the day. Privacy is respected
but camaraderie among guests is common.
</P>
<P>
   Children are as plentiful as the bananaquit birds, and no age
group seems to be missing. The camp is host to yoga and
environmentalist groups.
</P>
<P>
   More than 30 species of tropical birds breed on the island. The
camp pea-hens are all named Gertrude. Determined pelicans cruise
along the beaches, diving for fish. More than 800 species of trees,
shrubs, flowers, and other plants cover the island.
</P>
<P>
   Maho days have their routines. There's coffee at 7 in the
pavilion. We clean our swimming goggles so that they are as clear
as the Caribbean air. We place buckets of water in the sun for a
warm afternoon shower.
</P>
<P>
   St. John has 39 beaches: some sandy, some pebbled, some rocky.
We visit a beach a day, transported on corkscrew-like roads by one
of the many island trucks fitted with bench seats and canopies. We
travel as light as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the afternoon we read and rest, and in the starlight we
walk to a deserted beach. In the distance the giant island of St.
Thomas lights up the sky.
</P>
<P>
   Some of St. John's best beaches are those closest to the camp.
Big Maho Bay, whose shore is shaded by coconut palms and seagrape
trees, is just a short walk down the Donkey Trail. Francis Bay,
with its long sandy beach and hiking trail, is in the other
direction. Many visitors to the camp spend their first day walking
to the nearby Annaberg sugar plantation ruins and Waterlemon Bay,
passing a large mangrove swamp. (Beyond that lies the Johnny Horn
Trail, which leads to Coral Bay on the other side of the island _
an interesting hike.)
</P>
<P>
   Trunk Bay, several bays down the coast from Maho, is considered
one of the finest beaches in the world, but for years we stayed
clear of it. Hundreds of thousands of people go there every year,
mostly shipped in from cruises. A much-hyped underwater trail is
one attraction. When I swam there, I found it difficult maneuvering
through the clusters of swimmers. While Trunk Bay does have
wonderful sand, Jumbie Beach, next door, is as secluded as Trunk is
overpopulated.
</P>
<P>
   Mary worries as I swim away to islands or around rocky
headlands. Most people prefer to hover over a small section of
coral, but I prefer to see much quickly. I search for green and
hawksbill turtles. I'm likely to encounter silver tarpon, orange
spotlight parrotfish, schools of blue tang, and odd-looking
trunkfish. When snorkeling, I do everything I can to stay clear of
the island's fragile coral.
</P>
<P>
   The camp activities desk offers excursions to every part of the
island.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 I circled the island on the Cinammon Bay, a 42-foot
wooden motor yacht that was once owned by Laurence Rockefeller.
When we dived into Brown Bay we encountered a large green (and
harmless) nurse shark who lurked between two large coral
formations, slowly moving its tail.
</P>
<P>
   This time Mary and I sailed on the High Country, a 42-foot
gaff-rigged ketch with dark orange sails. We crossed the Francis
Drake Channel, passing Great Thatch island, on our way to Jost Van
Dyke, one of the British Virgin Islands.
</P>
<P>
   We visited Foxy's Bar, ordering chicken roti (a boneless curried
chicken/potato mixture rolled in a chapati shell), and a painkiller
(rum, pineapple and orange juice, creme of coconut, topped with
freshly grated nutmeg). At noon the party had already started. Foxy
sang impromptu songs, told incorrect jokes and imaginative stories.
One song rhymed Ulysses Grant and hair transplant. A book about
Foxy and Jost Van Dyke says that once there was a clock on the
island, but it broke.
</P>
<P>
   The bar has a pleasantly rowdy crowd of yachtspeople from
morning to night. Jost Van Dyke has just a couple hundred
inhabitants _ a legendary four cars and four bars. Its Great
Harbour is filled with fine yachts.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the week we grabbed a ride with Hamilton Eugene to the
head of the Reef Bay Trail on Centerline Road. The walk down the
cool, dark jungle path eventually led to the sea. We were sheltered
from the sun by tall mango, bay rum, silk cotton, genip, and thorny
lime trees. Some trees support massive termite nests.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way we stopped near a small waterfall to view ancient
petroglyphs, mostly primitive faces carved by Arawak, Carib
Indians, or African slaves. A nearby plaque read, ``Around a pool
are strangler figs and the greenish fruit of the black calabash
tree . . . grey green bromelaids resembling pineapple cling among
tree branches. Razor grass fringes pool and small Christmas orchids
sometime bloom on the rocky cliffs.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the trail was Lameshur Bay _ a welcome sight
because as we walked we became progressively exposed to the sun.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the week I rented a kayak at the camp's dive shop
and paddled to Whistling Cay. When I snorkel I prefer deep water:
the canyons below the surface. I circled the island and after an
hour was relieved to see the kayak again, especially so after
spying a large barracuda hovering in the water nearby.
</P>
<P>
   We find that traveling around the islands is free of stress
because everything seems so well organized. And we prefer to
vacation in a place that respects nature. The Maho management
actually discourages guests from renting cars.
</P>
<P>
   Soon we will return to St. John, and someday may surpass author
John Steinbeck, who visited the island nine times.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
