A0273 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ADVERTISE-EVERYWHERE-     03-28 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADVERTISE-EVERYWHERE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADS GALORE NOW PLAYING AT A SCREEN RIGHT NEAR YOU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Take an elevator ride in downtown Boston these days and you're
likely to see a video screen flashing news and a five-day weather
forecast _ along with commercials for restaurants and temporary
employment agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in line at the convenience store, you might see a stock
market update and get a flashy color advertisement for discount
brokerages.
</P>
<P>
   At the gas pump, get sports scores and an ad for a new Buick.
</P>
<P>
   Now that consumers have mastered the mute button on their TV
remote controls, marketers have begun to exploit the minutes in a
day when they have consumers' undivided attention. Video screens,
each playing a two- to three-minute loop of news and commercials,
are going up across the country at the rate of nearly 100 a day.
And with a handful of companies dreaming up novel places to put
them, even restroom stalls are not out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking for all those moments when people have nothing
better to do than stare at the tops of their shoes,'' said Tom
Pugliese, chief executive of Minneapolis-based Next Generation
Network, which has installed about 6,000 ``Ebillboards'' across the
country, including 350 in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The movement has created a fast-growing category in advertising
known as ``digital out-of-home.'' As the economy roars and
companies compete for ever-more-expensive advertising spots on TV,
radio, and billboards, many have begun looking for alternatives.
Promoters of the new medium say the sudden proliferation of
commercial video screens has been further fueled, ironically, by
the clutter of traditional ads people are subjected to every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have become really good at filtering,'' Pugliese said.
``The trick is to get to them when they're ready to tune in, not
when they're tuning out. If you're standing in line at the
convenience store, it's either watch the back of the head of the
guy in front of you or look at one of our screens. People actually
appreciate it. It's useful and it's entertaining.''
</P>
<P>
   While advertisers have flocked to the new medium, companies are
not yet sold on the effectiveness of the ads, which are typically a
fleeting 10 seconds of video or come in the form of banner ads
displayed across the bottom of the screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is ready to bet the farm,'' said Tobe Berkovitz, a
communications professor at Boston University. ``Just because
people are looking at the screen in an elevator doesn't mean
they're processing the information emotionally or cognitively. Only
time will tell whether these ads are sticking in people's minds or
whether the video screen is just a way to avoid eye contact with
other people in the elevator.''
</P>
<P>
   But advertisers are hungry for more effective ways to reach
elusive markets _ especially 20- to 30-year-olds, who watch less TV
and don't read newspapers as often as older consumers. Since the
commercials that run on the screens are fed over the Internet to
each individual location, they can target audiences and tastes with
specificity. Elevators in office towers, for example, are prime
spots for restaurant ads aimed at corporate lunchers. And Internet
sites have found almost instant response in elevators.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people get to their desks, they log on to their computer
and check out the site they just saw advertised a minute before on
the elevator,'' Berkovitz said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if advertisers' theories about consumers' willingness to
respond to these ``untapped time'' ads proves to be wrong, there is
little doubt people watch them.
</P>
<P>
   At 150 Federal St. in Boston where screens _ flashing news,
trivia, weather reports, traffic conditions and, of course,
commercials _ were installed in elevators late last year, office
workers say they home in on the 12-inch panel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I forget to get off at my stop,'' one worker said
earlier this week, nearly missing her floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something to do,'' said Bill Mahr of Hartford Insurance
Group, who says he watches but doesn't pay much attention. ``I
mean, you are stuck in an elevator.''
</P>
<P>
   Focus groups conducted by Next Generation Network and other
companies found viewer attention riveted on the screens for the 2
1/2 minutes of the average elevator ride and checkout line wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, there's nothing else to do but watch,'' Pugliese
said.
</P>
<P>
   Which is a reason the screens have not only become popular with
advertisers, but also with convenience store companies, who say the
screens at their counters distract customers from the fact that
they are waiting in long lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who come to convenience stores want to get in and out
quickly,'' said Margaret Chabris, a spokeswoman for Dallas-based
7-Eleven Inc., which has video screens near the checkout counter in
stores across the country, including 102 in the Boston area. ``But
if they happen to find themselves in a line, they get some
entertainment, and time passes more quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Advertising time in elevators or any other place where people
are trapped for short periods is seen as so potentially lucrative
that companies, including the Canadian firm Thinc Ideas and North
Carolina-based ATM/Rio Net, have sprung up to capitalize on it,
trying out places like ATM kiosks and movie theater lobbies.
</P>
<P>
   Next Generation Network, which is about to go public with a $115
million stock offering, said it is already reaching 40 million
consumers annually. And it has signed agreements to install video
displays in some of the 1.2 million elevators maintained by Otis
Elevator Co., train platforms at the New Jersey Transit Authority,
and at checkout counters of Cumberland Farms and 7-Eleven
convenience stores. It also has struck deals with Shell Oil Co. to
put screens at gasoline station pumps. The company plans more than
10,000 installations during the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the craze, companies say they must take care in their
zeal to worm advertising into every corner of consumers' lives lest
they rebel.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a line out there somewhere, and we have to be careful
not to cross it,'' Pugliese said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
