<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONEY-SAVING DEALS IN THE CARIBBEAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a strange time to be thinking of the Caribbean. After all,
the time for the islands is winter, when it's cold and snowy. It's
then that those sunny isles beckon.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, is also the time to think about a Caribbean
vacation. The reason is simple: money-saving deals. Mid-April to
mid-December is off-season for the Caribbean, which means savings
of 15 to 50 percent on resort packages, and, in some cases, added
amenities to lure you to these sunny isles.
</P>
<P>
   Many people believe the Caribbean will be just too hot in
summer. It isn't. Temperatures range from 81 to 85, and it's the
dry season right into July. There's no fear of having a week's
vacation wiped out by rain as may happen along the US East Coast in
summer. The hurricane season does officially begin in July, but
most hurricanes don't appear until at least late August.
</P>
<P>
   At Bolongo Bay Beach Club &AMP; Villas on St. Thomas the resort has
a continental plan, which includes accommodations, daily breakfast
buffet, complimentary use of nonmotorized watersports, snorkle
gear, tennis, and nightly entertainment. In winter, the price is
$112.50 per person per night, and from April 24 through May 31, the
price is $87.50 a person and drops to $72.50 a person from June 1
through Sept. 30. Children under 12 receive all the features free.
Those who book seven nights also receive a complimentary sail and
beach outing to St. John, including lunch and open bar; a
$95-a-person value.
</P>
<P>
   Another way to save money on a Caribbean vacation is to stay at
an all-inclusive resort. For example, SuperClubs, with 13
properties on four islands and in Brazil, includes accommodations,
all meals, drinks, sports including equipment rental and
instruction, entertainment, recreational activities, taxes, and
airport transfers in one price. And no tipping is allowed. The
SuperClubs Breezes Golf &AMP; Beach Resort in Jamaica offers the only
golf school on the island. It has a 187-acre golf course. The
resort was awarded the Professional Association of Diving
Instructors Gold Palm Resort Certification and has added new dive
sites where several planes were sunk. ``We're reaching a lot of new
divers who've never had the chance to try it before. It's all
included, so why not try something new?'' said Cheddy Parchment,
resort general manager. For information on SuperClubs, call
800-467-8737 or visit www.superclubs.com.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the off-season things are happening. Many islands have
festivals throughout the year. In June, Grenada holds a Spice Jazz
Festival; St. Martin, an African Festival; St. Vincent, Carnival;
and in July, Barbados holds it Crop Over Festival; the Caymans, the
13th annual Taste of Cayman; the US Virgin Islands, the 34th Annual
Youth Games 2000 National Championships; and in August, Curacao
holds a Salsa Festival, and Antigua offers Carnival.
</P>
<P>
   One note of caution. Since the summer is a slower season in the
Caribbean, check to be sure that all the amenities you wish are
available and that the resort is not using the time to renovate.
Those changes could affect your vacation.
</P>
<P>
   For information on the islands, call 800-356-9999, ext. 799, and
request a free Caribbean Vacation Planner, a 168-page guide
covering 27 destinations with island maps, facts, figures, Web site
addresses and general information to help select a vacation
destination.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
B&AMP;B open house
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bed-and-breakfast inns throughout northeast Connecticut's Quiet
Corner will open for a self-guided tour on April 8 and 9 from noon
to 5 p.m. each day. Each home will feature the craftsmanship of a
local cottage industry and serve refreshments. Proceeds will
benefit The Hole in the Wall Gang Camp, a summer residential camp
in Ashford, Conn., for children with cancer and other serious blood
diseases. The camp, founded by actor Paul Newman, will also be open
for tours 11 a.m. to 5 p.m. on the two days. Lunch will be
available (at an additional cost) at the camp from 11 a.m. to 1
p.m. each day. Advance tickets for the tour are $15 ($17 weekend of
the event) by calling 860-974-0490 or 860-974-3571. For more
information or directions, call the Northeast Connecticut Visitors
District at 860-928-1228.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Ski museum
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first museum in Vermont documenting the history of skiing
from 1888 to the present has opened at Mount Snow, one of the
Northeast's oldest ski resorts. The high-tech, high-impact Snowseum
features a wide range of vintage ski objects as well as a timeline
tracing the rich and colorful history of snow sports in the United
States and particularly at Mount Snow. For more information on
Snowseum, call 888-680-7669.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
HoJo memories
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Howard Johnson Hotels &AMP; Inns is giving away an all-expense-paid
four-night vacation in Puerto Rico for two to the winner of an
essay contest on favorite memories of a stay at a Howard Johnson
property. The contest celebrates the 75th anniversary of the brand.
``Late last year, the brand unveiled an exhibit in honor of its
namesake, Howard Dearing Johnson, at the Hospitality Industry Hall
of Honor in Houston. The exhibit contains physical reminders of the
brand's early years,'' said Mary Mahoney, president of Howard
Johnson International. Entrants should describe their fondest
Howard Johnson memory in 750 words of less. In addition to content,
creativity, and style, entries will be judged on how well they fit
with the brand's longstanding commitment to serving customers well,
offering solid value, and making guests feel at home. Entries may
be sent by mail to Howard Johnson Favorite Memory Sweepstakes, Box
5244, Parsippany, NJ 07054-6244 and be postmarked by May 1. Entries
may also be submitted to www.hojo.com. The Howard Johnson Co. was
founded in Quincy, Mass., and its restaurants soon were throughout
the country. Today few restaurants remain, but hotels bearing the
Howard Johnson name are found in more than 500 locations worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Fondue, anyone?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you enjoy fondue, you don't have to travel to Switzerland.
The Swissotel Boston's Cafe Suisse says it is the only restaurant
in the Boston area offering this meal. ``It has been interpreted by
many to be more of an appetizer or dessert, surely not dinner!''
said David Gibbons, general manager of the hotel. ``But fondue is
the ultimate Swiss dining experience and a wonderfully creative way
to eat.'' The hotel's Fondue Festival is available through April.
For information, call 617-451-2600.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Snowmobile tours
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Snowmobile resorts in Maine are planning on grooming their
trails and offering vacation packages through the first weekend in
April. For information, call 877-275-3363 or visit www.sledme.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
