<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 MONEY HOTSHOTS LEAVE TRADITIONAL FIRMS FOR START-UPS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wall Street is out. Venture capital is in.
</P>
<P>
   Sheryl Marshall is living the transition. In August, she quit
her longtime gig as a high-profile stockbroker for Donaldson,
Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette Inc. She pushed her Christian Dior suits to the
back of her closet and cut off her mane of curly hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got the venture capital haircut,'' she says. No time for bad
hair while she's jetting around the country, raising $50 million
from investors. Marshall's Axxon Capital Inc. aims to invest in hot
young companies, especially those run by women.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never lived in a time like this,'' says Marshall, who
started Axxon with a partner, Paula Groves. ``We think we are going
to make a ton of dough.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall is part of a stream of talent leaving traditional
financial firms across the nation to ride the latest wave to
riches: venture capital. The money hotshots of the 1990s _
investment bankers, analysts, and stockbrokers to the wealthy _ say
financing upstarts in the high-flying technology industry is more
interesting and fulfilling than doing quick deals, and it allows
for closer relationships.
</P>
<P>
   But not one of them would have traded in their pinstripes for
khakis if the money potential weren't big. Really big.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're good at this, the upside is greater'' than
investment banking, says Ken Mabbs, the former chief of corporate
finance for First Albany Corp. in Boston. After 19 years of taking
high-tech companies public, he's launching a venture arm for the
investment firm.
</P>
<P>
   Venture capitalists put money into young, private firms,
especially in the hot Internet, e-commerce, or telecommunications
sectors, in hopes of ultimately taking them public or selling them.
By contrast, investment bankers sell companies' shares to the
public and arrange mergers and acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``All investment bankers want to be venture capitalists when
they grow up,'' Mabbs says. He told his boss, First Albany chairman
George C. McNamee, as much about a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``George said, `Why don't you do it here?' '' Mabbs recalls. Now
the 46-year-old veteran of such IPOs as Plug Power Inc.,
Informatica Corp., and U.S. Web Corp. is raising a $125 million
fund for First Albany's fledgling FA Technology Ventures.
</P>
<P>
   The frustration of investment banking, Mabbs says, is that
dealmaking involves a string of transactions. They're short and
intense, and they end abruptly.
</P>
<P>
   Bankers live and breathe a client for several months, working
long hours and getting to know every detail of the business. They
spend a lot of time in airports, eat too much hotel food, and get
little sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they call you in the middle of the night and say they want
you to do 15 jumping jacks, you've got to do 15 jumping jacks,''
Mabbs says of banking clients. Then comes the IPO, or the merger,
and it's over. All that intimate knowledge goes out the window.
</P>
<P>
   That's a common complaint, says Alex Thomson, a recruiter with
Pendleton James Associates in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're deal junkies. They move from deal to deal, and in the
end, they don't own anything,'' he says. ``I can't tell you how
many of these guys tell me they want to own something.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall says the stock-peddling business lost its panache as
investors started buying stocks online. She hated the day-trading
mentality and wanted to get back to longer-term investing.
</P>
<P>
   One of her claims to fame was convincing clients in the early
1990s, before the Internet was ubiquitous, that American Online
Inc. would take off. Piles of profits later, she boasts a Rolodex
of loyal clients, many of whom are investing in Axxon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a history of making money in this town. I'm a careful
investor,'' Marshall says. ``I have the same instinctual feel for
companies that I did for stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the job requires more than instinct. While it's been
relatively easy, and quick, making money in venture capital over
the past couple of years, much of that has had to do with the hot
IPO market and the explosion of new businesses starting up around
the Internet and telecommunications. A failure to make smart
investments could be costly.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Rao, the former chief executive of Chadwicks of Boston Ltd.,
is one of Marshall's longtime clients. He's investing in the first
Axxon fund, he says, because she helped him make money before.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key ingredient, to me, is the people,'' Rao says.
``Sheryl's track record was a big plus.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall says she's got a large amount of her own money at stake
in the fund. And she's attracted big investors such as Citizens
Bank, John Hancock Financial Services, and State Street Bank _ no
easy task with a first-time fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``Raising the fund is one of the hardest things I've ever done
in my life,'' says Marshall. At 50, she's got the energy of three
twenty-somethings, a prerequisite in the venture game. She's
constantly on the phone, in a cab, or on a plane. She's trying to
find the perfect cappuccino machine for her office, for those
all-important afternoon caffeine fixes. In January, she was home
only five nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate airplane food. I hate flying coach,'' she says. ``I
told my husband before I started this, `I'm going to be a very bad
wife for about nine months.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone in the business can relate. The hectic lifestyle isn't
terribly different from investment banking. Says FA's Mabbs:
``Choose your poison. They're both insane.'' Most venture
capitalists frequently miss dinner at home. And they've got what
many lightly refer to as an attention-deficit issue. They have an
uncanny ability to juggle dozens of plans, meetings, and
conversations in a single day.
</P>
<P>
   Those pressures don't seem to faze those who've tasted Wall
Street's pace.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Kanter, managing director of DLJ in Boston _ and, as it
happens, Marshall's former boss _ is leaving his post after 17
years with the respected firm. He's starting a private-equity
partnership, Marathon Capital Group, which will include venture
capital investing as well as legal and financial advisory services.
</P>
<P>
   Some DLJ principles, but not the firm itself, are investing with
Kanter, he says. ``I don't want to be owned,'' he says. ``I want to
be fully independent.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Tobin, a 30-year-old principal at Battery Ventures in
Wellesley, epitomizes the new generation of venture capitalists. He
had started and sold a software company by 1995 and was looking for
a financial job. There were few openings in VC back then, he says,
so he became an investment banker for a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hated it,'' he says. ``It's a glorified sales business.''
</P>
<P>
   Twelve months later, he was at Battery. And it wasn't just about
money, he says. For Tobin, the draw was building longer-term
relationships with entrepreneurs, and helping to build companies.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Bono of Weston Presidio Capital came to a similar
conclusion a year ago. He was the former co-head of mergers and
acquisitions at Tucker Anthony Inc., a Boston investment banking
firm. After 13 years as a banker, he wanted to be a principal, or
an owner, instead of an agent doing deals.
</P>
<P>
   He says the challenge was more intriguing for him than the
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my former life, you could meet a company and it would be
clear very quickly if you could help them,'' Bono says. ``It's very
different to say whether you want to be an owner of that
business.''
</P>
<P>
   The brain drain from investment banking into venture is becoming
a huge problem for Wall Street firms. Thomson, the recruiter, says
the flow of IPOs and buyout deals has bankers busier than ever.
They're having to delve into the ranks of consultants and managers
of operating companies to find new blood. An MBA with just two or
three years' experience can command an $800,000 pay package,
Thomson says.
</P>
<P>
   At the business schools, MBAs are more interested in joining
dot-com companies or venture firms than Wall Street firms, a big
shift from the 1980s and mid-1990s. At Harvard Business School, 12
percent of the class went into venture capital last year, up 50
percent from 1997. Meanwhile, 10 percent went into investment
banking last year, down from 16 percent in 1997 and much higher
levels in the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   In venture capital, Thomson says, ``the wealth finally rivals,
and in some ways surpasses, investment banking numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Venture capitalists are quick to point out that while
investments with sizzling IPOs can sometimes lead to returns in the
billions of dollars, those aren't the norm. What Wall Streeters
give up when they move into venture are those beefy paychecks and
bonuses. The big returns take longer to come to fruition, and they
depend heavily on a healthy stock market.
</P>
<P>
   These folks seem to thrive on that risk, even as they admit they
had it good in their former jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Says DLJ's Kanter: ``I`m going into the big abyss.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
