<SLUG> BC-BKC-FLORIDA-DONOVAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COACH'S JOURNEY LEADS HIM BACK TO FINAL FOUR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. _ When he was summoned to cut the last nylon
strands during Florida's net-cutting ceremony Sunday at the Carrier
Dome, where the fifth-seeded Gators had just defeated No. 3 seed
Oklahoma State, 77-65, to win the NCAA East Regional and a trip to
the Final Four in Indianapolis, it was with a sense of deja vu that
coach Billy Donovan triumphantly ascended to the top rung of the
stepladder.
</P>
<P>
   The prideful and purposeful steps he took were no different from
those he took 13 years ago in Louisville, Ky., where as a gutsy
point guard for coach Rick Pitino, Donovan helped lead Providence
College to an improbable 70-57 victory over Big East rival
Georgetown in the finals of the Southeast Regional and a berth in
the 1987 Final Four. Coincidentally, it was the same year the NCAA
vacated the tournament records of Marshall and Florida _ the two
schools Donovan would go on to coach.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Rockville Centre, N.Y., Donovan was a gym rat's gym
rat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've really dedicated my whole entire life to the game of
basketball,'' said Donovan, who came to Florida four years ago from
Marshall University, where he became the youngest head coach in the
nation and turned around the foundering Thundering Herd by going
35-20 in two seasons at Huntington, W.Va. ``As I've gotten older,
I've realized there's probably more things to life than basketball.
There's my wife and my kids, but when I was growing up and I was
younger, that's all I did. I just played ball all day long, and I
loved it.''
</P>
<P>
   He was first exposed to the game by his father, William, a
standout point guard at Boston College who graduated in 1962 as the
school's third-leading scorer. Donovan starred at St. Agnes High
School, where he led the Long Island powerhouse to a 51-5 record in
his final two seasons. On more than one occasion, he worried his
mother, Joan, by sneaking out of his bedroom late at night to steal
away a few hours of court time at St. Agnes, where the school
custodian eventually relented and finally gave Donovan his own key.
</P>
<P>
   ``True story,'' said Donovan's 59-year-old father, as he stood
on the Carrier Dome court and recounted the now famous story about
his son's school days. ``His mother and I went over to the gym and
found him there, and we were like, `Billy, do you have any idea
what time it is?' and he says, `I just lost track of time.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It was a story Donovan told over and over again in Louisville
with the nylon net draped around his neck, his heart bursting from
his Providence jersey and his hair a sweaty mop. Donovan was only
too happy to oblige hungry reporters because he had just fulfilled
every basketball junkie's hoop dreams by making it to the Final
Four.
</P>
<P>
   But that was 13 years ago, when he was a player. It seemed like
another lifetime. Another era. Another epoch. Another chapter in
Donovan's basketball diaries.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From Elite 8 to elite company
</P>
<P>
   Sunday he authored yet another chapter for the memoirs. In just
his fourth year as Florida's coach and sixth as a head coach,
Donovan stood at the top rung of his profession at the tender age
of 34, making him the third youngest coach ever to reach the Final
Four. He also became the sixth person in NCAA history to play and
coach in a Final Four, joining the illustrious company of Vic
Bubas, Dick Harp, Bob Knight, Bones McKinney, and Dean Smith.
</P>
<P>
   As Donovan stood atop the ladder, it was as though his amazing
transformation from a Long Island gym rat into a slick-haired, New
York-accented, Pitino protege had been completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really felt, as a player, in order for me to play at the
level I played at, obviously I had to be a student of the game,''
Donovan said. ``I love watching games as a basketball junkie, and I
still am. I mean, I love watching games. The one thing about the
NCAA tournament is that I don't get a chance to watch any of the
games, because I'm always watching film on upcoming opponents. I
love watching film. I love being at practice. I love being on the
floor with these guys, and I love trying to find innovative ways to
try to motivate them and try to bring out the best in them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that's really, really important to me,'' he
added. ``In life, very few people are fortunate to be able to do
something that they love, and I feel very privileged to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   While Donovan genuflected to the coaches who helped mold him _
from the recently deceased Joe Mullaney of Providence to high
school coach Frank Morris _ he said Pitino made the most indelible
impression on his career. It was, after all, Pitino who gave
Donovan his first coaching break by offering him a chance to leave
his job with an investment firm on Wall Street for a low-paying
graduate assistant's job at Kentucky in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Jim O'Brien, who replaced Donovan at Kentucky and also was an
assistant to Pitino on the Knicks when Donovan played for New York,
is well-acquainted with the young coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're in the coaching profession and you watched Billy
play for Rick at Providence, and saw what he was able to
accomplish, and how he turned his game around from a chubby kid to
a really great player in one year, you saw his work ethic and you
saw how he improved,'' said O'Brien. ``And he spent so much time
with Rick at Kentucky. You almost have to be brain dead not to
become a good coach with Rick because he gives so much
responsibility to his people. Billy has such a passion and a love
for the game of basketball and for teaching it. He also has proven
himself to be a tremendous recruiter. That's an unbeatable
combination. I don't think many people in the country are surprised
that Billy took the Florida program to the Final Four. They might
be a little surprised that it happened this soon.''
</P>
<P>
   The move to join Pitino at Kentucky, for all intents and
purposes, was like having Bill Gates ask you if you were interested
in getting in on the ground floor of an upstart software company
called Microsoft. For Donovan, it was a no-brainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a tremendous amount of respect for Coach Pitino and
certainly the opportunities he's afforded me as a player and
coach,'' Donovan said.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan had no sooner developed a reputation on Pitino's staff
at Kentucky for being a young go-getter with a tireless work ethic
and a voracious appetite for watching film when people all around
the Bluegrass State began drawing obvious comparisons with Pitino.
</P>
<P>
   Some have even suggested Donovan has become a Mini-Me version of
Pitino by adopting many of his former mentor's coaching
philosophies and tactics. But what Donovan has done is to adapt
what he learned from Pitino. He took the same up-tempo, all-out
style of basketball that was played at Kentucky and branded it
``BillyBall'' at Florida, where it has become the perfect
complement to the ``Fun `N' Gun'' offense of football coach Steve
Spurrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I got schooled by one of the best basketball
coaches around,'' Donovan said. ``But I am not him. I am my own
man. But it doesn't bother me one bit when I'm compared with him.
What he's done for me as a player and as a coach and as a person, I
wouldn't be here right now. So I'm not bothered in the least when
his name is brought up in the same breath as mine. It's a
tremendous honor.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The highest recommendation
</P>
<P>
   And so when Florida athletic director Jeremy Foley sought a
successor to Lon Kruger, who left the Gators to take the job at
Illinois in 1996, the first person he contacted about Donovan was
Pitino.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to know about the style of play, and he said nobody
knew it better,'' Foley said. ``Nobody knew Rick Pitino's style
better than Billy Donovan because he played in it and he coached in
it. He told me that he was a ferocious worker and a tireless
recruiter. I asked him about his character and integrity, and he
told me that Billy Donovan was going to go straight to heaven.
</P>
<P>
   ``His only concern was that we had patience with Billy, meaning
there was a lot to do with the program. That's why we gave him a
six-year contract right off the bat, because I wanted him to know
that we were committed to him.''
</P>
<P>
   When Foley returned to Gainesville, Fla., from an interview at
Donovan's home in Huntington, W.Va., sufficiently impressed by his
high level of energy and enthusiasm, he knew the Gators had found
their coach.
</P>
<P>
   So, too, had Mike Miller, one of four McDonald's All-Americans
Donovan lured to Florida. The Gators lured Miller away from such
established programs as Kansas and Kentucky. Initially, the
decision Miller wrestled with in leaving his home in Mitchell,
S.D., was difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have Kansas and Kentucky, and then you have Florida,
who's going to pick Florida over those two schools?'' said Miller,
a 6-foot-8-inch sophomore forward who led the Gators in scoring as
a freshman (12.3 points per game) and again this season (14.3 ppg).
``But I believed so much in what Coach said that it made the
decision easy. People say, `How was it easy?' Well it just was. It
was easy for me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
