<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN PAIR LEFT OUT IN THE COLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NICE, France _ She had been coughing and was worried about
getting bronchitis before the European Championships. So Elena
Berezhnaya got some pills from a New Jersey doctor, went to Vienna
last month, and won the pairs gold medal for Russia with partner
Anton Sikharulidze.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, the phone rang with bad news from Moscow.
Berezhnaya's doping sample had come back positive for ephedrine,
and the Russian Federation was yanking her and Sikharulidze out of
the world championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``I opened my eyes and made them like saucepans, and the same
did Elena,'' said legendary coach Tamara Moskvina, whose pupils
were shooting for a third straight title here. ``We thought cough
is not an important sickness. For 30 years, nobody paid attention.
But they said it was like doping and she is not eligible.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time in skating history that a woman had tested
positive for a banned substance, and it will likely cost Berezhnaya
both her European title and a three-month suspension when the
International Skating Union council takes up her case here next
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they will be sent to Siberia _ together with me,'' mused
Moskvina, who took the blame for Berezhnaya's mistake. ``Elena and
I always considered doping a great disgrace. We believe we are well
prepared and we can win without any help. The only special pills I
give them were artistry and psychology.''
</P>
<P>
   Though many over-the-counter cold medications contain ephedrine,
Moskvina said she had never read the banned list and that
Berezhnaya hadn't thought to question the doctor or read the label.
``When you eat bread, do you know the ingredients of bread?''
shrugged Moskvina. ``You eat bread. She took a pill.''
</P>
<P>
   So the finality of the word `doping' hit her and Berezhnaya like
an uppercut. ``We think, ahh, we are criminals, everybody will
point fingers and say, `How can you do that?' '', Moskvina said.
``The whole day yesterday I was with her, looking for places where
we can jump out of the mountains and into the Mediterranean Sea.
Then we decide we did nothing wrong, nothing prohibited. So we
finish not in the sea, we finish in the restaurant.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Berezhnaya and Sikharulidze were up the road in Monte
Carlo, but they are planning to return to watch the medals be
awarded without them Tuesday night. ``We are not going to hide; we
are not going to run away,'' said Moskvina. ``They don't feel
guilty about what she did. They will stay here until the end of the
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   The competition now figures to be a walkover for China's Shen
Xue and Zhao Hongbo, who won the silver last year and dominated
Monday night's short program ahead of Russia's Maria Petrova and
Alexei Tikhonov. ``We are satisfied,'' said Zhao. ``We performed
all the elements good. But this is only the short program.''
</P>
<P>
   If he and Shen can hang on, they'll make history. The Chinese
have never won the pairs title, and only Chen Lu has ever won a
global gold. The Americans had no illusions about making the podium
here. After injuries put two of last year's three entries down for
the season, the US was content with two spots in the top 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said, `Just attack,' '' said Kyoko Ina, who was sitting in
sixth with John Zimmerman. ``We just wanted to skate clean.'' So
did Tiffany Scott of Hanson, Mass., and partner Philip Dulebohn,
who were ninth in their world debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've skated against everybody here, but not all together,''
said the 22-year-old Scott, who was skating juniors only three
years ago. ``We told ourselves it was just another competition.
People in the crowd, frozen water. It's all the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Though their skating was crisp and clean, Scott and Dulebohn
were hung with rookie marks, including a brutal pair of 4.7s from
Czech judge Jarmila Portova. ``We're still kind of new,'' shrugged
Scott. ``It's a game. But I'm willing to wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, the men twiddled their thumbs for nearly
eight hours while their field was being whittled from 47 to 30 for
Tuesday's short program. ``That stupid qualifying round is over,''
exulted two-time champion Alexei Yagudin of Russia, who landed a
quadruple toe loop to win his group ahead of US champion Michael
Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to get off the ground,'' said Weiss, the defending
bronze medalist. ``It would have been nice to have hit the quad,
obviously, but I have to save something for later.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Goebel did hit a quad salchow-triple toe combination but
missed most everything else in a nightmarish program that included
a fall on another quad, a single axel, and a step-out on a triple
flip. ``It stunk,'' admitted Goebel, who ended up eighth in his
group, which Canada's Elvis Stojko won ahead of Russia's Evgeny
Plushenko. ``That was not a world-level program. I have no idea
what happened. I've been training extremely well here. I really
don't know what went wrong. There is no excuse for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Goebel, who figured to contend for a medal here after finishing
third in the Grand Prix final, needs at least to climb back into
the top 10 if the US is to earn back a third men's spot for next
year's world championships in Vancouver. ``Next year is so far
away,'' said Weiss. ``I'm just trying to get through this year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
