<HEADER>
A0283 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SCI-TRANSPLANT-BOS &LR;      03-28 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-TRANSPLANT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPTIMISM ON ANIMAL-TO-HUMAN ORGAN TRANSPLANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Despite daunting scientific and ethical issues, biotech
companies are closing in on a new generation of animal-to-human
organ transplants, with one top executive predicting that her
company could be ready to implant pig hearts or kidneys in patients
within two to five years.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, none of the few dozen patients who have received a
solid animal organ _ called xenotransplantation _ survived for long
and most died almost immediately, largely because their immune
systems treated the organs like an invader. In recent years, a few
patients have survived the wait for a human organ by being hooked
up to a pig organ kept outside the body.
</P>
<P>
   Though the stubborn problem of the patient's immune system
rejecting foreign organs hasn't been overcome, new techniques for
overcoming rejection are showing promise in experimental animals,
said Corinne Savill, chief operating officer of Imutran, based in
Cambridge, England.
</P>
<P>
   ``Xenotranplantation has a lot of hurdles to overcome,'' she
said, ``but we are getting monkeys to live two to three months on a
pig heart or kidney,'' Savill said.
</P>
<P>
   Tried without much success for decades, xenotransplantation
continues in research because of the drastic and worsening shortage
of human organs for patients who could be saved from death if
substitute organs were available. One analyst has estimated that
the market for pig kidneys, lungs and hearts could exceed $6
billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   Savill was among several scientists, regulators and company
sponsors of xenotransplant research who spoke at the Bio2000
conference in Boston on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of animal transplants has been clouded by fears
that dangerous viruses could be transferred to patients along with
the organ, and scientists previously discovered that pigs _ the
most likely organ donors _ harbor a specific type of retrovirus in
their own cells.
</P>
<P>
   Savill presented reassuring data from a 1999 study in which she
and officials from British biotech company Imutran probed the blood
of dozens of monkeys given pig organs, as well as a number of
patients who had received animal transplants, in search of viruses
that might have made their way from the organs into the hosts. They
found none.
</P>
<P>
   None of the patients, however, had received solid organs, but
instead had undergone less intrusive procedures such as skin grafts
from pigs, or had had pancreatic islet cells (which produce
insulin) from pigs. Still others had had their circulation hooked
up to pig livers outside their bodies to cleanse their blood
temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Savill's experiment does not end worries over
animal-to-human infections, a subject that still preoccupies
scientists and regulators, such as the Food and Drug
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the survival rate for patients who have received solid
animal organs remains grim: In 1992, a human patient in Poland
survived just 24 hours with a pig heart, while, in 1996, a patient
in India died during a similar operation.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, some of the only xenograft experiments are being
carried out by a Boston biotech company, Diacrine Inc., in
collaboration with Genzyme. Surgeons have transplanted fetal pig
brain cells into patients with Parkinson's disease and Huntington's
disease, and the researchers have reported improvement in some
patients. Moreover, examination of a patient who died confirmed
that the fetal cells had survived for eight months in the
recipient's brain.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the tough medical issues, xenotransplantation
raises ethical and social questions.
</P>
<P>
   John Logan, a vice president at Nextran Inc., a Princeton, N.J.,
company, said that recruiting patients will be difficult because of
stringent safety precautions. Volunteers need to give large amounts
of blood recurringly to test for any viruses that may have infected
them from the transplant. They will have to promise to use birth
control for the rest of their lives, and to get family and close
friends to agree to be tested as well, to track any infections.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, volunteers will probably have to take
immunosuppressive drugs forever because the rejection battle is
still not won. Even getting ethics boards to approve the
experiments will be difficult because most board members have only
a ``primitive'' knowledge of xenotransplantation, Logan said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
