<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLE IN THE SOX? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUNEDIN, Fla. _ Worriers make me nervous. I don't like to get
into cars with worried drivers; don't like to accept food from
worried chefs; and don't like to play pickup ball with worried
point guards, quarterbacks, and goalies.
</P>
<P>
   This is all covered extensively in the Holley Lama's manifesto,
soon to be available online for free. We don't have time to explore
that entire document, but let me say this: When sports worriers
come my way _ you can always see the angst in their eyes _ I search
for exits. With that said, it's time for a confession.
</P>
<P>
   I am officially worried about the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Their 8-17 Grapefruit League record has nothing to do with it.
They were a 10-minute drive from Jimy Williams's offseason home
when they lost to the Blue Jays on Monday at Dunedin Stadium, 8-6.
They lost. Who cares? The Martinez Brothers, Nomar Garciaparra,
Troy O'Leary, Derek Lowe, and Mike Stanley didn't even make the
two-hour bus ride here from Fort Myers.
</P>
<P>
   Even if they had come, they wouldn't have been on the mound
starting for Boston. That job belonged to Jeff Fassero. Fassero is
a pleasant man. But if you've got any restless habits you are
trying to shake, you don't want to watch him pitch. You want to vow
to stop biting your fingernails after he starts. I'd like to tell
you that it's only spring and not to worry, but Fassero is no
spring pitcher; he's slated as Boston's third starter.
</P>
<P>
   Worried yet?
</P>
<P>
   In the first inning, Fassero threw a backdoor slider to Raul
Mondesi. Such pitches are supposed to be discreet, hence the name.
But the pitch Fassero threw was so wide and visible that I swear I
saw a ``How's My Driving?'' sticker on the seams. Mondesi saw it,
too, and easily yanked the pitch over the left-field fence.
</P>
<P>
   Disclaimer: Fassero said he wouldn't throw that pitch during the
regular season.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth inning, third baseman Tony Batista faced Fassero.
There was a pitch and, suddenly, there was a baseball heading over
the left-field fence.
</P>
<P>
   Disclaimer: The wind was blowing out all day, thus making home
runs easier to hit.
</P>
<P>
   Following his five-inning, four-run performance, Fassero said he
had his best overall outing of the spring. Mostly, he kept the ball
down and forced the Blue Jays to hit a lot of ground balls.
Williams said Fassero pitched well and emphasized that he is a
starter, not a reliever. By giving up only four runs, Fassero
lowered his spring ERA to 7.71 (it had been 7.94). He gave up 35
home runs last season. In 16 innings, he's allowed seven homers.
</P>
<P>
   It should also be noted that very few pitchers in Major League
history have been winners past age 35. Fassero is 37.
</P>
<P>
   (I've got a copy of a CD entitled ``The Big Calm'' with me, so
there is no panic over here. But I can't say there hasn't been a
little seat squirming.)
</P>
<P>
   I can easily argue against myself in several areas. Fassero has
had one bad year _ last year _ in his career. It is still spring
training, where the sad Minnesota Twins are the fourth-best team in
the 20-team Grapefruit League. And, don't forget, this time last
year I went on record and said the Sox would win 80 games.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just Fassero. As the exhibition games come to a close,
I'm starting to ask myself questions that don't have the best
answers.
</P>
<P>
   Question: Whose rotation would you rather have, Boston's, New
York's, or Cleveland's?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: Let me think about that for a while.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox have Pedro and Ramon Martinez, Fassero, Tim Wakefield,
and either Brian Rose or Juan Pena. In other words, one dominant
pitcher, three questions, and a .500 reliable (Wakefield). The
Yankees have Orlando Hernandez, Roger Clemens, David Cone, Andy
Pettitte, and, probably, Ramiro Mendoza. No dominant pitcher, but
fewer questions. The Indians have Bartolo Colon, Chuck Finley, Dave
Burba, Charles Nagy, and Jaret Wright. Four solids and one question
(Wright).
</P>
<P>
   Is this enough for the Sox to win the World Series?
</P>
<P>
   All spring, Sox players have been giggling at fans and media
predicting greatness. Their response is always something like this:
We basically have the same team we had last year and didn't win the
World Series, so why pick us now? I giggled with them until Monday.
And then I found myself saying, ``Good question.''
</P>
<P>
   I guess it's progress that I am not worried about a few of the
team's roster moves, although they make me nervous. It looks as if
the Sox are prepared to send the versatile and speedy Donnie Sadler
to the minors. On some jaunts from first to third, Sadler breaks
the sound barrier. Imagine Carl Everett, Jose Offerman, and Sadler
in the same lineup. The Sox have never had such swift runners.
</P>
<P>
   If Sadler is sent down, it will mean the Sox released Marty
Cordova and optioned Sadler in the same week. Replacing them will
be Jeff Frye and Gary Gaetti, both of whom I like very much. I
would still take the Cordova-Sadler ticket over Frye-Gaetti, even
though I love the stories Gaetti has to tell.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this is all premature. The season begins in a week and
nothing is clear until July's All-Star break. But I've still got
this urge to bite my nails.
</P>
<P>
   (Michael Holley is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
