<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMETS-LIFE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GUNSHOT HELPS IN UNDERSTANDING CELESTIAL LINKS TO LIFE ON
EARTH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Experiments with high-speed guns indicate that
comets could have delivered the building blocks of life to Earth
billions of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   An unexpectedly large percentage of organic molecules survived
being shot from a large gun and slammed into a wall of felt at
several miles per second, one researcher reported Monday during a
meeting of the American Chemical Society.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very excited because it's a really new result. . . .
Scientifically, it's extremely interesting,'' said Randall E.
Winans, an organic chemist at Argonne National Laboratory, a U.S.
Energy Department-funded facility in Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   The findings strengthen the suspicion of some scientists that
terrestrial life descended from nonliving organic chemicals that
literally fell from the sky, back when the solar system was young.
</P>
<P>
   From the 1950s to the 1970s, most scientists held a contrary
view: They argued that life had first emerged on Earth itself, a
few billion years ago. Many agreed with the 19th-century naturalist
Charles Darwin that the first organic molecules formed by chance
agglomerations of chemicals in a ``warm little pond.'' Over time,
those molecules supposedly evolved into more and more complex
structures, and eventually into living plants and animals.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1950s, laboratory experiments first showed that
amino acids _ building blocks of proteins, essential to life _
formed readily in flasks of laboratory chemicals that supposedly
simulated Earth's early atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   However, the ``Earth first'' theory of the origin of life fell
on hard times in the 1970s. A big problem was that geological
research revealed Earth's primeval atmosphere possibly didn't
contain enough hydrogen-rich gases to spur the formation of organic
molecules.
</P>
<P>
   Some scientists began to wonder if our ancestral organic
molecules might have formed more easily in outer space, perhaps
within the icy, mountainous chemical snowballs known as comets.
Robotic space probes passed near comets and discovered that they
were indeed packed with organic molecules.
</P>
<P>
   There was one catch, though: As the comets fell to Earth, they
would have heated up from friction with the atmosphere. They would
have become so hot, in fact, that their precious organics might
have totally burned up.
</P>
<P>
   The new research suggests otherwise. Winans and his colleagues
packed five types of amino acids into a tiny projectile, then
inserted it into an 80mm, gunpowder-fueled howitzer with a 40-foot
barrel.
</P>
<P>
   They then fired the organic payload into a wall of
water-drenched felt. After the smoke cleared, they scooped up the
mess and analyzed its chemical constituents with a device called a
mass spectrometer.
</P>
<P>
   To their astonishment, 12 percent of the amino acids had
survived the simulated crash landing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were hoping for at least 1 percent, so we were happy,''
Winans said with a big grin.
</P>
<P>
   His colleagues were J.G. Blank of the geology and geophysics
department at the University of California at Berkeley, Mike J.
Ahrens of Argonne, G.T. Grey III of the Los Alamos National
Laboratory in New Mexico, and Sutatcha Hongsresawat and G.H. Miller
of the geophysical sciences department at the University of
Chicago. Miller has since moved to the University of California at
Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Their research is scheduled for publication in the scientific
journal Origin of Life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-00 1542EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
