<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-KRAFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS' OWNER SAYS `BAD APPLES' DON'T BELONG IN LEAGUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ With two NFL players under indictment on
murder charges, the most violent sport in America is ready to take
a stand against what it's been selling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under certain conditions, certain guys won't be eligible to
play (in the NFL),'' Patriots owner Robert Kraft said Monday during
a break at the annual league meetings. ``There may be certain
antitrust problems or other (legal) problems with that, but I know
as a fan it's how I feel. I'd go for the limit. We're really not
going to have bad apples on our team to the best of our ability.
Coach (Bill) Belichick agrees.''
</P>
<P>
   To some extent, so too does NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue, who
said that a group of team owners and head coaches will meet Tuesday
evening to discuss how the league's antiviolence policy might be
altered to address the reality behind the screaming headlines that
have rocked the league over the past three months _ when first
Carolina Panthers receiver Rae Carruth and later Baltimore Ravens
linebacker Ray Lewis were charged with murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know that most of our players are good citizens, but
the ones who get in trouble generate an enormous amount of negative
publicity for our league,'' Tagliabue said in a statement outlining
his opening remarks to the owners.
</P>
<P>
   Later Tagliabue wisely amended that when asked if the issue of
concern for the league was violent criminal acts by a handful of
its players or merely the bad publicity that came with their
arrests. ``It's not an image issue, it's a substantive issue of
player conduct,'' he said. ``We're trying to help players maintain
themselves professionally and stay out of trouble. Societal
standards are changing and there are raised expectations for
professional athletes, but it's also an issue of general concerns
about the level of violence in our society.''
</P>
<P>
   The league has begun a review of its antiviolence policy and
also has begun to study individual team policies, although Tampa
Bay head coach Tony Dungy said he was not sure this would lead to a
league-wide policy any time soon. ``I know my policy can't go for
the whole league,'' said Dungy, one of several head coaches on the
committee studying the growing problem of criminal behavior among
players. ``What we can do is try to reeducate guys about what is
acceptable and what is not.''
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore Ravens coach Brian Billick, who also is on the
committee, said Tuesday's open forum will be ``a sharing of ideas
about what individual clubs are doing to enhance the education of
our players. It's a starting process of brainstorming. If we see
some viable programs that could be expanded league-wide, all the
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you can't throw the baby out with the bath water. Just
because these things happened, we can't say our entire structure is
not working. You can't junk our whole system because someone
inevitably makes a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Kraft acknowledged that he feels much the same way despite his
strong public stance that certain players with a criminal
background be banned from the NFL. The problem, as he sees it, is
finding a balance between a desire to keep the league's image clean
and a sometimes counterbalancing desire to win football games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to think we have a high standard, but we're also a
microcosm of society,'' Kraft said. ``We're not trying to be Boy
Scouts about it. We want to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no perfect solution. We want to develop as strong a
support system as we can. And we want to screen as best we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue also spoke of teams begining to use an employment
screening process similar to what other businesses have designed to
eliminate potential employees whose history might make them likely
to make headlines off the job rather than on it. ``Some clubs are
doing in-depth screening of draft-eligible players,'' said the
commissioner. ``They're using tests employers generally use. Some
have suggested we do it league-wide to identify people who might
need support and counseling.''
</P>
<P>
   Although no major change is expected in league policy on players
involved in violent off-field altercations or criminal behavior,
Kraft said it is clear to him that the issue must be addressed. ``I
feel strongly the American public is fed up,'' Kraft said.
``They're sick of it. We in the NFL need to be mindful of that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
