<DOCNO> NYT20000328.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0288 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECHNO-REVERSE-BOS &LR;      03-28 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNO-REVERSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWSUIT PUTS `REVERSE' ENGINEERING TO THE TEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The computer experts who recently found a way to defeat the
popular Net filtering program Cyber Patrol think they're striking a
blow for freedom of thought.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsystems Software, the Massachusetts company that made
the software, thinks the hackers are just a couple of thieves,
swiping computer software that doesn't belong to them.
</P>
<P>
   Who's right? It depends on how the federal courts interpret the
laws governing ``reverse engineering,'' the common but sometimes
controversial business of analyzing somebody else's software.
</P>
<P>
   Reverse engineering can be a legitimate business tool. But
Microsystems executives say that it's being used in this case to
violate their intellectual property rights and ruin their business.
</P>
<P>
   ``These pointless and malicious acts damage the company,'' said
Microsystems attorney Irwin Schwartz. ``But worse still, they
undermine parents' ability to protect their children from
inappropriate or sexually explicit material on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the sort of material Cyber Patrol is
</P>
<P>
   supposed to filter out. But Eddy Jansson of Sweden and Matthew
Skala of Canada used reverse engineering to decipher the list of
Web sites that Cyber Patrol blocks.
</P>
<P>
   They then produced a program, called CPHack, that will let any
Cyber Patrol user decipher the list and that also deciphers the
main password for Cyber Patrol. Anybody with this password can turn
off Cyber Patrol, thus defeating the purpose of the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think they are more capable of judging the wisdom of kids
looking at these materials than the parents of the kids
themselves,'' said Schwartz, who filed suit against Jansson, Skala,
and their ISPs in a Boston federal court.
</P>
<P>
   That court has issued a temporary restraining order against the
two men, requiring that they stop distributing CPHack. The court
will hold another hearing on the matter today and may issue a
preliminary injunction against Jansson and Skala.
</P>
<P>
   To show support for the two men, Net users around the world have
put copies of CPHack on their own sites. Schwartz said that
Microsystems Software is contacting these users' Internet service
providers, demanding they delete the software from their customers'
sites. That move has roused the anger of the American Civil
Liberties Union, which will appeared in court Monday to support the
right of Net users to post the software.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of the case could turn on whether the court decides
Jansson and Skala had a right to reverse engineer Cyber Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   Reverse engineering is hardly new. Companies routinely take
apart competing products to see how they work. But it's a little
more complicated when the product is a piece of software.
</P>
<P>
   This software is created as ``source code,'' written by humans
in a particular computer language, such as Java or C++. This source
code is then run through a program called a compiler, which
converts it into an ``executable'' digital file that the computer
can understand.
</P>
<P>
   Only a handful of extremely smart people could understand this
digital language. But there are programs that can ``decompile'' the
code. In this way, someone can recreate the original source code
and discover how the program works. But the recreated code is
protected by copyright law, and a software maker who re-used
somebody's source code could be taken to court.
</P>
<P>
   But what if the reverse engineers don't want to copy a program,
but simply figure out how it works? In a number of such cases,
courts have declared that reverse engineering is perfectly legal.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Sega Enterprises Ltd., the maker of home computer game
consoles, sued a firm called Accolade Inc., which was making
unauthorized games for use on Sega equipment. Accolade had used
reverse engineering to learn how to make their games
Sega-compatible. Sega claimed Accolade had no right to do this, but
a federal appeals court held that Accolade had a right to study
Sega's source code to produce a compatible product.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Zittrain, lecturer on technology law at Harvard Law
School, says the case established a key principle for reverse
engineering. ``It's not legal if what you're doing is literally
ripping off the product,'' Zittrain said. ``It is legal if you are
reverse engineering to learn about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The same rule came into play earlier this year, when a federal
court held that Connectix Corp. could legally produce a program
that would allow owners of Apple Macintosh computers to play games
written for Sony's PlayStation game console.
</P>
<P>
   But does the principle apply in the Cyber Patrol case? Both
Accolade and Connectix made products that were intended to enhance
the products of Sega and Sony. But Microsystems argues that Jansson
and Skala are seeking to ruin the market for their product.
</P>
<P>
   ``The effect of the use in the affected market is essentially to
destroy the product's functionality,'' agrees Steve Bauer, partner
at the Boston law firm Testa, Hurwitz &AMP; Thibeault, and a specialist
in intellectual property law. For that reason, Bauer is skeptical
the court will side with Jansson and Skala.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Pamela Samuelson, a law professor at the
University of California at Berkeley, believes that CPHack was
mainly created to learn about how Cyber Patrol functions, and to
share that information with others.
</P>
<P>
   ``What these people did here was to go inside to try to learn
something, which is the same thing they did in the Sega v. Accolade
case,'' said Samuelson.
</P>
<P>
   Even if CPHack causes harm to Microsystems Software, Samuelson
said, it can still be a legal product if it serves a legitimate
purpose, such as public education.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, the Cyber Patrol case is likely to provide
the software industry with an education on how far reverse
engineering can go.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
