<P>
   HOLBROOKE'S CAMPAIGN
</P>
<P>
   HOLBROOKE-CENTERPIECE _ Richard Holbrooke, the U.S. ambassador
to the United Nations, wants to improve U.S.-U.N. relations and
re-engage America in the world. He also wouldn't mind being Al
Gore's secretary of state. By James Traub.
</P>
<P>
   CAPITAL OFFENSE
</P>
<P>
   JUSTICE-CENTERPIECE _ On Feb. 24, a new Gallup poll revealed
that American support for capital punishment has fallen to 66
percent, its lowest level in 19 years. And only 52 percent favor
the death penalty if the law were to allow a life sentence without
parole. Just as remarkable, 91 percent (an 11 percent rise from
last year) recognized that innocent people have been sentenced to
death. By Bruce Shapiro.
</P>
<P>
   WATER: A SOLUBLE _ AND SOLVABLE _ PROBLEM
</P>
<P>
   PRIVATIZE-WATER-ECONOMIST _ What could be more basic to life
than a drink of water? Yet more than a billion people have no
access to safe water. Three times as many lack adequate sanitation.
World demand for fresh water is expected to grow sharply, by 70
percent (for household use) by 2025. Shortages seem inevitable,
which could lead to war. This dismal reckoning lies behind the big
world water summit held in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN'S DARE, CHINA'S SCARE
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-`ONE-CHINA'-ECONOMIST _ Taiwan's election, which ended 50
years of Nationalist rule and chose as the island's next president
Chen Shui-bian, the candidate of a hitherto pro-independence party,
is a clear rebuff to China's Communists, who claim Taiwan as their
own. What will China do now? The only solution remains for the two
sides to decide together, through negotiation, whether they are to
be one China or two.
</P>
<P>
   GREENSPAN'S DRIP-TORTURE STRATEGY IS DANGEROUS
</P>
<P>
   RISKY-FED-RATES-ECONOMIST _ Pour boiling water on a frog and it
will jump away; heat it up slowly in a pot of cold water, and it
will die. America's Federal Reserve, which raised short-term
interest rates by another quarter-point to 6 percent on March 21,
may need reminding of this tale. The Fed's strategy of slowing an
overheating economy by raising rates gradually might prove just as
risky for America _ and for the world economy, as well.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA ISN'T PAKISTAN'S SIAMESE TWIN
</P>
<P>
   RESPECT-INDIA-OPED-IHT (New Delhi, India) _ India resents being
treated by U.S. policy as a Siamese twin of Pakistan. It also frets
at the respect accorded to China, to the extent that Washington has
let Beijing off the hook on its nuclear and missile transfers to
Pakistan. India would like Washington to be on the side of the
world's largest democracy, not on the side of the world's largest
autocracy. By Brahma Chellaney.
</P>
<P>
   WHY RISING GAS PRICES KEEP AL GORE AWAKE AT NIGHT
</P>
<P>
   GORE-GAS-PAINS-INDEPENDENT (Washington) _ With the stock market
up since President Clinton took office, unemployment and crime both
down, and the world _ however uneasily _ at peace, the status quo
should work in Al Gore's favor. But eight months is a very long
time in electoral politics, and recent days have foreshadowed just
how much could go wrong between now and Nov. 7, and how much is
actually out of Gore's control. By Mary Dejevsky.
</P>
<P>
   `E-WASTE': TOXIC COMPUTER PARTS POSE POLLUTION NIGHTMARE
</P>
<P>
   TOXIC-COMPUTERS-INDEPENDENT _ Millions of redundant computers
and their highly toxic components are storing up a huge hidden
environmental problem in Britain and America. If action is not
taken soon, campaigners say, the countries will have billions of
pounds of hazardous contaminants in their soils. The full scale of
the potential pollution nightmare can be judged by the U.S.
experience. By Paul Lashmar.
</P>
<P>
   MASSACHUSETTS IN HOT WATER OVER BOYCOTT. TEA, ANYONE?
</P>
<P>
   MASS.-VS.-MYANMAR-ECONOMIST _ Call it a case of states' rights
vs. nations' wrongs. Little Massachusetts is once again standing up
for the democratic values it so boldly asserted before the American
Revolution. Then it boycotted English imports by tossing crates of
tea into Boston Harbor. Today the state is boycotting companies
that do business with Myanmar, home of one of the world's harshest
military regimes. Alas, two lower federal courts have ruled that
Massachusetts' well-intentioned foray into foreign affairs is
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   PRIMARY COLOR: QUIRKY MOMENTS ON THIS WEEK'S CAMPAIGN TRAIL
</P>
