   FICKLE FANS, JOCKS FLOCK TO EVER-NEW ARENAS
</P>
<P>
   DOOMED-JOCK-PARKS-SE-ECONOMIST _ During the past decade about
half the stadiums in the nation that house football, baseball,
basketball or hockey games have been replaced _ usually to lure new
teams to a city, or, in the case of Seattle, to prevent the
departure of existing teams. What's going on?
</P>
<P>
   THE TAXING DILEMMA OF E-COMMERCE
</P>
<P>
   TAXMAN-INTERNET-ECONOMIST _ With the Internet currently
displacing motherhood and apple pie at the top of the list of
American virtues, proposals to tax the Net are not popular. But if
e-commerce grows as quickly as predicted, failing to tax it could
do serious damage to the finances of America's state and local
governments, which depend on sales taxes for much of their
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   `CHOLO' ALEJANDRO TOLEDO: PERU'S FAIRY-TALE CANDIDATE
</P>
<P>
   FUJIMORI-RIVAL-ECONOMIST _ Political fairy tales are not unknown
in Peru. In 1990, a university rector named Alberto Fujimori rose
from nowhere in the final weeks of a presidential election campaign
to trounce Mario Vargas Llosa, a world-famous novelist. Now
Fujimori is seeking a third term in an election on April 9. He has
seemed assured of easy victory. Yet suddenly he has a serious
challenger.
</P>
<P>
   TERABEAM: THE NEXT TELECOMS GIANT?
</P>
<P>
   TERABEAM-ME-UP-ECONOMIST _ When it comes to ground-breaking
technology and ingenious new Internet businesses, the `digerati'
who show up for Esther Dyson's annual PC Forum are blase to the
point of weariness. That makes the buzz caused last week by
Seattle-based TeraBeam Networks all the more remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   THE NEW-AGE DOG
</P>
<P>
   CANINE-CENTERPIECE _ Having had the civilizing influences of
organic dog chow, calming balms and organic medicine foisted upon
them, is it any wonder that our pampered pooches just want to get
back to their doggie-dog roots? By Charles Siebert.
</P>
<P>
   BORIS BEREZOVSKY: KREMLIN PUPPETEER OR FUTURE PUTIN VICTIM?
</P>
<P>
   BORIS-BEREZOVSKY-ECONOMIST _ Will Boris Berezovsky, Russia's
oligarch-extraordinaire, see out the year in jail, exile or the
comfortable nook between business and government that he currently
occupies? The answer will give a clear sign of where the country is
headed under Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
   VLADIMIR PUTIN: RUSSIA'S POST-COLD WARRIOR
</P>
<P>
   THREE-FACES-PUTIN-ECONOMIST _ Spies are good at concealing their
motives. Presumably Vladimir Putin, most of whose working life has
been spent with the KGB, is no exception. Does he come to power
with the bottled-up energies of a hitherto frustrated reformer,
determined to take Russia into Europe? Or does his heart lie in the
paranoid, ruthless old world of the Cold War Soviet security
services? Or is he in reality a Kremlin insider, a crafty
new-Russian power-broker who revels in sleaze and arm-twisting? Any
one of these three faces could be the real Putin, the other two
just political disguises.
</P>
