<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 15:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0291 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     03-28 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNUBBING THE FED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why isn't the stock market bothered by the Federal Reserve's
campaign to raise interest rates?
</P>
<P>
   That's the obvious question to ask in light of last week's big
rally. The Fed raised rates last Tuesday, its fifth rate hike in
recent months, and investors reacted as they have to each of the
past hikes: They bid up the price of stocks. The Nasdaq is back
within striking distance of 5000 and the Dow Jones industrial
average is in the neighborhood of 11,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market seems impervious to rate increases,'' said Ned
Riley, chief investment strategist at State Street Global Advisors.
</P>
<P>
   Call us old-fashioned, but we were brought up to believe that
higher interest rates are bad for stocks. Did someone change the
rules without telling us? More significantly, is there some logic
to the market's behavior?
</P>
<P>
   Money managers and economists are divided on the question. But
when pushed, they came up with some plausible explanations for the
current state of affairs.
</P>
<P>
   They say stocks are ignoring the Fed because:
</P>
<P>
   --The market is awash in liquidity. Investors pumped $65 billion
into equity funds in the first two months of the year, according to
Riley. That money has buoyed stock prices, in effect, offsetting
the Fed's handiwork.
</P>
<P>
   --Long-term rates are falling. The rate on the 30-year Treasury
bond has dropped to 6 percent, down from nearly 6.75 percent in
January. The reason? The government is using money from the budget
surplus to buy back debt. Barry Evans, chief fixed-income officer
at John Hancock Funds, says that those lower long-term rates are
also offsetting the Fed's attempt to rein in the economy.
</P>
<P>
   --Investors in tech stocks are looking to the distant future.
The logic here goes like this: The hottest tech firms are
relatively young companies whose earnings payoff may be three to
five years out. With such a long time horizon, who cares if
interest rates are a little higher or a little lower? If you have
your money in the next Cisco _ doesn't everyone? _ you won't even
notice the difference.
</P>
<P>
   --Investors are counting on the Fed to engineer a soft landing.
``The market is envisioning a rosy scenario,'' said Wayne Ayers,
chief economist at FleetBoston Financial Corp. Under that scenario,
the Fed raises rates a little more _ say 50 basis points _ the
economy slows down modestly, productivity keeps rising, and
inflation remains under control. As Dr. Pangloss put it in
``Candide,'' ``All is for the best in this best of all possible
worlds.''
</P>
<P>
   We don't buy it. From where we sit, it looks as if investors are
in a deep state of denial.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, the economy shows few signs of slowing down. Gross
domestic product climbed at a 7 percent rate in the fourth quarter
of 1999 and most forecasters are looking for about 5 percent growth
in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed would be more comfortable with a number like 3 percent.
What's more, it is clear from everything the Fed has said and
published that the central bank means business. ``It is inevitable
that the Fed will slow the economy,'' said Mark Zandi, chief
economist at RFA Dismal Sciences, a Pennsylvania forecasting firm.
``It is a just a question of how much higher rates will have to go
to accomplish that.''
</P>
<P>
   In the just-released minutes from the February meeting of the
Federal Open Market Committee, Fed officials worried aloud about
the ``imbalances'' in the economy and the budding inflationary
pressures.
</P>
<P>
   Several committee members also thought it might be time to raise
rates by 50 basis points, instead of the 25-basis-point doses
Greenspan seems to favor.
</P>
<P>
   There is no indication the chairman is ready to take such
drastic action, but you have to wonder if the thought hasn't
crossed his mind. If you hit the economy with a stick and nothing
happens, maybe you need to use a two-by-four?
</P>
<P>
   Zandi thinks the federal funds rates, currently at 6 percent,
could easily go to 7 percent and possibly higher by the end of the
year. If he's right, you have to think the news can't be good for
stocks. Those higher rates will produce a slower economy, weaker
profits, more hesitant consumers, and quite possibly a crack in the
belief that tomorrow will always be better than yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   So far investors have chosen to ignore the Fed. We're betting
that they won't be able to do that forever.
</P>
<P>
   (Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
