<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0294 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-28 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PASSING THE BATON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Kenneth Galbraith is an old man now, no longer spry at 91
but active. For fifty years he has been the single most visible
symbol of the American Left: not socialist but rather
associationist, in contrast to the creed of individualism that has
made such headway in the past 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Private affluence, public squalor is the essence of the
Galbraithian diagnosis. Always there has been a prescription as
well: from price controls to progressive taxation to micro-lending.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of benchmarks help put this associationist impulse in
American historical perspective. Next Monday evening at 10, PBS
will air ``Brother Can You Spare a Billion? The Story of Jesse H.
Jones.'' The Texas developer and banker was chairman of the
Reconstruction Finance Corp. under Franklin Roosevelt and later
secretary of commerce.
</P>
<P>
   The RFC was a government business partnership conceived under
Herbert Hoover that pumped plenty of public money into American
businesses, the railroads in particular, without much effect.
Arlington filmmaker Eric Stange's documentary is a vivid reminder
that government-directed industrial policy is the great Road Not
Taken in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Similar is David Hart's book ``Forged Consensus: Science,
Technology and Economic Policy in the United States, 1921-1953,''
which chronicles the ins and outs of an all but forgotten debate
about the governance of technological change in the years before
and immediately after World War II _ including the attempt by
Senator Harley Kilgore of West Virginia to create an Office of
Technology Mobilization with the power to oversee all federal
research and development.
</P>
<P>
   Among the partisans of these New Deal battles, only Galbraith is
still standing, and differences of opinion that once seemed great
have lost their power to divide. Since 1958, when he published
``The Affluent Society,'' but especially since 1967 when ``The New
Industrial State'' appeared, Galbraith has been the foremost
exponent of the view that oversight by government and business
technocrats working together was the best way to bind communities
and ameliorate the lot of their least fortunate members.
</P>
<P>
   He has, in other words, been on the losing end of a lot of
arguments.
</P>
<P>
   So who is there to carry on? Well, a potent clue may be obtained
from the Global Development and Environment Institute, an
associationist think tank administered by the Fletcher School of
Law and Diplomancy and the faculty of arts and sciences at Tufts
University.
</P>
<P>
   The institute is in some part a vehicle for the enthusiasms of
Neva Rockefeller Goodwin, its codirector with Tufts professor
William Moomjaw. On Monday, she awarded its first Leontief Prize
for Advancing the Fronters of Economic Thought jointly to Galbraith
and Amartya Sen.
</P>
<P>
   Leontief? He was a longtime Harvard professor whose career as an
economist ranged from Czarist jails during the Russian Revolution
to the forefront of quantitative methods and, eventually, a Nobel
Prize. In later years he became a pungent critic of mathematical
economics for its divorce from pressing policy concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Sen, who is master of Trinity College at Cambridge University
and professor emeritus at Harvard University, is no stranger to
mathematical economics. But since his boyhood in India he has been
among the profession's foremost students of the relationship
between human well-being and economic growth. His Nobel citation
credited him for having ``restored an ethical dimension to the
discussion of economic problems.''
</P>
<P>
   At age 66, Sen doesn't have the same demotic touch nor the
stylistic flair of the older man (Galbraith wrote for a time for
Fortune magazine.) He is, instead, a formidable institutional
politician and policy entrepreneur.
</P>
<P>
   But no one who has read ``Development as Freedom'' can doubt
that Sen is Galbraith's most prominent heir, as an intellectual and
humanitarian. And anyone who considers the history of the last 250
years will be heartened by a line of implacable optimism from the
journals of Ralph Waldo Emerson: ``I am defeated all the time, yet
to victory I am born.''
</P>
<P>
   (David Warsh is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
