<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0297 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v BC-CELL-PHONE-SAFETY-BJT     03-28 0475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELL-PHONE-SAFETY-BJT-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; March 28,2000 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As cell phones explode in popularity _ 30,000 new users are
being added daily to the total of 86 million existing users in the
United States _ federal regulators are questioning whether the
microwaves emitted by cell phones pose a health hazard.
</P>
<P>
   A cell phone emits microwave radiation through its antenna, with
the radiation field concentrated near the user's head. The
assumption for years had been that the low-level radiation emitted
by a cell phone antenna was safe.
</P>
<P>
   However, that assumption is now being re-examined by federal
safety regulators as the result of two industry-sponsored studies.
</P>
<P>
   While federal safety regulators say there is no evidence that
cell phones are safe _ or that they are unsafe _ the two studies
raise questions that have led the U.S. Food and Drug Administration
to sponsor more research on cell phone safety.
</P>
<P>
   In a package of stories, photos and graphics for release Sunday,
April 2, the Hearst Newspapers and The San Antonio Express-News
explain how the safety issue originated and what is being done to
resolve it.
</P>
<P>
   The sheer number of cell phone users ``translates into a
potentially significant public health problem,'' if the devices
even slightly increase the risk of health problems, the FDA says.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the story lineup:
</P>
<P>
   CELL-PHONE-SAFETY (Washington) _ Federal safety regulators are
investigating cell phones to determine whether the microwave
radiation they emit might cause cancer or other diseases. By ERIC
ROSENBERG and JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   With photos: CELL-PHONE-BASILE and CELL-PHONE-
</P>
<P>
   ANGELOS.
</P>
<P>
   With graphics: CELL-PHONE-REVENUES and CELL-PHONE-USERS.
</P>
<P>
   CELL-PHONE-WORKS (Washington) _ A cell phone works by using
microwaves to transmit pulses of radio energy through the phone's
antenna to a base station. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic: CELL-PHONE-WORKS.
</P>
<P>
   CELL-PHONE-PRECAUTIONS (Washington) _ If you're concerned about
the microwave radiation from your cell phone, the Food and Drug
Administration advises that you take a few precautions. By ERIC
ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic: CELL-PHONE-PRECAUTIONS.
</P>
<P>
   CELL-PHONE-CARLO (Washington) _ After the cell telephone
industry asked scientist George Carlo to oversee $27 million in
research on cell phone safety, he spent the next six years managing
40 studies. When Carlo reported back that some of the studies
raised safety questions requiring further investigation, this began
the career of George Carlo, whistleblower. By JENNIFER CORBETT
DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   With: photo CELL-PHONE-CARLO.
</P>
<P>
   - - - - -
</P>
