<DOCNO> NYT20000328.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0298 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CELL-PHONE-SAFETY-RDP     03-28 1765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELL-PHONE-SAFETY-RDP-$ADV02-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FEDERAL INVESTIGATORS PROBE CELL PHONE SAFETY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, April 2)   &HT;     (Photos: CELL-PHONE-BASILE and CELL-PHONE-ANGELOS)   (Graphics:
CELL-PHONES-REVENUES,CELL-PHONE-USERS)  
 &HT;     For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   By ERIC
ROSENBERG and JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN   c.2000 Hearst
<TEXT>
Newspapers &LR;  &QC; WASHINGTON _ Federal safety regulators are
investigating whether microwave radiation from cell phones causes
cancer or other diseases.
<P>
   The probe was triggered by two industry-sponsored studies that
the U.S. Food and Drug Administration said require additional
research.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA hastens to add that there is no scientific basis for
concluding that cell phones are unsafe _ or that they are safe. The
only way to conclusively answer the safety question is through ``a
significant research effort,'' the FDA says.
</P>
<P>
   One study by researchers at the American Health Foundation in
New York found an association between cell phone use and a rare
type of brain tumor. The other study, conducted by Integrated
Laboratory Systems in Research Triangle Park, N.C., found that DNA
in human blood cells breaks down when exposed to large doses of
cell phone radiation, possibly laying the genetic groundwork for
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not sure what this means,'' said Dr. George Carlo, who
headed the industry's $27 million safety research project from 1993
until last year. ``This could be a colossal coincidence or the tip
of the iceberg,'' said Carlo, an epidemiologist and lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   With 86 million cellular phone users in the United States alone
and 30,000 new users signing up daily, ``this translates into a
potentially significant public health problem, should the use of
these devices even slightly increase the risk of adverse health
effects,'' the FDA says.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, the number of cell phone users in the United
States jumped by 10 million. U.S. cell phone sales soared over $37
billion in 1999, up $8 billion over the previous year and $12
billion over 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The Carlo studies showing a possible link between the phones and
illness have caught the attention of Peter Angelos, a prominent
Baltimore attorney who has successfully litigated against the
tobacco industry and asbestos manufacturers. Angelos is
investigating possible legal action against the cellular phone
industry but cautions that more scientific research is needed.
</P>
<P>
   The question of cell phone safety recently led Metrocall of
Alexandria, Va., the nation's third largest pager company and a
major seller of AT&AMP;T cellular phones, to warn its sales staff that
parents buying for a child or young adult should consider a pager
instead of a cell phone ``due to potential health risks.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason, said company officials, is concern that younger
people, whose bodies are still developing, may be more susceptible
to damage from microwave radiation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If an adult comes in with a teenager and says, `I want to buy
my kid a cell phone,' we say this is something that we want to make
you aware of,'' said Michael Scanlon, a senior vice president at
Metrocall.
</P>
<P>
   Carlo's cell phone research project _ which involved dozens of
scientists at universities, hospitals and private laboratories
across the nation over a five-year period _ produced more than 40
studies.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the research showed cell phone use had no effect
on the human body, Dr. Russell Owen, chief of the radiation-biology
branch of the FDA's Center for Devices and Radiological Health,
said the two studies ``raise some interesting scientific questions
but are no cause for alarm.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the new safety research will be coordinated by the FDA
and the cell phone industry represented by the Cellular
Telecommunications Industry Association (CTIA). The first study
will follow-up the North Carolina research on DNA breakdown linked
to cell phone radiation.
</P>
<P>
   That is ``a priority goal,'' said Owen, because _ if the
findings are accurate _ such genetic damage could lead to cancer or
other disorders.
</P>
<P>
   The details of the new research program won't be released until
later this year. It is unclear how long it will take to complete.
Meanwhile, the National Cancer Institute and the World Health
Organization are conducting separate studies on cell phone safety.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about cell phone safety were first raised in 1993 when
a Florida man, David Reynard, filed suit against NEC Corp., a cell
phone manufacturer, claiming his wife Suzy's fatal brain cancer was
caused by her cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   His suit and 12 other suits against cell phone manufacturers
have been dismissed for lack of scientific proof, according to
Angelos.
</P>
<P>
   Public anxieties were further heightened by the brain cancer
deaths of two prominent business executives in 1994 and 1993,
Michael Walsh, the chief executive officer of Tenneco, and Reginald
Lewis the CEO of TLC Beatrice. Both were cell phone users. At the
time, their illnesses sparked a sell off on Wall Street of wireless
industry stocks.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of public concern, the CTIA decided to fund the $27
million research project aimed at assuring consumers that cell
phones are safe.
</P>
<P>
   The industry association argues that cell phones are indeed
safe, despite the two studies that Carlo calls ``red flags.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These are just pieces of a much larger picture, and the larger
picture continues to reaffirm the fact that there are no adverse
health effects from using cellular phones,'' said Jo-Anne Basile,
CTIA's vice president for external and industry relations.
</P>
<P>
   Cell phones use microwave signals to transmit human voice or
data. Microwaves _ a specific category of radio waves _ also have
other applications, the most common of which is to cook food. The
major difference between cell phones and microwave ovens is the
amount of power that propels the signal. Cell phones use low power,
while ovens use high power.
</P>
<P>
   High levels of microwave radiation are known to be dangerous. A
microwave oven, for example, shoots a powerful microwave signal,
propelled by 100 watts of power, at a piece of food and cooks it by
heating its water molecules.
</P>
<P>
   The key question is whether the low level of microwave radiation
used by a cell phone _ a cell phone's microwave signal is propelled
by about 0.6 watts of power _ also can cause harm.
</P>
<P>
   Past research has shown no firm link between microwaves and
cancer, according to the American Cancer Society.
</P>
<P>
   ``While some epidemiological studies suggest associations with
cancer, others do not, and experimental studies have not yet
yielded reproducible evidence of carcinogenic mechanisms,'' ACS
said.
</P>
<P>
   The cell phone's radiation field is concentrated at about three
to four inches around the antenna, near the user's head.
</P>
<P>
   And this is where the potential problems lie.
</P>
<P>
   Current FDA rules on cell phone safety rely on a radiation
measurement called the ``specific absorption rate'' or SAR.
</P>
<P>
   Cell phones are allowed to emit a maximum SAR of 1.6 watts per
kilogram as measured over one gram of body tissue.
</P>
<P>
   However, the FDA now questions whether that safety limit fully
protects consumers. The limit is focused entirely on protecting a
user from phones that actually destroy cells by heating them, the
``thermal'' effect.
</P>
<P>
   This limit may not protect against ``any non-thermal effects of
chronic exposure,'' the agency said. DNA disintegration is an
example of a non-thermal effect.
</P>
<P>
   The 1.6 watt SAR was set in 1996 from the previous limit of 8
watts, following a recommendation from the Institute of Electrical
and Electronics Engineers _ a professional association.
</P>
<P>
   The 8-watt ceiling had been considered safe. But the group
proposed reducing the ceiling, which was first established in 1982
to govern two-way radios,
</P>
<P>
   by a factor of five to ensure that there would be no health
effects caused by cell phone use.
</P>
<P>
   Against this background, the North Carolina researchers at
Integrated Laboratory Systems were surprised to find cell damage
when tissue was exposed to radiation of 5 and 10-watts per kilogram
over a period of 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers found no problems when blood cells were exposed to
radiation of 1 watt per kilogram over a period of 24 hours. They
also found no damage when blood cells were exposed for three hours
at 1, 2.5, 5 and 10-watts per kilogram of radiation.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, problems appeared when blood was exposed to
higher levels of radiation over longer periods of time.
</P>
<P>
   What had previously been considered safe now appeared to pose
some risk. This led to the conclusion that no one knew exactly what
is a safe level of radiation for human exposure.
</P>
<P>
   One of the authors of the study, Dr. Graham Hook, said the
results don't necessarily mean the phones are harmful if they
operate below 5- and 10-watts per kilogram for short periods.
</P>
<P>
   The American Health Foundation used a different kind of
scientific tool known as case control studies. In still-unpublished
preliminary findings, the researchers compared the cell phone
exposure of a group of people with a particular health problem with
another group of people who did not have the condition.
</P>
<P>
   One study compared the cell phone habits of 465 patients newly
diagnosed with brain cancer against a group of 422 non-cell phone
users who did not have the disease. They found no association
between overall brain cancer risk and cell phone usage.
</P>
<P>
   But when the researchers looked at a specific type of brain
cancer _ known as neuronal tumors, which grow from the periphery of
the brain inward _ they found that 14 out of 34 patients with that
kind of cancer were cell phone users. Compared with the control
group, cell phone users had more than double the risk of developing
the tumor.
</P>
<P>
   However, in a somewhat paradoxical finding, the researchers
found that the risk did not increase with the duration of cell
phone use, which they would expect to occur with a carcinogen.
</P>
<P>
   Joshua Muscat, the lead researcher on the study, called the
findings ``not a red flag, but a pale red flag.'' He said that the
link between phones and the rare brain tumor requires a larger
study of larger populations of people.
</P>
<P>
   Muscat also cautioned that the long-term health effects of cell
phone radiation are unknown, adding that there is often a
decades-long latency period among certain types of cancers. ``To be
prudent, surveillance is needed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists from both research projects later briefed the FDA
about their findings. The agency then ordered the new round of
safety investigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-00 1555EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000328.0131 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0299 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CELL-PHONE-CARLO-$ADV     03-28 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELL-PHONE-CARLO-$ADV02-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GEORGE CARLO CAMPAIGNS ON CELL PHONE SAFETY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     For release Sunday, April 2)   &HT;     (With photo: CELL-PHONE-CARLO)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN and ERIC ROSENBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After the telecommunications industry asked
scientist George Carlo to oversee $27 million in research on cell
phone safety, he spent the next six years managing 40 studies at
universities and private labs around the nation.
</P>
<P>
   In findings that neither he nor the industry expected, Carlo
reported back last year that two of the studies raised safety
questions about radiation emitted from the devices. He urged more
industry leadership in researching cell phone safety.
</P>
<P>
   But the industry downplayed Carlo's conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Wheeler, president and chief executive officer of the
Cellular Telecommunications Industry Association (CTIA), said ``the
weight of scientific evidence continues to reaffirm that there are
no adverse health effects from the use of wireless phones.''
</P>
<P>
   CTIA would no longer work with Carlo, Wheeler said, but would
cooperate with the U.S. Food and Drug Administration to design
further studies.
</P>
<P>
   This falling out between Carlo and his former employers in the
cell phone industry marked the start of a new career for Carlo. He
became a cell phone industry gadfly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said we should tell people that we don't know whether cell
phones are safe and that until we do know, users should take
precautions,'' Carlo said, recounting a February 1999 meeting with
cellular phone executives.
</P>
<P>
   No one agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Lacking a receptive audience, Carlo went public with the
scientific findings, which are awaiting publication in a scientific
journal. He's had a cool relationship with the industry ever since.
</P>
<P>
   When he first started the cell phone research project in 1993,
Carlo expected the studies would show that cell phones were
perfectly safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't think we'd find anything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's because it had been widely assumed cell phones couldn't
cause health problems in humans because the phones operated at such
low power.
</P>
<P>
   After he and CTIA went their separate ways, Carlo began working
almost full-time without pay to alert consumers about possible
health effects from cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   His organization published a half-inch thick consumer manual
called ``Wireless Phones and Your Health,'' in which he concludes:
``The science is in a gray area. Phones may or may not cause brain
cancer. Most studies have found no connection, but enough have
found a connection that a potential cannot be ignored.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the two studies that raised questions found an increased
risk of a rare brain tumor in people who used cell phones; the
other study reported genetic damage in blood cells exposed to cell
phone radiation.
</P>
<P>
   Carlo cautions that the two studies don't necessarily mean cell
phones are dangerous and that much more follow-up needs to be done.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, he says consumers should take steps to protect
themselves by using a headset or ear phones to keep the device's
antenna away from the user's head. With such an arrangement, the
antenna and the cell phone are stashed in the user's pocket or on
the user's belt.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1983, Carlo, 46, has run his own company _ currently known
as Health Risk Management Group, of Washington, D.C. _ which
researches public health issues. He received a doctorate in
experimental pathology and epidemiology in 1979 from the State
University of New York at Buffalo and a law degree from George
Washington University in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Carlo blasts the cell phone industry for maintaining that phones
are safe when ``they should say the science is uncertain.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The right approach is, `We don't know,''' he said. ``Consumers
should protect themselves until we find out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We could be on the threshold of a public health disaster,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Or his research could be proven incorrect.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that happens I'd be the happiest guy in the world,'' Carlo
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-00 1557EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
