<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000328.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0300 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CELL-PHONE-PRECAUTION     03-28 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELL-PHONE-PRECAUTIONS-$ADV02-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FIRMS PUSH ANTI-RADIATION DEVICES FOR CELL PHONES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, April 2)   &HT;     (Graphic: CELL-PHONE-PRECAUTIONS)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If you're concerned about the microwave radiation
emitted from your cell phone, the Food and Drug Administration
suggests these precautions:
</P>
<P>
   _ Avoid using cell phones for long durations. ``Time is a key
factor in how much exposure a person receives,'' the agency is
advising consumers. People should use convention telephones for
longer conversations, the agency says.
</P>
<P>
   _ If cell phones must be used for lengthy calls, the FDA advises
switching to a model that places greater distance between the
user's head and the phone ``since the (radiation) exposure level
drops off dramatically with distance.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, headsets or earphones let users make calls while
keeping the antenna several feet from the head. Another example is
a car phone with the antenna on the outside of the car.
</P>
<P>
   The agency also is asking manufacturers to design cell phones
``in a way that minimizes any (radio frequency) exposure to the
user that is not necessary for device function.''
</P>
<P>
   One such model is Motorola's Star-Tac phone series, which have
an antenna that angles the radiation away from a user's head. The
company maintains that the antenna position is driven by the sleek
design and compact size _ not because of any concern about
radiation safety.
</P>
<P>
   While the makers of cell phones maintain that their phones are
safe, some smaller companies sense an emerging ``safety'' market
and are devising accessories to deflect a phone's radiation away
from the user's head.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at the University of Surrey in Britain have
developed what they call a ``smart antenna'' that they say blocks
radiation from the user's head.
</P>
<P>
   The device _ comprised of four mini-antennas twisted to form a
helix _ could be in use by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies are developing special shields to deflect
radiation from the user.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis-based Aegis Corp. sells a shield that the company says
protects the user from up to 99 percent of a cell phone's radiation
emissions. MicroShield of Enfield, England, is selling a cell phone
with a nickel-lined shield.
</P>
<P>
   Integrated Wave Technologies, Inc., of Fremont, Calif., is
marketing a special ``hands-free'' voice activated accessory kit.
The technology allows users to place cell phones several feet away
and use their voices to dial numbers or answer calls, even in
high-noise environments found in vehicles and most other places
phones are used.
</P>
<P>
   Cell phone manufacturers say the safety devices are unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   Jo-Anne Basile, vice president for external and industry
relations for the Cellular Telecommunications Industry Association,
says existing designs are safe. She dismissed shield products as
``people preying on the fears of consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Federal Communications Commission is prodding the
industry to develop a standardized test to ensure that
</P>
<P>
   cell phones don't exceed radiation standards. If there's no
agreement in the next few months among the corporations, the FCC
says it will impose one by this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC also is setting up its own testing equipment to
independently assess whether cell phones exceed the radiation
threshold.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address eric(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
