<HEADER>
A0301 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CELL-PHONE-WORKS-$ADV     03-28 0364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELL-PHONE-WORKS-$ADV02-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HOW A CELL PHONE WORKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, April 2)   &HT;     (With graphic: CELL-PHONE-WORKS.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A cell phone uses microwaves to transmit pulses of
radio energy through the phone's antenna to a larger antenna or
tower at a base station.
</P>
<P>
   The base station is connected to a computerized mobile telephone
switching office (MTSO).
</P>
<P>
   When the phone is turned on, in a split-second it determines
which base station to contact, depending on which has the strongest
signal.
</P>
<P>
   The phone transmits a rapid burst of information _ an electronic
serial number _ to the base station. In a responding burst of
electronic information, the base station assigns a ``channel'' to
the phone on which to conduct a conversation.
</P>
<P>
   The MTSO then assigns the cell-phone caller a voice frequency or
channel to use during a particular conversation. This all takes
place in a fraction of a second.
</P>
<P>
   The MTSO is able to determine whether the call is being made to
another cell phone user or to a person using a conventional phone.
If the call is being made to a conventional phone, the MTSO routes
the call into the local telephone network which then takes over the
call.
</P>
<P>
   If the call is being made to another cell phone user, the MTSO
contacts the other cell phone using microwave signals. The signal
is sent to a series of base stations (and perhaps even a satellite
if the call is long-distance) and then is picked up by the
receiving cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   During the phone call the MTSO's computer is constantly
monitoring the strength of the voice signal. If the signal drops
too low, the MTSO will send the call to a new base station or cell.
The sizes of a cell varies, ranging from two to 10 square miles. A
person using a cell phone in a car may travel through a series of
cells.
</P>
<P>
   It's estimated that there are more than 100,000 base station
antennas in the United States. They can range from a stand-alone
tower rising several hundred feet, to an antenna the size of a
pizza box on the top of a building.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
