<SLUG> BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS TOWN BASKS IN NIKE ADS' SPOTLIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The make-believe town of ``Bracketville,'' a basketball
community conjured up and sponsored by Nike to promote the NCAA
Basketball Tournament, might soon lose its fictional standing and
be swallowed up by the very real South Texas town of Brackettville.
</P>
<P>
   For hundreds, maybe thousands of people, they were never
different places to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   ``The local people are in an uproar about it,'' said
Brackettville City Manager David Luna. ``They want to know how it
happened and what can we do to get more exposure. They love it.''
</P>
<P>
   An ad agency conceived Bracketville, the Nike town with just one
``t.'' The agency designed the town name to reflect the tournament
bracket that outlines the 64 teams that are invited to the national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Brackettville, the Texas town, started as a general store built
near Fort Clark in Kinney County, just 22 miles from the Rio
Grande. Fort Clark was one in a series of forts built to protect
settlers from Comanche and Apache raiding parties. Fort Clark was
also the home of the famous Black Seminole Indian scouts, several
of whom became Medal of Honor winners.
</P>
<P>
   Brackettville is also the home of Alamo Village, the movie set
where John Wayne filmed the epic movie ``The Alamo.'' The set
remains as a family theme park and continues to be a movie set.
</P>
<P>
   The nearly 2,000 people who live in Brackettville appear to like
basketball OK, but there isn't a local college that can aspire to
the national tournament.
</P>
<P>
   In the fictional Bracketville, everybody loves basketball and
the local drive-in theater shows basketball movies all the time.
</P>
<P>
   There isn't a drive-in in Brackettville.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out-of-town people have been calling here asking where they
can go to buy a Nike hat or something, so they can say they bought
it in Brackettville,'' Luna said. ``We have to tell them we don't
have a place in Brackettville that sells Nike products.''
</P>
<P>
   The city manager said he thinks that might change if the
sporting goods company decides to make the Bracketville commercials
a yearly event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have talked to the promotional people who handled the
commercials for Nike and they contacted the company,'' Luna said.
``They let them (Nike) know that all this interest had occurred and
Nike ended up sending 21 boxes of balls and bats and sports-related
items to the schools here.''
</P>
<P>
   Luna said Nike is now the favored brand name at the local
schools, and school teams are hoping for a lasting relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a big-time public relations gain for Nike,''
Luna said of his southwest Texas community between Uvalde and Del
Rio.
</P>
<P>
   Because the public has made a connection between the fictitious
town and the real one, Nike has sent film crews into Brackettville
to shoot additional footage for their commercials.
</P>
<P>
   ``They shot at the courthouse and at the hardware store that's
smack dab in the middle of town,'' Luna said. ``They shot at two or
three places, and I have a feeling there will be more of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The city manager said local people are clamoring for more,
enjoying the new spotlight on their community. ``They want us to do
more, but you and I both know the tournament is winding down and
when it's over, it's over,'' Luna said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are lingering hopes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The schools are quite interested in advertising for Nike. They
think they might get a scoreboard out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly column on things Texan. You can
call him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
