u i BC-CHINA-DISSIDENT-NYT &LR;      03-28 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-DISSIDENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER OFFICIAL CHALLENGES CHINA TO RESPECT HUMAN RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ A former senior official who spent seven years in
prison for sympathizing with democracy advocates has challenged the
authorities to abide by the Chinese Constitution and stop
restricting his freedom to speak out.
</P>
<P>
   The former official, Bao Tong, 67, has risked re-arrest over the
last year and a half with public calls for democratic changes and a
re-appraisal of the 1989 student demonstrations in Tiananmen
Square, which were officially labeled as counter-revolutionary and
violently crushed.
</P>
<P>
   On March 13, as China worked to fend off a U.S.-sponsored
resolution censuring China's rights record at a U.N. meeting in
Geneva, Bao wrote a letter to the Chinese authorities. It was
distributed to reporters Tuesday by Human Rights Watch, a group
based in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In the letter, Bao charged that the government had whitewashed
its human rights record in a recent report and that based on his
own treatment he felt he had to set the record straight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am an old man, and I have neither fear nor illusions, but I
feel obligated to confront such violation of a citizen's civil
rights, even if that means my own imprisonment,'' Bao wrote.
</P>
<P>
   By continuing his lonely advocacy here _ most dissidents are now
in prison or in exile _ Bao is taking a serious risk. Although he
theoretically regained his rights as a citizen in May 1998, he said
in the letter that security agents have since warned him eight
times that his statements ``endangered state security.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Bao granted many interviews to foreign journalists
despite harassment and warnings from officials. In the letter he
said his treatment had worsened in recent months, with six agents
following him day and night.
</P>
<P>
   ``They come with me when I accompany my granddaughter to school,
and when I go to the hospital, bank or shops,'' he wrote. ``They
watch very closely to see who I talk to, what I do and what I
say.''
</P>
<P>
   Bao challenged the authorities to compare his treatment with the
right to free speech enshrined in China's Constitution and laws,
and urged the U.N. Human Rights Commission, which is meeting in
Geneva, to note the inconsistency.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, when student demonstrations in favor of democratic
change erupted, Bao was a senior aide to the Communist Party
chairman at the time, Zhao Ziyang, helping him to plan economic
reforms.
</P>
<P>
   In late May 1989, less than two weeks before the army crushed
the demonstrations in Tiananmen Square and Zhao was ousted for
being too soft, Bao was arrested and imprisoned, ostensibly for
sharing information about the coming crackdown with the students.
</P>
<P>
   After seven years in prison he had two years of virtual house
arrest with no political rights. But in May 1998, when that
probation ended, he defiantly spoke to foreign reporters, saying
China urgently needed political change. He has been under police
scrutiny ever since, required to live in a monitored apartment
where his telephone is sometimes shut off.
</P>
<P>
   His former boss, Zhao, has been under house arrest since 1989
even though no legal charges were filed against him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
