<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATTISMITH-CD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATTI SMITH IS BACK, AND SHE'S STILL `GUNG HO'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Forget the '60s,'' punk/poet icon Patti Smith said in an
interview at last week's South by Southwest conference, ``and the
'70s and the '80s and the '90s. We're living in the 21st century.
There's work to be done and fun to be had.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day she was onstage at Austin's Waterloo Park,
hollering, ``People, the time is now! Wake up! Wake up!'' as her
amazing, two-hour-plus show crashed to a close in a howl of
feedback and shredded guitar strings.
</P>
<P>
   To be a longtime fan was to leave the show with a sense of
profound happiness _ and relief.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is one of the most important, elusive voices to emerge
from the New York punk scene, an adventurer who dared to mix poetry
indebted to Arthur Rimbaud and music indebted to '60s rock and soul
into a shape-changing, valiant whole.
</P>
<P>
   And to see her back _ radiant, singing as well as ever, leading
a crack band and dancing like a high schooler _ is a thrill of
major proportions, because of what she's done, and what she hasn't.
</P>
<P>
   After establishing herself with records such as her 1975 debut
``Horses'' and its follow-up, '76's ``Radio Ethiopia,'' Smith's
career has been one of long gaps, few live appearances, and more
than a little tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   And some of the worst times have been the most recent. Smith
released nothing between 1979's ``Wave'' and 1988's ``Dream of
Life,'' preferring to live in suburban Detroit, raising children
with her husband, former MC5 guitarist Fred ``Sonic'' Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was another long gap _ until 1996, when she put out
``Gone Again.'' That CD, and '97's ``Peace and Noise,'' were dark
records that explored a host of losses: Her husband; former
bandmate Richard Sohl; Kurt Cobain; her brother Todd; and her
one-time roommate Robert Mapplethorpe.
</P>
<P>
   Released last week, ``Gung Ho'' is a far more upbeat,
pop-friendly affair, filled with hope for community and romance _
and historical references that include Ho Chi Minh, the slave trade
and Gen. George Custer's wife. It's as if Smith has been healed by
time and is now ready to take on the world again, and this
positivity and a sense of purpose and immediacy easily carry ``Gung
Ho'' past a few clunker couplets and ``Libbie's Song,'' an
unsuccessful stab at country.
</P>
<P>
   ``One Voice'' begins the CD with these lines: ``In the garden of
consciousness/In fertile mind there lies the dormant seed.'' As the
song progresses, you realize that in Smith's perfect world we would
all help out someone less fortunate. Several songs later, on
``Upright Come,'' she sings ``Swift is the arrow/Dark is the
thorn/The slate is clean/The future awaits/Awake.''
</P>
<P>
   These sentiments may be viewed as corny and archaic in this
irony-obsessed world, but Smith makes her case very well. She was
always an outsider, an iconoclast, a rebel, and watching her at the
Austin show was a delight: After 25 years, Patti Smith can still
summon up the fierce joy of being alive, can still address the
world in ways that make us think a little harder.
</P>
<P>
   She carries with her an appreciation for rock's history and for
how today and yesterday intersect.
</P>
<P>
   Two examples: ``Strange Messengers,'' which Smith wrote with
longtime guitarist Lenny Kaye, is a heart-rending look at slavery.
With a nod to the first great anti-slave song, the Billie Holiday
classic ``Strange Fruit,'' Smith casts the slaves as bearers of
history, totems for man's inhumanity to man, people whose cries and
pain will be heard as long as we remember the past and try to learn
from it.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's ``Glitter in Their Eyes,'' a fun, upbeat pop-rock
song with an instantly memorable chorus that warns young people
against being simply mindless consumers: ``They'll trade you
up/Trade you down/Your body a commodity/Our sacred stage/Has been
defaced/Replaced to grace/The marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   A more searing indictment against the dumbing-down of pop music
and pop culture can scarcely be imagined _ and the fact that Smith
casts it in what could be a pop-radio hit just makes it hit all the
harder.
</P>
<P>
   This is Smith at her best: Cunning, angry, literate, moral,
intriguing, vital. ``Gung Ho'' is a swirl of images and topics, one
that is not afraid to move through a variety of emotions or shoot
for the moon and sometimes miss. When Smith succeeds, she is
brilliant. When she misses, she misses big. But at least she isn't
afraid to lay her soul and her thoughts bare.
</P>
<P>
   That was once the norm in rock 'n' roll, and now it's the
exception. And in that way Smith is the most impressive sort of
veteran rocker: She sings these songs with the zeal of a
19-year-old cutting a debut, tempered with the hard truths and
knowledge of the world that are (or should be) part and parcel of
being a 52-year-old mother and widow. And in combining the two, she
now sounds like both an oracle and a wandering spirit.
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7839, or e-mail:
dfer(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
