<HEADLINE>
GEISHA THREATENS TO SUE `MEMOIRS' AUTHOR FOR LIBEL  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This 425-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 By RICHARD LLOYD PARRY  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KYOTO _ The woman who in inspired ``Memoirs of a Geisha,'' the
best-selling novel about Japan which is soon to be filmed by Steven
Spielberg, is threatening to sue its American author, accusing him
of libelling her in his depiction of the book's central character.
</P>
<P>
   The principal complaint of Mineko Iwasaki, the legendary Kyoto
geisha who supplied much of the detail about life in the closed
world of Japan's pleasure quarters is with Arthur Golden's detailed
descriptions of the custom known as mizuage, by which a geisha's
virgnity is auctioned off among her patrons to the highest bidder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is wrong, wrong, all, ALL wrong,'' she told The Independent
in an interview at her home in the old Japanese capital, Kyoto.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him that I would never sell myself for any amount of
money... He says that it is fiction, but people do not read it in
that way. They think it is my story, they think that I did all
those things.''
</P>
<P>
   Since its publication in 1997, ``Memoirs of a Geisha'' has sold
4 million copies in English and been translated into 21 languages.
Spielberg has bought the rights to make the film, and has already
sent researchers to scout out locations.
</P>
<P>
   But in Gion, Kyoto's famous and exclusive geisha quarter, where
the action of the book is set, the shutters have come down since
the publication of a Japanese translation last November.
</P>
<P>
   A debate about the book organized by its Japanese publisher had
to be cancelled after it was collectively boycotted by the Gion
geisha community.
</P>
<P>
   According to people in Kyoto, the geisha are furious that the
book's success has torn the veil from their closed and secretive
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Gion, there are things that are tacitly understood, but not
discussed publicly,'' says Yoshiki Nishiyama, of Golden's Japanese
publisher, Bungei Shunju. ``Because this book is written in such
detail, people can't accept it.''
</P>
<P>
   Golden insists that, despite being fiction, the details of the
book are accurate and he stands by his claim that the details of
mizuage were given to him by Mrs. Iwasaki based on her own
experience of deflowerment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd never have said such a thing if I'd thought that she'd
have been so upset,'' says Golden. ``But she's seen any number of
articles in which I discuss what she told me with great pride, and
she's never objected before.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 425-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
