<HEADLINE>
IT'S THE END OF 3-CHARACTER DOT.COMS  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This 250-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By CHARLES ARTHUR  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Dot coms, you've had your dot lot. Officially there
are no more three-character names on the Internet ending with
``.com'' and the last four-character dot-com domain names are
expected to have been snapped up in a matter of months.
</P>
<P>
   The last 47,952 three-character (letters, digits or a middle
hyphen) domain names _ Internet equivalent of house addresses _
were taken this year.
</P>
<P>
   Three-letter names are popular with companies seeking to
establish a brand, because they are easy to remember. And they have
definitely all gone. Tried aaa.com? Taken by the American
Automobile Association in 1990. Or zzz.com? Owned by Internet
Communications of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is as acute for four-letter domains, where there are
3.45 million combinations. That may sound plenty but John Sewell,
at the domain registration and auction company Phase8, says most
meaningful ones were grabbed long ago.
</P>
<P>
   One option, says Sewell, is the advent this month of longer
domain names or suffixes such as ``.eu'' and ``.shop'' for Internet
businesses. But the dot-com lure is likely to continue and big
money is at stake.
</P>
<P>
   In the U.S., James Titcomb, who registered his three-letter
domain for fun in 1996, is entertaining bids of $1 million for the
site, which, despite having no content, gets thousands of visits
every week.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's predictable: it is at www.tit.com. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 250-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
