<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASTER THAN YOU CAN SAY SOUP 
</HEADLINE>
  (Dining) 
(af) 
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It would be hard to find a more powerfully complex natural
convenience food than miso. This Japanese paste of fermented beans
(usually soy), grains (usually rice) and salt can be a revelation
to the home cook looking to give food a fast flavor boost.
</P>
<P>
   Miso _ think of it as soy sauce squared, more intense but not
saltier _ can be used in dressings for salads, meats, tofu and
vegetables. It is often mixed with sesame seeds, mirin (sweet
wine), sake or even eggs to make an intensely flavored sauce.
</P>
<P>
   But miso's most amazing feat is turning a cup of hot water into
soup in about 30 seconds. This ultrasimple soy-based soup _ a
tablespoon of miso whisked or blended into water _ is delicious.
</P>
<P>
   The soup can be used in place of stock in many recipes calling
for Asian flavors, but you have to take care, as it has much more
character than most stocks and could easily overpower the other
ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional miso soup _ the kind served throughout Japan and in
most Japanese restaurants in the United States _ is a little more
complicated, and begins with dashi, a Japanese stock made with kelp
(konbu) and flakes of dried bonito (a relative of tuna). Although
dashi has definite character and is easy enough to make, it is a
light stock, pretty much overpowered by the miso anyway. For the
home cook, it is usually not worth the extra work.
</P>
<P>
   I prefer to put my energy into turning miso soup into a meal,
adding cubed tofu and a couple of vegetables _ minced scallions or
carrots, or some sliced shiitakes _ at the last moment. Those who
do not find tofu alluring might throw some shrimp or boneless
chicken pieces into the soup, where they will cook in two or three
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The best miso (and the kind most commonly found in stores)
develops its flavor over months or years of fermentation and aging.
Depending on other ingredients, it can be smooth or lumpy, and it
ranges in color from white (actually tan, in most cases) to yellow
(golden) to red or brown.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, thick, dark brown hatcho miso is used to make
soup, but the lighter varieties, which are more often used to make
dressings and sauces, are fine too.
</P>
<P>
   Fine miso is unpasteurized, containing cultures as yogurt and
cheese do, and inexpensive: it's tough to spend more than $8 on a
pound. It is sold in plastic tubs or jars in Japanese markets
(Katagiri, at 224 East 59th Street, has an extensive selection),
although other stores, including those that sell natural foods,
carry it as well. It has a long shelf life, keeping for at least
several months in the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a quick-made pasteurized miso, which does not
contain living cultures. It might last even longer, but has
decidedly less character.
</P>
<P>
   But about that soup: figure about a tablespoon of miso per cup
of water, which means about a third of a cup to serve four people.
You may like the soup more or less intensely flavored, but don't
make the common mistake of new cooks and use too much: the soup may
be too strong to eat.
</P>
<P>
   The only trick lies in dissolving the miso properly so that you
create a smooth, almost creamy soup rather than a lumpy one. Just
whisk or blend the miso with a few tablespoons of hot water before
adding the rest of the liquid. Cook the soup gently, for just a
minute or so, to preserve the miso's flavor and aroma. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEARLY INSTANT MISO SOUP &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: About 15 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup miso, preferably dark
</P>
<P>
   { pound tofu, cut into {-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   \ cup peeled and minced carrots
</P>
<P>
   \ cup peeled and minced scallions. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Bring 6 cups of water to a boil in a medium saucepan. Turn
heat to low, and mix about { cup water with miso in a bowl or
blender; whisk or blend until smooth. (If you have an immersion
blender, the fastest and easiest tool for this, do the operation in
a tall measuring cup.)
</P>
<P>
   2. Pour miso mixture back into hot water and add tofu and
carrots; stir once or twice and let sit for a minute, just long
enough to heat tofu through. Add scallions and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Variations: For miso soup with shrimp or chicken, substitute
{-inch cubes of peeled shrimp (deveined, if you like) or boneless,
skinless chicken for tofu. Cook 2 minutes, or until nearly done.
Add carrots and, when soup is done, scallions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-00 1634EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000328.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0323 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-MTBE-WATER-HNS &LR;      03-28 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MTBE-WATER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SCIENTISTS PUZZLED ABOUT TREATING EFFECTS OF GASOLINE
ADDITIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JANE KAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Decades after they approved the use of the
gasoline additive MTBE to clean the air, U.S. Environmental
Protection Agency scientists still do not know how to effectively
remove it from soil and ground water or how to treat people who
inadvertently consume it.
</P>
<P>
   But the scientists do know that the bad-tasting chemical has
adversely affected ground water in at least 38 states, according to
members of the American Chemical Society who met in San Francisco
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the EPA has yet to study the health effective of the
additive or found efficient, inexpensive ways to clean up the
thousands of sites where MTBE has leaked from boats, cars,
refineries, pipelines or underground tanks into water, said Matthew
Small, an EPA researcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know the problem is there. We know the problem is real. We
know the problem is growing,'' Small said. ``The states want EPA to
complete human health studies that lead to (standards). It's going
to take time.''
</P>
<P>
   Small estimated that it would be 2006 before there was an
enforceable federal standard.
</P>
<P>
   J. Michael Davis, senior scientist in the EPA's National Center
for Environmental Assessment in Research Triangle Park, N.C., said
the EPA has been working with other agencies to try to determine
the health effects of MTBE.
</P>
<P>
   But most of its effort has been aimed at measuring effects of
inhaling MTBE as people stand by gas pumps, and not from drinking
it as a pollutant in water, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   At least three studies have found that MTBE causes cancer in lab
animals. In 1997, an influential interagency task force, of which
the EPA is a member, determined that MTBE had the potential to
cause cancer in humans.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said the EPA had not been quick to launch human health
studies because ``information we had under (the law) in late 1980s
and early 1990s didn't show MTBE was toxic relevant to other toxics
we see.''
</P>
<P>
   California and Alaska already have decided to phase out MTBE,
and other states are considering it.
</P>
<P>
   Dissatisfied with EPA's record, a San Francisco environmental
group, Communities for a Better Environment, filed a petition
Monday with the EPA asking it to regulate MTBE under the Toxic
Substances Control Act.
</P>
<P>
   EPA Administrator Carol Browner announced last week that she
would seek to regulate MTBE under the toxic substances law, which
would let the agency limit or ban the chemical.
</P>
<P>
   Browner also asked Congress to give EPA the authority to move
even more quickly to control it and to replace the requirement for
the use of an additive in heavy air pollution areas with a standard
to use renewable fuels like ethanol.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA authorized the use of MTBE, or methyl tertiary butyl
ether, as an octane booster in the 1970s. The Clean Air Act of 1990
required that regions with severe air pollution use an
oxygen-adding compound such as MTBE or ethanol, an alcohol, to
reduce the auto emissions that form smog.
</P>
<P>
   Most gasoline with such additives contains MTBE. Refineries
chose it because it is made of products related to refining. Many
Midwestern states selected ethanol, which comes from corn and other
organic matter. Thus far, ethanol has not created ground water
problems, though some scientists think it can exacerbate MTBE
pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Water managers started to find widespread problems with MTBE in
water supplies by the early 1990s. The chemical dissolves in water
and does not cling to soil particles. It moves 75 times faster
through the ground than other pollutants in gasoline such as
toluene, xylene and benzene.
</P>
<P>
   At least people know when MTBE is there, say scientists. They
complain of a bad taste at about 0.5 parts per billion compared to
above 5 parts per billion with a solvent like trichloroethylene, or
TCE.
</P>
<P>
   Some MTBE cleanup methods have worked on a small scale by
forcing oxygen into the ground water, encouraging bacteria that
eats the MTBE. Others have pumped the water through carbon filters.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 38 states, the EPA reported that:
</P>
<P>
   _ In California, 40 wells in public water systems are
contaminated with MTBE, among them South Lake Tahoe, Santa Monica,
San Jose and Napa.
</P>
<P>
   _ New Hampshire has found MTBE in 215, or 18 percent, of its
1,150 public water supplies.
</P>
<P>
   _ Maine has located MTBE in 16 percent of its private wells.
</P>
<P>
   _ Montana's public wells are thus far free of MTBE, but 30
percent to 50 percent of its leaking underground storage tanks show
the additive in the plume created by the leaks.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Kansas, 18 of 1,122 public water supply system have wells
contaminated with MTBE.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wisconsin, which uses more ethanol than MTBE, still has MTBE
in half of its leaking underground fuel tanks. In the southwest
corner of the state, there is a 4,500-foot plume containing MTBE.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Baltimore and Washington metropolitan area has MTBE in 66
of 1,060 public water systems. More than 210 private wells contain
MTBE.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
