<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0326 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT &LR;      03-28 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHOCOLATE COFFEE CREME BRULEE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This is the fifth of eight columns by Christian Delouvrier,
the executive chef at Lespinasse in Manhattan. They are being
written with Melissa Clark.) 
(jt) 
 &HT;     
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Creme brulee is all about contrast, about the way the crackling
crust of hot caramelized sugar yields to the creamy richness of the
cold custard underneath. It's a perfect dessert made with just
vanilla, but I wanted to take it to another level.
</P>
<P>
   Literally.
</P>
<P>
   What I conceived is a layering of two separate flavored custards
under that crunchy crust. A spoon scooped into this creme brulee
captures not just the caramelized topping but also a base of
chocolate and a center of coffee custard. The flavors almost
cascade.
</P>
<P>
   Odd as it may sound, I took my inspiration for layering from a
fish terrine made with a base of pale ivory fish mousse under an
intense orange lobster mousse. To combine them neatly, the bottom
layer is frozen before the top layer is added. I wasn't sure if
this technique would work with custards, which are thin and runny
compared with firm mousses.
</P>
<P>
   My pastry chef, Chris Broberg, put my concept to the test.
First, he made a dark chocolate custard _ like the most intense
chocolate pudding you can imagine _ and froze it in ramekins
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, he poured a coffee custard over the tops, then
baked the ramekins until the edges were set.
</P>
<P>
   Once they cooled, we could see that our little trick had worked.
The top layer solidifies before the bottom layer melts.
</P>
<P>
   The advantage to this creme brulee is that most of it can be _
in fact, must be _ made in advance. The custards can be baked up to
two days ahead (though one day is optimal), then caramelized just
before serving.
</P>
<P>
   I like to keep the caramel layer very, very thin, just a hint of
crackle across the top. We use a miniature blowtorch to caramelize
the sugar, but a broiler works very well.
</P>
<P>
   Watch the custards very carefully, moving them around if they
begin to caramelize unevenly, and pulling any from the heat before
they get too dark. Bitterness from burning ruins the contrast.
</P>
<P>
   CHOCOLATE-COFFEE CREME BRULEE
</P>
<P>
   Time: about 2 hours, plus overnight freezing and chilling
</P>
<P>
   For the chocolate custard: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3{ tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon plus 1 teaspoon unsweetened cocoa powder
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   2 large egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   \ vanilla bean, halved lengthwise, seeds scraped out and
reserved
</P>
<P>
   For the coffee custard: &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 large egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   2{ tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon instant coffee
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   \ vanilla bean, halved lengthwise, seeds scraped out and
reserved
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons extra-fine granulated sugar.
</P>
<P>
   1. To prepare chocolate custard, whisk together 2 tablespoons
sugar and the cocoa in a small bowl. Bring cream to a simmer in a
small saucepan. Add cocoa mixture and whisk well. Return to a
simmer, then turn off heat and let cool.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a medium bowl, whisk together the egg yolks, remaining
sugar and vanilla bean scrapings. Whisk in cooled cream mixture.
Strain custard through a fine sieve and divide among 6 4-ounce
ramekins or custard cups. Cover with plastic and freeze for at
least 8 hours or overnight.
</P>
<P>
   3. Preheat oven to 350 degrees. To prepare coffee custard, whisk
together the egg yolks, sugar and instant coffee in a medium bowl
until coffee dissolves. Whisk in the cream and vanilla bean
scrapings. Strain mixture, then pour it into ramekins over frozen
chocolate custard.
</P>
<P>
   4. Arrange ramekins in a baking pan and place it on oven rack.
Pour enough very hot water into pan to reach 2/3 of the way up
sides of ramekins. Cover baking pan with foil, and prick in a few
places with a knife. Bake custards 40 to 45 minutes, until set
around edges but still slightly jiggly in center. Transfer ramekins
to a rack and cool. Cover and refrigerate at least 6 hours or
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   5. Right before serving, sprinkle a thin, even coating of
extra-fine granulated sugar on each custard. Using a preheated
broiler or kitchen blowtorch, caramelize sugar. It will take about
1 to 2 minutes under a broiler, about 30 seconds with a blowtorch.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
