<HEADER>
A0329 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-SIMPLICITY-MAGAZINE-T     03-28 1225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLICITY-MAGAZINE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME INC.'S NEW LAUNCH, REAL SIMPLE, DECLARES LESS IS MORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GAILE ROBINSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who would have suspected when People magazine first appeared on
newsstands that it would spawn People en Espanol and Teen People?
And who would have predicted the visual impact of Martha Stewart
Living when it debuted to a collective response of ``Huh?''
</P>
<P>
   Another seminal moment in magazine publishing could be happening
this week in a newsstand near you. The People magazine group, a
division of Time Inc., is launching Real Simple, a magazine that is
supposed to whack through the clutter of our lives and show us the
path to better living through having and wanting less stuff.
</P>
<P>
   It exists because of the ``voluntary simplicity movement,'' says
Susan Wyland, the magazine's managing editor. She says she is the
target audience, a woman ``overextended'' and ``struggling for
balance.''
</P>
<P>
   To create a vehicle for less, Real Simple carves a niche on the
bones of magazines that promoted more. Real Simple emulates many of
them, offering one-dish-dinner recipes, financial advice and a
stress-reduction technique. There is also a departure point.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we wanted to do something different and relevant that
speaks to women. I thought, `What if there was a magazine that
could guide you in every aspect of your life?'''
</P>
<P>
   Wyland included pieces that address do-it-yourself rituals,
passion, meditation, nature and practical solutions _ elements that
are rarely found on other indexes.
</P>
<P>
   The look of Real Simple is in the familiar Martha mode. When
Martha Stewart Living premiered, its serene imagery changed the way
products were photographed and the way magazine pages were
designed. Designers, advertisers and photographers emulated the Zen
quality of light-filled, simple settings and heroic objects. That
style still rules the printed page. Real Simple dutifully follows,
adding a few edgy shadows, where Martha Stewart Living is heavy on
pastels.
</P>
<P>
   Wyland knows how to do the Martha look. She spent 3 1/2 years at
the helm of Martha Stewart Living. She is quite aware of the
similarities and refuses to diss the competition, even though her
efforts could pass for Martha Stewart Living Lite.
</P>
<P>
   But real simple does not mean easy, or inexpensive. Within the
fashion pages, $365 wool T-shirts are depicted as a ``new basic.''
What happens when you search for simplicity is found in an essay
from Meghan Daum, a writer who moved from Manhattan to Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned that living a simple life of your own volition is
more difficult than living a complicated life because somebody else
told you to,'' writes Daum.
</P>
<P>
   Living more simply does not necessarily mean living with less or
without the products of such advertisers as Neiman Marcus, Ralph
Lauren and De Beers.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Sareyan, the magazine's publisher, tries to explain
the concept of simplicity. ``People want beauty; they don't want to
be deprived,'' he said. ``Simple is not about plain or
uncomplicated. It's about balance, being smart and having quality
over quantity.''
</P>
<P>
   Which seems a lot to ask of a monthly publication, even if it
does come from the makers of People, People En Espanol, InStyle and
Teen People _ a money-minting machine that pulls in $350 million in
pretax earnings for parent company Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   There are pieces that work _ establishing serene spaces in our
homes is a lovely idea. The photographs fairly hum with a
meditative mantra and are coupled with suggestions such as, ``Sleep
better by taking the stress out of your bedroom. Replace everything
that doesn't suggest relaxation _ a desk, a TV _ with comfortable
furniture and soft lighting.''
</P>
<P>
   The final page, a premium piece of magazine real estate, is
given to a meditation rather than to hyping multiple advertisers'
products. This, too, is a nice touch; it will be interesting to see
whether this element stays in this position.
</P>
<P>
   The premise of Real Simple raises a paradox _ if life is to be
kept simple, shouldn't we strive for fewer subscriptions and less
junk mail?
</P>
<P>
   Wyland address the junk-mail topic in her first issue but
maintains there is a constant, evolving need for the subjects she
and her editorial staff have planned. Living a life Real Simple
means a constant need for operating instructions.
</P>
<P>
   This conflict of interests is not lost on media watchers. ``How
many things can you make simple?'' asks Steve Greenberger, a senior
vice president at MediaCom. Even the big-office guys at Time were
skeptical. Norman Pearlstine, Time editor in chief, admitted as
much to The Wall Street Journal. ``A number of us had a hard time
imagining the table of contents to take it forward, but the more I
have seen it, the more I have come to understand it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There are parts of the magazine that cause an upward strain on
the eyebrows. A millennial spin is put on tuna-noodle casserole by
turning it into Tuna Noodle Bowl. Capers, carrots, sugar-snap peas,
tuna and bowtie pasta are piled, artistically, into a shallow dish
that is sure to be scorned by most children.
</P>
<P>
   There is the obligatory skin-care story with multiple pages of
instruction on keeping the daily routine simple. Another story
covers paying your bills online, which is not new, but it does
illustrate a new department in many magazines _ the latest line on
online.
</P>
<P>
   Wyland, whose last job was with Family.com, the Disney family
Web site, says there will be an online-related story every month.
This connection to the online world is a natural, since America
Online and Time Warner are becoming one. Real Simple will be
featured on the AOL home page for the next month, and AOL
subscribers will be offered special magazine subscription rates.
</P>
<P>
   For everyone else, the rate is $19.95 for the eight issues
planned for 2000, or $2.95 on the newsstand. Next year, there will
be 10 issues, with December/January and June/July as the double-up
months.
</P>
<P>
   This cross-pollination of print and PC is great at bolstering
the subscription sales. Anne Moore, president of the People group,
told The New York Times. ``We can leverage Time Inc. assets to
promote the magazine, and when you crank up AOL on top of that and
use the power of their 21 million subscribers _ well, put it this
way, I haven't broken out in a sweat.''
</P>
<P>
   The initial printing for Real Simple is 400,000 _ the largest
first edition ever published by a Time Inc. start-up.
</P>
<P>
   There are problems with the first issue of Real Simple. In
trying to establish a unique look, several visual clues typical to
all magazines are deleted, and that makes reading this one a
challenge. The variety of type styles, columns widths, lack of
headlines and other missing graphic devices create visual
confusion. Is it an ad? Or is it a story? Where did the story
begin?
</P>
<P>
   Wyland admits there are graphic problems that they ``are
thinking about changing for the second issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The magazine needs to find a workable style. The monthly format
is just the beginning of Real Simple. Wyland foresees books as the
logical extension of the simple life _ Real Simple Food, Real
Simple Clothes, Real Simple Looks.
</P>
<P>
   Really.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
