<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0330 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-POOH-COMPUTERGAME-TEX     03-28 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POOH-COMPUTERGAME-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
READING `WINNIE THE POOH' ON THE PC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I don't know what it is about Winnie the Pooh that makes me want
to play with him. Not exactly how I like spending my Friday nights,
but I've gotta admit ``Disney's Winnie the Pooh Activity Center''
(Disney Interactive for PC, $40, all ages) has probably been the
most exciting thing happening in my social life since, well, the
Little Mermaid.
</P>
<P>
   This game revolves around the ``Winnie the Pooh and the Blustery
Day'' story. Through pop-up windows, players read the tale, while
at the same time solving a variety of challenges that star Winnie's
friends.
</P>
<P>
   Stop giggling _ this is actually pretty fun. I don't plan on
becoming an interior designer anytime soon, but helping clean up
and decorate Owl's room has occupied me for a few hours. Now if I
could only clean up my pigsty.
</P>
<P>
   Players must also guide Pooh and Piglet through an obstacle
course, build a bridge to stop floating debris and create matching
Heffalumps and Woozles _ whatever those are. I like Pooh and his
pals, but I don't like 'em ``that'' much.
</P>
<P>
   Think I have more racing games on my desk than I do nasty
Post-it notes from editors irked that I never turn my stories in on
time. Right now, the only one that's worth a flip _ the racing
games, not the editors _ is ``Ridge Racer 64'' (Namco for N64),
Nintendo's very successful attempt at porting over a game that did
so well on the Sony PlayStation, that old thing.
</P>
<P>
   Players choose from more than 25 cars and nine courses,
including four new courses that the PlayStation obviously couldn't
handle. That's where ``RR64'' excels: The courses are imaginative
and gorgeously detailed. We've seen construction sites and mountain
ranges and desert roads, but ever play a racing game in which the
course swings by a luxury liner? At night, with all the lights
glimmering? ``That's'' cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``RR'' also pays lots of attention to small details: smoking
tires, skid marks, working (and sometimes nonworking) headlights
and lens flares are all here, making the game that much more
realistic. Good stuff.
</P>
<P>
   The premise of ``Jackie Chan Stuntmaster'' (Midway for
PlayStation, ages 13 and up, $40) sounded as simple as it did
promising: Kick everyone's behind. But even in this day and age of
Next Gen gaming or whatever, it's easy to mess up something as
simple as a walk-around-and-beat-up-people fighting game.
``Jackie's'' got its cool moments, like you can waste three guys
with one pool stick. But the control's too unresponsive and the
game play's too clunky; it's more frustrating than fun. Rent one of
his movies, instead.
</P>
<P>
   (Malcolm Mayhew is pop culture critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7713, or e-mail:
mmayhew(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
