<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Wednesday, March 29. The N.Y. Times News Service
night supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-NETANYAHU (Jerusalem) _ After a seven-month
investigation, the Israeli police on Tuesday recommended that
former Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and his wife, Sara, face
criminal prosecution on charges of bribery, fraud and the theft of
$100,000 worth of gifts to the state. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT1.
</P>
<P>
   UGANDA-CULT (Rugazi, Uganda) _ In one room, the concrete floor
looked a little newer and, on a hunch, the police began to dig.
First they found a human foot, sole upturned, poking up from the
rubble. Within a few hours Tuesday, 28 corpses were hauled out of a
pit _ carefully sealed over with cement, maybe months ago _ inside
the house owned by a leader of a cult in western Uganda. By dark,
the pit was only half emptied. It was, on one level, another
horrifying discovery in the two weeks since more than 300 people
were found burnt to death at a church not far from here. The death
toll, from three different sites, has now risen to at least 593.
There are at least two more suspected grave sites. But the
discovery of the pit may also indicate just how well-organized and,
perhaps longstanding, this march to mass murder in Uganda was. By
Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-SEARCH (Washington) _ An anonymous tip that a person is
carrying a gun is not enough to justify a stop and frisk by the
police without some further sign that the information is reliable,
the Supreme Court ruled with surprising unanimity Tuesday. The
court rejected the argument put forward by Florida, the Clinton
administration and a broad coalition of state attorneys general
that because guns are inherently so dangerous, the police can act
on a tip involving a gun on the basis of less evidence than the
Constitution would otherwise require. While the decision was an
important ruling that placed a constitutional curb on a particular
type of police-citizen encounter, the court did not address the
more controversial and heavily freighted question of what actions
the police can take based not on a tip but on their own observation
and judgment. In the current climate of increased tension over
police tactics, the court's ruling in January that unprovoked
flight at the sight of a police officer can justify the police in
chasing and frisking the person may prove more significant. By
Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Miami) _ Elian Gonzalez's Florida relatives lashed
out at immigration authorities Tuesday and said they still had not
signed an agreement that the government demands by Thursday
promising to surrender the 6-year-old if they lose their court
fight. (Summary from wires) By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   TENN-EXECUTE (Nashville) _ Philip Workman, who was convicted of
killing a police officer during a fast-food restaurant robbery in
1981 in Memphis, could become the first person executed in
Tennessee in 40 years. Lawyers for Workman, whose execution is
scheduled for April 6, have made a fairly compelling case about the
fairness of his trial, including some ballistics evidence that
suggests the officer may have been killed by friendly fire from
other cops. The only eyewitness at the trial has recanted, saying
he fabricated his story after being coached and threatened by
police. And just a few weeks ago, the medical examiner turned over
a potentially exculpatory x-ray of the victim that had never been
seen by the defense. The issue may ultimately be whether Workman is
guilty of felony murder even if he didn't fire the fatal shot
because he clearly committed the crime that led to the officer's
death. The question is now before the U.S. 6th Circuit Court of
Appeals. By Kevin Sack. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-EDUC (Somerset, N.J.) _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas
proposed a $5 billion program Tuesday to address what he termed a
national literacy crisis among children, making his boldest
statement yet that he intends to moor his campaign on the kind of
educational initiatives that have long been identified with
Democrats. By Clifford J. Levy.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT10.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   OPEC (Vienna) _ Despite a deep split between Saudi Arabia and
Iran, the president of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries said the group had reached agreement on a plan to
increase oil production and should at least halt the recent surge
in prices. ``I believe we have an agreement,'' said Ali Rodriguez,
Venezuela's oil minister and the newly named president of OPEC.
Though oil ministers were still hammering out last-minute details,
officials said the increase in quotas would be very close to Saudi
demands for about 1.7 million barrels a day. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ The mediator in the Microsoft
antitrust case has told officials that he might be able to broker a
settlement, and set a detailed schedule for 10 days of proposals
and counter proposals. The move won a delay from Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson who had said that he was prepared to issue a
verdict Tuesday. Instead he announced an unspecified postponement.
By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NASA-MARS (Washington) _ An in-depth review of NASA's Mars
exploration program, released Tuesday, was highly critical of the
management of the program and said that lack of funding, testing
and planning led to the failure of two recent Mars probes. Because
of these problems, NASA announced the cancellation of the planned
Mars 2001 lander awaiting approval of a new overall Mars
``architecture'' plan. By Warren E. Leary.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NEANDERTHAL-DNA (Undated) _ Did modern humans wipe out the
Neanderthal people who inhabited Europe until 28,000 years ago, or
did the two populations merge through interbreeding? New DNA
evidence, extracted from the ribs of a Neanderthal infant, one of
the last of its kind, supports the thesis that these hardy,
beetle-browed people left little or no genetic legacy in today's
populations. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``s'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   HKN-RANGERS (New York) _ The N.Y. Rangers, unlikely to make the
NHL playoffs despite having a league-high $61 million payroll,
fired their general manager, Neil Smith, and their coach, John
Muckler. The moves happened the day after the Rangers had given up
14 goals in back-to-back games, a sign that the players had given
up. By Jason Diamos.
</P>
