<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA'S TASTE FOR TERROIR
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT6 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.) 
(Dining) 
(af) 
 By ERIC ASIMOV   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The word terroir, French for soil, has an almost mystical
meaning in Burgundy. It connotes not only the character of a
vineyard's soil but the soul of the terrain as expressed through
the wine.
</P>
<P>
   In Burgundy, where vineyards are often divided into tiny plots
among many winemakers, the concept of terroir can be tested because
the source of the grapes is often easy to determine. But elsewhere,
terroir becomes trickier to discuss.
</P>
<P>
   In California, wines have long been identified by the dominant
grape rather than by the land where those grapes were grown. But as
Californians learned more about the characteristics of different
areas, they began to include geographical distinctions on labels.
</P>
<P>
   First came county designations and then subdivisions like
Carneros or Santa Maria Valley. Some wineries go even further and
identify the single vineyard from which their grapes were grown.
Sometimes these vineyards are owned outright by a single winery,
but in many cases independent grape-growers may sell their produce
to as many wineries as they wish.
</P>
<P>
   Dutton Ranch, a vineyard in the Russian River Valley of Sonoma
County, sells chardonnay grapes to more than two dozen wineries.
Back in 1967, when Warren Dutton first planted chardonnay grapes on
a 60-acre plot, it might have been easier to taste the wines for
terroir, but Dutton's son, Joe, said that today Dutton Ranch
consists of more than 1,000 acres scattered over 43 sites, too
broad an area for generalizations.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the wines I tasted shared a zesty acidity and bright
green-apple flavors. They seemed better able to stand up to oak
barrel aging than many chardonnays.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Dutton said the vineyard sites are all within 10 miles of
one another and share the same climate. The Duttons, by the way,
have started their own winery, Sebastopol Vineyards. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FRITZ WINERY, 1997 $22.50 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Aromas of apples and pineapples, elegant and delicious. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RUTZ CELLARS, 1996 $30 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tangerine aroma, creamy, with apple, pear and toffee flavors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEBASTOPOL VINEYARDS, 1997 $23 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Aromas of pears, vanilla and nuts, anise and caramel flavors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEBASTIANI SONOMA CASK CELLARS, 1997 $35 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sweet, oaky aroma, mild apple and pineapple flavors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EHLERS GROVE, 1998 $30 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oaky aroma with bright fruit flavors and zingy acidity. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIAN HILL, 1998 $25 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mild pear flavor with lots of oak, toasted caramel on the
finish. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Prices are those paid in various New York City wine shops. &QL;
</P>
