<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0340 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-CANCER-DOCUMENTARY-LA     03-28 0504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-DOCUMENTARY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HBO'S PRACTICAL GUIDE TO CANCER
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
 
 
By PHIL DAVIS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HBO boldly claims its latest original documentary is ``150
minutes of television that could save your life.'' And it delivers.
</P>
<P>
   The groundbreaking special ``Cancer: Evolution to Revolution,''
which premieres at 8 p.m. Thursday on HBO, is making the signal
available for free to all cable operators during its showings.
</P>
<P>
   Directed and produced by veteran health journalist Joseph Lovett
and narrated by tireless Hollywood cancer fund-raiser Lily
Tartikoff, the documentary urges cancer patients to take an active,
aggressive role in the treatment of their disease.
</P>
<P>
   This new kind of medical consumerism can be a lifesaver.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the case of Gary Schine, a 46-year-old Rhode Island
businessman. Nine years ago, his physician told him there was no
hope to stop the disease. But Schine did his own research and found
a clinical trial in San Diego that had been recently approved. The
treatment put his cancer in remission.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he had listened to his doctor, he'd be dead,'' said Lovett,
who lost his father, two brothers and sister to cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The special is not intended to encourage rebellion against
doctors. The underlying philosophy is that patients and doctors
should be partners in fighting the disease. And, in a field where
breakthroughs and advances occur on a monthly basis, many doctors
suffer information overload. A patient may spot an option to doctor
missed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it inspires people to challenge their doctors, to go
out on their own and make sure they get as much information as they
can possibly get about their disease,'' said Tartikoff, whose
husband, Brandon, died of Hodgkin's disease in 1997 after battling
it for 16 years. ``The message of this special is to be active, to
be informed, to be smart and, at the very least, to never give
up.''
</P>
<P>
   The documentary provides a plethora of cancer resources, all of
which are also listed at www.hbo.com. Information also is available
at the National Cancer Institute's help line, (800) 422-6237.
</P>
<P>
   Lovett uses a combination of stunning statistics, intriguing
research and touching personal stories to present the state of
cancer in the new millennium. There is both humor and horror.
</P>
<P>
   In one segment, a young boy who lost his sister to cancer
screams, ``I hate cancer. I hate it. I hate it. I hate it. I hate
it.'' Women compare the scars of breast cancer surgery. And, in
another, a charming 11-year-old girl shows off her collection of
hats.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of my favorite ones,'' she says, smiling and
holding up a wild, multicolored hat for the camera, ``but it
doesn't match anything so I can't wear it.''
</P>
<P>
   ________ &QL; 
The show: ``Cancer: Evolution to Revolution.'' &QL; 
Documentary on cancer treatment. &QL; 
Where: HBO. &QL; 
When: 8 p.m. Thursday, rebroadcast at 4:30 p.m. April 5, 10 a.m.
April 8 and 2:30 p.m. April 17.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-00 1703EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000328.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0344 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-28 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     IMAGES CAN DECEIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ First impressions are important. In politics, early
images of presidential candidates often freeze in our heads
regardless of how irrational or inaccurate those perceptions may
be.
</P>
<P>
   Thus we have Vice President Al Gore seemingly stuck in a
permanent time frame as wooden and stiff, which is the way we saw
him during his cautious years as President Clinton's sidekick. And
Texas Gov. George W. Bush could live forever with a reputation for
being half a bubble off plumb, which stems primarily from his early
verbal stumbles on foreign policy questions.
</P>
<P>
   Yet common sense tells us that both men are far more complex,
intelligent and personable than their images. Boring dummies do not
quickly and overwhelmingly win the presidential nominations of
their parties.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is making a major effort to shake the totem pole problem,
but it is tough going. He truly does have a funny bone in private.
I have seen it in action. But getting that message out to the
public is a tedious process, requiring the accumulation of one
witty speech and interview after another.
</P>
<P>
   Gore gave such a speech last Saturday night before a cynical
audience of jaded journalists and prominent government officials.
He brought down the house with self-deprecating jokes and jolly
jabs at his rival, Bush. The laughter and the subsequent standing
ovation were bipartisan, which is the way it should be when an
American statesman turns in a great performance.
</P>
<P>
   Gore didn't write the lines himself. Anonymous speechwriters
were invented expressly to help out busy politicians. But at the
banquet, sponsored by a journalistic group called the Gridiron
Club, he produced some good ad libs and delivered his talk with
such gusto and glee that ``wooden'' seemed an outdated description.
</P>
<P>
   ``My inner alarm bells go off in a room where everyone's dressed
the same,'' he quipped, comparing the robes of the Buddhist monks
at his controversial 1996 fund-raiser with the white-tie uniform of
the male Gridiron guests. He made several cracks about the Buddhist
event, which has become symbolic of excessive campaign fund-raising
tactics. ``I remember wondering, `Which one is Richard Gere?''' he
joked.``And I remember admiring the majestic, burnt-umber robes and
thinking, `Hmmm earth tones.'
</P>
<P>
   `` So now it's down to George Bush and Al Gore,'' he went on.
``Finally, some refreshing new names in American politics.''
</P>
<P>
   He confided that during a debate with Governor Bush, ``I'm going
to lay a little trap for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing off former Democratic Vice Presidential candidate Lloyd
Bentsen's famous put-down of President George Bush's running mate,
Dan Quayle, after Quayle compared himself with President John F.
Kennedy, Gore said,`` I'm going to say something critical so he has
to defend President Bush. That's when I'm going to say, Governor, I
knew George Bush. George Bush was a friend of mine. And you, sir,
are no George Bush which I think will hopelessly confuse him!''
</P>
<P>
   Gore is also trying to shake off his early image in other ways _
for instance, proposing a new federal endowment fund to underwrite
elections as a way of achieving fundamental campaign finance reform
and getting himself off the hook as an abuser of the process.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, for his part, is also working to change the early
impression voters got of his mental limitations.
</P>
<P>
   He refuses to do any more pop quizzes, at which he has proved to
be something less than a genius. He sticks to subjects he is
familiar with as governor and he is working on two things: trashing
Gore and using appearances where he can exhibit his considerable
personal charm.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is basically an affable fellow with more political smarts
than the public realizes. Gore does recognize Bush's intellect, and
while he is willing to joke about it, he does not underestimate it.
</P>
<P>
   Bush likes to accuse Gore of being ready to do and say anything
to get elected. But it takes one to know one. Bush proved in the
South Carolina primary he would stoop lower than a turtle if it
meant winning. Not a noble strategy, but not a stupid one either.
</P>
<P>
   So we have two smart, ambitious guys with good genes and
different views of how to run the country going head to head for
the presidency. We could do worse _ and have.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-00 1705EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
