<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINE VALUES FROM ITALY'S SUN-BAKED SOUTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By FRANK J. PRIAL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Southern Italy is torrid in more ways than one these days. In
the course of a few years it has become one of the most
sought-after wine-producing regions in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Not by wine drinkers, at least not yet, except for a handful of
smart folks who know enough to shrug off labels and grapes, and
concentrate on values. No, the wine people who are most interested
in southern Italy at the moment are big producers from the north
like Antinori, Santa Margherita and Zonin, who, lured by bargain
prices, are buying hundreds of acres of actual or potential
vineyard land, and importers from Britain and the United States
looking for good affordable wines.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, the talk in the wine trade was of Tuscany,
Piedmont and the Veneto, with Lombardy, the Alto Adige and Friuli
following along. Now, Abruzzi, Campania, Apulia, Sicily and
Sardinia are hot topics, with Calabria, Basilicata and even obscure
Molise beginning to be known for their wine and wine potential.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if southern Italy hasn't been involved in wine in
the past. The Greeks, who colonized the region before Roman times,
called it Oenotria, which comes from the word oinos, Greek for
wine. Greco del Tufo, from Campania; greco di bianco and greco nero
from Calabria; and grechetto from north of Rome all trace their
origins to early Greek settlers.
</P>
<P>
   These sun-baked provinces have always produced wine, most of it
heavy alcoholic stuff shipped off in bulk for blending with thin
northern wines. There have been good wines made here, too. The
Mastroberardinos have been making fine wines near Naples for
generations, while families in Sicily have produced well-known
wines like Corvo and Regaleali for hundreds of years.
</P>
<P>
   But hundreds of other wines have been made and enjoyed in the
south, ignored by the Northerners and totally unknown to the rest
of the world. Suddenly, people are talking about grapes with names
like negroamaro, cannonau, primitivo, aglianico (which derives from
Hellenic) and the nero d'Avola, the best grape of Sicily and
perhaps one of the best in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Italy is usually defined as everything south of Rome,
plus the Abruzzi to the east and the islands of Sicily and
Sardinia. On the mainland, almost all of this region is cut off
from the north by the Appenine mountains, meaning it suffers few of
the weather problems that plague Tuscany and the Piedmont. It is an
area as yet untouched by large international demand; it's out of
reach for wine enthusiasts who drive down from Germany and
Switzerland to bid the prices of Italian wines up to Bordeaux and
Burgundy levels.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Italy is an impoverished region. Unemployment in the
Veneto, the booming industrial and wine-producing region around
Verona in the north, is about 4 percent. In the far south, it is 15
to 20 percent, and more.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Italy, at least until now, has enjoyed a special kind
of stability, unknown in more modern cultures. As Leonardo
Locascio, an American importer, said: ``These regions have lived
under so many conquerors _ Greeks, Muslims, Normans, Spanish _ that
there has always been a visceral attachment to family and land,
particularly land. Property, at least until recently, never changed
hands.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Consequently,'' he explained, ``the price of a bottle of wine
rarely reflects rising land prices the way it does in northern
Italy, where prime vineyard land currently sells for $200,000 an
acre.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, low demand, a willing work force, good land prices and
unfamiliar wine names all contributed to what is still an
attractive relationship between price and quality. Many of these
wines are between $8 and $12 a bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the names are unfamiliar. Sicilian wines, for example,
have long been widely available in this country. Now, there are
some new ones. Try the La Segreta wines from Planeta, particularly
the merlot-based red. Or Regaleali's delightful Nozze d'Oro (Golden
Wedding) sauvignon blanc, created for the fifth wedding anniversary
of the owners, Giuseppe and Franca Tasca. Morgante's nero d'Avola,
which resembles a young syrah, is also worth seeking out.
</P>
<P>
   Sardinia, a truly remote wine source a decade ago, now exports
several intriguing wines from Argiolas, including Turriga, a red
blend of cannonau and malvasia nera, and a Cannonau di Sardegna
Riserva from Sella &AMP; Mosca, the island's largest wine producer.
Cannonau is the local name for grenache, the principal grape in
Spain, which once owned Sardinia. For a unique but engaging
cabernet sauvignon, try the barrel-aged Marchese di Villamarina,
also from Sella &AMP; Mosca.
</P>
<P>
   Mastroberardino is still the most respected wine name in
Campania, and for me its most respected red is its Taurasi, made
from the aglianico grape. The riserva is aged up to four years and
can be laid down for many more. Falerno del Massico Rosso, from the
Villa Matilde, is another Campania red worth sampling.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Mastroberardino is also the best-known source of
greco del Tufo, a fine dry wine with a hint of almonds on the
palate. For an inexpensive red that still manages to display some
complexity, the Copertino Riserva, made from the negroamaro grape
at a cooperative in Apulia, is a good bet, although, like others on
this list, not yet widely distributed. The Vigna Spano from Calo,
another Apulia producer, is a bigger wine, with depth and a long
finish.
</P>
<P>
   Another Apulian wine rather well known in America is Salice
Salentino, also made from the negroamaro grape. It, too, is a big
wine, made to last. A prominent producer is Taurino. It also comes
in a rose version. (One day, southern Italy's rose wines will be
much sought after. They are lighter than the reds but have body and
lots of flavor. Some people apparently age them successfully.)
</P>
<P>
   The aglianico grape turns up in another relatively well-known
red wine, Aglianico del Vultura, from vineyards near Potenza, in
Basilicata. This is another keeper, with great power and
concentrated flavors. I'm told the 1985's are just now at their
best.
</P>
<P>
   These are just a few of the hundreds of wines produced in the
southernmost reaches of the Italian boot. If they are not yet in
your local shops, try the ones that are. A whole new world of wine
awaits.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
