<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEESE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN CHEESES CATCH UP TO THE WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It would have been impossible to produce a book like ``The New
American Cheese'' 20 years ago. Back then, only about a quarter of
the 50 or so American cheese makers featured in this big, lavishly
photographed volume by Laura Werlin (Stewart Tabori &AMP; Chang, $35)
were in business.
</P>
<P>
   Revolution is not too strong a term to describe what has
happened on the American cheese-making scene in recent years. It is
part of the new can-do spirit of American food producers, inspired
by Europe to innovate and excel.
</P>
<P>
   Though the author, a food writer, says that the Pilgrims brought
goats with them on the Mayflower and used the milk to make ``curds
and whey,'' American goat milk cheeses were virtually nonexistent
before the late 1970s. It took another 10 years for sheep's milk
cheeses to appear. The book clearly shows that American cheese
makers are making up for lost time, creating cheeses that can rival
famous imports.
</P>
<P>
   The book begins with a strongly worded foreword from Steven
Jenkins, the cheese expert at Fairway, who praises the best America
has to offer while condemning regulations that standardize cheese
making. The work of artisans, he says, is why American cheese ``is
catching on like wildfire.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the book is devoted to profiles of small cheese
companies, and as the list unfolds, the reader's curiosity is
whetted about some of the enticing cheeses they are creating, like
a Roquefort-style Bergere Bleue, from Northland Sheep Dairy in
Marathon, N.Y., and Ewezarella, a sheep's milk mozzarella, from
Bass Lake Cheese Factory in Somerset, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   At one long-established company, Vella Cheese of Sonoma, Calif.,
a new cheese was created when a supply of Monterey Jack was
unintentionally left to age. The result was Dry Jack, a hard
grating cheese. Other cheeses are fledgling experiments, like the
Sagpond Farmstead Emmenthaler that the winemaker at Wolffer
Estates-Sagpond Vineyards in Sagaponack, N.Y., started making two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The alluring collection of recipes in the book include those in
which the cheese takes center stage, like cheese fondue or macaroni
and cheese. In others, like salads, it amounts to a flavorful
garnish. A gougere, a kind of cheese puff, is a classic that has
been bolstered with hot red pepper. Sauteed spinach with blue goat
cheese, caramelized onions and currants amounts to a piquant
rethinking of creamed spinach.
</P>
<P>
   In most recipes, using a particular cheese is usually not
essential, and substitutes are given. That's good, since many, like
Mossholder, a semisoft cheese from Appleton, Wis., and Ku'oko'a
Farm's smooth Hawaiian goat cheese, are sold only locally.
</P>
<P>
   Ricotta in a bread pudding, fromage blanc to enrich a risotto,
and blue cheese on pizza or bruschetta are a few of the more
innovative recipe ideas. It is also clear from the recipes, which
emphasize fairly common cheeses, that the best, most distinctive
cheeses, like Cypress Grove's Marble Mountain, which is pyramid
shaped, are meant to be nibbled by themselves.
</P>
<P>
   There seems to be no order in which the book presents cheese
makers: Great Hill Dairy in Massachusetts, which makes a blue
cheese, follows Lovetree Farm in Wisconsin, which specializes in
aged sheep cheeses. A state-by-state listing of cheese makers
includes more than 100 that are not profiled, but does not give the
page numbers for those that are.
</P>
<P>
   General information does not apply just to American cheeses.
Readers are guided on how to evaluate cheese, with tips on good and
bad aromas, flavors and textures. They also learn how cheese should
be served, how to pair it with wine and how to cook with it. The
rule of thumb that four ounces of hard cheese makes one and a half
cups grated is one I will hard-wire into my brain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The New American Cheese'' offers about the best, most detailed
instructions on how to wrap and store cheese, complete with a chart
divided according to type of cheese. It would pay to photocopy it
and tack it to the refrigerator door. With a mouse-shaped magnet.
</P>
<P>
   RED PEPPER GOUGERE Adapted from ``The New American Cheese''
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour, plus cooling
</P>
<P>
   { cup (1 stick) unsalted butter, cut in pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon dry mustard
</P>
<P>
   } teaspoon crushed red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups coarsely grated Gruyere-style cheese (about 5 ounces)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons finely grated Dry Jack or other hard grating
cheese.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 425 degrees. Grease baking sheet with a bit
of butter.
</P>
<P>
   2. Place one cup water in saucepan, add butter and gradually
bring to a boil. Remove from heat, add flour all at once and mix
vigorously with a wooden spoon until mixture comes together. Return
to heat briefly, until mixture starts to film pan. Remove from heat
and beat in eggs one at a time. (Alternatively, flour mixture can
be placed in food processor and eggs added one at a time, each
processed briefly to incorporate.) With wooden spoon, mix in
mustards, red pepper, salt and cheeses.
</P>
<P>
   3. Using pastry bag fitted with wide tip (or a small but heavy
self-sealing plastic bag with { inch cut off one corner), pipe
one-third of batter onto baking sheet in a ring about 9 inches in
diameter. Top with another third of batter, then the rest, to make
a three-layer ring. Or pipe batter into individual 2-inch mounds
about 1{ inches apart.
</P>
<P>
   4. Bake 20 minutes. If making large ring, reduce heat to 375
degrees and bake 20 minutes longer, until ring is puffed up, well
browned and sounds hollow when tapped. For individual puffs, bake a
total of 25 minutes without reducing heat. Remove finished ring or
puffs from oven. Cool on rack 15 minutes, then serve as hors
d'oeuvres.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 1 large or 36 to 40 small gougeres, serving 6 to 8. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
