<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-NETANYAHU-0329-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NETANYAHU TAKES TO TV TO COMBAT ALLEGATIONS OF CORRUPTION
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ As defiant as ever, former Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu Tuesday said he was the victim of a ``hunt'' and
denied police allegations of corruption while in office.
</P>
<P>
   The comments, in an interview on Israeli television, came after
Israeli police recommended that prosecutors file several corruption
charges against he and his wife, Sara.
</P>
<P>
   Between them, they are accused of trying to keep up to 700 gifts
they received while Netanyahu was in office _ including a gold
letter opener from Vice President Al Gore _ and accepting work from
a contractor who expected political favors. Police have been
investigating the couple, including long questioning sessions with
each, for seven months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't define this as though they are after me, I would
define it as a hunt,'' Netanyahu said during the 50-minute
interview in which he often appeared sarcastic and angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of these allegations have no basis at all,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Though he lost a bid for re-election in 1996 and then dropped
out of politics, Netanyahu has been courted recently to make a
comeback, either for his Likud Party or a new party. His three
years in office were marked by a combative style, and reluctance to
carry out peace agreements with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   In the TV interview, Netanyahu said the police investigation
could preclude another political bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``They, in essence, are neutralizing me politically,'' he said,
apparently referring to the police.
</P>
<P>
   The decision on whether to charge Netanyahu lies with Attorney
General Elyakim Rubinstein, who has in the past refused to charge
Netanyahu on other police allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Police recommend that Netanyahu be charged with accepting a
bribe, breach of trust by a public official, obstruction of justice
and attempted fraud. Police said Sarah Netanyahu should be charged
with theft and attempted fraud. They also recommended charges
against two Netanyahu aides.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli law professor Ze'ev Segal said that Netanyahu, if
convicted of all his charges, could face three to seven years in
jail. He could also be barred from again seeking office.
</P>
<P>
   For now, that is a long way off. But, the recommendation is the
latest in a wave of scandals rippling through Israel's public
elite.
</P>
<P>
   Current Prime Minister Ehud Barak and his aides face a police
probe into his campaign fundraising. President Ezer Weizman is
being investigated for accepting more than $400,000 in gifts over
his political career from a French millionaire.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Rubinstein opened an investigation of the spiritual
leader of the large Shas political party, Rabbi Ovadia Yosef,
because he compared a political opponent to ``Satan'' and a
biblical figure who set out to eliminate the Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Such language can be considered incitement to violence and has
been closely scrutinized since the assassination of Prime Minister
Yitzhak Rabin in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The corruption scandals, especially, are seen as a sign of
growing influence of Israeli prosecutors in a still young country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The standards have risen. The things that were possible in the
past and would have gone unnoticed are not possible now,'' said Uri
Dromi, publications director for the Israel Democracy Institute.
``The public is not tolerating it as it did before.''
</P>
<P>
   The Netanyahu inquiry began shortly after the elections, when a
contractor submitted a bill to his office for work done for the
Netanyahus. It appears police believe the contractor did $50,000
worth of work with the understanding that Netanyahu would repay him
with political favors.
</P>
<P>
   The contractor has since become a witness for the prosecution.
Police accuse Netanyahu of trying to get the contractor to lie in
the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The police searched the Netanyahus' home and properties, and
reportedly found gifts with the inscriptions removed and that had
been re-packaged. Israel Radio reported that the gifts were worth
more than $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu said he was allowed to take gifts for the office he is
provided by the government as former prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
