<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0357 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-TORNADOES29-COX     03-28 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADOES29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOMES CAN BE REINFORCED AGAINST TORNADO DAMAGE, FEMA REPORTS
 &HT;    By ISMAIL TURAY Jr.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even in powerful tornadoes, homes can be protected
from severe damage if they are strongly reinforced with the latest
building techniques, the Federal Emergency Management Agency
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't control the weather, but, in effect, we can control''
the amount of damage caused by tornadoes, FEMA Director James Lee
Witt said as he released a report on the devastating Oklahoma City
tornado of May 1999.
</P>
<P>
   More than 280 people living in 15 states, including Florida,
Georgia and Texas, were surveyed for the study, which began days
after the tornado ripped through parts of Oklahoma and Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Construction flaws and use of poor-quality materials resulted in
damage to thousands of homes that could have been avoided, the
study found.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of the homeowners surveyed said they did not know
they could act to prevent tornado damage to their homes. Others
knew the steps to take, but just didn't take them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is much we can do to build stronger structures that will
stand up even if they are near the direct path of a violent tornado
_ or even in the direct path of weaker tornadoes,'' Witt said.
</P>
<P>
   FEMA issued a set of recommendations for homeowners, including:
</P>
<P>
   _ Retrofit masonry chimneys that project six feet above the roof
of the home with continuous vertical reinforcing steel.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reinforce garage doors, particularly double-wide doors, or
install a replacement with better wind resistance.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use drilled-in or cast-in-place fasteners to attach concrete
to other materials.
</P>
<P>
   _ Simplify roof designs, for example by avoiding dormers, to
resist their tendency to uplift in windstorms.
</P>
<P>
   He urged homeowners to upgrade their homes if they don't meet
the most recent national model building codes and standards. People
have a better chance of surviving a tornado ``if you make sure that
your building exceeds the national standards,'' Witt said.
</P>
<P>
   The FEMA director also asked local officials in tornado-prone
areas to adopt and rigorously enforce the latest model codes and
national wind engineering standards.
</P>
<P>
   The FEMA team also found that manufactured homes don't resist
wind forces as well as conventional houses, but that manufactured
homes perform better during tornadoes if they are installed on
permanent foundations.
</P>
<P>
   Witt recommended that insurance companies offer lower rates to
people who anchor their manufactured homes or put them on permanent
foundations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recommendations for building better against high winds is
important, but perhaps the most important thing to do when in the
direct path of a tornado is to seek shelter in a well-built safe
room or shelter,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Safe rooms can provide ''next-to-absolute level of protection,''
Paul Tertell, a civil engineer with FEMA, said recently.
</P>
<P>
   FEMA, working with the Wind Engineering Research Center at Texas
Tech University, has designed small windowless, structurally
reinforced rooms meant to be installed in the center of a home.
</P>
<P>
   After inspecting more than 90 towns that had been struck by
tornadoes, they found that small rooms in the central part of
houses often remained standing even when the rest of the dwelling
had sustained severe damage.
</P>
<P>
   FEMA officials said the safe rooms can withstand winds of up to
250 mph and protect occupants from a 14-pound object measuring 2
feet by 4 feet and flying at 100 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Safe rooms, built of steel and reinforced concrete, were
developed primarily for use in new houses, but some can be
installed in existing houses. Although anyone with adequate
building skills can construct the rooms, officials suggested hiring
a professional contractor.
</P>
<P>
   Materials for the safe room cost from $2,000 to $4,000,
depending on its size.
</P>
<P>
   Plans for the safe room and a free brochure, ''FEMA 320: Taking
Shelter From the Storm,'' can be requested at 1-800-480-2520 or
www.fema.gov. The full set of recommendations for reinforcing homes
against strong winds is also available on the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Ismail Turay Jr.'s e-mail address is ismailt(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
