<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0360 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-SPRING-SORREL-ART-2TA     03-28 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRING-SORREL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SECRET LIFE OF SORREL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT9 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.) 
(Dining) 
(af) 
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I held the vibrant green sorrel leaves in my hands. They were
the color of a sprout and as fragile as flower petals. Moist, cool
and tender, they were nothing like the hard, starchy fruits of
winter. They seemed to possess both the optimism of spring and its
temperament.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as I had done so many times before, I treated them like
spinach, wilting them in a hot pan and watching with dismay as the
fresh leaves rapidly shrank and turned the shade of food-service
broccoli.
</P>
<P>
   Sorrel is an odd vegetable. After seducing you with thoughts of
spring, it tests your honesty, your commitment to its flavor.
Despite its dull color when cooked, sorrel does taste bright and
exuberant.
</P>
<P>
   No other vegetable at this time of year has such power, or
complexity. Sorrel is fruity like rhubarb. It is tart like lemon.
It is herbal like basil. And it can be treated like all three.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, I was like many home cooks and chefs. I would
soften sorrel in a pan and add cream, or sometimes a little chopped
spinach for a side dish, or I would make a soup of it. But sorrel
is so much more interesting than that.
</P>
<P>
   The spade-shape leaves, which closely resemble young spinach,
are really an herb and are often sold in small bunches in the herb
section of markets. In France, sorrel is a familiar sign of spring.
Chefs use it to make tart sauces for rich fish like salmon or
pureed soups.
</P>
<P>
   But here in America, it is an esoteric green that shows up right
about now, maybe alongside shad, then gets pushed aside by
asparagus and artichokes. But what a shame.
</P>
<P>
   The chefs who understand sorrel use it inventively, almost
secretively. At Five Points, for instance, a thin layer of sorrel
separates layers of country bread and Gruyere in a savory bread
pudding. At Veritas, it is added to a mixture of herbs _ tarragon,
chives, basil and chervil _ and sprinkled over salad or roasted
fish. At Chanterelle, its tart, fruity leaves are treated like
rhubarb, mingling with green apple in, of all things, a dessert.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps one of the most subtle uses of sorrel is in a risotto at
Fressen. Bright green fava beans and sugar snap peas are nestled in
warm rice. Right before serving, Lynn McNeely, the chef, whirls
blanched arugula and sorrel in a blender with olive oil, then
swirls the mixture into the risotto. The leaves, their color
preserved, tint the rice a pale green and give it a zesty, peppery
flavor.
</P>
<P>
   It is a smart dish, but hardly something I was planning to cook
at home. I wanted to understand sorrel better without having to
hire a sous-chef.
</P>
<P>
   As I discovered, all you really need to do is get in the
kitchen, swish the soft leaves around in water (they can be quite
dirty) and get cooking.
</P>
<P>
   I started off slowly, with the classics, to serve as a reminder
of what I knew and liked about sorrel. I wilted the leaves in
butter. When they are young and fresh, they seem to melt, their
structure breaking down until they are soft and silky.
</P>
<P>
   As with spinach, it is important to cook off the water, so that
the greens do not taste soggy. It was as good as I remembered _
vigorously tart _ and a great side dish to accompany sauteed fish
or roasted chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Sorrel's sharpness can be softened by blending it with other
greens like spinach or chard. I did this two ways, first mixing
half spinach and half sorrel and wilting them in a pan. Another
time, I finished the blend of greens by pouring a little cream over
it and reducing it to a sauce. No surprise, the cream did not hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Then I tried a recipe from ``The Herbfarm Cookbook'' (Scribner,
$40) by Jerry Traunfeld that calls for sauteing spinach and tossing
it with chopped sorrel, mint and anchovy. The sorrel was essential
as the acid in the dish, and yet it did not compete with the
spinach.
</P>
<P>
   Next I layered slices of potato in a gratin dish, covered them
with sorrel leaves, then another layer of potato. I mixed heavy
cream and chicken stock together, sprinkled fine gratings of
Parmesan cheese and Gruyere over the potatoes and put it all in a
hot oven.
</P>
<P>
   Half an hour later, I pulled the dish from the oven. It was a
beautiful moment: the cream was bubbling, the potatoes had curled
and were coated with browned cheese. The sorrel had compressed to a
wafer-thin layer, and its rich, lemony flavor had permeated the
entire dish. Why not, I later thought, simply fold fresh leaves
into warm, creamy mashed potatoes?
</P>
<P>
   I moved on to another classic, an omelet. I heated butter in a
pan, cracked a few eggs into a bowl, added a dash of cream and sea
salt and frothed them with a whisk. When the butter was bubbling
and snapping, I poured in the eggs, then covered them with fresh
sorrel leaves. Once the bottom had turned a toasty brown, I swished
the eggs and sorrel, then flipped the omelet.
</P>
<P>
   What emerged from the pan looked like a nature collage with the
sorrel leaves preserved whole in the omelet. Their color had faded
so that they looked like grape leaves, and they gave each bite a
fresh, citrusy flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Another experiment was inspired by a dish at Five Points,
steamed mussels sprinkled with a chiffonade of sorrel. Here, sorrel
was used more like an herb. It seemed more garnish than herb until
I tasted it. The slices of sorrel fell into the shells and broth
but stayed fresh enough so that, every bite or so, I crunched down
on the fresh leaf and got a tart burst of flavor. It was a
delightful, easy touch.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, I chopped sorrel fine and mixed it with
chopped basil, parsley and tarragon, and used it as Veritas does,
sprinkling the mixture over salads and warm potatoes. It is the
same idea as the mussels, only less concentrated, balancing
sorrel's tartness with the pepperiness of basil and the clean
licorice flavor of tarragon. Using it raw like this is also the
only way to retain its bright green color.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Paging through ``How to Eat'' (John Wiley &AMP; Sons, $35) by
Nigella Lawson, I came across a recipe for chickpeas with sorrel.
In it, the sorrel works like any other aromatic, whether coriander,
parsley or garlic. I simmered onion and garlic with cumin and red
chili, added first the chickpeas and then a large handful of
chopped sorrel.
</P>
<P>
   Sorrel's sharpness was just the right counterpoint to the sweet,
nutty legumes. In fact, it would work with almost any bean or
grain, whether black-eyed peas, lentils or farro.
</P>
<P>
   The last dish I tried was a potato-leek soup from ``Cafe Boulud
Cookbook'' (Scribner, 1999) by Daniel Boulud and Dorie Greenspan. I
learned from it, too. Rather than incorporating the sorrel into the
soup, as I have always done, Boulud's recipe starts with a
straightforward potato-leek soup.
</P>
<P>
   While it simmered, I made a sorrel cream by pureeing raw sorrel
and folding it into whipped cream. To serve the soup, I set a
spoonful of the stiff, green-flecked cream on the surface. It began
melting and frothing in the hot broth. Then something unexpected
happened. The soup turned the color of a baby pea leaf and its
aroma bloomed. It smelled faintly of leek, vibrantly of sorrel.
</P>
<P>
   My image of sorrel had also bloomed. I began thinking of it as a
lemon-flavored spring green. Eventually, I realized that is about
as accurate as saying that celery root simply tastes like celery.
Now, after seeing all that sorrel can do, even the idea of adding
it to a dessert no longer seems so outrageous. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SPINACH WITH SORREL, MINT AND ANCHOVY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``The Herbfarm Cookbook'' by Jerry Traunfeld &QL; 
Time: 15 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4 anchovy fillets
</P>
<P>
   1 medium shallot, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 large bunch (about 1 pound) spinach, trimmed and washed
</P>
<P>
   1 cup gently packed, thinly slivered sorrel leaves
</P>
<P>
   \ cup coarsely chopped spearmint
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. In a large skillet, heat oil over medium-low heat. Add
anchovies and shallot, and cook, stirring and mashing anchovy
fillets with the back of a spoon until the shallot is softened but
not browned and the anchovy is dissolved.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add as much spinach as will fit in pan, increase heat to
medium-high, and toss spinach with tongs until it is wilted. Add
remaining spinach, along with sorrel, mint and salt. Continue to
toss until all the spinach is wilted and most of the liquid has
cooked off, about 3 minutes. Taste, and adjust seasoning with salt
and pepper. Serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   POTAGE PARISIEN WITH SORREL CREAM &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Cafe Boulud Cookbook'' by Daniel Boulud and Dorie
Greenspan &QL; 
Time: 40 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1{ tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   3 medium leeks, white and light green parts only, split
lengthwise, thinly sliced and washed
</P>
<P>
   6 cups low-sodium chicken or vegetable broth
</P>
<P>
   3 medium Yukon Gold potatoes, peeled and diced into \-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground white pepper
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces sorrel leaves, stemmed and washed
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup heavy cream, whipped to firm peaks. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. In a stock pot over low heat, melt butter. Add leeks, and
cook, stirring until tender but not colored, 8 to 10 minutes. Pour
in stock, increase heat, and bring just to a boil. Add potatoes,
season with salt and pepper, lower heat, and simmer for 8 to 10
minutes, or until potatoes are cooked through. Adjust seasoning as
needed. Keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a blender, process sorrel to a smooth puree. If it seems
stiff, add a tablespoon of whipped cream. Carefully fold puree into
whipped cream, and season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   3. Ladle soup into bowls, and top each bowl with a spoonful of
sorrel cream. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHICKPEAS WITH SORREL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``How to Eat'' by Nigella Lawson &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 10 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 small onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, finely sliced
</P>
<P>
   Large pinch ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   { dried red chili pepper, crumbled
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirdscup or large handful shredded sorrel
</P>
<P>
   1 15-ounce can chickpeas, drained. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. In a medium pan, heat olive oil over medium heat. Add onion,
garlic and cumin, and stir. Sprinkle chili pepper on top, and
season with salt. Cook until onion is soft but not brown, about 3
to 5 minutes. Lower heat if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   2. Stir in sorrel, then chickpeas. Cook until chickpeas are
warm. Taste, and adjust seasoning. Serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 3 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
