<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0363 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-EVERYDAY-ETHICS-COLUM     03-28 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERYDAY-ETHICS-COLUMN-ADV02-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV02 
 EVERYDAY ETHICS 
 FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 2 AND THEREAFTER.
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by EVERYDAY ETHICS clients. Nonsubscribers can
use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, see end of text. 
 By RANDY COHEN 
 c.2000 Randy Cohen 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. When I fill out my census form, I am considering declaring
myself poor and African-American. That would be a lie because I am
middle-class and white, but it strikes me as responsive to a higher
ethic. Adding one more tally to a group known to be undercounted
would help right the inaccurate figures. Should I suppress my
socially conscious concerns?
</P>
<P>
   _ J. Sommer, New York
</P>
<P>
   A. You should express your concerns, but not in the way you
propose. While the census is seriously _ and, many say,
deliberately _ flawed, it is not so utterly discredited as to
justify the small civil disobedience you describe. Instead, write
to your representatives and demand the use of sampling techniques
that would yield a more accurate count, and urge your local
officials to make every effort to see that all are tallied. But
when the census form arrives, fill it out honestly.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the legal objection to falsifying the form, it is in
everyone's interest to make the count as accurate as possible. If
your policy were universally adopted, the census would be
discredited as little more than fiction, particularly the part
about the 35 Guamanians living in my apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Q. My school's parking lot has only 47 spots for 100 students
who drive. I asked a school administrator where I could park off
campus legally. I parked where he told me, but my car was ticketed
and towed because the fire chief thought that the many cars on that
street caused a fire hazard. Who should pay for the impound and
ticket? Who is at fault?
</P>
<P>
   _ Joshua Fink, Englewood, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   A. Bad advice offered in good faith is not bad ethics. If that
administrator says it will be sunny tomorrow, you can't sue him if
it rains. He is offering an opinion outside the authority of his
office. The responsibility to wear a hat is yours.
</P>
<P>
   If you parked in a legal spot, fight the ticket and ask the
school official to support you. If the spot was not legal, his
opinion doesn't change that, so you're stuck. Tell the official
what happened so he will know he is misinformed and will stop
giving bad advice. And who knows: he may offer to pay part of the
ticket to compensate for his bad advice.
</P>
<P>
   Q. At a gourmet market where I shop, more than a few customers
help themselves to handfuls of nuts and dried fruits without
paying. This is clearly unsanitary. I've mentioned it to the
cashiers, who say that no one in charge cares enough to stop it.
May I say something to these freeloaders or should I ignore the
situation and fume inwardly?
</P>
<P>
   _ N. Levy, New York
</P>
<P>
   A. If you catch people actually napping in the pickle barrel,
you may jostle them awake and give them a stern talking to. In the
cases you describe, however, I think the health risk is minimal.
Perhaps what makes you fume is less a matter of hygiene than moral
outrage. However, while the behavior you describe sounds like
stealing to me, if the owners of the shop know about it and do
nothing to stop it, your ethical imperative is lifted. The store
may be willing to tolerate this sampling for the good will it
engenders, or at least to avoid the hassle. Their store, their
choice. My anti-fuming advice is to tell the owners that you intend
to shop elsewhere, and why, and then do so.
</P>
<P>
   Q. About a year ago, a friend borrowed $10,000 from another
friend of mine. Not only has the borrower not returned the money,
he also shows no inclination of ever doing so. By remaining friends
with the welsher without so much as a comment, am I condoning his
reprehensible behavior? Am I wrong to remain his friend?
</P>
<P>
   _ Lawrence Toffler, Los Angeles
</P>
<P>
   A. If every time two friends quarreled and all their mutual
friends had to choose sides, none of us would have many friends
left. Fortunately, you are not obliged to cut off all ties to the
deadbeat, but you should not ignore his bad behavior. Use your
continued association to remind the defaulting friend of his
obligation _ gently, but persistently _ and make it clear that you
do not condone his lapse.
</P>
<P>
   Your situation will become more difficult if the injured party
demands that you break off with the deadbeat. Then you may have to
take a side. But while there are indeed transgressions grave enough
to sink a friendship, for now, at least, this isn't one of them.
Still, I wouldn't lend him any money. Or a cup of sugar. Or a cup.
</P>
<P>
   Do you have ethical questions that you need answered? Send them
to ethicist &LR; nytimes.com, or Everyday Ethics, New York Times
Syndicate, 122 East 42nd St., 14th floor, New York, N.Y. 10168.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on EVERYDAY
ETHICS and other features. &QL;
</P>
