<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NINERS-SEASON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CLARK DEFENDS ROLE IN DEMISE OF THE 49ERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN CRUMPACKER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ If only the San Francisco 49ers had had Steve
Young and Garrison Hearst healthy for the entire season, they might
have been a playoff team once again.
</P>
<P>
   That is the opinion of Dwight Clark, the man who lost a bid to
become club president and fled to Cleveland to become vice
president and general manager of the Browns.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being a playoff contender, the 49ers tumbled to their
worst record in 20 years, 4-12, as Young missed the last 13 games
of the season after suffering concussions on consecutive weeks.
</P>
<P>
   People within the 49ers organization and around the league blame
Clark and Carmen Policy, now president and part owner of the
Browns, for the predicament the San Francisco club is in. The two
executives ran up a huge salary cap debt that had to be paid off in
a series of painful moves in February as the 49ers slashed $24
million from the payroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was always understood the team would have had to go through
a couple of bad years'' as a result, said Clark, in Palm Beach for
the NFL owners meetings. ``I knew it would have happened at some
point and I wanted to stay around and go through it.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the salary cap purge, the 49ers were not able to
seriously pursue any unrestricted free agents this year. It was all
they could do to get under the $62 million per-team cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a problem for the foreseeable future,'' general
manager Bill Walsh said. ``There was no way for us to acquire a
free agent of consequence because of cap problems. We're looking at
the draft. There are no short-form answers.''
</P>
<P>
   After Policy left for the Browns in the summer of 1998, Clark
campaigned for his club president's job. When then-owner Edward
DeBartolo Jr. told him that was not going to happen, Clark left for
Cleveland after the '98 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our plan was as long as Steve Young and Jerry Rice were
playing at a high level and gave us an opportunity to win a Super
Bowl, we were going to keep patching holes around them and make a
run at it,'' Clark said. ``At some point we knew because of the cap
situation we were going to go through a down year or two. I don't
think I'm without fault. The most important thing to me was I
didn't get to the point where the team was getting ready to
collapse and then bolt. I tried to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers are waiting to hear from Young regarding his football
future. He is currently on his honeymoon with bride Barbara Graham.
The 49ers do not expect to hear from him one way or another until
after the draft April 15-16, perhaps not until June.
</P>
<P>
   Rice's situation is strictly a financial one. He is due to count
nearly $5.5 million against the 2000 salary cap. The 49ers want to
negotiate a more cap-friendly contract with him before June 1, the
date in which roster moves count toward the 2001 salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're closing in on a time period when both their situations
have to be dealt with and addressed,'' Walsh said. ``We have two
months, basically, to get their situations resolved. With Steve
it's whether he's able to play. With Jerry it's a matter of us
being able to resolve his contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh said the 49ers would probably hold onto the first of their
two first-round draft picks, No. 12 overall, and use it on one of
four need positions: quarterback, defensive end, linebacker and
cornerback. With or without Young, San Francisco will look to draft
a quarterback, though probably not with the 12th pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to go into the draft taking the position we need a
quarterback for the future,'' Walsh said. ``We would have anyway.
Steve knows we're looking in the draft for a quarterback we can
nurture into a starting role.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
