<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-MYSTERIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FIRST THRILLER HARBINGER OF BRIGHT FOR AUTHOR 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (ATTN: N.Y., Texas)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BOBBIE HESS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chris Larsgaard's thriller, ``The Heir Hunter'' (Delacorte
Press, $23.95, 356 pages), is a fast-paced debut that points to a
bright future for this writer.
</P>
<P>
   Like the author, Larsgaard's protagonist specializes in a very
lucrative field of private investigations. Nick Merchant and his
partner, Alex Moreno, hunt for the heirs of people who die leaving
no will and no known relatives. If they find the heirs, they get a
percentage of the estate.
</P>
<P>
   Merchant works out of the San Francisco office and Moreno out of
her home in Albany, N.Y. They are being squeezed by a very
unethical company in Los Angeles that is willing to pay bribes to
get early, insider information. As the story begins, Moreno is
going to the Columbia County (N.Y.) clerk's building to offer a
bribe to the attorney in charge of the county's probate files. The
probate attorney has agreed that he will give Merchant and Moreno
``an exclusive 10-day sneak preview'' of the files in exchange for
$5,000. But when he meets with Moreno, he demands $10,000 because
one of the files is worth more than six figures. When she reads the
files, she calls Merchant, saying she'll fax the file to him
because he isn't going to believe that they have got the case of a
lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Raymond Jacobs died in Hudson, N.Y., and left an estate
of $22,346,000. Excited, they start looking into Jacobs' life. What
they don't know is that the attorney also sold the information to
their chief rivals and for some unknown reason, the FBI wants no
one to look into Jacobs' past.
</P>
<P>
   The search will cause Merchant to break into Jacobs' home
searching for clues, then a hit man will shoot a cop and make the
FBI think Merchant did it. His apartment will be bombed, his
secretary murdered, his office torched as he keeps a step ahead of
the FBI and the hit man who is trying to kill him. His search will
take him to the Midwest, Austria and Switzerland. As he and Moreno
discover Jacobs' heirs, two will turn up murdered and Moreno will
try to keep the third alive as they try to get the money released
to her.
</P>
<P>
   Larsgaard makes a subject that could be boring into a real,
intriguing whodunit. Good characterization, terse dialogue and a
well-constructed plot add to a fascinating first work. I really
look forward to Larsgaard's second outing.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chill Factor.'' By Chris Rogers. Bantam Books. $23.95. 325
pages.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Rogers' third mystery featuring bounty hunter Dixie
Flanagan is a Texas joyride.
</P>
<P>
   While on a stakeout, Flanagan discovers that her checking
account is missing a lot of money. After she captures the con,
Flanagan heads for the bank to discover what happened to her money.
Turns out someone got some of Flanagan's old canceled checks to use
in a scam to empty her account. But before she leaves the bank,
there is a holdup, a shot is fired and a little old lady who looks
suspiciously like her 66-year-old neighbor Edna makes off with
several bags of cash. Edna is chased down, shot and killed by the
police and the money is nowhere to be found. The day before,
another Granny Bandit had held up another bank, was shot and
killed, with the money gone missing.
</P>
<P>
   Edna's son begs Flanagan to try to find out what drove his
mother to such a crazy and irrational act. Of course, Flanagan gets
involved and uncovers the story of lonely widow who set out to
create a new life, with new friends and interests, only to become a
pawn in the hands of a cold-blooded killer with a devious plan to
destroy a former adversary.
</P>
<P>
   This is a chilling look at how con artists and others prey on
the lonely and the elderly. Flanagan is one of those smart-mouth
protagonists you can't help but like. Off-beat characters add up to
a fast-paced beach book.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-00 1737EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
