<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0372 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SEXPISTOLS-FILM-REVIE     03-28 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEXPISTOLS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 `THE FILTH AND THE FURY': A ROCK BAND THAT HURLED ROCKS AT '70s(Eds: Production notes at end of review) 
(jt) 
 By A.O. SCOTT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   By any reasonable standard, the Sex Pistols would scarcely rate
a footnote in the annals of rock 'n' roll: in the 26 months of
their existence, they recorded exactly one album, were dropped by a
succession of record labels and self-destructed in the course of
their only tour of the United States. But the violent obliteration
of reasonable standards _ of rock decorum, of musical competence,
of decent behavior _ was what the Sex Pistols were all about.
</P>
<P>
   In case you thought the passage of time and the putative
coarsening of popular culture had dulled the group's ferocity,
``The Filth and the Fury,'' Julien Temple's electrifying new
documentary, will make you think again. The film presents the Sex
Pistols in all their scabrous glory: spewing obscenities on British
television, spitting at journalists and fans and generally smashing
through the drabness and hypocrisy of 1970s Britain like a brick
through a shop window. At a time when every obscenity or aesthetic
shock tactic feels like the product either of careful market
research or dutiful graduate-school training, the filth and fury of
British punk rock at its moment of impact retains a surprising
dignity. These people hated everything, but at least they believed
in something.
</P>
<P>
   In the 20-odd years since their chaotic rise and messy demise, a
number of legends have sprung up in the Sex Pistols' wake, among
them that they were never a rock band at all but rather an impish
piece of Conceptual Art masterminded by their manager, the
erstwhile London boutique owner Malcolm McLaren.
</P>
<P>
   Temple allows McLaren to repeat his claim that the Sex Pistols
were ``my sculpture, my painting, my little artful dodgers,'' but
``The Filth and the Fury'' is devoted to the anti-McLarenite
version of Sex Pistols history. In this view, most passionately
argued by Johnny Rotten, the band's lead singer and intellectual
conscience, punk was the spontaneous organic expression of
working-class rage and boredom and McLaren was a poseur and an
opportunist who stole the band's money and turned its members
against each other.
</P>
<P>
   Though Temple stacks the deck somewhat _ his interviews with
McLaren are played over the image of a rubber bondage mask swelling
with what we can only assume is hot air _ he makes a persuasive
case that the Sex Pistols were nobody's art project. And his own
artfulness lifts ``The Filth and the Fury'' above the run of the
rockumentary mill, placing it in the rarefied company of D.A.
Pennebaker's ``Don't Look Now'' and ``The Decline of Western
Civilization,'' Penelope Spheeris' 1981 anatomy of the Los Angeles
punk scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Filth and the Fury'' is a bit like punk fashion, a rough,
safety-pin-in-cheek assemblage of found materials: BBC public
affairs programs that seemed to have been modeled on Monty Python
parodies; mock superhero cartoons recycled from ``The Great Rock
and Roll Swindle,'' Temple's earlier Sex Pistols epic (never
released in this country); grainy evening-news glimpses of
Britain's social disintegration; and scenes from Laurence Olivier's
``Richard III.''
</P>
<P>
   Bad King Richard in doublet and hose is a devilish premonition
of Johnny Rotten in his torn black suit coat and skinny tie,
rolling his eyes and his Rs, pronouncing anarchist to almost rhyme
with antichrist and burning with a hard, gemlike flame of
intelligence and rage. If there is one complaint to be made about
``The Filth and the Fury,'' it is that there's not enough music;
only three songs are performed in something like their entirety.
But they're songs you want to hear: ``Anarchy in the U.K.''
(twice), ``Holidays in the Sun'' and, of course, ``God Save the
Queen,'' the No. 1 single in England in the summer of 1977, which
could not be heard on the BBC or even mentioned in the pop charts.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Young once sang, apropos of Johnny Rotten, that ``it's
better to burn out than to fade away.'' The demise of the Sex
Pistols was as fast and ugly as their music. Temple doesn't avert
his gaze from the wasted life of Sid Vicious, a young groupie who
replaced Glen Matlock as the group's bass player, in spite of his
utter lack of musical aptitude, and who died of a heroin overdose
after being charged with killing his girlfriend. Nor does the film
ignore the betrayals and recriminations that followed the group
across the Atlantic, and finally destroyed them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Filth and The Fury,'' like the career it documents, ends
on a San Francisco concert stage, with Rotten demanding of the
audience, ``Ever get the feeling you've been cheated?'' It was a
rhetorical question at the time, but in retrospect, the answer is
no. The Sex Pistols gave everything they had, and Temple's film is
a gift to them and to their fans. Nihilism like this makes you glad
to be alive.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE FILTH AND THE FURY'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Julien Temple; edited by Niven Howie; produced by
Anita Camarata and Amanda Temple; released by Fine Line Features.
Running time: 105 minutes. This film is rated R.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: The Sex Pistols: Paul Cook, Steve Jones, Glen Matlock,
Johnny ``Rotten'' Lydon and Sid Vicious, and Malcolm MacLaren (the
band's manager).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
