<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0375 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER29-COX     03-28 1389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Forbes in Bush camp
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush is gaining the endorsement of former rival Steve
Forbes in the latest move toward reconciliation within the
Republican Party after a bruising primary contest. Forbes, the
wealthy magazine publisher, plans to announce his support Tuesday
night at an appearance with Bush in Manville, N.J., Forbes' home
state. Forbes adviser Greg Mueller confirmed the planned
endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   ILLITERACY PROPOSALS SPELLED OUT
</P>
<P>
   Addressing Asian-American businesspeople at the headquarters of
Sallie Mae in Reston, Va., George W. Bush called illiteracy among
schoolchildren a ``national emergency'' Tuesday, and proposed
spending $5 billion over five years to address the problem. The
money would pay for diagnostic programs to identify troubled
children in kindergarten and first grade, and pay teachers a
stipend of $230 a day to receive training in diagnosing student
reading problems. The program's biggest emphasis _ $900 million
annually _ would be on literacy programs designed and implemented
at the local level. Sallie Mae is the nation's largest provider of
student loans.
</P>
<P>
   GIULIANI'S COOLNESS HEATS UP RACE
</P>
<P>
   A new poll suggests that Rudy Giuliani's unsympathetic response
after the latest police shooting of an unarmed black man is hurting
him in his Senate race against Hillary Rodham Clinton. A Zogby
International poll shows Giuliani's seven-point lead has vanished
following the killing of Patrick Dorismond on March 16. Clinton now
has 45 percent to Giuliani's 42 percent _ within the poll's
3.8-point margin of error. Eighty percent of the people polled said
the mayor should have offered condolences to the victim's family,
and one in four said the issue would be a factor in whether they
vote for Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   POWER STRUGGLE NOT OVER YET
</P>
<P>
   A day after his chairmanship of the Reform Party was upheld by a
federal judge, Pat Choate moved to stabilize the fractured third
party with plans to raise $1 million in the next several months and
to reach out to his vanquished rival. But there was no sign that
Jack Gargan, ally of Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura who fought Choate
for the chairmanship, would accept the gesture. Gargan vowed to
leave the party and take his supporters with him after U.S.
District Judge Norman Moon ruled that the chairmanship belongs to
Choate.
</P>
<P>
   DON'T FORGET YOUR DAY JOB
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush's quest for the White House has left him with
little time to spend on state business in the Texas Capitol.
According to the governor's official calendar and records kept by
his campaign, during the 25-week period from Oct. 1 through March
23, Bush spent 103 days out of the state campaigning and 20 days in
his state office doing the job he tells voters qualifies him to be
president. Bush's calendar, which tracks his Monday-through-Friday
work week, showed him in his office just one day each in January
and February, three so far this month, three in December and six
each in October and November.
</P>
<P>
   TEST FOR WELCOMING MCCAIN SUPPORTERS
</P>
<P>
   The Log Cabin Republicans, a gay rights organization, have been
pressing for a meeting with George W. Bush since last spring, but
Bush has demurred because the group's leaders supported Bush's
chief rival, John McCain. ``We think that's shortsighted,'' said
Richard Tafel, a top Log Cabin official. ``We are exactly the
people he should be meeting with. A lot of McCain people are
watching the Bush campaign wondering if they want us back, whether
we will be welcome in the party.'' Bush spokesman Scott McClellen
said there probably would not be a meeting _ because the group
``continues to politicize'' the question of whether there would be
a meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACKS IN THE FORM OF A QUESTION
</P>
<P>
   In the latest effort to influence the presidential race via
secret contributors, a group of high-profile California Republicans
is running TV ads calling Al Gore a hypocrite on campaign finance
and other issues. Former California Gov. Pete Wilson is raising
money for the new group, Shape the Debate, but the donor list is
not public information. Patterned after the game show
``Jeopardy!,'' the 30-second spot pretends to be a show called
``Hypocrisy.'' A contestant chooses ``political hypocrites for
200'' and is told: ``He says he supports campaign finance reform,
but held an illegal fund-raiser at a Buddhist Temple.'' The answer:
``Who is Al Gore?''
</P>
<P>
   ROLE REVERSAL
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore and George W. Bush have swapped places, the Boston Globe
has observed. To wit: Months ago, Bush's personality was his
biggest asset; now Gore's personality is a bigger asset than
Bush's. Months ago, Bush's leadership style was a big plus for him;
now Gore's leadership style is a bigger asset. Months ago, Bush was
considered the candidate most likely to appeal to independents;
now, Gore is. The Globe called this change in dynamic one of the
most astonishing alterations in a political campaign in history.
</P>
<P>
   LIKE VENUS AND MARS IN ELECTION, TOO
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore will need a substantial turnout of women in his home
state in November, according to a new poll, because the gender gap
so visible across the country is also a major factor in Tennessee.
The Mason-Dixon poll shows that while women in Tennessee favor Gore
by a margin of 20 points over George W. Bush, men prefer Bush by an
8-point margin. Overall, Gore leads Bush, 47 percent to 41 percent,
with 10 percent undecided. The poll, conducted 10 days ago, has a 4
percentage point margin of error.
</P>
<P>
   OK, WOMEN, LET'S BRUSH UP HERE
</P>
<P>
   They are the most sought-after voters, the ones who can make or
break presidential campaigns. But when it comes to knowing facts
about politics, women inexplicably lag behind men. That conclusion,
reached in a study by the Annenberg Public Policy Center at the
University of Pennsylvania, is true for issues ranging from
positions on nuclear test ban treaties to abortion rights. Of 25
questions about specific issues in this year's presidential
campaign or the backgrounds of four major presidential candidates,
women outperformed men on only one question _ about the Democratic
candidates' positions on public financing of campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT BETTER PLACE FOR SHOW BIZ?
</P>
<P>
   After a rocky start marked by resignations and charges of
disorganization, planning for the Democratic National Convention is
picking up steam. The convention delegates' biggest job in August _
nominating the Democrats' presidential candidate _ is already
settled; Al Gore has the nomination sewn up. What the party wants
most from Los Angeles is a good show _ and a smooth one. Sherry
Bebitch of Claremont Graduate University's School of Politics and
Economics, doubts that any convention glitches _ and there will be
glitches _ will reflect badly on Gore. She figures people will
chalk it up to ``Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   NELSON LOOKING GOOD IN NEBRASKA
</P>
<P>
   In the contest to fill the seat of retiring Democratic Sen. Bob
Kerrey in Nebraska, former Gov. Ben Nelson, also a Democrat, leads
the six potential Republican nominees. An Omaha World-Herald poll
shows Nelson would defeat each of the Republicans by a margin of
more than 2-to-1. The leading Republican, state Attorney General
Don Stenberg, has been an outspoken opponent of abortion,
characterizing certain procedures as something close to
infanticide. The poll found that Nelson had a favorable rating of
71 percent.
</P>
<P>
   HE'D BEEN BETTER OFF NOT VOTING
</P>
<P>
   James Epperson faced no opposition in the March 14 Republican
primary for his county commissioner seat in Edwards County, Texas,
so he crossed over to vote in the Democratic primary. But now,
because he voted in the Democratic race, Epperson cannot run for
his own seat as a Republican in November, according to Texas state
election laws. ``I just made a stupid mistake. That's all it boils
down to,'' Epperson told the San Antonio Express-News.
</P>
<P>
   Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
