<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0377 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-SMOKING-VERDICT-HNS &LR;      03-28 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMOKING-VERDICT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     JURY VERDICT OPENS DOOR TO MORE LAWSUITS AGAINST TOBACCO
COMPANIES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By EMILY GURNON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A jury verdict awarding $20 million in punitive
damages to a former smoker who is now dying of lung cancer is the
latest in a handful of significant courtroom defeats for the
tobacco industry in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Superior Court case involved a Ventura County
woman, Leslie Whiteley, who was awarded $10 million each from the
R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Company and Philip Morris Cos.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the jury awarded Whiteley and her husband an
additional $1.7 million for medical costs and pain and suffering.
</P>
<P>
   The case is significant because it is the first lawsuit the
industry has lost involving a smoker who took up the habit after
government-mandated warning labels began appearing on cigarettes in
the late 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   It proves that ``the tobacco companies are wrong that just
getting Congress to put this warning label on a product is going to
protect them from misleading the public for 50 years,'' Madelyn
Chaber, the lead lawyer for Whiteley and her husband, said after
the verdict on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Whiteley case was the third straight major defeat for the
tobacco industry on the West Coast. Those and other adverse
verdicts have sent the value of Philip Morris shares plummeting.
The company makes about half the cigarettes sold in the United
States each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't really expecting any good news to come out of that
trial,'' said Brian Eisenbarth, a portfolio manager and tobacco
industry analyst with Collins &AMP; Co. LLC in Larkspur, Calif., whose
company owns some Philip Morris stock. ``The chances of winning at
the jury level, I think, are slim for the tobacco industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Though it is ``not a lot of money'' for the gigantic companies,
Eisenbarth said the verdict may encourage other sick people who
began smoking after the warning labels came out to take their cases
to court. ``The problem is, this is only one person,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But industry representatives denied the verdict represents a
trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juries in general tend to believe, and we believe, that
despite today's verdict smokers have long been aware of the
significant inherent risks of smoking, and that people who choose
to smoke in the face of these known risks should not be financially
rewarded,`` Seth Moskowitz, a spokesman for R.J. Reynolds, said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   He said tobacco companies have won six out of the last nine
cases involving individuals and smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Moskowitz said that California juries tend to behave differently
than those elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``One must remember that we are in a state where people are not
allowed to smoke even in bars,'' he said. In future cases, the
company will take into account the fact that ``jurors in Northern
California come into the courtroom with a different mind-set'' and
it will ``provide additional information to help (them) put the
facts in the proper perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the cases the industry has lost in recent years, three have
been overturned on appeal and two have had their damages amounts
reduced by judges. R.J. Reynolds has said it will file a post-trial
motion to get the Whiteley verdict overturned by the judge; if that
fails, it will appeal.
</P>
<P>
   R.J. Reynolds currently has about 530 cases pending against it,
Moskowitz said.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris Cos. could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Whiteley, a 40-year-old mother of four from Ojai, used her lunch
money to buy her first pack of cigarettes out of a vending machine
when she was 13. She smoked Marlboros and Camel Lights, averaging
two packs a day. She quit smoking 25 years later.
</P>
<P>
   Chaber said Whiteley's family was ``very happy'' about the
verdict, ``but it comes at the expense of her life. They would be
happy to trade this money back in exchange for her life.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said she would probably die this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-00 1750EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
