<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0378 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-JAPAN-SHAREHOLDERS-37     03-28 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-SHAREHOLDERS-375&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKHOLDER ACTIVIST LOSES ANOTHER FIGHT WITH JAPANESE COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ A Japanese shareholder activist, whose failed effort to
buy a company in Japan's first hostile takeover fight attracted
widespread attention, suffered a second defeat Tuesday when that
company repulsed his requests to raise its dividend and make him a
director.
</P>
<P>
   Shoei Co., a small electronics parts maker with valuable real
estate holdings that are not reflected in its share price,
announced at the annual shareholders meeting that the requests by
Yoshiaki Murakami had been voted down. But it did not give a
precise vote, and Murakami's aides indicated he might challenge the
results.
</P>
<P>
   Murakami is a former civil servant who quit public service
nearly a year ago and formed his own investment group with the goal
of investing in poorly run Japanese companies and driving their
share prices up. He is regarded as somewhat of a threat to the
entrenched corporate interests in Japan, where many companies own
controlling stakes in each other and the well-being of individual
shareholders is largely ignored.
</P>
<P>
   His struggle to acquire Shoei in a tender offer to shareholders,
which failed last month despite the 14 percent premium he offered,
was widely viewed as a test of corporate Japan's willingness to
change.
</P>
<P>
   Murakami did gain control of 6.52 percent of Shoei, however, and
said he would try to press the company to disperse the roughly $660
million in unrealized gains on its real estate and securities
holdings through a higher dividend to shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Shoei has aggressively resisted Murakami. It has hired Hideaki
Kubori, a prominent lawyer best known for his efforts to fight
sokaiya, or shareholder racketeers linked to the Japanese mob, in a
not-so-subtle effort to cast Murakami as an unsavory character.
</P>
<P>
   The company also marshaled the support of bigger, more powerful
members of its corporate group, or keiretsu.
</P>
<P>
   Shoei is part of Fuyo Group, clustered around Fuji Bank and its
sister financial companies like Yasuda Fire &AMP; Marine Insurance Co.
and Yasuda Trust Bank. Members of the group control more than 60
percent of Shoei's shares, and the company's board has long served
as a sort of preserve for former Fuji executives. This type of cozy
system exists throughout corporate Japan.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Even with the defeats of Murakami, however, his public challenge
to the system has helped highlight what critics call its stifling
effects.
</P>
<P>
   Murakami received the backing of Jean-Marie Eveillard and
Charles de Vaulx, who manage the First Eagle SoGen investment
funds, and other foreign money managers, as well as many individual
shareholders. According to Shoei, of the 253 shareholders who
presented their proxies, 150 backed Murakami.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think this effort was a failure,'' said Kenya
Takizawa, a partner in Mergers and Acquisitions Consulting Inc.,
Murakami's firm. ``Of course, we didn't win the game today, but it
was a much closer match than we expected.''
</P>
<P>
   The overall vote count, however, remained unclear. When Murakami
asked Shoei's president, Tanehiko Kamiura, to enumerate the votes
for and against, Kamiura demurred, according to Takizawa. He was
not at the meeting but got a report from others there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, there was confusion,'' he said. ``For us, it is
not clear how many voted for Murakami's proposals and how many
against, so we will ask to examine the proxies.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that Murakami might take legal action if there were any
discrepancies in the count.
</P>
<P>
   Takayuki Uchiyama, a spokesman for Shoei, said that as most
senior executive of the company, it was Kamiura's responsibility to
count the proxies received in advance of the shareholders' meeting.
``He said more than two-thirds of the shareholders opposed the
proposals,'' Uchiyama said. ``It is up to the chairman's judgment.
He is entrusted with the count.''
</P>
<P>
   Makoto Saito, a spokesman for Yasuda Trust Bank, said the bank
had voted against Murakami's proposals because it trusted current
management and was not interested in fatter dividends.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not necessarily better to receive the dividends in
cash,'' Saito said. ``We prefer the accumulation of capital and
internal reserves.''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
,
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
