<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, March 29, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(jt) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Chilly air will continue to circulate into the Northeast around
a sprawling low pressure zone over southeastern Canada. Gusty
breezes will add to the chill of the day from the eastern Great
Lakes to the Northeast Coast. Sunshine will be limited near the
northern Appalachians, where scattered mountain snow showers and
valley sprinkles will occur. Coastal areas will stay dry with a
mixture of clouds and sun.
</P>
<P>
   A front separating summer heat over South Texas from cooler air
to the north will be the focus for clouds and thundershowers. A
cluster of thunderstorms will weaken early Wednesday over East
Texas and Oklahoma, but will regenerate during the midday over the
southern Mississippi Valley. Some storms will have hail and
damaging winds.
</P>
<P>
   Lighter showers will dampen parts of the western Plains and
northern Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: RADIOACTIVE SNOW
</P>
<P>
   Mountains are water reservoirs for the West, collecting and
storing snow during winter. Once the dry season begins in late
spring, runoff from melting mountain snow provides fresh water for
many communities. To ascertain the amount of water in the snow,
water officials sometimes employ gamma radiation. In autumn,
detectors aboard low-flying aircraft sense gamma rays naturally
emanating from bare ground. Readings are repeated the following
spring. Based on the reduction of gamma rays by the snowpack, the
amount of water stored in the snow can be determined.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
