<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GETAWAY-FESTIVALS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The ``Top 20'' events in the Southeast for spring
 &HT;    By Howard Pousner and Paula Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pollen isn't the only thing blanketing the South now that spring
has sprung. Festivals of all types are popping up across the
region.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping track of it all is the Atlanta-based Southeast Tourism
Society, which judges more than 1,000 entries each year to come up
with quarterly lists of the best events in 10 Southeastern states.
It has just issued the following ``Top 20 Events'' lists for each
month of spring:
</P>
<P>
   APRIL
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  April 1, 7, 8: Florida State University ``Flying High''
Circus, Tallahassee. Students act as riggers and costumers as well
as performers, doing high wire and flying trapeze acts in three
rings. 850-644-4874, www.fsu.edu.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  April 6-9: DoubleTake Documentary Film Festival, Durham, N.C.
The Carolina Theatre of Durham hosts this international festival of
documentary cinema. This year's theme: Youth and Coming of Age.
919-660-3663, www.carolinatheatre.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  April 6-9: North Carolina Azalea Festival, Wilmington, N.C. A
seasonal celebration of heritage, arts, culture and hospitality
with a street fair featuring food, entertainment, fireworks.
910-763-0905, www.azalea
</P>
<P>
   .wilmington.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  April 6-15: 53rd Annual Gulf Coast Spring Pilgrimage, includes
the Mississippi cities of Pass Christian, Diamondhead, Ocean
Springs, Pascagoula, Bay St. Louis, Gulfport, Biloxi, Long Beach,
Gautier. Landscaped homes, landscaping seminars, music.
228-875-7248.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  April 7-9, 14-16: Spring Stroll 2000, Covington, Ky. Historic
Main Strasse Village, a restored 19th-century German neighborhood,
hosts an event featuring shopping, dining and visits with the
Easter Bunny. 606-491-0458, www.mainstrasse.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  April 7-9: Odessa Rodeo &AMP; Festival, Odessa, Fla. Bronc-riders,
bull-wrestlers entertain; also, carnival rides, barbecue and music.
727-869-6677, www.odessarodeo.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  April 7-30: Dogwood Arts Festival, Knoxville. Art exhibits,
dance, music and theater, plus 60 miles of Dogwood Trails.
865-637-4561.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  April 8-9: Ponchatoula Strawberry Festival, Ponchatoula, La.
``America's Antique City'' honors another product that has made the
parish famous: strawberries. 504-386-6677, www.tangi-cvb.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  April 10-16: MCI Classic _ The Heritage of Golf, Hilton Head
Island, S.C. Harbour Town Golf Links hosts this PGA Tour
tournament. 843-671-2448.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  April 13-16: Country Cajun Crawfish Festival, Biloxi, Miss.
More than 10,000 pounds of hot, spicy crawfish are the center of
attention. Kenny Chesney, Sawyer Brown, LeRoy Parnell and Andy
Griggs entertain. 228-594-3700, www.mscoastcoliseum.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  April 14-16: French Quarter Festival, New Orleans. The world's
largest jazz brunch includes more than 100 hours of free
entertainment on 14 stages. 504-522-5730, www
</P>
<P>
   .frenchquarterfestivals.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  April 14-May 7: Kentucky Derby Festival, Louisville, Ky. The
world's most famous horse race is the main event, but more than 80
community activities precede it. 502-584-6383, www.kdf.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  April 15: Riverfest, Columbia, S.C. The Mayor's 5K River Run
and Walk and the Celebrity River Raft Race, as well as arts and
crafts, live music, food and family fun. At Riverfront Park.
803-926-0071, www.epilepsysc.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  April 15-16: Dollywood's Grand Opening Weekend and 15th
Birthday Celebration, Pigeon Forge, Tenn. Dolly Parton returns to
her native Sevier County to kick off the 15th season. New
attraction: Dreamland Forest, a 15,000-square-foot interactive
children's area. 1-800-365-5996, www.dollywood.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  April 24-30: Norfolk's International Azalea Festival _ A
Salute to NATO, Norfolk, Va. Each year one NATO country _ Iceland
this year _ is honored and a young woman from this country is
crowned Azalea Queen at Norfolk Botanical Garden. 757-662-2525,
www.hrccva.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  April 27-May 21: 4th Annual Virginia Waterfront International
Arts Festival, at venues from Williamsburg to Virginia Beach, Va.
An eclectic lineup of artists from around the world perform
throughout a 50-mile region. Includes the Farukh Ruzimatov and
stars of the Russian Ballet, the Mark Morris Dance Group, Trinity
Irish Dance. 757-664-6490, www.virginiaartsfest
</P>
<P>
   .com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  April 28-30: Panoply, Huntsville, Ala. Dance, theatre, music
and visual arts. 256-519-2787, www.panoply.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  April 28-30: Delray Affair, Delray Beach, Fla. Three stages
feature music and dance, and more than 400 artists and craftsmen
set up along eight blocks of Atlantic Avenue. 561-278-0424,
www.delrayaffair.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  April 29-30: Celebrate the Arts! Callaway Gardens, Pine
Mountain, Ga. With a background of spring's botanical splendor,
performing artists are headlined by pianist-entertainer Charles
Wadsworth. 1-800-225-5292, www.callawaygardens.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  April 29-June 11: Georgia Renaissance Festival, Fairburn, Ga.
Adventure, comedy and romance at a 93-acre re-creation of a
rollicking 16th-century English kingdom. 770-964-8575,
www.garenfest.com.
</P>
<P>
   MAY
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  May 2-14: Contraband Days, Lake Charles, La. Legend has it
that French pirate Jean Lafitte buried his treasure along the
lake's shores. The annual re-creation of this event kicks off the
fest that includes a pirate invasion, parades, crawfish eating
contests and music. 337-436-5508, www.contraband.usunwired.net.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  May 3-7: Sunfest 2000, West Palm Beach, Fla. On Flager Drive
along the Intracoastal Waterway, thousands enjoy 40 national
recording artists on three stages, 160 artists in a juried art show
and fireworks. 561-659-5980, www.sunfest.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  May 5-27: Memphis in May International Festival, Memphis.
India is in the spotlight as the city hosts events including the
Beale Street Music Festival, the World Championship Barbecue
Cooking Contest and the Sunset Symphony. 901-525-4611,
www.memphisinmay.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  May 6: Virginia Gold Cup, The Plains, Va. Thoroughbreds race
over the four-mile Mercedes-Benz Gold Cup classic course of 23
timber fences. Also, plenty of tailgate parties. 540-347-2612.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  May 6: Market Street Festival, Columbus, Miss. Features three
entertainment stages, Kid's Corner, petting zoo, pony rides, train
and carriage rides, and juried art show. 662-328-6305.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  May 6-27: Natchez Opera Festival, Natchez, Miss. Professional
opera stars appear in seven productions, including the ``Barber of
Seville,'' ``Man of La Mancha,'' ``La Traviata'' plus the Broadway
comedy, ``I Do, I Do.'' 1-800-647-6724.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  May 6-27: 600 Festival, Charlotte and Concord, N.C. The NASCAR
Coca-Cola 600 kicks off with a free air show and the Food Lion
Speed Street, offering three stages and 42 bands performing rock
'n' roll, country, etc. 704-455-6814, www.600festival.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  May 12-13: International Bar-B-Que Festival, Owensboro, Ky.
Cooking teams compete in this fest that produces 10 tons of mutton,
5,000 chickens and 1,500 gallons of burgoo. 1- 800-489-1131.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  May 12-14: Kentucky Scottish Weekend, Carrollton, Ky.
Performers from Scotland, piping, drumming, athletic events, ``Wee
Scots Day,'' and cultural and historical seminars. 513-574-2969.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  May 13-14: Prater's Mill Country Fair, Varnell. Held at the
old water-powered mill that still grinds corn and wheat, the fair
focuses on mountain music, Southern foods, living history exhibits
and handmade arts and crafts. 706-694-6455, www.pratersmill.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  May 19-21: Florida Springfest _ Pensacola's Musical
Celebration, Pensacola, Fla. On downtown streets, all kinds of
music on three main stages. 850-469-1069, www.springfest.net.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  May 19-21: Wilmington Greek Festival, Wilmington, N.C. Greek
cuisine and pastries, cooking demonstration, church tours.
910-392-4484.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  May 19-21: Mainstrasse Maifest 2000, Covington, Ky. Thirty
food booths offer traditional German favorites such as brats and
potato pancakes. Country, blues and rock music. 606-491-0458,
www.mainstrasse.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  May 19-20: Gadsden Area Riverfest Festival, Gadsden, Ala. Held
along the Coosa River. The Beach Boys and the Gap Band will
entertain on Friday, John Michael Montgomery and Trisha Yearwood on
Saturday. 1-800-320-1692.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  May 20: Mayfest on the Rivers, Rome. The celebration of Rome's
three rivers includes free riverboat rides on a 48-passenger
excursion boat, the Corrugated Mad River run, and a concert
featuring Percy Sledge and Three Dog Night. 706-295-5576,
www.romegeorgia.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  May 24-28: Gullah Festival, Beaufort, S.C. The celebration of
Gullah culture features Mapapas, the African acrobatics team, the
Black Inventions Museum, cultural workshops, boat building, the
Gullah Golf Tournament, quilting and Lowcountry cuisine.
843-525-0628.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  May 25-28: Mudbug Madness, Shreveport, La. Cajun cuisine,
dance contests, a crawfish-eating contest, children's activities
and Cajun and zydeco music, with Doug Kershaw closing the downtown
fest. 318-222-7403.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  May 26-June 4: Roanoke Festival in the Park, Roanoke, Va. The
children's area offers 30 activities; teens can get glamour
makeovers; adults/families chose from four stages of performing
arts, seven sporting events and car shows. 540-342-2640,
www.rev.net/festival.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  May 26-June 11: Spoleto Festival U.S.A., Charleston, S.C. A
mix of 110-plus world-class performances, plus the literary and
visual arts. 843-722-2764, www.spoletousa.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  May 27-29: Alabama Jubilee Hot Air Balloon Classic, Decatur,
Ala. As many as 75 colorful balloons from around the country
compete in five races. Includes a two-hour balloon glow; plus, a
new extreme sports area. 256-350-2028, www.decaturcvb.org.
</P>
<P>
   JUNE
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 2-3: 10th Annual Country by the Sea Music Festival,
Jekyll Island, Ga. George Jones performs at the South's
longest-running beachside country music festival with other
nationally known artists. 1-877-453-5955, www.jekyllisland.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 2-5: 49th Annual Sun Fun Festival _ A Celebration of
Summer, Myrtle Beach, S.C. Beach games, sporting events, jazz
concerts in the park, parade, an air show and the Miss Bikini
Wahine contest. 843-626-7444, www.myrtlebeachlive.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 2-July 29: Jekyll Island Music Theatre Festival, Jekyll
Island, Ga. Professional actors and students from Valdosta State
University's theater department perform ``Always ... Patsy Cline,''
``She Loves Me'' and ``Carousel'' at the Jekyll Island
Amphitheater. 1-877-453-5955, www.jekyllisland.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 3-18: Fiesta of Five Flags, Pensacola, Fla. Parades,
treasure hunts, a visit by a Spanish tall ship, boat parade and
children's activities. 850-433-6512, www.fiestafiveflags.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 3-Aug. 19: Summer at Callaway Gardens, Pine Mountain, Ga.
Take the kids for miniature golf, the Chickadee Choo Choo, and
enjoy the Florida State University ``Flying High'' Circus.
1-800-225-5292, www.callawaygardens.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 6-8: Mississippi Arts Fair for the Handicapped, Long
Beach, Miss. Featuring 1,500 special participants sharing their
talents of song, dance, drama and arts and crafts. 228-867-1313.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 9-11: 19th Annual Fairfax Fair, Fairfax, Va. Nationally
known entertainers on six stages, hot air balloon rides, carnival,
fireworks and high-tech science exhibits. 703-324-3247,
www.FairfaxFair.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 9-11: Grenada Lakes ``Thunder on Water'' Safe Boating
Festival, Grenada, Miss. Fishing rodeo, light parade on the lake,
ski shows and dragboat races, plus live entertainment, arts and
crafts, antique car show, hot air balloon rides, kid's events and
fireworks. 1-800-373-2571, www.grenadamississippi.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 9-17: Riverbend Festival 2000, Chattanooga. Jethro Tull,
Chicago and Alabama headline; river cruises, sporting events,
fireworks, fine arts exhibits. 423-756-2211,
www.riverbendfestival.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 9-18: 50th Annual Louisiana Peach Festival, Ruston, La.
Entertainment in Railroad Park, rodeo, fishing tournament, softball
and tennis tourneys, cookery contest, fine art reception, peach
hunt, parade and arts and crafts. 1-800-392-9032.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 10-11: North American Sand Soccer Championship, Virginia
Beach, Va. Players from 10 states and a dozen countries compete;
plus a carnival along 14 blocks of boardwalk. 757-471-3337,
www.vbeach.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 10-24: Fiesta Playera 2000, Jacksonville Beach, Fla.
Latin music from salsa and merengue and the cuisine of Puerto Rico,
Cuba, Jamaica and Mexico. 1-877-423-4378, www.fiestaplayera.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 12-16: International Country Music Fan Fair, Nashville.
More than 200 country artists participate in concerts, autograph
sessions, etc. 615-889-7503, www.cmaworld.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 15-18: 45th Annual Boardwalk Art Show, Virginia Beach,
Va. A day at the beach with 330 fine artists; music and theatre
under the stars. 757-425-0000, www.cacv.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 16-18: City Stages, Birmingham's World Class Music
Festival, Birmingham. Three days of music _ acoustic to zydeco, big
band to alternative _ featuring more than 250 acts on 14 stages;
dancing, a children's festival, arts and crafts. 205-251-1272,
www.citystages.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 22-25: Helen Keller Festival, Tuscumbia, Ala. An art
competition for the impaired, parade through downtown, arts and
crafts, tour of historic sites, entertainment including outdoor
performances of William Gibson's ``The Miracle Worker.''
256-383-4066.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 23-24: Beaufort Old Homes &AMP; Gardens Tour, Beaufort, N.C.
The pirate Blackbeard makes appearances during the tour of 10
historic homes and gardens. 252-728-5225, www.historicbeaufort.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 23-25: Bayou Lacombe Crab Festival, Lacombe, La. Held
under moss-laden live oaks in Lacombe Park, the fest features
boiled crabs, crab pastas, soft-shelled crabs, crab po-boys and
other Cajun delicacies. 1-800-634-9443.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 25: Singing on the Mountain, Linville, N.C. Bring a lawn
chair and enjoy musical groups performing gospel all day at
Grandfather Mountain, with a midday sermon. 828-733-2013,
www.grandfather.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 30-July 4: 52nd Annual Mississippi Deep Sea Fishing
Rodeo, Gulfport, Miss. Categories of competition: saltwater, fresh
water and blue water. Fireworks on July 4. 228-832-0079.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB: 'THE TOP 20 EVENTS IN THE SOUTHEAST'
www.accessatlanta.com/travel
</P>
