<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLOOMSIDE33-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Remember: Nature is not on the clock
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, March 30. Story goes with graphic
page.
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there's one thing gardeners know to count on it's that there
are few givens when it comes to the outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   That's an important reminder now that you've checked out Home &AMP;
Garden's bloom calendar in this section. The chart should help you
achieve the most attractive color combinations and time the bloom
periods of plants so that as one splash of color fizzles another is
about to burst.
</P>
<P>
   As you use the calendar, allow us to provide a few reminders:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cameo vs. lead roles: Some plants bloom for only a few days
while others flower for weeks and even months.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Size does matter: Big plants produce showier displays than
small ones. One blue mophead hydrangea will have more impact than a
dozen blue ageratum.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Millennium madness? You can usually bet on when a dogwood or
azalea will bloom. But some plants vary from year to year because
of a variety of factors. (Read on ...)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bizarre temperatures: Spring arrived early in Georgia, forcing
many plants to bloom three to four weeks ahead of ``schedule.'' By
the same token, freezes, known to occur as late as April, can wipe
out an early or even normal display of color. ``Temperature is the
real biggie,'' said Mildred Pinnell, horticulturist at the Atlanta
Botanical Garden.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Swamps and deserts: Droughts, such as the current one, can
affect when plants bloom, though most gardeners are able to manage
with proper watering techniques.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Their own little worlds: Remember that microclimates exist
within climates. These pockets shelter plants from exposure and can
affect bloom times.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dirty business: Soil conditions can have an impact, too. In
poor, unamended soil, for example, plants will struggle and lag
behind others.
</P>
<P>
   With those things in mind, make a date with your plants.
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
