<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-NETANYAHU _ JERUSALEM _ Israeli police Tuesday
recommended that former Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu be
charged with accepting a bribe and illegal gifts while in office.
The charges, if filed and if they lead to a conviction, could bring
a jail sentence. Police also recommended that Netanyahu's wife,
Sarah Netanyahu, be charged. The bribery recommendation stems from
work a contractor did on the Netanyahus' private house, apparently,
police say, in expectation that the prime minister would give him
contracts. The gifts included those from foreign dignitaries,
including a gold letter opener from Vice President Al Gore.
Netanyahu will hold a televised news conference at 1 p.m. EST to
dispute the allegations. (Kaplow, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   WACO-RENO _ WASHINGTON _ Janet Reno is scheduled to be deposed
Tuesday by plaintiffs' attorneys in the Branch Davidian civil
lawsuit. (Malone, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   TORNADOS _ WASHINGTON _ Reinforcing homes and other buildings
can protect them against all but the strongest tornados, according
to a study of the May 1998 Oklahoma City tornado released Tuesday
by Federal Emergency Management Agency Director James Lee Witt.
(Turay, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SCFLAG _ COLUMBIA, S.C. _ Few, if any, local NAACP
officials will be in the audience Wednesday when President Clinton
speaks at a fund-raising dinner in Columbia, where he's expected to
denounce the Confederate flag flying atop the Statehouse. What
would seem a natural rally for flag opponents, such as the NAACP,
is complicated by the organization's national economic boycott of
South Carolina. ``We would have preferred that the president come
in and leave,'' said Dwight James, executive director of the
NAACP's South Carolina conference. ``We are hopeful that any
visitors coming in for the dinner will not stay in hotels or
frequent other tourist venues in Columbia.'' A look at how the
boycott is inconveniencing black organizations and colleges, pegged
to Clinton's speech at a $500-per-person state Democratic Party
fund-raiser to honor U.S. Rep. Jim Clyburn, chairman of the
Congressional Black Caucus. (Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLBUS-TRAIN _ CHATSWORTH, Ga. _ A Murray County, Ga., school
bus and a train collided at a crossing just across the Tennessee
border Tuesday morning. Early reports say two kids dead, five
critically injured. The collision was at an intersection with no
signals or bars. (Schneider, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ALAMIN _ ATLANTA _ A grand jury indictment is possible today in
the case of Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin, formerly H. Rap Brown, who is
suspected of the slaying of Deputy Ricky Kinchen. (Warner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   RAYLEWIS _ ATLANTA _ Ray Lewis was a willing participant in the
fracas that left two men dead of stab wounds in Buckhead, according
to a key witness in the case. Jeff Gwen, also known as rapper Chino
Nino, has told police that he saw Lewis take off his chain to
prepare to fight and then engage in a fight with the victims. Gwen
is a key witness for the prosecution; he also will face tough going
under cross-examination. His rap lyrics speak of gang violence and
he's now in a halfway house for violating probation in an Ohio drug
conviction. (Rankin/Torpy, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-EDUCATION _ RESTON, Va. _ George W. Bush called illiteracy
among school children a ``national emergency'' Tuesday and he
proposed spending $5 billion over five years to address the
problem. (Heath, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-UNITER _ AUSTIN, Texas _ He is, he tells us constantly, a
``uniter, not a divider.'' But George W. Bush's self-proclaimed
big-tent credentials are under fire from the Log Cabin Republicans,
a gay group that says Bush's unwillingness to meet with them is
``no way to win converts, which Bush needs to do for the sake of
the GOP's chances of winning elections.'' (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   POL-LATENIGHT-JOKES _ David Letterman calls George W. Bush ``a
colossal boob.'' Jay Leno makes fun of the number of executions
under Bush's watch. And Bill Maher insists he hates both Al
``Bore'' and George W. ``Gush.'' Late-night political humor is
rampant this campaign season. It may have been funnier and more
exciting during the primaries, before Bush and Gore wrapped up
their respective party nominations, but it likely will get meaner
and nastier as we head toward the general election. (Holloway,
Austin American-Statesman) WITH ILLUSTRATION. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 6
p.m.
</P>
