<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0388 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HEANEY-BEOWULF-ART-2T     03-28 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEANEY-BEOWULF-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ANGLO-SAXON CHILLER (WITH AN IRISH TOUCH) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036 or 888
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By MEL GUSSOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the beginning of the new millennium, one of the surprise
successes of the publishing season is a 1,000-year-old masterpiece.
The book is ``Beowulf,'' Seamus Heaney's modern English translation
of the Anglo-Saxon epic, which was created sometime between the 7th
and the 10th centuries.
</P>
<P>
   The first great poem to be written in English, or rather, Old
English, ``Beowulf'' has been required reading in university
classics courses for decades: Beowulf, the legendary dragon slayer
and the model for countless heroic figures that followed him.
</P>
<P>
   The book is a best seller in Britain and the United States
(where it is published by Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux). On Sunday it
will be No. 13 on The New York Times Book Review list. There are
80,000 copies in print in the United States, an exceedingly high
number for a volume of poetry. A British list on which it ranks No.
5 describes it as ``much praised retelling of Anglo-Saxon
chiller.''
</P>
<P>
   To coincide with the publication of the Anglo-Saxon chiller,
Heaney, the Nobel Prize-winning poet, recorded the poem on tape (on
sale in Britain but not yet in the United States). The rolling
timbre of his mellifluous voice fills ``Beowulf'' with drama and
intensity and underscores the narrative elements of the text. This
is a story to be told.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, Heaney tested his memory and began
reciting the poem, warming to the words as he spoke them: ``So. The
Spear-Danes in days gone by/and the kings who ruled them had
courage and greatness.'' Characterizing the difference between the
Anglo-Saxon and the Heaney versions, he said: ``The original is
barbaric in a beautiful way. To encounter `Beowulf' is like taking
a sledgehammer to a quarry face. You must bang in there'' _ and
make one's own imprint.
</P>
<P>
   In the writing, as in Heaney's recitation, there is an Irish
tinge, and occasional words that are more Ulster than Anglo-Saxon,
but the translation is authentically of its period and genre. It
is, he said, about one-third Heaney, two-thirds ``duty to the
text,'' and is therefore a merging of the anonymous author and the
contemporary poet. To appeal to the scholars among readers, the
poem appears in both versions on facing pages of the book.
</P>
<P>
   Heaney began the adaptation in the mid-1980s at the suggestion
of the editors of ``The Norton Anthology of English Literature.''
After he translated 100 lines, he said, the project ``fell into
desuetude.'' A dozen years later, he set aside the time and took up
Beowulf's sword with greater enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   A breakthrough came with his discovery of the verb ``thole'' in
the text. Anglo-Saxon for suffering, it was a word that he had
heard in his childhood in Northern Ireland. That offered him a
bridge between cultures and centuries. Searching for an equivalent
oral tradition, he remembered his father's cousin Peter Scullion, a
man who had ``a large voice and a very stately method of speech.''
As Heaney said, ``That's how I got started on `Beowulf,' with those
voices from my country past.''
</P>
<P>
   The first problem was the first word, hwaet in Old English,
which had been translated as lo, hark, behold, attend and listen.
By choosing the more conversational ``so,'' Heaney called for
attention and plunged the reader into the middle of the story.
</P>
<P>
   While working on the translation, he was guided by Alfred David,
an Anglo-Saxon scholar who acted as a kind of ``minder,'' keeping
the adapter within the boundaries of the text. Still, Heaney
managed a few personal insertions, for example his use of the word
gumption. For him, gumption had an Anglo-Saxon forthrightness about
it.
</P>
<P>
   Why Beowulf now? ``Well,'' he said, ``because I did it.'' He
laughed and elaborated: ``My motive was a kind of dumb sense of
challenge, facing up to something that's absolute. In a way,
Anglo-Saxon poetry cannot be translated'' (although, as was pointed
out, there have been more than 60 English translations of
``Beowulf'').
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought of the lines as being big monkey wrenches welded
together,'' he said. ``Very strong, forceful things, and modern
English doesn't quite have the material to match it.'' At that
point, invention took over.
</P>
<P>
   As he worked on his version, he did not read it aloud. ``You
listen into yourself,'' he said. ``It's one of the curious
questions of composition of verse. You hear it in your own voice.''
As he wrote it, he could also ``hear the heft of it.''
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the story are Beowulf's three great battles,
against the monster Grendel, Grendel's mother and, 50 years later,
a dragon. Years ago, John Gardner's ``Grendel'' told the adventure
from the monster's point of view. While Heaney admired that novel
as a post-colonial reading of the poem, he said that he found the
dragon a more interesting character: ``The dragon lurks
underground, and he is awakened by accident. Psychologically, this
is the way trouble enters a life or a society. The dragon is
haunting, a condition in the imagining of the poet. Grendel is a
scene in a movie.'' To illustrate, he offered a brief mime of
Grendel gobbling up everything in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Heaney said that he agreed with J.R.R. Tolkien, who in an essay
on ``Beowulf'' assumed that the original author was an individual,
imaginative writer rather than a folkloric invention. Working on
the poem, he said, ``I've come to love the earned wisdom, the
homiletic aspect. There is an intonation of a grave but sturdy
human understanding.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Beowulf'' fits as a new chapter in the continuing saga of
Heaney. In his career, he has gone through cycles, which the critic
Helen Vendler has characterized as anonymities, archaeologies,
anthropologies and so on. He acknowledged the accuracy of Vendler's
categories: ``The first four books were looking into the ground,''
he explained. ``They were archaeological and self-exploratory.''
</P>
<P>
   The next few books were ``airier.'' Later he confronted
political questions in Ireland and then returned to more personal
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he wrote poetry, he quoted his friend Joseph Brodsky,
who said that he wrote poetry ``to get a buzz from the language.''
``The excitement of something coming out right, that is indeed its
own reward,'' Heaney said. ``As a young poet, you need
corroboration, and that's what publication does.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He began writing poems as a schoolboy, without a sense of risk:
``The first poems where I risked failing, where I was a-tremble
with the need that this would work, were written in November 1962
when I was 23.'' Those poems were inspired, he said, by ``the
voltage of reading'' Ted Hughes. Published in The Belfast
Telegraph, they in effect began his career.
</P>
<P>
   For all his subsequent productivity and acclaim, he hesitated
about claiming poetry as his profession. ``I came from a farming
background, and my career was teaching. My attitude was that you
had a job and poetry was a grace of sorts but not a profession.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything changed, of course, in 1995, when he was awarded the
Nobel Prize for literature, or as he calls it, ``the Stockholm
intervention.'' He explained his continuing reserve on the subject:
``You cannot possibly begin a sentence, `I have won,' which ends
with `Nobel Prize.' It's against all decorum.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that he began a poem with ``a memory energy around a
specific image,'' which might be verbal or visual. ``I tend to
revise as I go along,'' he added. ``There are poems I write quickly
of which I am totally grateful, and then there are poems I write
more slowly, which gradually attain inevitability. And then there
are ones that you're not quite sure of yourself.'' Naturally the
poems he likes best are those that derive from immediate
inspiration: ``Something breathes _ exhalation.''
</P>
<P>
   How does he know when a poem is finished? ``When it leaves you
alone and you leave it alone.''
</P>
<P>
   In speaking about the power of poetry, Heaney once said that
``no lyric has ever stopped a tank,'' but on the other hand the
impact can be unlimited: ``It is like the writing in the sand in
the face of which accusers and accused are left speechless and
renewed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I use the writing in the sand analogy,'' he said, ``because
poetry is totally fragile and creates a moment of concentration. If
you meet people to whom poetry means something, there's an
excitement and a conveyance of value. `Miles to go before I sleep'
is, in one sense, an obvious simple poem, but in another sense for
many people it houses understanding.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``I don't think art necessarily changes the world.
It changes, as Frost said, the plain of regard. It helps your
certitude as a creature, as a consciousness. If you steady yourself
in front of a work, whether it is painting or poetry, it has a
verifying effect.''
</P>
<P>
   He interrupted himself: ``God these are very tricky words.'' And
then went on: ``As a reader, my hero is Czeslaw Milosz. When I hear
that voice which is wise and full of wisdom-speak, I feel
steadied.''
</P>
<P>
   In writing and speaking about other writers, Heaney has only
occasionally referred to Samuel Beckett. Once he said that Beckett
was ``the most admirable writer we have known in our time,''
because he was ``purely the writer'' and ``purely himself.''
</P>
<P>
   To explain his distance from his countryman and fellow laureate,
he said: ``I didn't learn from Beckett in my own writing. I'm in a
different family or a different reservation.'' His artistic
predecessors are not Joyce or Beckett but the Irish poets Yeats and
Patrick Kavanagh _ ``from the rural Irish outback, the un-European
line.''
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, a Beckettian line in Heaney's ``Beowulf'':
``For every one of us, living in this world/means waiting for the
end.'' When that line was quoted to him, Heaney said that he does
not believe in an afterlife, but does believe ``in a phrase like
eternal life.'' ``Life is sacred,'' he said, ``and I would very
unwillingly relinquish'' that conviction.
</P>
<P>
   When it was suggested that he himself _ turning 61 on April 13 _
was having a good life, he said, with a smile, ``It's not that I
deny it.'' But he placed a finger in front of his lips as if to
keep that fact a secret. Of his life as a poet, he said he could
not have imagined it when he was a young man. ``It is a kind of
surprise,'' he said. ``Ongoing.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he admitted that each time he took up his pen, he felt a
``sense of the perilousness.'' ``I think every poet thinks he's
written his last poem. Yeats used the phrase, the will doing the
work of the imagination. That's a marvelous statement. It's the
fear at the back of a poet's mind, that you're going on because of
habit, not because of necessity.''
</P>
<P>
   And, as Beckett said, ``habit is the great deadener.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' he agreed, and then sounded an optimistic note: ``But
it's also a great keeper of things. It's got a virtue. One
definition of meter would be the habit of doing it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
