   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   BKC-WISCONSIN _ When Dick Bennett became head coach at Wisconsin
five years ago, his new players were presented with a theme _ start
the dream. Saturday, the Badgers will actually reach out and touch
the dream as they meet Michigan State in the Final Four in
Indianapolis. They've won with a style that's not flashy or
popular, but it has been successful enough to lead them to their
first Final Four in 59 years. (Barnhart, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GLF-MARTIN _ ATLANTA _ For three years, Casey Martin has tried
to understand why the PGA is against him playing on tour. Martin,
bothered by a disease that affects his ability to walk, has a legal
right to ride in carts while playing on the PGA Tour, and that's
what he'll be doing this week at the BellSouth Classic. But the
latest decision from the PGA _ to take the case to the Supreme
Court _ has angered Martin. ``It has become personal,'' he says.
(Sheeley, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ENRON-FIELD _ HOUSTON _ Tal Smith was the biggest 7-year-old
fan of the Boston Red Sox at Fenway Park that summer afternoon in
1940. As much as he was taken by the grace of Ted Williams, Smith
was just as overwhelmed by the giant outfield fence known as the
Green Monster and the meandering quirks and cozy charm of the
stadium where he could almost reach out and touch Dom DiMaggio or
Bobby Doerr. Now as president of the Houston Astros, Smith brought
his love of ballpark nuances and idiosyncrasies to the design of
the new Enron Field, a $250 million palace in downtown Houston.
(Bohls, Austin American-Statesman) WITH PHOTOS. MOVED.
</P>
