<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0395 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SUN-FILM-REVIEW-ART-N     03-28 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUN-FILM-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JOURNEY TO THE SUN': THE MORAL EDUCATION OF AN INNOCENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to New York Times photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(Eds: Production notes appear at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By ELVIS MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The haunting ``Journey to the Sun'' teems with life.
Set in Istanbul, it tells the story of Mehmet (Newroz Baz), a young
man with one of the more interesting occupations you'll see in
modern movies. His job is to find leaks in the water pipes below
his city, and he uses a long brass rod he places on the pavement,
listening through it to catch the rumbles. He even employs the rod
to impress his girlfriend, Arzu (Mizgin Kapazan), using it to tell
how far the approaching train is from their stop. The rod becomes a
rather awkward metaphor in ``Journey,'' as Mehmet discovers an
entire world his senses didn't detect: he can hear turmoil under
the streets but not on them.
</P>
<P>
   The writer and director, Yesim Ustaoglu, quickly does away with
the device. It's an arresting image, though, Mehmet and his rod:
the filmmaker uses it evocatively, and it's missed when it's gone.
</P>
<P>
   Mehmet becomes friendly with Berzan (Nazmi Qirix), who sells
music from his street cart. Berzan is a Kurd, and his father was
beaten and kidnapped. Because of his dark skin, Mehmet, too, knows
what it is like to be picked on. Berzan is part of the Kurdish
rebel underground in Turkey, and his friendship with Mehmet
provides an unexpected education for him. He learns of persecution
firsthand.
</P>
<P>
   After a search of the bus he is riding, Mehmet is pulled off and
viciously interrogated. A man fled the bus, leaving a gun in a
knapsack behind, and the authorities assume that it is Mehmet's. By
the time they are done with him his face is a patchwork of wounds,
and the image of him emerging from a tunnel, dragging his rod
behind him, is unforgettable.
</P>
<P>
   Ustaoglu has a knack for details. When Mehmet sees a woman on
the streets wearing stockings with exposed seams and admires them,
Arzu has a co-worker draw seams on her legs. Arzu grew up in
Germany, and when she gets to know him better, tells him, ``Ich
liebe dich.'' Ustaoglu's accumulation of emotional detail quietly
pays off, and ``Journey to the Sun'' vibrates with knowing.
</P>
<P>
   The shadow of Graham Greene looms over the film as it tracks the
moral education of an innocent. After Mehmet loses his job, his
roommates turn him out into the streets. Only Arzu sticks by him.
</P>
<P>
   He is determined to find out more about Berzan's struggle. ``My
nanny used to say, if you have a nightmare, turn over,'' Berzan
says. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A puzzled Mehmet responds, ``How can you turn over when you're
asleep?''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Journey to the Sun'' is an incisive drama about a waking
nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `JOURNEY TO THE SUN'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Yesim Ustaoglu; in Turkish, with English
subtitles; director of photography, Jacek Petrycki; edited by
Nicolas Gaster; music by Vlatko Stefanovski; art director, Natali
Yeres; produced by Behrooz Hashemian.
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 104 minutes. This film is not rated. Shown
Wednesday night at 6 and Thursday night at 9 at the Museum of
Modern Art in Manhattan, as part of the 29th New Directors/New
Films series of the Film Society of Lincoln Center and Department
of Film of the Museum of Modern Art. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With: Newroz Baz (Mehmet Kara), Nazmi Qirix (Berzan) and Mizgin
Kapazan (Arzu).  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
