<DOCNO> NYT20000328.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0397 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-POPLIFE-NYT     03-28 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPLIFE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE POP LIFE: A BRAIN COMES FULL CIRCLE; STOMPING ON SUMMER
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Maynard James Keenan's Hollywood loft is a shrine
to identity confusion. Red curtains, dozens of sticks of incense
and statues of Eastern deities lend an aura of spiritual searching
to his front room; at the same time, barbells and weights place him
firmly in the cult of body worship. Then there are the soundproof
walls and studio equipment of a rocker and artist, and finally a
sense of clutter and an aversion to deep cleaning that give the
room the look of a bohemian bachelor pad.
</P>
<P>
   Keenan is a former Army enlistee and art student best known as
the reclusive, emotionally riveting singer for the heavy-rock band
Tool. But on a recent afternoon he was in the clothing of the new
group A Perfect Circle, of which he is also the singer. As further
testament to his identity confusion, Tool was rehearsing for a new
album in the back room of his loft while he was in the front,
sitting with Billy Howerdel and giving an interview about A Perfect
Circle, which is set to release its first record, on Virgin, on May
23.
</P>
<P>
   A Perfect Circle began as instrumental compositions by Howerdel,
a New Jersey native who met Keenan while working as a guitar
technician for the hyperkinetic ska-rock band Fishbone. Howerdel
went on to work as a guitar tech with Tool, the Smashing Pumpkins
and Nine Inch Nails, and more recently worked as a computer
engineer on Guns 'n' Roses' painfully gestating next album.
</P>
<P>
   All along he had been making connections and plotting his entry
into the creative side of the music world. Two years ago he began
writing the music that would become A Perfect Circle. At first he
composed half-hour-plus songs that he imagined as soundtracks for
visually rich movies like ``City of Lost Children.'' Then he
shortened his pieces and imagined them as tighter pop pieces sung
by a woman. Finally Keenan entered the picture, writing lyrics to
the songs and rushing Howerdel into a recording contract faster
than he ever thought possible.
</P>
<P>
   Some Tool fans may not be happy with A Perfect Circle, not
because the music isn't as heavy and monochromatic as Tool's, but
because there hasn't been a new Tool album since ``Aenima'' in
1996. With A Perfect Circle scheduled to tour as an opening act for
Nine Inch Nails this spring, it would seem as though the Tool album
would be delayed even further.
</P>
<P>
   Keenan, however, said that he did not believe A Perfect Circle
would interfere with his more popular band. Though the others in
Tool are said to have been upset with him for signing to a new
major label contract without them, Keenan denied this. ``There's a
range of emotions they've gone through,'' he said. ``Most people's
base reaction would be anger or jealously. But they're very
rational people, so they came back to accepting that this was
cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason for the long wait for a new Tool record was a
drawn-out legal battle between the band and its record label, with
each suing the other. Tool claimed that its contract was no longer
valid; the label, Volcano (which took over Tool's contract after
the breakup of its former label, Zoo Entertainment) claimed that
Tool owed it seven more albums and $25 million in damages. Last
year, however, the lawsuits were dropped when Tool renegotiated its
relationship and contract with Volcano.
</P>
<P>
   But a strong animosity toward the music business lingers in
Keenan's mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if an artist only sells one record, the profits
should be split at the very least,'' Keenan said. ``This has gone
on long enough, this system of having to pay for everything
yourself and then getting only one-tenth of the money made on your
art.''
</P>
<P>
   Comparing Tool and A Perfect Circle, Keenan said: ``The music
was very different, so I responded differently. The process that we
go through in recording with Tool is very organic, but at the same
time it is very thought out. There is a very left-brain process of
dissecting what we're doing and drawing from source material; it's
very research oriented and esoteric.
</P>
<P>
   ``With A Perfect Circle the process is far more mechanical and
computer oriented, but at the same time it is also far more
emotional and intuitive. Tool is more a left-brain masculine
result, and this is more a right-brain feminine result.''
</P>
<P>
   The music on A Perfect Circle's debut album ranges from
straight-forward big-riff rock to heavy, droning soundscapes to
clean, simple pop to hard, heavy emoting. Howerdel said he was
happy with the results. ``I didn't even know that a human could put
lyrics to some of these songs,'' he marveled.
</P>
<P>
   Stomping on Summer
</P>
<P>
   'N Sync albums may be flying out of stores faster than Harry
Potter's Nimbus 2000 broomstick, but this summer the good boys may
be taking a back seat to the bad boys. The summer season is shaping
up to be the revenge of hard, loud, ugly rock 'n' roll. At least
four hard-rock tours are to stomp through amphitheaters, arenas,
stadiums and fairgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   Ozzfest has announced its lineup, which includes the tour's
namesake, Ozzy Osbourne, along with Pantera, Godsmack, Incubus,
Monster Magnet, P.O.D., Static-X, Tap Root, Crazy Town, and Kittie.
Tickets for the July 24 show at the PNC Bank Arts Center in
Holmdel, N.J., will be on sale on April 8.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the Warped Tour, which includes less heavy, more
punk bands, including Green Day, NOFX, Long Beach Dub All-Stars,
Mighty Mighty Bosstones and the Suicide Machines, and the rappers
Jurassic 4. The tour comes to Randalls Island on July 15.
</P>
<P>
   In addition a music-booking company called the Agency Group,
which represents Slipknot, Coal Chamber and Sevendust, is trying to
jump on the new hard-rock bandwagon with its own tour, called
Tattoo the Earth. Finally Korn's Family Values Tour, gearing up to
run in late summer and early fall, has been busy looking for its
own headliner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
