<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBI-INTERNET-CRIME-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FBI DIRECTOR ASKS FOR TOUGHER INTERNET CRIME LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     (EDS: Filed in ``w'' and ``f'' categories.)  
 &HT;     By AUSTIN ZALKIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ FBI Director Louis Freeh urged Congress Tuesday to
ease restraints on law enforcement officials so they can more
aggressively pursue Internet criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh praised pending legislation co-sponsored by Sens. Charles
Schumer, D-N.Y., and Jon Kyl, R-Ariz. that would make it easier for
investigators to trace e-mails and other Internet communications.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI director told the Senate subcommittee on technology,
terrorism and government information that present law requires
investigators to obtain multiple court orders so they can trace a
single communication across judicial districts.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would require only a single judge's ruling for law
enforcement officials to trace Internet crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not asking for extraordinary powers,'' Freeh told the
panel. ``We are not asking for any more authorities than are
currently contemplated under the Constitution and the Bill of
Rights.''
</P>
<P>
   The Schumer-Kyl bill would:
</P>
<P>
   _ eliminate the requirement for federal prosecution that an
Internet crime inflict a minimum of $5,000 damage;
</P>
<P>
   _ allow federal prosecutors to go after juvenile offenders as
young as 15 in Internet crime cases. Present law bars prosecutions
of defendants under 18 years of age in such cases.
</P>
<P>
   _ remove the existing six-month minimum sentence for convicted
offenders, which Kyl said keeps lesser offenders from being tried
at all.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh told the panel that Internet crimes should also carry
tougher penalties. The damage caused by Internet criminals
outweighs the length of jail terms currently handed down in such
cases, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh said the FBI needs a bigger budget to go after these new
Internet criminals, explaining that the bureau's computer intrusion
caseload had doubled since 1998.
</P>
<P>
   He said the FBI handled almost 500 cases of cyber child
pornography last year, including instances where adults arranged
via the Internet to travel across state lines to have sex with
minors. This type of crime is `a completely new phenomenon,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., a member of the panel, noted
that even the FBI's web site was brought down by hackers last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh said Congress must make it possible for private companies
victimized by cyber crime to come forward and prosecute offenders
without fear of disclosing their own trade secrets. He said he
would support a measure to close judicial proceedings to the public
in some cases to protect a business' confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   Internationally, Freeh said that the FBI coordinates its
anti-terrorism efforts with many nations, including `almost a
seamless'' relationship with Canada.
</P>
<P>
   He reported that FBI agents and computer examiners had worked
with other nations to get `direct access to computers, hard drives,
which in some cases were the actual plans of terrorists to murder
Americans, large numbers of Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Austin Zalkin can be reached at 202-298-6920).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
