<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
Tnyt timeshold the NYTimes News Service for Wednesday, March 29. If
you have any questions, nyt bcv ubxtic-z  
RESCUE (Undated) - When a freak snow storm blew in, two parties of
hikers on the Arizona-Utah border found themselves trapped by
waist-deep drifts and frigid temperatures. Two were soaking wet.
One was injured. It took the compassion of strangers and rescue
groups coordinated by two states and Navajo reservation officers to
bring them all out safely. By BARBARA YOST. Story will move in the
``A'' category. 
 
SLEEPY (Phoenix) - A new study by the National Sleep Foundation
shows Americans are flat out exhausted. How does sleepiness affect
productivity, especially among 18- to 29-year-olds. And how does it
contribute to dangerous driving behavior? By JANIE MAGRUDER. Story
will move in the `A` category. 
 
CENSUS (Phoenix) - About 44 percent of Arizonans have returned
their census forms so far, slightly more than the national average
but behind most other Western states. Among Valley cities, El
Mirage and Surprise have already met their target rate, Gilbert and
Peoria are over half and Phoenix is right at 44 percent. Why are
fast-growing Western states doing so well? By SHAUN MCKINNON. Story
will move in the `A` category. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-00 1815EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000328.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0408 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ART-ENTREPRENEUR-NYT &LR;      03-28 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-ENTREPRENEUR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WENDELL CASTLE TRANSFORMS ART INTO ENTERPRISE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL WELLMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   While many chief executives have nailed down the art of the
deal, not many know the deal on art.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Wendell Castle, artist in residence at the Rochester
Institute of Technology and one of America's foremost furniture
makers. His one-of-a-kind art pieces grace corporate collections
all over the country and are in cultural emporiums like the
Metropolitan Museum of Art, the Smithsonian Institution and the Art
Institute of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   If you have to ask the price, well, you can't afford it. His
pieces start around $20,000 and then begin to become expensive.
</P>
<P>
   So why has Castle decided to disrupt a successful art career at
the age of 67 and become an entrepreneur? Last year, he started a
business called Icon Design that will market a ``budget'' line of
his works _ the Wendell Castle Collection, as it is called _ for
prices ranging from $1,000 to around $15,000. Icon will also look
into producing pieces designed by other furniture makers.
</P>
<P>
   Part of his motivation for going downscale was to make more
money, Castle said. ``There are only two ways I can think of if you
want to have a better income out of it: you can either make more or
charge more,'' he said. ``I sort of tried the making more back in
the early '80s and really didn't like it. There was always somebody
saying, `What am I going to do next?' It distracted me so much that
I couldn't really concentrate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Charging more is a great option,'' he added. ``But you can't
just do that instantly. You kind of have to tweak the prices up.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I wanted to do more than that. I had all these ideas for
things that I probably was never going to do because they really
weren't far out enough to justify making one.''
</P>
<P>
   Every year, hundreds of thousands of Americans start their own
businesses, from gift-basket ventures to Web retailers. No matter
how high- or low-technology their products are, most of these
entrepreneurs share two distinct traits, the experts say: A desire
to run their own show and a knack for seizing opportunities nobody
else sees. Castle filled the bill on both counts.
</P>
<P>
   His brainstorm came when he starting running numbers through his
head. The effort of making more than just one would pay off
financially if he made 20 copies, or 50, he figured. But then, he
said, ``I thought, if you have something really nice why do you
want to stop at 20 or 50, especially if somebody else is making
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he was talking mass production _ on a limited scale _ and
that takes more than a studio, even if the studio is as large and
rambling as Castle's in Scottsville, near Rochester. The Wendell
Castle Collection is already being made on a small scale in the
studio, but is about to be transferred to Icon's new
37,000-square-foot plant in nearby Le Roy.
</P>
<P>
   Castle designs the pieces _ sold at Holly Hunt in New York and
other locations _ for the new line and builds prototypes, but after
that the work is turned over to his crew. He expects to add designs
every year and to retire pieces that don't sell. After all, as he
put it in Rule No. 10 of a 1996 poster, ``My 10 adopted rules of
thumb,'' that graces his Web site (www.wendellcastle .com): ``If
you hit the bull's-eye every time, the target is too near.''
</P>
<P>
   The new plant was bought last fall and is expected to be in full
operation this spring. It will eventually have about 50 workers and
will be laid out with production efficiency in mind _ unlike the
Scottsville studio with its Escher-like stairs that seem to lead
down to higher levels when they are not taking you up to lower
ones.
</P>
<P>
   Going to all of this trouble to open a plant also points out
another reason to produce in quantity, although Castle said it was
not the most important one: ``An artist really never has a business
that you can sell. Other businesses have value. You build a
business up, and you can sell it to somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   But back to the president and chief executive formerly known as
the artist.
</P>
<P>
   Icon is about a $2 million project, Castle said. He said he had
sold 30 percent of the company to raise $1 million and then had
received low-interest loans and grants to cover the rest. He
estimates revenue of $1.2 million for this year, and expects the
company to become profitable in 2001. Most of that business, he
says, will be with people who use architects or interior designers.
To his delight, people who already own his art pieces are also
buying his new line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another way of doing this is to not sell any of it and start
much slower,'' he added. ``I didn't have a million dollars lying
around, but I could come up with a couple hundred thousand and
start much smaller and grow.''
</P>
<P>
   But when you're in your 60s, he added, ``the idea of slow isn't
so appealing.''
</P>
<P>
   All of this has created new challenges. Castle has always been
skillful at marketing his artwork, but the intricacies of marketing
an entire company are of a different magnitude. He is involved with
bringing in a public relations team and a marketing team _ another
associate, Hunter Kariher, the operations officer, will run the
plant day to day. ``Everything I've ever done in my whole life, I
think I probably jumped in naively,'' he said. ``I didn't realize
how much we have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of this he is still carrying on at RIT, where he
has no teaching schedule but does give seminars, ``where we talk
about current issues, design problems, problems of starting a
business _ some of the practical things that go along with
furniture making in addition to aesthetics.''
</P>
<P>
   Is something lost when an artist takes on the role of
full-fledged entrepreneur?
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to think that it's possible to wear two hats,'' Castle
said, ``though it is pretty hard to wear them at the same time. You
have to take one off to put the other one on. And the transition is
not instant. It takes a little adjustment period. Right now I'm in
the production mode, and after this spring we're introducing about
12 new things so some pressure will be off. And at that point I
really can get back to some art work.
</P>
<P>
   ``If economics didn't enter the picture,'' he added, ``the art
work would be the clear choice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
