RESCUE (Undated) - When a freak snow storm blew in, two parties of
hikers on the Arizona-Utah border found themselves trapped by
waist-deep drifts and frigid temperatures. Two were soaking wet.
One was injured. It took the compassion of strangers and rescue
groups coordinated by two states and Navajo reservation officers to
bring them all out safely. By BARBARA YOST. Story will move in the
``A'' category. 
 
SLEEPY (Phoenix) - A new study by the National Sleep Foundation
shows Americans are flat out exhausted. How does sleepiness affect
productivity, especially among 18- to 29-year-olds. And how does it
contribute to dangerous driving behavior? By JANIE MAGRUDER. Story
will move in the `A` category. 
 
CENSUS (Phoenix) - About 44 percent of Arizonans have returned
their census forms so far, slightly more than the national average
but behind most other Western states. Among Valley cities, El
Mirage and Surprise have already met their target rate, Gilbert and
Peoria are over half and Phoenix is right at 44 percent. Why are
fast-growing Western states doing so well? By SHAUN MCKINNON. Story
will move in the `A` category. 
 
