<SLUG> BC-MUSEUM-HOUSTON-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON MUSEUM HAS HIGH HOPES FOR ITS NEWLY OPENED AUDREY JONES
BECK ANNEX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDREW MARTON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ It was a public-relations gift from the gods. Under an
ominous sky, a press procession left the safe confines of the
Caroline Wiess Law Building of The Museum of Fine Arts, Houston, to
tour its newly opened sibling, the Audrey Jones Beck Building. It
was a nervous parting from the confident grace of the main museum's
Mies van der Rohe glass-and-steel design, heading toward uncharted
territory.
</P>
<P>
   But just as the nagging doubts began to settle in, the sun
knifed through the clouds, casting an Emerald City iridescence over
the new Beck building. Suddenly, all that was uncertain about the
new building became inviting, its granite blocks taking on a
marbleized gloss, its burnished bronze accents assuming the shade
of Godiva chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   Being diplomatic, one might term the exterior of the Beck
building, which officially opened Saturday, as admirably
restrained. A harsher critique would deem it just this side of
utilitarian. To be sure, it takes its puritanically elegant cues
from Joseph Havel's 9 1/2-foot bronze curtains, which unassumingly
frame the front entrance.
</P>
<P>
   But the museum's astringent touches amount to an architectural
red herring. The unadorned Beck exterior camouflages an interior of
boldly vertiginous and intimate proportions. Indeed, to say that
the $85 million Beck building is a mere addendum to the
well-established Museum of Fine Arts is akin to calling Paris'
Georges Pompidou Center a design trifle. It is abundantly clear
that Houston's art hierarchy intends for its newly charged museum
to be a national must-see destination, sheltering an exhaustive
collection.
</P>
<P>
   The Beck addition, culminating a 15-year expansion project, has
helped vault Houston's Museum of Fine Arts from the nation's 30th-
to its sixth-largest museum in floor space. When one adds the
exhibition space of the museum's Wiess Law building to the newly
opened Beck, one arrives at a head-turning total of 158,150 square
feet. That number alone, combined with the more than 40,000 works
that make up the museum's permanent collection, pushes the Museum
of Fine Arts from back burner to contender status overnight. And
because the Museum of Fine Arts already lures a reported 1 million
visitors annually, one of the largest draws in the Southwest, its
new addition spurs some museum officials to boast about it becoming
the country's ``mini-Met'' _ as in New York's Metropolitan Museum
of Art.
</P>
<P>
   That's setting the bar pretty high, but it might not be so flip
a goal considering the Beck building's prodigious second floor.
That level is a maze of 28 galleries that takes patrons from Roman
and Greek vases and artifacts to Picasso via the Renaissance and
Baroque periods. Just a brief sampling of the exhibits
commemorating the Beck building's official opening, from ``Faces of
Impressionism: Portraits From American Collections'' to ``A Closer
Look: English Silver, 1670-1760,'' speaks volumes about the
museum's versatility.
</P>
<P>
   The building's architect, Spain's Rafael Moneo, renders an
intimate, discreet introduction to the museum by lowering the
ceiling just inside the main doors.
</P>
<P>
   But within a matter of feet, Moneo sends the ceiling rocketing
up to an atrium that bombards a Roman marble sarcophagus relief
below with columns of natural light. The main lobby's escalator, a
potential eyesore, is invisible, thanks to its sheathing in a mocha
skin of bronze.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast to the blaring list of the museum's benefactors on
the main atrium wall, Moneo's tasteful overall design never needs a
bullhorn to broadcast its intentions. ``So many museums insist on
being so much about architectural statements that they kill the
art,'' says Barry Walker, curator of prints and drawings at the
Museum of Fine Arts.
</P>
<P>
   From the canny choice of materials (creamy Portuguese limestone,
Dakota mahogany granite, and tongue-in-groove oak floors) to the
classical sense of proportion, Moneo successfully skirts that line
between grand and grandstanding. His deft choreography of
partitions and temporary walls creates intimate galleries within
meandering spaces. And many of Moneo's gallery entryways are lined
in gold-tinted bronze, calling to mind frames for the galleries
themselves. ``It seemed to me that bronze doorjambs make a
connection with the golden frames around so many of the Old Masters
collection,'' says Moneo.
</P>
<P>
   But the Beck building's principal leitmotif is light itself.
One's eyes are ineluctably drawn to its wide assortment of
skylights. Each serves as a gallery prism, refracting natural light
to let it fall gently on a work of art without assaulting the
viewer with glare.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-00 1828EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
