<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR  
   
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
Tnyt timeshold the NYTimes News Service for Wednesday, March 29. If
you have any questions, nyt bcv ubxtic-z  
RESCUE (Undated) - When a freak snow storm blew in, two parties of
hikers on the Arizona-Utah border found themselves trapped by
waist-deep drifts and frigid temperatures. Two were soaking wet.
One was injured. It took the compassion of strangers and rescue
groups coordinated by two states and Navajo reservation officers to
bring them all out safely. By BARBARA YOST. Story will move in the
``A'' category. 
 
SLEEPY (Phoenix) - A new study by the National Sleep Foundation
shows Americans are flat out exhausted. How does sleepiness affect
productivity, especially among 18- to 29-year-olds. And how does it
contribute to dangerous driving behavior? By JANIE MAGRUDER. Story
will move in the `A` category. 
 
CENSUS (Phoenix) - About 44 percent of Arizonans have returned
their census forms so far, slightly more than the national average
but behind most other Western states. Among Valley cities, El
Mirage and Surprise have already met their target rate, Gilbert and
Peoria are over half and Phoenix is right at 44 percent. Why are
fast-growing Western states doing so well? By SHAUN MCKINNON. Story
will move in the `A` category. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-00 1828EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000328.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0416 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-MUSEUM-HOUSTON-2ndTak     03-28 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSEUM-HOUSTON-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: with glare. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One skylight, hanging 79 feet above a courtyard, dissects the
sun's rays so that they caress Paul Manship's monumental bronze
work ``Hercules Upholding the Heavens.'' ``Light is a much-changing
entity here,'' says Moneo on the roof of the museum, shaking his
head as if Houston's fickle light were a stalwart challenge.
</P>
<P>
   But Moneo's skylights are not just some ego-sating bit of
trickery. They show his willingness to tamp down his architectural
prowess in favor of creating the natural illumination that would
have surrounded each painting in its time. Moneo also understands
that unfiltered natural sunlight risks being a blunt instrument,
obscuring more than enhancing. ``In fact, what we decided on
finally was to take a combination of the cooler artificial light
and warmer incandescence of natural light for certain works,'' says
Mary Morton, the museum's assistant curator of European art.
</P>
<P>
   THE MUSEUM'S AMBITIONS are certainly bold when it comes to the
panorama of art it contains. The building's 10 galleries and
sculpture niches on its first floor boast a broad collection of
19th- and early 20th-century American art, tapping into the
museum's permanent collection of 5,000 prints and 650 drawings in
that genre. ``Bayou Bend,'' the special wing of the Museum of Fine
Arts devoted to an excerpt from the museum's decorative arts
collection housed in a nearby mansion, is a low-ceilinged, cozy den
of furniture and ceramics accented by such late 18th- and early
19th-century American painting classics as Thomas Cole's ``Indian
Pass.''
</P>
<P>
   Down an echo-chamberlike side-lit corridor, meant to evoke a
cavernous mansion setting, is a stunning collection of works by
Frederic Remington, including ``Fight for the Water Hole.''
``Somehow, this setting seems to reveal even more clearly that
Remington's brush-stroke technique was heavily influenced by the
French impressionists,'' says Wynne Phelan, the Museum of Fine
Arts' conservation director.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere on the first floor, the galleries follow a logical
American chronology, departing Remington for the luscious society
portraits of John Singer Sargent, including ``Mrs. Joshua
Montgomery Sears.''
</P>
<P>
   The Beck's lighting scheme is so in sync with the art's
requirements that it can extract both the brooding solitude of
William Merritt Chase's ``Mother and Child (The First Portrait)''
and the bronze gleam from ``Diana,'' by Frederick William
MacMonnies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such is the way that everything is lit now _ and keep in mind
I've worked here for 14 years _ that I often come upon something
and say, `My God, I didn't really know we had this,' '' says Janet
Landay, exhibitions curator at the museum.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, it is in the kickoff point for the Beck's
28-gallery second floor _ the museum level that most aspires to
``mini-Met'' heights _ that one discovers several weak spots.
Though housing some choice examples of Hellenic art such as a Greek
myrtle wreath dating from 330-250 B.C., its overall cache of
Mediterranean-based art is noticeably thin. And the meandering
warren of galleries that follows can occasionally lose its thematic
or chronological flow, careening a hundred years off in a confusing
tangent.
</P>
<P>
   The Beck does recover its footing in the area devoted to the
second half of the 14th century, with a collection of
ecclesiastical subjects executed by Florentine, Sienese and Spanish
artists. The intersection of Moneo's luminous touch and great art
occurs with Sandro Botticelli's ``The Adoration of the Christ
Child.'' James Clifton, the museum's curator of Renaissance and
Baroque painting, marvels at how well the Botticelli ``benefits
from all of Moneo's natural light, bringing out all the colors,
helping accentuate the work as a real art object, not some
artificially lit reproduction.''
</P>
<P>
   Camille Corot to create ``Orpheus Leading Eurydice From the
Underworld.'' ``Be it music or descriptions by the artist himself,
all of it makes the art come even more alive,'' says Beth
Schneider, the museum's education director.]
</P>
<P>
   THOUGH IT'S TOO EARLY to appraise the overall impact of the Beck
building's arrival on the museum landscape, some signs already hint
at its impact. It is no mean feat that the Beck commemorated its
opening by adding three masterworks to its collection: a Greek
sculpture heralding the Golden Age of Athens, a Francesco Solimena
painting and a Picasso print.
</P>
<P>
   On a more subtle level is the new museum's sublime harmony of
internal design and its highly accomplished art. Surrounding
Edouard Vuillard's ``The Promenade,'' Henri Rousseau's ``The Eiffel
Tower'' or Georges Braque's ``Fishing Boats,'' the gallery's wall
colors, pale rose, taupe or blended yellow-ocher, seem to magnetize
the tints of the works almost literally out of their frames.
</P>
<P>
   This moment of synthesis between artwork and gallery only
confirms that the Beck is ambitious indeed. By actually teasing the
individual shades from a static canvas, the new design has elevated
the visceral experience of viewing the art. Any museum, new or old,
should aspire to nothing less.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   INFO BOX:
</P>
<P>
   The Museum of Fine Arts, Houston, Audrey Jones Beck Building
</P>
<P>
   Address: 5601 Main St.
</P>
<P>
   Hours: 10 a.m.- 7 p.m. Tuesday, Wednesday and Saturday; 10 a.m.
- 9 p.m. Thursday and Friday; 12:15-7 p.m. Sunday. Closed Mondays.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (713) 639-7300
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
