<DOCNO> NYT20000328.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0417 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-REFORM-PARTY-DEBATES-     03-28 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFORM-PARTY-DEBATES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     REFORM PARTY SEEKS SUPPORT FOR ROLE IN TV DEBATES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Reform Party opened a campaign Tuesday to rally
enough public support to enable expected nominee Pat Buchanan to
qualify for the nationally televised campaign debates this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman Pat Choate, the party's 1996 vice presidential
candidate, said the step-by-step effort over the next six months is
designed to generate a 15 percent showing in nationwide polls for
the Reform party nominee by September.
</P>
<P>
   The private Presidential Debate Commission requires participants
in the influential debates to have earned the support of at least
15 percent of the voters in nationwide polls to win a seat at the
debates.
</P>
<P>
   Latest polls show Buchanan facing an uphill challenge to meet
the 15 percent minimum. A CBS News survey released Monday showed
Buchanan drawing just 4 percent of the vote, compared to Bush with
46 percent and Gore with 41 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Even among independent voters, Buchanan was trailing, with 5
percent of the vote compared to 45 percent for Bush and 35 percent
for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Choate said that a federal court decision ending a divisive
struggle over control of the Reform Party has freed to party to
fully plunge into the coming election campaign ``in an aggressive
way and build a very competitive challenge'' to the Republican and
Democratic parties.
</P>
<P>
   Choate outlined an ambitious effort by the Reform party
designed, in part, to generate public support for the nominee to
take part in the debates.
</P>
<P>
   Choate:
</P>
<P>
   _ Challenged Gore and Bush to agree to admit the Reform party
nominee to the fall debates.
</P>
<P>
   _ Demanded that the two rivals drop claims of being reformers
because it sows ``confusion.'' Choate insisted that Gore and Bush
cannot claim the mantle of reform unless they match Buchanan's
rejection of campaign donations from political action committees
and the unlimited, unregulated soft money given political parties
by corporations, unions, special interests and wealthy individuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walk the walk if you're going to talk the talk on reform,''
Choate told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   _ Announced plans to establish a national party headquarters in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   _ Vowed to raise $1 million by August to augment the $2.5
million in federal funds for the party convention and $12.6 million
for the fall campaign.
</P>
<P>
   _ Promised three grassroots conferences via the Internet on such
hot button issues as political reform, trade policy and China.
</P>
<P>
   _ Announced nine committees to flesh out the Reform party's
infrastructure in time for its three-day national convention in
Long Beach, Calif., beginning on Aug. 12 _ just two days before the
Democratic convention in nearby Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Choate emphasized the importance of the Reform nominee
participating in the debates, noting that the success of party
founder H. Ross Perot's challenge to the two-party system was
directly affected by his participation in the debates.
</P>
<P>
   Perot, the Texas billionaire who won a seat at the campaign
debates in 1992, captured 19 percent of the popular vote _ the
strongest showing for a third party or independent candidate since
former President Theodore Roosevelt won 27 percent of the vote in
1912.
</P>
<P>
   But after Perot lost a court challenge in 1996 to get into the
presidential debates, he captured barely 9 percent of the popular
vote in his second bid for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan has already filed a complaint with the Federal Election
Commission on March 20 asking the bipartisan panel to overturn the
15 percent rule established by the Commission on Presidential
Debates.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan contends that the debate commission is violating a law
enacted by Congress in 1974 that awards benefits such as federal
matching funds and federal campaign subsidies to any party that
wins national party status by securing 5 percent or more of the
popular vote in a presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   By virtue of its success as a ``minor party'' in 1996, the
Reform party nominee qualifies for $2.5 million in federal funds to
finance the party convention and $12.6 million to finance the fall
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Gore, as representatives of a ``major party,'' qualify
for $13.5 million in convention funding and $67.6 million for the
fall campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The FEC has 90 days to respond to Buchanan's complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Choate vowed federal court action by the Reform party if the FEC
fails to adopt the Reform party's position.
</P>
<P>
   The legal follow-up coupled with steps outlined on Tuesday
should enable the Reform party to generate widespread public
support for its candidate to take part in the debates, Choate said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you're going to see over the next several months is this
party is going take a real lead in discussing the issues,'' Choate
said. ``We'll then go into a national convention and we will be
unified in that convention. We should come out of that convention,
I would say, in striking distances of that 15 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Choate said that the Reform party is on the November ballot in
22 states so far, with plans to get on the ballots in all 50
states.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, a conservative commentator who unsuccessfully sought
the GOP presidential nomination in 1992 and 1996, left the GOP last
October to join the Reform party.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge ended weeks of party infighting on Monday,
ruling that Choate and his faction of the party allied with Perot
had legally ousted Jack Gargan, an ally of Minnesota Gov. Jesse
Ventura, at a party meeting in Nashville, Tenn., in February.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewart(at)hearstdc.com )
</P>
