<DOCNO> NYT20000328.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0421 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-MICROSOFT-LAWSUIT-HNS     03-28 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-LAWSUIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     JUDGE DELAYS RULING IN MICROSOFT CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal judge on Tuesday delayed delivering his
ruling in the antitrust case against software giant Microsoft Corp.
to give the company and Justice Department officials time to reach
a settlement, according to government sources.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Court Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson said last week
that he would be willing to postpone his decision _ which had been
expected Tuesday _ if he saw progress toward an out-of-court deal.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said Jackson will delay his ruling until April 7 to give
both sides a chance to reach an agreement _ something the judge has
publicly stated he wants.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, U.S. officials rejected a Microsoft proposal,
saying it didn't meet enough of the government's demands. But the
two sides have continued to negotiate through Judge Richard Posner,
chief judge of the U.S. 7th Circuit Court of Appeals in Chicago,
who has been mediating the case since last November when Jackson
asked him to help both sides reach a settlement. On Tuesday neither
Microsoft nor representatives of the Justice Department and the 19
states that brought the suit in 1998 had any official comment on
where things stood.
</P>
<P>
   According to Ronald Cass, an antitrust expert at Boston
University, Jackson's delay provides new hope that a settlement,
which seemed unlikely last week, could happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people had more or less figured a settlement wasn't
in the cards, but this move by Jackson shows that Microsoft and the
government are making a real effort to end this case,'' Cass said.
</P>
<P>
   If Jackson does issue his ruling, he is expected to deal harshly
with the Redmond, Wash.-based company. On Nov. 5, Jackson issued
``findings of fact'' that said Microsoft had used its monopoly
power to stifle innovation, reduce competition and hurt consumers
by bundling its Internet Explorer browser with its Windows
operating system. A computer's operating system is the core program
that allows other programs, such as word processing, to operate.
</P>
<P>
   Because Windows runs 95 percent of all computers, Jackson said,
Microsoft's bundling, or tying together, of its operating system
and its browser means that browser competitors _ such as Netscape _
are at a severe disadvantage when it comes to selling their own
browsers. This Microsoft practice led to less competition and less
innovation, which hurt consumers, he said. Microsoft contends that
the browser, which allows users access to the World Wide Web, is
not a separate product but an ``integrated feature'' of Windows.
The November findings represent Jackson's conclusions about which
side presented the most believable case during the year-long
hearing that opened in his court on Oct. 19, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson will use those findings to determine whether Microsoft
actually broke the law. But since his findings of fact were against
the company, many antitrust experts say they expect he will
conclude that it did violate antitrust law. If he does, the case
will move to its final phase: the penalty stage. At that time,
Jackson could order the breakup of the company into separate parts
to end its monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's latest proposal to settle the case reportedly would
allow manufacturers of computers or software to modify Windows so
that rival products, such as Internet browsers, could be attached
to the operating system. The company also would offer a version of
Windows that would not include Microsoft's own Internet Explorer
browser.
</P>
<P>
   In the proposal, Microsoft also reportedly offered equal pricing
and shipping terms to all computer makers who use its Windows
operating system software. Such a move would end Microsoft's
ability to offer pricing breaks to computer retailers that favor
other types of Microsoft software, such as Microsoft Word, over
competing products.
</P>
<P>
   Government sources said federal and state lawyers reviewed
Microsoft's proposal over the weekend but decided it lacked enough
assurances that the company would not bundle future software
products to Windows.
</P>
<P>
   While backing away from proposals to break up the company, the
Justice Department was expected to demand that Microsoft limit the
number of software products that the firm can add to Windows.
</P>
<P>
   If Microsoft wants to make a deal, experts said, the company
will do it before Jackson's ruling on whether the firm broke the
law.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's findings of fact showed that he found the government's
case against the company credible and that he rejected as
``specious'' virtually all of Microsoft's arguments.
</P>
<P>
   With a half-dozen private antitrust suits now filed against the
company, Microsoft wants to avoid giving the plaintiffs' lawyers
any negative ruling by Jackson, which they could use as a potent
weapon in their civil suits against the firm. Microsoft stock rose
following news of the delay, climbing as high as 107-7/16 before
settling at 116, up 1-15/16 for the day.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
