<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-Q&AMP;A-0326-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service AUSTIN, Texas _
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: We will be traveling by airplane with a 2-year-old and were
wondering what to do about equalizing the pressure in his ears.
</P>
<P>
   _ T.M.
</P>
<P>
   A: As the airplane rises and descends, the air in the inner ear
expands or contracts as the pressure changes. There are as many
cures for this as for hiccups. To assist your youngster, have him
chew gum, yawn or suck on a lollipop during takeoff and landing.
The other tried-and-true technique is to pinch the nostrils closed
and blow, which backs up air into the ears, causing a ``pop.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I had my 1- and 3-year-old nephews visiting my home. The
3-year-old wrote on my newly painted white walls with a green
crayon. I've tried Fantastik, 409, warm water and even hairspray,
but the crayon isn't coming off. Any suggestions? I can repaint, if
there are no other solutions.
</P>
<P>
   _ Marsha Roose
</P>
<P>
   A: No need to redecorate.
</P>
<P>
   Spray the wall with WD-40 and wipe with a soft cloth. If there
is still some crayon gracing the wall, use a little Ivory
dishwashing liquid and water _ work in a circle with a sponge. That
should do it, according to Binney and Smith, maker of the Crayola
Crayons that often end up in some very creative places!
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you give me any information on Citizens Against
Government Waste?
</P>
<P>
   _ Barbara Racino A: Citizens Against Government Waste is a
legitimate group. Check out its quarterly magazine, The Government
Waste Watch, and the annual tome, ``The Congressional Pig Book
Summary.''
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1984 by the late industrialist J. Peter Grace and
syndicated columnist Jack Anderson, CAGW may be reached at (800)
BE-ANGRY or on the Web at www.cagw.org. A recent example? The
group's ``Pork Alert'' on North Carolina's Swine Waste Management
Program, in which the government gave $500,000 for research into
``pig doo-doo'' at North Carolina State University, in the district
of House Appropriator David Price, D-N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a 7-year-old fascinated with miniature corn on the
cob. He wants to know where they grow, and if we can get the seeds
to grow them in our yard. Clayton is going to be watching daily for
the answer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Michelle R.
</P>
<P>
   A: It's doable and the time is now. Grow baby ears of corn with
any variety of sweet corn. The trick? Plant the corn close
together, and harvest the ears earlier than usual. Full-size corn
plants are spaced about a foot apart and harvested after the silks
have turned brown. Mini-corn is the product of cramming plants
together, stunting their growth. Harvest is just before the silks
turn brown.
</P>
<P>
   Pick these puppies five days after the silk appears, and peel
carefully to reveal a tiny but perfectly formed ear about 3 inches
long.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I know George W. Bush has a brother, Jeb, the governor of
Florida. I believe he has two other brothers, Neil and Marvin. What
do they do, and where do they live?
</P>
<P>
   _ Polly Metz
</P>
<P>
   A: Neil lives in Houston and heads a company that develops
educational software. Marvin lives in Alexandria, Va., and is a
partner in an investment firm. Jeb's full name is John Ellis.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do I get in touch with the Guinness Book of Records to
report a record in an unusual category?
</P>
<P>
   _ E.C.
</P>
<P>
   A: Documentation guidelines exist for all world record
categories _ from human achievement (e.g. human centipede) to the
material world (e.g. fastest flying boa, biggest tricycle). New
categories are continually added. Write Guinness Media Inc., 6
Landmark Square, Stamford, Conn. 06901, or e-mail
infousa(at)guinnessrecords.com. Keep me posted _ I would love to
know if a Texan is among the likes of the 60 members of Singapore's
Nanyang Technological University who hold the record for the
longest paper clip chain (16 miles, 978 yards).
</P>
<P>
   Q: We have a strange mold/fungus popping up in our back yard,
near our swimming pool. It is bright yellow and puffy, and when
lifted up there is a bright red, almost liquid-type substance
underneath. Any idea what this is? It has shown up between cracks
in the cement patio and now is growing on a rock bed. I have been
cleaning the affected areas with bleach.
</P>
<P>
   _ J. Miller
</P>
<P>
   A: Mycologist (fungi guru) David Lewis suspects this fungus is a
plasmodium. You do not need bleach to clean it away _ a simple
garden hose will do. Lewis says you may have to live with the
fungus (it's not poisonous, just unsightly) until it goes away.
Plasmodium thrives on dampness and eats bacteria and algae. Want
Lewis to identify it? Pick some and dry it well (over a light
bulb), slip it in a plastic bag and mail it to him, Route 2, Box
194 L, Newton, Texas 75966. Best part? It's a free service.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Please tell me what the life of a quality mattress and box
spring should be.
</P>
<P>
   _ Patricia M.
</P>
<P>
   A: Typically eight to 10 years, say the experts at Serta, where
warranties are for 10 years of normal use. Tips for getting the
most out of your mattress and box springs? For the first three
months, turn the mattress every two weeks; then every eight weeks
thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig at P.O. Box 670, Austin, TX 78767; (512)
445-3697; e-mail jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968. Due
to the number of inquiries, Jane cannot respond to every request.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
