</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMF-KOEHLER-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMF SHOULD EXPAND ROLE IN GLOBALIZATION, SAYS INCOMING CHIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Laying out his vision of the future of the
International Monetary Fund, Horst Koehler, the new managing
director, said Tuesday that rather than shrinking as some critics
have suggested, the fund should expand its role as ``a crucial
cornerstone'' of globalization.
</P>
<P>
   His remarks in one of the first interviews he has given since
his appointment this month came amid a welter of conflicting
proposals for reforming the IMF, one of the world's important
financial institutions, both in the U.S. Congress and in the
Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   The thrust of some of those arguments, notably in a report this
month from a congressional commission led by Professor Allan H.
Meltzer of Carnegie Mellon University, was that both the IMF and
its sister institution, the World Bank, should be radically pared
back because they often do more harm than good in developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Lawrence H. Summers has opposed some of the
commission's findings, and Koehler, a 57-year-old former high
official in the German finance ministry, sought in the interview to
avoid an impression that he and Summers were on a collision course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do see a lot of communality in the ideas expressed by Larry
Summers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, in the 45-minute interview at his office at the
London-based European Bank for Reconstruction and Development,
where he will leave as president to join the IMF, Koehler made
clear that his concept of reform would not limit the broad reach of
IMF influence that some critics want trimmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``My own vision is, in rather broad terms, that the IMF should
be even more than in the past a crucial cornerstone to secure
growth and stability in the world, or in the global economy,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever we do with crisis management, aid to the developing
countries, the most important thing to achieve is sustained growth
in the world economy, and that's not only in developed countries
but really in the global economy including the developing countries
and the emerging markets. That's my most important thing.''
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged, however, that the huge capital flows that have
come to be associated with globalization had implications both for
the IMF's role as a lender and the relationship between its loans
and those available on the international capital markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think that after the experience with the crises in Russia
and Asia,'' Koehler said, ``the IMF should be the center of
excellence for the international financial markets, for the
international financial and monetary system.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, he said, the IMF should ``set up standards and
codes for sound banking systems, sound behavior and, based on that,
do more to prevent crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   But he made clear that that did not preclude a shift in the way
the fund allocates its vast resources. ``The IMF also, of course,
has to adapt to changes in the world economy,'' he said. And,
reflecting the views of the Clinton administration, he said in
seeking to promote growth, ``the biggest part should be done by the
private capital markets.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think that there's need to review the focus of the IMF,''
Koehler said. ``And reviewing the focus also means that we have to
understand IMF lending in principle as a temporary lending and not
as a permanent lending which would substitute the possibilities of
the private capital markets.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The German official is joining the IMF after 18 months as head
of the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development, an
institution established in the early 1990s to promote private
investment and market economic values in the former Soviet bloc
countries.
</P>
<P>
   He came into that job within weeks of the Russian default in
August 1998, and was obliged to write off a series of bad debts
from Russia. The experience has clearly bred a degree of caution.
</P>
<P>
   Koehler was one of the first Western officials to meet with
Russia's president-elect, Vladimir Putin, as he leapt to prominence
in the just-ended presidential election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   While Koehler said Tuesday that the IMF should ``remain engaged
in Russia'' and while he praised Russia's ``progress in terms of
adjusting to a market economy'', he also urged the new Russian
leader to avoid his country's past mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lesson from some experience in the past is that the IMF,
like others, should judge Mr. Putin and the Russian government not
just by their words but by their deeds. And I hope that President
Putin will build up new confidence in demonstrating that he's able
to take prior action before international support is coming in,''
Koehler said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the issues he addressed coincided with the U.S. view,
such as the notion that the IMF should be prepared for greater
transparency in its dealings with what he termed ``civil society.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about demands from developing countries for the
cancellation of their debts, Koehler said that any debt
cancellation should only be part of a broader strategy for economic
recovery in developing nations.
</P>
<P>
   He stressed that the IMF lending should continue as a means of
influencing the broad economic development of these countries
rather than concentrate simply on emergencies. Without lending to
the developing nations, he said, the IMF would have little
influence on economic policy.
</P>
<P>
   Koehler was chosen for the top job at the IMF after tortuous
trans-Atlantic wrangling that had soured relations between the
Clinton administration and Germany's chancellor, Gerhard Schroeder,
who lobbied first for one German candidate _ Caio Koch-Weser, who
was vetoed by President Clinton _ then swung his weight behind
Koehler, who had said just four months earlier that he was not
interested in the job.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's endorsement of Koehler was depicted in Washington as a
reluctant move designed principally to avoid further strains with
Germany. Some European officials supporting different candidates,
moreover, also raised questions about Koehler's qualifications,
despite his prominent role in designing the financial framework of
Germany's reunification and of the European single currency.
</P>
<P>
   Koehler insisted those circumstances would not undermine his
authority at the head of the IMF ``I think that the dust will
settle after this rather heated debate,'' he said. ``I'm quite
confident that we'll do a good job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
