<HEADLINE>
GASOLINE PRICES MAY NOT EASE IN U.S. UNTIL AUTUMN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Gulf Coast)   (sidebar with OPEC)  
(bl) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Regardless of how quickly oil-exporting nations can
increase production, motorists in the United States may not get
relief from high gasoline prices until this autumn at the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   While the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
negotiated a new production agreement Tuesday, petroleum industry
analysts said pump prices could remain at current levels for most
of the summer, or even rise, because domestic supplies of gasoline
and crude oil were severely depleted.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're seeing now is inventories that look closer to what
we'd expect after the summer driving season, rather than heading
into it,'' said Jonathan Cogan, a spokesman for the U.S. Energy
Information Administration, part of the Department of Energy.
</P>
<P>
   As of mid-March, motor gasoline stocks were at 199.3 million
barrels, compared with 221.6 million barrels at the same time last
year, according to the agency. Similarly, crude-oil inventories had
292.6 million barrels at mid-March, compared with 330.9 million
barrels last year.
</P>
<P>
   It takes two months or so for Middle East oil to travel to the
United States, be refined into gasoline, and make it to the
gasoline pumps. But some analysts say an OPEC production increase
might not have a noticeable effect on gasoline prices even after
that time. Not only are domestic supplies already very low, but
American consumers, feeling prosperous from the strong economy, are
expected to take a lot of driving vacations this summer, regardless
of the price. That will keep demand for fuel high.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost any action taken now is an action that will have its
greatest effect next fall or next winter,'' said Philip K.
Verleger, a senior adviser to the Brattle Group, an economic
consulting firm in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Government forecasters have predicted that average retail
gasoline prices could peak at $1.75 to $1.80 this summer. Prices
could rise even more in some parts of the country, particularly
California, which has requirements for cleaner-burning fuel.
California is ``vulnerable to any supply problems,'' said Cogan.
``Any sort of refinery problem gets reflected in the prices
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with the run-up in gasoline prices, refiners have not been
refining as much fuel as they can. The reason is that the price
they have paid for crude oil, until recently, had risen faster than
the prices for the refined products they sell, giving them less
reason to produce more gasoline. In a report earlier this month,
the International Energy Agency, which monitors petroleum
consumption in developed countries, said this was an important
reason why gasoline supplies in the United States were low.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, Verleger said, some lenders have grown more
cautious with the credit lines that refiners use to buy crude oil
because of the uncertainty over prices _ another reason why
refiners have not been increasing production.
</P>
<P>
   Verleger said any major refinery disruptions this summer _
including fires, maintenance and damage from Gulf Coast hurricanes
_ could help drive up prices more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The direction of gas prices this summer will be determined
primarily by the success of the refining industry,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Political pressure has been building to release oil from the
United States' Strategic Petroleum Reserve. Were that to happen, it
could have a quicker impact on gasoline prices, he added, because
it would take only a few weeks for that oil, which is in Louisiana,
to flow to the market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
