   (gm) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Wednesday, March 29 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   OPEC (Vienna, Austria) _ Despite a deep split between Saudi
Arabia and Iran, the president of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries said the group had reached agreement on a plan
to increase oil production and should at least halt the recent
surge in prices. ``I believe we have an agreement,'' said Ali
Rodriguez, Venezuela's oil minister and the newly named president
of OPEC. Though oil ministers were still hammering out last-minute
details, officials said the increase in quotas would be very close
to Saudi demands for about 1.7 million barrels a day. By Edmund L.
Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   UGANDA-CULT (Rugazi, Uganda) _ In one room, the concrete floor
looked a little newer and, on a hunch, the police began to dig.
First they found a human foot, sole upturned, poking up from the
rubble. Within a few hours Tuesday, 28 corpses were hauled out of a
pit _ carefully sealed over with cement, maybe months ago _ inside
the house owned by a leader of a cult in western Uganda. By dark,
the pit was only half emptied. It was, on one level, another
horrifying discovery in the two weeks since more than 300 people
were found burnt to death at a church not far from here. The death
toll, from three different sites, has now risen to at least 593.
There are at least two more suspected grave sites. But the
discovery of the pit may also indicate just how well-organized and,
perhaps longstanding, this march to mass murder in Uganda was. By
Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NASA-MARS (Washington) _ An in-depth review of NASA's Mars
exploration program, released Tuesday, was highly critical of the
management of the program and said that lack of funding, testing
and planning led to the failure of two recent Mars probes. Because
of these problems, NASA announced the cancellation of the planned
Mars 2001 lander awaiting approval of a new overall Mars
``architecture'' plan. By Warren E. Leary.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT16.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-SEARCH (Washington) _ An anonymous tip that a person is
carrying a gun is not enough to justify a stop and frisk by the
police without some further sign that the information is reliable,
the Supreme Court ruled with surprising unanimity Tuesday. While
the decision was an important ruling that placed a constitutional
curb on a particular type of police-citizen encounter, the court
did not address the more controversial and heavily freighted
question of what actions the police can take based not on a tip but
on their own observation and judgment. In the current climate of
increased tension over police tactics, the court's ruling in
January that unprovoked flight at the sight of a police officer can
justify the police in chasing and frisking the person may prove
more significant. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   HAITIAN-PARENTS-DEPORT (Miami) _ Esta Pierre built a solid life
on shaky ground in Florida, scrubbing hotel room toilets and
bathing people in nursing homes to earn a living. She married a
Haitian immigrant and made payments on a little house in southwest
Florida. They had two children here, Jean Gardy, now 6, and Gaelle,
21 months. Ms. Pierre has received a deportation order from the
U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service, and barring one last,
thin appeal, said her Miami lawyer, she will be sent back. Her
husband, who also entered the U.S. on fake documents, has also been
ordered home. But their children, born here, are U.S. citizens by
birthright and cannot be deported. So, Ms. Pierre, like thousands
of other Haitian mothers and fathers in the U.S., must someday
choose whether to take her children with her or leave them, to save
them? By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-EDUC (Somerset, N.J.) _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas
proposed a $5 billion program Tuesday to address what he termed a
national literacy crisis among children, making his boldest
statement yet that he intends to moor his campaign on the kind of
educational initiatives that have long been identified with
Democrats. By Clifford J. Levy.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT10.
</P>
<P>
   FUNDRAISING-LOOPHOLE (Washington) _ The tiny remnant of the
American peace movement had a little money and was looking for a
voice in the political process. The pharmaceutical industry had a
lot of money and was looking for a bullhorn. Both found it in an
obscure corner of the IRS known as Section 527, a provision that
allows groups to raise and spend unlimited sums on political
activities without any disclosure as long as they do not expressly
advocate voting for one candidate or another. Section 527 has
become the loophole of choice this year for groups large and small,
left and right, to spread their messages without revealing the
sources of their income or the targets of their spending. And there
is no prohibition against accepting foreign money. By John M.
Broder and Raymond Bonner.
</P>
</TEXT>
