<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Every other week, The Chronicle features ``Learning
to Cook'' by Marion Cunningham, a cooking teacher and cookbook
author best known for her revisions of the Fannie Farmer cookbooks.
This column is intended for novices in the kitchen. &HT;     
 LEARNING TO COOK: Ginger Packs a Punch in Chicken Stir-Fry   By Marion Cunningham  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; This is a simple Cantonese-type dish, full of good
flavor and texture.
<P>
   Serve it with steamed, long-grained white rice. Add a good
teaspoon of jasmine tea leaves and a little salt to the rice water
a minute or two before you add the rice. You have no idea how good
this ``jasmine rice'' is with the sweet soy ginger sauce that is
cooked with the chicken.
</P>
<P>
   For this dish, I like to use the dark meat of the chicken _
thighs or legs _ but if you prefer white meat, chicken breasts work
fine, too. They will take a little longer to cook, though.
</P>
<P>
   I learned to make this dish many years ago in the kitchen of a
fine Chinese cooking teacher, Rose Chang, who lived in San
Francisco's Chinatown and taught classes on Saturday mornings.
</P>
<P>
   Cantonese cooking is ideally suited for home cooks. The recipes
are uncomplicated, quick to make and very satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   Use a skillet, saute pan or wok to make this dish _ preferably
one with a nonstick lining, which will prevent the chicken pieces
from sticking.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; CHICKEN WITH FRESH GINGER
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   5 ounces fresh ginger (see note)
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup dry sherry
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   4 scallions (also called green onions)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup peanut oil or vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   21/2 pounds chicken drumsticks
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Prepare the ginger and scallions: &LR;  You don't need to peel the
ginger. Cut it into 1/4-inch slices (you'll need 1 cup). Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the soy sauce, sherry and sugar in a bowl and stir until
blended. Set aside. Prepare the scallions by cutting off the roots
at the end of the white part. Leave about 2 inches of the green
leaves and cut the white and green leaves into thin slices. Set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Cooking the Chicken:  &LR; Pour the peanut oil into a saute pan or
skillet and place over medium high heat. When the oil feels hot
(put the palm of your hand 1 inch above the oil _ you will feel the
heat), add the chicken and ginger. Spread the chicken and ginger in
a single layer in the pan and, using a fork, move the pieces
occasionally as they cook so they don't stick to the bottom of the
pan. After about 5 minutes, turn the chicken pieces over if they
have browned. Let the chicken cook until well browned on all sides,
turning from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   Reduce the heat to medium low, then pour the sauce evenly over
the chicken and ginger. Cover the pan and let the chicken and
ginger cook for about 6 to 8 minutes. Remove cover and test the
chicken for doneness by cutting a slit to the bone. If there is no
pink or redness around the bone, the chicken is done. Transfer the
chicken and ginger to a warmed platter; sprinkle the scallions over
the top.
</P>
<P>
   Serve the jasmine rice on the side.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note:  &LR; Fresh ginger may be found in the produce department of
most supermarkets. Select ginger that is firm with no withered or
wrinkled spots.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 780 calories, &LR;   &LR; 54 g protein, 25 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 48 g fat (12 g saturated), 234 mg cholesterol,
1,590 mg sodium, &LR;   &LR; 0 fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
