<DOCNO> NYT20000328.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0444 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-SECRET-CHIX-SFCHRON &LR;      03-28 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECRET-CHIX-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the recipe
for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the chef's
secrets for making it a success. Tips and recipe follow in optional
trim. 
 
 SECRETS OF SUCCESS: Silky Caramel Chicken   By Michael Bauer  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Many experts from coast to coast claim the Slanted
Door serves the best Vietnamese food in the United States. That's
quite an accolade for Charles Phan, who was an architect and a
computer graphic artist before he followed his passion to open this
restaurant with his family.
<TEXT>
<P>
   At first his idea was to open a small stand and serve street
food, but then he found a space in the Mission and the idea grew
into a full-fledged restaurant. He did much of the design work
himself to come up with the sleek, simple look with an open kitchen
carved out of the back corner.
</P>
<P>
   While still living in Vietnam, his mother picked up many
cross-cultural techniques that she passed along to her son _ such
as mayonnaise in the spring rolls, for example. But Phan also
searched out the great food that's served from stands all over
Vietnam, and used them as inspiration for many of the great dishes
on the menu.
</P>
<P>
   One of those is the Chicken in Caramel Sauce, an unlikely blend
of pungent fish sauce, dark brown sugar and dark meat chicken. It
may sound strange but the two radically different flavorings are
balanced by rice wine vinegar, ginger and chiles. It's really a
simple dish to prepare, and the results are wonderful.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Slanted Door, 584 Valencia St. (near 17th Street), San &LR; 
 &LR; Francisco; (415) 861-8032. Lunch and dinner Tuesday-Sunday. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; SECRETS OF SUCCESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; The balance of ingredients. &LR;  The play between the fish sauce
and brown sugar creates a complex, alluring flavor.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; White and dark meat. &LR;  The use of both kinds of meat gives a
more interesting texture to the finished dish.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CHICKEN IN CARAMEL SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup dark brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup fish sauce (see note)
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons rice vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dark or regular soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon slivered ginger
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 small Thai chiles (fresh or dried), broken in half
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon canola oil
</P>
<P>
   1 shallot, sliced
</P>
<P>
   13/4 pounds skinless, boneless dark-meat chicken, cut into
bite-size pieces
</P>
<P>
   1/4 pound skinless, boneless white-meat chicken, cut into
bite-size pieces
</P>
<P>
   Steamed white rice
</P>
<P>
   Cilantro sprigs for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the brown sugar, water, fish sauce, vinegar, garlic, soy
sauce, ginger, pepper and chiles in a small bowl. Mix well. Set
sauce mixture aside.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a large pot over high heat. Add the shallot and
saute until brown, about 5 minutes. Add the chicken and saute until
slightly browned, about 5 minutes. Add the sauce mixture and bring
to a boil. Reduce heat to medium. Cook until the sauce has reduced
by half, about 12 minutes, stirring occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   Serve over rice and garnish with cilantro.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 to 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note:  &LR; Fish sauce is available in Asian markets and upscale
supermarkets
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 400 calories, &LR;   &LR; 41 g protein, 22 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 15 g fat (4 g saturated), 131 mg cholesterol, 903
mg sodium, 0 &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
