<DOCNO> NYT20000328.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0445 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-SOURCE-PEAS-SFCHRON &LR;      03-28 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOURCE-PEAS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: This column profiles Northern California growers,
anglers and artisans who make the region such a culinary
wonderland. Over the next few months, we'll take you from field to
forest to factory to look at the wealth of ingredients stocking our
larders. 
 
 AT THE SOURCE: Spring Bounty: Riverdog Farm shells out sugar snap 
 peas   By Karola Saekel  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 YOLO COUNTY, Calif. _  One of the perks of organic farming, says
Tim Mueller, is ``you eat well.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   And, of course, you also eat seasonally, from broccoli in the
winter to tomatoes and melons in the summer, made sweet by the sun
that sizzles on the Capay Valley (near Woodland, Yolo County).
That's where Mueller and Trini Campbell cultivate 70 acres that
make up Riverdog Farm.
</P>
<P>
   Four-year-old Cassidy completes the household. ``We actually got
married,'' Mueller jokes about himself and Campbell. ``We got
conventional.''
</P>
<P>
   That term may apply to their marital status, but not to their
farming practices.
</P>
<P>
   The couple, both raised as ``city kids,'' met at Grenelle
College in Iowa, where they became fascinated by the concept of
sustainable agriculture. They came west to practice what they
believed in, starting 10 years ago in Napa County and moving to the
tiny farming community of Guinda in Yolo County six years later.
</P>
<P>
   Just as their growing practices hark back to the days before
chemicals, genetic engineering and modern agribusiness invaded
America's farmlands, the couple's selection of crops reflects
traditional ways. Rather than growing one or two vegetables, they
plant as many as 60 crops.
</P>
<P>
   One of them is just coming to market: sugar snap peas. Picking
of over-winter peas (planted in October) usually starts in February
at Riverdog Farm, but this year the heavy rains delayed the start
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Mueller and Campbell grow several varieties of the peas on 21/2
acres, including Cascadia and Super Sugar Mel, both of which have
strings attached.
</P>
<P>
   Mueller says they prefer peas with strings to the stringless
variety: Getting the latter to table takes less effort, he admits,
but as with so many produce varieties developed for convenience,
there is a payback: The stringed peas, he asserts, have more
flavor.
</P>
<P>
   While he and Campbell _ ``we both cook, but we are not gourmet
cooks'' _ sometimes lightly steam the peas, he likes them best raw,
either as a snack or in a salad. One of his favorites is potato
salad with uncooked snap peas, spring onions and green garlic _
all, of course, picked at Riverdog Farm.
</P>
<P>
   Mentioning the farm's name inevitably brings up the question,
why Riverdog?
</P>
<P>
   When Mueller and Campbell farmed in Napa, they sold their crops
from a farm stand right by the Napa River and their big black dog
used to love to dive into the water, then shake himself off,
spraying the customers in the process. The couple called their
business Campbell-Mueller Gardens, but market goers took to calling
it the Riverdog stand. So when the couple moved to a new farm, they
decided to make the nickname official.
</P>
<P>
   They still sell from stands, though not by a river, as well as
by subscription and to Berkeley Bowl market. They now limit
themselves to the two Berkeley farmers' markets (Tuesday afternoon
on Derby Street at Martin Luther King Jr. Way, and Saturday morning
on Center Street at Martin Luther King Jr. Way).
</P>
<P>
   Organically grown produce, with generally higher prices, sells
well in some communities and not in others.
</P>
<P>
   Berkeley, Mueller says, has the ideal clientele. They gave up on
Sacramento, where they manned a stand for a while. ``Sacramento,''
he says, ``was like pulling teeth.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; For subscription information, call Riverdog Farm, (530) &LR; 
 &LR; 796-3802. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-00 1903EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
