<DOCNO> NYT20000328.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0446 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-NETANYAHU-1STL     03-28 1211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-NETANYAHU-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-940&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI POLICE PROPOSE CHARGING NETANYAHU WITH CORRUPTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS to update early version with Netanyahu's evening TV interview
and to clarify: grafs 2, 5, 6, 9, 10, 11 to clarify; inserts new
grafs 3, 7 with info from interview; 5th graf to add background on
legal system; 8th graf to add denial by Netanyahu; refines final
graf before optional trim and adds 2 new grafs (bgng `Sara
Netanyahu pushed...') before that graf with info. from police
report; adds new graf after optional trim with quote from
Netanyahu.) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT1 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ After a seven-month investigation, Israeli police on
Tuesday recommended that former Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
and his wife, Sara, face criminal prosecution on charges of
bribery, fraud and the theft of $100,000 worth of gifts meant for
the state.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu, who quit politics when he was defeated as prime
minister by Ehud Barak in May, said the charges were ``baseless''
and inspired by political enemies and an overly zealous police
force. His lawyer, Yaakov Weinroth, said he was ``itching for a
trial'' to demonstrate that there is ``nothing to'' the
accusations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm being persecuted,'' Netanyahu repeated several times, in a
50-minute interview Tuesday night on Israel's Channel One, which
returned him to the prime-time spot that he dominated during his
three years in office. ``I define this as a hunt. It's a hunt.
They're hunting me and my wife down.''
</P>
<P>
   If justice officials take the police recommendation to put
Netanyahu on trial, it could thwart his ability to make a political
comeback. While he has not publicly expressed interest in doing so,
the right-wing opposition to Barak has been lackluster, and many
here assumed that Netanyahu would eventually be tempted back into
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Israeli legal system, police investigate and either
close a case or make a recommendation to the state prosecutor or
attorney general. But a police recommendation does not always lead
to prosecution, as Netanyahu well knows. In 1997, while he was
prime minister, the police suggested that he stand trial on
corruption charges. But the attorney general, Elyakim Rubenstein,
declined to prosecute, saying there was insufficient evidence.
Rubenstein remains in office.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the police said the Netanyahus ``illegally
removed'' 700 gifts to the state of Israel when they left the prime
minister's residence. The police said some of the objects, which
included candelabra, silverware, carpets and a gold letter opener
from U.S. Vice President Al Gore, had been altered to remove
inscriptions that clearly marked them as gifts to Israel. Some were
found in the Netanyahus' Jerusalem apartment and some in a
warehouse, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview Tuesday night, Netanyahu said that Barak had
kicked him out of the prime minister's residence prematurely _
although it was weeks after Barak took office _ and that Netanyahu
did not have time to sort his belongings while packing. He said he
was entitled to take some presents _ perhaps referring to the gifts
of minimal value that he can accept under the law. Holding up a
woman's brooch, he said the police had grilled Mrs. Netanyahu for
four hours about the pin, which an appraisal later showed to be
worth $1.50.
</P>
<P>
   The police also said the Netanyahus had accepted some $50,000
worth of free services from a contractor, Avner Amedi, over many
years. Netanyahu denied that Tuesday night, saying the amount was
wildly exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   The police described an illegal ``give-and-take relationship,''
which amounted under law to bribery. They said it began when
Netanyahu was a lawmaker and continued through his three-year
tenure as a charismatic prime minister who eventually lost the
confidence of the nation but retained many loyal followers.
</P>
<P>
   The police would not specify Tuesday what the contractor
received in return. They said they discovered ``a number of cases''
in which, they said, ``Netanyahu did, in fact, act on Amedi's
behalf.'' But the police report indicated that the relationship
broke down when Amedi did not get everything he requested _ he was
supposedly seeking a government contract _ and submitted a bill to
Netanyahu. But he did not get paid.
</P>
<P>
   After Netanyahu lost the election, the contractor, with the
knowledge of the Netanyahus, submitted another bill, for $110,000
of moving expenses, to the prime minister's office, the police
said. The ``very high bill raised suspicions about criminal acts,''
and government officials suspected that the Netanyahus were trying
to ``foist'' their private expenses onto the government, the police
said.
</P>
<P>
   The police investigation began after a newspaper, Yedioth
Ahronoth, reported on the suspicions of government officials.
According to the newspaper, the private work included ``four floor
polishings in a single month,'' a crane used to install bars on the
windows of the Netanyahus' private apartment and the repair of an
exercise machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sara Netanyahu pushed to have the debt paid off by the prime
minister's office while trying to do away with the Netanyahus'
personal debt,'' the police said.
</P>
<P>
   The police also said Netanyahu had summoned Amedi and had asked
him to deny the nature of their relationship, for which they
recommend that the former prime minister be charged with
obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   The contractor is the state's chief witness, and most of the
case outlined by the police is believed to be based on information
he provided. They questioned 100 other people, too, and noted what
they considered inconsistencies and ``improbabilities'' in the
Netanyahus' account.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu said Tuesday night that Amedi was not telling the
truth and that the police were building a case on lies. ``They
penetrated our home, picked through our belongings, called me a
thief, my wife a thief and trampled our dignity with tendentious
leaks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu's political allies echoed his assertion that the
police were out to get him. ``The police have been behaving as if
they were on a chase mission to find Netanyahu guilty of
something,'' said Uzi Landau, a legislator from Netanyahu's Likud
Party.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But as Netanyahu's television interviewer pointed out, the
Israeli police have numerous investigations before them, targeting
figures across the political spectrum. President Ezer Weizman is
under investigation for accepting a large cash gift from a French
businessman. The campaign fundraising practices of Barak are under
investigation. And on Monday, the police began an inquiry into
whether a leading rabbi, Ovadia Yosef, should be prosecuted for
incitement after a blistering sermon against the education
minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very dark day for Israeli politics,'' said Ophir
Pines-Paz, who is the chairman of Barak's governing coalition.
``The whole spate of investigations looks bad and is bad. We all
have to be very careful. We have to understand that we are not
above the law.''
</P>
</TEXT>
