<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 COOKS' BOOKS: Rose Pistola Belongs on Kitchen Shelves   By Miriam Morgan  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  ``The Rose Pistola Cookbook'' has found a
semi-permanent place on The Chronicle's Top 10 cookbook list ever
since it was published last fall. And for good reason. With this
book the home cook can replicate many of the recipes from
chef-owner Reed Hearon that have made his restaurant one of the
most popular in North Beach.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even though Hearon is an award-winning chef _ just last week he
was nominated for a prestigious James Beard Award for best chef in
California _ at Rose Pistola he focuses on traditional home cooking
of the Ligurian region of Italy. That means the dishes themselves
are straightforward and uncomplicated, but Hearon's knowledge and
skills make them far from ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   He and co-author Peggy Knickerbocker make all of that accessible
for the home cook. True, most American homes don't have the sort of
wood-burning oven that is a mainstay of Hearon's restaurant, and
the same dishes cooked even in the hottest conventional oven or
charcoal grill won't have all the smoky characteristics. But
Hearon's direct, confident approach ensures that home versions are
excellent nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   For example, one of Hearon's signature restaurant dishes, Roast
Fish with Potatoes and Artichokes, may not taste exactly as it does
in the restaurant, but it's so good that it doesn't matter. And the
home-cooked version is true to the spirit of the original.
</P>
<P>
   The fish _ whole or in fillets _ roasts in a blend of white wine
and its own juices, nestled in a melange of sliced Yellow Finn
potatoes and parboiled baby artichokes, scattered with nicoise
olives and fresh rosemary.
</P>
<P>
   It requires so little preparation that it works well for
mid-week meals, but is special enough for company, particularly if
it's cooked in an attractive oven-to-table gratin dish or copper
baking pan. And by varying the type of fish _ from halibut to rock
cod to salmon, for example _ the dish is versatile, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the book, Hearon shows how to use high-quality
ingredients simply to create unexpected flavor sensations. In Salad
of Mushrooms, Endive and Parmesan, for example, the mushrooms and
endive bring out each other's earthiness, and the nutty Parmesan
plays off the endive's bite. One caveat, as he warns _ the
ingredients must be sliced paper-thin, which is best done on a
mandoline.
</P>
<P>
   Hearon carefully explains his basic techniques, like how to
perfume an oil before using it, and how Italian sauce-making
differs from the French method. Even without following any of his
recipes, this information alone can help home cooks with their own
preparations.
</P>
<P>
   Rose Pistola is named after a legendary North Beach bar owner,
and Hearon and Knickerbocker pay their respects with a tribute in
the book's introduction. They also describe the role that Ligurians
and other Italian immigrants played in establishing North Beach as
a unique, vibrant community.
</P>
<P>
   It's all part of San Francisco's heritage _ which is another
reason why ``The Rose Pistola Cookbook'' is a nice addition to the
libraries of Bay Area cooks.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  ``The Rose Pistola Cookbook,'' by Reed Hearon and Peggy &LR; 
 &LR; Knickerbocker (Broadway Books; 276 pages; $35). &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ROAST FISH WITH POTATOES &AMP; ARTICHOKES
</P>
<P>
   Halibut, sea bass, rock cod, salmon, Arctic char or ono will all
work well. You can use individual fillets, one large fillet or a
whole fish. A whole fish will take longer to cook but the flavors
are enhanced because the skin and skeleton are left intact.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   10 baby artichokes
</P>
<P>
   1 pound yellow Finn potatoes, peeled, cut into 1/4-inch slices
</P>
<P>
   1 medium whole fish (approximately 21/2 pounds), cleaned and
scaled, or 11/2 pounds fish fillets with skin
</P>
<P>
   Kosher or sea salt and freshly cracked black pepper
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil, plus extra for drizzling
</P>
<P>
   1 garlic clove, bruised
</P>
<P>
   1 sprig rosemary
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 24 nicoise olives (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Trim and slice the artichokes and keep them in a bowl of water
(with a squeeze of lemon juice to prevent discoloring) until ready
to use.
</P>
<P>
   Blanch the potatoes in a small pot of salted boiling water until
they are tender; drain.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 550 degrees, or the highest setting. Season
the fish generously with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Toss the potatoes with the remaining ingredients except the fish
and spoon into an oval gratin or baking dish. Nestle the fish in
the mixture, turning it to make sure the top is well coated with
olive oil. If using fillets, leave skin-side up. Roast until the
fish is opaque, the skin is brown and the potatoes have begun to
dry out, about 10 minutes per inch of thickness of the fish.
</P>
<P>
   If using a whole fish, lift the top fillet off the fish with a
spatula or cake server and place on a warm plate. Grab the head,
tail and backbone (it will come out in one piece), remove and
discard. Discard the rosemary. Lift the bottom fillet onto the warm
plate. Divide the fish, potatoes and artichokes (and olives, if
using) among 3 warm plates. Pass additional olive oil for
drizzling.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 3.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 510 calories, &LR;   &LR; 53 g protein, 32 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 17 g fat (2 g saturated), 84 mg cholesterol, 295 mg
sodium, 6 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
