 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, wine editor Gerald Boyd discusses a
variety of wine topics. 
 
 WINE POTPOURRI: Evenings Were Meant for French Brandy   By Gerald D. Boyd  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Despite the fact that it's officially spring, Bay
Area evenings still can be chilly. Summer in San Francisco brings
especially cold nights, which means Cognac and Armagnac, the twin
brandies of France, are perfect for after-dinner sipping all year
long.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Good grape brandies are distilled in Spain, Italy, the United
States and Germany, but France still is viewed as the leader of
high-quality brandy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COGNAC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Cognac is the best-known brandy in the world, produced in a
region of Western France along the Atlantic coast, just north of
Bordeaux. Cognac is divided into six zones, with Grande Champagne
and Petite Champagne producing the best Cognac. A blend of the two
often is labeled Fine Champagne. The other zones are Borderies,
Fins Bois, Bons Bois and Bois Ordinaires.
</P>
<P>
   Cognac starts with a thin, acid white wine made from Ugni Blanc,
Folle Blanche and Colombard; It is not that great for drinking, but
just right for distilling. The wine is distilled twice in pot
stills, then aged in French oak to tame its fiery spirit and give
it color. Although there is rising interest in vintage-dated and
single-vineyard Cognacs, Cognac usually is a blend of different
vintages and growing zones.
</P>
<P>
   Most Cognac does not carry an age statement, but is known by a
set of terms that generally distinguishes the age of one Cognac
from another. V.S. (Very Superior) usually is aged a minimum of two
years in cask, although four to five years is more likely the
overall standard. V.S.O.P. (Very Superior Old Pale) is aged a
minimum of four years in wood, with the industry average between 10
and 15 years. X.O. (Extra Old) is aged a minimum of six years,
although the average can run to 20 years or older.
</P>
<P>
   Top Cognacs are produced by Delamain, Fussigny, Pierre Frapin,
Hennessy, Hine, Remy Martin, Louis Royer, Courvoisier, Gabriel &AMP;
Andreu, Pierre Ferrand and Hardy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ARMAGNAC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This hearty brandy dates back to the 15th century, which makes
it the oldest brandy in France. Armagnac is distilled in Gascony,
in the Southwestern corner of France. The main zones are
Bas-Armagnac, Haut-Armagnac and T &LR; e &LR; nar &LR; e &LR; zecq &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Armagnac distillers use the same three grapes as Cognac, but
distill their brandy in a unique type of column still that produces
a brandy that is more rustic and assertive than Cognac. Another
factor that contributes to the distinct character of Armagnac is
aging in barrels made from the local Monlezun ``black'' oak,
although most distilleries now use Limousin and Troncais oak, the
same used by Cognac distillers.
</P>
<P>
   Like Cognac, Armagnac is designated on the label as V.S.,
V.S.O.P. and X.O., although there are more single-vintage and
single-vineyard bottlings than in Cognac.
</P>
<P>
   Look for these brands: Janneau, Marquis de Cassaude, Samalens,
Larressingle, Cles des Ducs and Marquis de Montesquioucq &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Wine Country News &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The first quarter of the year has seen a flurry of activity in
the West Coast wine industry that may impact the kind of wines
consumers will see from many of the large wine companies.
</P>
<P>
   _ Perhaps the biggest surprise was the sale of Matanzas Creek
Winery in Sonoma's Bennett Valley to Artisans &AMP; Estates, the
collection of premium wineries owned by wine magnate Jess Jackson.
Matanzas Creek has long been a leader in first-rate Chardonnay,
Merlot and Sauvignon Blanc. Artisans &AMP; Estates' other brands
include Cardinale, Hartford Court and Lokoya.
</P>
<P>
   _ Stimson Lane, the parent company of Washington's Chateau Ste.
Michelle and Columbia Crest, has joined forces with Australia's
Petaluma Vineyards to market a line of premium Australia wines in
North America and Australia. Last year, Stimson Lane joined forces
with Italy's Antinori to create Col Solare, a red wine made from
Washington grapes. The Washington-based wine giant also owns
California wineries, including Villa Mt. Eden and Conn Creek Winery
in the Napa Valley.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chalone Wine Group has strengthened its Napa Valley Cabernet
Sauvignon position with the purchase of Suscol Creek Vineyard. CWG
recently purchased Hewitt Vineyard on the Rutherford Bench, which
will be the source of grapes for a luxury-priced single-vineyard
wine.
</P>
<P>
   _ In an effort to provide U.S. direct marketing and Internet
sales, Australia's Mildara Blass has purchased Windsor Vineyards,
the largest consumer-direct winery in the United States. Robert
Mondavi has purchased a minority stake in Tenuta dell'Ornellaia,
owned by Marchese Lodovico Antinori and also purchased La Capitana
in Tuscany to be developed into vineyards for Lucente, the joint
venture wine with the Marchesi de Frescobaldi family.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Sonoma, Don and Rhonda Carano, owners of Ferrari-Carano
winery, have purchased Vintners Inn and John Ash &AMP; Co. restaurant
in Santa Rosa.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Wine Q &AMP; A &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Sasikala Devi of McKinleyville writes to say that she is
``decidedly fond'' of Amer Picon but cannot find it at retail.
That's because Amer Picon, a French bitters, based on brandy, has
not been in the California market for a few years. As an alternate
choice, I suggest the popular Italian bitters, Fernet Branca.
</P>
<P>
   _ John Ammons expressed a concern recently via e-mail about The
Chronicle reviewing wines that he believes are not currently in the
market. While that is understandable, limiting reviews to current
release wines would exclude those in personal wine collections and
on restaurant wine lists. Also, not every winery releases the same
vintages of a wine type at the same time of year or the same year.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle Tasting Panel attempts to cover as many wines as
possible and we realize that not all of the wines we recommend are
available at individual retail stores.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
