EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel of
professional tasters tries a different product available in
supermarkets.  
 
 TASTER'S CHOICE: Water May Surpass Vegetable Broths   By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  For vegetarians, chicken and beef broth are out of
the question when making soups and stews. But according to The
Chronicle tasting panel, the vegetable broths available aren't a
very good choice, either.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's panel tasted five vegetable broths, most available in
cans and some in boxes. The panel was surprised how bad some of
them tasted. Some were too salty; others tasted strongly of celery
or had no depth of flavor.
</P>
<P>
   The tasters disliked the broths so much that they would not
drink any of them straight as a broth, and most of them would
prefer to use water instead of the broths in most cooking.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pritikin &LR;  (141/2 ounces, $1.79 at Draeger's) ranked the
highest. One panelist detected a bitter edge, but thought it would
smooth out if used as a base for a soup. Another mentioned that it
might be good in risotto or tomato sauce. But one other panelist
thought it had a strange color and tasted strangely of apricots.
One would buy it, one might buy it and three would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Hain &LR;  (14 ounces, $1.59 at Whole Foods) came in second.
Panelists detected overly strong notes of celery and herbs. Many
disliked the cloudy appearance. One panelist thought the flavors
were muddy, but the broth might be OK if used in a soup with other
strong flavors. One might buy it; four would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Health Valley &LR;  (32 ounces, 99 cents at Trader Joe's) and
 &UR; Pacific &LR;  (32 ounces, $2.39-$3.19 at many supermarkets) tied for
third place.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists described Health Valley as tasting harsh, bitter and
metallic. One might buy it; four would not.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists described Pacific as ``the least offensive'' _ watery
and innocuous. One might buy it; four would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Swanson &LR;  (141/2 ounces, 77-99 cents at many supermarkets) came
in fifth. All the panelists thought it was far too salty _ it has
1,000 mg of sodium per cup, as compared with 290-480 mg for the
other products. Three panelists thought the salt made the product
inedible. One commented that he didn't think the product could be
used in any cooking because of the amount of salt. None would buy
it.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists were Flo Braker, cookbook author and Chronicle Food
columnist; John P. Carroll, cookbook author; Donna Katzl,
chef-owner, Cafe For All Seasons, San Francisco; Kim Severson,
Chronicle staff writer; and Kirk Webber, chef-owner, Cafe Kati, San
Francisco. All products are tasted blind. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-00 1905EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
