A0454 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BKC-WISCONSIN-COX     03-28 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WISCONSIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Old School' Wisconsin keeps alive coach's dream
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Dick Bennett became head coach at Wisconsin five years ago,
his new players were presented with a theme: ``Start the Dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Back then, The Dream was to make Wisconsin competitive in the
rough-and-tumble Big Ten. Once that was accomplished, Bennett
modified the theme to ``Reach for the Dream.'' The Badgers did that
in 1999 when they went 22-10 and earned a spot in the NCAA
Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The theme for this season? ``Touch the Dream.''
</P>
<P>
   And now that the Badgers (22-13) have defied all odds and
reached their first Final Four since 1941?
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought I was going to be able to say this to a
team,'' Bennett told his squad after they had beaten Purdue 64-60
for the West Regional championship. ``But now you can live the
dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin is living that dream and living it large. On Feb. 12,
when it lost to Michigan State 61-44, the Badgers thought the NIT
was a long shot. They were 13-12 and 5-8 in the Big Ten.
</P>
<P>
   But since then Wisconsin has been the model of efficiency. They
are 10-3 in their past 13 games, all three losses to Michigan
State, Saturday's opponent in the RCA Dome in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin's players have no question about who gets the credit
for the comeback. In an age of consummate hip, of style over
substance, Bennett is definitely ``Old School.''
</P>
<P>
   He has coached in the same state for 35 years. His role model is
Wisconsin's leading sports icon, the late Vince Lombardi of the
Green Bay Packers. Bennett admits to spending an inordinate amount
of time watching Lombardi's practices and drawing his basic
principles from the Hall of Fame coach.
</P>
<P>
   Principle No. 1: ``Do a few things, and do them well.''
</P>
<P>
   While many of today's players are overly interested in making
the highlight reel for the next ``SportsCenter,'' Bennett demands
that his players adhere to the most basic fundamentals of the game:
Picking and rolling, blocking out, making the safe pass and milking
every possession to get the best possible shot.
</P>
<P>
   It comes as no surprise that McDonald's All-Americans are not
flocking to Madison to play in Bennett's system. None of
Wisconsin's starting five even received an honorable mention when
the All-Big Ten team was announced. It is not an overstatement to
say that none of Wisconsin's players could crack the starting
lineup of the other three teams in the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   So Bennett recruits players of good athletic ability who are
willing to buy into his system and his belief that, with enough
selflessness, the whole of the team can be better than the sum of
its parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``To play at Wisconsin, you really have to buy into the whole
team concept,'' junior forward Mark Vershaw said. ``If we had to
play our opponents one on one, we'd probably lose every time. But
we don't have to do that, so we help each other and win as a
team.''
</P>
<P>
   But don't think the grandfatherly looking Bennett sells his
system by giving his players the warm-and-fuzzies. Like Lombardi,
Bennett takes pride in pushing his players out of their comfort
zones. It is the only way to make them realize their full
potential. And he makes no apologies for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it hurts some players, and some parents are unhappy
with the way I deal with their sons,'' Bennett said. ``But I
understand the need to confront those who tend to accept too little
of themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just relentless. He will not accept anything less than
the best from you,'' junior forward Mike Kelley said. ``If you
can't do that, you are going to hear about it.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a system that has served Bennett well at every stop along
the coaching trail. His last three squads at Wisconsin-Stevens
Point were 79-13. At Wisconsin-Green Bay, he won 187 games and had
the team nobody wanted to play in the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   But not everybody has appreciated the purity Bennett attaches to
the game of basketball. After Wisconsin lost to Southwest Missouri
State 43-32 in the first round of the 1999 NCAA Tournament,
athletics director Pat Ritcher started to hear some grumbling. Some
alumns were not bashful in saying that the game had long ago passed
Bennett by and that it was time for Wisconsin to move into the
modern age.
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason, those close to the program say, that Bennett
started crying in the moments before Wisconsin's West Regional
championship game with Purdue. After years of ridicule, Bennett's
way had a chance at validation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it finally dawned on him that what he has been
building for 35 years was about to happen,'' assistant coach Brad
Soderberg said.
</P>
<P>
   While Bennett and his style of play might not get a lot of face
time on television, he is much respected in the coaching
fraternity. Last season, Sports Illustrated polled 115 college
coaches and asked them if they could attend only one coaching
clinic, whose would it be? The top vote-getters: Duke's Mike
Krzyzewski, Utah's Rick Majerus and Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   But it is one thing to labor well in relative obscurity. On
Saturday, 19 days short of his 57th birthday, Dick Bennett will put
his system _ his very life _ on college basketball's grandest
stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought we were playing the game the way you were
supposed to,'' said Bennett, tongue in cheek. ``It wasn't until
recent years that I learned we were setting the game back.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
