<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0456 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-GLF-MARTIN-COX     03-28 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MARTIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Martin's ability to walk, career on shaky ground
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _Great instability remains in his life. Casey Martin's
PGA Tour status teeters year to year on a judge's ruling or an
appeal. His withered right leg, which suffers from a rare
circulatory disease, survives day to day, searching for even
ground.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the road is filled with potholes to affect both
systems _ legal and circulatory. Earlier this month, the courts
denied the PGA Tour's appeal, extending Martin's ability to use a
cart. In February for a few perilous seconds, Martin feared his leg
might snap. Walking along at the Nissan Open in Los Angeles, he
stepped in a hole surrounding a sprinkler and spent a chilling few
seconds wondering whether his golf career was about to end.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was absolutely the worst day of my life, physically,'' said
the 27-year-old Martin. ``I kind of stepped down about an extra 2
inches than I was expecting. It jarred my leg, and that came
totally unexpected. I am realizing that my leg is more and more
fragile. I don't think you'll see me jumping too many creeks.
Hopefully, I'm hitting it better, so I won't be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Without a cart, perhaps he could attempt flat Florida courses,
but a place such as the hilly, massive TPC at Sugarloaf _ this
week's venue for the BellSouth Classic _ he could not even ponder.
Surely, some fellow players this week must be jealous that Martin
has wheels, while they trudge Sugarloaf's expanse.
</P>
<P>
   People forget that Martin never enjoys the luxury of getting to
know a golf course through the feel of his feet. Or walking from
teebox to fairway, slowly organizing his thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   People don't realize that just moving from the cart path to his
ball, Martin will walk a few painful miles. For those days more
painful than others, Martin just pops a few more Advils and hopes
that eventually the road flattens out. He also has been bothered by
neck and shoulder problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just kind of gut it out,'' he said. ``I do take a lot of
Advil, which tends to help quite a bit. But even that doesn't
always get it. There is not a lot you can say, nothing I can really
do. I am not going to go pout most of the time, so you just suck it
up and get through it. . . . I'm not better (than two years ago),
but I don't think I'm a lot worse. . . . I just play the best I can
and leave the rest in God's hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows how long Martin will be able to survive, even with
the cart ruling, granted in his favor in 1998 and then retained
through an appeal won last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know the future at all,'' Martin said, ``but looking
back, I know that if I didn't have (the cart), I wouldn't be
playing right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Things have changed since the controversy exploded into the
lawsuit against the PGA Tour and a trial in Eugene, Ore. Two years
ago, many critics still thought that the PGA Tour was correct in
enforcing its rules about walking as an integral part of
competition.
</P>
<P>
   The tour still thinks that other players with back or knee
injuries, for example, would attempt to piggy-back off the Martin
ruling, through the Americans with Disabilities Act, and seek the
same cart assistance. But it is getting more difficult these days
to find anyone in agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Even Arnold Palmer, who testified on behalf of the tour, said,
``I've been opposed to golf carts on the regular and Senior tours
since the beginning, (but) it has nothing to do with Casey Martin.
If it works that Casey can play and use a golf cart, what's to
prevent anybody with a physical problem or any other ailment to
petition to use a cart? If I could use a cart, I might still be
able to play the regular tour. That might be a stretch, but I can
see a lot of things like that happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin seems to understand that opinion better now and knows
it's not a personal attack against the kid from Stanford with the
graceful swing. Although most people think that the tour would be
better off, after such a public-relations disaster, to drop its
suit, commissioner Tim Finchem says the tour must protect from a
potential avalanche of others also seeking a cart. Reportedly, Ed
Fiori already has requested a cart because of a back ailment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that has been a big crux of the issue,'' Martin said.
``I think that's why they've been hesitant to grant an exception,
because there are other exceptions out there with guys that are
hurting who aren't, quote, unquote, disabled like I am. I
acknowledge that, because I am protected under the law, what about
a guy with a really bad back? So, I recognize it as a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of players today who will tell you that if they
could play with a cart, they could compete better,'' Finchem said.
``And those players, based on the 9th circuit decision, could ask
for relief.''
</P>
<P>
   The cart controversy clouds any close examination of Martin's
wonderful game. At a recent press conference at the Honda Classic,
an insensitive photographer asked Martin ``to walk for him'' after
an interview. When he gets over the ball, the weakness in his right
leg is barely discernible. His length is as impressive as his
courage. He stands second in driving distance _ ironic for a man
behind a wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Without a cart at Sugarloaf, Martin could not get from the
parking lot to the first tee. He hasn't walked 18 holes in
competition since a Hooters Tour event in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long time,'' he said. ``I don't know if I could go
72 holes (anywhere), and I hope I don't have to find out.''
</P>
<P>
   Martins says he doesn't fear collapsing on a swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the fear of failing,'' Martin said. ``I don't want to let
people down.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
