<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0460 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-BUSINESS-FUTURE-COX     03-28 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-FUTURE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Business schools' obsolescence predicted
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a harsh message, but they took it well. Gary Hamel, a
Harvard business strategist and high-tech guru, told leaders of
Emory's Goizueta Business School that the days are numbered for
``old business'' approaches and traditional business colleges on
campuses.
</P>
<P>
   The ``branding'' of business training by schools like Emory and
Harvard will wane, he said, and give way to new interactive online
education taught by the best minds of the day, not fixed faculties.
And business schools had better brace for it.
</P>
<P>
   Hamel gave his thoughts last week in an hour-long video
conference between his office in California and a Goizueta
classroom filled with deans, faculty and an advisory panel of
business people.
</P>
<P>
   Hamel also said traditional businesses depending on incremental
growth had better come up with something new, including innovative
ways to let entrepreneurs within their walls receive money to put
new ideas to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``For too long we have lived in a time when profits were the
result of cost cutting ... mergers for efficiency,'' Hamel said.
``Well corporate liposuction (shedding fat to be profitable) can
get you only so far _ we're down to the heart and the lungs in some
industries.''
</P>
<P>
   The age of creating wealth from marketing, in the style of star
performers like Coca-Cola, has waned, Hamel said, and the new route
to wealth will be dominated by innovation and brand-new ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Smart business students already perceive this, he said, and that
is why ``the top 40 percent of Harvard graduates now go to
companies with 50 employees or less, and the second tier of
students go to the big names like Goldman Sachs and McKinsey &AMP;
Co.''
</P>
<P>
   Much to the frustration of strategic thinkers like Hamel, the
potential capital for big new enterprises is often locked up by big
companies that mostly work to defend the economic ground they
occupy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many spend their time as incumbents, defending themselves,
instead of spending on radical innovation,'' Hamel said.
</P>
<P>
   In his research and consultant work with Strategos, a Bay Area
firm, Hamel said he had encountered a few forward looking companies
that devised ways to reward ``game changing'' ideas with capital.
</P>
<P>
   Enron, the Texas energy company, is such a company, he said,
where a lower level employee was allowed to come up with a highly
profitable Internet business, the kind of enterprise that normally
senior executives would not embrace. Dell Computer, another Texas
firm, is another innovative exception.
</P>
<P>
   As for business schools, Hamel said the traditional system makes
feeble use of the top talent, and in the bargain fails to
disseminate the best ideas, best thinking and best strategies out
into the business world.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than put the best business teachers in front of 150
students in a lecture hall, he said, the most brilliant minds
should be on the Internet or at the service of other technologies
that reach millions, not hundreds.
</P>
<P>
   In that way, education would be enhanced, and leading educators
could be paid in keeping with their value.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soon students will boast not about a degree from Harvard, but
that they spent two years with the best business minds in the
world,'' Hamel said.
</P>
<P>
   Dean Thomas S. Robertson of Goizueta was an attentive listener
to Hamel. He said there was a lot of merit to Hamel's observations
but insisted that strong business schools like Emory's are making
accommodations to the new economy.
</P>
<P>
   Like Hamel, who is a Harvard faculty member and an international
consultant with many streams of income, some scholars at Goizueta
and other schools do much the same.
</P>
<P>
   Goizueta, which ranks 21 among the hundreds of business schools
around the nation, according to U.S. News &AMP; World Report, has
beefed up courses about electronic commerce and arranges video
conferences for students similar to the Hamel encounter.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson said he was especially proud of a split-screen video
conference some months ago that brought together students and
teachers from Goizueta and schools in London and Czechoslovakia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also have alliances with other schools to expose our
students to information beyond their own classrooms,'' Robertson
said.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that the marketplace will likely make electronic
learning and distance learning even more of a force in graduate
training, especially for busy executives in training for the
master's degree in business administration.
</P>
<P>
   Hamel and Robertson both said the competition for the business
education market, to put the best teachers together with students,
will likely cause a shakeout in academia.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dream,'' said Hamel, ``is to be to innovation what (W.
Edwards) Deming was to quality standards in industry, to redefine
it in very basic ways...''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
