r f BC-MANSION-DWELLERS-COX     03-28 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANSION-DWELLERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consultant is can-do man for well-to-do
 &HT;    By Jeffry Scott
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Adams wheels his white Jeep Cherokee into the driveway of a
client's massive Buckhead mansion. ``That's not a house,'' he
exults. ``It's a castle!''
</P>
<P>
   And it could darn sure use a vacuuming, or the grass mowed, or
the pool cleaned, or a billionaire's socks washed.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to make these people feel like they live in a
five-star hotel,'' says Adams, an exuberant, tireless 24-year-old
entrepreneur.
</P>
<P>
   If you're rich, especially if you're very rich, and live in
Buckhead in a house large enough to double as an airplane hangar,
there's a good chance you know Mike Adams. You may have called him
today. Maybe twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I manage my clients' lives so they can live the kind of
lifestyle their income allows,'' says Adams, headed up Tuxedo Road.
Another errand. Another client. Another crisis: leak in a pool
heating unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of people have heated pools up here,'' Adams says. ``I
had a client call me the other day and ask me if she knew who could
install a heated driveway.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams, who grew up in a middle-class Cobb County neighborhood,
introduced himself to the inner circle of Buckhead's super-rich six
years ago with a landscape design and at-home car detailing
business. Now he has become the major-domo of much of the
neighborhood's major dough.
</P>
<P>
   His company, MBA Management _ which is really just Adams and a
resource file of ``exclusive'' subcontractors _ provides domestic
staff for homes, lawn maintenance, chefs, wine stewards, even
helicopter pilots.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing I can't get for my clients with a phone
call,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Adams himself is no pauper. He's paid a monthly retainer by 24
full-time clients, and charges an hourly fee to work for another
100 or so Buckhead residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I make enough to own one of these homes?'' he asks. ``I
couldn't say. I'm as discreet about how much I make as I am about
how much my clients make.''
</P>
<P>
   He never leaves Buckhead, but he's almost constantly on the
move. ``This Jeep is only 4 months old,'' he says, ``and it's got
16,000 miles on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Marjorie Greenberg hired him after being impressed with his car
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must talk to him several times a week,'' Greenberg said.
``He makes my life so much easier. Just last week I called him
because I had lost some help. He had a new woman for me the next
day.''
</P>
<P>
   The maid, a Russian immigrant, didn't speak English. So Adams
hired a Russian translator to work with the maid.
</P>
<P>
   Today Adams has dealt with several crises. A client's car was in
the shop, so he picked it up for her.
</P>
<P>
   Another client called, worried about the barbecue being served
at an upcoming dinner for 15 guests. Would Adams be there to help
serve dinner?
</P>
<P>
   Sure. No problem.
</P>
<P>
   His cell phone rings. A client is worried about a pair of
$10,000 mahogany doors he's having installed. Can Adams check on
that?
</P>
<P>
   He makes two phone calls. The doors are on schedule. The phone
rings again. A client wonders if he can have some antiques picked
up in Fort Myers, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   He hangs up.
</P>
<P>
   ``YBYJ,'' he says. ```You Bet Your Job' every single decision
you make.''
</P>
<P>
   He picks up the phone, chats awhile with his delivery guy. ``I
want you to pick up some antiques for this lady,'' he says. ``I'll
pay top dollar.''
</P>
<P>
   The lady will get her antiques.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
