<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURKEY'S PRESIDENT WANTS ANOTHER TERM 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ After months of intense political
maneuvering, the Turkish Parliament is about to begin the delicate
work of deciding whether to re-elect President Suleyman Demirel.
</P>
<P>
   Demirel, 75, has been in public office for nearly all of his
adult life. He served a record seven terms as prime minister before
rising to the presidency in 1993. Most Turks cannot remember a time
when he was not a power broker.
</P>
<P>
   That longevity is both Demirel's greatest strength and his
greatest weakness. His supporters say he is a guarantee of
stability as Turkey enters a decade that is likely to bring
wrenching domestic and international challenges.
</P>
<P>
   But critics view him as a symbol of Turkey's political
immobility. They say that a country of 65 million people must have
more than one person qualified to be president.
</P>
<P>
   The Turkish presidency has little formal authority, but in the
last decade, as one government after another has succumbed to
political paralysis, it has become a key power center.
</P>
<P>
   The constitution stipulates that presidents be chosen by
Parliament and serve only a single seven-year term, so Demirel is
currently ineligible for re-election. He has been maneuvering to
arrange a constitutional amendment that would allow him to serve
for another five years.
</P>
<P>
   To win passage of the amendment, Demirel needs the votes of
two-thirds of the 550 members of Parliament. He and his backers are
using a combination of incentives and threats to win them. Intense
political horse trading is expected before the first vote
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   If Demirel wins approval of his amendment, he will almost
certainly be re-elected. If he fails, a host of candidates will
probably emerge.
</P>
<P>
   This could threaten the stability of Prime Minister Bulent
Ecevit's government, which is based on an uneasy coalition between
his left-oriented party and another that is far-rightist. If the
presidency suddenly comes up for grabs, the two parties would
almost certainly offer opposing candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Asked in an interview what he would do if he is not re-elected,
Demirel replied: ``I've never been interested in taking care of
flowers or feeding chickens. I'll find something to do. Nobody
should worry about that.''
</P>
<P>
   That comment was widely interpreted as a declaration that
Demirel is ready to re-enter party politics, a move that could
transform the political landscape and threaten the careers of some
current party leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Some politicians have urged that Turkish voters, rather than
Parliament, be given the power to choose their president, but a
proposal to do that failed to win approval in a parliamentary
committee earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The military has clearly opted for Demirel's re-election,''
wrote a news commentator, Etyen Mahcupyan, in a recent analysis.
``This is because it has been Demirel's function to ensure that
civilian politics stays within the boundaries drawn up by the
military, and to make that seem like a normal state of affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Mahcupyan said Western powers favor Demirel because they see him
as ``the ideal solution to keep Turkey on the right track while
bridling any process of change,'' and that business groups, labor
unions and private citizens ``are not really demanding
democratization and principled politics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the circumstances, is there a better candidate than
Demirel?'' he asked. ``We are him, and he is us. He personifies
certain aspects of Turkish society.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
