<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0485 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     03-28 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: METS ENJOYING REGULAR FOLKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The thought of two hours on the team bus sent shivers up
the backbones of many of the Mets. They had endured enough of that
particular torture in the minor leagues.
</P>
<P>
   So they did what any sensible person would do: they took public
transportation. John Rocker, the avowed enemy of New York's No. 7
elevated line, might hate the concept, but that's what at least 10
wise Mets did Monday evening. They rode with the people.
</P>
<P>
   After their victory over the Seibu Lions in the distant suburb
of Tokorozawa, one cluster of Mets, along with a few family
members, followed the crowd to the station of the Seibu Ikebukuro
Line, heading back toward Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ran into a guy in a Mets jacket that Benny had met before
the game,'' Rick Reed said. ``He took us right to our hotel. We'd
still be on the train if he hadn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe they would have done just fine on their own, since this
trip is bringing out the adventurous world traveler in a number of
the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   As it happened, Benny Agbayani, Kurt Abbott, Darryl Hamilton and
Turk Wendell all rode the train, switched to the subway at
Ikebukuro, and lived to tell the tale.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets were recounting their adventures in Tokyo leading up to
the opening of the regular season on Wednesday night in Tokyo,
which corresponded to 5:05 a.m. Eastern time Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night's 9-5 loss to the Tokyo Yomiuri Giants did not
dampen the Mets' spirits. They are having a great time in Tokyo,
which they find far more hospitable and far less daunting than they
might have anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   On their train ride, for example, they had a number of friendly
fans keeping an eye on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sort of stood out,'' Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Piazza had more of a horde following him. He and four
teammates _ John Franco, Melvin Mora, Edgardo Alfonzo and Todd
Pratt _ all declined a return bus ride through the narrow two-lane
roads of the region. They, too, opted for the train.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a huge crowd in our car,'' said Piazza, modestly
skipping over the fact that the fans are fascinated by his long
hair, large frame and sizzling line drives.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a fascination with Americans,'' Piazza said, ``but we
moved to another car, and it was almost empty. It was easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Mets have ventured out of the team hotel, a
luxurious hilltop fortress that could encourage them to stay
inside. Instead, they have been out and about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am thoroughly enjoying my time here,'' said Hamilton, who is
also cool in his own country.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton came to the Mets in a trade last season and decided he
would live in the belly of the beast, Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just thinking this afternoon that I probably would never
have a chance to visit Tokyo except for baseball,'' Hamilton said.
``Sure, the flight is long _ but so what?''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton is willing to play ambassador, on the theory that
``baseball is an international sport, we can show the world what we
do. This is no offense to the Japanese, but Major League Baseball
is the standard. It's a treat to play games that are more than a
goodwill tour.''
</P>
<P>
   And he particularly likes being an ambassador if it takes him to
a world of shops and sights sprawling below him. His wife,
Ursaline, is enjoying it, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we finally had sushi,'' he said. ``Been here three days
and finally got to it. It was good.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed has been eating in the hotel, but he did get to a Buddhist
temple and went on a shopping expedition on Tuesday. He said:
``Thirty million people in the area as opposed to 8 million in New
York. It's amazing how clean it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Agbayani, who came here with a Hawaiian high school all-star
team in 1989, is seeing Tokyo on a major league salary and an
adult's curiosity this time: ``Kobe steak and sushi and lots of
rice. We have the same Japanese rice in Hawaii.''
</P>
<P>
   Ballplayers love to shop on their free afternoons in the States,
and many of them found their way to the sprawling electronics
district _ blocks and blocks of stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bought a bunch of CD's and a new Diskman,'' Piazza said with a
smile that indicated he just might have cut a swath through a few
shops.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Phillips and Omar Minaya, the general manager and
assistant general manager, visited a pearl shop recommended by
Bobby Valentine, who managed the Chiba Lotte team here in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a wall of fame of some of the people who've been in
there,'' Phillips said. ``Henry Kissinger. Brooke Shields.''
</P>
<P>
   Together? Phillips hated to ruin a good story, but no.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Mets had their own little tales of expeditions
outside the hotel. The ones who were grumping have kept it to
themselves, once they saw how hospitable the hosts have been, and
by extension, the entire nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing how many people speak English, and how helpful
they are,'' Hamilton said.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, the trains and subways and stations all have
English marking as well as Japanese. But the players wouldn't have
known that if they hadn't had the courage _ or the desperation _ to
stay out of the team bus. Even major leaguers are allowed to get
enthusiastic about a new experience, once in a great while.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
