<HEADLINE>
GOLDMAN, SACHS RECOMMENDATION PUSHES BONDS HIGHER
</HEADLINE>
  (mg) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bond prices were mostly higher on Tuesday amid a drop
in the main stock market gauges, which caused some investors to
seek shelter in fixed-income securities.
</P>
<P>
   The shift out of stocks came after Abby Joseph Cohen, the chief
investment strategist at Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., recommended that her
firm's clients reduce their allocation of stocks to 65 percent from
70 percent, with the 5 percent going into cash. She also
recommended switching from a 5 percent allocation in long-term
bonds to 5 percent in short-term Treasury bonds.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, shorter-maturity paper led the market higher. The
price of the two-year note rose 2/32, to 99 27/32, while its yield,
which moves in the opposite direction of the price, dropped to 6.58
percent from 6.62 percent on Monday. The 30-year bond lagged
behind, gaining only 1/32, to 103 25/32. Its yield was unchanged at
5.98 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year bond also was held back by OPEC's failure to agree
on increases in oil production.
</P>
<P>
   Treasuries took some strength from Monday's consumer confidence
data from the Conference Board, whose index fell for the second
consecutive month after reaching a record in January. The index
that measures consumer expectations for the next six months also
dropped, to its lowest level since October, after the most recent
increase by the Federal Reserve Board in short-term interest rates,
the fifth since June.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Chan, managing director and chief economist at Banc One
Investment Advisers in Columbus, Ohio, said, ``Going into this
confidence report, credit market investors painfully realized that
the Fed is facing an economy that just doesn't seem to want to slow
down despite the cumulative increase of 125 basis points in the
federal funds rate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Therefore, in this environment, there is no doubt that many
investors have begun questioning whether the Fed is falling behind
in its fight against potential inflationary forces,'' Chan said.
</P>
<P>
   Although he disagrees with that assessment, Chan said, it cannot
be fully erased from investors' minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result,'' he said, ``the dip in the confidence,
especially in the more important expectations component, had to
offer great relief to those that have spent countless hours
worrying about the growth pace last quarter and what they can
expect to learn in the first quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Chan said Cohen's announcement was a breath of fresh air for the
credit market, where most investors took the news as an indication
that the bond market might face less competition from the equity
market.
</P>
<P>
   Investors in the longer maturities did not celebrate initially
because they viewed Cohen's comments as being more supportive of
the shorter maturities. However, they did embrace her statements as
the day wore on.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pugliese, senior vice president and director of the
fixed-income department at the J.W. Genesis Financial Corp. in Boca
Raton, Fla., said all the markets were skittish, making hedging
ineffective and forcing many investors to sit on positions longer
because of the lack of liquidity.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, the Treasury supply is back in force this week, and
the market is not expected to have much trouble digesting
everything. The government sold $35 billion in 21-day
cash-management bills yesterday and will offer $30 billion in
19-day bills today along with $12 billion of two-year notes. Cash
management bills are used to meet the government's short-term cash
needs outside the regular schedule of bills notes and bonds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
