<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0489 &Cx1f; tta-z
u e BC-LINCOLN-CENTER-RESIGN     03-28 1417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LINCOLN-CENTER-RESIGN-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER 17 YEARS, NATHAN LEVENTHAL PLANS TO LEAVE IN DECEMBER
</HEADLINE>
 (mg) 
By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As the Lincoln Center's third summer arts festival
ended in July 1998, Nathan Leventhal, the center's president, made
no secret of his profound relief.
</P>
<P>
   He announced that the performances, ranging from a multimedia
``Faust'' to a production of ``Twelfth Night'' featuring Helen
Hunt, had exceeded box office projections.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am one happy guy,'' he said. ``I lost 10 years off my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   The personal toll exacted by such ventures and myriad other
tensions seem to be part of the reason that Leventhal announced on
Monday that he would step down in December after nearly 17 years of
running the center's daily operations. He said he was looking
forward to a more relaxed life.
</P>
<P>
   Although Leventhal can't take complete credit for all of the
innovations over the last 17 years, arts professionals say that he
was instrumental in expanding Lincoln Center's fare.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made Lincoln Center function 365 days a year,'' said Paul
B. Guenther, chairman of the New York Philharmonic. ``Under his
presidency Lincoln Center has become an even more vital part of the
arts community in New York City.''
</P>
<P>
   Such efforts were not always appreciated by the center's 11
constituent groups, which include not only the Philharmonic but the
Metropolitan Opera and the New York City Ballet. Each is
represented on the board.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did some resist Leventhal's introduction of
non-traditional programming, but some of the constituent groups
resented that Lincoln Center played an expanding role as a producer
rather than remaining merely a landlord.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lincoln Center continues to emphasize classical
programming, during Leventhal's tenure it has branched out to
include jazz, American popular song and ballroom dancing on the
plaza. These innovations, which contribute to more than 350
performances a year, have caused growing pains as constituents
watched the additions pilfer some of their fund-raising sources,
talent pools and audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now not only is Lincoln Center Inc. a parent and guardian of
its constituents, but also a competitor,'' said Martin J.
Oppenheimer, the board chairman of the City Center of Music and
Drama, the parent organization that oversees the City Opera and
City Ballet. ``The constituents view Lincoln Center as a sponsor,
as a supporter. Nat has been vigorous in promoting Lincoln Center
as a producer.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Clashes have occurred between the president and constituents _
mainly Joseph Volpe, general manager of the Metropolitan Opera _
but generally Leventhal seems to have earned respect, however
grudging, from his colleagues. Even Volpe had only diplomatic words
about Leventhal: ``He's going to miss me. Who else is going to be
around to heckle him?''
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging these tensions, board members said that
broadening the definition of Lincoln Center productions was a
matter of financial survival, given that dark theaters drain
coffers. ``Don't forget, the health of Lincoln Center is very
important to all the constituents,'' Guenther said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Beverly Sills, the center's chair, said the role of Lincoln
Center Inc. is not what it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``When this place was originally conceived it was as a parental
umbrella,'' she said. ``Until we realized we couldn't fill the
theaters for 52 weeks a year. It took Lincoln Center to help fill
those houses.''
</P>
<P>
   When Leventhal arrived in March 1984 from his post as deputy
mayor for operations under Edward I. Koch, the auditoriums of what
are now Avery Fisher Hall, the New York State Theater and the
Metropolitan Opera were dark in the summer. Now during July and
August, Lincoln Center is hopping with outdoor dancing _ from swing
to reggae _ and indoor programs. ``On any given night, you can see
10,000 people on the plaza,'' Sills said.
</P>
<P>
   Leventhal said he was most proud of ``the evolution of Lincoln
Center into an innovative, creative force.'' That emphasis, he
said, grew from sitting on grant panels of the National Endowment
for the Arts, where he was derided by fellow panelists for not
having more venturesome programming.
</P>
<P>
   This was particularly troubling because Lincoln Center is looked
to as one of the world's premier arts institutions. Leventhal
noted, for example, that since making jazz part of the regular
Lincoln Center repertory, other arts organizations have followed.
</P>
<P>
   Thus while preserving Lincoln Center's core classical repertory,
Leventhal has made program development a top priority. Jazz at
Lincoln Center and the new American Songbook series of concerts
featuring great American composers have expanded the center's
reach. The Lincoln Center Festival showcases the global
avant-garde. Even the 34-year-old Great Performers series, which
presents internationally renowned classical artists and orchestras,
now offers unorthodox events under the title ``New Visions.''
</P>
<P>
   The PBS broadcast ``Live From Lincoln Center'' has also begun to
include more experimental works. Last March the broadcasts included
the New York City Opera's ``Lizzie Borden,'' a departure from the
galas that dominated the program's previous seasons.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But Leventhal has had to walk a fine line between taking
artistic risks to attract younger, more diverse audiences and
continuing to satisfy core supporters. In March 1999, Lincoln
Center seemed to go out on an artistic limb in deciding to present
a 20-hour production of the classic Chinese opera ``Peony
Pavilion'' similar to the one canceled the previous summer after
officials in Shanghai refused to allow the performers to leave
China.``The forces that tend to prevent freedom of expression can't
win,'' Mr. Leventhal said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Yet seven months later Lincoln Center declined to sign a letter
from some of New York's most prestigious cultural institutions
criticizing Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani for threatening to evict the
Brooklyn Museum of Art from a city-owned facility for mounting the
cutting-edge ``Sensation'' exhibition, which the mayor had
lambasted.
</P>
<P>
   The Brooklyn Museum incident may have been an example of
Leventhal's political sensitivities, which his admirers say are
important to the president's position and which were honed during
years in government. In addition to serving as a deputy mayor under
Koch, he was chief of staff to Mayor John V. Lindsay and served as
chief counsel to the United States Senate Subcommittee on
Administrative Practice and Procedure, led by Senator Edward M.
Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 Leventhal endorsed Giuliani for mayor against Ruth W.
Messinger, which was a surprise given his work in Democratic
administrations and his former position as the leader of mayoral
transition team of David N. Dinkins in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has proven to be a friend of Lincoln Center. In 1997
the mayor said he would veto the Metropolitan Transportation
Authority's plan to name a developer for Columbus Circle unless a
theater tied to Lincoln Center was included as part of the
high-rise tower planned for the intersection.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Leventhal noted that he had fostered more collaboration between
Lincoln Center constituents, for example, during the Mozart
Bicentennial when from January 1991 to August 1992, the center
gradually performed all of the composer's work. ``We've seen more
and more cross-fertilization,'' Leventhal said. ``There's the sense
that this is much more of a campus.''
</P>
<P>
   Cross-fertilization has had its casualties, however. Mostly
Mozart, for example, which is approaching its 34th season, has been
scaled back to make way for the Lincoln Center Festival. Some
reviewers criticized the Mozart Bicentennial as an unsuccessful
attempt to spread the composer's wealth among the Lincoln Center
constituents and visiting performers.
</P>
<P>
   Leventhal and Sills suggested that Lincoln Center's planned $1.5
billion renovation, which is expected to take about 10 years,
wouldfurther unite the constituents in that upgrading the buildings
benefits everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Leventhal's departure just as Lincoln Center is about to embark
on major reconstruction makes some board members nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be tough filling his shoes,'' said Oppenheimer,
the board member. ``We have an extraordinarily difficult
fund-raising operation ahead of us.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
