<SLUG> BC-ATT-IPO-1STLD-WRITETHRU-500-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IPO FOR AT&AMP;T  ` TRACKING STOCK ' MAY SET U.S. RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
 (SUBS to fix time elements  from `yesterday` to `Tuesday')(hm/mp) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most things about AT&AMP;T are big, so perhaps it is fitting that
the upcoming initial public offering of shares meant to track
AT&AMP;T's wireless communications unit is set to be the biggest U.S.
IPO yet.
</P>
<P>
   In a filing Tuesday with the Securities and Exchange Commission,
the AT&AMP;T Corp. said it intended to raise up to $13.2 billion in the
offering. That would be more than double the record $5.5 billion
raised by United Parcel Service Inc. when it first offered shares
to the public last November. At a minimum, AT&AMP;T intends to raise
$9.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Chagrined that investors were not giving AT&AMP;T full financial
credit for the value of the company's fast-growing wireless unit,
AT&AMP;T said last year that it would issue a separately traded
``tracking stock'' meant to represent its wireless operation.
Tracking stocks are newly popular financial instruments that are
meant to represent, or track, a particular line of business within
a corporation. Unlike common shares, however, tracking stocks do
not represent actual ownership of a piece of that company.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T declined to say when the initial stock offering wwould be
held. But next week, the wireless unit's senior management, led by
John D. Zeglis, AT&AMP;T's president, is set to begin a ``road show''
to present the offering to institutional investors. Since people
close to the company said the road show is to last about three
weeks, the offering will probably take place in late April.
</P>
<P>
   In the SEC filing, AT&AMP;T estimated that the tracking shares would
be offered at between $26 and $32 each. The company intends to sell
360 million shares, representing 15.6 percent of the wireless
operation, but the company said that figure could increase to 414
million shares, representing 17.5 percent of the unit.
</P>
<P>
   If the shares are sold at $32 each, the wireless unit will have
an initial market value of about $74 billion. That would be the
largest value for a newly public U.S. company, beating UPS' $60.2
billion initial valuation, according to Comm-Scan, a financial
research firm. At $26 per share, the offering would give the
wireless unit a market value of $60 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Of the billions of dollars to be raised, most will go to the
wireless unit, presumably to underwrite the building of new
communications networks and the expansion of old ones. Some of the
money, however, will go to AT&AMP;T, the parent company.
</P>
<P>
   After the offering, AT&AMP;T will retain between 82.5 percent and
84.4 percent of the wireless tracking stock. AT&AMP;T said Tuesday that
some of that stake would be distributed to owners of AT&AMP;T's common
shares, but would not say how much. The company said it was
considering allowing holders of AT&AMP;T's common stock to exchange
those shares outright for wireless tracking shares, and said it may
also sell more of the tracking stock to the public in a later
offering.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-00 1948EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000328.0252 </DOCNO>
