u e BC-VANGOGH-DETROIT-NYT &LR;      03-28 1200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VANGOGH-DETROIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DETROIT MUSEUM ON THE REBOUND WITH VAN GOGH  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Great museums acquire their reputations not just
through the size and quality of their collections but through the
special exhibitions they organize, borrowing works from around the
world. Even fairly small museums have won fame by wheedling prized
artworks from scattered institutions and bringing them together
briefly for the world to see.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the Detroit Institute of Arts, the fifth-largest
art museum in the nation in terms of floor space and the largest
west of the Appalachians, has drifted into obscurity because
financial troubles prevented it from initiating any major
exhibitions for the last 14 years. But a new management structure
and a big infusion of cash from private donors have brought the
museum back from the brink of closing, allowing it to organize a
major exhibition of paintings and drawings by van Gogh that opened
on March 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``Van Gogh: Face to Face'' has been an instant hit. More than a
third of the tickets have been sold for the show, which runs
through June 4 before moving to the Museum of Fine Arts, Boston and
then the Philadelphia Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   The institute has temporarily stopped closing on Mondays and
Tuesdays, as visitors from southeastern Michigan and a sprinkling
of people from elsewhere cause traffic jams and parking shortages
in the once-desolate cultural quarter of the city.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with its status as a privately managed but city-owned
institution in the largest American city with a black majority, the
museum has tried to attract a racially diverse audience. It has
advertised heavily in publications catering to African-Americans
and has advertised mostly on billboards in the city rather than the
suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   William Daniels, a retired teacher and Detroit resident, was
surprised and pleased by the heavy turnout on a recent day. ``I
haven't seen it this crowded, the lines were terrific,'' he said,
sitting on a bench after seeing the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Face to Face'' is being praised by scholars too. Though there
have been many van Gogh exhibitions in the last 20 years, the
Detroit show is the first to focus on the painter's development as
a portrait artist.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gogh's portraits have been analyzed in books, but the
current exhibition brings them together for ready comparison, a
first, according to Bogomila Welsh-Ovcharov, a professor of fine
art at the University of Toronto who has written six books on van
Gogh and was not involved in organizing the exhibition. ``What is
more contributory and interesting for scholars and connoisseurs is
to see them in a new context,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   With 31 drawings and 36 paintings, the exhibition traces van
Gogh's rapid development in capturing faces on canvas. The earliest
drawings demonstrate how van Gogh, a disillusioned theology student
literally studying how-to books on becoming an artist, produced
works of a style and vision that went far beyond the instructions
in the manuals. The later paintings show his evolution from
realistic representations of the faces of the poor to
interpretations of his face and those of friends in his final
years, in France.
</P>
<P>
   So strict were the curators of the Detroit, Boston and
Philadelphia museums about keeping the emphasis on portraiture that
they did not ask to borrow one of van Gogh's ``The Potato Eaters,''
because it depicts five peasants instead of just one and because it
presents an entire scene.
</P>
<P>
   George S. Keyes, the Elizabeth and Allan Shelden Curator of
European Painting at the museum, said that the inspiration for the
exhibition had come after Josephine Ford, a granddaughter of Henry
Ford, donated a famous van Gogh portrait of a postman, Joseph
Roulin, to the museum in late 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1997 the museum began organizing an exhibition of van
Gogh's paintings of the Roulin family, then broadened its scope to
the gamut of the artist's portraiture after discussions with the
Philadelphia and Boston museums, Keyes said.
</P>
<P>
   The institute only recently emerged from near financial
disaster. The museum has long had an excellent collection and a
sprawling building because of big donations by the Ford family and
other auto barons, but it never had much of an endowment or
received many donations for operations and maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   It struggled through the hard times of Detroit and American
automakers in the 1970s and '80s. Its last major exhibition, in
1986, featured the work of Diego Rivera, a Mexican muralist who
painted one of his finest works in the huge marble central court of
the museum in 1932.
</P>
<P>
   The institution's management spent the late '80s planning an
ambitious renovation and expansion of the buildings, only to be
devastated in 1991 when Gov. John Engler, a Republican trying to
balance Michigan's budget, cut almost all state aid to the museum.
A third of the museum's $25 million annual budget disappeared,
forcing a reduction in museum hours to 12{ a week from 48, and the
elimination of many educational programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were exhibitions planned that had to go right into the
trash can because staying alive became the first order of
business,'' said Samuel Sachs II, the museum's director from 1985
to 1997 and now the director of the Frick Collection in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The museum had trouble attracting donations for its operating
budget partly because it was city-owned and staffed mainly by civil
servants. After a nasty two-year political battle that ended in
early 1998, daily management of the museum was transferred to its
private donors, who live mostly in the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   The donors have given lavishly since then: a fund-raising
campaign that began 11 months ago has brought in $93 million. The
state government, flush again from the strong economy, has offered
another $40 million if further matching contributions can be
raised. An ambitious five-year renovation of the museum's main
building and its two annexes will begin after the van Gogh
exhibition closes, although the museum will remain open during
construction.
</P>
<P>
   The rejuvenation of the auto industry has also helped the museum
raise money. DaimlerChrysler, for instance, is sponsoring the van
Gogh exhibition. Eager to allay local worries about foreign control
and to please the many German managers assigned to what some of
them perceive as a Midwestern cultural backwater, DaimlerChrysler
says it has increased by 20 percent the already substantial
donations that Chrysler had been making to the arts in southeastern
Michigan before it was purchased by Daimler-Benz in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Welsh-Ovcharov, the van Gogh expert, said that the Detroit
museum's choice of van Gogh for its return to presenting
world-class exhibitions showed the strength of its financial
revival. Impressionist paintings and Post Impressionist works like
those by van Gogh have become so valuable that the insurance and
other costs of exhibiting them exceed the resources of most
institutions, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a major coup from their point of view,'' she said. ``Van
Goghs are very difficult because of the financial budget
required.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-00 1949EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
