<HEADLINE>
IN HISTORICAL TERMS, MARGIN DEBT IS NOT OUT OF LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Alan Greenspan is worried about a stock market bubble, say
those looking for easy answers, the Federal Reserve chairman should
push for tighter margin requirements instead of higher interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
   This view has emerged as a form of conventional wisdom in the
wake of reports that the use of credit to finance stock purchases
has been rising substantially over the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Concern about borrowing to speculate in the stock market traces
its history to the 1929 crash, which was followed by numerous bank
failures and a Great Depression that lasted on and off for a
decade. Folklore holds that many banks failed because they had lent
excessively to finance market speculators. Subsequent research
showed this wasn't true, but the myth already had become embedded
in the national psyche.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, when headlines recently heralded dramatic increases in
margin debt, many on Main Street figured the Fed could let the air
out of Wall Street's bubble by further restricting the amount of
debt allowed to finance stock purchases. Generally speaking,
regulations currently limit borrowing to 50 percent of the market
value of the assets in the account.
</P>
<P>
   This way, the thinking goes, speculation can be discouraged
without risking a recession. The problem with such thinking,
however, is that margin debt isn't excessive in the historical
context, and certainly nowhere near its level preceding the 1929
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   A Federal Reserve study done in the mid-1980s estimates that
margin debt in 1929 was about 10 percent of the market value of all
stocks. Back then this form of debt was referred to as ``broker's
loans'' or ``securities credit.'' The study, which dealt with the
New York Stock Exchange because that pretty much was the market in
those days, showed margin debt fairly steady in the 8 percent to 9
percent range throughout the 1920s. Some old-timers claimed it
spiked at 15 percent before the crash, but Fed researchers couldn't
confirm these memories.
</P>
<P>
   After the crash, margin debt collapsed from 10 percent to about
1 percent of market value and has since fluctuated mostly between 1
percent and 2 percent of total stock market value.
</P>
<P>
   So, you ask, how big a factor is margin debt now? The most
recent numbers show it to be 1.5 percent of the total value of the
entire U.S. stock market. Gerald D. Cohen, senior economist with
Merrill Lynch, recently ran some numbers showing that during the
'90s, margin debt has ranged from about 1 percent to 1.5 percent,
or precisely in keeping with post-crash historical norms.
</P>
<P>
   None of this is to say the stock market isn't frothy. Nor is it
to defend the Fed's relentless tightening of the monetary screws to
slow the economy, fight inflation or discourage ``irrational
exuberance'' in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, it's to point out that margin debt doesn't seem a
problem. This form of debt may be rising proportionately faster
than the value of the market. It also may be historically high as a
percentage of U.S. household income. Even so, it remains well
within the post-1929 range, and thus indicates nothing untoward, in
any direction.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed is catching a lot of flak, some of it deserved. Its
disinclination to fiddle with margin requirements, however, isn't a
valid concern.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
