<SLUG> BC-BUSH-EDUCATION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush unveils $5 billion education proposal
 &HT;    By Jena Heath
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RESTON, VA. _ Gov. George W. Bush declared illiteracy a
``national emergency'' Tuesday and unveiled a $5 billion plan to
combat it.
</P>
<P>
   He also won the endorsement of former GOP rival and millionaire
publisher Steve Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also telephoned vanquished presidential rival John McCain
from his car in Virginia. An aide to McCain, who declined to be
identified by name, said the two talked briefly about the ``reform
agenda'' that helped fuel the Arizona senator's brief rise in the
primaries.
</P>
<P>
   They also talked about getting together, but set no date.
</P>
<P>
   Before an audience at Sallie Mae, a national provider of
federally guaranteed student loans based in suburban Washington,
Bush rolled out his new proposal, called ``Reading First.'' The
reading initiative is the latest salvo in Bush's battle with Vice
President Al Gore over how to improve the nation's schools _ an
issue Democrats have long dominated and Republicans want to own.
</P>
<P>
   ``This plan is different,'' Bush said. ``It's different from my
opponent. It's different from the administration. And it's
different from those who would say there is no federal role for
education, different from those who would throw money into schools
without reforming them, from those who would argue against any
federal money or responsibility at all. ... I won't close down the
Department of Education, but I will transform it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has called for expanding Head Start, spending $50 billion
over a decade to provide universal preschool, and spending more
than $400 million annually to train elementary school teachers.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign also touted a $260 million administration grant
program designed to improve reading and took aim at Bush's
proposed, five-year $483 billion tax cut proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush is playing follow the leader,'' said Gore campaign
spokesman Doug Hattaway. ``This goal was set by the administration
back in 1996. Bush's real agenda is an enormous tax cut for the
rich that won't leave any money to invest in education unless he
dips into the Social Security surplus or goes back to deficit
spending.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's proposal is based on the Texas Reading Initiative, now
being implemented, that calls for students to read at or better
than grade level by third grade.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan announced Tuesday, $5 million annually would go
to assess reading skills in children from kindergarten to first
grade. Another $90 million would be used to train teachers of
kindergarten and first grade. The largest amount _ $900 million
annually _ would pay for tutoring, after-school and summer school
programs for the approximately 900,000 children Bush advisors
estimate would need reading help.
</P>
<P>
   States and school districts would have to apply for the money
and demonstrate that they had used, ``certain standards based on
scientific research,'' to assess reading skills and fix problems.
</P>
<P>
   So eager is Bush to capture the education mantle that he invoked
the spirit of Albert Shanker, former leader of the American
Federation of Teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The late Albert Shanker used to tell the story of visiting a
class of disadvantaged students stuck in the rut of easy work and
low expectations,'' Bush said. ``He asked them, `What should we ask
you students to read?' After a pause one student raised his hand,
and said, `Mr. Shanker, what do the smart kids read?'''
</P>
<P>
   Bush repeated his call to consolidate some 60 federal education
programs into block grants, annual testing of students in grades 3
through 8 and allowing low-income parents with children in
consistently underperforming schools to use public money to pay for
private education.
</P>
<P>
   Jena Heath can be reached at jenah(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
