<SLUG> BC-WACO-RENO29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RENO SAID TO TESTIFY THAT AGENTS EXCEEDED AUTHORITY AT WACO
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno testified Tuesday that
</P>
<P>
   she had not authorized some actions taken by FBI agents during
the 1993 assault on the Branch Davidian compound near Waco, Texas,
an attorney for the sect said.
</P>
<P>
   Reno acknowledged in two hours of questioning that federal
agents had used military-issue incendiary tear gas canisters and
``flash-bang'' grenades without her approval, said Michael Caddell,
the leading lawyer in a wrongful-death lawsuit against the
government.
</P>
<P>
   Reno also said she had not authorized the FBI to demolish the
compound, and held to her past position that agents sent in tanks
only to inject tear gas, Caddell said.
</P>
<P>
   The private questioning of the attorney general all but wraps up
the pre-trial interviewing by the plaintiffs, who are charging that
FBI officials on the scene overstepped their authority during the
assault on the compound on April 19, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   About 80 Davidian adults and children were found dead after the
wooden structure caught fire and was quickly consumed by the
flames. The government says that sect members set the fire after
the assault began.
</P>
<P>
   Caddell said in an interview late Tuesday that the assault was
carried on under two separate and contradictory assumptions, one
held by senior authorities in Washington and another by the
on-scene commanders, Jeffrey Jamar and Richard Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jamar and Rogers testified that they believed they had implied
authority to demolish the building that morning if they chose to do
so, implied authority to use military tear gas rounds that morning
if they thought it was appropriate, that they had implied authority
to use flash-bangs,'' Caddell said.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the top FBI leadership and Reno said that, absent
an emergency, ``there was no authority or approval'' for any of
these actions during the assault of the Davidian compound, the
lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Caddell said he had learned little in questioning Reno. ``I
didn't expect to learn anything from her,'' he said. ``Frankly, in
her position she doesn't know very much and I think she's
politically adept at dodging questions, at not giving a straight
answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, at a news conference outside the Justice Department
where he appeared in blue jeans, a shirt without tie, a jacket and
cowboy boots, Caddell criticized Reno for a lack of candor,
especially on the demolition of the building.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department spokesman Myron Marlin disputed that
characterization.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was forthcoming,'' he said. ``She was candid, and her
comments were consistent with her past testimony. Obviously we
would disagree with what her plaintiff's attorneys say.''
</P>
<P>
   Caddell said that he would release a transcript and videotape of
the Reno deposition at a later date.
</P>
<P>
   One area where the Reno testimony could make a difference to his
case was on the lack of a plan to fight a potential fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``She acknowledged that no one ever told her'' that the FBI
operations included a written plan excluding the use of
firefighters, Caddell said. ``And she was never told that if the
local fire departments came out at the scene that they would be
held at the gate'' of the complex, known as Mount Carmel, out of
concern that the Davidians might shoot at the fire fighters, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Caddell said that the attorney general acknowledged that she had
not been aware of any discussions about fire fighters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should have had armored fire-fighting equipment there,''
Caddell said. ``They spent $6 million on the operations at Mount
Carmel on tanks and helicopters and tear gas and grenade launchers
and machine guns. And they didn't spend a penny on fire fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities have said most of the victims died either in
the fire and or from shots fired by fellow cult members. The trial
is set for mid May in federal district court in Waco.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
