<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE SUCCESSES RAISE HOPES FOR EVENTUAL TRUE WORLD SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ After the New York Mets lost to the Tokyo Yomiuri
Giants, 9-5, on Tuesday night, Manager Bobby Valentine walked to
home plate and bowed deeply toward the Giants' dugout. Valentine,
who managed the Chiba Lotte Marines in 1995, knows the importance
of a respectful gesture in the Japanese culture.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants wound up winning both exhibition games against the
so-called major leaguers, having beaten the Chicago Cubs, 6-0, on
Monday night. Valentine felt this unofficial little series was just
a start toward a competition that would produce ``a true world
champion, not just an American champion.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, that is, 5:05 Wednesday morning in New York,
two major league teams will play official league games outside
North America. The Mets and the Cubs will play here again Thursday
night before heading home.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants whacked 12 hits off four pitchers who will be going
to the Mets' farm team in Norfolk as soon as the club returns to
the United States on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Pulsipher, who was officially optioned to Norfolk earlier
in the day, was whacked for five runs in four innings, including a
two-run homer by Domingo Martinez, a 32-year-old first baseman from
the Dominican Republic, who played with Toronto in 1992 and '93.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh inning, Yoshinobu Takahashi belted a two-run
homer off Bobby M. Jones, the left-hander who was along for the
ride so the Mets would not chew up their pitching staff before the
official season opens. The Mets, however, did not make excuses
about losing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's kind of anxious to go,'' Mike Piazza said. ``Every
year brings a curiosity. You want to find the intangibles, find the
`wa,''' he added with a smile, referring to the Japanese word for
``spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants, who open their Central League season against the
Hiroshima Carp at home Friday night, did not claim to be world
champions, based on the two exhibition games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before this series, I felt the major leaguers were more
powerful and speedy,'' said Masahiro Kawai, the 35-year-old
shortstop. ``I have the same impression now. To keep up with them,
we have to improve.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
