<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Wednesday, March 29, and thereafter. If you have any questions,
please call Bob Schenet on the national-foreign desk at (206)
448-8037.
</P>
<P>
   FOSTER-LAWSUIT (Seattle) _ An unprecedented class action lawsuit
has been launched alleging that Washington state inflicted needless
suffering on thousands of foster children by routinely subjecting
them to repeated moves while failing to meet their emotional and
physical needs. Experts say if succesful, the case could not only
force the overhaul of the state's foster-care system, but set a
precedent for improved standards nation-wide.
</P>
<P>
   By Ruth Teichroeb. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN (Seattle) _ On Gary Payton. In a sporting
landscape that has seen superstars such as Shawn Kemp, Randy
Johnson and, biggest of them all, Ken Griffey Jr. leave Seattle,
could the volatile point guard be next? It's a question the Sonics
will be forced to ask themselves.
</P>
<P>
   By Laura Vecsey. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
