A0500 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-FLAG-VETERANS-HNS &LR;      03-28 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAG-VETERANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AMERICAN LEGIONNAIRES LOBBY LAWMAKERS FOR FLAG AMENDMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ More than 1,000 American Legion members swarmed
Capitol Hill Tuesday hoping to persuade a few wavering senators to
support a proposed constitutional amendment that would make
desecrating the U.S. flag illegal. A Senate vote is expected
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The veterans, here for their annual Washington conference of the
American Legion, buttonholed lawmakers in their offices or in
hallways. Several Legion members escorted Miss America, Heather
Renee French, whose father is a disabled Vietnam veteran, to
senators' offices.
</P>
<P>
   But many Legionnaires conceded that Wednesday's vote is likely
to fall two or three votes short of the two-thirds majority needed
for the Senate to join the House in passing the amendment and
sending it to the states for ratification.
</P>
<P>
   American Legion National Commander Alan G. Lance indicated that
his organization would target senators who fail to support the
measure at the ballot box this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the ability to protect Old Glory,'' Lance said at a
news conference where he stood with seven Medal of Honor winners
before dispatching his troops to the Senate. ``If we win, we in the
states will ratify. If we lose, we in the states will rectify,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-nine state legislatures _ all except Vermont's _ have
enacted resolutions asking Congress to send the amendment to them
for ratification. If Congress passes the flag amendment, three
fourths of the states must approve it before it can become part of
the Constitution. The House passed the flag amendment with
two-thirds majorities in 1995, 1997 and last year. The measure
failed by three votes in the Senate in 1995 and was not taken up in
1997 or 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Max Cleland, D-Ga., a supporter of the flag amendment, said
Wednesday that Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., is
bringing up the measure again even though he knows it will fail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trent Lott just brought it up because he wants to put a lot of
Democrats on the record,'' Cleland said. Senate sources said he was
referring particularly to Sens. Robert C. Byrd of West Virginia,
Jack Reed of Rhode Island and Charles S. Robb of Virginia, who have
been considered swing votes and who are up for reelection. ``Lott
is just waiting to run 30-second spots against them,'' Cleland
added.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, sponsor of the flag amendment, said at
the Legion's news conference that ``burning the flag, defecating on
it or urinating on it is not free speech. Standing up for the flag
will send a strong message that there are some common values and
ideals in America _ ideals worth protecting, fighting for and, when
warranted, dying for,'' Hatch said.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents argue that incidences of flag burning are rare and
don't warrant altering the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Patrick Brady of the American Legion said flag burners are
not the problem. ``It's those that call flag burning speech that
are the problem.'' Brady referred to Supreme Court decisions in
1989 and 1990 that rejected state and federal statutes against flag
desecration as violations of free speech rights in the First
Amendment to the Constitution. He said the rulings ``destroyed our
Constitution, and we should not stand still for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch said later he is fighting an uphill battle, but he added,
``Win or lose, we're going to keep fighting for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch's amendment says: ``Congress shall have the power to
prohibit the physical desecration of the flag of the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., another flag amendment sponsor,
said she agrees that amending the Constitution is ``serious
business, and we need to tread carefully.'' But Feinstein said the
flag that flies in front of her home in San Francisco is ``an
important symbol of unity'' and ``a revered object as well as a
national symbol'' that deserves protection. She conceded later that
the amendment is likely to fail and also predicted it will become
an issue in the November elections.
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
