<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-SEARCH-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANONYMOUS TIP NOT ENOUGH TO JUSTIFY GUN SEARCH, JUSTICES RULE
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Fla.)   (See also SCOTUS-HATE-CRIME) 
(nk) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An anonymous tip that a person is carrying a gun is
not enough to justify a stop and frisk by the police without some
further sign that the information is reliable, the Supreme Court
ruled with surprising unanimity Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The court rejected the argument put forward by Florida, the
Clinton administration and a broad coalition of state attorneys
general that because guns are so inherently dangerous, the police
can act on a tip involving a gun on the basis of less evidence than
the Constitution would otherwise require.
</P>
<P>
   ``Firearms are dangerous, and extraordinary dangers sometimes
justify unusual precautions,'' Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg said in
her opinion for the court. However, she added: ``An automatic
firearm exception to our established reliability analysis would
rove too far. Such an exception would enable any person seeking to
harass another to set in motion an intrusive, embarrassing police
search of the targeted person simply by placing an anonymous call
falsely reporting the target's unlawful carriage of a gun.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a rule, Ginsburg said, would not be easily confined to guns
but would logically extend to ``bare-boned tips about narcotics,''
on the ground that guns are often associated with drug dealing.
</P>
<P>
   Ginsburg said that for an anonymous tip to be reliable enough to
justify police action, it must do more than simply describe a
suspect's appearance and location _ in this case, that a black
teen-ager dressed in a plaid shirt was standing with two companions
at a Miami bus stop and was carrying a concealed handgun. Two Miami
police officers, responding to a telephone tip, went to the scene,
found it as described and pulled a gun from the young man's pants
pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Ginsburg noted that the tip offered nothing beyond mere
description and, in contrast to an anonymous tip the court found
adequate in a decision 10 years ago, gave the police no way to test
its accuracy. In the earlier case, a person left a building as
predicted, and drove to another address before the police moved in.
Recalling that the court had described the earlier case as
``close,'' Ginsburg said: ``This one surely falls on the other side
of the line.''
</P>
<P>
   In the current climate of frequent and tense encounters between
the police and citizens, this case, Florida vs. J.L., No. 98-1993,
drew wide attention from a variety of civil-liberties and
law-enforcement groups.
</P>
<P>
   James Tomkovicz, a law professor at the University of Iowa who
filed a brief for the National Association of Criminal Defense
Lawyers and other groups against searches based on anonymous tips,
said Tuesday that the decision had broad implications as a
demonstration that ``crime control is a concern of a free society,
but not the only concern.''
</P>
<P>
   The court's unanimity can be explained, he said, by the fact
that ``this was an extreme claim; that when someone says the magic
words `firearm,' the protection of the Fourth Amendment
disappears.'' The Fourth Amendment bans unreasonable police
searches and seizures.
</P>
<P>
   Dealing solely with anonymous tips, the court did not address
the more controversial and heavily freighted question of what
actions the police can take based not on a tip but on their own
observation and judgment. The justices found law-enforcement
arguments to be much more persuasive in ruling in January that a
person's unprovoked flight at the mere sight of a police officer
can justify the officer's chasing and frisking the person.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, of 11 criminal law cases the justices have decided so
far this term, the decision Tuesday was the first in which the
defendant prevailed. It is perhaps a measure of the Clinton
administration's conservatism on criminal law issues that its
arguments tilted too far toward the police even for this Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   The decision affirmed a 1998 ruling by the Florida Supreme
Court, which suppressed the gun the police had found in the pocket
of the 15-year-old subject of the tip, identified only as J.L.,
because, the court said, the search violated his Fourth Amendment
rights. The charge against him was never brought to trial.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida Supreme Court was actually in a minority of courts
to refuse to give special weight to the purported presence of a gun
in an anonymous tip; most other state and federal courts to have
considered the question had treated the gun as a highly relevant
factor in judging whether a tip provided the requisite ``reasonable
suspicion'' for the police to act.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The concept of reasonable suspicion as justification for a stop
and frisk, as opposed to the probable cause police need for a
formal search, comes from a 1968 Supreme Court decision, Terry vs.
Ohio, which permitted police officers who observe suspicious
behavior to conduct a limited pat-down search for weapons for their
own protection. In the context of a tip rather than observed
behavior, Ginsburg said Tuesday, reasonable suspicion ``requires
that a tip be reliable in its assertion of illegality, not just in
its tendency to identify a determinate person.''
</P>
<P>
   She suggested the need for reliability might be relaxed in other
contexts where great danger was alleged, such as a report that
someone was carrying a bomb, or in places such as schools or
airports ``where the reasonable expectation of Fourth Amendment
privacy is diminished.''
</P>
<P>
   In a concurring opinion, Justice Anthony M. Kennedy and Chief
Justice William H. Rehnquist said that while ``the court says all
that is necessary to resolve this case,'' there would be more to
say in future cases about the ways in which anonymous tips might be
tested for reliability.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
