<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES CURB POLICE POWER IN SEARCHES BASED ON ANONYMOUS TIPS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Police cannot stop and frisk someone based solely
on an anonymous tip that the person is armed, a unanimous Supreme
Court ruled Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In their 9-0 decision, the justices said the Constitution
requires officers to have more specific information about criminal
behavior before they can act on an unverified allegation from an
unknown s &UR; EI .
</P>
<P>
   An allegation of gun possession generally doesn't give police
the reasonable suspicion of illegal activity that the Fourth
Amendment requires officers to have before they can accost a
suspect, the justices added in a rare display of solidarity in a
case addressing police authoratpbk &QL; BherR &QC; 91
</P>
</TEXT>
