<HEADER>
A0506 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-HATE-CRIME-560     03-28 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-HATE-CRIME-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J., N.C.)  
 HIGH COURT HEARS CASE ON WHETHER JUDGES OR JURIES SHOULD RULE ON
BIAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ During a Supreme Court argument on the
constitutionality of New Jersey's unusual sentencing procedure for
hate crimes, the justices Tuesday appeared troubled by the state's
law but also troubled by the broader implications of overturning
it.
</P>
<P>
   While most states have laws that treat crimes committed because
of bias as warranting special or more severe punishment, only New
Jersey and North Carolina authorize judges, rather than juries, to
make the finding that bias was the motive. The two state laws
specify that the finding need not be ``beyond a reasonable doubt,''
the usual standard in criminal law, but only by a ``preponderance
of the evidence,'' a low evidentiary standard that means
essentially ``more likely than not.''
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey's Ethnic Intimidation Act, enacted in 1990, is being
challenged in an appeal by a Vineland man who confessed to having
fired several rounds from a .22-caliber rifle into the house of the
black family living next door and who pleaded guilty to unlawful
possession of a firearm. The sentence for that crime ranged from 5
to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The judge then concluded that the state had shown by a
preponderance of the evidence that the shooting was racially
motivated, an accusation that the defendant, Charles C. Apprendi
Jr., vigorously disputed. Apprendi, who is white, said he suffered
from an obsessive-compulsive disorder and, under the influence of
drugs and alcohol, felt an urge to shoot at the glass pane of the
home's brightly painted door.
</P>
<P>
   Under the New Jersey hate crime law, the judge's finding that
bias was the motive doubled the possible sentence, and Apprendi
received a sentence of 12 years instead of the maximum of 10 he
could otherwise have received.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case is about the erosion of the jury by the New Jersey
Legislature,'' Apprendi's lawyer, Joseph D. O'Neill, told the court
Tuesday. ``If a person is to be stigmatized as a racist, that
should be found by the broadest cross section of the community, and
that is the jury,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The defendant's argument got a sympathetic response from
justices across the court's ideological spectrum, from Clarence
Thomas and Antonin Scalia among the conservatives to John Paul
Stevens and David H. Souter among the court's more liberal members.
</P>
<P>
   Scalia said that under the Sixth Amendment's right to trial by
jury, there was an ``unbroken tradition'' that it was the jury that
had to find the facts that could increase the possible sentence.
Scalia grew so animated in picking up the slack in O'Neill's
somewhat halting argument that Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist
teased him at one point for arguing the defendant's case.
</P>
<P>
   Other justices, however, appeared troubled by the potential
implications of finding the New Jersey system unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you do with capital sentencing schemes?'' Justice
Sandra Day O'Connor asked O'Neill, noting that in some states it is
the judge who decides, after a jury's finding of guilt, whether a
convicted murderer will receive a death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   And Justice Stephen G. Breyer, an author of the federal
sentencing guidelines when he worked in the Senate in the 1970s,
told O'Neill: ``If I agree with you, I guess I'm holding the
Sentencing Commission unconstitutional'' because judges, not
juries, apply the various factors that determine a convicted
defendant's sentence.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The court has struggled in several recent cases over where to
draw the constitutional line between the respective roles of judge
and jury in laws that provide for longer sentences when, for
example, the defendant has used a gun in the commission of a crime
or has a criminal record. In its decision last June upholding
Apprendi's sentence, the New Jersey Supreme Court acknowledged the
ferment in this area of criminal law and said that ``the final word
on this subject will have to come from the United States Supreme
Court.''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa S. Gochman, a deputy attorney general from New Jersey who
argued in defense of the law, emphasized the difference between
``intent'' and ``motive'' in criminal law. Whether a defendant had
the requisite intent to commit the crime, essential to the finding
of guilt, remained as it always has been, a question for the jury
under New Jersey's approach, she said. But the question of motive,
or why the defendant committed the crime, was traditionally treated
as a sentencing factor, she said. For example, Gochman said, it had
never been considered the prosecution's duty to prove why someone
committed a burglary, whether to feed a drug habit or feed a
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``But motive has never had the significance it has under the New
Jersey statute,'' Souter told the state's lawyer. ``New Jersey has
chosen to give it a very different role,'' so the traditional
treatment did not necessarily apply, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the federal hate crime sentencing law, under which the
jury makes the finding of biased purpose, nor the laws of most
states will be affected by the decision in this case, Apprendi vs.
New Jersey, No. 99-478. But the Justice Department entered the case
on the state's side because of a variety of federal laws that
provide for enhanced sentences in other contexts.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, who rarely speaks during the court's argument sessions,
offered a pointed response to the argument that an assistant
solicitor general, Edward C. DuMont, made on behalf of the law.
``You argue that if it's an element of the offense it goes to the
jury and if it's a sentence enhancement it goes to the judge,''
Thomas said. ``The difficulty I have is that you nowhere define
what the distinction is.''
</P>
<P>
   When DuMont said that legislatures should be given wide
discretion to decide where the decision should be made, Scalia told
him, ``You have to give me some way to protect the citizens from a
legislature that doesn't like juries.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-00 1958EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
