<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-1070-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV NOTES: ELIAN INTERVIEW; OSCAR RATING 
</HEADLINE>
  (hm) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABC's ``Good Morning America'' seemed to score the newsmaker
interview of the week with Diane Sawyer's exclusive chat with Elian
Gonzalez, which ran Monday and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the interview has been heavily criticized by President Fidel
Castro, network competitors at NBC and, ABC says, the U.S. Justice
Department.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's installment, taped Thursday and Friday in the
presence of a psychoanalyst, the 6-year-old boy recounted how he
was saved by dolphins when the boat that had been carrying him, his
mother and 11 other people from Cuba to Florida sank. The boy told
Sawyer that he had thought his mother, who drowned, had survived
the disaster but had not found him because she lost her memory.
</P>
<P>
   But Sawyer broke what appeared to be the real news on Tuesday.
``The relatives in Miami say Elian repeatedly insists he does not
want to go back to Cuba,'' she said. ``He told us that, too, but in
this inflamed climate, on this inflamed subject, we thought it best
not to broadcast the exact words of a 6-year-old child.''
</P>
<P>
   While this was important news in the debate over whether the
child should be returned to his father in Cuba or remain with
relatives in Miami, for many people, her statement begged a
question: Then why broadcast the exact words of a 6-year-old child
in the first place? And why leave out the child's opinion, an
integral part of the story?
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Zucker, executive producer of NBC's ``Today,'' said the boy
did not appear on his program because it did not consider such an
interview proper.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never been interested in this interview,'' he said. ``We
thought it was inappropriate to interview a 6-year-old boy,
especially this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Zucker acknowledged that a ``Today'' show booker responded
positively to the Gonzalez family when asked if the producers were
interested in interviewing the child. But, he said, the booker
acted without his approval.
</P>
<P>
   Castro called the interview ``monstrous and sickening,'' The
Associated Press said.
</P>
<P>
   ABC executives said the Justice Department had expressed
displeasure with the segments. It has threatened to take custody of
the boy as early as tomorrow unless his family agrees that it will
surrender him if it loses its legal battle to keep him in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Journalistic opinion was divided over whether ``Good Morning
America'' had acted appropriately.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Saltzman, associate dean at the Annenberg School for
Communication at the University of Southern California, told The
Miami Herald he didn't have a problem with the interview. But
Robert M. Steele, director of the ethics program at the Poytner
Institute, a journalism education center in St. Petersburg, Fla.,
called the interview unethical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elian is 6 years old and is clearly very vulnerable for a
variety of emotional and psychological reasons and has undergone a
great deal of trauma,'' Steele said. ``What we have to do is
balance the potential value of the interview, in terms of the
subject matter,'' he said, ``and what the child could meaningfully
offer against what the level of intrusion would be on a 6-year-old
when asked such hard questions _ particularly when they have
undergone such emotional trauma as Elian has.''
</P>
<P>
   The president of ABC News, David Westin, defended the interview.
He said that it had been carefully considered before it was taped
and that ABC had gone out of its way to make sure the interview was
appropriate and tasteful.
</P>
<P>
   ``We concluded that it was a very legitimate and important news
story,'' he said. ``The one point of view we hadn't heard anything
about was the little boy whose life is really involved here.'' He
said the network decided not to show the scenes in which Elian said
he wanted to remain in Miami because it feared they would be taken
out of context and used for political purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good Morning America,'' incidentally, received higher than
usual ratings Monday morning: It was viewed in an average of 5.2
million homes, compared with its usual 4.3 million. But the show
tends to do better than usual after the Academy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   The last installment of Sawyer's interview with the boy is to be
shown tonight on ``20/20.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Oscar Rating
</P>
<P>
   ABC was more than pleased with the results from this year's
Academy Awards broadcast, pointing to ratings up about 2 percent
from last year's.
</P>
<P>
   But the show lagged far behind the rating of two years ago, when
``Titanic'' won many awards. This year's show also had the
advantage of Billy Crystal as host.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second year the show has been on a Sunday. ABC moved
the show from Monday with much fanfare two years ago, hoping for a
significant ratings increase, because Sunday is usually the
most-watched television night of the week.
</P>
<P>
   This year's show had a higher rating than the 1997 show, when
``The English Patient'' was chosen as best film. And it was also
behind the 1996 broadcast, when ``Braveheart'' was the year's big
winner. Both of those shows were broadcast on Mondays.
</P>
<P>
   ABC did miss badly on one goal that the network emphasized after
last year's show: making the elephantine broadcast shorter. It ran
more than 10 minutes longer.
</P>
<P>
   One big reason the overrun didn't hurt the ratings, however, was
that by that point, at ABC's request, counting for the ratings had
stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Although the show ended at 12:41 a.m. EST, the rating went only
until 12:17 a.m., when the last commercial ran. ABC asked Nielsen
Media Research to consider the rest of the show, which included all
the biggest awards, as what is known as ``sustaining.''
</P>
<P>
   That usually means programming that is not sponsored. Surely
this is the only programming anywhere in television that gets
almost a 30 rating and is not considered sponsored. But ABC chose
to do it this way because the rating falls off sharply at that
hour. ``We moved the last commercial up this year to try to keep
the rating up,'' said Andrea Wong, vice president for specials at
ABC.
</P>
<P>
   That also had the advantage of grouping most of the truly big
awards _ all except leading actress this year _ at the end without
a commercial interruption. This year's show went from best director
to best actor to best picture without a commercial. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-00 2000EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
