<HEADLINE>
DICKSON IMPRESSIVE IN VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. -- Jason Dickson all but wrapped up a spot in the
starting rotation with his performance in the Angels' 3-2 victory
over the Oakland A's Tuesday afternoon at Tempe Diablo Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Dickson gave up one run and six hits in six innings. His spring
ERA is 4.87, but more importantly, Dickson gave up only two runs in
11 2/3 innings in his final two starts in Arizona. He'll probably
pitch in a camp game Sunday, then make his season debut on Friday,
April 7 against the Red Sox at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say timing is everything,'' Dickson said. ``I've pitched
pretty well in my last couple of starts, and that's a pretty good
time to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickson, though, is not counting on anything just yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea,'' Dickson said when asked if he thinks he'll
be in the rotation. ``I've done everything I wanted to do. I've
thrown the ball the way I wanted to in spring training. That's all
I can control. ... I wouldn't want to be in their (coaches') shoes
making the decisions. It can be an unbelievably tough job.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickson's command of his pitches Tuesday was not as good as he'd
like it to be -- he walked four -- but he showed manager Mike
Scioscia how he could pitch on a day he didn't have his good stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think he was quite as sharp as his last time,''
Scioscia said. ``But obviously the results were good, he did a
great job of battling. If you give up one run in six innings you
did a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Dickson, Ken Hill, Kent Bottenfield and Ramon Ortiz
(barring a setback with his shoulder) are in the rotation. The
remaining spot will be either Kent Mercker or Scott Schoeneweis.
However, both could make the club if Mercker is sent to the
bullpen. Scioscia said he expects to have the rotation set today or
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels made five cuts Tuesday, reducing their roster to 27
players. Among those sent down was Brian Cooper (Glendora High,
Citrus College, USC). Cooper went into camp among those competing
for a spot in the starting rotation, but his inconsistency showed
the Angels he needs a little more ``fine tuning,'' acording to
Scioscia.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to work on the consistency of his stuff,'' Scioscia
said. ``We saw sporadic parts where he was effective. But to become
a major league pitcher he needs to take it out there a little more
often than he has this spring.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before being sent down, Cooper had a feeling it would
happen after his start Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if I get sent down today, I wanted to go on a good
note,'' Cooper said Monday after giving up one run and four hits in
five innings. ``Then I'll go to triple-A coming off a good one. I
know I can pitch up here.''
</P>
<P>
   The other cuts were infielders Larry Barnes and Trent Durrington
(optioned to triple-A Edmonton) and catcher Steve Decker and
pitcher Eric Weaver (reassigned to minor league camp).
</P>
<P>
   Jarrod Washburn (strained muscle in right side) threw 30 pitches
in two innings of a simulated game Tuesday and felt good. He'll
pitch Sunday at Edison Field against Cal State Fullerton and could
be ready to join the rotation in a couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If everything's healed and I'm throwing well, I go down (to
the minors) and earn my way back,'' Washburn said. ``I'm taking
nothing for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   DAILY BOX
</P>
<P>
   WHEN/WHERE (split-squad): 12:05 p.m. at Tempe Diablo Stadium;
12:05 p.m. at Peoria Sports Complex.
</P>
<P>
   TODAY'S GAMES: Diamondbacks at Angels -- Kent Bottenfield starts
for Anaheim against Arizona's Brian Anderson. It will be
Bottenfield's first start for the Angels. Angels at Padres -- Ken
Hill starts for Anaheim against San Diego's Sterling Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY'S RESULTS -- Jason Dickson gave up one run and six hits
in six innings as the Angels (13-16) beat the A's, 3-2. Darin
Erstad went 0 for 4, his hitting streak snapped at 15 consecutive
games.
</P>
</TEXT>
