<SLUG> BC-CMBUY29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Owner of Variety magazine to buy CMD Group
 &HT;    By Russell Grantham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The rapidly growing owner of Variety and other trade
magazines has agreed to buy CMD Group Inc. for $299.5 million, the
companies said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   CMD, formerly called Construction Market Data Group, operates
construction trade publications. It also provides national and
regional directories and other data on the industry in print and on
its Internet sites.
</P>
<P>
   New York-based Cahners Business Information said it will pay
cash for the privately held company, which has about 300 employees
at its headquarters in Norcross, Ga., and 1,400 worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Cahners, which owns 140 Web sites and more than 100 trade
publications such as Variety, Publishers Weekly and Design News,
hopes to integrate CMD's building and construction information on
its online construction Web sites, Buildingteam.com and
HousingZone.com.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies said they had already been working together
prior to the deal to produce Buildingteam.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, we see our operations out here growing,'' said
CMD spokeswoman Piritta Luoto, because the combination will help
CMD shift its products more quickly onto the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, most of its products have some online connections,
but are mostly print, she said.
</P>
<P>
   CMD's flagship Construction Market Data product line, for
instance, consists of weekly regional print editions listing new
construction projects in various states and metropolitan markets,
with daily updates available online.
</P>
<P>
   CMD recorded $126 million in revenue last year from its print,
CD-ROM and online products. Luoto said the firm's main competitors
are a number of publications owned by McGraw-Hill Inc., which
publishes Business Week, and several small regional publishers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an Internet play for us,'' said Cahners spokesman Tom
Nutile. He added that Cahners has ``no immediate plans ... to move
anything out of Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the acquisition is expected to be completed in a month
to 45 days.
</P>
<P>
   Cahners, with $860 million in revenues last year and 3,900
employees, has acquired nine other companies during the past year
and launched three Web sites and two magazines.
</P>
<P>
   The firm is owned by Reed Elsevier Plc, a joint venture of
London-based Reed International Plc and Amsterdam-based Elsevier
NV.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
