<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-HATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES CONSIDER CONSTITUTIONALITY OF HATE-CRIME STATUTES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trim) 
 
By STEVE LASH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Tuesday grappled with the
constitutionality of a state ``hate crime'' law that allows judges
to increase prison sentences for violent offenders who acted out of
hatred for their victims' race.
</P>
<P>
   Several justices, considering a case from New Jersey, pressed
the lawyer for Charles Apprendi Jr. on why it violated the man's
constitutional rights for a judge to double his sentence under the
state law. The judge, after all, had sufficient evidence to
conclude that Apprendi fired shots into the home of black neighbors
because he didn't want people of their race to live in his
neighborhood, the justices said.
</P>
<P>
   But the high court was just as inquisitive of the New Jersey
prosecutor, asking her how the state could justify allowing a judge
to add 10 years to a prison sentence even though a jury had not
decided that Apprendi acted out of racial hatred. Several justices
said that perhaps the Constitution required that a jury, not a
judge, decide whether a crime was committed due to bigotry.
</P>
<P>
   The hourlong argument before the court marked the first time the
justices have considered the constitutionality of hate-crime
statutes. Many states enacted these laws following the high-profile
killings two years ago of James Byrd Jr., a black man in Jasper,
Texas, and of gay University of Wyoming student Matthew Shepard in
Laramie, Wyo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Texas has no law calling for enhanced penalties for people who
kill out of racial hatred. Gov. George W. Bush vetoed a hate-crime
bill last year, despite intense lobbying from Byrd's family, whose
relative was beaten, tied to the back of a pickup and dragged to
his death June 7, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Three men were convicted last year of killing Byrd. Two of them,
John William ``Bill'' King and Russell Brewer, have been sentenced
to death and the third, Shawn Berry, was sentenced to life in
prison. Bush has cited these convictions and sentences as evidence
that Texas does not need a special hate-crime law.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the case before the justices, Apprendi pleaded guilty to
possessing a firearm for an unlawful purpose in connection with the
firing of several rounds into the home of Michael and Mattie
Fowlkes and their three children. The crime carries a penalty of
between five and 10 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   But Cumberland County, N.J., Judge Rushton Ridgway, citing the
state's hate-crime statute, raised the punishment to up to 20 years
in prison after concluding that Apprendi fired his weapon out of
racial bigotry. The Fowlkes were the only black family in
Apprendi's white neighborhood of Vineland, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Apprendi appealed the sentence, arguing that the issue of
whether he acted out of racial hatred is a factual question that a
jury must decide beyond a reasonable doubt. The judge, by making
that factual finding based only on a preponderance of evidence,
denied Apprendi his constitutional 6th Amendment right to a fair
trial, he said.
</P>
<P>
   When the New Jersey Supreme Court rejected that argument, he
appealed to the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
