<HEADER>
A0518 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     03-28 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE TURNS A SOUND BITE INTO A GNAW
</HEADLINE>
  
 
 c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Following the candidates along the campaign trail, the New York
Observer's  &UR; Philip Weiss &LR;  writes that although standard Clintonisms
are ``evasions,'' Bushisms are ``idiotic blather. ... Then there's
Gorespeak.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Al Gore  &LR; routinely uses a ``combination of high-flown imagery
and diplomatic roundaboutness,'' writes Weiss. The following
remarks were made by the candidate at an appearance in Manhattan on
March 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hypothetical circumstances surrounding that are so
numerous as to make it unwise to construct a little box and get
inside it. ... There have not been such steps as would cross the
threshold of damage to our ability to perform a constructive role.
... The answer to your question must be addressed in the status of
final negotiations, but the outcome is hardly in doubt, and my
desires are the same as your desires.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _The story of  &UR; Janet Cooke &LR; , the Washington Post reporter who
returned a Pulitzer Prize in 1981 after it was revealed that she
had made up her story's main character, is the subject of a movie
in the making. The film will be based on an interview Cooke gave in
1996 to GQ reporter &UR; Mike Sager &LR; . According to  &LR; medianews.com &LR;  cq &LR; ,
Cooke will get 55 percent, Sager 45 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_In a speech he made two weeks ago at the University of Georgia,
``Jeopardy'' host  &UR; Alex Trebek  &LR; said unkind things about ``Who
Wants to Be a Millionaire?,'' reports Entertainment Weekly. Trebek
complained that the questions on the rival show are too easy.
Furthermore, he said, ``Millionaire'' host &UR; Regis Philbin &LR;  came in
last both times he appeared on ``Celebrity Jeopardy.''
</P>
<P>
   Philbin challenged Trebek, in return, to appear on a
``Millionaire'' show in May that will feature celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ARTnews reveals that  &UR; Pierce Brosnan &LR; , who studied painting before
he became an actor, and makes a habit of packing a sketch pad, will
play an artist in ``Burnt Sienna,'' &UR; David Morrell &LR; 's book about a
Marine pilot who becomes a painter.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _ &UR; Tony Curtis  &LR; indicated to the New York Daily News that his
reaction to  &UR; Jane Fonda &LR; 's Oscar gig was mixed. ``She gets picked
out, only because of her notoriety,'' he said. ``I'm not dumping on
Jane. But there are a lot of great actors in the hills of Hollywood
who'd love a few minutes of that sunlight. That's all right. We
shall overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _ &UR; Spike Lee &LR;  is on Martha's Vineyard making a six-minute
promotional movie for Jaguar; the Boston Herald reported recently
that he had traded in his Mustang for a Mercedes.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _ &UR; Malcolm Kushner &LR; , whose business is ``making humor work for the
business professional,'' has compiled his annual Cost of Laughing
Index, in the course of which he discovered that while the price of
Mad magazine is up this year ($2.50 to $2.99), the cost to send a
dancing chicken singing telegram is the same ($75).
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _If there happens to be an emergency in the middle of the night,
and a crew of good-looking firefighters shows up to rescue you, you
don't want them to see you without lipstick, do you? Fitness
magazine reports on a new nighttime lip balm with red tint and on
Brighten Up, Tighten Up, a concealer and moisturizer to be worn
while sleeping.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _ &UR; Maureen O'Rorke &LR;  suggests a new moving violation for drivers who
run red lights while talking on their cell phones or drive
gas-guzzling SUVs: ``Driving under the affluence.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``(Elaine May) looks happy. I hear her chuckle sometimes,
which &LR; 
 &UR; is reassuring. In my experience, when these plays get closer to &LR; 
 &UR; opening, everything can change. ... They stop pussyfooting &LR; 
 &UR; around. ... You're finally ready to open when people are &LR; 
 &UR; shouting, `What are you doing? You're killing the show!''' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Matthew Broderick &LR;  in Interview magazine. Broderick will open
on Broadway next month in  &UR; Elaine May &LR; 's ``Taller Than a Dwarf.''
 &UR; Alan Arkin &LR;  is directing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
