<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-LAWSUIT (Washington) _ U.S. District Court Judge
Thomas Penfield Jackson delays his ruling in the antitrust case
against software giant Microsoft Corp. as the company and Justice
Department officials continue settlement talks. Government sources
say the delay could last until April 7. By MARK HELM. (Also filed
in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-TIP (Washington) _ A unanimous Supreme Court rules that
the police cannot stop and frisk a person based solely on an
anonymous tip. By STEVE LASH. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NASA-PROBE (Washington) _ Space agency officials release a
report on the loss last year of the Mars Polar Lander. It outlines
a series of mistakes in testing, software and management that
likely led to the engines on the craft shutting down when the craft
was still 130 feet above the Mars surface. By MARK CARREAU and
PATTY REINERT.
</P>
<P>
   NASA-MARS (Washington) _ NASA is attempting to revamp its Mars
program in light of the damning report on the funding and
management of past missions. By PATTY REINERT.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-HATE (Washington) _ The Supreme Court is asked to require
juries, not judges, to decide whether an illegal act against a
protected minority should be elevated to a hate crime, thus worthy
of a enhanced punishment. The case could affect state laws that
allow longer prison terms for defendants convicted of acts designed
``to intimidate an individual because of ``race, color, gender,
handicap, religion, sexual orientation or ethnicity.'' By STEVE
LASH. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   FLAG-VETERANS (Washington) _ More than 1,000 members of the
American Legion swarm Capitol Hill searching for two more senators
to vote for a proposed Constitutional amendment that would make
desecrating the U.S. flag illegal. They are joined by Miss America,
Heather Renee French, whose father is a disabled Vietnam veteran.
By JUDY HOLLAND. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   FBI-INTERNET-CRIME (Washington) _ FBI Director Louis Freeh tells
Congress that law enforcement agencies need more legal powers to
prosecute Internet criminals, including hackers and thieves. He
says the law should be changed to allow suspects as young as 15 to
be prosecuted in federal courts. By AUSTIN ZALKIN. (Also filed in
the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OPEC-TALKS (Vienna, Austria) _ The Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries has reached an agreement in principle on new
oil output quotas, says the oil minister from Venezuela, the
current OPEC president. By DAVID IVANOVICH.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   REFORM-PARTY (Washington) _ Pat Choate, head of the Reform
Party, vows to stabilize the fractured party and mount petition
drives to put the likely presidential nominee on general election
ballots. Choate predicts that former Republican firebrand Patrick
Buchanan will be the Reform Party nominee. By R.G. RATCLIFF and
BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   REFORM-PARTY-DEBATES (Washington) _ The Reform Party launches a
campaign to gain full participation for its likely presidential
nominee, Patrick Buchanan, in this fall's televised debates with
Republican George W. Bush and Democrat Al Gore. By STEWART M.
POWELL. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Kissimmee, Fla.) _ The Houston Astros, the defending
Central Division champs, are about to break camp and play the New
York Yankees in Enron Field, which opens Thursday. By CARLTON
THOMPSON.
</P>
<P>
   With: BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   BKC-IOWA-STATE (Undated) _ Iowa State's sudden rise to the Big
12 title and NCAA's Elite Eight came amid concerns over the
Cyclones' recruiting tactics. By DANNY ROBBINS.
</P>
<P>
   BKC-MICHIGAN-STATE (Undated) _ The prohibitive favorite to win
the national title, Michigan State will lean on several Final Four
veterans this weekend. By JERRY WIZIG.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-ROCKETS (Houston) _ The Houston Rockets, 26-44, host the
17-53 Golden State Warriors in the Compaq Center. By MICHAEL
MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ First impressions are important, and
in politics early images of the candidates are often hard to shake
no matter how inaccurate they are. Vice President Al Gore is stuck
with the wooden bit, and Gov. George W. Bush is forever a dim bulb.
Yet both men are more complex than their images. Gore can be witty,
and Bush is smarter than you think. By MARIANNE MEANS. (Already
filed.)
</P>
