<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0523 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-NETANYAHU-2NDL     03-28 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-NETANYAHU-2NDLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    2NDLEDE-WRITE-THRU
 &HT;    Eds. CHANGES THROUGHOUT
 &HT;    Former Israeli leader denies allegations of corruption
 &HT;    By Larry Kaplow
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jerusalem _ Former Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
defiantly said Tuesday he was the victim of a ``hunt'' and denied
police allegations of corruption while in office.
</P>
<P>
   The comments, in an interview on Israeli Television, came after
Israeli police recommended that prosecutors file corruption charges
against him and his wife, Sara.
</P>
<P>
   They are accused of trying to keep up to 700 gifts they received
while Netanyahu was in office _ including a gold letter opener from
Vice President Al Gore _ and accepting work from a contractor who
expected political favors. Police have been investigating the
couple _ and have held long questioning sessions with each _ for
seven months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't define this as though they are after me, I would
define it as a hunt,'' Netanyahu said during the 50-minute
interview, in which he often sounded sarcastic and angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of these allegations have no basis at all,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Though he lost a bid for re-election last year and then dropped
out of politics, Netanyahu has been urged recently to attempt a
comeback, either for his Likud Party or a new party. His three
years in office were marked by a combative style and reluctance to
carry out peace agreements with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   In the TV interview, Netanyahu said the police investigation
could preclude another political bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``They, in essence, are neutralizing me politically,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The decision on whether to charge Netanyahu lies with Attorney
General Elyakim Rubinstein, who in the past declined to charge
Netanyahu after police allegations of preferential hiring for a
Cabinet post.
</P>
<P>
   Police recommend that Netanyahu be charged with accepting a
bribe, breach of trust by a public official, obstruction of justice
and attempted fraud. Police said Sara Netanyahu should be charged
with theft and attempted fraud. Police also recommended charges
against two Netanyahu aides.
</P>
<P>
   The police recommendation against Netanyahu is the latest in a
wave of scandals involving Israeli officials.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak and his aides are facing a police
probe into his campaign fund-raising. President Ezer Weizman is
being investigated to see whether he accepted more than $400,000 in
gifts from a French millionaire since the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Rubinstein opened an investigation of the spiritual
leader of the large Shas Party, Rabbi Ovadia Yosef, because he
compared a political opponent to ``Satan'' and a biblical figure
who set out to eliminate the Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Such language can be considered incitement to violence and has
been closely scrutinized since the assassination of Prime Minister
Yitzhak Rabin in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The corruption scandals, especially, are seen as a sign of the
growing influence of Israeli prosecutors in a still young country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The standards have risen. The things that were possible in the
past and would have gone unnoticed are not possible now,'' said Uri
Dromi, publications director for the Israel Democracy Institute.
``The public is not tolerating it as it did before.''
</P>
<P>
   The Netanyahu inquiry began shortly after the elections, when a
contractor submitted a bill to the prime minister's office. Police
believe the contractor performed $50,000 worth of work with the
understanding that Netanyahu would repay him with political favors.
</P>
<P>
   The contractor has since become a witness for the prosecution.
Police accuse Netanyahu of trying to get the contractor to lie in
the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Police searched the Netanyahus' home and properties, and
reportedly found gifts with the inscriptions removed and gifts that
had been re-packaged. Israel Radio reported that the gifts were
worth more than $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu said he was allowed to take gifts for the office he is
provided by the government as a former prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
