<HEADLINE>
BUILDING WITH EXPERIENCES
</HEADLINE>
  (hm) 
 (Bob Clyatt is chief executive of Horizonlive.com, an online
distance learning company) 
By BOB CLYATT with JULIA LAWLOR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I was 10, my sister Sally died in a car crash. She was 16.
She was the third in line of us five kids; I was the fourth. She
had taught me to read when I was 4.
</P>
<P>
   After this happened, I had this notion that I had to fill up my
life with as many experiences as possible because every day is a
gift that can be snatched away from you at any point. I've done
rock climbing, mountaineering, climbed glaciers. I've biked from
one end of Britain to the other. I graduated from MIT, and I've
always worked.
</P>
<P>
   When I was 9, I was doing yard work for my neighbors. I made up
little 3-by-5 cards that said ``The Handy Kid'' and handed them
out. I worked in a gas station on Saturdays from the time I was 14.
I teamed up with one of the guys I worked with at the station and
started a cleaning service, doing parking lots and doctors' offices
at night.
</P>
<P>
   When I was 22, I spent a summer in the south of France working
as a bartender for $4 an hour in a town called St. Paul de Vence. I
worked at the Cafe de la Place, which was owned by Yves Montand and
Simone Signoret. I had had a French girlfriend, so I was fluent _
at least fluent enough to be a bartender.
</P>
<P>
   In the mornings, I'd show up for work and squeeze about three
cases of oranges. They were Israeli oranges. Then, one day, I
noticed the oranges were from South Africa. There was a boycott of
South African products going on to protest apartheid. I went to the
boss and asked if someone else could do the oranges. ``These are
oranges,'' she said. ``Who cares where they're from? Either squeeze
them or leave.'' So I quit.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that the writer James Baldwin was one of the
patrons of the bar, and when he heard what happened, he invited me
out to his 17th-century farmhouse. I got to be buddies with him. We
spent many whiskey-soaked evenings talking about politics.
</P>
<P>
   I started my first business, a Web design company called I/O
360, at age 36. I had been a manager at Reuters, and people who
reported to me there thought they had to laugh at my jokes.
Managing a bunch of 20-somethings in a start-up was completely
different.
</P>
<P>
   Our first ``office'' was a summer sublet near N.Y.U. that we
rented from a Buddhist nun who left to do a film on the Dalai Lama
for the summer.
</P>
<P>
   We would work in the front room, and my three partners,
including two of my wife's cousins, Nam and Gong, would sleep in
the back rooms. I had this romantic notion of what it would be like
to be my own boss. I didn't know it meant all this work and no pay.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen months later, we hit rock bottom. We were constantly
trying to find new customers. Fortunately, my wife, Wonda, was
supporting our family on her income as an immigration lawyer. But
the others were living like students, and realizing their peers who
were employees of big companies were making more. They were losing
the will to go on.
</P>
<P>
   Without telling me, my wife talked to her parents, who moved
here from China. Her mother called her sister, Aunt Grace, who is
Nam and Gong's mother. Aunt Grace called her sons up and read them
the riot act: ``Do what Bob says and work harder.'' These guys have
shaved heads and tattoos. But they really do respect their parents.
After that, things went fine.
</P>
<P>
   We sold the company in August 1998, and all became
multimillionaires. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
