<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILLIPS DOES SOME DEFENDING   ON FLUTIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bills coach Wade Phillips does not expect any problems from
quarterback Doug Flutie when the two next meet.
</P>
<P>
   Flutie has been critical of Phillips and the Buffalo
organization for benching him before the playoffs, and for
releasing some veteran stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read what Doug said, but I'm not worried about it,'' said
Phillips. ``Doug is a competitor. He wants to do well. He wants to
win. I don't have problems with guys like that. I know he said some
things and sometimes something else he said might have been left
out or changed around a little. I know when Doug comes back to the
team he's going to play hard like he always does.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips said Rob Johnson has the slight edge at QB entering
training camp, ``but I'm not naming him the starter,'' the coach
said.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips surprised the football world when he benched Flutie for
the Bills' playoff game against the Tennessee Titans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rob played the best game of the year we had (from a QB)
against Indianapolis in the final game of the season. After seeing
that performance, I felt he was the better man at that time, and
could do more for us in the playoffs. Doug had been doing a good
job for us, but teams were starting to figure him out and were
making it hard for us to move the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think it was the right decision, even if we lost. We
outplayed Tennessee and should have won. We just got some bad
breaks.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips hinted he might use both Johnson and Flutie at various
times. ``With Doug's unique ability to do some things that Rob
can't do, there might be games, or times in games, when we can use
that ability to our advantage. That's something we are talking
about right now.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Colts have horses
</P>
<P>
   In a poll of the AFC East coaches, the Indianapolis Colts were
the overwhelming favorite to win the division. Bill Belichick of
the Patriots, Dave Wannstedt of the Dolphins, Al Groh of the Jets,
and Phillips made Colts the team to beat. Indianapolis coach Jim
Mora said Buffalo was the team he thought would win. ``At the end
of the regular season, when we played them in Buffalo, I thought
they were the best team in the AFC,'' said Mora. ``But I didn't
realize how good Tennessee was until they beat us in the playoffs.
Buffalo, to me, will be as strong as any team in the AFC.''
Belichick on Indianapolis: ``They've got the same team they had a
year ago, and just through experience they should be better.You
really can't stop them. You just try to slow them down and make
them work for everything they get.'' . . . Groh on Indy: ``To start
with, they've got the quarterback (Peyton Manning). After winning
it last year, they are going to be even more mature as a team this
year. This could be the start of a little bit of a run for them.
The pieces are in place.'' . . . Wannstedt on the Colts: ``They won
it last year, and they should be even better this year. But we are
going to be the surprise team. We've got all our players back
except the quarterback (Dan Marino). I still think our defense can
be outstanding, and that should keep us in every game.'' . . .
Phillips said of the Colts: ``Indianapolis is the team to beat, and
I think we have as good a chance as anyone. We felt like if we beat
Tennessee in that playoff game we could have taken it all the way
last year. We're going to be just as good this year.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Replay with twist
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's vote on instant replay could have an interesting
twist. The last proposal the owners were discussing is one that
would bring replay back for one more year. If it is voted in for
the 2000 season, a year from now, at the annual league meeting, a
vote would be held to install it permanently. Since replay first
came to the league, it always has been voted on one year at a time.
Replay is expected to pass easily Wednesday, but next year will be
the real test.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Coaches cornered
</P>
<P>
   The owners might vote on a proposal Wednesday that is sure to
drive the assistant coaches in the league crazy. ``If they go ahead
and do this, it will be horrible,'' said Larry Kennan, head of the
NFL Coaches Association. ``It's (an attempt) at keeping us in
bondage, and trying to keep the coaches' salaries down.'' What is
being discussed is a motion that would eliminate all coaching
titles, and prevent any assistant from going to another team unless
it is to be a head coach. In other words, an assistant who coached
only a position could not leave to be an offensive coordinator.
``This is an attempt,'' said one GM at the meetings, ``to keep the
coaches on the clubs who don't want to spend money from jumping to
the clubs who will spend.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
