<SLUG> BC-DIANA-WRITER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW A WRITER KEPT SECRET OF DIANA BOOK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to New York Times photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By MEG McCONAHEY   The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAPA, Calif. _ A week after the sole survivor of the crash that
killed Princess Diana met with the world press in New York to
promote his new book, ``The Bodyguard's Story,'' Moira Johnston sat
in her living room overlooking a finger of the Napa River,
marveling at the secret she skillfully kept for nearly two years.
</P>
<P>
   The prize-winning investigative journalist whose exhaustive
reporting has explored repressed memory and taken on powerful
corporations, was the writer to whom Trevor Rees-Jones broke his 2
1/2-year silence about the events leading up to the fatal crackup
in a Paris tunnel. Reporters around the world had salivated for the
journalistic coup and tabloids had offered seven figures to buy the
exclusive.
</P>
<P>
   In the process of reporting and writing Jones' story, Johnston
found herself a central player in a dramatic, and finely crafted
plan to protect the book from Internet hackers and pre-emptive
legal attacks by Mohammed Fayed. The Egyptian business tycoon's
son, Dodi, died in the Paris crash that also killed driver Henri
Paul and crushed Jones' face beyond recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Since the tragedy, Fayed has waged a fierce public relations
campaign to convince the world that Dodi and Diana were engaged and
that the crash was arranged to keep the mother of a future British
King from marrying an Arab. He accused Rees-Jones of being part of
the cover-up. Fayed failed earlier this month to win a count
injunction to stop a London newspaper from serializing the book.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were so fearful of leaks,'' said Johnson, who was answering
a raft of lawyers and editors' questions up until three weeks
before publication.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not fearful now. But I'm fearful for Trevor and for the
publishing house that lawsuits could still come. It doesn't matter
that that's what you're insured for. You can be terribly disrupted
and hurt by lawsuits.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bodyguard's Story,'' Johnston believes, undermines many of
Fayed's claims, chief among them that Fayed had heard Diana's last
words and that Diana and Dodi had picked out an engagement ring
while cruising the Mediterranean. Rees-Jones says the couple did
not visit the jewelry store when they were reported to have picked
out a ring.
</P>
<P>
   Jones also relates how Dodi had engaged in a pattern of erratic
disregard for security, often impatiently ordering drivers to step
on it in heavy traffic, repeatedly failing to tell his bodyguards
of his plans and insisting that Paul _ later found to be legally
drunk _ act as substitute driver for the couple. Rees-Jones
overrode Dodi's insistence that he and Diana drive in the Mercedes
alone while the bodyguards took off separately in a decoy car.
</P>
<P>
   Rees-Jones said Fayed repeatedly turned down his pleas for more
security during the weeks of the short summer romance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted the world to know the lovers were out there,''
Johnston said. However, Rees-Jones still can't remember anything
directly before or after the accident, leaving critical questions
unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   Fayed has called the book ``rubbish'' and threatened to sue his
son's former bodyguard, who has steel plates in his head and is
only now digging out of debt with book proceeds and a new security
job.
</P>
<P>
   But now that the book is out and poised to debut Sunday on the
New York Times best-seller list, Johnston is free to spill her own
secret. She had longtime friends and neighbors guessing for months
about the cloaked project that took her to England and kept her
holed up in a downtown Napa office for 12 hours a day as she
frantically tried to meet the most demanding deadline of a long
career, all the while nervously looking over her shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``My fear is that those who didn't want the book published would
find me in Napa, break in and steal it, and I would wake up one
morning and find it gone,'' the British Columbia-born Johnston said
in a lyrical Canadian accent. She used two tape recorders for every
interview and made back-up files that she kept at home and the
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think my best cover was this quiet rural town where I'm
trusted and liked. I was living such a normal life going off for my
little latte every morning, such a simple, humble ritual, it
certainly wouldn't occur to anyone here to betray me and call
anybody. This was probably as secure a cover as I could find.''
</P>
<P>
   That didn't stop the good-natured speculation that she was
working with everyone from controversial British author Salman
Rushdie to British au pair Louise Woodward.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston was an unlikely recruit to do a book that smacked of
celebrity journalism. She was the author of six respected
investigatory books, including the ``The Last Nine Minutes'' about
a 1974 Paris plane crash and most recently ``Spectral Evidence,''
exploring truth and repressed memory.
</P>
<P>
   Her longtime agent Michael Carlisle, who arranged the
assignment, thought Johnston would be ideal for the book, with her
expertise in memory issues and in sorting out complex legal cases.
She also had a British background. Her father, like Rees-Jones, had
served in the British military and was raised not far from the
bodyguard's small town of Oswestry.
</P>
<P>
   Like everyone associated with the book, Johnston had to sign a
confidentiality agreement even before Carlisle would disclose the
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   She worried at first about how others would perceive her latest
project.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't do tabloid. I don't do celebrity. I don't do,
as-told-to. I'm my own author. And I don't do Diana books. What
could draw me to this?''
</P>
<P>
   But after meeting with Trevor and his mother and stepfather,
Jill and Ernie Rees-Jones, a month later, she was convinced there
was a more important, human story to be told.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are really two books. The one I was drawn to is this
extraordinary story of this ordinary family under extraordinary
pressures surviving and holding on to their souls,'' she said.
``There's no book in the world I would write unless I felt it was
worth telling, and that it would contribute some insight into the
human condition and history's record.''
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the Rees-Jones' had resisted offers to sell their
story. During the final push to polish the manuscript, the stoic,
32-year-old former paratrooper ruefully observed how he could have
accepted $1 million _ more than he'll likely make in book royalties
_ from the National Enquirer for only a half day's work. But the
former bodyguard eventually decided he needed to regain his
credibility after Fayed publicly blamed him for the crash.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
