<DOCNO> NYT20000328.0280 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0528 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-DIANA-WRITER-ART-2NDT     03-28 0420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIANA-WRITER-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
NAPA, Calif.: the crash.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Johnston decided to write in the third person, going beyond
Rees-Jones to gain perspective of his story while he was
incapacitated in the hospital. To reduce the risk of leaks, she and
Carlisle kept her sources to only six beyond Trevor: his parents,
his fellow bodyguard Kez Wingfield and three lawyers through whom
she gained information from the official crash investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston devised an elaborate story to throw off townsfolk in
Oswestry during the month she spent toiling in a small rental
cottage. She and her sister, Sheilagh Simpson of Vancouver, British
Columbia, who assisted in transcribing 100 hours of tape, posed as
ordinary American tourists doing genealogical research.
</P>
<P>
   She took cabs to town, taking different routes and asking to be
dropped off several blocks from Trevor's alley. She kept a map and
guidebooks at hand to throw over her work whenever the cleaning
lady or repairmen dropped by. During the writing of the book, the
sisters kept e-mail cryptic.
</P>
<P>
   ``My physical fear, frankly, was from the crazies who if they
got wind of it, wouldn't want anyone challenging the conspiracy
theories,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   She had one terrifying moment when a van load of neatly dressed
men with rifles poured out onto her lane. They turned out to be
pheasant hunters.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   The web of secrecy was maintained during marketing of the book,
when Carlisle presented Johnston's 80-page proposal to publishers
in secret at a London hotel only after they had signed
confidentiality agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Several turned it down, fearful of the litigious Fayed. Little,
Brown in London finally took it on.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston, who has two grown children and is married to Dr. Alvin
Lee Block, an internist, remained largely in the shadows while the
laconic and media shy Rees-Jones last week endured a punishing
interview schedule in New York before returning to England in hopes
of regaining his life. That's fine with Johnston, who said it was
always understood ``it was Trevor's story.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you've read this book,'' she said, ``you're going to see
that if anyone deserves to get on with his life peaceably, it's
this honorable, decent young man who has told his story truthfully.
To me, the power is in its truthfulness.''
</P>
<P>
   (Meg McConahey writes for The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa,
Calif. The Press Democrat is part of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
