<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0529 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-ISS-KLAUS29-COX     03-28 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISS-KLAUS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Young owner of ISS gives $15 million to would-be alma mater
Georgia Tech
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Young tech entrepreneur Christopher Klaus has given
$15 million to a university where he has yet to earn a diploma.
</P>
<P>
   The donation, the fifth-largest ever to Georgia Tech, will be
used _ pending approval by the Board of Regents _ to help build an
advanced computing complex that will be named for Klaus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been a big believer in education as a driver in
helping the economy and helping society as a whole,'' Klaus said,
interviewed a few hours before teaching a class in the Georgia Tech
College of Computing. ``The point of living isn't to see how much
money you can make. The point is to do something to improve
peoples' lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Klaus said the natural beneficiary for his charity is Georgia
Tech, the school that taught him how to be an engineer, the place
where he teaches part-time _ for free _ despite having no degree.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Georgia Tech wouldn't have been willing to pass him the
parchment. It's just that in the mid-1990s, Klaus departed academia
to give more attention to the startup company he had founded in his
dorm room.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Internet Security Systems stock is worth $5.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which develops and sells software aimed at
protecting networks from intruders, had revenues last year of $116
million and lists among its customers 21 of the 25 largest U.S.
commercial banks, many of the largest telecommunications companies
and several dozen government agencies, including the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   Klaus hired Tom Noonan as chief executive to handle daily
operations and made himself his company's chief technology officer,
symbolically serving as guru, a back-lab whiz and grand old man of
a new industry.
</P>
<P>
   Klaus is 26 years old.
</P>
<P>
   While ISS has become a leading Internet security company,
success is not the work of one person _ or even one company, he
said. ``We have been fortunate to live in this time and age, and we
should do something to give back.''
</P>
<P>
   And what young Klaus has given is one of the largest donations
in Georgia Tech's history. Previous top-tier donations _ more than
$25 million from Lettie Pate Evans and similar amounts from George
W. and Irene K. Woodruff and Mrs. Lee Candler _ came largely in
deferred gifts from their estates, said Georgia Tech spokeswoman
Elizabeth Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Thomas E. DuPree Jr. has pledged more than $25
million.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Klaus' donation, ``the largest single outright
gift while living that Georgia Tech has ever received,'' Campbell
said.
</P>
<P>
   His beneficence will not leave Klaus broke.
</P>
<P>
   He has sold thousands of shares in ISS, presumably to diversify
his portfolio. But his remaining stake in the company he started is
presently worth about $700 million _ even after the stock took a
nasty tumble Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find him to be thoughtful, responsible and very
respectful,'' said Peter Freeman, Georgia Tech dean of computing.
``Typically, people who don't get degrees carry a chip on their
shoulder. Chris is not like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Klaus' contribution pushes the university past the $500 million
mark in its current campaign to raise cash for improvements.
Included in that campaign is a new complex for the college of
computing, which currently serves 1,300 undergraduates, 275
graduate students and more than 50 members of the faculty.
</P>
<P>
   Tentative plans call for a $50 million building, with design to
start later this year and construction beginning in 2001, said
Freeman, whose own position is endowed by John P. Imlay, an
entrepreneur of an earlier tech generation.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech alumni _ with or without degrees _ have been
especially generous, Freeman said: The university has received 75
gifts of $1 million or more in the last four years.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Klaus has broken new ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sets a very interesting mark, and my hope is that it will
trigger some additional contributions,'' Freeman said. ``I hope it
sets an example to other entrepreneurs, not just in Georgia, to
show that they can make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the surge of technology at the tail end of the 20th
century has meant the minting of many new millionaires _ and
billionaires. However, only a relative few have shifted into
heavy-duty philanthropy _ at least partly because the new wealth is
so fresh that many of them are still immersed in working the long
hours associated with amassing their fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Some have retired early, others have found the free-time urge to
write big checks.
</P>
<P>
   Alicia Philipp, president of the Community Foundation for
Greater Atlanta, said the typical donor used to be a man older than
65, someone thinking about a legacy to be left behind. Klaus
represents a new wave, she said. ``I really believe that
entrepreneurs in high-tech are going to dominate philanthropy.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who count their money in seven, eight and nine
figures, giving it away has become news _ maybe even trendy.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Turner, CNN founder and Time Warner vice chairman, pledged
$1 billion to the United Nations and has begun writing $100 million
checks annually.
</P>
<P>
   James Clark, founder of Netscape and Healtheon, gave $150
million last year to Stanford University to build a biomedical
engineering center.
</P>
<P>
   Kenan Sahin, founder of Kenan Systems, gave $100 million to MIT
after he sold his company to Lucent Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft founder Bill Gates and his wife, Melinda, last year
gave away an estimated $2.4 billion _ still a fraction of their
wealth.
</P>
<P>
   The Community Foundation for Greater Atlanta endeavors to link
causes to contributors, who _ unlike Klaus _ might not have a
specific beneficiary in mind. For instance, she has worked with
Bert Ellis, founder of IXL Corp., and his wife, who have said they
want to give away 90 percent of their wealth in their lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis last year gave Georgia Tech's DuPree School of Management
an initial endowment of $1 million to fund a center for e-commerce
and promised to raise an additional $4 million for the school over
five years. In 1996, Parker H. Petit, founder of the Healthdyne
companies, donated $5 million to Georgia Tech to found a center for
bioengineering and bioscience.
</P>
<P>
   Like Ellis, many donors come from the new-monied class of
technology entrepreneurs, many of them far younger than previous
generations of wealthy donors. The money-come-latelys commonly look
for nontraditional routes of contribution, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Klaus has chosen a conservative means of giving, the kind of
name-on-the-building project that Andrew Carnegie might have
recognized.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is really unlike the guys I have been running into,''
Philipp said. ``It will be interesting to see how much goes to
traditional charities and how much goes to completely new ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
