<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-EDUC-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH PROPOSES $5 BILLION PLAN TO FIGHT CHILD ILLITERACY 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Va.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT10 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOMERSET, N.J. _ Once again mooring traditionally Democratic
issues to his agenda, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas proposed a $5
billion program on Tuesday to address what he termed a national
literacy crisis among children.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the 5-year program would provide grants to states to
test reading in kindergarten and first grade, train teachers and
provide tutoring. He soberly contrasted the nation's economic
success with its educational failings, and declared that he would
bring the same improvements in reading on the national level that
he said he had achieved in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   He said every child should know how to read by third grade,
vowing that states that failed to increase student performance
would lose federal money. ``There is nothing more fundamental than
teaching our children how to read,'' Bush said in a speech Tuesday
afternoon in Reston, Va., the first in a series of events this week
intended to spotlight his commitment to improving education.
</P>
<P>
   ``America must confront a national emergency,'' he said. ``Too
many of our children cannot read. In the highest poverty schools _
I want you to hear this statistic _ in the highest poverty schools
in America, 68 percent of fourth-graders could not read at a basic
level in 1998.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush plan was quickly dismissed by aides to the Democratic
contender, Vice President Al Gore. They sought to shift attention
to Bush's tax cut proposal, saying that it would leave no money for
new education initiatives. Gore has called for $115 billion in new
federal financing for education over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Bush unveiled his plan as the Republican Party continued to
close ranks around him, with Steve Forbes endorsing him at a local
Republican event Tuesday night here in New Jersey, Forbes' home
state. In the primaries, Forbes, a millionaire publisher, had
pounded away at Bush as a weak-kneed conservative.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's chief rival in the primary, Sen. John McCain of Arizona,
has resisted an endorsement, but Bush called McCain on Tuesday in
an apparent bid to salve some of the lingering wounds. Bush said he
hoped that the two would meet soon, and described the conversation
as amiable.
</P>
<P>
   ``John and I both understand that the past is the past and it's
time to move forward,'' Bush told reporters aboard his campaign
plane.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's speech offered striking evidence of how he is returning
to what was his original strategy _ positioning himself as a
soft-edged, centrist Republican _ after veering to the right in the
primary to fend off McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking before a coalition of Asian-American groups at the
headquarters of the Student Loan Marketing Association, the
federally sponsored provider of student loans, he proclaimed that
the federal government had to redouble its efforts to confront the
educational plight of poor people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not tolerate illiteracy amongst the disadvantaged
students in the great country called America,'' he said. ``I know
this is something a little new. Others have proposed throwing money
at the problem. But they have proposed resources without reform.
That approach has no history of results, and really no prospect of
success. Under my plan new resources will be an instrument of
reform, not another investment in failure.''
</P>
<P>
   In an allusion to the Kerner Commission's description of racial
division, Bush said: ``More and more we are divided into two
nations: one that reads and one that can't. And therefore one that
dreams and one that doesn't. Reading is the basis for all learning,
and it must be the foundations for all other education.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bush is not abandoning his belief that the federal
government should not meddle in what is rightly a state and local
issue. Tuesday evening, appearing at a fund-raiser in Parsippany
with Gov. Christie Whitman, he spiritedly declared, as he often did
during the primaries, that he did not want to be the ``federal
superintendent of schools.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You are looking at the wrong man if you want me to be the
national principal,'' he said. ``I believe in local control of
schools. The best education policy is that which bubbles up from
the bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech in Virginia, Bush hewed a middle path, criticizing
Gore for seeking to spend large sums without demanding
accountability, and chiding some congressional Republicans for
saying that the federal Department of Education should be
abolished.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   He praised governors and mayors for their education reforms,
pointedly citing Democrats before Republicans. He even approvingly
referred to an anecdote about the importance of high standards told
by Albert Shanker, the late president of the American Federation of
Teachers, a bete noire of many Republican politicians, who say the
teachers unions are obstacles to change.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   While Bush sought a conciliatory tone, barely mentioning Gore in
the speech, the Gore campaign showed no such reticence. Douglas
Hattaway, a campaign spokesman, said the Bush plan would be
ineffective, and contended that the Clinton administration had
already established a successful national program to improve
reading.
</P>
<P>
   Hattaway also renewed the Gore campaign's criticism of Bush's
tax plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He won't have the money to pay for a new initiative like this
without dipping into the Social Security surplus or going back to
deficit spending,'' Hattaway said. ``He has to make a choice and he
hasn't said how he is going to pay. That is a very substantive
issue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
