<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGO-U.N.-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSPECTS FOR U.N. PEACEKEEPING MISSION IN CONGO QUESTIONED 
</HEADLINE>
   (corrects earlier misidentifications of Masire and Miyet)  
 (bl)  
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The chances that a U.N. peacekeeping mission
can actually be deployed in Congo were not looking good Tuesday as
the Security Council heard a briefing from the head of its
peacekeeping department, who recently visited the region.
</P>
<P>
   Council members, meeting in a closed-door session, were told
that factions were rearming, despite promises on all sides to end a
civil war and abide by a peace agreement reached last July.
</P>
<P>
   An African mediator, Sir Ketumile Masire of Botswana, briefed
council members Tuesday; he left Congo last week after being
blocked from traveling within the country.
</P>
<P>
   Undersecretary-General Bernard Miyet, the head of the
peacekeeping department, also informed the council that the Congo
government of Laurent Kabila had told him that the United Nations
would have to sign an accord covering its activities that would
impose unacceptable restrictions on the peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has encountered similar problems with Kabila
in the past. For more than a year, he blocked investigations into
accusations of massacres of Hutu refugees from Rwanda and of
Congolese reported to have taken place during Kabila's rise to
power in 1996-1997. More recently, he prevented U.N. liaison
officers from moving around the country to begin preparing for a
cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   In February, the Security Council decided to authorize a force
of about 1,000 soldiers and a 4,000-member support staff to back up
500 military observers who were assigned last fall to help put the
cease-fire into effect.
</P>
<P>
   But the council stated at the time that the force would not be
deployed until there was peace on the ground and adequate
assurances that all international personnel would be safe.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats said Tuesday it did not appear that the situation was
even close to meeting those requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Half a dozen African nations and several rebel groups are
involved in the Congo war. Miyet met with most of the protagonists
on his trip, among them Kabila and President Robert Mugabe of
Zimbabwe, who strongly supports Kabila. Miyet also held talks with
leaders in Namibia, Rwanda and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
   Rwanda and Uganda, once allies of Kabila, are now his enemies.
He accuses them of invading Congo and creating a rebellion that
would otherwise barely exist.
</P>
<P>
   In January, nearly all the national leaders engaged in the Congo
war came to New York for council meetings arranged by Richard C.
Holbrooke, the U.S. ambassador to the United Nations, who was
council president for the month. The leaders, while revealing deep
splits and distrusts, nevertheless pledged to support the peace
accord. Diplomats and officials almost immediately began to
question those assurances.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-00 2021EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000328.0284 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0532 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-CRUISE-TAX-COX     03-28 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRUISE-TAX-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CBy S.V. Date and Noah Bierman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE _ Florida's cruise industry got a lesson in
Tallahassee hardball Tuesday as a six-figure publicity campaign to
defeat a baseball stadium tax was struck out by a single lobbyist's
phone call.
</P>
<P>
   The industry seemed on the verge of taking an early lead by
seeing the $4-per-day passenger tax stall in its first committee
for yet another week. Then Aventura lobbyist Ron Book got to work.
</P>
<P>
   Strike one: Book told his aide to call a powerful ally, Senate
Majority Leader Jack Latvala.
</P>
<P>
   Strike two: Latvala returned to the committee room and pulled
aside chairman Sen. Lisa Carlton.
</P>
<P>
   Strike three: Carlton, just minutes after announcing she would
postpone a vote on the idea until next week, told the packed room
that the committee would in fact vote before meeting's end.
</P>
<P>
   A one-week delay could have been a fatal blow to Florida Marlins
owner John Henry's attempt to make cruise ship passengers from the
Port of Miami pay for most of a new $400 million stadium. The
proposal must clear three committees in the Senate and an unknown
number in the House before the chambers can vote.
</P>
<P>
   So when Carlton, R-Sarasota, told the assembled lobbyists and
750 cruise ship workers flown in for the day that she intended only
to hear public testimony on the matter Tuesday and take the vote
next week, the cruise industry seemed to have won a minor victory _
only to see it evaporate minutes later when she reversed herself
and cut off public comments to hold the vote.
</P>
<P>
   The measure to allow Miami-Dade voters to decide on the tax in a
referendum cleared the committee 7-1. Cruise industry lobbyists
felt stung that their leader _ Celebrity Cruise President Richard
Sasso _ wasn't given time to address committee members before the
vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a $4 pina colada. It's a $40 million tax on
tourism,'' Sasso said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Book acknowledged having an aide call Latvala _ who was not on
the committee and therefore couldn't vote _ but only to let him
know that the bill was being considered.
</P>
<P>
   Latvala denied Book had called him and denied telling Carlton to
push ahead with the vote. Carlton also denied that Latvala had
anything to do with her decision, which she said was based on her
assessment that controversy on the issue had been resolved _ at
least within her committee.
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins donated $111,795 to the state Republican Party
between May 27 and Dec. 10 last year. On the national level, Henry
has been active in Democratic fund-raising. Last year, he hosted
Bill Clinton at his Boca Raton home for an event that was expected
to raise $500,000 for the Democratic Congressional Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Marlins officials called the questions about political
maneuvering a distraction from their primary message _ that voters
deserve the opportunity to decide whether to use tax money for a
ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little concerned after 22 years (in public office) when
people are afraid to let the voters decide on an issue,'' said Sen.
Ron Silver, D-North Miami Beach, the bill's sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   Cruise industry lobbyist Curt Kiser, himself a former senator,
said the proposal might have a constitutional problem: taxing a
ship based on how long it stays out of port, even though most of
that time is spent in international waters.
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials from five cruise lines chartered three planes
and filled them with 750 employees who got the day off to carry
placards around the Capitol. A calypso band played Ray Parker Jr.'s
hit Ghostbusters. The employees said they believed jobs were on the
line.
</P>
<P>
   Cruise tax opponents _ who include all Miami-Dade commissioners
_ lost the effort of a key ally when senators added an amendment to
the bill that would exclude Broward County from potentially being
included in the tax. The bill had been worded to allow a similar
tax in Broward in the next three years if cruise traffic there
reaches 1.8 million passengers a year, as expected.
</P>
<P>
   That cleared the way for committee member Steve Geller,
D-Hallendale, to add his tentative support. Geller said with
Broward out, he was considering the tax a Miami-Dade issue and
would vote according to a poll he took of the seven Dade senators.
Most observers, however, see the cruise tax as somewhat of a
longshot.
</P>
<P>
   Should it pass and become law, generally anti-tax Republican
leaders will have to explain this sentiment, contained in the text
of the Senate bill: ``Every passenger embarking on a multi-day
cruise initiating its voyage from a major cruise ship port ... is
exercising a taxable privilege under this act.''
</P>
<P>
   Latvala, R-Palm Harbor, said he had no problem with that
language, nor with the idea of taxing cruise ship passengers _
rather than baseball ticket buyers _ to build a baseball stadium.
He said cruise ships generally do not pay federal income tax,
social security tax, state sales tax, or any number of other taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they're overburdened with taxes,'' Latvala said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they ought to contribute to the community.''
</P>
<P>
   -- sv date(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   -- noah-bierman(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
