r a BC-FLORIDA-LOTTO-COX     03-28 0366
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLORIDA-LOTTO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida's Lotto at $80 million
 &HT;    By Clay Lambert
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Monday night Jamie Orlowitz's dinner guests inexplicably threw
away their fortune cookie slips, somehow missing the winning
lottery numbers printed plainly on the back.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight Orlowitz figures they will be sorry.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday morning Orlowitz fished those slips out of the trash,
drove from Boca Raton to the Delray News and Tobacco Center on East
Atlantic Avenue and ordered up tickets for tonight's $80 million
Florida Lotto drawing _ tickets bearing those numbers hidden under
the noodles from the night before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will win,'' she said, noting that she often buys tickets at
the newsstand because of a positive ``energy'' in the small room
packed with newspapers and magazines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in the stars,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. Maybe not. But one thing is clear: Orlowitz isn't the
only one seeing stars over tonight's 11 p.m. lottery drawing.
</P>
<P>
   The lottery jackpot has now rolled over eight times. Sales of
tickets prior to Saturday's failed drawing peaked at 7 p.m. that
day when frenzied purchasers statewide bought tickets at a rate of
27,000 per minute, according to Florida Lottery calculations.
</P>
<P>
   This is the sixth highest jackpot in the 12-year history of the
state lottery. It is the highest jackpot currently on the table
among 40 state or multi-state games, lottery spokesman Roger
Sockman said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the line for tickets formed early Tuesday at a
Publix in Wellington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you could say it's an investment,'' said accountant
Charles Dunagin, who stood there in his business suit buying $25
worth of tickets. ``And a pretty good return if it pays off. But
I'm really here because it reached my threshold of interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's drawing apparently holds enough drama to capture the
attention of the very well-heeled. Richard Block of Palm Beach
Gardens picked up a slew of lottery tickets for a friend at the
Publix on Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't give you his name, but he's worth many millions,''
Block said.
</P>
<P>
   claylambert(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
