<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROFIT-TAKING AND COHEN ANNOUNCEMENT LEAVE STOCKS DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices declined Tuesday, as investors took
profits in a number of companies that have been big winners so far
this year and Abby Joseph Cohen, the influential stock market
strategist at Goldman, Sachs, announced that she had pared the
exposure to stocks in her model portfolio to 65 percent, a
reduction of 5 percent. It is the first time that Cohen has reduced
the recommended stock allocation in the portfolio since January
1999.
</P>
<P>
   Intel, which has risen sharply since Jan. 1 and had a good run
on Monday, was a big drag on major market indexes. The chipmaker's
stock price fell 7 Tuesday, to 135 11/16.
</P>
<P>
   The decline helped to pull the Dow Jones industrial average down
89.74 points, or 0.8 percent, to 10,936.11. Hewlett-Packard and IBM
were also major contributors to the Dow's decline.
</P>
<P>
   Intel, Cisco Systems and Sun Microsystems were big losers among
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, which slumped 16.13 points,
or 1.1 percent, to 1,507.73.
</P>
<P>
   Those same stocks and other technology companies that trade on
the Nasdaq stock market combined to generate a big slide in the
Nasdaq composite index. The index fell 124.67, or 2.5 percent, to
4,833.89.
</P>
<P>
   And widespread selling of smaller technology issues was
instrumental in a 2.5 percent decline in the Russell 2000 index,
which closed at 559.04, down 14.61.
</P>
<P>
   With the quarter winding down and no substantive economic
reports expected until April 7, when March employment data will be
released, traders said there was no fundamental catalyst that
triggered the selloff.
</P>
<P>
   Before the markets opened, however, Cohen announced she had
pared the exposure to stocks in her model portfolio to 65 percent,
a reduction of 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Even as she reduced her equity weighting, Cohen maintained her
recently increased end-of-the-year estimate on the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index at 1,575. And she did not cut her forecast for
corporate earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Traders and analysts said the change in Cohen's position hardly
qualified as a major shift in sentiment. Still, it probably served
as a catalyst for profit taking.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the nice rally the market had last week, we were cruising
for a bruising,'' said Bryan Piskorowski, a market analyst at
Prudential Securities. ``And as we wait for a decision on oil
production out of OPEC, a possible settlement in the Microsoft case
and first-quarter earnings numbers, we are in a bit of a news
vacuum.''
</P>
<P>
   Trading activity picked up a bit from Monday, but was quite
subdued compared with the recent hectic pace. On the New York Stock
Exchange, 959.1 million shares changed hands. Volume on the Nasdaq
stock market was 1.5 billion shares. ``The markets feel quieter in
all areas, from the Big Board to Nasdaq to flows in international
stocks,'' said Jonathan Olesky, head of block trading at Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter. ``Normally, you would expect to see more
quarter-end dynamics. It is almost as if investors have their
portfolios in order and are letting the quarter go out on its
own.''
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks, which for the most part took a hit on Monday,
bounced back a bit Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Among Dow stocks, American Express rose 2, to 152; J.P. Morgan
gained 1 7/8, to 133; and Citigroup closed at 61, up 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   A decline in oil prices led to a healthy gain in airline stocks.
</P>
<P>
   UAL Corp., parent of United Air Lines, climbed 5/8, to 59 5/8.
AMR, parent of American Airlines, rose 1 5/16, to 32 7/16. And
Delta Air Lines rose 2 3/4, to 54 3/4.
</P>
</TEXT>
