<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBMD-PRESIDENT29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    First woman to head ABC tapped for Healtheon/WebMD top slot
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Patricia Fili-Krushel, the first woman to run one of
the major networks, was named head of Healtheon/WebMD's consumer
division Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Fili-Krushel, who had been president of ABC Television, will
oversee WebMD Health as its president and chief executive officer.
That unit includes WebMD TV, a joint effort by WebMD and Fox
Television. The channel is expected to be launched this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Healtheon/WebMD, based in Atlanta, hired Fili-Krushel with the
hope that her experience will allow her to find ways to help draw
visitors to its consumer site, www.webmd.com. Fili-Krushel begins
her new job April 10 and could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The online company is relying on research that shows women make
most of the health care choices in families, said Reggie Bradford,
chief marketing officer. Fili-Krushel, 46, brings a strong
background in developing programming aimed at women.
</P>
<P>
   Before being named head of ABC in 1998, she was in charge of
daytime television for the network. Fili-Krushel is largely
credited with launching ``The View,'' a daytime talk show.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to that, she was an executive with Lifetime, a cable
channel that describes itself as ``television for women.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She has a proven ability to attract a female audience,''
Bradford said.
</P>
<P>
   Fili-Krushel will work out of WebMD-TV's New York headquarters,
said Jeff Arnold, Healtheon/WebMD's chief executive.
Healtheon/WebMD's consumer division employs more than 200 people,
Bradford said.
</P>
<P>
   Healtheon /WebMD is something of an online health care
conglomerate, if such a thing is possible for a nascent company
with no profits. Besides its consumer division, the company also is
trying to move health care transactions _ insurance verification,
doctor billing, laboratory results _ to the Internet. The goal is
to link doctors, insurance companies and patients through the
Internet and make money, in part, off the transactions.
</P>
<P>
   It is also trying to make its consumer-oriented site the place
patients turn to for health information, discussion and
health-related purchases.
</P>
<P>
   When its February acquisition of OnHealth Network closes later
this year, WebMD.com will be one of the 50 most frequently visited
Web sites, Bradford said. It is already one of the top
health-related sites.
</P>
<P>
   Fili-Krushel joined ABC in 1975 as a secretary in the sports
department. She was named president of the network in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   She was named one of 18 ``Women Who Will Rule for the Coming
Era'' by iVillage, a Web site geared toward women.
</P>
<P>
   Fili-Krushel ``is not just one of the most powerful women in the
world of television, she is one of the most powerful people in the
business,'' iVillage wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Disney, which owns ABC, was asking ABC executives to move to
Burbank, Calif., where Disney is based. Fili-Krushel has been based
in Manhattan and, according to Tuesday's Wall Street Journal, was
reluctant to move.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
