u w BC-BUDGET-REPUBS-NYT     03-28 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-REPUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE REPUBLICANS PUSH TAX, SPENDING PLAN
</HEADLINE>
 (mg) 
By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate Republicans on Tuesday moved ahead on
several fronts with their tax-and-spending proposals, calling for a
tax reduction for married couples, setting out a budget plan that
seeks to restrain government growth and laying the groundwork for a
vote on reducing gasoline taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Budget Committee took up a budget outline written by
Sen. Pete Domenici, the Republican from New Mexico who is the
panel's chairman, that called for an increase in spending next year
on education and the military, cutting or freezing many other
domestic programs and reducing taxes by at least $150 billion over
the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democrats attacked the plan even before Domenici had
released details, saying it required unrealistic and damaging cuts
in domestic spending and put the nation's fiscal health at risk in
a headlong rush to pass an election-year tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   Domenici's proposal closely tracked the Republican budget plan
passed last week by the House. Unlike the House bill, however, the
Senate version specifically calls for repeal of the 4.3 cents a
gallon tax on gasoline passed by Congress in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Republican lawmakers have been seeking ways to offset rising
gasoline prices and to criticize President Clinton and Vice
President Al Gore, who had pushed hard for the 1993 tax increase,
for failing to pursue an effective energy policy.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate might hold a procedural vote later this week on a
Republican plan that would repeal the 4.3 cents a gallon tax for
the rest of this year and suspend the entire 18.4 cents a gallon
gasoline tax whenever average prices at the pump exceed $2 a
gallon. Although they vary by region, prices have so far remained
well below $2.
</P>
<P>
   Domenici offered his budget plan only after several weeks of
negotiations with conservatives within his own party who wanted
less spending. Sen. Phil Gramm of Texas, whose vote Domenici needed
to hold the Republican ranks together and pass the plan in the
committee, agreed to go along only after receiving assurances from
Senator Trent Lott of Mississippi, the Republican leader, that the
Senate would not take up a supplemental spending bill this year.
</P>
<P>
   The House is moving toward consideration of a bill that would
spend up to $9 billion this year on several programs and projects,
a amount that fiscal conservatives like Gramm consider excessive.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said he would try not to allow consideration of a catchall
supplemental bill in the Senate. He said he would seek instead to
have roughly $5 billion for the most pressing needs, including
money for the peacekeeping effort in Kosovo, antidrug efforts in
Colombia and aid for victims of hurricanes, be considered as part
of the regular appropriations process.
</P>
<P>
   The maneuvering over the budget came as Republicans pressed
their plans to force a showdown with Clinton over tax cuts. Sen.
William V. Roth Jr. of Delaware, the chairman of the Senate Finance
Committee, proposed a package of tax cuts for married couples that
totals $240 billion over 10 years, $58 billion more than contained
in a similar measure passed last month by the House.
</P>
<P>
   As they did in the House, Republicans portrayed the proposal as
a reduction in the so-called marriage penalty tax suffered by many
two-income couples. But its benefits, including an increase in the
standard deduction and an expansion of the 15 percent tax bracket
for married couples filing jointly, would also go to couples who do
not suffer any marriage penalty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
