A0553 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE-JACKSON29-COX     03-28 0381
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-JACKSON29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jackson to meet with group organizing Coca-Cola bus `ride for
justice'
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Rev. Jesse Jackson is scheduled to meet in Atlanta
today with former and current Coca-Cola employees who have been
trying to pressure the company to quickly settle a racial
discrimination lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting between Jackson, president of the Rainbow/PUSH
Coalition, and the group organizing a ``ride for justice'' to
Coca-Cola's annual shareholders meeting next month is another
signal that the case is gaining national attention.
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, Jackson may announce his support for the
protest ride, which will hold rallies in Greensboro, N.C.,
Richmond, Va., and Washington, D.C., before arriving at the annual
meeting in Wilmington, Del., on April 19.
</P>
<P>
   The company declined to comment Tuesday on Jackson's visit.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers say more than 50 people already have signed up for
the three-bus convoy, which will transport about 150 former and
current employees to the shareholders meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson will hold talks with Larry Jones, a former Coca-Cola
manager and chief organizer of the bus trip, as well as a small
group of former and current employees, said Joe Beasley, regional
director of Rainbow/PUSH.
</P>
<P>
   The 9 a.m. meeting will be held at Rainbow/PUSH's Atlanta office
in the Atlanta Life Insurance building. Jackson will hold a press
conference at 9:30 a.m., Beasley said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit and bus trip have gained considerable media
attention lately.
</P>
<P>
   The federal suit, filed by eight current and former employees,
alleges that Coca-Cola has discriminated against African-Americans
in pay, promotions and performance evaluations.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs are seeking class-action status so they can
represent about 2,000 current and former black salaried employees
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The company has denied the suit's allegations and opposed the
plaintiffs' efforts to make it a class-action case.
</P>
<P>
   Settlement talks, facilitated by a court-ordered mediator, are
currently scheduled to take place on April 17 and 18 _ in the
middle of the bus trip and right before the shareholders meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
