<HEADER>
A0554 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CLINTON-SCFLAG29-COX     03-28 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCFLAG29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Flag boycott taking toll on some S.C. blacks
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ President Clinton's visit today to the last
state capital to fly the Confederate flag would seem a natural
rally for opponents of the controversial banner. But one of the
flag's leading foes, the NAACP, expects few of its representatives
to attend the state Democratic Party fund-raiser at predominantly
black Allen University.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's visit illustrates how the NAACP's national economic
boycott of South Carolina is exacting a cost on black organizations
that support it.
</P>
<P>
   The $500-per-person dinner will honor U.S. Rep. Jim Clyburn,
chairman of the Congressional Black Caucus. The Columbia Democrat
said he'll look for an opportunity to criticize the flag and that
he expects Clinton to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   But Dwight James, executive director of the NAACP's South
Carolina Conference, said, ``We are not encouraging any people to
attend. We are hopeful that any visitors coming in for the dinner
will not stay in hotels or frequent other tourist venues in
Columbia.''
</P>
<P>
   James, who does not plan to attend, said he is concerned that
``the call for sanctions not be violated. I would commend
(organizations) for bearing the inconvenience, despite the
short-term pain that it might cause.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People
vows to continue the boycott until South Carolina's Legislature
votes to remove the flag from the Statehouse. It has flown atop the
dome since 1962, when legislators raised it as part of a Civil War
centennial, a gesture critics say was actually a slap at
integration.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Sunday, Charleston Mayor Joseph Riley will lead a
five-day march from Charleston to Columbia. He hopes the march will
pressure legislators to remove the flag, which Riley said portrays
the state as clinging to the past, when, in fact, polls show a
majority of South Carolinians want it taken down.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of Confederate symbols has become a racial divide
touching other states. In Alabama this week, black lawmakers
angered that Gov. Don Siegelman declared April ``Confederate
History and Heritage Month'' asked him to amend the proclamation to
include a condemnation of slavery. A Siegelman spokeswoman said the
governor ``certainly condemns slavery'' but the proclamation has
been issued and cannot be amended.
</P>
<P>
   In Columbia, opposing sides in the flag fight say they're
willing to consider one of the latest legislative proposals _ a
plan to display on the Statehouse grounds two authentic flags of
the Confederacy as well as a flag carried by black Union soldiers
from South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   But David Swinton, president of predominantly black Benedict
College in Columbia, is worried that legislators will fail to agree
on a plan before the Legislature adjourns in June, extending the
controversy and the NAACP's boycott. It already has been an
inconvenience, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Benedict men's basketball team traveled to
Charlotte for its conference tournament. It had been relocated from
Orangeburg, about 40 miles south of Columbia, to comply with the
NAACP's boycott. ``We are willing to make the sacrifice,'' said
Swinton.
</P>
<P>
   Some big names are, too, or are thinking about it:
</P>
<P>
   _ Black tennis star Serena Williams, the reigning U.S. Open
champ, said she may skip April's tournament at Hilton Head Island
because of the flag. ``Maybe I won't play. ... I'm not going to
support anything that's putting down my race,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   _ State Sen. Darrell Jackson (D-Columbia), who opposes the flag,
has called for Tiger Woods to skip next month's MCI Classic golf
tournament at Hilton Head.
</P>
<P>
   _ The New York Knicks decided to stop holding their NBA playoff
training camp in Charleston until the flag is removed.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hip-hop performer Wyclef Jean canceled a recent concert in
Charleston. _ Internationally known dancer/choreographer Bill T.
Jones withdrew from Charleston's Spoleto arts festival in May.
</P>
<P>
   _ Other performers, including the O'Jays and Patti LaBelle,
canceled plans for South Carolina performances. Attendance at the
National Black Family Summit at Myrtle Beach two weeks ago was only
about half that of previous years because of the boycott, officials
said. In the small, majority-black town of Atlantic Beach, along
South Carolina's Grand Strand, the Town Council urged the
Legislature to put the flag in a museum. But town officials refused
to cancel the economically important black bikers' festival over
Memorial Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   By its own admittedly ``unscientific estimate,'' the NAACP's
boycott has cost South Carolina more than $100 million in tourism
and related businesses, the state NAACP's James said.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted some ``major cancellations'' soon that will bolster
growing support for the flag's removal. Confederate heritage groups
disagree. ``They've had a few rock stars who did not come, but the
boycott has not worked,'' said Elijah Coleman, a Mableton, Ga.,
member of the Sons of Confederate Veterans. His group and several
similar heritage groups are urging supporters to vacation in South
Carolina to counteract the boycott. If, in fact, the NAACP boycott
has resulted in a loss of $100 million, flag supporters said, that
would represent around 1 percent of the state's economic activity,
bolstered by last year's record $6.4 billion in capital
investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``This boycott is a burp in a whirlwind,'' said state Sen. Glenn
McConnell (R-Charleston), a leading flag supporter. ``It has
strengthened the resolve for a presence of the flag.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
