<HEADER>
A0560 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-AL-AMIN29-COX     03-28 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AL-AMIN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Al-Amin indicted; selection of lead defense attorney surprises
some
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The indictment Tuesday of Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin in
the murder of a sheriff's deputy may have come as no surprise, but
the selection of his lead defense attorney did.
</P>
<P>
   After rumblings from celebrity attorneys from Atlanta to
California and talk of a ``dream team,'' Al-Amin, the 1960s black
militant once known as H. Rap Brown, selected Michael Mears, who
defends indigent suspects in murder cases across Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin met with Mears on Friday at the Montgomery, Ala., jail
where he has been confined since his capture March 20.
</P>
<P>
   Mears is the most experienced death penalty defender practicing
in Georgia, with more than 30 such cases handled, but he wants
nothing to do with any publicity-seeking ``dream team.''
</P>
<P>
   Several more lawyers will be selected for the defense team, he
said, ``but none of them are going to be holding press conferences
and making pontifical statements.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been far too many lawyers making too many
statements about what is or isn't going to happen,'' Mears said. To
make his point, he declined comment on the indictment issued by the
Fulton County Grand Jury.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Paul Howard announced the indictment at a
mid-afternoon news conference. It accuses Al-Amin, 56, with 13
offenses, including five counts of murder.
</P>
<P>
   Fulton County Deputies Ricky Kinchen, 35, and Aldranon English,
28, were trying to serve a Cobb County warrant on Al-Amin the night
of March 16 when a man standing beside a black Mercedes outside
Al-Amin's storefront abruptly opened fire on them with a rifle and
a handgun, according to English.
</P>
<P>
   Kinchen was killed; English was seriously wounded. The next day,
English picked Al-Amin out of a photo lineup as the man who shot
him.
</P>
<P>
   The warrants they were trying to serve stemmed from Al-Amin's
failure to appear in court on relatively minor charges _ theft by
receiving a stolen car, impersonating an officer and no proof of
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference Tuesday, Howard confirmed tests showed
the .223 caliber Ruger Mini-14 carbine and Browning Hi-Power pistol
recovered when Al-Amin was arrested in Alabama were the same
weapons that fired ``the cases left at the scene and the
projectiles recovered from the body of Deputy Kinchen.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Gov. Roy Barnes signed the extradition papers Tuesday
afternoon and Howard said he expects Barnes will send the papers to
Alabama today. But if Al-Amin's Alabama attorneys fight the
extradition as promised, it could take ``30 to 60 days to get him
back here.''
</P>
<P>
   Extradition papers for Al-Amin must be physically presented to
the Alabama governor's legal staff, so it will be today or Thursday
before Alabama gets them, according to Alabama Gov. Don Siegelman's
office.
</P>
<P>
   Howard said he would consult with Kinchen's family before
deciding to ask for the death penalty, but it is virtually
automatic in the case of a peace officer killed in the line of
duty.
</P>
<P>
   Mears said if the district attorney decides not to seek the
death penalty, he would withdraw from the case.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff Jackie Barrett said the indictment ``really begins to
breathe life back into the department.''
</P>
<P>
   She said English ``wants to come back to work, and we want him
back, but it will be a long recovery.'' The deputy is at home under
constant guard, and while neither Barrett nor Howard would go into
specifics, Barrett said, ``We're not going to expose him
unnecessarily.''
</P>
<P>
   No motive has been officially ascribed to the killing, but some
law enforcement authorities believe it had to do with Al-Amin's old
Mercedes. Atlanta police said the tag to the car had been found in
Alabama, but the car had not been located as of late Tuesday.
Howard said he had no comment on the role the auto played, or a
motive.
</P>
<P>
   Howard said Al-Amin's suggestion at an Alabama court appearance
that his arrest was part of a government conspiracy is
``ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Mears declined to comment directly on the conspiracy suggestion.
``The lawyers that will be representing him will focus on the
issues,'' he said. ``I haven't seen anything that would lead me to
believe that we have any need to focus on anything but the
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The issues, he said, are simply whether Al-Amin is guilty or
innocent of the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Mears said Al-Amin's wife Karima, an attorney who handles
immigration cases, and his brother, Ed Brown, who works for an
Atlanta engineering firm, ``are in contact with several attorneys
to assist us.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Mears nor Brown would reveal any names, but Mears said
``certainly I have input'' as to who is chosen to be part of the
defense team.
</P>
<P>
   Mears, 56, is director of the Multi-County Public Defender
Office, a statewide agency devoted to defending penniless murder
defendants. He filed a motion Tuesday to have Al-Amin declared
indigent, although it won't be heard unless someone challenges it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defendant has no funds himself with which to pay an
attorney,'' Mears said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff writer Gita Smith
contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
