<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-WILLIAMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS GETS CONTRACT EXTENSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ In what has become an annual end-of-spring
exercise, Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette strolled into the
press room at City of Palms Park on Tuesday and announced the club
had extended manager Jimy Williams's contract through the 2001
season, which would take Williams to his 58th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is in his fourth season as Boston manager; if he
finishes the year, he will have held the job longer than any Sox
manager since Mike ``Pinky'' Higgins, back when Ike was President.
Higgins was hired in '55, fired on the 4th of July, 1959, then came
back the following June when his successor, Billy Jurges was fired,
and managed two more seasons.
</P>
<P>
   If he manages through the extension year, Williams will have the
longest unbroken term of any Sox manager since Hall of Famer Joe
Cronin, who managed the club for 12 seasons, 1935-47. Jimmy
Collins, the team's original manager (1901-05), is the only other
Sox skipper who has managed as many as five consecutive seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, typically, was disinclined to discuss his deal, which
he said was reached Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today it's more important to think about this roster and
figure this out,'' said Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Told of his standing among Sox managers, Williams chuckled. ``I
don't know anything about that,'' he said. ``I'm going to do my
best tomorrow. That's all I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 14 teams in the American League, only five have managers
who have been with the same team longer than Williams has been with
the Sox: the Twins' Tom Kelly (14th season), the Mariners' Lou
Piniella (eighth season), the Rangers' Johnny Oates (sixth season),
the Yankees' Joe Torre (fifth season), and the A's Art Howe (fifth
season).
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the deal were not announced, but CEO John Harrington
has said that Williams would be paid more than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimy's well-compensated,'' Duquette said. ``His contract
reflects his contribution. His results on the field speak for
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the third extension Williams has received as Sox manager
after signing a two-year deal to manage the club on Nov. 19, 1996.
Previously, he managed the Toronto Blue Jays for three seasons,
averaging 90 wins a season, before being fired with a 12-24 record
two months into the 1989 season.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox stuck with their policy of giving Williams just a
one-year extension, even though he has taken the team to the
postseason in each of the last two seasons. ``That's worked well
for us,'' Duquette said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it has, but other managers have been awarded longer,
more lucrative deals. Torre last year was given a two-year contract
extension and will be paid $3 million by the Yankees this season.
Phil Garner, fired by the Brewers last fall, was given a four-year
deal for close to $6 million by the Tigers. Tony La Russa of the
Cardinals reportedly is being paid $1.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Williams's contract, meanwhile, probably comes closer to the
$1.4 million Felipe Alou reportedly is being paid by the Montreal
Expos.
</P>
<P>
   You'll never find that out from talking with Williams, though.
Asked if negotiations were protracted, he feigned ignorance.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does that mean?'' he asked. ``I'm fine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-00 2056EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
