<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATRICK-STEWART-THEATER-ART-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRICK STEWART'S UNFINISHED BUSINESS  
 FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 2) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036 or 888
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 Mervyn Rothstein, an editor in the Real Estate section of The New
York Times, frequently writes about theater.  
 By MERVYN ROTHSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Patrick Stewart's first ``Ride Down Mount Morgan,''
at the Joseph Papp Public Theater in 1998, brought him mixed
reviews and a mild concussion. So why has he decided to star again
in the Arthur Miller play _ this time on Broadway?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some roles that gnaw at you,'' the Royal Shakespeare
Company veteran and ``Star Trek: The Next Generation'' captain said
recently; he was taking a lunch break during rehearsals. ``Leontes
in `The Winter's Tale' is one, and Lyman Felt in `The Ride Down
Mount Morgan' is another. There's this impulse that I must do it
again, that I almost got it right, but not quite.''
</P>
<P>
   In the play, Stewart, 59, plays a bigamist who has led a
self-indulgent life; the character is in part Miller's comment on
the Reagan era. After a near-fatal automobile accident, Lyman is
visited by both his wives. And as he drifts in and out of
consciousness in a hospital bed, he slowly realizes that his
duplicity is about to be exposed and his double life is ending.
</P>
<P>
   The play's director at the Public Theater, David Esbjornson, has
returned for the Broadway production, as has Frances Conroy, who
portrays Theo, Lyman's Manhattan wife of 36 years, with whom he has
a daughter.
</P>
<P>
   New to the cast are Katy Selverstone as Leah, whom Lyman married
nine years earlier without divorcing Theo and with whom he lives on
an upstate farm, and Shannon Burkett as the daughter. The play
opens next Sunday at the Ambassador Theater for a limited run
through July 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the Public, we had only three weeks of rehearsals, four
counting the technical rehearsals, and we could only run for about
four weeks,'' Stewart said. ``So there wasn't much time.'' In all,
there were 29 performances.
</P>
<P>
   It was in the last three seconds of the 29th performance,
Stewart said, that ``something happened that somehow led me to
realize I couldn't let Lyman rest.'' The lights were dimming that
Sunday afternoon as Lyman lay in the hospital bed, with ``the face
of a man in agony, left alone, trying to face the future,'' Stewart
said. ``Suddenly, a tiny pin spotlight snapped. And as it snapped,
something fell from the grid and hit me on the head. I knew it was
metal because I heard it clang on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was stunned. I got out of the bed and went into the wings to
get ready for the curtain call. Somebody flashed a torch in my face
and screamed, because blood was pouring down. I went onstage for
the curtain call, and the audience gasped because blood was running
down my shirt. It turned out I had a mild concussion. I spent
Sunday evening in an emergency ward undergoing CAT scans and being
stitched up.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day, he flew to Los Angeles. ``On Wednesday or Thursday
I felt myself coming out of the mild shock I was in,'' he said.
``And somehow what I was left with was the absolute conviction that
`The Ride Down Mount Morgan' was unfinished business.''
</P>
<P>
   So what has Stewart learned about his character? ``In the old
days of the Royal Shakespeare Company, when we used to transfer
plays from Stratford to the Aldwych in the West End, there would
often be a three- or four-month gap,'' the actor said. ``That gap
was critical in fermenting the experience of the play. With `Mount
Morgan,' I've had more than a year.'' At the Public, Stewart added,
he explored Lyman's passion and energy. This time, the question is
what drives him.
</P>
<P>
   And the answer? ``Arthur Miller has helped us a great deal with
this,'' Stewart said. ``We've found that Lyman is running away from
death every single day of his life. That is the underpinning of
everything he attempts. So the next bit of action has got to be
even more intense and extreme and outrageous. In pushing these
extremes we've found that the play is funnier than we thought.
We've found much more comedy and much more passion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
