<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOSTER-LAWSUIT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUIT AIMS TO ESTABLISH NEW STANDARD OF CARE FOR FOSTER KIDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH TEICHROEB  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Washington state has failed to provide stable homes
for thousands of foster children, instead subjecting them to
repeated moves, neglect and even abuse, an unprecedented
class-action lawsuit claims.
</P>
<P>
   Billed as the first class-action suit in the country to target
the emotional damage inflicted when children are moved from home to
home, the goal is to force an overhaul of Washington's frayed
foster-care system, said attorney Tim Farris.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, which began as a case filed on behalf of 13 current
and former foster children, was recently expanded to class-action
litigation after a national child-advocacy group agreed to join
Farris as co-counsel.
</P>
<P>
   One of the goals of the lawsuit is to set a new standard of care
that can be followed in other states, Farris said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no excuse for the number of times children are being
moved,'' said Farris, who filed the original lawsuit in November
1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a biological parent abandoned a child in 29 different
homes, we'd call that neglect. That's exactly what the state does
when it brings these children into care and then abandons them with
strangers again and again.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the 13 children named in the lawsuit was moved 29 times
during her 14 years in foster care. As a result of those moves, the
girl, who is now 18, attended 20 different schools, had 19
different therapists and seven caseworkers. She suffers from
depression, doesn't trust anyone and has had two psychiatric
hospitalizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want a family,'' the girl told her foster-care
caseworker, according to notes subpoenaed from the Department of
Social and Health Services.
</P>
<P>
   After the Post-Intelligencer published a story last October
about Farris' original lawsuit, the case caught the interest of the
San Francisco-based National Center For Youth Law.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Grimm, an attorney with the youth law center, said they see
the case as an opportunity to tackle a problem that has plagued
child-welfare systems nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has got to stop,'' said Grimm.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the worst ways the system treats children is moving
them around. ... We want DSHS to learn a lesson _ that it is not
free or cheap to move these children around.''
</P>
<P>
   On the national scene, Washington's record on foster care is
somewhere in the middle of the list of best and worst states, Grimm
said.
</P>
<P>
   Almost two weeks ago, a judge in the Whatcom Superior Court
granted a motion which allowed the original lawsuit to be amended
to a class-action suit.
</P>
<P>
   Farris and Grimm plan to file a motion within the next month to
ask the court to certify the case as a class-action suit and hope
to get a trial date later this year.
</P>
<P>
   But assistant attorney general Jeff Freimund said the state will
oppose certification of the class-action suit.
</P>
<P>
   He said the case assumes all foster children are treated the
same way, and unfairly blames the state for psychological problems
which existed before they came into care.
</P>
<P>
   ``By definition, these children are victims of severely
dysfunctional upbringings,'' Freimund said. ``That seems to be a
more likely explanation (for their problems).''
</P>
<P>
   But Grimm said the state has known for years that foster
children were repeatedly being moved, and even commissioned an
in-house study of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state knows this is a serious problem but their actions
have belied their words,'' Grimm said. ``We want them to make this
a priority.''
</P>
<P>
   The state study published in 1996 found that 44 percent of
children who stay in care for one year or longer are moved three or
more times, while 15 percent of children in care more than a year
end up in five or more homes.
</P>
<P>
   About 28 percent of the state's 11,000 foster children are in
care longer than one year. Fifty percent of foster children go home
within two months, while the rest go home after two to 12 months in
care.
</P>
<P>
   Not only are some children moved frequently, the state often
fails to provide the mental-health and medical treatment they need
to recover from the abuse and neglect they've suffered, said
Farris.
</P>
<P>
   Foster parents are expected to cope with disturbed children
without being given background histories or the training and
support they need. As a result, the placement breaks down and
children are moved again, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the solution is providing intensive help to foster
parents and carefully assessing children's needs when they first
come into care so that they can be returned home, or adopted, as
soon as possible, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In other cases, leaving children in their homes would be less
traumatic than shuttling them between the homes of strangers, said
Grimm.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Hosford joined the original lawsuit on behalf of her
former foster son who has been in the state's care since he was an
infant. His birth mother was a 15-year-old foster child, while his
father, a convicted felon, also spent years in foster care.
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband took the boy into their Seattle home more
than four years ago when he was 7 years old, intending to adopt
him.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he arrived in their home, the boy had been moved
more than 10 times, had been sexually and physically abused and had
a multitude of behavior problems.
</P>
<P>
   After two agonizing years, the Hosfords were forced to halt the
adoption because the boy's sexual aggressiveness put their own
daughter at risk and the state had refused to pay for intensive
residential treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so excited about this lawsuit,'' said Hosford, who is the
boy's court-appointed guardian for the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it can reform the system, it's wonderful. ... I'm going to
tell him I'm fighting for him, and that this will make his life
better down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit will also seek financial compensation for the 13
current and former foster children named in the case.
</P>
<P>
   But the most important goal is pressuring DSHS and state
legislators to provide the kind of care foster children deserve,
said Grimm.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it means the state and the governor have to find more
resources, then, by God, they should,'' said Grimm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
