<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0566 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-IOWAST-BROWN-HNS &LR;      03-28 2708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-IOWAST-BROWN </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By DANNY ROBBINS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
In 30 years as a college basketball coach at various levels, Joedy
Gardner heard his share of unusual stories. But one he recounted
recently will always stand out.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner was coaching at Mesa (Ariz.) Community College last
spring when he learned his 7-foot center, Ernest Brown, had decided
to transfer after just one season to another junior college, Indian
Hills Community College in Ottumwa, Iowa. A New York City native
who signed with St. John's out of high school but failed to meet
NCAA freshman eligibility standards, Brown had just completed a
season in which he led the nation's junior-college players in
rebounding and field-goal percentage.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Ernest came in and told me he was going to transfer, my
first question was, `Why?''' Gardner said. ``He couldn't give me an
answer. Didn't have one.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were a young coach, I would have been bouncing all over
the place, but I didn't do that. I gave him about six or seven
reasons to stay. I said, `Give me one reason to go. If it's in your
best interests to leave, I'll help you.' He said, `I'll think about
it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of days later, he came back and said, `Personal
reasons.' I said, `Ernest, if I told the press you were leaving
because of personal reasons, they could believe anything.'
</P>
<P>
   ``About three days later, he and his girlfriend finally came up
with a reason. He said, `Well, we'll be closer to New York.'''
</P>
<P>
   Gardner believes Brown's decision to relocate to the Midwest
after only one season in Arizona was based on a different kind of
geography _ putting him on the doorstep of current Big 12
Conference powerhouse Iowa State.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's move to Indian Hills coincided with Iowa State's hiring
last spring of an obscure Mesa Community College employee named
Tres Chapman for an administrative position in the university's
athletic department.
</P>
<P>
   An academic adviser and assistant basketball coach at Mesa,
Chapman had been instrumental in recruiting Brown to the Arizona
junior college and helping him become eligible at the school.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Chapman was hired by Iowa State as the university's
athletic camp coordinator. Shortly thereafter, Brown transferred to
Indian Hills, 120 miles from the Iowa State campus in Ames, and
announced he would play college basketball at Iowa State.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner, for one, sees Iowa State's hiring of Chapman as little
more than a cheap recruiting maneuver and isn't shy about saying
so, raising questions about the methods of the Cyclones'
second-year coach, Larry Eustachy, at a time when his program has
gained national prominence. Winners of the Big 12 regular-season
and tournament titles, the Cyclones made an impressive NCAA
Tournament run that ended with a loss to Michigan State in the
Midwest Regional final.
</P>
<P>
   Asked recently what would have qualified Chapman to be hired as
Iowa State's athletic camp coordinator, Gardner laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had control of a 7-footer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For some college basketball programs, ``package deals''
involving recruits and those close to them, usually high school or
junior-college coaches, are an almost regular occurrence, a legal,
if occasionally awkward, recruiting tool.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation of Kansas' 1988 national championship was laid
when then-Jayhawks coach Larry Brown found a spot on his staff for
Ed Manning, a former professional basketball player working as a
truck driver in North Carolina. Enhancing Manning's resume was the
fact his son, Danny, was rated the top high school player in the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most important move Tom Penders made when he was
coaching at Texas was to hire Vic Trilli, the coach at Lon Morris
College in Jacksonville, thereby ensuring that several of Trilli's
players, including star forward Dexter Cambridge, would join the
Longhorns.
</P>
<P>
   Even by those standards, the Brown-Chapman scenario invites more
than the usual skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   Chapman, 33, had worked as an academic adviser for athletes and
assistant basketball coach at Mesa Community College for four years
when he was hired last spring as Iowa State's athletic camp
coordinator, a position that made him responsible for all
university-sponsored sports camps and clinics except those
involving football.
</P>
<P>
   Before working at Mesa, Chapman had been an assistant basketball
coach at a Phoenix high school.
</P>
<P>
   Based on his background, Chapman was an odd fit for the camp
coordinator's job as it was described by Iowa State in an ad
seeking applicants for the position last March in the NCAA News,
the NCAA's official publication. The qualifications outlined in the
ad included ``one to three years of experience as director of
multiple camps/clinics; experience in athletics administration or
closely related work experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The ad directed those interested in the position to send a
letter of application, a resume and the names, positions and phone
numbers of three references to J. Elaine Hieber, the university's
senior associate athletic director.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts by the Chronicle to contact Hieber over the last 10
days were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   After four months in the camp coordinator's job, Chapman was
shifted to the position of administrative assistant on the Iowa
State basketball staff, a move that followed Cyclones assistant
coach Steve Barnes' being named head coach at San Jose State in
August.
</P>
<P>
   Although Chapman's salary as camp coordinator, $28,200, was
slightly less than the $30,167 he had earned in his final year at
Mesa Community College, his salary increased 74 percent, to
$49,075, when he moved to the Iowa State basketball staff.
</P>
<P>
   Chapman declined to respond to questions regarding his job and
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I have no comment on those issues,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A hugely talented player with a spotty academic record at St.
Raymond's High School in the Bronx, Brown came to Mesa in 1998 as
something of a windfall, Gardner said, the result of recruiting
contacts Chapman had made in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Tres told me we had a shot at Ernest Brown, I said,
`You've got to be kidding. That guy is big-time,''' Gardner said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Gardner, Brown did not graduate with his class at
St. Raymond's but was able to complete requirements for his diploma
by taking summer classes in Arizona at Mesa High School, an
arrangement worked out by Chapman.
</P>
<P>
   Proving to be worth the effort, Brown averaged 22.7 points and
15.3 rebounds in leading Mesa Community College to a 27-5 record in
1998-99, the program's third-best record in 34 years.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner said Chapman made it known at the end of the season he
was going to be hired at Iowa State as an assistant basketball
coach but never said anything about a job directing the
university's sports camps.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner said he received a memo from Chapman last April 1 in
which Chapman said Eustachy had offered him a coaching position for
the 1999-2000 season. Chapman stated in the memo he would take the
job as soon as he received an official offer in writing from Iowa
State athletic director Gene Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner said he received another memo from Chapman on May 3 in
which Chapman said he had officially been offered a coaching
position at Iowa State and had accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Asked when he realized Chapman had actually been given an
administrative position at Iowa State, Gardner said: ``I don't know
that I ever did until somebody told me much later.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown's move to Iowa occurred during roughly the same time
period. He left Mesa without taking his final exams, which were
scheduled for May 10-13, and subsequently enrolled in summer school
at Indian Hills.
</P>
<P>
   On July 27, six weeks after Chapman had begun working at Iowa
State, the Des Moines Register reported that Brown had made an oral
commitment to sign with Iowa State.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, the father of three children, told the newspaper he
transferred to Indian Hills primarily because he would be able to
receive a full scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm going to do a year here, then go to Iowa State
and see how everything turns out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (According to Gardner, Brown did not qualify for a scholarship
in his first year at Mesa because he was not an Arizona resident
but would have been able to receive one in 1999-2000.)
</P>
<P>
   Brown signed a letter of intent with the Cyclones in November
but has since dropped out of Indian Hills and has indicated he
plans to make himself eligible for the NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner said he initially saw no reason to question Iowa State's
decision to hire Chapman because he knew Chapman had built a
relationship with Steve Barnes, then Eustachy's top assistant.
</P>
<P>
   But when Brown left for Indian Hills, apparently without a
compelling reason to do so, Gardner saw the matter in a different
light. No longer willing to play the good soldier, he contacted the
NCAA and the National Junior College Athletic Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``The connection is they hire Tres to bring Ernest _ period,''
he said. ``Everybody in the (college basketball) business knows
it.''
</P>
<P>
   For the NCAA, the issue is whether Chapman or others from Iowa
State had improper contact with Brown last spring and summer.
</P>
<P>
   As a player in the middle of his junior-college career, Brown
was off-limits to college recruiters except under certain
circumstances. Because Chapman was not hired as a coach at Iowa
State, he could not have been involved in off-campus recruiting for
the university under any circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   In a March 21 news release, Iowa State announced the NCAA had
looked into the university's recruitment of Brown and had been
``satisfied with the process.'' The two-paragraph release provided
no details.
</P>
<P>
   The university had previously confirmed it had received
correspondence from the NCAA regarding its men's basketball program
but had refused to make the documents public or discuss their
contents, contending the information was exempt from disclosure
under Iowa public records law because it related to a specific
prospective student-athlete.
</P>
<P>
   Although Iowa State mentioned Brown by name in its own news
release March 21, the university continued to take the position
that the correspondence relating to the matter was not subject to
public disclosure when the Chronicle requested it last week.
</P>
<P>
   Reacting to Iowa State's announcement indicating the NCAA had
found no irregularities in Brown's recruitment, Eustachy told the
Des Moines Register: ``I have said all along that we will run a
clean program here, and that is what we are doing. I hope that will
be the clear perception of this program now.''
</P>
<P>
   Eustachy, previously a head coach at Idaho and Utah State,
received a ringing _ and lucrative _ endorsement from Iowa State on
March 14 in the form of a new 10-year contract worth $900,000 per
year.
</P>
<P>
   While Brown's move to Iowa may indeed prove to be a footnote in
a dream season for Iowa State and Eustachy, it will be remembered
in a different light by Gardner and others at Mesa Community
College.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of losing Brown and several other key players, Mesa
went 9-21 in 1999-2000, a complete reversal from 1998-99. Gardner's
roster was so thin that at times he had only six available players.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, a player who had left the team following an
argument with Gardner, Raheem Oliver, went public with a claim that
the coach had sought to prevent Brown's transfer by trying to
persuade Mesa instructors to lower the player's grades.
</P>
<P>
   On March 13, Mesa announced that Gardner's contract would not be
renewed.
</P>
<P>
   According to Mesa's athletic director, Allen Benedict, the
school found no evidence to support the grade-manipulation charge
but still believed a change in the direction of the basketball
program was necessary.
</P>
<P>
   A plain-spoken ex-Marine fighter pilot who has been an NCAA
Division I head coach (at West Virginia and Northern Arizona) as
well as an assistant (Iowa), Gardner makes no bones about the fact
he notified the NCAA of the Brown-Chapman matter _ via an exchange
of e-mails with NCAA vice president for enforcement David Price
last summer _ but says he did so only because his superiors at Mesa
requested it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the culprit who supposedly snitched on Iowa State,''
Gardner said. ``Well, I didn't snitch on them. I was directed by
the athletic director and the administration here to submit the
information on Ernest Brown to the NJCAA and to contact the NCAA
and ask if we had any alternatives with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Gardner said it is his understanding that Eustachy threatened to
sue him for slander as a result of his actions, a notion he
considers laughable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't know Larry Eustachy if he walked in the room,'' he
said. ``I might recognize him, but I don't know the guy. Never had
a conversation with him. The only thing I know is he threatened me
with a lawsuit once, in July, and I didn't even know what the hell
he was talking about. He called our dean of students.''
</P>
<P>
   Mesa's dean of students, Brian Johnson, did not respond to phone
messages from the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner said Mesa officials initially believed the Brown-Chapman
situation warranted investigation but subsequently downplayed the
idea. He said he was kept out of the loop when an NCAA enforcement
representative visited Mesa to collect information regarding the
matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration here told me to just be quiet and they'd
handle it,'' he said. ``So I sat in a meeting (with the NCAA
investigator), but I didn't say much.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he kept a detailed chronology of the events surrounding
the departures of Brown and Chapman but did not share it with the
NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   According to one entry in the chronology, Gardner reported that
Chapman had been ``in and out'' of his office at Mesa after
resigning to go to Iowa State.
</P>
<P>
   ``Word I received is he's getting ready to move to Iowa,''
Gardner wrote, ``and Ernest is taking some of his stuff over to
Tres' house to move his gear.''
</P>
<P>
   Gardner's documentation also reveals that Brown was being
advised at the time by a California sports agent. Gardner told the
Chronicle he was introduced to the agent, Gerald Duncan, by Chapman
at a Mesa game during the 1998-99 season.
</P>
<P>
   Benedict, the Mesa athletic director, said the fact Brown left
for Indian Hills at the same time Chapman became an administrator
at Iowa State may cause some to wonder but is not proof that
anything improper occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, you can wonder,'' Benedict said. ``But you've also got
to understand the kid (Brown). He's got a girlfriend and children.
We have no scholarships to pay room and board. He was on financial
aid, but that doesn't pay for everything. To be offered an
opportunity to play basketball in a good program and get things he
wasn't getting here, from a kid's perspective, that's something.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, you can wonder whether it's coincidence Tres is at Iowa
State and Ernest moves to Indian Hills. But in order to get from
Indian Hills to Iowa State, the kid had to accomplish a hell of a
lot academically. I'm not going to speculate that Iowa State's
hiring Tres was because of Ernest Brown. I have nothing to document
that. Tres and I had a pretty good relationship. If that was the
case, I would hope he would have come and told me, and that didn't
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   For Gardner, the most troubling aspect of the matter is not so
much what may or may not have transpired between Iowa State and
Chapman but what has happened to Brown, who had a subpar season at
Indian Hills and will be challenged to prove he is ready for the
NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Brown averaged 11.9 points and 7.0 rebounds at Indian Hills and
suffered the ignominy of being pulled from the Warriors' final
playoff game after playing only six first-half minutes, during
which he scored two points and failed to get a rebound. Despite a
lineup that included Brown and another player planning to go
straight to the NBA, 6-8 guard Cory Hightower, Indian Hills failed
to reach the NJCAA national tournament for the first time in five
years.
</P>
<P>
   Rummaging through his office recently, Gardner found a reminder
of Brown's time in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have his All-America plaque here,'' Gardner said. ``I'm just
trying to figure out where to send it.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
