<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0568 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-HIP-HOP-FILMS-$ADV02-     03-28 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIP-HOP-FILMS-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIP-HOP, HOW THEY LOVE YA  
 FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 2) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By A.O. SCOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Midway through ``Dogma,'' Kevin Smith's unlikely stew of
millennial theology and turn-of-the-century pop culture, Loki, the
voluble, sociopathic angel of death played by Matt Damon, muses on
his shortcomings as a prophet of mass taste.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, he still can't believe that ``E.T.'' was the
Hollywood blockbuster of the 1980s, instead of ``Krush Groove,''
Michael Schultz's rags-to-riches showbiz parable featuring the rap
group Run-D.M.C.
</P>
<P>
   But Loki sorely underestimates his powers of cultural
divination. Hip-hop, to the discomfort of artistic purists and
cultural puritans alike, has become the lingua franca of global
youth culture. Nowhere is this more evident than at the movies,
where hip-hop increasingly provides not only a source of subsidiary
revenue (thanks to soundtrack sales), but a repertory of styles,
references and attitudes now showing at theaters everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Krush Groove'' may not have broken box office records or made
Reese's Pieces a popular snack, but a case for its belated
influence can be found in the listings and advertisements on the
entertainment pages. How many lovable aliens do you see? Garry
Shandling doesn't count.
</P>
<P>
   A glance at some of the hip-hop inflected movies released since
Christmas reveals both the music's ubiquity and its mutability. Its
idioms and its beats permeate, among other releases, a big-budget
pro football opera (``Any Given Sunday''), a blood-soaked art-house
samurai epic (``Ghost Dog''), a martial arts romance (``Romeo Must
Die''), a pair of raucous ghetto comedies (``Next Friday'' and ``3
Strikes'') and an amoral morality tale about outlaw stockbrokers
(``The Boiler Room.'')
</P>
<P>
   The transracial appeal of a genre that started out as homemade
party music in Queensbridge and the South Bronx is, in different
ways, the subtext of ``Ghost Dog'' and ``The Boiler Room'' as well
as an integral part of the marketing strategy behind ``Next
Friday'' and ``Romeo Must Die.'' It's also the subject of James
Toback's ``Black and White,'' which opens Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Toback's film stars the rapper Raekwon and the producer Oli
``Power'' Grant of the Wu-Tang Clan, along with the New York Knicks
guard Allan Houston (playing a basketball player), the supermodel
Claudia Schiffer (playing a doctoral candidate in cultural
anthropology) and Mike Tyson (playing Mike Tyson).
</P>
<P>
   Brooke Shields shows up as Sam Doneger, a documentary filmmaker
intrigued by a band of affluent white New York teen-agers who talk,
dress and ambulate as though they were auditioning for a Puff Daddy
video directed by Whit Stillman. ``I'm doing a film on a phenomenon
I've actually observed across America,'' Doneger explains to her
initially skeptical subjects, who are themselves the phenomenon in
question.
</P>
<P>
   It is, of course, not a new phenomenon. It happens that one of
the producers of ``Black and White'' is Michael Mailer, whose
father, Norman, anticipated many of the movie's themes in his
notorious 1957 essay ``The White Negro.'' The elder Mailer
identified, and identified with, the figure of the hipster, a white
man who was able, by imitating the sexual bravado and criminal
cunning supposedly characteristic of black men, to flout the
repressive conformity of postwar American society.
</P>
<P>
   ``The White Negro'' gave credence to a pernicious mythology of
black manhood, but if the elder Mailer was naive in subscribing to
such mythology, he was also prescient in describing its power.
</P>
<P>
   If a movie like ``The Boiler Room'' updates Mailer's hypothesis
by presenting stock trading as the ultimate existential outlaw kick
(according to its hero, selling stock is ``the white-boy way of
slinging crack rock''), hip-hop itself brings Mailer's argument
full circle. The aggressive masculine personae of many rappers
appropriate cinematic archetypes, including not only blaxploitation
and Bruce Lee, but ``Goodfellas,'' ``Butch Cassidy and the Sundance
Kid'' and a grab bag of science fiction, horror and action movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any Given Sunday'' turns on the racial and generational divide
across which an aging white football coach (Al Pacino) and his
brilliant, undisciplined black quarterback (Jamie Foxx) confront
each other. But viewed from another angle, the relationship is not
so simple. If Foxx is a child of hip-hop, Pacino is _ along with
Oliver Stone, the director of ``Any Given Sunday'' _ one of its
godfathers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scarface'' (1983), directed by Brian De Palma from Stone's
screenplay, in which Pacino played the profane, ultraviolent Cuban
refugee turned cocaine kingpin Tony Montana, has inspired too many
rap lyrics and videos to count. A climactic scene in Hype Williams'
rap-driven high-fashion shoot'em-up ``Belly'' _ one of the most
visually mesmerizing and narratively stupefying films of the last
few years _ is so closely patterned on the climactic shootout in
``Scarface'' that the victim mutters ``I'm Tony Montana'' as he
opens fire on his attackers.
</P>
<P>
   Like the music that drives them, ``Ghost Dog,'' ``Black and
White'' and ``The Boiler Room'' sample and recycle familiar story
lines and images to uncover something new. In the latter two movies
a young man _ explicitly Jewish in ``The Boiler Room,'' implicitly
so in ``Black and White'' _ is alienated from a powerful,
disapproving father, and discovers his own identity, his own voice,
by donning a kind of cultural blackface.
</P>
<P>
   Sound familiar? It's the plot of ``The Jazz Singer,'' a
masterpiece of racial ambiguity that inaugurated the 20th century's
exemplary form of storytelling, the talking picture. And according
to the Wu-Tang Clan's Power, hip-hop, revitalizing the culture that
has sometimes grudgingly sustained it, will be ``the narrative
voice of the 21st century.'' You ain't heard nothing yet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-00 2102EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
