<HEADLINE>
OPTIMISM AS BASEBALL GOES INTERNATIONAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Near the end of a long day of interviews last Friday,
almost everybody seemed to have grown weary of questions about the
first regular-season major league baseball games outside North
America. New York Mets manager Bobby Valentine had answered a final
question when a thought popped into his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the games here are a progressive move,'' he said about
the Mets and Chicago Cubs facing Japanese teams and then starting
the National League season with games Wednesday and Thursday (5
a.m. EST each day). ``Another step for the players of the future
and for baseball. But remember, we're not here to export. We're
here to influence. There should be an exchange, not a raid.''
</P>
<P>
   High-minded thoughts from a man who had traveled with his team
more than 6,000 miles in one day just to play baseball. The Mets
came all the way from Florida, and Sammy Sosa and the Cubs took an
8 a.m. flight from Phoenix. Some of them undoubtedly weren't happy
about the journey, but they realize these days their sport is a
business.
</P>
<P>
   It's all part of baseball deciding to test the feasibility of
being truly international. The Mets and Cubs got into the swing and
battled the Tokyo Giants and Seibu Lions of the Japan League, and
now they are set to start the season. If this is the future, so be
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ready to rock and roll,'' said the Cubs' Mark Grace at
the interview session. ``It was a long trip, but our attitude is
that if we've come over here, then we'd better win a couple of
games. The Japanese have got some guys who are good enough to be in
the big leagues. It's a different type of baseball, but there is
talent here.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Tokyo Giants defeated the Mets and Cubs, although
the major league teams both defeated the Seibu Lions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball is a game whose global potential is untapped,'' said
commissioner Bud Selig, who made the trip. ``We needed to do this.
We've been criticized in the past because the NBA and the NHL have
been more aggressive and already booked regular-season games here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact here is you have two nations where baseball is the
national pastime. There is a chance to do so much more than pure
baseball by establishing this kind of relationship. You don't worry
about economics. The economics will take care of themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Until about 10 years ago, it wasn't thought the Japanese would
be major players in the economics of the game, including marketing
and merchandising. Major league owners saw the Japan League as only
Triple A ball, a closed shop whose ownership was tied up in
railroads, newspapers, and department stores. Clubs worked with a
basic agreement in which players had practically no chance of
escape. But that was then. Now players can become free agents after
nine years. That's not as good as the major leagues, where the
jumping-off point is six years. But it's good enough to enable a
handful of strong-armed pitchers to make the major leagues. Hideo
Nomo broke a 29-year drought when he signed with the Los Angeles
Dodgers. Approximately two dozen have followed. Finding everyday
players is the next goal of every major league club, and what's
happening with these games will help.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the increased consideration of Japanese players is
partly the result of a rare US loss in the series between the
countries in 1990. The major leaguers took winning for granted that
year and didn't have enough healthy players. So when they lost the
series, 4-3-1, there was an uproar among baseball officials. A
better team was sent over in 1992 and it prevailed, 6-1-1. But the
'90 result made some owners wonder whether the Japanese had
improved enough to rise above the minor leagues. Except for
pitchers, the answer was no, but it's getting closer.
</P>
<P>
   In '90, the US team didn't sell out a stadium. Veterans Chuck
Finley, Randy Johnson, Ken Griffey, and Barry Bonds received little
or no media attention. There wasn't much merchandising. Since then,
owners in both the US and Japan have worked to develop a marketing
strategy. It's coming along, and in two short years Sosa has become
the most popular major leaguer in Japan since Babe Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pride thing,'' says Cubs manager Don Baylor, who was a
coach on the '90 team. ``I've warned my players to be alert. This
week we're (seeing) a whole new and interesting approach to the
game. But we're also here to face the Mets.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, the Japanese established rules to discourage raids
or runaway free agents. Three years ago, the movement of players
between countries became easier. Major league teams like the Red
Sox can get good money for players such as Lou Merloni (Yokohama
Baystars) and Reggie Jefferson (Seibu Lions). Creating a worldwide
market for players' services long has been a goal of Donald Fehr
and the Players Association, and he's getting his way.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is finally getting the message.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked about regular-season games for years,'' said
organizer Peter Miller, son of former Players Association chief,
Marvin Miller. ``The fans wanted it. Baseball wanted it. There have
been administrative hurdles. But the sport has been so popular. I
think Nomo's coming to the major leagues has something to do with
it. It increased international consciousness.''
</P>
<P>
   Selig agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in a global economy,'' he said. ``It's so much
different than the world of even 10 years ago. Baseball has to
learn to live in that world. I said a few years ago that we were
going to change the way we thought and the way we did business. We
have.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had come up with the idea of this series 10 years ago,
you'd have been turned down. We're here. And the game will be more
popular if there is a worldwide dimension to it. I've told the
clubs that we're in an international phase. This is just a
modification. There will be more.''
</P>
<P>
   Those modifications might include a true world series with teams
from the US, Japan, Canada, Latin America, and perhaps eventually
Australia. There is plenty of talent out there, but the quality is
not consistent. Baseball has to be aggressive in spending its money
and yet keep salaries within a workable budget. In recent years,
baseball has lost fans and revenues to soccer and the NFL. Going
international could help stop that slide.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it were short-term economics you were doing it for, then
you wouldn't do it,'' said Selig. ``It isn't worth importing teams
and other things for the short term. This might help baseball
economically in the long term. That's what it's all about.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets and Cubs are serious, but are continuing at a spring
training pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to pitch and play good defense,'' said Baylor. ``We're
not going to be able to hit too many home runs due to the makeup of
our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine is ready, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking about my job,'' said Valentine, who once managed
the Chiba Lotte Lions. ``We're on a schedule, and people have to
get ready for the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came away from Japan with a real good feeling about myself
and about baseball,'' he said. ``I came away feeling my ability to
deal with change and baseball players regardless of language and
culture had improved. I'm going to have a lot of fun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
