<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KARROS HURT, SHOULD BE OK FOR OPENER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JUPITER, Fla. - When Dodgers first baseman Eric Karros didn't
pop right up after fouling a ball off his left ankle, everyone knew
it was serious.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for the Dodgers, though, it turned out to be only a
bruise that will keep Karros out for the next three or four games.
General manager Kevin Malone said Karros would be ready for
Monday's season opener at Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The swelling has already gone down and just talking with him,
he said he already feels better,'' Malone said a few hours
afterward. ``I had a stomach ache because usually he gets up. I'm
pretty sure we won't see him until Friday or Saturday (in Toronto).
I'd doubt if (manager Davey Johnson) would overextend Eric,
especially on the carpet.''
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh inning of Tuesday's game against Montreal, Karros
fouled a Felipe Lira pitch off his ankle and immediately fell. He
remained on his knees for a few minutes before being helped off the
field. He was taken to the clubhouse on a golf cart, and he left
the complex on crutches.
</P>
<P>
   X-rays taken at St. Mary's Professional Building by Dr. Frank
Cook were negative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy it was just a bruise. I should be back in a few
days,'' said Karros, who signed a three-year contract extension
that guarantees him $24 million days before spring training began.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the better ones I've had. Let's put it this
way, it's the only time I've come off the field (after doing it).''
</P>
<P>
   It's the second potential disaster the Dodgers narrowly averted
this spring, and one that could have been a terrible setback.
Karros has hit at least 30 homers and driven in 100 runs in four of
the last five seasons, and his presence in the order behind cleanup
hit Shawn Green is irreplaceable.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month left fielder Gary Sheffield needed three
stitches to close a cut on his left pinkie, which he cut diving
into third. He missed eight spring training games with the injury.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson eyes 12 hurlers: There is concern that since the Dodgers
begin the season with seven games in seven days, and since Orel
Hershiser and Carlos Perez are in the middle of the rotation and
neither averaged more than six innings a start last season, that
opening the season with 11 pitchers wouldn't be enough.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, manager Davey Johnson said beginning the season with
12 pitchers is a strong possibility. The likely candidate is
right-hander Matt Herges, who can eat up innings in a long relief
role. Herges pitched a shutout inning against the Expos, and will
make the trip to play Atlanta today.
</P>
<P>
   With Hershiser in the starting rotation, the Dodgers don't have
any long relievers in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``With playing the first seven days and getting the first start
under everyone's belt, you want to make sure you have enough
innings in the `pen,'' Johnson said. ``If I did carry another guy,
it would be because of that.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the Dodgers go with 12 pitchers, it means beginning the
season with six outfielders is impossible and could mean the end
for Geronimo Berroa unless the Dodgers can come up with a creative
way to make it possible to keep him.
</P>
<P>
   Kreuter catches on: Veteran Chad Kreuter, a Pepperdine product,
won a spot on the Dodgers' roster long ago, and the club finally
made it official by purchasing his contract. Kreuter, signed as a
non-roster invitee, will back up Todd Hundley. He has a $450,000
base salary.
</P>
<P>
   It's likely Kreuter will make most of his starts against
left-handers. A natural righty, the switch-hitting Kreuter batted
.279 against lefties last season. Hundley, meanwhile, had four hits
in 40 at-bats from the right side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that signing here was going to be a role backing up
Todd, and I plan on doing that well,'' Kreuter said. ``It's going
in when heneeds days off, going in late in games and possibly
playing defensively, and maybe some pinch-hitting.''
</P>
<P>
   It also means catcher Paul Lo Duca, the Dodgers' backup much of
last season, is expected to be sent to Triple-A Albuquerque today.
To make room for Kreuter on the 40-man roster, pitcher Kris Foster
put on the 60-day disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Speculation is Montreal closer Ugueth Urbina is
close to being dealt to Atlanta for the world's most hated
ballplayer, John Rocker. But it's clear how the Expos players feel
about bringing Rocker into their clubhouse. Before the game with
the Dodgers, one of the Expos clipped a newspaper story about the
deal and drew a circle with a diagonal slash through it over
Rocker's face. Copies of it where everywhere in the Expos'
clubhouse ... Lefty Onan Masaoka pitched three innings and allowed
one run in a Triple-A game. Masaoka is the Dodgers' situational
lefty in the bullpen, but he was sent to a minor league game to
stretch out his arm, which he did in throwing 51 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers vs. Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   When/Where: 10:05 a.m., Disney's Wide World of Sports, Lake
Buena Vista, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Radio: XTRA 1150 AM
</P>
<P>
   Today's game: Both clubs set up their rotation to start the
season, which means Kevin Brown against Greg Maddux in the Dodgers'
last road game of the Grapefruit League. Brown leads Dodger
starters with a 1.23 ERA.Wednesday's result: Shawn Green hit a pair
of homers as the Dodgers beat the Montreal Expos 4-3 in 10 innings.
It was the Dodgers' fifth straight win. Darren Dreifort was sharp
in pitching six innings. He allowed two runs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
