<HEADLINE>
REFORM CHAIRMAN VOWS TO UNITE PARTY IN TIME FOR ELECTION DAY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
and R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With a court upholding his chairmanship of the Reform Party, Pat
Choate predicted Tuesday that he would unite the party's bickering
factions before the fall's general election.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Bush will have a tougher time getting John McCain's
endorsement than I am pulling this party together,'' Choate said at
a Washington news conference, where he discussed plans for the
party.
</P>
<P>
   Choate, who was Ross Perot's vice-presidential running mate in
1996, won a federal court ruling Monday that he is the legitimate
Reform Party chairman, not Jack Gargan. Gargan was elected by a
party convention last year, but he was ousted earlier this year
during an acrimonious executive committee meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Choate said the party will establish headquarters in Washington
and will move ahead with plans for three issues conferences, using
the Internet, to reach voters on subjects, including political
reform, trade and China.
</P>
<P>
   He said that although the race for the party's presidential
nominee is still open, the only candidate working to get on state
ballots is conservative commentator Pat Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   When asked why Democrats and Republicans may be working to deny
the Reform Party candidate a place at the presidential debates next
fall, Choate replied, ``Pat Buchanan is what they fear. He is a
great debater.''
</P>
<P>
   Choate said the Reform Party is already on the ballot in 22
states and organizers are working in all of the other states,
including Texas.
</P>
<P>
   He said ``the Texas clock began to run on March 15 ... the only
person working the clock is Pat Buchanan.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Reform Party Chairman Larry Steele of Corpus Christi
recently sent party members a letter saying there are two petition
drives going on in Texas. One is to get the party ballot status,
and the other is for Buchanan as an independent candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since our secretary of state (Elton Bomer) is a Bush
appointee, they (Buchanan's campaign staff) feel they must make the
extra effort to petition as an independent,'' Steele wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Steele said Buchanan would run as a Reform Party candidate if
the party gains ballot status, otherwise Buchanan wants to be on
the Texas ballot as an independent.
</P>
<P>
   Although only 37,380 valid signatures are required on a petition
to get a third party on the ballot in Texas compared with 56,116
needed for an independent candidate, a third party faces additional
legal hurdles that a candidate does not.
</P>
<P>
   Ann McGeehan, director of elections for the secretary of state,
said in addition to the Reform Party there also are ballot-access
petition drives under way for the Constitution Party, Green Party,
Patriot Party and the Natural Law Party. The Democratic, Republican
and Libertarian parties already have ballot access.
</P>
<P>
   Choate said the Reform Party will launch a fund-raising drive,
using the Internet, with the goal of raising $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   The party is eligible for $2 million in federal funds for its
national party convention. And the Reform Party presidential
nominee will qualify for another $12 million in public funds for
the general election, Choate said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXXX &QL; 
