<HEADER>
A0592 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TENN-EXECUTE-ART-NYT &LR;      03-28 1339
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TENN-EXECUTE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUESTION OVER WHO FIRED FATAL SHOT STIRS DEATH ROW DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT32 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ There is no dispute that a drug-addicted
drifter named Philip Ray Workman robbed a Wendy's restaurant in
Memphis on the night of Aug. 5, 1981. There also is no question
that Workman, armed with a .45-caliber pistol, exchanged fire with
Memphis police officers as he fled and that Lt. Ronald Oliver was
killed.
</P>
<P>
   But 18 years after Workman's conviction for felony murder, there
is now an intriguing dispute over whether the bullet that killed
Oliver was fired by Workman or by one of two other police officers
on the scene. The resolution to that question may determine whether
Workman will become the first man to be executed by the state of
Tennessee in 40 years. He is scheduled to die on April 6 unless the
6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals grants him a new evidentiary
hearing or Gov. Don Sundquist grants him clemency.
</P>
<P>
   Because the execution would be the first since Tennessee
reinstated the death penalty in 1977, Workman's conviction has
received far more public scrutiny than capital cases in surrounding
states where executions have become commonplace. Among the 38
states that have the death penalty, only four _ New Hampshire,
South Dakota, Connecticut and New Mexico _ have gone longer without
an execution.
</P>
<P>
   The Workman case is set against a national backdrop of growing
attention to wrongful capital convictions. In Illinois, so many
death penalty convictions have been exposed as faulty that Gov.
George Ryan has suspended executions until the process can be
reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   As Workman's execution date approaches, his lawyers are working
frantically to convince both the federal judges and Sundquist, a
Republican, that there are problems with his conviction. The only
eyewitness to testify at Workman's trial recanted last year and
prominent ballistic experts have said they doubt that the bullet
could have come from Workman's gun.
</P>
<P>
   The state's attorney general, Paul Summers, a Democrat, is
working just as intensely to keep the execution on track. He said
none of the defense arguments have shaken his conviction that
Workman is guilty. He resents the defense's suggestion that
Tennessee politicians are sacrificing due diligence in their rush
to join the country's other state executioners.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview here Tuesday at Riverbend state prison, the
46-year-old Workman said he believed that the political imperative
to execute had overwhelmed any sense of fairness. He gave himself a
1 percent chance of winning legal relief, but said his conversion
to Christianity a decade ago had made him ``as ready as I'm going
to get'' to face death.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are frustrated and that's understandable,'' said
Workman, who was shackled. ``They're frustrated with crime and the
frustration of 40 years since there's been an execution. People
say, `Well if it's on the books it needs to be utilized.' But
unfortunately finality seems to be more important than what the
facts may actually bear out.''
</P>
<P>
   Workman, who is represented by a state-financed office for
indigent capital defense, has accumulated an interesting coalition
of advocates. His lawyers convinced 5 of the 12 jurors in his trial
to sign statements saying they would not have convicted Workman of
first-degree murder had they heard the new evidence. One of the
five state Supreme Court justices who declined in January to block
the execution issued a partial dissent calling for Sundquist to
commute the sentence because of ``extenuating circumstances.'' The
dead policeman's daughter, Paula Dodillet, who was 11 when he was
killed, is pleading for the state to show mercy.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Dodillet sat with Workman's daughter, Chrystal
Michelle Workman-Burnham, at a news conference. ``Taking her father
will not bring mine back,'' Dodillet said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors contend that the defense is grandstanding and that
its claims are flimsy. Last fall, Summers suggested that it did not
even matter whether Workman fired the fatal shot. He still could
have been convicted of the capital offense of felony murder _ a
murder that takes place in the commission of another felony _
because he clearly committed the armed robbery that led to Oliver's
death, the attorney general said.
</P>
<P>
   But in an interview, Summers acknowledged that the Tennessee
courts have not resolved that question. ``We're not addressing that
argument because that's not what happened,'' he said, referring to
the possibility of friendly fire.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his prosecution, Workman simply assumed that he had
fired the fatal shot. It passed through the officer's torso, but
investigators could never definitively identify the death slug.
</P>
<P>
   Workman says he was trying to surrender when he was hit on the
head and involuntarily fired two shots. ``I pulled the trigger,''
he testified at his trial. ``I had my hand around the gun, and I
guess it was pointed at the officers.'' His defense was focused on
convincing the jury that his judgment was so clouded by cocaine
that he was not responsible.
</P>
<P>
   The other two officers on the scene, Aubrey K. Stoddard and
Stephen C. Parker, maintained at the trial and again in interviews
Tuesday that they never fired their weapons.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Both former officers said they were offended by the defense's
implication that they colluded to cover up a death by friendly
fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've spent my whole life prosecuting criminals, including
public officials for perjury and abusing their power,'' said
Parker, who is now an assistant U.S. Attorney in Memphis. ``Now
they're accusing me of being a murderer and a perjurer, even though
they know the evidence points the other way.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   The new evidence that could be most troubling for the state is a
videotaped perjury confession by Harold Davis, a drifter and the
only bystander to testify that he saw Workman shoot Oliver. Found
by defense lawyer Jefferson T. Dorsey in a Phoenix motel last fall,
Davis now says he heard shots from a distance but never saw the
shooting. When he volunteered his help to police on the day after
the shooting, they coached him, he now says.
</P>
<P>
   ``They basically told me what happened, how it happened, when it
happened,'' Davis says on the videotape. ``I said, `Well, I didn't
see all that.' They said, `Well, this is what you're going to
say.'''
</P>
<P>
   Curry Todd, a former Memphis police officer who is now a state
representative, denied in an interview exerting any such influence
when he took Davis' statement.
</P>
<P>
   Summers dismissed Davis, who has changed his story regularly
over the years, as ``a throwaway witness'' and argued that Workman
would have been convicted without the Davis testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The new theory in the Workman case was first developed when one
of his appellate lawyers noticed that Oliver's autopsy had
concluded that the exit wound was smaller than the entrance wound.
That was curious, the lawyer thought, given that Workman was firing
hollow-point bullets, which typically mushroom upon impact.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequently, the defense solicited reports from two respected
forensic pathologists, who concluded that Oliver's wounds were
inconsistent with Workman's ammunition. The state has countered
with its own expert, who wrote that hollow-point bullets do not
always expand as intended.
</P>
<P>
   In a previous rejection of Workman's appeal, the 6th Circuit
judges suggested that the death slug may have fragmented, which
would explain the smaller exit wound. But an X-ray of the corpse,
produced by the Shelby County medical examiner only this month
after years of requests by the defense team, showed no
fragmentation.
</P>
<P>
   The defense has accused prosecutors of deliberately hiding the
X-ray. The state blames the mistake on a clerical filing error.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-00 2133EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
