u f BC-BIOTECH-VENTURE-BOS &LR;      03-28 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOTECH-VENTURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUG ENTREPRENEURS MAKE THEIR PITCH FOR CASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ John Rogers said he was embarrassed to tell the crowd
how little venture money he's managed to raise so far for his
company, AquaGene Inc.: a mere $600,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to show this in Boston and Silicon Valley,'' said
Rogers, speaking before a group of potential corporate clients and
investors at the Bio 2000 conference. ``What we need today is an
investor or a partner, or both.''
</P>
<P>
   Anything below $1 million is spare change when venture
capitalists are raising billion-dollar funds _ mostly for
Internet-related startups _ and biotechnology is a hot industry.
Many of the drug entrepreneurs have come to Boston this week not
just to show off possible genetic cures for cancer, Alzheimer's,
and AIDS, but to gun for money.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as easy as it would seem.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers has been having a hard time drumming up $500,000 to $2
million for his ``designer proteins'' for cancer therapy, despite
claiming a niche he says no one else is exploiting _ farming human
protein from genetically engineered fish. He said his
disease-fighting proteins will be cheaper than those harvested from
goats or cows.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers blames the problem largely on his headquarters location,
in Alachua, Fla. ``We have extraordinarily low costs,'' is the
upside, he said. But, ``We have an extraordinarily hard time
raising money. There's no venture capital in Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston's mainstream venture capitalists, and even many of those
with an interest in biotechnology, are skipping the conference this
week, saying it's a waste of their time. However, the specialists
are attending, as are legions of big drugmakers, who could enter a
joint venture with a small firm like AquaGene.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I have a big company as a customer, then when I call the
Boston venture capitalists, they'll ask me to stop by to see
them,'' Rogers said.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1990s, biotechnology startups were attracting big
money from venture capitalists. Boston was a hub of such investing,
with important research coming out of Harvard Medical School and
Massachusetts General Hospital in particular. Then came the
Internet craze.
</P>
<P>
   Most venture firms with any high-tech expertise at all shifted
their focus to Internet startups, where the rewards have been huge,
thanks to initial public offerings that flew off the shelves.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, New England biotech firms were reaping about 12 percent
of the venture money in the market, according to a study by
PriceWaterhouseCoopers, the accounting and consulting firm. By
1999, that number had shrunk to 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Total dollars being invested in biotechnology have nearly
doubled in that period, to $121.8 million. But total venture
dollars in New England have surged sevenfold, to $4.14 billion,
with large portions of that money going into software, new media,
and Web companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are fewer people doing (biotech) today than five years
ago,'' said James Cavanaugh, president of HealthCare Ventures, a
Princeton, N.J., venture firm with a Cambridge office. ``Most of
them dropped health care.''
</P>
<P>
   But not Cavanaugh's firm. He appeared on a panel at the
conference Monday, discussing the economics of biotechnology before
a packed audience. He concludes that there is growing interest in
the next generation of drugs, which tackle cancer as well as
diseases of the central nervous system, particularly Alzheimer's
disease.
</P>
<P>
   As baby boomers live longer, helped by advances in therapies to
combat heart disease and cancer, there will be a growing demand to
treat ailments of the nervous system, Cavanaugh predicts.
</P>
<P>
   The hurdle, as always, will be raising funds to finance the
research and development of such treatments, he said. This is no
overnight effort like a consumer Web site with some banner
advertisements. Bringing a drug to market can take years.
</P>
<P>
   HealthCare Ventures boasts a 90 percent investment return on its
fifth fund. That used to be something to brag about, Cavanaugh
said, before dot-com investments started yielding triple-digit
returns in a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little bit humbling to show your limited partners those
returns when the guys who went in before you had 100 percent
returns or more,'' Cavanaugh said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-00 2136EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
