<HEADLINE>
HEALTH INSURERS URGE RIGOROUS DRUG STANDARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY LIZ KOWALCZYK AND RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Even as biotechnology companies spend millions of
dollars developing hundreds of new drugs, health insurers warned
Tuesday that they're often ignoring important steps in getting
their products to patients: Proof that they work better than
existing drugs.
</P>
<P>
   And proof that they save money.
</P>
<P>
   Dashing the excitement of the world's largest biotech
conference, health insurance executives said they're not going to
cover the approximately 360 drugs in advanced human trials unless
companies meet rigorous standards.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Allan Korn, chief medical officer for the Blue Cross and
Blue Shield Association, said insurers cannot trust hype when
they're making coverage decisions that have a huge financial
impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one ever comes to market and says, `I have an expensive new
drug and it's a dog,' '' he said. ``So we have to be very careful
in looking at the evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Korn and two other panelists spoke at the symposium Managed Care
and Biotechnology _ Partners or Adversaries? during the Bio 2000
gathering in Boston. While the audience of 50 was small by
conference standards, the topic is largely a sore one between the
two industries.
</P>
<P>
   Biotechnology companies spend $300 million to $500 million and
take five to 10 years to develop a new drug, and yet, even after
the US Food and Drug Administration approves the medicine for sale
based on successful clinical trials, they often find health
insurance companies won't pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   Panel moderator Roger Louis, senior corporate counsel for the
biotechnology company Genzyme in Cambridge, said the process has
been sometimes ``rancorous and adversarial,'' with his industry
colleagues often not understanding why some new drugs are covered
and others are rejected.
</P>
<P>
   With 6,000 drugs in the pipeline _ 40 percent of them for cancer
and 20 percent for muscle and nerve pain _ the debate will only get
more intense, said Dr. Grant Lawless, who spent 10 years as medical
director for Blue Cross and Blue Shield in Pittsburgh and now works
for Amgen Inc. as its director of pharmacoeconomics.
</P>
<P>
   Korn said that Blue Cross-Blue Shield plans depend on a panel of
19 independent experts who evaluate new drugs solely on their
medical effectiveness, and that in 60 percent of the cases, the
plans agree to cover the drug. He said cost does not enter into the
scientific evaluation, but he acknowledged that the panel chooses
to study drugs that are heavily advertised and could be used by a
large number of people.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not the only ones who want more money,'' he said. ``The
pharmaceutical companies want more money, the doctors want more
money, and the hospitals. At the end of the day, someone has to
make a budget.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawless predicted that within the next 24 months the criteria
for insurance reimbursement of new drugs will go beyond their
medical effectiveness and safety and may include cost.
</P>
<P>
   He said many of the new drugs will be priced higher than
existing medications. Determining whether the more expensive
biotech medications are signficicantly better compared to currently
available drugs that cost less is becoming a growing issue for
large insurers who are being asked to pay for both of them. ``Some
large health insurers are overwhelmed and they may start to
consider cost effectiveness as as a criteria for reimbursement,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The biotech industry has maintained that if new drugs can
significantly reduce hospitalizations _ the most expensive portion
of health care _ then they should be able to command higher prices
than existing medications that are not as effective.
</P>
<P>
   But Korn said this theory has yet to be proven. He pointed out
that hospital stays have been declining for many patients since the
early 1980s, but said that insurers are still paying more to
hospitals annually than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   Korn repeatedly returned to one example of a treatment for
breast cancer _ expensive bone-marrow transplants and high-dose
chemotherapy _ as a warning against anecdotal evidence. Widely used
by doctors for years as a last-resort treatment for advanced
cancer, recent studies show it's no more effective than
conventional therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years ago we said we have no evidence. Thirty thousand
transplants later and we still have no evidence,'' he said. ``We
have to be careful not to get ahead of the scientific evidence.
Women in this room who get cancer would be offered a 1989
treatment; that's because we got stuck for a decade. Let's not make
that mistake again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
