<HEADER>
A0597 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-PRINTS-ART-2NDTAKE-$A     03-28 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRINTS-ART-2NDTAKE-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
  
 PHILADELPHIA: William Hogarth.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was not surprising, therefore, that when the Dutch master
engraver Hendrick Goltzius visited Rome in 1590, he became
preoccupied with ancient sculpture, which he made the subject of
more than 50 drawings. He was apparently so engrossed that neither
an outbreak of plague nor its dreadful accompaniment _ the stench
of rotting corpses piled up near the statuary he was copying _ kept
him from his work.
</P>
<P>
   After he returned home, he engraved three of his drawings, and
the two in the exhibition show the artist looking up at the Apollo
and at another recent discovery: a huge statue of Hercules that had
been found in the Baths of Caracalla in 1556. Taken by the powerful
Farnese family to their new palazzo near the Tiber, which had been
designed by Michelangelo, the Hercules became an essential sight
for visitors to Rome. By 1590 it was so familiar that Goltzius
could show it from the rear and know that it would be instantly
recognizable.
</P>
<P>
   Ancient buildings were less numerous than sculptures, but they,
too, became common currency throughout Europe. Though he never left
his native land, the Dutchman Jan van de Velde put a recognizable
Temple of the Sybil from Tivoli in one of his landscapes. And
despite the disfigurement of the actual Pantheon by two bell towers
and a new wing, Hubert Robert could show it as it had been in
antiquity.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, it was the sheer variety of the printmakers'
themes that made their influence so pervasive. Inscriptions and
reliefs were lovingly copied, and a fascinating section of the
exhibition documents their appeal to designers of funerary
monuments, who also had a fondness for antique tombs, notably that
remarkable Roman landmark the pyramid of Gaius Cestius.
</P>
<P>
   The reliefs were sources, too, for pastoral scenes, for battles,
arms and triumphs, and for stories about gods, myths and ancient
heroes. The breadth of the subject matter the engravers derived
from arches, columns and other relics amounted to a cornucopia of
sources for the basic vocabulary of Renaissance and Baroque
painting, architecture and sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the 18th century, however, the air of
discovery and excitement seems to wane. Piranesi was no longer
etching Roman remains so as to convey to an international audience
the structures and shapes that might inspire new artistic images.
Like Canaletto in Venice, he was earning a living by supplying a
market eager for views of the places tourists had seen or wanted to
see.
</P>
<P>
   His workshop became a center for the restoration and sale of
antiquities, and the clearest testimony to the change in outlook
was the pair of etchings he produced in 1769 of an elegantly
decorated marble vase that had just been discovered at Hadrian's
villa in Tivoli. Its fruits and putti, lovingly reproduced, were
intended not to enlarge the store of Roman images, but to advertise
the value of the vase to potential buyers.
</P>
<P>
   For Mantegna or Poussin, the deterioration of Rome's inspiring
images into mere commercialism might have seemed sacrilegious. Yet
the contribution of the printmakers to the passion for antiquity
that swept Western art had been completed long before. Nothing
found at Pompeii was to be as famous as the Laocoon, the Apollo or
the Hercules.
</P>
<P>
   Convinced by the scientific revolution that they had progressed
beyond their forebears, Europeans no longer looked so urgently to
Greece and Rome to animate the forms and substance of artistic
creativity. Flashes of neoclassical ambition were to recur, notably
during the French Revolution, but now new interests were needed to
stimulate the long-term vigor that for centuries had been aroused
by the ancient world.
</P>
<P>
   The change in European culture is almost palpable, and the
Philadelphia exhibition, though unassuming in scope and intention
(as is often the case with the devotees of the black-and-white,
unglamorous print), demonstrates not only the role of humble
etchers and engravers in the ascendancy of the antique but also
their subtle reflection of the decline and fall of Rome's empire in
the arts.
</P>
</TEXT>
