<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: SLOUCHING TOWARD PHILLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MAUREEN DOWD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a droll speech to a ballroom full of journalists
and pols at the Gridiron dinner last Saturday night, Al Gore
confided his ``secret'' plan for winning the White House.
</P>
<P>
   He would associate himself with the good stuff that has happened
during the last eight years and disassociate himself from the bad
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``A low unemployment rate and a sound economy? Clinton-Gore,''
he said. ``Grand jury testimony? Clinton . . . Impeachment? Not
me.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president was mocking his own image as an opportunist.
He was also ribbing his Republican rival, whose campaign is based
on the assumption that everyone is fed up with ``the Clinton-Gore
era.''
</P>
<P>
   But America is bursting with contentment. Our only worry is a
new malady that The L.A. Times calls ``sudden wealth syndrome,''
the ennui that comes from making too many millions too fast.
</P>
<P>
   People scorned Bill Clinton's morals. But they love his economy,
and the way he tackles hard things, like the Middle East, Ireland
and guns.
</P>
<P>
   If W. keeps banking on disgust with Clinton-Gore to propel him
to the White House, he'll lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't work to connect Gore to Clinton,'' a Gore adviser
says. ``It didn't even work to connect Clinton to Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans tried to run against Bill Clinton's character in
'92, '96 and '98. It didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   So it is truly remarkable that W. is repeating the willful
mistakes of '92, given that the loss was so searing.
</P>
<P>
   The father thought: I can't lose to a low-class hick from
Arkansas. Now the son thinks: I can't lose to a &UR;  &LR; cutthroat phony
who did stinky things with a low class-hick from Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   The contempt of the Bushes blinds them to the need to fight
harder, fight sooner and fight smarter.
</P>
<P>
   After he soared to 90 percent with his victory in the Persian
Gulf, the father coasted, failing to capitalize with any grand
domestic plans.
</P>
<P>
   W. coasts also, on his first national run (compared with four
for Gore). He does not go on the offensive or offer much substance.
He does not communicate in any interesting way, or outline core
principles. He merely waits for the public to realize he is the
better man. His campaign is like the Cheshire cat, fading to a
smirk.
</P>
<P>
   He parrots sound bites about reform, but he doesn't have the
foggiest notion of why John McCain evoked such excitement. The
governor finally deigned to call the senator on Tuesday, after
prodding by Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by The Times about the McCain phenomenon, Bush replied
curtly: ``Well, then how come he didn't win?''
</P>
<P>
   As Lars-Erik Nelson wrote, it was an eerie echo of the comeback
favored by Bush senior when he rejected advice in '92: ``If you're
so smart, why aren't you president?''
</P>
<P>
   W. appealed to Republicans because he was a baby boomer, but he
keeps Reagan hours. You picture Al up all night plotting. (You know
Karenna has already chosen the convention theme song.) You picture
W. hugging his pillow and belittling his rivals for being too
hungry. But voters like to see a little gumption.
</P>
<P>
   W. thinks the vice president will come off as duplicitous for
pouncing on campaign finance reform. He thinks the words ``Buddhist
temple'' will end any argument. But the Republican can't play the
purist. Voters know he shot the moon on campaign money, too. And
Americans believe in redemption. A real crack at a campaign finance
plan from Gore the reformed sinner is still better than W.'s
empty-shell proposal.
</P>
<P>
   His insular Austin team keeps trying to graft a campaign onto a
brand name. Realizing how hard it is to get Bush the Younger
intellectually engaged, his advisers have reshaped his campaign to
be about the one subject _ besides baseball _ in which he seems
fluent: education. But his big speech on Tuesday, reviving his
mother's pet issue, literacy, does not a vision-thing make.
</P>
<P>
   Like his father's, W.'s basic message is: Trust me _ I've been
bred for this job. Like Bill Bradley, W. is counting on Gore's
smarmy, Eddie Haskell personality to rub people the wrong way.
</P>
<P>
   But W. is expecting Americans to get riled up about what they
already know. He might take a page from Bill Clinton: Elections are
always about the future, not the past.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
