<SLUG> BC-HKN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: CHECKETTS MUST PURSUE LAMORIELLO 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As the Madison Square Garden impresario who will
search for the Rangers' next general manager, Dave Checketts
quickly and understandably declined to discuss any candidates to
succeed Neil Smith other than that he intended to hire ``the best''
he can find, that he ``won't settle'' for anyone but the best.
</P>
<P>
   That simplifies Checketts' search. Hockey's best general
manager, Lou Lamoriello, will soon be at liberty and other than
getting E-Z Pass for the Lincoln Tunnel, he wouldn't even need
moving expenses.
</P>
<P>
   As the New Jersey Devils' major-domo since the 1987-88 season,
Lamoriello has the track record that Checketts demands and that the
Rangers need _ the 1995 Stanley Cup, 11 playoff teams in 13 years,
a bargain $37.6 million payroll and a solid staff of scouts that
have stocked a productive farm system.
</P>
<P>
   Because Lamoriello's contract will be up as soon as the
YankeeNets combine's $175 million purchase of the Devils from John
McMullen is completed in July, he will be that rarity _ a coveted
front-office free agent.
</P>
<P>
   If Checketts means what he says about wanting to hire ``the
best'' available general manager, the Rangers must pursue
Lamoriello as their first choice. That could take time. Lamoriello
won't talk about it now and, even though he would be at liberty in
July, he might not want to discuss a job offer while the Devils are
in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   And if George Steinbrenner is as smart as he always thinks he
is, the YankeeNets will surely try to keep Lamoriello as the
Devils' president and general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Lamoriello, now 57, might prefer to remain with the Devils under
the YankeeNets combine, but he then would be subject to the tension
of working for the Yankees' principal owner, always a factor in the
``job description'' of any Steinbrenner employee, no matter how
serene Joe Torre has appeared as a baseball manager. Lamoriello
also might decide to count his share of the Devils' sale,
reportedly as much as $25 million, and relax.
</P>
<P>
   But if Lamoriello prefers to go elsewhere in the National Hockey
League next season, the Rangers' job as president and general
manager should be his for the asking.
</P>
<P>
   By hiring Lamoriello, the Rangers would also be weakening the
organizational structure of their rivals on the New Jersey side of
the Lincoln Tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   Checketts, once the general manager of the Knicks and the Utah
Jazz, is basically a basketball man with no tactical hockey
knowledge. He wants a Rangers general manager he can trust to do
the job, as Smith was trusted to do the job for 11 seasons until
Tuesday's dismissal of both Smith and Coach John Muckler.
</P>
<P>
   For many of those 11 seasons, Smith did a good job. When the
Rangers won the Stanley Cup in 1994 for the first time in 54 years,
Smith had assembled the players, notably Mark Messier, and hired
the volatile coach, Mike Keenan.
</P>
<P>
   About a month after the cup celebration, Keenan suddenly
defected to the St. Louis Blues in a contract dispute. Messier
remained for three more seasons and Wayne Gretzky arrived for three
seasons, but the Rangers gradually dissolved into the disaster that
had some Garden loyalists leaving before the third period of Monday
night's 6-0 loss to the Detroit Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   On top of Sunday's 8-2 strafing in Detroit, the Rangers had been
outscored, 14-2, in two important games. Whatever slim playoff
chances had existed were now doomed.
</P>
<P>
   The Garden mood Monday night resembled the mutinous mood of the
pro football Giants fans in 1978 when some of them hired a small
plane to tow a ``15 Years of Lousy Football. We've Had Enough''
banner above Giants Stadium during a November loss in a long,
dreary season.
</P>
<P>
   If the Garden didn't have a roof, some fans might have been
tempted, considering the Rangers' $61.2 million payroll, to hire a
small plane with a banner saying, ``Three Straight Years of No
Playoffs. We've Had Enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the frustrated fans chanted, ``Fire Muckler,'' and
Checketts did. Smith also cleaned out his desk. All the Garden
honchos agreed with what most Ranger fans had come to realize,
that, as Checketts said Tuesday, this Ranger team ``should have had
more scoring, more defense, more accountability, more leadership,
more pride.'' Instead of more and more losses.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Rangers hire Lou Lamoriello, they will be getting
``the best man'' for the job.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
