<SLUG> BC-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS IS A SURVIVOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ Sometimes it's hard to remember that
professional baseball players are employees. For some reason,
``employee'' and ``millionaire'' don't seem to be natural dance
partners.
</P>
<P>
   But if you peel away the hype surrounding major leaguers and
their staggering contracts, what you will find is this: Baseball
players are similar to many of us. They draw a paycheck from
someone else. They have a boss. They are not upset when the boss is
a maniac, as long as the mania is not solely directed at them (a
democratic maniac). They also thinks it's funny when the boss is so
quirky that his lack of hipness actually becomes hip.
</P>
<P>
   All of these issues were relevant Tuesday at City of Palms Park.
The Red Sox announced that they were extending the contract of
manager Jimy Williams through 2001. If Williams makes it through
that contract, he will have been a Boston boss for five seasons.
</P>
<P>
   If you talk with the men who are supervised by Williams, you
quickly understand why he is able to survive. Simply, he is a boss
who is respected by those who work for him. Tuesday, the employees'
statements about the boss were supported by the decor in his
office.
</P>
<P>
   There was a Franklin batting glove on his desk. Next to it was a
bottle of sunblock. Behind him, on a bookshelf, there was some
serious literature. No, we're not talking about Ellison, Allende,
Hemingway, or Joyce. Instead, there was a library of baseball media
guides.
</P>
<P>
   The meaning was obvious. James Francis Williams had slipped on
the glove, grabbed a bat, protected his skin from the 83-degree
temperature and gone outside to work with any player who wanted to
work with him.
</P>
<P>
   The boss does as the boss preaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does a lot of different things that I've never seen a
manager do,'' said outfielder Darren Lewis. ``He's a hard-working
man. You don't see a lot of managers around the batting cages. You
don't see a lot of managers in the tunnel, throwing batting
practice. He's in the trenches.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, there are some nice benefits in Williams's line of
work. The best manager in the business, Joe Torre, makes about $3
million a year. Williams is about $2 million short of that status,
although $1 million a year isn't bad. But being a baseball boss
today is challenging. You know how some businesses talk about being
diverse? If you are going to be a successful manager, you had
better be ready to do more than talk about being diverse; you had
better be diversifying.
</P>
<P>
   Williams has done this daily. At the beginning of spring
training, there were as many as five languages being spoken in the
clubhouse: English, French, Spanish, Korean, and Japanese. There
were teenagers hanging around with players in their mid-20s, 30s
and (hello, Gary Gaetti) early 40s. A manager not only has to make
sure that mix works socially, he is on the hook if it doesn't work
on the field.
</P>
<P>
   The balancing act becomes more tenuous when you add the media
factor. Almost every player claims not to pay attention to the
media when, truth is, almost all of them do. They notice when a
manager protects them and they notice when a manager protects
himself. They also notice when the protection comes with an amusing
one-liner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got plenty of those, doesn't he?'' closer Derek Lowe
said. ``He should write a book. He's got some classic one-liners.''
</P>
<P>
   And that makes the 56-year-old boss even more compelling. He has
a team of young dot-commers, yet his language is the verbal
equivalent of an old Smith-Corona. Globe baseball writer Gordon
Edes has accurately described this Jimy As A Second Language
phenomenon as ``Jimywocky.'' Perfect. The players love Jimywocky.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't get to hear it as much as you guys do,'' Lowe said.
``Jimy's pretty quick. Very quick.''
</P>
<P>
   While speculating about the team Tuesday, Williams tried to make
the point that the 25-man roster would be filled out
systematically. You know, 11 pitchers and 14 position players.
``Fifteen and 11 is 25,'' he said. He paused as the numbers crashed
in his head. ``Ohhh,'' he said. ``No it's not.''
</P>
<P>
   He laughed at himself. He was asked about his contract
extension, but he didn't want to talk about it much. He wanted to
talk about ``the kids.'' One of those kids, Brian Daubach, said he
owes his entire career to Williams and general manager Dan
Duquette.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many managers would go into the season with a nonroster
invitee and bat him third?'' Daubach said. ``Especially in
Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   Daubach soon learned that Williams doesn't do brand names. He
has two great players in Nomar Garciaparra and Pedro Martinez. That
seems to be OK with him. He also likes managing the skills of
unknown and little-publicized players.
</P>
<P>
   The 32-year-old Lewis fits into that category.
</P>
<P>
   That could be a reason Lewis likes everything about the boss and
the boss likes everything about him. Well, almost everything.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis walked out into the sun Tuesday, sporting a pair of
designer, Tommy Hilfiger sunglasses. The boss doesn't do brand
names. A nondescript pair of shades would have been fine with him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-00 2201EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
