<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Strategist Suggests Curb On Stocks, and Prices Fall
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices fell as investors took profits and Abby Joseph
Cohen, the influential stock market strategist at Goldman, Sachs,
recommended that her firm's clients reduce their allocation of
stocks to 65 percent. It is the first time Cohen has reduced the
recommended stock allocation since January 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average fell 89.74 points, or 0.8
percent, to 10,936.11. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index
slumped 16.13 points, or 1.1 percent, to 1,507.73, and the Nasdaq
composite index fell 124.67 points, or 2.5 percent, to 4,833.89.
</P>
<P>
   The decline in stock prices lifted bond prices modestly. The
yield on the benchmark 30-year issue was unchanged at 5.98 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Koehler Calls for Wider IMF
</P>
<P>
   Role Laying out his vision of the future of the International
Monetary Fund, Horst Koehler, the new managing director, said that
rather than shrinking as some critics have suggested, the fund
should expand its role.
</P>
<P>
   Aerospace Web Exchange Formed
</P>
<P>
   Boeing, BAE Systems, Raytheon and Lockheed Martin have formed an
Internet trading exchange to buy and auction parts for aircraft and
other aerospace equipment. A sale of shares in the venture could
take place next year, the companies said.
</P>
<P>
   Intel Introduces Its Latest Chip
</P>
<P>
   Intel, seeking to one-up its archrival, Advanced Micro Devices,
in the relentless creation of faster chips for low-cost computers,
introduced its latest Celeron processor for computers priced at
less than $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T Stock May Raise $13.2 Billion
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T said that it intended to raise up to $13.2 billion in the
coming initial public offering of shares meant to track its
wireless communications unit. That would more than double the
record $5.5 billion raised by United Parcel Service when it first
offered shares to the public last November. At a minimum, AT&AMP;T
intends to raise $9.4 billion. Shares of AT&AMP;T fell 62.5 cents, to
$59.6875.
</P>
<P>
   Paintball Lessons Lost on the Job
</P>
<P>
   Companies spend $55 billion a year on training, often using
elaborate and eccentric methods like paintball wars and
fighter-pilot simulations to make their point. The trouble is, many
of these programs have no practical value, so employees return to
their daily chores and forget the training.
</P>
<P>
   Airport Thieves Focus on Laptops
</P>
<P>
   Thieves who steal laptop computers are having a field day in
places frequented by business travelers. A good many of the laptops
are being stolen at airports, sometimes by organized rings.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer Confidence Fell in March
</P>
<P>
   Consumers' confidence in the nation's economy fell for the
second consecutive month in March, and their expectations for later
this year sank to a five-month low, a survey by the Conference
Board showed.
</P>
<P>
   Setback for Japanese Shareholder
</P>
<P>
   A Japanese shareholder advocate, whose failed effort to buy a
company in Japan's first hostile takeover fight attracted
widespread attention, suffered a second defeat when that company,
Shoei, repulsed his requests to raise its dividend and make him a
director.
</P>
<P>
   Websense Shares More Than Double
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Websense, whose products allow companies to monitor
how employees use the Internet at work, more than doubled in value
after the company's initial public stock offering. Websense closed
up $29.75, to $47.75.
</P>
</TEXT>
