<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0617 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-REDS-HNS &LR;      03-28 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JODY GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
SARASOTA, Fla. _ When Mark Portugal finished up his stint with the
Boston Red Sox last season, he figured his 13-year baseball career
was over.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Then the Reds called. They asked him if he would be willing to
return to Cincinnati to compete for the No. 5 spot in the starting
rotation. Portugal was torn and decided he would leave the decision
to those most important to him _ his kids.
</P>
<P>
   To them, the choice was easy. Sure, it meant they would have him
around less. But it meant a chance to meet one of their idols.
</P>
<P>
   ```Yeah, Dad, they're trying to get Ken Griffey Jr. That would
be good,''' Portugal said, relating his conversation with his
7-year-old son, Jacob. ``I think he was paying a lot more attention
to what was going on in the winter than I was. But they're excited
about it, and I was excited about it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard not to get excited around the Reds this year. This is
a team that won 96 games last year before losing a one-game playoff
for the wild card to the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of taking their chances with the same lineup, the Reds
went out and got better _ possibly much better. They added Griffey,
arguably the best player in baseball. They also brought in Dante
Bichette, a key acquisition that has gone largely unnoticed because
of Griffey's presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we said, `We have a chance,''' Reds manager Jack
McKeon said. ``This year you say, `Hey, we can win this thing.'''
</P>
<P>
   His teammates have been virtually ignored as attention has been
focused on Griffey this spring, but that's not something opposing
teams can afford to do in the regular season. Consider the rest of
the Reds' lineup:
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Sean Casey batted .332 with 25 home runs and 99
RBIs last year.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman PokeyReese hit .285 and stole 38 bases.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Barry Larkin hit .293, batted in 75 runs and stole 30
bases.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Aaron Boone batted .280 with 14 home runs and 72
RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Eddie Taubensee batted .311 with 21 homers and 87 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Left fielder Dmitri Young batted .300 with 14 homers and 56
RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in right fielder Bichette's .298 average, 34 home runs and
133 RBIs last year with the Rockies, and Griffey (.285, 48 homers,
134 RBIs for the Mariners) is far from the only Red who will pose
problems for opposing pitchers this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like our chances,'' Larkin said. ``We'll be able to go as
far as our pitching takes us.''
</P>
<P>
   With power throughout the lineup, the bigger question mark does
seem to be the pitching. The rotation will include Denny Neagle,
Pete Harnisch, Steve Parris and Ron Villone. Portugal will be the
No. 5 starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``On paper, we certainly look better,'' Harnisch said. ``The big
thing is for us to get 135 to 150 starts between our five starters
and not have to use eight, nine, 10 starters this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Harnisch was 16-10 last year and is 30-17 over his past two
seasons. Neagle was only 9-5 a year ago, but all nine wins came
after a stay on the disabled list prompted by tendinitis in his
shoulder. Parris and Villone both started the season in Class AAA
and were later recalled. Parris then went 11-4 with a 3.50 ERA.
Villone finished 9-7 with a 4.23 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to win this division, we've got to have
Harnisch and Neagle win 15 games,'' general manager Jim Bowden
said. ``If a healthy Denny Neagle can win 15 to 20, that might make
the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reds' bullpen has one of the best trios of righthanders in
the league. Danny Graves was 8-7 with 27 saves and a 3.08 ERA last
year. NL Rookie of the Year Scott Williamson was impressive with a
12-7 record, 19 saves and a 2.41 ERA. Scott Sullivan went 5-4 with
three saves and a 3.01 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds hope they can improve on last year's numbers, though
they feel pretty confident another 96-win season would earn them a
postseason berth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone said we won 96 last year (and) we need to win 97 this
year,'' Graves said. ``That's just not the case. It's a strange
year when you win 96 games and don't get into the playoffs. That's
not going to happen again. It's not going to take 97 wins to get to
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year and the year before, we didn't really set goals. Our
goal was really just to get better. Now, our goal is definitely to
get to the playoffs. If we don't make it this year, it would be
considered a bad year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reds certainly have the talent. Now it's a matter of proving
they can put it together again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel like we have as good a chance as anybody,'' Harnisch
said. ``Everyone in this locker room feels like the pieces are in
place.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
