<DOCNO> NYT20000328.0341 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0619 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BEN&AMP;JERRY-MARKETPLACE     03-28 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEN&AMP;JERRY-MARKETPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETPLACE: BEN &AMP; JERRY'S REPORTEDLY GOING PRIVATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ben &AMP; Jerry's Homemade ice cream company became as well known
for its commitment to causes like helping the homeless and saving
the rain forests as for selling pints of Chubby Hubby and Cherry
Garcia. But it has long struggled to balance its social initiatives
with shareholder demands for better profits. On Tuesday, it
appeared that part of the struggle was over.
</P>
<P>
   The company, founded by Ben Cohen and Jerry Greenfield in a
Burlington, Vt., gas station in 1978 and taken public in 1984, will
become private in a $38-a-share deal to be announced soon, possibly
as early as Friday, said a shareholder who was briefed on the
agreement. The shareholder said the board approved the deal, which
would be valued at about $260 million, last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   As described by the company shareholder, the agreement would
give Cohen, who owns about a million shares of Ben &AMP; Jerry's,
control of 36 percent of the company. Meadowbrook Lane Capital, a
group of investors that describes itself as socially responsible,
would have a similar stake, and the remaining 28 percent would be
held by Unilever, the British-Dutch giant that owns the Breyer's
ice cream brand as well as Good Humor bars. Greenfield would retain
no interest in the company.
</P>
<P>
   The decision appears to have caused a rift between Cohen and
Greenfield, who was described as unhappy with the involvement of
Unilever. Battling giants like Pillsbury for market share, the
founders gained an unusual public image and a loyal following but
never resolved some important issues, including how to get their
product onto store shelves reliably. For years, Ben &AMP; Jerry's used
a distribution system owned by Dreyer's Grand Ice Cream, based in
Oakland, Calif. The agreement was terminated by Ben &AMP; Jerry's in
September, and the company switched to relying on both Dreyer's and
the Haagen-Daz unit of Diageo, the big British food and beverage
holding company. Both companies are among Ben &AMP; Jerry's biggest
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The issues will remain under the new structure, one analyst
said. ``This does nothing to solve Ben &AMP; Jerry's domestic
distribution problems,'' said Jeffrey G. Kanter, a food stocks
analyst for Prudential Securities. ``All it does is create a much
weaker franchise. Five years from now, Ben &AMP; Jerry's may be known
in France, but it will be a fraction of what it could be.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Greenfield said he had no comment. ``There's
nothing I can add,'' said the spokesman, Chris Miller. ``All I can
say is, Jerry is not interested in chatting.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement recombines aspects of several offers Ben &AMP; Jerry's
received in the last several months. Unilever had offered to pay
$40 a share, which was later increased to $43. Dreyer's had offered
$31 a share on Feb. 2, which was topped by an offer two days later
from Meadowbrook Lane, which said it would pay $32.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, money was left on the table to create the new Ben &AMP;
Jerry's, and not every shareholder was pleased. ``This is basically
the board acquiescing and giving Ben Cohen another chance to take
control of the company,'' one said.
</P>
<P>
   At $38 a share, most shareholders would recover their
investments, and then some, but perhaps at the cost of the
company's growth. ``The shareholders will finally win, but this
does nothing to solve the competitive issues,'' Kanter said.
</P>
<P>
   Meadowbrook Lane listed Anita Roddick, founder of the Body Shop,
a line of natural cosmetics and skin-care products, and Chartwell
Investments II, a venture capital firm based in New York, among its
investors. It pledged to create a ``social performance plan'' that
would place women and minorities on the board, pay about 7.5
percent of the company's pretax profits into the Ben &AMP; Jerry's
Foundation, and provide venture capital to other ``progressively
minded enterprises,'' among other social efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Chartwell Investments II has since dropped out of the group,
said a person close to the talks leading up to the deal. He added
that Cohen had brought Unilever into the group over Greenfield's
objections.
</P>
<P>
   Ben &AMP; Jerry's said in early December that it had received
``indications of interest'' and would be evaluating them. Owners of
Ben &AMP; Jerry's franchises nationwide have been anxiously watching to
see what the outcome would be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't heard anything, but I've been watching the stock,
and I know 181,000 shares traded on Friday, when our average volume
is about 30,000,'' said Lori Johnston, who operates two stores in
Washington, D.C. ``Something must be happening.'' Shares of Ben &AMP;
Jerry's fell 28.125 cents, to $29.96875.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston said she went to a franchise-owners' advisory council
meeting three weeks ago at which the company handed out lapel pins
that said: ``No implications should be drawn. No decisions have
been made.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the big winners in a sale would be Perry D. Odak, Ben &AMP;
Jerry's chief executive, who joined the company in early 1997.
According to the most recent filing with the Securities and
Exchange Commission, he was given options to buy 360,000 shares for
$10.88 a share when he joined the company. He received 67,000 more
options last year, priced at $24.625 a share.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
