<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEADERSHIP-ART-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROFESSOR USES ART TO SHOW IMPORTANCE OF LEADERSHIP SYMBOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ It's highly unlikely Louis XIV, the ``Sun
King'' of France whose reign prospered in the late 1600s, ever wore
ancient Roman battle gear while riding a horse.
</P>
<P>
   And Benjamin Franklin, inventor, author and a political father
of America, never walked around Philadelphia or Boston in a toga.
</P>
<P>
   So why did sculptors depict them that way?
</P>
<P>
   And why do MBA candidates in Rockhurst University's Executive
Fellows Program study those sculptures at the Nelson-Atkins Museum
of Art?
</P>
<P>
   It's all about the trappings of leadership _ the symbols that a
culture uses to convey authority.
</P>
<P>
   Each semester, Rockhurst economics professor Michael Tansey
leads MBA students on tours of the Nelson's collection. Tansey
points out how leaders throughout time have borrowed or been imbued
with emblems of power. Cultures use these visual keys to incite
awe, loyalty and, sometimes, fanaticism.
</P>
<P>
   Tansey helps fast-track executives remember that effective
leadership involves more than financial acumen or inherited
position. It helps to look and act the leader's part too, in order
to get anyone to follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Throughout history, leaders often looked to shared symbols and
values to build support among their followers,'' Tansey said. ``It
often was a matter of life or death. They looked to things like
religion, politics, family and nationality to connect.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Tansey noted, those are affiliations that ``modern
corporate America can't touch.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's business leaders have to connect with employees through
different sets of core values, such as honesty and empathy _
characteristics that are a lot harder to illustrate than religion
or military might.
</P>
<P>
   A sculptor put Louis XIV on a horse to convey speed, height and
a position of honor, Tansey said. The king's right hand is raised
in a languid point ahead, a visual cue for his ability to set a
course for France.
</P>
<P>
   Was the pose unrealistic? Yes. But it was, Tansey argued, more
effective as a motivator of Louis XIV's subjects than plopping the
Versailles-building, power-grabbing king on a painted throne.
</P>
<P>
   So what about Franklin in a toga?
</P>
<P>
   Remember, Tansey said, that those who rocked the cradle of
American democracy revered the quest for knowledge undertaken by
the fine minds of ancient Rome. The sculptor's reverential draping
on the bust was a nod to Franklin's rise to leadership through
brilliant thinking, not divine right, aristocracy or military
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Tansey, who came to art appreciation naturally as the son of a
noted art historian, Richard G. Tansey, acknowledged that
photographs, perhaps more than painting or sculpture, conveyed
modern symbols of power in picturing corporate leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The trappings of leadership _ a gleaming mahogany desktop, a
sleek laptop or pocket-size computer, a mansion in an upscale
neighborhood or a luxury automobile _ often provide the backdrop
for CEO portraits.
</P>
<P>
   Those symbols of power, when pictured with established leaders,
set standards for others to emulate, Tansey said. (Louis XIV's
frenzied palace-building spurred French noblemen to build their own
monstrous homes, thus bankrupting some of them.)
</P>
<P>
   On the museum tour, Tansey said a knight's armor was perhaps the
most blatant symbol of the power and security that such an honored
position offered. But times have changed, he said; simple symbols
don't always suffice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology has changed the way people connect with each
other,'' the professor said. ``We don't have to, at least in
business, be ready to die for our leader or our leader for us. But
we do have to connect values, to figure out what we believe in and
where we fit in.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the signals sent from the top _ the emblems of power _
don't fit our values, we don't belong there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
