<SLUG> BC-PHONE-SCAMS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHONE SCAMS HIT RESIDENTS IN KANSAS CITY AREA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD ESPINOZA  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Scam artists have been calling area residents
with tales that piles of cash are waiting for them with just one
catch: The lucky winners must send thousands of dollars to Canada
to cover taxes first.
</P>
<P>
   It's a scam, say Mission, Kan., police and the Royal Canadian
Mounted Police. Canadian authorities have been working since
February to track down the criminals behind it.
</P>
<P>
   The scam has been directed only at U.S. residents, beginning
with Texans, said Sgt. Bob Mainwaring of the Canadian police's
commercial crime section in Calgary, Alberta.
</P>
<P>
   Mission police first heard about this revival of an old scam
Thursday, when a man told them a caller had tried to talk him into
sending money to Canada. The man, who did not fall for the ruse,
received the call in Overland Park, Kan. ,so Mission police sent
him to that city. Overland Park detectives had not heard from the
man by Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Later Thursday, a woman told Mission Police Officer Krista
Shannon that a man said that she had won $125,000 in a Canadian
class-action lawsuit, but that she had to send $7,840 to cover the
taxes. The woman did not have the money, so she went with her
husband to the police station because she was upset about not being
able to claim the $125,000 immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt so bad for them,'' Shannon said. ``They wanted to win
so badly.''
</P>
<P>
   Shannon assured the man and the woman that someone was just
trying to steal from them.
</P>
<P>
   The scam artists work hard to be convincing, said another
Mission man who received a call Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The caller spent about 30 minutes trying to make the man and his
wife believe they could claim $100,000 from Publisher's
Clearinghouse Sweepstakes if they first paid a tax on the prize.
The U.S. government would take $30,000, but the man said the
sweepstakes company could route the prize through Canada, which
would cost only $10,000 in taxes, the Mission man said.
</P>
<P>
   The caller told the wife to get her hair done March 30, because
that's when celebrities would stop by with the prize money and take
them to lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Myself and Ed McMahon and Dick Clark are going to be
there on the 30th to give you $100,000, but we want it kept secret
because we're going to be carrying a lot of money,' &UR; '' the Mission
man said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mission man said that he had fun keeping the caller on the
line as long as he could, but that he did not fall for the scam. He
reported it to police Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The scam artist who called about the class-action lawsuit told
the woman she could reach him at a number that rings in southern
Alberta, near the U.S. border in Montana. No one returned a call
left at the number on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The second call recipient in Mission was given an 800 number,
which was busy every time he and police called it.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian authorities said the scam artists had been using a
block of southern Alberta phone numbers that were issued to a
company, but they had been unable to get a warrant to find out to
whom they belonged. The numbers could forward the calls somewhere
else, Mainwaring said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. residents who have sent money to the scam artists have used
Western Union money transfers, which let people with the right
numbers claim the money at any North American Western Union office.
At least some of the money had been claimed in Montreal, Mainwaring
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian police are working with FBI and U.S. Customs agents
to track down the criminals. Those who receive calls asking them to
send money should tell police.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
