u i BC-R-UGANDA-CULT-1STLD-W     03-28 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-UGANDA-CULT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-470&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BODIES AT A NEW UGANDA SITE INDICATE EARLIER CULT DEATHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Repeating with clarification in sub explanation; 591 is the
corrected figure)  
 (Subs 3rd graf to change death toll from 593 to 591; subs 2nd graf
to change `cement' to `concrete'; inserts new graf after 10th graf
to mention discovery of 153 bodies on Friday)  
 (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By IAN FISHER   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   RUGAZI, Uganda _ In one room the concrete floor looked a little
new, and on a hunch, the police began to dig Tuesday. First they
found a human foot, sole upturned, poking up from the rubble.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few hours, 28 bodies were hauled out of a pit _
carefully sealed with concrete, maybe months ago _ inside the house
owned by a leader of a cult in western Uganda. By dark the pit was
only half emptied.
</P>
<P>
   It was, on one level, another horrifying discovery in the 11
days since more than 300 people were found burned to death at a
church not far from here. The death toll, from three different
sites, has now risen to at least 591, including 74 bodies found
buried in the backyard of this same house Monday. There are at
least two more suspected grave sites.
</P>
<P>
   But the discovery of the pit may also indicate just how well
organized, and perhaps longstanding, this march to mass murder in
Uganda was.
</P>
<P>
   The Ugandan police pathologist, Dr. Thaddeus Barungi, said
Tuesday that the corpses buried inside the house were ``much
older'' than the ones in the back yard, which he estimated had been
killed less than a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   And the care taken in constructing and sealing the pit may
suggest that the leaders thought they could get away with some
murders early on. There was even an explanation why they needed a
hole in the middle of their house: They had told a local politician
that they planned to install an ``underground'' refrigerator,
police said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   As each day passes, the police say it becomes clearer that most
_ maybe even all _ the people were slain and were not the victims
of mass suicide, as was originally suspected when the bodies at the
church in the village of Kanungu were discovered March 17.
</P>
<P>
   Some investigators say they cannot rule out suicide for some
people in the church. After all, the cult _ called the Movement for
the Restoration of the Ten Commandments of God _ professed to
believe that the world would end on Dec. 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But many of the other victims found since then show signs of
strangulation: One woman, for example, found in the back yard of
the house here had a banana leaf tied around her neck. The skull of
another corpse was crushed.
</P>
<P>
   And on Friday the police unearthed the bodies of 153 people who
had been slashed or strangled from a mass grave at a cult site in
Rutoma, about 30 miles from Kanungu.
</P>
<P>
   The police say their investigation has also begun to turn to
exactly how so many people could have been killed _ seemingly
without any neighbors hearing the first of it. There has been much
speculation that many victims were poisoned, particularly because
many corpses show no sign of violence at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't kill all these human beings alone,'' said Godfrey
Bangirana, an assistant police commissioner, on Tuesday as he stood
aside a row of several dozen corpses in the back yard here. ``This
was an organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``And an organized crime cannot be committed by one person,'' he
added. ``It must be a group.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The police have not ruled out the possibility that the leaders,
and particularly the overall leader, Joseph Kibwetere, are still
alive, perhaps having escaped to the Democratic Republic of the
Congo, not far away.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies found Tuesday were in the home of Dominic Kataribabo,
62, an excommunicated priest reported to hold a doctorate in
theology. He lived in a well-constructed stone house of 10 rooms at
the top of a hill in the village here, surrounded by a small banana
plantation, in shouting range of the children who play at the
Rugazi Central Primary School.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors and police said the house was apparently a place where
cult members came to study. Both neighbors and the police also say
that cars and small trucks often came to the house at night.
</P>
<P>
   What strains belief is that no one interviewed by reporters
Tuesday at the site _ or by the police _ admitted to having any
idea what was happening there. Even Kataribabo's brother, Arsen
Oworynawe, 78, who lives in a house maybe 20 yards from where the
74 bodies were buried, said he did not know.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know such a thing could happen,'' said Oworynawe, a
carpenter who said he helped build his brother's house. The back
yard, he said, had been shielded off by huge reed mats and he could
see nothing.
</P>
<P>
   He had little to say about his brother, except that he did not
seem crazy to him and that he last saw him on March 12, when
Kataribabo said he was going to Kampala, the capital of Uganda.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was normal,'' his brother said. ``I have a son in Kampala
and I asked him to send greetings.''
</P>
<P>
   Owarynawe said he himself belonged to the cult for about three
months several years ago. ``I didn't like the way they were
preaching,'' he said. ``They never wanted anyone to drink or smoke.
And eating, you know, was a problem. They would eat only once a
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, his family sat with cloths covering their noses because
the stench from the bodies was so strong. Owarynawe had his own way
of combating the horror: ``I need a drink,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the local police dug up 74 bodies from one large hole
in the back yard, then reburied them in two other holes the cult
members had already dug. But the local police were supposed to have
waited until Tuesday, when senior investigators arrived to perform
more detailed forensic tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a breakdown in communications,'' said Mugenyi
Assuman, a Uganda police spokesman at the site. ``We had told them
to wait but somehow somebody misinformed them yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   So Tuesday a pack of prisoners and laborers in bare feet _ some
with their hands wrapped in garbage bags _ unearthed the bodies
again. Quick autopsies were performed out in the open on some of
the corpses and tissue samples were taken for analysis.
Investigators counted 46 females, 26 males and two of uncertain
sex, including a baby less then three months old.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 28 bodies pulled so far from the pit, 15 were female and
13 were male. Several were young children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-00 2217EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
