<DOCNO> NYT20000328.0347 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0628 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-NASA-MARS-HNS &LR;      03-28 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASA-MARS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASA ADMITS ITS `CHEAPER' TRIPS TO MARS WENT TOO FAR 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the wake of a critical report on its failed Mars
Polar Lander mission, NASA conceded Tuesday that it has pushed its
``faster, better, cheaper'' revolution too far, unfairly asking its
scientists and engineers to do the impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've found the boundary, and we're stepping back from it,''
said Edward Weiler, NASA's associate administrator for space
science. ``We can do missions faster and cheaper, but the major
emphasis must be on the better.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiler's comments, and the cancellation of another robotic
landing on Mars planned for 2001, came in response to an
independent report, made public Tuesday, that said the Polar Lander
likely was destroyed when it slammed into the Red Planet at 50 mph
after a software glitch signaled the engine to shut off
prematurely.
</P>
<P>
   That glitch, the report said, should have been detected by
NASA's contractor, Lockheed-Martin, or by engineers at NASA's Jet
Propulsion Laboratory in Pasadena, Calif. It was not found because
of inadequate testing, a shortage of experienced staff, poor
communication and a budget that was at least 30 percent less than
needed.
</P>
<P>
   The lander was last heard from Dec. 3, nearly a year after it
left Earth on a mission to search for frozen water on the Martian
south pole, evidence that would support the theory that Mars once
supported life, and could again.
</P>
<P>
   The report also looked at past missions that had succeeded and
others that had failed. In past decades the Mars program worked on
single, large projects with heavy oversight that launched only when
they were ready. That gave way under the faster, cheaper mandate to
smaller, multiple missions with tighter staffing. The report's
author said downsizing at NASA had left the project staffs ``one
person deep'' and forced 80-hour weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Weiler, pledging that NASA would learn from its mistakes, said
the agency remains committed to the long-term goal of exploring
Mars, first with robots, and later with a human mission.
</P>
<P>
   He announced that all of the agency's Mars projects would be put
under one official to improve coordination.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Hubbard, associate director for astrobiology and space
programs at NASA's Ames Research Center in California, will move to
the agency's Washington headquarters to serve as Mars program
director, Weiler said.
</P>
<P>
   The agency also will change the way it doles out money for Mars
projects, keeping some funds in reserve at headquarters to be used
when problems arise. That process, Weiler said, would encourage
better communication between NASA headquarters and its centers
around the country, which would have to ask for extra funds,
hopefully alerting top officials to serious problems before launch.
</P>
<P>
   ``This means they will know there is a relief valve in
Washington,'' he said. ``It doesn't mean we're going to be a blank
check, but it means if you have a real serious problem, if you're
on the verge of making the wrong decision based on cost and only
cost, you better get your body to Washington and talk to me. We do
not want our best people at JPL to be afraid to raise issues.''
</P>
<P>
   But Weiler said he doesn't blame anyone at JPL for the loss of
the Polar Lander.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pushed them too far and I will not condemn them because
they failed,'' he said. ``In fact, I salute them for trying to
succeed against these substantial odds.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration already has asked Congress for $20
million more for Mars exploration in next year's budget proposal,
and NASA Administrator Dan Goldin said last week that the agency
plans to hire 2,000 more employees and improve its training and
mentoring programs.
</P>
<P>
   A planned orbiter mission to Mars will go forward next year,
Weiler said Tuesday, as will the ``systematic search for evidence
of life on Mars.''
</P>
<P>
   The key to that, he said, is to ``follow the water.'' Finding it
on Mars would be the basis for humans one day landing on the planet
and exploring it in person because water would provide not only
sustenance, but also the building blocks for air to breathe and
fuel to explore the planet and to return home.
</P>
<P>
   Space aficionados praised the report and NASA's response to it,
but cautioned the space agency not to let up on Mars exploration,
which has drawn enormous public interest and support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Faster, better, cheaper moved us in the right direction, but
it was too far in the right direction,'' said Robert Zubrin,
president of the Colorado-based Mars Society and author of ``The
Case for Mars.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, there have always been mistakes, but the
difference is that there were other people to help catch the
mistakes,'' he said. ``Now the missions are underfunded, we don't
have enough people with the right expertise working on them. And
there's too much saluting going on, saying, `Yes, we can do it for
this amount of money. Yes, the probes are ready to fly now. So it
is written. So it shall be.'
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just too much of that,'' he said. ``The missions have
to go when they're ready to go and not because someone has
scheduled them.''
</P>
<P>
   But Zubrin also said NASA needs a well-defined goal, supported
by the next U.S. president, of sending humans to Mars, just as the
space program got its original boost from President Kennedy's
famous speech pledging to put a man on the moon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a president in the spring of 2001 who will commit us
to getting to Mars in the next decade,'' he said. ``If we don't do
it, we're admitting we are a nation of people who are much less
than we were before.''
</P>
<P>
   Louis Friedman, executive director of the California-based
Planetary Society, also encouraged the space agency and politicians
to embrace the Mars program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it doesn't slow down too much. Everybody wants the
problems fixed, and corrections made, but I hope they don't slip
into less ambitious missions in the future,'' he said. ``The danger
is in overreacting, so we learn from our mistakes and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
