<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0629 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BROOKLYN-MUSEUM--SUIT     03-28 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROOKLYN-MUSEUM--SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROOKLYN MUSEUM ISN'T GLOATING AFTER FEUD WITH MAYOR ENDS
</HEADLINE>
 (mg) 
By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Robert S. Rubin, the chairman of the Brooklyn Museum
of Art, sounded a bit grumpy.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, he had forced Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani, a man not
prone to backing down, to do just that. There will be no more
eviction threats, no more budget grenades.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Tuesday on the telephone, Rubin was in little mood to gloat,
at least not publicly. He reacted cautiously, like a child tasting
eggplant for the first time, to a softball question about whether
the museum would emerge stronger from its bitter six-month feud
with Giuliani. ``I really thought that it was over,'' he said,
sighing.
</P>
<P>
   In this topsy-turvy case, the winners are worried about what may
have been lost _ in public trust, in long-term government and
corporate support, in the willingness to display art that offends
some people _ just as the losers are hopeful about what may have
been won: Roman Catholic votes in a certain Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was real scary to a lot of us,'' said Alan J. Friedman,
chairman of the Cultural Institutions Group, a consortium of 33
museums and libraries that receive financing from New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sensation,'' an exhibition of contemporary British art,
angered Giuliani and many Catholics because it included a portrait
of the Virgin Mary with a breast fashioned from elephant dung.
Giuliani threatened to evict the museum and cut off its subsidies
for staging ``Sensation,'' an act that prompted the museum to sue
the city for violating its First Amendment rights.
</P>
<P>
   Although that case has now been settled, Rubin, for one, seemed
genuinely uncertain on Tuesday about the long-term consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Rubin said, museum membership is up 20 to 25 percent since
``Sensation.'' But, he said, who knows whether those new members
will remain a year from now? Sure, he said, new donors have ``come
out of the woodwork.'' But that too might be a temporary response,
he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, meanwhile, has mentioned the controversy in his
campaign literature, and he seized on the issue on Tuesday to make
an appeal to Catholics and cultural conservatives, two vital
constituencies for him in his Senate campaign against Hillary
Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe if I get the opportunity to vote sometime in the United
States Senate,'' he told reporters, ``I would vote very, very
differently than my opponent on the issue of whether public funds
should be used to desecrate people's religion, which I think is an
abominable use of public funds.''
</P>
<P>
   Mario M. Cuomo, the former governor of New York and a frequent
Giuliani critic, said Giuliani's capitulation was politically
smart. The mayor, Cuomo said, long ago scored his points with
Catholic voters. ``You don't have to bring it up,'' he said. ``They
know what you've done.''
</P>
<P>
   So there was no further gain in prolonging a lost legal cause.
``This was a necessary step,'' Cuomo said, ``and therefore an
intelligent one to take.'' Among museum professionals, Monday's
settlement was more an occasion of relief than of jubilation.
</P>
<P>
   For some, the case became an embarrassment, because it laid
open, in a public way, the messy and sometimes ethically uncertain
business of financing and staging a major art exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the museum were forced to give the city thousands of
pages of museum documents related to ``Sensation,'' from
memorandums by museum executives to e-mail messages by
representatives of Charles Saatchi, the advertising magnate who
owns the ``Sensation'' works.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the records revealed the extent to which the
director of the Brooklyn Museum of Art, Arnold Lehman _ having
failed to secure financial help from traditional corporate sources
_ resorted to raising money from those with a commercial interest
in the ``Sensation'' art.
</P>
<P>
   Although museum officials denied receiving financial support
from Saatchi, the records showed that he was the single largest
contributor, and that Lehman gave him a major role in shaping the
content of the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the disclosures, several museum officials said,
Lehman's standing has suffered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is something of a consensus that Arnold erred in
two areas,'' said one New York City museum director. ``First, the
advertising campaign was simply over the top,'' he said, referring
to mock public health advertisements warning that ``Sensation''
might cause vomiting. ``And second, it was obviously foolhardy to
dissemble about Saatchi's financial support.'' But neither is a
serious mistake, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman did not respond to messages left at his office seeking
comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
