<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0630 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-HATE-CRIMES TWOTAKES-KAN &LR;    03-28 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HATE-CRIMES, </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBATE OVER HOW TO PUNISH HATE CRIMES HAS FEW DEFINITE ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
 TWO TAKES-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Punch somebody in the nose because you're
angry, or just because you're a jerk, and risk a simple assault
charge.
</P>
<P>
   Slug them because you can't stomach that person's sexuality,
skin color or religion and _ in the 22 states with America's
broadest hate-crime laws _ that smack and the penalties for it
become something more.
</P>
<P>
   Why, wonder critics, is one wallop different from another? As
Shakespeare wrote, ``If you prick us, do we not bleed?'' Whether
gay or straight, white or black, Jew or gentile?
</P>
<P>
   Yet research on gay bashings, at least, suggests that beatings
delivered out of ill will toward a group of people really are
different. University of California-Davis psychologist Gregory
Herek found that anti-homosexual attacks leave victims suffering
deeper and longer-lasting depression and fear than other violent
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do more damage to the victim than the average assault,''
Herek said. ``It makes sense for policy to take that into
account.''
</P>
<P>
   A swastika scratched on a Jew's car is more, the argument
continues, than merely damage to a paint job. A cross burned on a
black family's lawn does more than just singe some grass.
</P>
<P>
   Those crimes terrorize whole communities, say those urging
Congress to expand federal hate-crime jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents respond that hate-crime laws go beyond punishing
actions. By exploring a criminal's prejudices, they say, this level
of political correctness attempts to police thought.
</P>
<P>
   Serious penalties already exist for serious offenses, they say,
and hate-crime laws only feed resentment between groups.
</P>
<P>
   The Libertarian Party, opposed to hate-crime laws on grounds
that they violate standards of equal justice, seized on federal
statistics recently to contend that blacks are twice as likely as
whites to be charged with hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hate-crime laws are apparently being used as another legal
weapon to prosecute African-Americans,'' said Steve Dasbach,
national director of the Libertarian Party.
</P>
<P>
   He noted the case of Obie Weathers, a black man accused of
beating two elderly white men and bludgeoning to death an
82-year-old white woman in San Antonio in mid-February. He
allegedly told police, ``I hate all white people.'' The attacks are
being investigated as hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Early this month, Ronald Taylor was accused of shooting two
persons and critically wounding three others in Wilkinsburg, Pa.,
in a spree that witnesses said spared blacks but not whites. He has
been charged with hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another example of the law of unintended consequences:
Legislation designed to punish white racists has wound up
condemning more blacks to prison to serve longer sentences,''
Dasbach said.
</P>
<P>
   The Libertarians came to their conclusions by comparing federal
tallies of the 2,336 anti-black hate crimes blamed on whites in
1997 to the 718 anti-white crimes blamed on blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adjusting for the fact that blacks make up just 13 percent of
the (U.S.) population, they were statistically twice as likely as
whites to face prosecution for hate crimes,'' a Libertarian news
release concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the same FBI data show anti-black crimes to be more
than three times as common as anti-white crimes.
</P>
<P>
   And those statistics suggest anti-gay crimes are more than 300
times as common as those against people who are targets because of
their heterosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Such comparisons sometimes prompt discussion of the death last
September of Jesse Dirkhising, a 13-year-old boy drugged, bound,
raped and suffocated in Arkansas. Why, wonder some, don't
supporters of hate-crime laws champion this case? Is it, they
suggest, because the accused killers are gay?
</P>
<P>
   Those questions about the Dirkhising case, civil-rights
activists respond, miss the point of hate-crime laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that a white attacks a black, or a gay man attacks a
heterosexual man does not a hate crime make,'' said Mark Potok,
editor of the Intelligence Report, which tracks hate groups. He
said that ``you have to have some evidence that bias motivated the
crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Potok doubts hate-crime laws work as deterrents, but he supports
them as symbolically important.
</P>
<P>
   The case for more far-reaching hate-crime laws often is argued
in the context of the 1998 death of James Byrd Jr., a black man
dragged to pieces behind a pickup in rural Texas by avowed racists
motivated by prejudice. Likewise, the slaying of Matthew Shepard _
a gay man beaten, burned and tied to a fence in 1998 by two men who
admitted to singling him out because he was homosexual _ is cited
as the kind of case that would benefit from federal law enforcement
help.
</P>
<P>
   Yale University political scientist Donald Green warned against
drawing conclusions from hate-crime statistics or high-profile
stories. The statistics, he said, don't mean much.
</P>
<P>
   States and cities compile and report with wildly varying
precision. Some simply don't collect the numbers. Others keep track
but don't report their figures to the federal government. So the
numbers used to make any case should be viewed, he said, with great
skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very critical of people who say it's a growing problem,''
Green said. ``And people who say the laws don't work have no
evidence, either. The truth is we just don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   His research found that hate crimes were most common during the
rapid migration of new groups into once-segregated areas. Green
believes hate crimes are more serious than other acts of violence,
but he says hate-crime laws don't necessarily work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they're effective because I don't think they're
given a fair chance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, he said, public service announcements to make
people aware of hate-crime laws _ ostensibly a deterrent _ are
rare.
</P>
<P>
   Quick: Does Missouri, does Kansas, does the place where you live
have a hate-crime law? Research suggests you probably don't know. A
hate crime can buy you extra jail time in Missouri, but not in
Kansas, where lawmakers are considering legislation.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 42 states and the District of Columbia have hate-crime
statutes.
</P>
<P>
   The sole federal hate-crime law rests in a 1968 civil rights act
that calls for added penalties for violence carried out ``because
of the actual or perceived race, color, religion, or national
origin of any person.'' (MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
