<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0632 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-HATE-CRIMES SECONDTAKE-KAN &LR;    03-28 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HATE-CRIMES, </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBATE OVER HOW TO PUNISH HATE CRIMES HAS FEW DEFINITE ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
 SECOND TAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (any person'') &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pending legislation to change that law would give federal law
enforcement the power to step into more cases, especially when
state and local police lack the resources or desire to pursue hate
crimes. It would also add gender, disability and sexual orientation
to the protected categories.
</P>
<P>
   The existing federal law has not been used to prosecute more
than 10 persons in any year. No case has involved black-on-white
violence. Instead, the cases have been like the conviction of four
men who burned a cross on a woman's lawn in Rushville, Mo., in 1997
because they thought she was involved in interracial dating.
</P>
<P>
   Although reliable statistics remain elusive, legal experts say
most cases have been prosecuted under various state laws rather
than the federal statute.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri amended its hate-crime law last summer _ with a bill
sponsored by a legislator outraged at the Shepard case _ to include
sexual orientation. So now singling someone out for attack because
that person is gay or lesbian could turn a one-year jail sentence
into a five-year prison term, or a five-year prison term into a
seven-year penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri Supreme Court upheld hate-crime penalties in 1994
in a case of a man convicted of burning a cross on the porch of a
West Plains church.
</P>
<P>
   A Wisconsin case involving black men who beat up a white man and
stole his sneakers after they emerged angry from a screening of the
movie ``Mississippi Burning'' gave the clearest court test of
hate-crime laws. It led to a 1993 U.S. Supreme Court ruling that
said racism and other biases can be calculated in setting penalties
for a crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point of these laws is that you can be a bigot, but if you
act on that attitude you could serve serious time,'' said Michael
Lieberman, who lobbies for the federal bill on behalf of the
Anti-Defamation League.
</P>
<P>
   ``A crime which happens merely because of someone's race or
religion or sexual orientation, that's something as a society we
can say is against our core values,'' Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   Critics, though, say hate-crime laws amount to good intentions
gone bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the people who are caught up in these things are
teen-agers or poor people who don't follow public affairs,'' said
Tim Lynch, an attorney at the libertarian Cato Institute. ``So how
is it going to stop them if they're not even aware of the laws in
the first place?''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the federal legislation advances this year, observers
say, may turn on the emergence of a particularly ugly crime that
echoes the meanness that left Matthew Shepard mortally wounded and
lashed to a fence. So far, there have been hearings in Congress but
no committee votes.
</P>
<P>
   Groups such as the American Civil Liberties Union weigh in with
conditional support. The ACLU says it will back the bill only if
strict limits are added on how evidence can be used in hate-crime
prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hate-crime legislation raises difficult questions,'' said
Christopher Anders, an ACLU lobbyist in Washington. ``You need to
make sure you answer them in a way that protects people from a
special kind of violence while still not infringing on what someone
used to read or what someone used to think.''
</P>
</TEXT>
