   Editors, please note the following elimination and correction:
</P>
<P>
   We have have sent out an elimination advisory for NYT20 of
tonight's file. Due to an editing error, the Associated Press
photo, slugged BUS-TRAIN-CRASH-2, was incorrectly made available to
clients of the news service.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT37) NEW YORK -- March 28, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 2 --
PATRICK-STEWART-THEATER -- Patrick Stewart in Arthur Miller's play
``The Ride Down Mount Morgan.'' Stewart's first ``Ride,'' at the
Joseph Papp Public Theater in 1998, brought him mixed reviews and a
mild concussion. So why has he decided to star again in the Arthur
Miller play - this time on Broadway? ``There are some roles that
gnaw at you,'' said the Royal Shakespeare Company veteran and
``Star Trek: The Next Generation'' captain. ``There's this impulse
that I must do it again, that I almost got it right, but not
quite.'' (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) UNDATED -- March 28, 2000 -- VANISHED-BOXER-B&AMP;W --
Federal prosecutors have charged two Russian mobsters with
abducting and murdering a professional boxer who had mysteriously
disappeared from a Brooklyn garage in late 1995. The two men were
identified as Alexander Nosov, 24, who is in jail in Germany on an
unrelated charge, and Natan Gozman, about the same age, who is at
large. The boxer, Sergei Kobozev, a cruiserweight, had amassed a
22-1 record. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) UNDATED -- March 28, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 2 --
PRINTS-ART -- What was it that printmakers chose to show when they
depicted the ancient world? That is the question the exhibition
``Revivals, Reveries and Reconstructions: Images of Antiquity in
Prints From 1500 to 1800,'' on view at the Philadelphia Museum of
Art until April 16, seeks to answer. Giambattista Piranesi's
``Large Marble Vase With Putti and Grape Vines Found in Hadrian's
Villa in 1769,'' left; the engraving ``The Farnese Hercules''
(circa 1592), by Hendrick Goltzius. (Philadelphia Museum of Art/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) UNDATED -- March 28, 2000 -- NY-WOMENS-MUSEUM -- More
than 150 years after the first convention on women's rights
unfolded in upstate New York, Gov. George Pataki has proposed
social progress of a different sort: a major museum devoted to
women's history. The $125 million museum, seen in an artist's
rendering, would be built in Battery Park City near the southern
tip of Manhattan, under a proposal by Pataki that has been endorsed
by a group of prominent civic and business leaders. (Ralph
Appelbaum Associates Inc./The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) UNDATED -- March 28, 2000 -- OBIT-COMFORT -- Dr. Alex
Comfort, whose graphically illustrated 1972 book ``The Joy of Sex''
became the coffee-table Kama Sutra of the baby-boom generation,
died Sunday at a nursing home in Banbury, northwest of London. He
was 80. The book sold more than 12 million copies and outshone the
author's other achievements. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) NASHVILLE, Tenn. -- March 28, 2000 -- TENN-EXECUTE --
Philip Ray Workman, right, is to be executed on April 6 for the
1981 killing of Lt. Ronald Oliver. Workman's daughter, Chrystal
Michelle Workman-Burnham, seated at left, and Lieutenant Oliver's
daughter, Paula Dodillet, appeared together Monday at a press
conference in Nashville. (Christopher Berkey/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) UNDATED -- March 28, 2000 -- SCI-NEANDERTHAL -- New DNA
tests show little evidence linking Neanderthals to modern humans.
The skull of a Neanderthal found near Krapina, Croatia. (Croatian
National History Museum/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) LONDON -- March 28, 2000 -- IMF-KOEHLER -- Laying out
his vision of the future of the International Monetary Fund, Horst
Koehler, the new managing director, said Tuesday that rather than
shrinking as some critics have suggested, the fund should expand
its role as ``a crucial cornerstone'' of globalization. His remarks
came amid a welter of conflicting proposals for reforming the IMF,
one of the world's important financial institutions, both in the
U.S. Congress and in the Clinton administration. (Carlos
Lopez-Barillas/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) WILMINGTON, Calif. -- March 28, 2000 -- OPEC-COSTS-3 --
Though surging fuel prices and rising costs for chemicals and other
products have driven up expenses for many businesses, not all
industries or companies have been affected equally. And those that
have suffered have not, by and large, passed along the higher
costs; in part because global competition and a relatively strong
dollar have made it unwise to raise prices. This Texaco oil
refinery is located along the Pacific Coast Highway in Wilmington.
(Monica Almeida/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) WASHINGTON -- March 28, 2000 -- OPEC-COSTS-2 -- Though
surging fuel prices and rising costs for chemicals and other
products have driven up expenses for many businesses, not all
industries or companies have been affected equally. According to
the Fed's most recent ``beige book'' report on the economy, some
truckers indicate they are hurt more than might be expected because
competition from rail carriers hampers their ability to pass on
higher costs. A sign was displayed on the rear of a truck's cab
during a recent protest in Washington against the federal excise
tax on fuel. (Susana Raab/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) WAXAHACHIE, Texas -- March 28, 2000 -- OPEC-COSTS-1 --
Though surging fuel prices and rising costs for chemicals and other
products have driven up expenses for many businesses, not all
industries or companies have been affected equally. And those that
have suffered have not, by and large, passed along the higher
costs; in part because global competition and a relatively strong
dollar have made it unwise to raise prices. Donald Patman, a Texas
farmer, is paying 40 cents a gallon more this year to fuel his
diesel tractors, but his customers won't shoulder the increases.
(Mark Graham/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) SPARTANBURG, S.C. -- March 28, 2000 -- EMPLOYEE-TRAINING
-- According to the American Society for Training and Development,
companies spend about $55 billion a year on formal training of all
kinds, offten using elaborate and eccentric methods to put their
point across. Trouble is, many of these programs have no practical
value. To learn team building, Elise Tienken of Eurest Dining
Services drove blindfolded, while a co-worker, Lenny McFall, guided
her through an obstacle course at the BMW Performance Center in
Spartanburg. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- March 28, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 2 --
TV-VIDEO-ART -- On March 23, 1969, the infant medium of video art
launched a guerrilla raid on broadcast television, airing on
Boston's WGBH. The attack, a show titled ``The Medium Iis the
Medium'' and described in the program guide as ``six avant-garde
artists take over television,'' consisted of a barrage of abstract
images and visual non sequiturs. Nam June Paik's ``Electronic
Opera, No. 1'' jolted viewers with the distorted face of Richard
Nixon. (Electronic Arts Intermix, New York/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) OFF ST. LUCIA, the British West Indies -- March 28, 2000
-- HORIZONLIVE -- Bob Clyatt, chief executive of HorizonLive.com,
an online distance learning company, sailing amidst the British
West Indies. ``I started my first business, a Web design company
called I/O 360, at age 36,'' he writes. ``I had been a manager at
Reuters, and people who reported to me there thought they had to
laugh at my jokes. Managing a bunch of 20-somethings in a start-up
was completely different. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) BAYONNE, N.J. -- March 28, 2000 -- NJ-RAIL -- A half
century after the region's last streetcar tracks were torn up to
make way for more cars and buses, New Jersey officials are set to
open the first leg of a $1.1 billion trolley system along the
Hudson River, one that will eventually move more than 100,000
people through the most densely populated area in the state. A
streetcar arrives to the Jersey Avenue stop during a test run,
Tuesday. In the background is the World Trade Center in lower
Manhattan. (Keith Meyers/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) UNDATED -- March 28, 2000 -- SUN-FILM-REVIEW -- Newroz
Baz in the haunting ``Journey to the Sun,'' written and directed by
Yesim Ustaoglu. The film tells the story of Mehmet (played by Baz),
a young man with one of the more interesting occupations you'll see
in modern movies. His job is to find leaks in the water pipes below
his city, and he uses a long brass rod he places on the pavement,
listening through it to catch the rumbles. (Film Society of Lincoln
Center/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NAPA, Calif. -- March 28, 2000 -- DIANA-WRITER -- Moira
Johnston with a copy of ``The Bodyguard's Story'' which she wrote
based on the account by Trever Rees-Jones of the crash that killed
Princess Diana, Dodi Fayed and the driver. The prize-winning
investigative journalist whose exhaustive reporting has explored
repressed memory and taken on powerful corporations, was the writer
to whom Rees-Jones broke his 2 1/2-year silence about the events
leading up to the fatal crash in a Paris tunnel. (Kent Porter/Santa
Rosa Press Democrat) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) TENNGA, Ga. -- March 28, 2000 -- BUS-TRAIN-CRASH-1 --
Firefighter Carl Helton collects items at the scene of a fatal
school bus crash with a CSX freight train in Tennga on Tuesday. The
train slammed into the bus Tuesday morning at an unmarked crossing
near the Georgia-Tennessee line, splitting it in two and killing
two children. The five other elementary school pupils on board were
critically injured. No one on the CSX train was injured. (John
Spink/The Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) UNDATED -- March 28, 2000 -- HEANEY-BEOWULF-2 -- The
opening lines of ``Beowulf'' from the sole surviving Old English
manuscript (circa 1000 A.D.), at the British Museum (British
Library Publications and the University of Michigan Press/The New
York Times). A recent translation into modern English by the poet
Seamus Heaney, right, is a best seller in Britain and the United
States. (Michelle V. Agins/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) UNDATED -- March 28, 2000 -- HEANEY-BEOWULF-1 -- At the
beginning of the new millennium, one of the surprise successes of
the publishing season is a 1,000-year-old masterpiece. The cover of
Seamus Heaney's verse translation of ``Beowulf,'' which has become
a best seller in Britain and the United States. (Farrar, Straus &AMP;
Giroux/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) WASHINGTON -- March 28, 2000 -- SCI-NASA-MARS -- Dr.
Edward Weiler, left, associate administrator for space science, and
Thomas Young, chairman of the investigative team looking into the
failure of the Mars Polar Lander mission, speak to reporters
Tuesday after issuing a report on NASA's Mars exploration program.
The report was highly critical of the management of the program and
said that lack of funding, testing and planning led to the failure
of two recent Mars probes. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) UNDATED -- March 28, 2000 -- NY-NUKE-PLANT-B&AMP;W -- In the
largest deal ever for an American nuclear reactor, the New York
Power Authority was expected to choose Tuesday between two bidders
for two upstate plants. After several weeks of delays and
complications, the authority appeared to be leaning toward the
larger company, Entergy Nuclear of Jackson, Miss, which already
owns five other plants. The company has bid more than $800 million
for the plants: James A. FitzPatrick plant in Oswego County, top,
and Indian Point 3 in Westchester County. (New York Power
Authority, top, Joyce Dopkeen)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) BOSTON -- March 28, 2000 -- TECHNO-VENTURE-BOS -- Wall
Street is out. Venture capital is in. Venture Capital is drawing
the hottest talent, among the gray hairs and the new MBAs. Sheryl
Marshall is living the transition. In August, she quit her longtime
gig as a high-profile stockbroker and cut off her mane of curly
hair. ``I got the venture capital haircut,'' says Marshall, who
started Axxon Capital Inc. with a partner, Paula Groves. (Dominic
Chavez/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) FALL RIVER, Mass. -- March 28, 2000 --
FOOD-TECH-SCHOOLS-BOS -- Culinary arts programs at vocational
technical schools are booming. A big part of the reason appears to
be the popularity of colorful television chefs. At Diman Regional
Vocational Technical High School in Fall River, Ed Kerr, who heads
the school's culinary program, assisted students in the preparation
of a seafood tortellini flambe. ``They come in here and ask if we
can make what they see on TV, and it's really made them see how
exciting cooking can be,'' said Kerr. (Barry Chin/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WASHINGTON -- March 28, 2000 -- FLAG-DESECRATE -- The
Senate on Tuesday was deliberating an amendment to the U.S.
Constitution that could make desecrating the American flag illegal.
Meanwhile, outside the Capitol, representatives of various
veteran's groups from around the United States protested in favor
of the amendment. The pending proposal, sponsored by Sen. Orin
Hatch, R-Utah, is likely to mirror the last flag-desecration vote
in the Senate, in 1995, when supporters fell three short of the
two-thirds majority needed to amend the Constitution. (Stephen
Crowley/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) UNDATED -- March 28, 2000 -- BLACKS-TAXIS-COMMENT-COX --
No black man is exonerated from the socio-political liability of
his black identity in the United States, writes Marcus Franklin.
The actor Danny Glover, who filed a complaint last year with New
York City because taxis whizzed by him, can attest to this fact.
The artist's rendering depicts a black man being passed up by a
cab, which proceeds to the opposite corner and promptly picks up a
white man. (The Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) RESTON, Virg. -- March 28, 2000 -- BUSH-EDUC -- Gov.
George W. Bush, running for the Republican presidential nomination,
poses with a supporter, left, before delivering a speech on
education, Tuesday. At right are members of Bush's Secret Service
detail. Bush laid out a $5 billion plan to address reading problems
in the nation's youngest school students Tuesday, declaring their
illiteracy amounts to a ``national emergency.'' (Stephen
Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- March 28, 2000 -- SPRING-SORREL -- Risotto
with sorrel, arugala and pesto at Fressen, in Manhattan. No other
vegetable at this time of year has such power, or complexity as
sorrel. It is fruity like rhubarb, tart like a lemon and herbal
like basil. And it can be treated like all three. (Norman Y.
Lono/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WASHINGTON -- March 28, 2000 -- SCOTUS-HATE-CRIME -- A
lawyer for a white New Jersey man who fired shots into a black
family's home asked the Supreme Court Tueday to require juries to
decide whether such acts can be punished more harshly under
hate-crime laws. New Jersey's lawyer, Lisa S. Gochman, right,
argued that motive is a traditional sentencing factor that properly
was decided by the judge in the case. Judges can sentence people to
death by finding aggravating factors, and they also can increase
sentences under hate-crime laws, she said. Gochman and John Farmer,
the New Jersey attorney general, center, spoke to reporters,
Tuesday on the steps of the court after presenting arguements. In
the background is Gochman's son Jordan, 9. (Justin Lane/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- March 28, 2000 -- KITCHEN-WARES -- The Kuhn
Rikon grater looks like either a failed attempt at an industrial
fly swatter or a very awkward spatzle maker. But this odd little
tool is actually a cheese and chocolate grater. And quite a good
one at that. (Tony Cenicola/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- March 28, 2000 -- TASTINGS -- Dutton Ranch
consists of more than 1,000 acres scattered over 43 sites, too
broad an area for geographical distinctions on labels. Still, the
wines tasted shared a zesty acidity and bright green-apple flavors.
They seemed better able to stand up to oak barrel aging than many
chardonnays. (Tony Cenicola/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WASHINGTON -- March 28, 2000 -- GORE-MUBARAK -- President
Hosni Mubarak of Egypt, right, meets with Vice President Al Gore at
Blair House, the official resident of visiting dignitaries,
Tuesday. Mubarak met earlier with President Clinton where they
discussed the status of Middle East peace negotiations. (Paul
Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WASHINGTON -- March 28, 2000 -- CLINTON-MUBARAK --
President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt talks to reporters as President
Clinton and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright look on in the
Oval office, Tuesday. Mubarak's White House visit Tuesday coincided
with the windup of another round of inconclusive
Israeli-Palestinian negotiations and follows Clinton's unproductive
meeting Sunday in Geneva, Switzerland, with President Hafez Assad
of Syria. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) STATE CENTER, Iowa -- March 28, 2000 -- IOWA-PORK-2 --
Big corporate operators have taken over the bulk of Iowa's pork
production, with dire results not only for the small farmer but
also for those of us who were raised on succulent pork chops and
pork roasts. Fat gives pork some of its flavor, but modern hogs are
bred to minimize fat. Kelly Biensen, a fifth-generation hog farmer,
is determined to do things differently. Biensen and his wife are
retro-pioneers who are producing pork, like this young piglet, the
old-fashioned way; giving them lots of room to move about. They
also refuse to use the drugs and hormones many corporate farms use.
(Rodney White/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) STATE CENTER, Iowa -- March 28, 2000 -- IOWA-PORK -- Big
corporate operators have taken over the bulk of Iowa's pork
production, with dire results not only for the small farmer but
also for those of us who were raised on succulent pork chops and
pork roasts. Fat gives pork some of its flavor, but modern hogs are
bred to minimize fat. Kelly Biensen, a fifth-generation hog farmer,
seen with his pigs, is determined to do things differently. Biensen
and his wife are retro-pioneers who are producing pork the
old-fashioned way; giving their pigs lots of room to move about and
eschewing the drugs and hormones many use. (Rodney White/The New
York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) ISRAEL -- March 28, 2000 -- ISRAEL-NETANYAHU -- Police
recommended Tuesday that former Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
be indicted on corruption charges. Investigators recommended that
Netanyahu be charged with fraud, attempted misuse of state funds,
breech of trust and obstruction of justice, police said in a
statement. Netanyahu's wife, Sarah, should be charged with theft
and attempted misuse of state funds, the statement said. Benjamin
Netanyahu listens to his wife Sarah in a 1997 file photo. (Rina
Castelnuovo/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
