<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0640 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-NASA-PROBE-HNS &LR;      03-28 1275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASA-PROBE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL BLAMES TOP NASA OFFICIALS FOR LAPSES IN MARS PROGRAM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   An investigative panel Tuesday blamed a mismanaged Mars program
for the design flaw that most likely caused NASA's Mars Polar
Lander to crash on the surface of the Red Planet in December.
</P>
<P>
   The flaw, triggered by improper electrical wiring and
inadequately tested computer software before its launching, caused
its landing rockets to shut off while the the probe was still
airborne, the panel concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Though the 18-member panel and its half-dozen consultants
identified the flaw as the most likely cause of the Polar Lander
failure, investigators found even more troubling, underlying
reasons for the losses of the Polar Lander and a companion
spacecraft, the Mars Climate Orbiter, in September.
</P>
<P>
   The agency's aggressive efforts to explore Mars with robot
probes is underfunded, understaffed and fails to employ the kinds
of pre-launch testing and critical independent oversight that
should have uncovered and corrected the problems.
</P>
<P>
   The findings will force NASA to slow its efforts to determine
whether Mars, now arrid and frigid, was once warm and wet enough to
harbor some form of life. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``It's important to recognize that in space it's a
`one-strike-and-you-are-out' business,'' said Thomas Young, the
former Martin Marietta Corp. aerospace company executive and space
agency official who chaired the investigative panel. ``Thousands of
functions can be done correctly, but one mistake can cause a
mission failure.''
</P>
<P>
   The panel blamed NASA's top administrators in Washington, Mars
program officials at the Jet Propulsion Laboratory in Pasadena,
Calif., and the agency's spacecraft contractor, Lockheed Martin
Astronautics of Denver, for the lapses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found significant flaws in the formulation and execution of
the Mars program,'' Young told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging its shortcomings, the space agency said it expects
to reshape its Mars exploration strategy by mid-summer after a
critical review and make immediate changes to the way it manages
the effort. However, JPL will continue to develop and control the
probes.
</P>
<P>
   ``In hindsight we asked them to do the impossible,'' Ed Weiler,
NASA's associate administrator for space science, said of the JPL
staff. With more funding, the mission could have succeeded, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   The retooling will slow the efforts NASA began in 1996 to launch
a pair of spacecraft to the Red Planet every 26 months. One is to
study the planet globally from orbit and the other to land and
explore a confined region. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Weiler said NASA has canceled plans for the 2001 launch of a
probe similar to the Polar Lander.
</P>
<P>
   The Young panel was formed in the aftermath of the Dec. 3 loss
of the Polar Lander, which was launched 11 months previously to
search for frozen water in the subsoil of the Martian south pole.
The space agency had invested $372 million in the Polar Lander and
the Climate Orbiter, which was lost as it reached Mars on Sept. 23.
The Climate Orbiter was to chart the daily migration of water vapor
in the planet's thin atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Flight control teams at JPL lost communications, as expected,
when the Polar Lander separated from the rocket stage that
delivered it from Earth. Communications were not to resume until
the probe had made a successful plunge into the atmosphere and a
controlled final descent by parachute and braking rockets.
</P>
<P>
   Transmissions to Earth were to resume after the probe reached
the Martian surface, deploying power-generating solar arrays and a
communications antenna. They never arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Handicapped by the lack of transmissions during the probe's 10
1/2-minute descent, the Young panel was nonetheless able to
pinpoint a flaw in the landing gear system of the spacecraft that
would have caused it to crash even if other complex systems had
worked perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   The flaw surfaced in late January as Lockheed Martin was
preparing NASA's 2001 Mars lander for its mission. The flaw led
investigators to re-examine the assembly of the Polar Lander, which
revealed that small sensors on its landing gear had been improperly
wired and that computer software associated with the sensors and
the probe's flight computer had not been adequately tested.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, investigators concluded, the three legs of the
landing gear deployed and locked into place as the Polar Lander
reached an altitude of 4,800 feet above the Martian surface.
</P>
<P>
   Each leg was equipped with a small magnetic sensor that was to
send a signal to the flight computer as soon as the first of the
legs made contact with the Martian terrain. The signal was to shut
off the probe's 12 small landing rockets, which began thrusting to
slow the Polar Lander's descent at an altitude of about 4,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   However, the investigators determined that on Polar Lander the
landing sensors could send an erroneous signal of landing as soon
as the legs were deployed. The signal would cause the descent
thrusters to shut off while the probe was still 130 feet above the
surface.
</P>
<P>
   Without the braking pulses from the thrusters, the Polar Lander
struck the surface at a speed of 50 miles per hour, causing a
destructive impact.
</P>
<P>
   The panel found that NASA conducted a pre-launch test of the
landing rockets but that the sensors did not generate the touchdown
signals as was intended.
</P>
<P>
   It traced the lack of signal to faulty wiring of the sensors.
After the sensors were re-wired, NASA did not repeat the testing
that would have unmasked the software problem.
</P>
<P>
   Further complicating the task of the investigators was NASA's
decision not to include a communications device on the lander that
would send ``telemetry,'' or data that would reveal what was
happening to the Polar Lander as it made its way to the surface.
The transponder was determined to be too expensive and too heavy
for the mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (panel) believes that not having a communications system
was a major mistake,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   The wider cause of NASA's Mars probe problems was linked to its
aggressive efforts to launch missions every 26 months at
increasingly lower cost, the panel said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the panel pointed out, NASA launched the Mars
Pathfinder, a lander and rover that successfully reached the rocky
terrain of the Martian equator on July 4, 1997. Two months later,
the Mars Global Surveyor, a camera-equipped orbiter, successfully
reached the Red Planet and continues to send images of
unprecedented detail to Earth.
</P>
<P>
   NASA spent $196 million on Pathfinder's development, but capped
combined development expenditures on the failed Polar Lander and
Climate Orbiter at $188 million.
</P>
<P>
   Young's panel concluded a 30 percent underfunding of the Polar
Lander mission prompted NASA to cut back on personnel as well as
the ground testing that would have uncovered the design flaws and
lack of communications gear.
</P>
<P>
   At JPL, only 10 people were assigned to the Polar Lander project
office that was supervising contract personnel at Lockheed Martin.
As a result, Polar Lander project personnel were working 60 and
sometimes 80 hours a week to prepare for the mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``There weren't the right number of people to do the kinds of
things you got to do to get a project off on its proper footing,''
said Young. ``They were trying to do everything humanly possible to
make this program work. There just wasn't enough of them. There
wasn't enough reserves (funding). In the end that all manifested in
them not having enough time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
