<HEADER>
A0641 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-GRADES-GRADES_SFCHRON     03-28 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRADES-GRADES </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Tech Alliance Gives State Mixed Grades  &HT;     By Carrie Kirby 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
California got a passing grade in educating its future workforce in
technology, according to a report card to be released by the
American Electronics Association today. But the state is at the
bottom of the class when it comes to infrastructure, such as
transportation and housing.
<P>
   The State Government Affairs Committee, a 35-member group made
up of the AEA's largest California companies, gave the state's
education and workforce training efforts a C-, an improvement from
last year's D+, and the group said that it expected the situation
to continue improving this year. But California still lags behind
other states in turning out qualified high-tech workers, according
to Teresa Casazza, AEA's vice president of California public
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our significant issue is lack of an educated workforce. We
have quite a few jobs that are unfilled right now,'' Casazza said.
About 269,000 high-tech jobs are empty nationwide, according to the
Computing Technology Industry Association.
</P>
<P>
   Less promising is the state's infrastructure _ its
transportation, housing and public facilities _ which the AEA says
is stagnating with a grade of D+.
</P>
<P>
   ``California has left our infrastructure in a state of decline
for the last 20 years,'' Casazza said. ``California is behind
almost any state I can think of.''
</P>
<P>
   In other areas, the state weighed in at a solid average: C+ for
corporate tax environment, C+ for environmental regulation, and C-
for legal environment.
</P>
<P>
   The AEA has been comparing California to other states and
grading it on issues that affect business since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the state's best subject was electronic commerce,
which it aced, mostly on the strength of the Legislature's passing
of the Uniform Electronic Transactions Act in 1999. The act allows
electronic contracts and digital signatures to be used in
transactions. Last year, electronic commerce got an A-.
</P>
<P>
   Education's improved grade reflects several bills that passed in
the state Legislature in 1999 which the AEA believes will lead to a
better educated pool of high-tech workers in the future. Casazza
said that a major step forward was the adoption of statewide
academic rankings for public schools, part of Gov. Gray Davis'
education reform package in 1999. The state also made it easier for
people with master's degrees in high technology to get teacher
credentials in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Today, 85 high-tech executives, members of the AEA, are at the
capitol in Sacramento, lobbying for _ among other things _ the
passage of two more education bills: AB1492, which would bring more
technology funds to classrooms with low computer-to-student ratios,
and AB2, which would exempt employees from paying taxes on tuition
reimbursement for graduate school.
</P>
<P>
   The report card rated the area's infrastructure harshly because
of the litany of problems that have accompanied California's
population and economic growth: lack of housing, transportation and
adequate water supply, as well as the deterioration of public
school buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The infrastructure problem that poses the biggest threat to
California's economy is transportation, said Mark Nelson, manager
of government affairs for Hewlett-Packard, one of the 35 companies
that voted on the report card.
</P>
<P>
   ``If individuals and goods and services cannot move effectively
around a community, pretty soon people want to move somewhere
else,'' Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   While the group praised the governor for creating a commission
to study infrastructure issues, Casazza said, ``We don't see any
really positive results in the short term.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Electronics Association is headquartered in Santa
Clara and in Washington, D.C. In California, about 1,400 technology
companies belong to the organization.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
