<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0642 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-PENDER-PENDER_SFCHRON     03-28 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PENDER-PENDER </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETWORTH/KATHLEEN PENDER 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Microsoft a Safe Date at Tech-Stock Party 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
If you think the tech-stock party has gotten out of hand, but
you're afraid to be a pooper in case it still has a long way to go,
here's a way to have some good safe fun.
<P>
   Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Yea, buying Microsoft is like taking your brother to the prom,
but it is almost a value stock by today's insane standards.
</P>
<P>
   In the past 12 months, Microsoft is up 17 percent. Respectable,
but over the same period, the Nasdaq composite index is ahead 100
percent, while Cisco Systems, which overtook Microsoft as the most
valuable company this week, rose 196 percent. Oracle, Microsoft's
nemesis, has gained a stratospheric 530 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Ron Elijah, manager of the RS Value Plus Growth fund
in San Francisco, considers Microsoft ``the cheapest tech stock.''
</P>
<P>
   The government's antitrust case against Microsoft has
overshadowed the start of a powerful new product cycle with Windows
2000, says Christopher Galvin, an analyst with Chase H&AMP;Q in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft could rise 40 percent during over  &LR; the next 12 months
as Windows 2000 starts ``rippling through their numbers,'' Galvin
says. ``The trial has presented a wonderful buying opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Some investors think any resolution of the case _ which could
take a few days or a few years _ will lift the lid on Microsoft
stock.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday, Microsoft shares surged $8.63, to $111.88, when
it looked as though the Justice Department was backing down on its
demand that the company be broken up, paving the way for a
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   When a deal wasn't forthcoming, the stock fell back, closing
yesterday at $104.31.
</P>
<P>
   But even a breakup might not be bad. (Think: Baby Bells.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We think there would be a 15 to 20 percent near-term increase
in the stock'' if Microsoft were broken up, said Michael Kwatinetz,
an analyst with Credit Suisse First Boston in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you pulled out the Internet piece, it would be worth $50
billion or so,'' he said. ``Currently, the Internet properties
(including the MSN portal and ISP) are subtracting from the stock
because they're losing money. But a separate Internet company would
be valued on revenues'' instead of earnings, or lack thereof.
</P>
<P>
   Over the longer term, however, Kwatinetz agrees with Microsoft
that shareholders would be better off if the company stays in one
piece, and that's what he expects will happen. ``We think the
resolution won't be structural, it will be behavioral.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Department of Justice seems to have the upper hand
at this point, and is pushing for a court verdict rather than a
settlement, Kwatinetz says that if the DOJ waits too long, it could
end up with a Republican president who might not be as
``pro-antitrust'' as the current one. The DOJ ``would be wise to
grab victory before the balance of power shifts. This is as
favorable as it's going to be for the Justice Department.''
</P>
<P>
   Kwatinetz thinks the stock could reach $150 to $170 in 12
months, assuming the antitrust case is either settled or at a ``low
ebb'' at that time.
</P>
<P>
   Elijah points out that Microsoft (MSFT) and Oracle (ORCL) are
growing at about the same rate _ both had an 18 percent gain in
revenues in the latest quarter, although Oracle's earnings per
share had a bigger jump _ 70 percent versus 31 percent for
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   For their latest fiscal years, however, Microsoft posted a 57
percent gain in EPS on a 29 percent increase in revenues. Oracle's
earnings grew 37 percent on a 24 percent gain in revenues.
</P>
<P>
   But Oracle stock is trading at 155 times earnings, while
Microsoft is trading at ``only'' 65 times. That's why Elijah
considers Microsoft a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Landis, portfolio manager with the Firsthand Funds in San
Jose, sees it differently. He calls Microsoft ``expensive, but that
doesn't mean overpriced.''
</P>
<P>
   In most corporations, he says, PCs are running Microsoft
operating systems and Oracle databases. This gives both companies a
``foot in the door'' for all kinds of e-commerce opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Looking forward, he thinks both companies have the same Internet
potential, but Oracle's market value ($244 billion) is smaller than
Microsoft's ($543 billion), making Oracle the better buy.
</P>
<P>
   While they differ on Microsoft's upside potential, most analysts
think the downside risk is modest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to envision it going a lot lower than 100,''
Kwatinetz said. ``There's just so much value there. There's more
market risk. If the market goes down, it'll be dragged down, but
not as much as some of these other highfliers.''
</P>
<P>
   Landis believes the downside is simpler. ``It's like the saying,
`Alexander wept for there were no more worlds to conquer.' That is
the risk in buying a big and famously successful company. They've
run out of ways to double and triple themselves. The market pays
you for growth and punishes you for stagnation.''
</P>
<P>
   Having a top-rated analyst definitely helps investment banks
land initial public offerings, but does it help investors who buy
the IPOs?
</P>
<P>
   Not really, according to a new, unpublished study.
</P>
<P>
   When companies choose an investment bank to take them public,
they always want one with an influential analyst who will give them
a glowing recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   But over the long term, it's the company, not the analyst, that
determines a stock's performance, says Revell Horsey, a managing
director with Bank of America Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Horsey's people recently looked at all IPOs since 1990 and
tracked their performance for 18 months versus the Nasdaq composite
index. Then they looked at the star quality of the analyst for the
lead investment bank on each IPO.
</P>
<P>
   When the investment bank had an analyst ranked No. 1 by
Institutional Investor magazine (the Wall Street equivalent of an
Oscar), the stock outperformed the Nasdaq by a whole (yawn) 1
percent on average.
</P>
<P>
   When the underwriter's analyst was ranked 2, 3, or 4, the
stock's performance was virtually identical to the index.
</P>
<P>
   When the analyst was not rated, the stock underperformed the
index by an infinitesimal 0.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh  &LR; Today's Tip
</P>
<P>
   If you have a hard time decoding the abbreviations in newspaper
stock and mutual listings (I do, and I work here), go to
http://markets.ap.org and click on Ticker Lookup. Here you can
search nearly all U.S. companies and mutual funds by name, ticker
symbol or abbreviation. It's run by the Associated Press, which
provides stock and fund listings to most American newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Net Worth runs Tuesdays, Wednesdays and Fridays. E-mail Kathleen
Pender at kpender &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
