<HEADLINE>
JACKSON WORRIES ABOUT OVERCONFIDENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO - The Lakers have the best record in the NBA, &UR;  &LR; an
insurmountable lead in the West and are about to reach the 60-win
plateau in near-record speed.
</P>
<P>
   And coach Phil Jackson sees a bit of attitude emanating from his
troops. So much so, that he almost would have welcomed a loss
Sunday in Sacramento, where the Lakers pulled out a dramatic
victory in the closing seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a coach, there's always the idea that it may not be such a
bad game to lose, on national TV and maybe get them a little
humbler about themselves,'' Jackson said. ``They're pretty damn
cocky right now. And they found a way to win it.''
</P>
<P>
   That cockiness, Jackson said, is OK -- ``as long as you wear it
on your sleeve, but you don't carry it in your mouth or demean
people, I feel that it's OK to carry that air, because that's
really what it's all about, is having that voice of confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not likely to ebb, with the Lakers riding a six-game
winning streak and heading into Vancouver tonight for what should
be a routine victory. That would give the Lakers a 60-12 record,
making them the second fastest team in franchise history to reach
the 60-win mark. The 1971-72 team got to 60 in 71 games.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran A.C. Green, perhaps the most humble guy in the locker
room, said cockiness is part of being a winning team.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have confidence,'' Green said. ``At this time of
the season, we're still shooting for goals in the regular season,
as well as trying to position ourselves for the playoffs and the
right frame of mind, as well as body.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we have to have a sense of pride to us. But we have to make
sure that we keep one another in check, that we don't have an
overconfidence position. But I don't think that will be the case.
We've got a lot of veteran guys on the team.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Lakers are certain of one thing -- with a seven-game
lead on Portland as of Tuesday, they've got the No. 1 seed in the
West locked up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, they believe that they've got it,'' Jackson said, ``and
I think they've believed (since) the night we beat Portland (Feb.
29). I thinkthatUs the time they really started believing, hey we
can go and play anywhere right now in this league and win. And
that's the important thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: Glen Rice is suffering from flu-like symptoms and
did not travel with the team to Vancouver on Tuesday. Rice said he
might catch a flight today if he feels better this morning.
</P>
<P>
   If Rice is unavailable, Jackson could start either Rick Fox or
rookie Devean George, who is recovering from the flu himself.
</P>
<P>
   When Rice missed a game in December, Jackson went with George,
rather than disrupt the rotation, but Fox played most of the game.
</P>
<P>
   LAKERS vs. VANCOUVER
</P>
<P>
   Time: 7 p.m., GM Place
</P>
<P>
   TV/Radio: KCAL-Channel 9; KLAC-AM (570)
</P>
<P>
   Lakers (59-12) update: They haven't lost to a Western Conference
team since Feb. 1, in San Antonio, and that trend doesn't figure to
change tonight. The Lakers have beaten Vancouver three times
already this season and have lost to them just once since the
Grizzlies' inception in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Grizzlies (19-50) update: They've been off since Saturday and
should be well-rested if nothing else. The Grizzlies have lost 13
of their last 14 games, the lone victory coming against Golden
State.
</P>
</TEXT>
