<DOCNO> NYT20000328.0364 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0649 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-TRAINING-TRAINING_SFC     03-28 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAINING-TRAINING </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Corporate E-Training Getting More Entertaining  &HT;     By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Taking a cue from the movie and video game industries, a San
Francisco startup is attempting to rescript the corporate training
industry.
<P>
   Rather than host pricey management lectures, print
dull-but-important books or put the same tried and trite material
online, the Ninth House Network is using the Internet to create a
personalized, interactive and cinematic alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Through a combination of storytelling, Hollywood-style
role-playing adventures, instant advice and ``virtual mentors'' who
track each user's progress, the company is attempting to
revolutionize the teaching of leadership, communication and other
management skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overarching idea was to create a media network for
corporate learning,'' said Ninth House co-founder and CEO Jeff
Snipes. ``We wanted to make it as engaging as watching
television.''
</P>
<P>
   Snipes and Ninth House Network are not the only ones expecting
big things from corporate e-training. A recent report from WR
Hambrecht &AMP; Co. suggests that corporate training is now a $66
billion industry and the Internet training component is ``poised to
explode.'' (The full report is available online at
www.wrhambrecht.com.)
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco investment bank expects corporate e-learning
to double in size each year from about $1.1 billion in revenue last
year to $11.4 billion in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   To build up his firm's corporate-training business, Snipes has
recruited 150 employees from Disney, Electronic Arts, Pixar, Sega
and a host of other entertainment, &LR;   &LR; gaming and Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   The employees work on scripts, edit filmed episodes and sign up
big company clients at Ninth House Network's temporary headquarters
at San Francisco's Showplace Square West, where dot-coms are
replacing interior decorators as the main tenants.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than create materials for top executives who already have
private coaches and are treated to lectures and management
retreats, Snipes is targeting ``the masses inside organizations who
also need critical business skills in the new economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Since its start three years ago, Ninth House Network has raised
nearly $50 million in venture capital from such blue-chip investors
as Chase Capital Partners, Hambrecht &AMP; Quist and Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   The company has signed up such business gurus as Tom Peters and
Ken Blanchard. Their lessons on innovation and leadership are
delivered directly to employees' desktops along with filmed stories
that illustrate their main points and invite the viewer to make
suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a video tale about a fish-and-bait shop asks the
viewer to click among several options to help an enthusiastic but
inexperienced employee who wants to establish a Web site for the
business accomplish the mission and become a self-reliant peak
performer.
</P>
<P>
   Another management problem, set in a mid-1800s California gold
mine, allows the viewer help a new manager choose the right
leadership style to help spur a talented but temperamental engineer
into finding more ore.
</P>
<P>
   Another enticing Ninth House Network product is eSeries, where
actors grapple with business problems at fictitious companies. In
one sitcom-style episode titled ``All Work, All Play,'' the learner
makes a series of decisions to help employees at WileyToys.com
overcome a variety of workplace obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   Ninth House training is available on an annual subscription
basis of $500 per employee. The company has more than 30 large
customers so far, including First Union National Bank, the U.S.
Department of Justice, Hewlett-Packard and Intel.
</P>
<P>
   Another area of strength for Ninth House Network is its ``soft
skills'' training, which is growing far faster than information
technology instruction and will surpass it in three years. (See
chart.)
</P>
<P>
   W. R. Hambrecht senior analyst Trace Urdan calls soft skills
``the sweet spot'' of corporate training. ``And no one is doing
exactly the same thing as Ninth House,'' said Urdan. ``The company
is on the cutting edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Some early clients agree. ``This is totally interactive and
engaging,'' said Lela Rotondo, a consultant with Empire Blue Cross
and Blue Shield in New York. ``I've seen a lot of online training
products but instead of the usual `talking head,' Ninth House
offers Hollywood-style videos.'' Empire Blue Cross has licensed to
train as many as 650 of its 6,500 employees using Ninth House
materials.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is far and away the best content I've seen, and the
delivery method lets people practice concepts,'' added Jennifer
Daake, employee development manager of Insight in Tempe, Ariz. The
direct marketer of computer products and service is using Ninth
House to teach management skills to about 200 of its 1,600
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Some competitors like SmartForce in Redwood City have much
larger libraries of information and deliver it online. But Ninth
House says it is more concerned about quality than quantity.
Currently, it has about 100 hours of programs.
</P>
<P>
   Snipes said the main difference between his company and some
rivals is its delivery of engaging, TV quality video. ``We believe
telling stories is what matters. You don't learn how to be a good
leader by reading bullet points off a page; you learn by
experiences.''
</P>
<P>
   Snipes, 33, didn't start out as a techie. He grew up in Tulsa,
Okla.,where his mother is a high school English teacher. He studied
philosophy at Southern Methodist University, before he put in a
stint as an investment banker for Dean Witter in New York and spent
two years teaching English to executives in Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   While in Spain it dawned on Snipes that in a class, ``you can
only move as fast as the slowest person.'' But if you tailor
instruction to the way an individual learns best, whether it be by
word exercises, role-playing, TV or other techniques, learning can
be much more effective.
</P>
<P>
   On returning to the United States, Snipes was chief operating
officer at a San Francisco startup called Interactive Media
Solutions, where he and SMU classmate Tom Fischmann worked on
custom corporate multimedia training. When the company was acquired
in 1997, the two co-founded Ninth House Network.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was again to personalize information to meet individual
learning needs. But this time they set their sights on making
entire workforces more productive.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than resorting to a high-tech name, Snipes reached back
to his philosophy classes where he learned about Sumerian culture
about 5,000 years ago and its 12 houses of learning.
</P>
<P>
   The ninth house, he recalls, was devoted to mastering higher
learning and exploring personal limits.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
