<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE DEMOCRATS  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GORE AND CLINTON TOGETHER
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore and President Clinton plan to appear
together April 15 at a fund-raiser in Beverly Hills for the
Democratic National Committee. The hosts of the event will be the
DreamWorks trio of Steven Spielberg, David Geffen and Jeffrey
Katzenberg. It will be held at Greystone manor, the fortress-like
Tudor mansion built in 1928 and still the largest home in Beverly
Hills. Gore has kept his distance from Clinton over the last few
months. Their first appearance together this year comes only after
Gore has secured the Democratic presidential nomination. They last
appeared at a fund-raiser together on Dec. 9 in Washington. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE VOTERS  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WHO'S THE REFORMER?
</P>
<P>
   A CBS News poll found that voters believe that Gore is more
interested in changing the system than is Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas. Forty-one percent of respondents said Gore was interested in
change and 23 percent said Bush was. Thirty-nine percent said Gore
wanted the status quo and 57 percent said Bush did. Forty-three
percent said Gore had made decisions based on campaign
contributions and 35 percent said Bush had. The survey found Bush
ahead of Gore, 49 percent to 42 percent. It was conducted last week
and had a margin of sampling error of three percentage points.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GOVERNORS' RACES  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HINT OF FUTURE IN WISCONSIN?
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Tommy G. Thompson of Wisconsin, who has remained quiet
about his future political plans, seems to have been upstaged by
his lieutenant governor, Scott McCallum, who is telling voters that
Thompson, a Republican, will not seek re-election in two years.
McCallum, a likely contender for the Republican nomination for
governor if his boss steps aside, earlier this month sent a
fund-raising letter to 30,000 Wisconsin voters saying that the
governor was in his final term. Thompson, who apparently was not
pleased with the letter, has told his staff that, from now on, he
wants to see McCallum's missives to voters before they are sent.
</P>
<P>
   NEW NEW HAMPSHIRE PRIMARY
</P>
<P>
   Republican challengers were expected. But Jeanne Shaheen, the
Democratic governor of New Hampshire, will also be facing a rival
from her own party this campaign season. Mark Fernald, a state
senator, planned to announce the formation of his exploratory
committee Wednesday. . He is running, he said, because the state is
in a 27-month-old crisis over how to finance its schools, and
Shaheen has refused to consider an income tax as the best source of
money. Fernald is proposing an income tax that would be dedicated
solely to paying for public education, and said that polls showed
that residents of New Hampshire, for all their tax-hating habits,
were ready for the idea.
</P>
<P>
   THE REFORM PARTY  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHAIRMAN'S PLANS
</P>
<P>
   Pat Choate, the interim chairman of the Reform Party, said Gore
and Bush should make campaign finance reform a priority if they
intended to use the reformer tag. ``Stop taking soft money, stop
taking PAC money, or quit calling yourself a reformer,'' Choate
said at a news conference in Washington. A federal judge in
Virginia ruled Monday that Choate, an ally of Ross Perot and Pat
Buchanan, was the party's chairman, not Jack Gargan, an ally of
Gov. Jesse Ventura of Minnesota. Gargan was ousted last month.
Choate said the party would move its headquarters to Washington and
begin raising $1 million, from individuals only.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY'S SCHEDULES  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH Newark, N.J.; New York City; Baltimore. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE No public events.
</P>
