<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-FLA-DONOVAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DONOVAN INSPIRES FLORIDA WITH FIERY CLIPS
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the big screen, Muhammad Ali and Gen. George Patton have
given the Florida basketball team a boost in its run through the
National Collegiate Athletic Association tournament. Fiery words
gleaned from movie clips of Patton and Ali helped the Gators,
seeded a modest fifth in the East Regional, reach the Final Four
for just the second time in school history.
</P>
<P>
   Going against top-seeded Duke in the regional semifinals,
Florida Coach Billy Donovan and his staff thought they needed a
whopper of a motivational tactic to keep their players unaffected
by Duke's reputation. ``Here we are a young team trying to break
through,'' Donovan said Tuesday in a national teleconference. ``We
needed something.''
</P>
<P>
   So they searched the movie archives and came up with just the
right inspirational words from the boxing legend and the war hero.
The clip of Ali showed him getting ready for a match against George
Foreman in Zaire in which he was not given much of a chance of
winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He talked about how he had to adjust during the fight,''
Donovan said. ``We basically took that fight and said: `OK, we're
in a 10-round battle with Duke and each round is four minutes. And
we've got to go round by round.'''
</P>
<P>
   Of the Patton clip, Donovan said: ``There was a battle going on.
He mentioned that this was the right moment in time and that an
opportunity like this wouldn't come around for another 1,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to take his lines and draw a parallel to what we're
doing,'' added the coach, whose team beat Duke, 87-78. ``I think
sometimes you can talk to guys in terms of motivating them, but
sometimes they need to see different things and hear different
things and tie everything in together.''
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, Donovan believes more than ever in the wonders of
motivation, as the Gators prepare for a national semifinal game on
Saturday against North Carolina.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
