<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0659 &Cx1f; taf-z
U s BC-HKN-RANGERS-NYT     03-28 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOEFUL RANGERS FIRE SMITH AND MUCKLER
</HEADLINE>
 (mg 
By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Saying that the late-season collapse of the New York
Rangers had embarrassed the organization and its fans, Madison
Square Garden President Dave Checketts on Tuesday fired the club's
president and general manager, Neil Smith, and the coach, John
Muckler, with only four games remaining in what has become another
futile season.
</P>
<P>
   ``When one makes a decision like this, the sooner the better,''
Checketts said. He said that he had decided it was time for a
change in the aftermath of Monday night's 6-0 drubbing at the hands
of the Detroit Red Wings at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   The loss came two days after the same Red Wings team had
humiliated the Rangers, 8-2, in Detroit on national television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see any reason to wait,'' Checketts said. ``I did not
want to have the players scatter at the end of the season and leave
unexplained what the issues are, why this group has performed the
way it has.''
</P>
<P>
   Checketts acted as the Rangers awaited elimination from the
playoffs for the third-straight season, a remarkable decline for a
team that had ticker tape rain down on them when they broke a
54-year curse and won the Stanley Cup in 1994, under Smith's
direction.
</P>
<P>
   This season, the Rangers seemed determined to reverse the
decline and spent lavishly on free agents like Theo Fleury and
Valery Kamensky. The team ended up with a $61 million payroll, the
highest in the league, but had little to show for it.
</P>
<P>
   When Checketts was asked Tuesday why the team had underachieved
so dramatically, he answered: ``I wish I knew and I'm going to find
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Checketts, who is considered far better grounded in basketball
than in hockey, said he planned on Wednesday morning to address the
Rangers, who will close the season with John Tortorella, one of
Muckler's assistants, serving as the interim coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to spend a lot of time with the Rangers'
organization over the next two weeks,'' said Checketts, who since
taking over as the Garden president in 1994 has always had Smith as
his No. 1 hockey man. Now he must hire a person to supervise the
rebuilding of the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   This also marked the second-straight season that Checketts
conducted a spring cleaning at the Garden. Last year, Checketts
fired Ernie Grunfeld as the Knicks' president and general manager
after it became apparent that Grunfeld and Coach Jeff Van Gundy
could not work together. The Knicks ultimately rebounded to make to
the National Basketball Association finals.
</P>
<P>
   Checketts said that unlike Grunfeld and Van Gundy, Muckler and
Smith were not bitter foes, even though there appeared to be
considerable tension between the two at various times this season.
And it was Smith's hope that after 11 years at the helm, and with a
Stanley Cup to his credit, his fate would not be twinned with that
of Muckler, whom Smith hired to replace Colin Campbell, on Feb. 19,
1998.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, it was, perhaps because Checketts and other
Garden officials had lost faith in Smith and in his contention that
the Rangers would soon prosper from a recently initiated youth
movement.
</P>
<P>
   Smith became the Rangers' general manager on July 17, 1989.
Under his direction, and with the on-ice guidance of Mark Messier,
the Rangers ended all the taunting they heard in other arenas by
finally winning the Stanley Cup in 1994. Under Smith, they also won
the President's Trophy twice, signifying the team with the best
regular-season record in the National Hockey League. But the team
never seemed to recover from the acrimonious departure of Messier
before the 1997-98 season. They have not made the playoffs since he
signed with Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Muckler, meanwhile, has also had his share of successes. He was
an assistant coach on the Edmonton Oilers teams that won the
Stanley Cup in 1984-85, the co-coach of their cup-winning teams in
1987 and 1988 and Edmonton's head coach when they won the cup in
1990.
</P>
<P>
   As general manager of the Buffalo Sabres from 1993-95, Muckler
also helped build the foundation for a team that advanced to the
Stanley Cup finals last season.
</P>
<P>
   But because the Rangers had so little to show for high payroll,
the firings of both Smith and Muckler were not nearly as surprising
as the timing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It did not work out,'' Checketts said during a conference call
yesterday afternoon. ``The bottom line is results here. I certainly
expect a better effort than what I've seen the last couple of
weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   What Checketts and his Cablevision bosses, Charles and James
Dolan, have witnessed is a Rangers' team that has disintegrated
over the past two months. Since the All-Star Game break, the
Rangers (29-38-11-3) have a 6-15-4-0 record and are on the verge of
missing the postseason for the third consecutive season for the
first time since the mid-1960s.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have played poorly over the last 10 games. With
their playoff destiny in their own hands, the Rangers have all but
dropped out of contention with a 1-8-1-0 skid. The Rangers have
been outscored, 18-3, in their last three games and 27-10 during
the five-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all expected better and deserve better,'' Checketts said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked who might succeed Smith, Checketts, in a radio
interview broadcast over WFAN, ``I want the best guy I can get. I'm
not going to speculate on who that might be.''
</P>
<P>
   Checketts did seem to indicate that Smith's assistant, Don
Maloney, would be considered. Checketts had nothing but praise for
the 41-year-old Maloney, a former standout with the Rangers as a
player. Maloney was also the general manager of the Islanders from
Aug. 17, 1992 to Dec. 2, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   There were also reports that Edmonton Oilers President Glen
Sather, a friend of both Smith and Muckler, was preparing to take
over as the Rangers' president and general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Other possible candidates include Devils President and General
Manager Lou Lamoriello, who will be available after the sale of the
Devils to the YankeeNets is complete, and perhaps the Rangers'
long-time television analyst, John Davidson. Davidson, 47, a former
Rangers' goaltender, has long maintained he has no interest in
leaving the broadcast booth for a front-office job. But more
recently, Davidson has indicated to friends that he has shifted his
stance, and that there was a chance that he would accept the job if
it were offered to him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-00 2239EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
