<HEADER>
A0662 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-TEN-VWILLIAMS-RETIRE2     03-28 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-VWILLIAMS-RETIRE29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Venus Williams' father suggest she retire
 &HT;    By Mark Woods
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEY BISCAYNE, Fla. _ One is 19. The other is 18. Each is ranked
as one of the top 10 women's tennis players in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, if Venus and Serena Williams listen to their father and
coach, they will do something more stunning than making it from the
courts in the ghetto of Compton, Calif., to venues such as
Wimbledon and Roland Garros.
</P>
<P>
   They will quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Venus should consider retiring from tennis,'' Richard
Williams said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Venus Williams, 19 years old and ranked No. 3 on the WTA Tour,
has been bothered by tendinitis in both wrists and hasn't played in
a tournament since the Chase Championship in New York last
November. She withdrew from the Ericsson Open last week, two days
before she was scheduled to begin her title defense. And if she
heeds her father's advice, she won't be returning to the tour.
Ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just my recommendation,'' he said. ``She doesn't need
tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the first time Williams has made outrageous
statements. It was just a year ago, as Venus and Serena were headed
to a showdown in the final of the event then known as the Lipton
Championships, that he talked about buying Rockefeller Center.
</P>
<P>
   Now this. Retirement.
</P>
<P>
   When asked why he recommends retirement for Venus, Williams
said: ``Because she has enough money.''
</P>
<P>
   Since turning pro in 1994, Venus has won $4,582,577 and earned
millions more in endorsements. These days she and Serena are busy
planning and overseeing construction of a 6,500-square-foot home in
Ballen Isles, about 10 miles from where they now live in suburban
Palm Beach Gardens.
</P>
<P>
   Venus will turn 20 on June 17. The question is whether she would
actually retire before then.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, she didn't like the idea,'' Richard Williams said.
``She didn't like it at all. But when she started thinking about
all the things she could do ... she's looking at it extremely
closely right now. There are a lot more things she can do than play
tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   He talked about Venus going to school full-time, expanding her
interest in fashion design and perhaps dabbling in the Internet. He
said she will make a decision by the middle of next month. And he
hinted at the possibility of Serena, who is 15 months younger than
Venus, walking away from the game when her contract with Puma
expires in three years.
</P>
<P>
   He said that their early retirements could serve as a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen too many black athletes come out of the ghetto and
earn all that money, and four or five years later they're broke and
no one cares who they once were,'' he said. ``Because of the
planning we've done with these two girls, they don't need tennis
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Serena has won $3,165,149 on the court, and her career seems to
be taking off. In 1999, she won six singles titles _ including the
U.S. Open _ en route to earning more than $2 million in prize
money. She entered the Ericsson ranked fourth on the WTA Tour's
2000 money list with $196,906, before losing to Jennifer Capriati
in a fourth-round match Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Neither was available for comment Tuesday. But after her
elimination, Serena said she doubted that Venus was ready to
retire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect to see her back and competing soon,'' Serena said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
