<SLUG> BC-FUNDRAISING-LOOPHOLE-AD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE AD CAMPAIGN: CALIFORNIA GROUP ATTACKS GORE
</HEADLINE>
  (With FUNDRAISING-LOOPHOLE) 
(nk) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER 
  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In yet another sign that the general election campaign is
already under way, a California group called Shape the Debate began
running commercials this week, entitled ``Hypocrisy,'' attacking
Vice President Al Gore. The group is headed by George Gorton, a
longtime Republican consultant with close ties to former Gov. Pete
Wilson of California. Two of the group's top officials have
contributed $1,000 each to Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCER: Shape the Debate.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE SCREEN: The advertisement was filmed on a set designed to
look like the television quiz show ``Jeopardy.'' The category for
all the questions is ``political hypocrites.''
</P>
<P>
   THE SCRIPT: The game show host says, ``Welcome to `Hypocrisy.'
Contestants, are you ready?'' The first player chooses ``political
hypocrites'' for $200. The host reads the question, which also
appears on the screen: ``He says he supports campaign finance
reform, but held an illegal fund-raiser at a Buddhist temple.'' The
contestant replies, ``Who is Al Gore?'' Another contestant chooses
``political hypocrites'' for $400. The question: ``He promised
never to cut Medicare expenses, but cast the deciding vote to cut
Medicare by $55 billion.'' The correct answer: ``Who is Al Gore?''
The third question, for $600: ``He crusades against tobacco, but
grew and sold it from his very own farm.'' The answer, once again,
``Who is Al Gore?'' The narrator then concludes, ``Al Gore has a
lot to answer for. That's `Hypocrisy.' Bye-bye.''
</P>
<P>
   ACCURACY: Gore's appearance at a fund-raising luncheon at a
Buddhist temple in California in the 1996 campaign is well known,
as is his recent enthusiasm for campaign finance reform. A
long-time Gore fund-raiser, Maria Hsia, was convicted of illegal
fund-raising in connection with Gore's temple visit and other
events. But Attorney General Janet Reno declined to pursue a
criminal investigation of Gore for his role in the event. Gore cast
the tie-breaking vote for the 1993 deficit-reduction package, which
included cuts in Medicare spending that were smaller than those
proposed by some Republican leaders. Gore has boasted in the past
about growing tobacco on his family's farm, but since his sister's
death from lung cancer in 1984, he has been an outspoken foe of
cigarette companies.
</P>
<P>
   SCORE CARD: Advertisements like these from groups not directly
affiliated with campaigns will be a staple of this year's
elections. Such groups have already spent or are committed to
spending $114 million on issue advertisements this year, according
to a study by the Annenberg Public Policy Center at the University
of Pennsylvania. Federal law says independent groups cannot
advocate the election or defeat of a candidate, but advertisements
like this one demonstrate how blurred the line between issue
advocacy and candidate advocacy has become.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
