<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-TEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORNADO TEARS THROUGH DOWNTOWN FORT WORTH, KILLING AT LEAST 2
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PETE ALFANO 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A tornado ripped through downtown Fort Worth just after 6:30
p.m. Tuesday, shattering windows in office buildings, overturning
cars and killing at least two people, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The powerful twister caused numerous injuries and sent
pedestrians and motorists scrambling for safety.
</P>
<P>
   The tornado was one of several reported throughout North Texas
as a line of heavy thunderstorms turned the sky dark and brought an
ominous and destructive end to what had been a picture-perfect
spring day.
</P>
<P>
   The storm was accompanied by gale force winds, torrential rain
and hail, some reported to be the size of softballs.
</P>
<P>
   Many motorists who were headed downtown seemed to be unaware of
the approaching danger. Storm sirens had been sounding for several
minutes but it appears that some people ignored them or were slow
to seek cover.
</P>
<P>
   The Bank One building, a glass structure standing 35 stories,
was buffeted so hard by winds and debris that hundreds of windows
blew out. Glass shards tumbled to the street and shattered. Windows
were also blown out of the Renaissance Worthington Hotel four
blocks north.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses reported trees uprooted and fragments from roofs and
other debris swirling through the city streets in the aftermath of
the tornado. The storm continued tracking south and east, hitting
neighboring cities Arlington and Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   There were reports of scattered power outages and interruptions
in telephone service as many people tried to call into North Texas,
checking on friends and relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a vortex,'' said Joe Garbe, who was on the 28th
floor of an office building in downtown Fort Worth and could see
the tornado weaving between buildings as it blew through.
</P>
<P>
   Javier Cardenas said he was in his apartment on the 16th floor
when he went to the window to look outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt the suction of the wind blowing through the apartment
building,'' he said. ``I couldn't hear anything. It was silent. But
the cyclone was immediately there, immediately in front of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Marc McDonald was walking out of Angelo's Barbecue restaurant
west of downtown in White Settlement when he looked down the road
and saw the tornado approaching. He ran back into the restaurant
and alerted the patrons and staff. More than 70 people sought cover
in the meat locker.
</P>
<P>
   ``We laid down on the floor,'' McDonald said. ``Then a woman
said, `Can we start talking? I don't want to hear the stuff
outside.' That kind of lightened the atmosphere for a moment.''
</P>
<P>
   McDonald said they remained in the meat locker for 20 minutes
before everyone gingerly walked out, some heading back to the bar
for their mugs of beer.
</P>
<P>
   When the rain and wind subsided, many people tried to leave the
city, negotiating past an obstacle course of debris. The flashing
lights and sirens of fire engines and police cars broke the erie
post-storm silence as they responded to the emergency. Police
sealed off the city center and would not allow people to enter.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
