u s BC-BKC-NC-COTA-NYT     03-28 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NC-COTA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COTA OFFERS A PERFECT FIT TO CAROLINA'S TRADITION
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ed Cota's game is straight out of Brooklyn, a refined version
now that fits firmly into North Carolina basketball's ``buddy
system.'' Cota began learning his game as a 9-year-old, walking
across the street from his front door on East New York Avenue to
watch older boys play at Hamilton-Metz Park. On some early
mornings, he would practice there alone, tuning his game. At 11, he
played in his first Brooklyn basketball league _ his team was
called Ice Tea _ and by the time he left for North Carolina, he was
ready to dish, shoot, score and shoot some more.
</P>
<P>
   Or so he thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started a lot as a freshman at Carolina, and I thought I
could go out and play my game and score at least 14 points in every
game,'' Cota said. ``But Coach Smith pulled me aside halfway
through my freshman year and said that wasn't what he wanted from
me, that my role as point guard was to run the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, four years later, I completely understand that Carolina
plays basketball the way it should be played. Every guy on the
court here has a role. On every play we run, all five guys are
involved and there are two or three options on every play. If one
guy does not know his role or perform it, the whole system breaks
down. It's like a buddy system. I feel me, I feel everybody else on
the court. It seems like I've been in this system forever. The
coaches know what I see, and they know I know basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Dean Smith, the former North Carolina coach, learned to trust
Cota.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Guthridge, the current coach, trusts Cota even more.
Guthridge has said that Cota ``sees things unfolding before other
people even know they're happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Little wonder that this North Carolina club _ a team that took
the entire regular season to perfect its system and then the
postseason to make it flourish _ enters the Final Four refreshed
and renewed. Carolina (22-13) meets Florida (28-7) in a national
semifinal game on Saturday night in Indianapolis with the direction
of the offense, the play calls on defense and so much in between in
the hands of Ed Cota.
</P>
<P>
   Cota's Carolina career has been striking. This is his third
Final Four in four years. He has played with the brilliant,
including the current pros Vince Carter and Antawn Jamison, and
with the current freshman whiz, Joseph Forte. He has played under
the coaching legend Smith and the mild, knowledgeable Guthridge.
Cota has absorbed it all.
</P>
<P>
   Through the last four years, Cota, 23, has helped to continue
the splendid Carolina basketball tradition.
</P>
<P>
   He is the only player in National Collegiate Athletic
Association history to record more than 1,000 points, more than
1,000 assists and more than 500 rebounds. He is the only player in
Atlantic Coast Conference history to lead the conference in assists
in four consecutive seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But it looked as if his senior season would be tainted when,
with his teammate, Terrence Newby, he was charged with assault in
an Oct. 31 brawl near the Chapel Hill campus after a Halloween
celebration. That case, originally scheduled for court next Monday,
has been continued until later this spring. When the Tar Heels
limped into the NCAA tournament with an 18-13 record, they were
expected to be bounced early.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started out OK in the first three or four games this
season, but then we had some injuries and we lost some chemistry,''
Cota said. ``Some guys were not playing as much and were playing in
different roles. Others were worried about their stats. Guys were
not moving the ball around on offense and weren't getting good
shots. And then our defense suffered after that. Once guys get fed
up on offense, once they don't like the way that it's going or how
they look, you can forget about them playing defense. They aren't
going to guard anybody. And that's where we were sometimes during
the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, once the tournament started, guys all of a sudden
accepted their roles. They were able to adjust. It was like they
said, `Hey, I might as well go out and do what I'm supposed to
do.'''
</P>
<P>
   Learn, understand and then accept the buddy system. Cota said he
did that as a freshman, and now with a different coach, with
different players, he does the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got used to not putting up big scoring numbers at Carolina,
but I know I could do that,'' he said. ``People think that a guy
who scores a lot is a great player, but that doesn't mean he is or
that he knows the game. I've hit a lot of big shots here. But I've
learned my role is to be the leader on the floor, not the scorer.''
</P>
<P>
   The scorer is Forte, the smooth shooting guard who made the
coaches and players take notice of his game. Cota sees plenty of
himself in Forte.
</P>
<P>
   ``He definitely matured as the season went along,'' Cota said.
``He is more relaxed and lets the game come to him. Sometimes
during the season, he would not do the other things _ box out,
rebound, stay with his man. He was in that high school mold. But
Joseph always had confidence. I think that's why we've clicked. He
came in with confidence, not just glad to be here. He wanted to
start, and he took other guys' spots. That is something I admire.
As a freshman, he carries a burden, but he carries it well.''
</P>
<P>
   Cota carries his well, too. All of the Carolina players respect
him, listen to him, watch him. The children back in Hamilton-Metz
Park do, too. They now call the Crown Heights place Eddie Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``They feel like I made it, but I have other goals, starting
with winning this national championship,'' Cota said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
