<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-KIMES-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INFORMER IN MURDER CASE TESTIFIES HE SOLD GUNS TO MOTHER AND SON
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By JULIAN E. BARNES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The FBI informer who turned in the mother and son
accused of murdering an Upper East Side woman testified Tuesday
that the two defendants had called him to New York to take over an
apartment building, evict the tenants and change the locks.
</P>
<P>
   The informer, Stanley Patterson, testified during the seventh
week in the trial of Sante and Kenneth Kimes, whom prosecutors have
charged with murdering Irene Silverman.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson, a Las Vegas maintenance man, said that in the months
before Silverman was last seen, he sold the Kimeses four guns and
taught them how to make a silencer out of a potato. Then on July 1,
Patterson said, Sante Kimes called him and asked him to come to New
York. He arrived on July 5, the day prosecutors have said the
Kimeses murdered Silverman as part of a plot to steal her Upper
East Side mansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come to New York and manage this apartment building for me,''
Patterson testified Mrs. Kimes had told him. She promised, ``You
will make more money than you ever made in your life,'' he
testified.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson testified that the Kimeses first met with him on Feb.
28, 1998, when they hired him to move them from Las Vegas to Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson said that he later sold them the four guns.
</P>
<P>
   During a later phone call, on July 1, Mrs. Kimes told Patterson
that she wanted him to manage an apartment building, whose current
owner was acting oddly, Patterson testified.
</P>
<P>
   On cross-examination, Patterson testified that he had asked Mrs.
Kimes what to do about the landlady, and she told him to just keep
an eye on Silverman.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson's testimony is important to prosecutors because it
links the Kimeses to lethal weapons and backs up the prosecution's
contention that the Kimeses planned to take over Silverman's house.
</P>
<P>
   Silverman's body has never been found, forcing prosecutors to
try to build a circumstantial case. Prosecutors have called 67
witnesses during the last seven weeks, moving the case forward in
small, incremental steps.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-00 2248EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000328.0375 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0668 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TENN-ERICSSON-OPEN-NY     03-28 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TENN-ERICSSON-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGASSI OVERCOMES RAFTER AND CONTROVERSIAL CALLS
</HEADLINE>
 (mg) 
By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEY BISCAYNE, Fla. _ It was a defining moment, the eighth game
of the second set between Andre Agassi and Patrick Rafter in the
quarterfinals of the Ericsson Open. Agassi was up by a set,
clinging to a 4-3 advantage and trying to hold serve.
</P>
<P>
   The game reached deuce an amazing 10 times on this blustery day,
thanks in part to two disputed line calls that went against Agassi,
one in which the referee overruled a line judge. Then, Agassi
brought the score to deuce for the last time with a strong forehand
and seized the next two points, and the game, as Rafter was long on
consecutive backhand shots.
</P>
<P>
   That proved pivotal as Agassi went on to close out the match,
6-4, 6-4, and reach the semifinals against Tim Henman, a 6-1, 1-6,
7-6 (4) victor over Marcelo Rios.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was his opportunity to get back in the match, and it was
my opportunity to kind of put the nail in the coffin,'' Agassi
said. ``It certainly made life a lot easier. We'd still be out
there battling right now, most likely.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Jennifer Capriati looked tired in a 6-3, 6-4 loss to
Sandrine Testud of France in the women's quarterfinals. Capriati
had little of the energy she showed in a three-set victory over
Serena Williams that shocked the tournament on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough,'' Capriati said. ``When I got out there, I kind
of felt the fatigue. My mind was telling my body, `Come on, move.'
But that just wasn't happening as well as I'd like it to be, how it
was yesterday or in the previous matches I've played.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Capriati broke Testud to make it 3-3 in the second set
and appeared ready to make a match of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt myself maybe coming back there in the second,''
Capriati said, ``but I just couldn't get any breaks there.
Especially with line calls.''
</P>
<P>
   Testud will play the Lindsay Davenport-Nadejda Petrova winner in
the semifinals. Capriati, Testud said, was not the only one who
felt a little sluggish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew she was tired, but I was very tired, too,'' Testud
said. ``I didn't start very well, but when I came back, I saw that
I was just more patient than her today. She was trying for too
much. It was important to keep the ball in play, and that's what I
did better than her today.''
</P>
<P>
   And that is what Agassi did against Rafter, improving his career
record against the Australian to 7-3. Yet Agassi, the top-seeded
player here, said he saw some of the vintage Rafter. Rafter won the
United States Open in 1997 and 1998, but he is playing just his
third tournament since he underwent rotator cuff surgery on his
right shoulder on Oct. 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the most important parts to Pat's game is his
movement,'' Agassi said. ``And to me, I was really pleasantly
surprised to see how well he moved.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafter, 27, who recently had been vaguely talking about retiring
from the tennis circuit, sounded like a rejuvenated man after the
match.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think things have definitely changed,'' he said. ``I'm
enjoying the work. I'm enjoying doing the training again, seeing
the results happen. It's still going to be a gradual process for me
to get back into the tournament swing. I still can't train as hard
as I'd like to. But I think in a couple of months I'll be back to
full training and playing good tennis again.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi, who will represent the United States in a Davis Cup
match against the Czech Republic next weekend in Los Angeles, kept
harking back to that decisive eighth game in the second set. He
thought he played it well, except for a drop shot when he was
facing break point for the seventh time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should just slap myself for hitting that shot,'' he said,
even knowing that it turned out favorably for him, with Rafter
hitting a wide forehand.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the self-flagellation, Agassi was grateful for a testing
match. ``It's nice to get that challenge and to move on through
it,'' he said, ``because it certainly gives you a lot of
confidence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
