<SLUG> BC-OPEC-TALKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPEC AGREES TO OIL PRODUCTION INCREASE DESPITE IRANIAN OBJECTIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAVID IVANOVICH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria _ Iran broke ranks with the rest of OPEC early
Wednesday, refusing to go along with an oil production increase it
says was forced on the cartel through political pressure.
</P>
<P>
   But by reacting to an intense lobbying campaign from Washington,
Iran has helped create uncertainty in the oil market and may hand
the Clinton administration the thing it was seeking _ a moderate
drop in oil prices, industry analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Nine members of the 11-nation Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries agreed early Wednesday to reverse cutbacks a
year ago and raise their collective production ceiling by about
1.45 million barrels a day to 21.07 million barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, President Clinton hailed the OPEC agreement,
predicting it not only would benefit U.S. consumers but would help
sustain economic growth worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he said, several weeks are likely to pass
before any price decreases reach the gas pump.
</P>
<P>
   ``While oil prices are projected to fall this year, we will
continue to closely monitor developments in world oil markets in
the coming months,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Iran, OPEC's second-largest producer, refused to sign the
accord, insisting such a substantial production increase was not
warranted. During two days of haggling, Iran tried to persuade
Saudi Arabia to accept a smaller production increase, but OPEC's
largest producer refused to budge.
</P>
<P>
   Making thinly veiled references to the United States and Saudi
Arabia, Iranian Oil Minister Bijan Namdar Zangeneh insisted OPEC
had been pushed into making a pre-ordained decision that Iran could
not accept.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our organization is not a political organization,'' Zangeneh
argued. ``OPEC is not an organization to rubber stamp the decisions
already made. ... OPEC needs the spirit of cooperation, which
unfortunately we did not have this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Iranian officials had been irritated Monday, when U.S. Energy
Secretary Bill Richardson's office placed a call to the Qatari
delegation in the middle of a sensitive negotiating session.
</P>
<P>
   Zangeneh refused to say Tuesday how much his country would boost
its own production. But OPEC Secretary Rilwanu Lukman indicated the
OPEC ministers expect these 10 OPEC producers to raise their
production ceiling by about 1.7 million barrels a day or 7 percent,
a figure anticipated prior to the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq, which remains answerable to the United Nations' Security
Council, has vowed to increase its production by 700,000 barrels a
day over the last few weeks. While few oil analysts take that claim
seriously, many expect Baghdad to eventually ship an additional
300,000 barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
   OPEC ministers plan to revisit the production issue again June
21, when they plan to meet again in Vienna.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico, while not a member of OPEC, has also vowed to boost its
oil production. Mexican Energy Minister Luis Tellez is expected to
announce Wednesday how much is country will produce.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Richardson hailed the OPEC move, calling it
``good news for American consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our objective is for stable prices,'' Richardson said. ``We
don't want this volatility in the markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson also said OPEC's decision should eliminate any need
to dip into the Strategic Petroleum Reserve, the nation's emergency
oil stockpile, to help bring down prices.
</P>
<P>
   In talks with OPEC ministers, Richardson said he has pushed for
a worldwide increase of 2 million barrels a day, not the 2.8
million as some news media have reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've achieved a large part of our objective,'' Richardson
told reporters. ``I think our quiet diplomacy worked.''
</P>
<P>
   The production increases announced by the OPEC countries are not
really as large as the numbers would suggest. The 10 OPEC countries
are already cheating on their production ceilings by anywhere from
1.2 million to more than 1.5 million barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainty and confusion caused by Iran's decision not to
join the agreement could force prices lower, at least temporarily,
a number of analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. consumer can be happy,'' said Raad Alkadiri, a
country analyst with the Washington-based Petroleum Finance Co.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, oil futures for delivery in May closed at $27.09 on
the New York Mercantile Exchange, down 70 cents per barrel.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few months, Iran's refusal to go along with a
general production increase could encourage other members within
the organization to flout their output ceilings, Alkadiri said. The
next few months will be a test of Saudi Arabia's ability to keep
quota cheating in check.
</P>
<P>
   But while the Clinton administration was leaning heavily on OPEC
in large part to appease angry U.S. motorists, oil analysts warned
gasoline prices could still continue to rise through the busy
summer driving season.
</P>
<P>
   While the price of crude, typically, is the dominant factor
affecting pump prices, this year the gasoline markets is being
driven by several other factors.
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline inventories now are at their lowest levels for this
time of year ever, noted Michael Rothman, director of energy market
research for Merrill Lynch in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Inventory statistics released Tuesday may push prices up in
trading Wednesday. The American Petroleum Institute released its
weekly inventory figures late in the day showing crude stockpiles
had declined 1.236 million barrels last week, more than expected.
</P>
<P>
   There was good news, however, for motorists as the trade group
reported gasoline stocks up 299,000 barrels at the end of last
week. Gasoline supplies were expected to drop as vacationers hit
the road for the Spring Break holiday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
