<HEADER>
A0672 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-MICHST-HUTSON-HNS     03-28 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MICHST-HUTSON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY WIZIG  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
Andre Hutson knows the numbers. He is not the first option in
Michigan State's offense. Point guard Mateen Cleaves ably fills
that role.
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the lone No. 1 seed to survive in the NCAA Tournament makes
its second straight Final Four appearance, Hutson also is aware he
is not likely to be the second option, because more often than not,
Morris Peterson has gotten Cleaves' first look. And if not
Peterson, then forward A.J. Granger or shooting guard Charlie Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Unless there is a special mismatch, Hutson, a 6-8, 245-pound
junior forward, again will be counted on for the performance he
gave in the Spartans' 75-64 Midwest Regional final win over Iowa
State. Hutson spent much of the game defending in the low post
against the Cyclones' Marcus Fizer, who was held to one field goal
for the final 11 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Hutson's task might be even more difficult. Eighth
seed and fellow Big Ten Conference member Wisconsin, the Spartans'
Saturday opponent in the national semifinals, milks the shot clock
more often than did Iowa State. Its offense is more
controlled-tempo, as the Spartans know from three meetings this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the style they play, and I know what they stand for,''
Peterson said of the Badgers. ``They stand for defense and
rebounding.''
</P>
<P>
   Until the latter stages of this season, that also pretty much
described Hutson's contributions. Unlike the Spartans' more
publicized starters, Hutson was on no Big Ten all-conference teams,
not even second, third or honorable mention. He simply took on a
number of the nation's better post players _ Texas' Chris Mihm,
Arizona's Loren Woods, Kentucky's Jamaal Magloire, Kansas' Eric
Chenowith, Ohio State's Ken Johnson, Syracuse's Etan Thomas _
before Hutson even got to Fizer. In each instance, Hutson held his
own or more.
</P>
<P>
   In the 30-7 Spartans' comeback wins over Iowa State, Syracuse
and Utah in their last three Tournament games, Hutson averaged 15.7
points and eight rebounds while shooting 72 percent (18-of-25). He
has taken 10 or more shots in just four games this season,
including a high of 11 twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Andre gets the ball, good things happen,'' Cleaves said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andre is a very unselfish guy,'' Bell said. ``But the last
couple of weeks, he has been demanding the ball. Everybody
appreciates that. Nobody is going to get mad because he wants the
ball. We're going to get it to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Hutson is a gunner. He got off just nine field-goal
attempts but produced 17 points and 11 rebounds in the Iowa State
game while helping to hold Fizer to 6-of-15 shooting, 15 points and
four rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Hutson was voted to the all-tournament team at the Midwest
Regional semifinals and finals last week in Auburn Hills, Mich. The
Spartans downed Syracuse with a 17-0 run and outscored Iowa State
23-5 down the stretch, a combined 40-5 closing blast.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Tom Izzo's five seasons as head coach, two constants
have been rebounding and defense. The Spartans lead the nation in
rebound margin (more than 12 per game) yet were outboarded 19-8 in
the first half and 38-27 overall by a shorter Iowa State. The only
other team to do that this year was Wisconsin, by a 29-26 margin in
the Spartans' 59-54 win at home. Michigan State won their other two
meetings this season by 61-44 at Wisconsin and 55-46 in the Big Ten
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Before the NCAA Tournament, Izzo said: ``Andre Hutson is a
15-point, nine-rebound guy. He's such a good kid. He's a very
intelligent kid. It's just in his demeanor that he doesn't want to
be selfish.''
</P>
<P>
   In high school at Trotwood, Ohio, a Dayton suburb, Hutson was
voted the state's Player of the Year as a senior, then started 26
games as a Spartans freshman when the team shared the first of
three straight Big Ten titles (the last two outright). Last season,
Hutson was a 34-game starter as the Spartans reached the Final Four
for the first time since the 1979 national championship season
before losing to Duke in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Hutson is a three-year starter for a Spartans program that
has compiled an 85-20 record in that time, three Big Ten
championships, consecutive Big Ten tournament championships, and
another chance for the biggest college basketball prize.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
