u f BC-INTEL-CHIPS-NYT &LR;      03-28 0467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-CHIPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTEL WINS LATEST BATTLE IN WAR OF PC CHIPS
</HEADLINE>
   (hm) 
 By MATT RICHTEL  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Seeking to one-up its archrival, Advanced Micro
Devices, in the relentless creation of faster chips for low-cost
computers, the Intel Corp. on Wednesday introduced its latest
Celeron processor for personal computers priced under $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   The new processor, which comes in 600- and 566-megahertz
versions, includes advances that should improve low-cost computers'
multimedia capabilities, said Keith Diefendorff, editor in chief of
The Microprocessor Report, an industry newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Diefendorff said the new chip should put pressure on Advanced
Micro to complete its own next-generation low-cost chip, which is
due out in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``This makes life uncomfortable to A.M.D. at the low end,''
Diefendorff said. The cutthroat competition between the companies
has led to a ``pretty substantial boost in the performance of
sub-$1,000 PC's,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Intel and Advanced Micro remain in a pitched battle to provide
the processors, the primary computing chips in PC's.
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide, Intel is the clear leader, with about 86 percent of
the PC market in the third quarter of 1999, according to Dataquest.
Advanced Micro's share was 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Advanced Micro plans to answer the latest Celeron introduction
later this year with a chip code-named Spitfire. The company has
said the chip will be a derivative of its high-end Athlon processor
and is meant to be more powerful than the Celeron.
</P>
<P>
   The company has said little publicly, however, about the speed
or architecture of the processor, side-stepping the question of how
its performance will differ from the new Celeron.
</P>
<P>
   Intel created the new Celeron as a derivative of its own
higher-end processor, the Pentium III.
</P>
<P>
   Diefendorff said the Celeron will have only half the on-chip
memory of the Pentium III. And it will have a slower bus speed,
which is the rate at which data moves between the processor and the
rest of the computer, including disk drive and memory.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff McCrea, director of marketing for Intel's Desktop Products
Group, said Intel was able to make faster chips less expensive by
improving manufacturing techniques and developing lower costs for
packaging the chips.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Grossberg, an Intel spokesman, said the timing of the
introduction had long been planned and had nothing to do with the
anticipated release of the Advanced Micro chip.
</P>
<P>
   Diefendorff concurred, adding: ``I wouldn't say either company
is in the reactive mode. They both know what the trend is, and they
know what they have to do to stay on it.''
</P>
<P>
   The upshot, he said, would continue to be good news for
consumers in the form of ``more performance at lower price.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
