<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0675 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SCHOOLBUS-TRAIN29-COX     03-28 1319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLBUS-TRAIN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Deadly train-school bus collision at Georgia line worst in 25
years
 &HT;    By Craig Schneider and Dan Chapman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TENNGA, Ga. _ Two children were dead and three others were
clinging to life after a freight train carrying Chevrolets collided
with a school bus transporting seven children _ the worst accident
of its kind in Georgia in more than 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   The 72-passenger bus from Murray County was early into its
morning run, carrying only seven children, when Rhonda Cloer, 34,
drove it down the slope of Liberty Church Road at 6:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The engineer of the 33-car CSX train heading from Cincinnati to
Tampa told police he blew the train's whistle when approaching the
crossing. Seeing the bus continue across the tracks, he jammed the
locomotive into an emergency stop, said Trooper Ken Uselton of the
Tennesee Highway Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Brown, whose home abuts the railroad, heard a ``boom'' that
sounded like dynamite exploding. One of the first to arrive on the
scene, Brown saw the train had dragged the bus more than 200 feet,
from Tennessee into Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The collision wrenched the bus' upper shell from its chassis and
engine.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, said Brown, ``There were little kids lying everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   He went over to one girl lying still on the ground. She was
dead. Other children were injured and crying. He knelt by one and
said, ``You'll be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   As ambulances arrived, Brown helped lift children onto
stretchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was going crazy,'' he said, standing by the ravaged
hulk of the bus. ``If you could help, you helped.'' Daniel Pack, 9,
of Tennga and 6-year-old Kayla Silvers of Cisco died at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin J. Sherrill, 8, and Amber Pritchett, 9, both of Tennga,
were in critical condition Tuesday night. So, too, was Kayli Cloer,
5, whose mother, the bus driver, was listed in fair condition. The
Cloers live in Chatsworth.
</P>
<P>
   Brittany Gaddis, 8, and Jordan Manis, 6, both of Tennga, were
listed in serious condition.
</P>
<P>
   All the injured were taken to Erlanger Medical Center in
Chattanooga, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Sluder, Daniel Pack's stepfather, said he heard about the
crash while listening to the radio at work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he was on the bus, but I didn't know if he was hurt,''
said Sluder. Later, he had to identify the body of the boy, who had
enjoyed horses and bicycles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in shock, I guess,'' he said. ``You really don't know how
to feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Darrell Silvers first saw the boy, his neighbor, was dead at the
scene. He then saw his daughter Kayla inside the shattered shell of
the bus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pulled her out,'' Silvers said. His little girl was dead.
</P>
<P>
   The National Transportation Safety Board said the bus had
crossed into Tennessee, made a loop and headed back to Georgia when
it was hit by the train.
</P>
<P>
   Trains are allowed to travel 60 mph at that spot; the engineer
was able to slow only to 50 before the collision.
</P>
<P>
   Trains are a part of life in this border community, rumbling
through at all hours, blowing their whistles. Some residents said
the crossing at Liberty Church Road, which has no signal lights or
mechanical crossing arms, was a tragedy waiting to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Herman Stinnett, 49, said motorists often can't see the train
coming because of tall, dense foliage along the tracks. It's too
early in the investigation to assign blame, authorities said late
Tuesday. They need to reconstruct the accident and interview the
engineer, the bus driver and others.
</P>
<P>
   Rhonda Cloer applied for her bus driver's license in July 1991.
The Murray County school system granted the license a month later.
</P>
<P>
   Cloer became a full-time school bus driver a year ago. She was a
substitute driver during the previous two years. She holds a valid
commercial bus driver's license and carries all proper endorsements
to drive a school bus, said Jim Shuler, spokesman for the Georgia
Department of Public Safety.
</P>
<P>
   Cloer also took a train safety workshop within the last two
months. The Bus Driver Training Institute seminar taught drivers
how to approach railroad crossings, Shuler said.
</P>
<P>
   Cloer had had no accidents within the past two years, according
to records available Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee Department of Safety officials said it was ``way too
early'' to consider any possible charges against the bus driver. A
routine blood-alcohol test was performed on Cloer and the train's
engineer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of unanswered questions right now,'' said Dana
Keeton, a Department of Safety spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday wasn't the first time for tragedy on the train tracks
near Tennga.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two years ago, 15 miles up the tracks, a CSX freight
slammed into a van carrying a Polk County, Tenn., family. The
parents and three young children were crushed. A witness described
the van as ``crushed into a box.''
</P>
<P>
   It is rare in Georgia for a child to be killed while riding a
school bus. Tuesday's fatalities were the first aboard a school bus
since December 1982, when a 6-year-old Hall County girl died after
a truck hit her bus.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's worst school bus accident happened in October 1974.
Seven children were killed and 61 injured when a Southern Railway
freight train backed into a Polk County bus. The caboose crushed
the bus beneath its steel wheels, dragging it 300 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The Polk bus driver, who was injured, told authorities he
thought the train wasn't moving or was moving too slow to matter.
The driver and train employees shared blame, according to federal
and state officials.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's paucity of school bus fatalities mirrors national
trends.
</P>
<P>
   From 1988 to 1998, 139 people aboard school buses _ 26 of them
drivers _ died in accidents, according to the U.S. Department of
Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday in Tennga, small turns of fate saved several children
who usually ride the bus. Daniel Pack's brother, Kody, had stayed
home with a cold.
</P>
<P>
   And Missie Dalton, 25, said, ``Both of my children should have
been on that bus.'' Instead, her kids were taken by car to
Northwest Elementary.
</P>
<P>
   Counselors were brought in from two other school districts, and
they rode on the buses taking children home. Bus routes were
reconfigured to avoid traveling over train tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could feel the sadness in the school. It was horrible,''
said Conda Lowery, 25, whose daughter is a student there.
</P>
<P>
   Jennie Webb, a neighbor, was looking after Kayla Silver's little
sister, 3-year-old Taylor. Webb said the little girl told her,
``I'm glad my sister is with Jesus, but I wish she were here.''
</P>
<P>
   Brittany Gaddis, torn and traumatized, was one of the survivors.
She had her seat belt on and was sitting in one of the first four
rows when the train hit the bus.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said she did not hear the train coming,'' said Brittany's
mother, Anita Beavers, who clung to her daughter's Winnie-the-Pooh
backpack in front of the Chattanooga hospital Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Brittany was ``slung all over the bus,'' her mother said.
</P>
<P>
   The girl unfastened her seat belt and called out to another
girl, she told her mother. The other girl didn't answer. Or move.
</P>
<P>
   Brittany had to grab on to the train to get out of the bus. She
told her mother she saw a boy lying on the ground. She talked to
the boy, shook him. But he didn't move, either.
</P>
<P>
   Brittany stumbled to a nearby store. A woman helped her,
consoled her and tended her wounds until rescue workers arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Brittany's mother saw her daughter briefly at the Murray County
hospital before she was flown to Chattanooga.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she found out I was there,'' Beavers said, ``she lifted
up her little hand and waved at me.''
</P>
<P>
   A candlelight vigil is planned for this evening on the
courthouse lawn in Chatsworth. Autopsies, being conducted in
Nashville, will delay funeral arrangements for a couple of days.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
