<HEADLINE>
LACK OF SLEEP IS DANGEROUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 BY JANIE MAGRUDER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Phoenix) - Falling asleep while driving on a busy Phoenix
street last fall was a wake-up call for Ruth Phares.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the grace of God there were no cars around,'' said Phares,
52. ``The next thing I knew, I was in the next lane. And I don't
know how I got there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Peoria woman isn't alone: Nearly one in five Americans has
dozed off while driving, according to the National Sleep
Foundation's 2000 Sleep in America Poll, released Tuesday. The poll
of 1,154 adults indicated that 51 percent of Ameri cans drive while
drowsy, a dangerous state of mind.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation also said that al though we work longer hours,
our productivity actually is suffering. The poll reported that half
of all employed Americans say sleepiness affects their
productivity, and that 19 percent admit making occasional or
frequent mistakes at work.
</P>
<P>
   Younger Americans aren't immune. More than half (55 percent) of
adults 18 to 29 years old acknowledge that they stay up too late
watching TV or surfing the Internet; as a result, they report
``waking unrefreshed.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason for all this fatigue? People exercise too little, eat
and drink too much _ and too close to bedtime _ and largely ignore
ex perts' recommendations that they get at least eight hours of
sleep to function properly. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
