<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE A BIT AHEAD OF U.S. IN
 CENSUS RETURNS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients) 
 BY SHAUN MCKINNON 
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Phoenix) - It's nearly Census Day _ do you know where your
question naire is?
</P>
<P>
   If it's still sitting in a pile of unpaid bills, you're in the
majority. Just 45 percent of Arizona residents have returned their
forms, barely ahead of the national average of 44 percent, the
Census Bureau reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   As of Tuesday, Ohio and Pennsylva nia led with 51 percent.
</P>
<P>
   State officials say it's too early to tell whether Arizona is on
track to avoid a costly undercount. The state is aiming for a
minimum return rate of 67 percent, 5 points higher than in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   In Arizona, Graham County has posted the best return rate, 49
per cent, followed by Maricopa County with 47 percent. Apache
County, with 27 percent, and La Paz County, with 22 percent,
bringing up the rear.
</P>
<P>
   El Mirage leads Phoenix area cities with 57 percent. In Phoenix
and Mesa, 44 percent of households have responded, while
fast-growing Gil bert and Peoria both have passed the halfway mark.
</P>
<P>
   Census Director Kenneth Prewitt said the agency is releasing the
mail-response rate to motivate peo ple. Although Saturday is Census
Day, the bureau will tabulate ques tionnaires through mid-April
before sending workers door-to-door.
</P>
<P>
   People who received the short form also may complete it on the
Internet at www.census.gov, or by telephone at 1-800-471-9424.
</P>
</TEXT>
