<HEADER>
A0801 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-VANISHED-BOXER-ART-NY     03-28 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VANISHED-BOXER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO CHARGED IN KILLING OF RUSSIAN BOXER
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Pa., Md., Germany)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By NEIL MacFARQUHAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Federal prosecutors have charged two men suspected of
being members of the Russian mob with abducting and murdering a
professional boxer who had disappeared from a Brooklyn garage in
late 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The two men were identified as Alexander Nosov, 24, who is in
jail in Germany on an unrelated charge, and Natan Gozman, about the
same age, who is at large. In an indictment filed Monday by the
U.S. attorney in Manhattan, the two men were each charged with four
counts of kidnapping and murder. Each also faces a weapons charge.
</P>
<P>
   The victim, Sergei Kobozev, was a former army captain who had
boxed for the Soviet national team before immigrating to the United
States in 1990. At 6 feet, 190 pounds, he was the U.S. Boxing
Association's cruiserweight champion. It was not quite a major
title in an often-overlooked division, between light heavyweight
and heavyweight, but he had a 22-1 record, including 17 knockouts.
</P>
<P>
   When he disappeared on Nov. 8, 1995, he was only months away
from his biggest bout: a $100,000 shot at the World Boxing
Council's cruiserweight title. He was 31.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment said Nosov and Gozman shot Kobozev in a Brooklyn
auto repair shop and then spirited him, still alive, to New Jersey.
After someone else broke his neck, the indictment said, the two men
and others buried the boxer in the back yard of a house in
Livingston, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI, acting on a tip last March, dug up Kobozev's body. The
current occupants of the house, which used to be the home of a
high-ranking Russian mobster, had nothing to do with the crime,
said Joseph Valiquette, an FBI spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Kobozev's remains were identified in part through a custom-made
mouthpiece that he used when he boxed, which fit the dental
formation of the skeleton found in New Jersey, Valiquette said. The
FBI was still pursuing a DNA match through relatives in Russia, he
said, but there was no doubt that the body found in the back yard
was Kobozev's.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment said he was shot on the day he disappeared during
a confrontation with the two men and others in the repair shop,
which was not identified. The investigation is proceeding into
others who might have been involved in the slaying.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said they would seek Nosov's extradition from
Germany, while Gozman is believed to be in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The two could face the death penalty for the charge of murder in
the aid of racketeering, although Germany in the past has refused
to extradite prisoners here until the U.S. government agrees not to
pursue capital punishment.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment says that Nosov and Gozman were members of a
Russian mob group known as Tatarin's Brigade that operates in New
York, New Jersey, Pennsylvania and Maryland, the indictment says.
Eight other members have already been indicted on numerous
racketeering charges for the group's involvement in murder,
kidnapping, robbery and extortion.
</P>
<P>
   Nosov and Gozman had sought a greater role in the mob group's
activities by kidnapping the boxer for ransom, the indictment said.
</P>
<P>
   Police officers assigned to his case and some friends have said
that shortly before his disappearance, the boxer may have scuffled
with a member of a Russian organized crime family at the Paradise
Bar, in the Sheepshead Bay section of Brooklyn. Kobozev worked
there as a bouncer.
</P>
<P>
   But neither the FBI nor prosecutors would confirm that incident
or speculate about what might have prompted the kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
   Kobozev's fellow boxers expressed relief Tuesday that someone
had finally been charged.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good,'' said Peter Kahn, who used to help train Kobozev.
``He was a great fighter and a great kid and it was a big
tragedy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
