<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0803 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-DORISMOND-RECORD-N     03-28 0502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DORISMOND-RECORD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLIC ADVOCATE TAKES ON MAYOR OVER RELEASE OF DORISMOND'S POLICE
RECORD
</HEADLINE>
 (mg) 
By THOMAS J. LUECK    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Using an obscure, nearly century-old section of the
New York City Charter, Public Advocate Mark Green obtained a court
order on Tuesday directing Mayor Rudolph Giuliani to show why he
should not be held legally accountable for the release of the
sealed court records of Patrick M. Dorismond.
</P>
<P>
   The City Charter authorizes a court to inquire into ``any
alleged violation or neglect of duty in relation to the property,
government or affairs of the city.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to a motion by Green, Judge Louise Gruner Gans of
the State Supreme Court in Manhattan issued a show-cause order
requesting that the mayor or his lawyers appear on April 13 to
determine whether confidentiality laws had been violated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best short-term remedy we have found to overturn the
mayor's self-created precedent that he is above the law is to have
a court tell him that no mayor is above the law,'' said Green, an
adversary of Giuliani's and a candidate to succeed him in the 2002
election.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference two hours later, Giuliani said he was
unaware of the judge's order. And he continued to defend his
decision to release the juvenile record of Dorismond, who was shot
and killed by a police officer on March 16.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor insisted that ``privacy interests end in death,''
although he acknowledged that the law was ambiguous.
</P>
<P>
   ``The statute says nothing about prohibiting the release of
those records after a person is dead, but at the same time the
statute doesn't authorize the release after death,'' Giuliani said.
``The fact is that I made that judgment based on solid legal
advice. I'm happy to defend it anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has said that Dorismond's record is an indication that
he was volatile, and that evidence surrounding his shooting
indicated that Dorismond had punched Officer Anthony Vasquez and
had a history of bad behavior.
</P>
<P>
   But the mayor's critics, and Dorismond's family, have questioned
Giuliani's decision to release details of a minor's police record.
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon Silver, the Democratic speaker of the New York Assembly,
last week ordered two Assembly committees to investigate whether
the mayor had violated state laws on confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   Green said he was hopeful that the little-known provision of the
City Charter would provide a speedier method of examining the
mayor's decision to release the records. In the motion to Judge
Gruner Gans, Green said he had asked the court to determine how the
police and City Hall had gained access to Dorismond's sealed
records, and the legality of the mayor's public disclosures.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani suggested that more information about Dorismond's
background would be released, saying ``there are a lot of factors
that will come out in the case that will indicate the picture is
much more complicated than the press has unfortunately painted
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-00 2317EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000328.0387 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0805 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKW-RUTGERS-STRINGER-     03-28 1230
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-RUTGERS-STRINGER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRINGER: OVERRATED? NO, OVERJOYED
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ The clock was nearly exhausted and C. Vivian
Stringer awaited the inevitable, standing with her arms folded at
the Rutgers bench. She was about to become the first coach, man or
woman, to take three different schools to the Final Four in college
basketball. As victory approached, she smacked her fist into her
palm, she smiled, she cried, she shook her head slightly in wonder,
and finally, she held her hands above her head like a referee
signaling a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The moment culminated five years of anguished conflict for her,
professional satisfaction mixed with personal melancholy. She had
gone to Rutgers in 1995, seeking to rebuild her career and her life
after the death of her husband, William, from a heart attack in
1992. She had a severely handicapped daughter who needed constant
care and a son who would later experience legal problems. She had
been accustomed to winning, but she lost more than she won that
first season at Rutgers and she was harshly criticized for being
overpaid and overrated.
</P>
<P>
   Late Monday night, a career that once seemed stripped and
withered was back in full bloom. Playing with a ferocious urgency
on defense and a ravenous insistence on rebounding, Rutgers
defeated top-seeded Georgia, 59-51, to win the West Regional and
advance to its first Final Four, where it will face six-time
champion Tennessee on Friday in Philadelphia. The victory ritual
called for Stringer to climb a ladder and snip a strand of the net,
which she ended up wearing around her neck like a triumphant
necklace.
</P>
<P>
   Her quiet sentences usually dart and soar like a kite, swooping
and diving and pulling up sharply, circling back on themselves in
barely tethered flight, but now she struggled to find the words.
Tears streaked at the corners of Stringer's eyes as she later sat
to talk with reporters. Tammy Sutton-Brown, the Rutgers center who
muscled Georgia inside for 14 points and six rebounds, put a
comforting hand on Stringer's arm, as if that might also steady her
coach's voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't imagine the emotion of pride,'' Stringer said.
``It's overwhelming. We were the only ones who believed in
ourselves. I think we represent all the have-nots. This is a team
of survivors.''
</P>
<P>
   As she stood on the sideline in those final moments, Stringer
said later, she had 28 years, a career of thoughts, dancing in her
head. It had taken her 11 seasons to reach the Final Four in 1982
with Cheyney State University, the nation's first black college.
</P>
<P>
   Stringer recalled that her team routinely traveled in vans with
holes in the floorboard, the road visible underneath, and she
sometimes jokingly wondered whether the drivers might have to start
pedaling with their feet. Her coaching success in 1982 had come
amid wrenching personal sorrow as her young daughter Janine had
begun to suffer from the debilitating effects of spinal meningitis,
which has now confined her to a wheelchair at age 19.
</P>
<P>
   It had taken a decade of coaching at the University of Iowa to
return to the Final Four in 1993. At Iowa, she had financial and
personal security and her teams won 20 games for 10 consecutive
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Now she returns to the national semifinals, although her five
seasons at Rutgers have sometimes seemed like 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may have to quit after this,'' the 50-year-old Stringer said
with a tired laugh. ``I know this much. I'm never going to go
anywhere and start a program again from scratch. It's been rough. I
just want to get some rest.''
</P>
<P>
   She had not intended to leave Iowa, but it became too much to
stay after the death of her husband, who was an exercise
physiolgist at the university. Too much to pass his empty office,
which was located near hers in the athletic department. ``I have
never made a big decision without Bill,'' she said in 1995. ``Never
bought a big piece of furniture, didn't know where the fuses
were.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of her sisters moved to Iowa to help her, but she found
herself becoming too dependent on them. She was listing, surviving
more than living, she said. So she looked to move back East, where
she could regain her personal ballast. Rutgers offered to pay
Stringer a reported $300,000 a year in salary and other benefits,
more than any other coach on campus, more than any other coach of a
women's basketball team. But Rutgers went only 13-15 during her
first season in 1995-96, then 11-17 in 1996-97. The jobs of
parenting and coaching tugged her hard in opposing directions. Her
daughter underwent two operations that first season, and for
several weeks Stringer found herself sleeping in a hospital room in
Philadelphia, then catching a train to Rutgers for morning
practices. Her two sons were going through an uneasy adjustment to
a new environment, and she grew tired and distracted. She was
harshly judged by fans and reporters, who focused on the bottom
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is special,'' Stringer said, still at courtside as Monday
night became Tuesday morning, her voice almost a whisper. ``I was
thinking about all the kids who believed, about things we overcame.
We came here with nothing. I read things that hurt me personally.
Hurt me. But what's important is that we believed. Sometimes you
think you don't have it all. You hear things that hurt. That you
don't know what you're doing. I wasn't used to that. Maybe I was a
little thin-skinned, but I just know the team always believed.''
</P>
<P>
   She recruited players who trusted her reputation and who had an
eagerness to build something from nothing. Players like guard
Shawnetta Stewart, who had broken Wilt Chamberlain's scoring
records in the Philadelphia Public League and whose bulky
assertiveness had drawn comparisons to Charles Barkley. Stewart
scored 22 points against Georgia, as Rutgers trailed only twice in
40 minutes, then held the ladder as Stringer cut down the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's been through a lot,'' Stewart said. ``Everyone doubted
her, but she refuted all the odds.''
</P>
<P>
   She had relied on her sisters to keep her buoyant, and her
former players, and she talked often with Temple's John Chaney, who
had coached the men's team at Cheyney State when she coached the
women.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, inexorably, Stringer revived Rutgers. The Scarlet
Knights reached the Round of 16 in 1998 and the last eight in 1999.
Still, her professional triumphs continued to be tempered by
personal distress. In January 1999, her oldest son, David, was
dismissed from the North Carolina State football team and suspended
from school for his alleged involvement in an altercation that left
another student dead from a gunshot wound.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice to get something and not have a tragedy in
your life, so you have to be happy and sad at the same time,''
Stringer said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, this season, sailing in calm personal waters, she has
become the third woman to reach 600 career victories, and she is
going to the Final Four for a third time. Stringer had no doubt
Rutgers would get there. When the team traveled to Philadelphia in
late February to play Villanova, she diverted the team bus to the
First Union Center, where the national semifinals and finals will
be played, and she had her team walk on the court for a moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``So it wouldn't seem strange when we came back,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
