<SLUG> BC-NY-ECSTACY-SENTENCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SENTENCING DRUG COURIER, JUDGE SCOLDS HASIDIC GROUP
</HEADLINE>
   (hm) 
 By ALAN FEUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dozens of Hasidic Jews packed together shoulder to
shoulder in a Brooklyn courtroom Tuesday, seeking leniency for a
teen-ager who forsook his strict upbringing to help run a huge
smuggling ring that flooded New York with the designer drug
Ecstasy.
</P>
<P>
   But to their surprise, the 70 members of the Bobover sect found
themselves the subject of a scathing lecture by a federal judge who
upbraided them in a quavering voice for allowing an international
drug smuggling ring to flourish in their midst.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where was the community when all of this was going on?'' the
judge, I. Leo Glasser, demanded of the crowd gathered in Federal
District Court in Brooklyn for the sentencing of the teen-ager,
Shimon Levita, 18. ``Where was the family when 18-year-old boys
were traveling from Paris to Amsterdam, Montreal, New York and
Atlanta?''
</P>
<P>
   ``They were gone for long periods of time,'' Glasser continued.
``They were traveling around Europe. They applied for passports.
Where were the teachers? Who was keeping tabs on these boys who
were bringing drugs back and taking money there?''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his stern words, Glasser sentenced Levita, who pleaded
guilty in December to drug trafficking, to only 30 months in a
government-run boot camp. He had faced a maximum of 15 years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   According to Levita's supporters, who wrote 30 letters on his
behalf to the judge, he was an earnest youngster disillusioned by
the plain garb and religious strictures of his community who was
tempted into a life of crime at 17.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors said Levita was a calculating criminal who
recruited his peers into a smuggling ring that moved hundreds of
thousands of dollars and more than a million pills of Ecstasy.
</P>
<P>
   Levita became involved in the scheme in October 1998, when he
met an Israeli man named Sean Erez, 29, who had been recruiting
couriers for his illegal Ecstasy business from the Hasidic youth in
Brooklyn's Borough Park, the government said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few months, the government said, Levita recruited
several young Hasidic Jews to fly between New York and Europe
carrying Ecstasy, a synthetic drug popular in New York dance clubs
that causes euphoria and extreme alertness.
</P>
<P>
   Erez and his girlfriend, Diana Reicherter, 22, were the
masterminds of the smuggling scheme, the government said,
distributing the drugs in New York City as Levita oversaw the
couriers. Hasidim were chosen on purpose, the government said,
because their black hats and traditional side curls were unlikely
to raise the suspicions of customs officials.
</P>
<P>
   Last April, after several couriers were arrested, Levita fled to
a tiny town near Amsterdam, according to government papers.
</P>
<P>
   But in July, he was arrested after being named in a federal
indictment with Erez, Reicherter and four other men. All pleaded
guilty except Erez and Reicherter, who are in custody in the
Netherlands, fighting extradition.
</P>
<P>
   Before handing down the sentence, Glasser noted that he had
sentenced many of the couriers in the last six months. ``As young
yeshiva boy after young yeshiva boy stands before me accused of
smuggling drugs,'' he said, ``I think there should be some very
serious thought given to what is going on here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
