<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-28 23:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0817 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NJ-TROLLEY-RAIL-ART-N     03-28 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-TROLLEY-RAIL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW JERSEY SEES FUTURE IN OLD TRIUMPH: TROLLEYS
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo _ NYT23 _ is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mg) 
 By ANDREW JACOBS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAYONNE, N.J. _ A half-century after the region's last streetcar
disappeared to make way for more cars and buses, New Jersey
officials are set to open the first leg of a $1.1 billion trolley
system along the Hudson River.
</P>
<P>
   It will carry 25,000 riders a day, and the entire project, when
completed in 2010, is expected to carry more than 100,000 people
through the most densely populated region in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The Hudson-Bergen Light Rail, which will carry its first
fare-paying passenger on April 15, is the metropolitan region's
most ambitious public transportation project since the 1960s, the
largest public works program in New Jersey history and an
intriguing look at the prospects for a transit system long deemed a
part of the past. Officials say they hope the system will one day
extend across New Jersey, linking light rail systems that are on
the drawing board in other parts of the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of those infrastructure investments you make at
the beginning of a century that serves you throughout the
century,'' said James Weinstein, New Jersey state transportation
commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Whether enough commuters can be coaxed out of their cars to make
the system a success remains to be seen. But officials say they
believe the 20.5-mile system, when completed, will not only
persuade commuters to leave their cars at home, relieving clogged
roads and easing polluted air, but will spur redevelopment in
places that have thus far missed out on the region's economic boom.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years in the making, the line will initially feed into the
ferries and PATH trains that carry thousands of commuters to
Manhattan as well as those who work along New Jersey's Hudson River
waterfront. Once a wasteland of abandoned rail yards and rotting
piers, the so-called Gold Coast in Hudson County has been
transformed into a city of office towers and luxury apartments. An
additional five million square feet of commercial space and
thousands of apartments are planned in the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   But until now, there has been no easy way to move north and
south through the county, something that frustrates many of the
31,000 people who work along the waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without this rail line, we'll drown in our success,'' said
Senator Frank R. Lautenberg of New Jersey, the ranking Democrat on
the Senate's Transportation Appropriation subcommittee who helped
secure more than half the project's financing.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM) Before the car became king in the years after
World War II, this heavily urbanized wedge of New Jersey was
crisscrossed by trolley lines, nearly all of them ending at the
waterfront, where riders could hop a train or ferry to Manhattan.
``We've clearly come full circle,'' said Martin Robins, director of
the Alan M. Voorhees Transportation Center at Rutgers University.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The concept of light rail was born in the 1970s, when engineers
began marrying new technology with the traditional streetcar. The
cars, which run on low-voltage electric lines, can quickly
accelerate to 55 miles per hour, effortlessly climb hills and brake
faster than a bus. Because they are entered without a step up, the
trains can more easily be boarded by the elderly, the disabled and
those pushing baby strollers.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, light rail advocates say, the lines are far less
expensive to build than subways, ``which makes them very attractive
to both taxpayers and politicians,'' said David Phelps, a light
rail specialist at the American Public Transportation Association
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Spurred by increasing traffic congestion and decreasing air
quality, two dozen U.S. cities now have light rail systems,
including such car-dependent stalwarts as Dallas, Los Angeles and
Denver. ``The verdict so far has been almost unanimously
favorable,'' Phelps said.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is so optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   Alan E. Pisarski, a transportation specialist and the author of
the book, ``Commuting in America,'' said cities like Buffalo and
Baltimore have found that their initial ridership estimates were
wildly overstated. As in many parts of the country, more and more
New Jersey residents are commuting from suburb to suburb, not from
suburb to city. Such commuters, he said, cannot be served by light
rail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think light rail is a slam-dunk solution to the
problem of congestion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some developers are betting on the project. On Jersey
City's Martin Luther King Boulevard, one of the area's most
neglected neighborhoods, a shopping center recently opened next to
a light rail station. A dozen blocks away, not far from a vast
expanse of metal scrap yards and vacant warehouses, the sleek
black-and-white cars glide past wooden skeletons for dozens of
luxury townhouses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The light rail will open up sites for development that until
now have been virtually inaccessible,'' said New Jersey Gov.
Christine Todd Whitman.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Transit officials plan to run the trains every seven and a half
minutes at rush hour and every 15 minutes at other times. Jeffrey
A. Warsh, the executive director of New Jersey Transit, said the
$1.50 one-way fare comes down to 60 cents if passengers use a
monthly pass, which will cost $53 and will allow free transfers to
local buses.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the 12 stations opening next month, four more
stops along the Jersey City and Hoboken waterfronts will open by
2002, linking the system to New Jersey Transit's commuter rail
terminus and the half-dozen Manhattan-bound ferries. In 2010, when
the line is scheduled to reach the Vince Lombardi Park and Ride
station in suburban Ridgefield, transit officials said, it will
carry more passengers than all of New Jersey Transit's rail lines
combined.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
