* u BC-CZECH-MUSIC-REVIEW-NY     03-28 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CZECH-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELEBRATING A PRAGUE SPRING AT LINCOLN CENTER
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lincoln Center is paying tribute to the Czech
Republic on the 10th anniversary of the Velvet Revolution by
presenting what it is calling the Prague Festival, the heart of
which is a three-concert visit to Avery Fisher Hall by the Czech
Philharmonic and Vladimir Ashkenazy, its chief conductor since
1997.
</P>
<P>
   To an outsider who knows the orchestra from several decades'
worth of splendid recordings and a few visits to New York, the
Czech Philharmonic has long seemed like a jewel in Prague's
cultural life. But it has had a rough decade, marked by unhappy
relationships with the two music directors who preceded Ashkenazy
and dwindling state subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   But at the first Prague Festival concert, on Sunday afternoon,
there was no musical evidence that the orchestra was under stress,
nor did there seem to be any diminution of its distinctive timbral
character. Its wind and brass still play with a coloration that
registers as earthier and more textured than that of most European
and American orchestras. And its strings have a bright tone that
often conveys more energy than warmth, although warmth is hardly
precluded.
</P>
<P>
   Ashkenazy's three concerts have a theme of sorts: All the
composers _ Krasa and Mahler on Sunday afternoon, with Mozart,
Janacek and Dvorak on Monday and Martinu and Tchaikovsky joining
the list Tuesday night _ had either personal or professional ties
to Prague. Some of those ties were strong and some were tenuous,
and as Michael Beckerman points out in an essay in the program
book, the links between Czech composers and Prague were not always
the happiest. Janacek, for example, was largely rejected by the
Prague musical establishment until late in life. Martinu was also
uneasy in Prague and left it for Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Krasa, whose youthful symphony (1926) opened the series, had
considerable success in Prague, where he was born in 1899. He might
have become one of the city's musical patriarchs had he not been
sent to Theresienstadt and from there to Auschwitz, where he died
in 1944. His symphony is a strange piece, dark-hued at first but
gradually brightening, and full of interesting musical imagery
meant to mirror the text of ``Die Lausesucherinnen'' (``The Lice
Pickers''). Krasa set this Rimbaud text, in a German translation,
as the work's finale. Charlotte Hellikant, mezzo-soprano, gave a
ravishing account of the setting.
</P>
<P>
   But the most interesting aspect of the work is the degree to
which it draws on two unrelated schools of compositional thought in
the air at the time. A hint of Parisian Impressionism is evident in
the shifting, gentle textures that give the work a sense of
mystery. And there are hints of the German cabaret style that
caught the attention of Kurt Weill in some of the parodistic march
figures in the second movement.
</P>
<P>
   Ashkenazy devoted the second half of the concert to Mahler's
Symphony No. 7, which was given its world premiere in Prague in
1908. Mahler was trying to be cheerful in the Seventh, and that
made for outer movements that can sound banal and uncohesive unless
a performance sweeps a listener into it. Ashkenazy did not quite
achieve that, but he did test his orchestra's mettle: There was
some spectacular brass playing, and the ``Nachtmusik'' movements
had a graceful, alluring flow and an appealing sense of intimacy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
