<SLUG> BC-RESCUE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORM TURNS HIKE INTO
 STRUG GLE FOR SURVIVAL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients) 
 BY BARBARA YOST 
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) - A treacherous hike and a freak storm have given
Kelly Vickrey of Chandler a new definition of adventure: ``When
you'd rather be home talking about it than doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Vickrey and seven other hikers, including three Phoenix area
resi dents, are lucky to have survived a hike to Rainbow Bridge
last week that started as a lark but turned perilous when the storm
blew in. Before it was over, one of them was thinking, ``This is
how people die.''
</P>
<P>
   Their adventure was part Jack Lon don and part ``Into Thin
Air,'' the ill-fated tale of climbers on Mount Everest. Reunited
for lunch at Nel lo's restaurant in Tempe on Sunday, the eight
hikers said next time they'll be better prepared. Even under the
best of circumstances, the path to Rainbow Bridge is demanding.
With unanticipated bad weather, it can be a recipe for disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Their lives were saved thanks to a big dog, high-tech equipment
and the compassion hikers show strangers they meet along the trail.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, March 17 was a spectacular day to view Rainbow Bridge on
the Navajo Reservation near the Arizo na-Utah border. The sky was
clear, the air was warm. Vistas of rugged canyons, landscape
brightened by junipers, sandstone and slick rock were breathtaking.
</P>
<P>
   Vickrey's group, including a friend from Milwaukee, were looking
for ward to a three-day hike. Four friends from Flagstaff and
Cotton wood began a similar excursion two days later.
</P>
<P>
   A battle against the elements would bring them together.
</P>
<P>
   As Vickrey and Jean Baker set up camp Friday night, they were
joined by a hospitable Rottweiler, a reserva tion dog partial to
hikers. They named him Shadow.
</P>
<P>
   Shadow followed them along the trail Saturday as they met up
with their Phoenix and Milwaukee friends. The pooch was friendly
not only to the humans but also to Phoenix resident Jane Simeth's
17-pound terrier mix, Beechnut.
</P>
<P>
   That night, Shadow's barking broke the stillness. Baker
discovered moun tain lion tracks and scat the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   Along the 13.5-mile trail to Rainbow Bridge, the party met two
hikers, Kelly Williams and Jeri Ree of Flagstaff, and exchanged
brief pleas antries. They also met Bob Read, a solitary California
hiker who men tioned he had encountered a hiker with a sprained
ankle holed up in a camp several miles back.
</P>
<P>
   As night fell Sunday, the wind began to pick up. Vickrey's group
awoke to the sound of rain and the roar of a now-swollen creek and
a previously dry wash. At dawn, they heard snow falling.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures turned frigid. With bad weather threatening, the
group decided to skip breakfast, pack quickly and head back to the
trail head. Vickrey had forgotten her gloves and slipped woolen
socks over her hands.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix hiker Diane Hicks tucked Beechnut into her backpack,
fearful the tiny dog would be lost in the deepening snow.
</P>
<P>
   After an hour, they came to the tent where Sarah Newberry, a
young mother from Cottonwood, was nurs ing an ankle sprain after
stepping on a rock as she and companion Glen Wesselmann hiked in.
They said they were waiting for the weather to clear before they
tried to hike out and catch a boat on Lake Powell back to Page.
</P>
<P>
   They asked that a message be relayed to their baby-sitter in
Cottonwood.
</P>
<P>
   It would be more than seven hours before Vickrey's group could
comply. Slowly plodding through snow that had obscured trail
markers, they kept each other in sight, navigating by the few
markers they could see and forging ahead when they longed to rest
and eat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just had to keep moving,'' Vickrey said.
</P>
<P>
   Shadow never left their side.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave us comfort knowing he was there,'' Hicks said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the trip that had started so pleasantly for Williams
and Ree had also turned nasty. They, too, woke Monday morning to
heavily falling snow. Wearing trash bags on their feet to keep
their boots dry, they had split from their friends, Newberry and
Wesselmann, and tried to make it to Rainbow Bridge. At Redbird
Pass, they found them selves walking through water and were soon
soaked head to toe.
</P>
<P>
   They returned to Newberry's camp, where rest had soothed her
aching foot. The four decided to wait out the storm, which
forecasters had woefully underestimated as a light snowfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were optimistic,'' Ree said.
</P>
<P>
   Then the wind blew in. At 11 p.m., poles in the tent Williams
and Ree were sleeping under cracked, and the tent collapsed. They
scambled out and huddled with Newberry and Wesselmann, hoping their
small tent wouldn't likewise collapse.
</P>
<P>
   In their haste, they left articles of clothing outdoors,
including Wil liams's gloves. By dawn, the clothes were frozen.
</P>
<P>
   Through a seemingly endless night, the four lay awake and
listened to the wind howl. No one spoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wind was so intense. We were so scared,'' Williams said.
``We were all waiting for the poles to snap. You can't imagine the
wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Without shelter, the four would have faced exposure. But the
flimsy little tent held.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday morning was still cold and blowing with snow, but the
sky had cleared some. The four decided to hike out.
</P>
<P>
   Williams and Ree put on all the clothes they had, though
everything was still wet. Newberry set off, gingerly, but made it
less than a mile before her ankle gave out. It was clear she and
Wesselmann would need a helicopter rescue.
</P>
<P>
   The two Flagstaff women pushed on, practically crawling through
waist-deep snow _ cold, dehydrated and a little disoriented.
</P>
<P>
   Williams thought, ``This is how people die.''
</P>
<P>
   At noon, they turned back to camp, where they met Read. He
promised to reach the trail head and summon help. Wesselmann gave
him the keys to his truck.
</P>
<P>
   Four hungry and exhausted hikers shared what scant food they had
left _ some Clif Bars, dried beef and water _ and tried to keep up
their spirits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't let ourselves panic,'' Wesselmann said. ``We just
kept each other laughing.''
</P>
<P>
   Just before sunset, they heard a beautiful noise: Rotors.
Williams and Ree ran out into the snow, barefoot, and saw a
helicopter circling. Pitched in a protected site, their tent was
difficult to spot from the air.
</P>
<P>
   The chopper flew away.
</P>
<P>
   What the four didn't know was that Vickrey had been on the phone
from her home in Chandler all day facilitating their evacuation
with au thorities from two states, two coun ties, Navajo officials,
the National Park Service, a Page search and rescue group, an
emergency medical technician from Kayenta and Newberry's
baby-sitter in Cotton wood.
</P>
<P>
   All worked together to locate and airlift the hikers.
</P>
<P>
   Baker had been able to supply coordinates from her GPS, or
Global Positioning System, for the approxi mate location of the
downed hikers' camp. When Read narrowed the location, the
helicopter returned.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, Wesselmann wants to share his favorite part of
the harrow ing story. Last Christmas, his 6-year-old godson gave
him a bright orange vest, telling his dad that some day it might
help Wesselmann if he ever got stuck in the snow.
</P>
<P>
   Wesselmann used that vest to flag down the chopper.
</P>
<P>
   With a flight nurse on board, the helicopter took Williams and
Ree back to the trail head while Newberry bundled up. She and
Wesselmann were flown to the Page hospital. X-rays showed no breaks
to her ankle.
</P>
<P>
   That night, the couple bunked at Canyon Colors bed and breakfast
in Page, with their wallets and credit cards still with Read in
Wessel mann's truck. Reunited the next morning with Read, the truck
and their money, they tried to pay for a night's lodging. Canyon
Colors pro prietors Rich and Bev Jones would have none of it.
</P>
<P>
   The kind-hearted Joneses have an arrangement with the Page
hospital to take in stranded visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I have a room available, we're happy to do whatever we can
for folks,'' Bev Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Far from being discouraged by their perilous adventure, they all
insisted they're ready to take off again. Hicks is on a hike this
week.
</P>
<P>
   But Williams plans to stay away from Rainbow Bridge, no matter
how seductive its beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Only half joking, she said, ``Jeri and I are going to stick to
day hikes for a while.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
