r s BC-FBC-PALMER-LADN     03-28 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-PALMER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROJANS COUNTING ON PALMER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ He's rusty, rested and ready.
</P>
<P>
   But does the appearance of USC quarterback Carson Palmer at
spring practices really mean the Trojans' savior has returned?
</P>
<P>
   It does if you ask wide receiver Kareem Kelly, who spent just 2
games playing with Palmer before the star quarterback broke his
collarbone last September against Oregon, which effectively ended
his season.
</P>
<P>
   Without a second of hesitation, Kelly knows how many games the
6-6 Trojans would have won with a healthy Palmer: ``All of them.''
</P>
<P>
   This may sound like a giddy fan or blowhard booster, but it
clearly demonstrates the effect a player with Palmer's talent has
on his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Palmer is just trying to regain his touch and timing
this spring, Kelly sees endless possibilities after just a handful
of practices the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just adds so much more to the offense,'' Kelly said. ``It
is a totally different team. Mike (Van Raaphorst) was consistent,
but there's nothing like having your starting quarterback. This
year, I think we'll put it all together.''
</P>
<P>
   The usually laid-back Palmer is thrilled to be back, but careful
not to put too much emphasis on his return. He knows everyone
speculates that it is only a matter of time before he leaves for
the NFL, and insists he will stay at USC at least two more years.
</P>
<P>
   But these days, he just wants to become a normal, healthy
college quarterback again, comfortable doing the drills he has
practiced since junior high.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I feel clumsy at times with my footwork and sitting
in the pocket,'' Palmer said. ``And you have to get used to having
defensive linemen flying toward you.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer even shies away from saying the Trojans would have been
better with him last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have hoped we would win a few more games if I hadn't
gotten hurt, but there's no way to tell,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Palmer is certain that he is a different quarterback than
the one whose 1999 season abruptly ended when Oregon rover Michael
Fletcher tackled him near the sideline, shattering his collarbone.
</P>
<P>
   ``One second changed my life,'' Palmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer eventually redshirted and got the year of eligibility
back, but he is definitely not the same person. He is still
considered a sure-fire NFL prospect and one of the top players at
his position in the country. But his attitude has changed immensely
from that late September night when he was injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made me think I couldn't take football for granted,''
Palmer said. ``You really can't take anything for granted. I used
to come to practice and go through the motions. I don't do that
anymore. I look forward to practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy every rep, every snap that I get. Before I wouldn't go
as hard as I could. Now I try to be perfect every chance I get.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of being perfect is avoiding another injury. USC is working
on sliding drills for quarterbacks this spring, specifically to
avoid another mishap, when Palmer was hurt trying to gain a couple
meaningless yards two plays before halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quarterback is about leadership,'' USC coach Paul Hackett
said. ``And leadership means being healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett won't object to Palmer rolling out and running next
season, he just wants a little discretion about when his franchise
player heads downfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it means the Super Bowl ... OK,'' Hackett said. ``I can
remember in '85 that Joe Montana ran in from 5 yards out and scored
a touchdown. But you have to understand when to do it. If it means
the game, it's something else. But it's a maturing process.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer understands he can't play with as much reckless abandon,
if for no other reason, than to not be forced to watch any more USC
games on TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire time I was out I was itchy,'' Palmer said. ``The
hardest part was watching games, especially the losses.''
</P>
<P>
   It became so depressing, Palmer vowed to stop thinking about his
injury, realizing it was starting to dominate his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized that if I kept thinking about it, it would always
put me in a bad mood,'' Palmer said. ``I thought about it for
awhile, but it's time to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps in order to take some pressure off Palmer's return,
Hackett stressed that he could not use the quarterback's absence as
an excuse to explain USC's mediocre record last season. The Trojans
had other problems too, but Hackett conceded that USC was severely
impacted by Palmer's injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask (San Francisco coach) Steve Mariucci if the 49ers without
Steve Young were a different team, or ask the Rams if they would be
the same without Kurt Warner,'' Hackett said. ``It's the nature of
the position.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer's collarbone is completely healed, and while it might
take until summer camp for him to reclaim all of his sharpness, he
isn't worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing football is like riding a bike, you never really
forget,'' Palmer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
