<SLUG> BC-NY-WOMEN'S </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN'S HISTORY MUSEUM PROPOSED IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
 MUSEUM-ART-480-(TRIMS)-NYT  (hm) 
 By WINNIE HU   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ More than 150 years after the first convention on
women's rights in upstate New York, Gov. George E. Pataki has
proposed building one of the first museums in the country to be
devoted to women's history.
</P>
<P>
   The $125 million museum would be in Battery Park City near the
southern tip of Manhattan, joining several recent museum projects
like the Jewish Heritage Museum and the planned Skyscraper Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, a Republican, has provided $1 million in state money for
the project and promises to carve out more from this year's budget.
Advocates for the museum, who include a group of prominent civic
and business leaders, are planning to raise the rest from private
donations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly have outstanding elements of history here in New
York,'' Pataki said in a telephone interview. ``The next logical
step is to pull it all together in one site that is visible and
reachable by most people. I think we're going to see a great deal
of support for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said the idea originated with a one-year commission that
he appointed in 1998 to honor the achievements of women. Libby
Pataki, the governor's wife, headed the commission. Its 52 other
members included Beverly Sills, Billie Jean King and Roz Abrams,
the television anchor.
</P>
<P>
   Although the museum is still in the planning stage, it has been
laid out on paper by Ralph Appelbaum Associates, a design company
that has left its imprint on the newly renovated Hayden Planetarium
in Manhattan and the United States Holocaust Memorial Museum in
Washington. A drawing shows a 10-story building whose floors,
linked by ramps, overlook a multilevel visual display at the
museum's center.
</P>
<P>
   The new museum, known formally as the Museum of Women: The
Leadership Center, would differ from existing collections around
the state in that it would not focus on individuals, but would
offer a comprehensive view of women's contributions to American
history, said Lynn Rollins, former deputy director of the state's
Division for Women, who is leading the efforts for the new museum.
</P>
<P>
   Rollins said the exhibits would include photographs, artifacts
and interactive displays that help tell the story of women in
American history, from the pioneers and suffragists to recent
immigrants. ``We want every woman to walk through the museum and
feel like they're part of their history,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibits would not be limited to things of interest only to
New Yorkers, Rollins said, but would be planned in consultation
with a national advisory board of historians. The building would
also include conference rooms and an auditorium to provide training
classes in leadership and business skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much of the seminal history of women took place in New
York, and this is a tourist mecca,'' she said. ``This is an
opportunity to let people know what women in America have
achieved.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's aides said they had approached Mayor Rudolph W.
Giuliani and the Battery Park City Authority, a three-member state
board appointed by the governor, about the project. It would
require the approval of city and state officials and the authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like a good idea, and we look forward to reviewing
the plan,'' said Matthew Higgins, a spokesman for Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy S. Carey, president of the Battery Park City Authority,
said the arrangement would be similar to one that helped bring the
Museum of Jewish Heritage there in 1997. If approved, the women's
history museum would not have to pay rent or other fees on the
property for 20 years, Carey said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, a diverse coalition of advocacy groups,
scholars and politicians around the country has sought to promote
women's history. A 1997 campaign persuaded Congress to restore a
marble statue depicting three suffragists _ Susan B. Anthony,
Lucretia Mott and Elizabeth Cady Stanton _ to the Capitol Rotunda.
The statue, which was commissioned by the National Woman's Party in
1921, had been kept in a downstairs corridor.
</P>
<P>
   A former opera house in Dallas is being transformed with $25
million in public and private money into the Women's Museum: An
Institute for the Future, which is expected to open in September.
It will borrow artifacts from the Smithsonian and other museums to
chronicle women's history from the 1500's to the present.
</P>
<P>
   Plans are also under way for the National Museum of Women's
History in Washington. And a host of educational programs and
Internet sites have sprung up to inform women about their role in
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a need for women's history museums,'' said Galen
Sherwin, president of the New York City chapter of the National
Organization for Women, who supports the creation of another one in
Manhattan. ``The problem with the study of history is that its
focus is on politics and economics, areas that, up until recently,
mostly excluded women.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In New York, some of the earliest exhibits about women's history
can be found in Seneca Falls, a village halfway between Syracuse
and Rochester that was the hometown of Stanton, the suffragist. She
helped organize the first women's rights conference there in 1848,
drawing nearly 300 people and setting off the American women's
movement.
</P>
<P>
   Today, these historic events are commemorated there by the
Women's Rights National Historical Park, which is managed by the
federal government, and the National Women's Hall of Fame, a
private center that opened in 1969 to honor the achievements of
individuals from Stanton to Madeleine K. Albright.
</P>
<P>
   The Hall of Fame, which has inducted 157 women so far, has
rebounded in recent years after nearly closing in 1989 because of
financial troubles. Mary Ann Oppenheimer, the executive director,
said the center now takes in enough from ticket sales and donations
to cover its $350,000 annual operating budget. Attendance has
climbed steadily to 10,000 visitors last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much out there that could be told,'' said
Oppenheimer. ``It's a very interesting idea, and I think there are
lots of opportunities for organizations like ours to find ways to
work together and achieve our mission.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Cott, a professor of history and women's studies at Yale
University, said the new museum would give historians an
opportunity to reach a broader audience. Other scholars and
advocates said they would like to see exhibits on everything from
the changing image of femininity in the 1990's to the role that
women played in the Civil War.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
