<SLUG> BC-SCOTCH-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: NEW AD AGENCY USES HOMESPUN APPROACH IN PITCHING
WHISKEY
</HEADLINE>
   (hm) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT 
  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADISON, Wis. _ The name of an agency that opened here last
month epitomizes its approach to aiming advertising at savvy,
skeptical consumers: Hayseed House.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd joke when we were in New York that we were the
hayseeds,'' said Anders Carlson, one of three founders of the shop,
who collaborated on a campaign for J&AMP;B Scotch whisky on behalf of
J. Walter Thompson. ``It's a self-consciously ironic sort of
exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   For the last year, Carlson, 25, and his friend Rick Streed, 28,
have free-lanced for Thompson to produce irreverent print
advertisements for J&AMP;B based on posters they created as managers of
Badger Liquor, a short walk from the University of Wisconsin campus
in Madison. The success of the ads in test markets prompted them to
go into business for themselves, along with Michael Kramer, 30, who
had been brand manager for J&AMP;B in New York. J&AMP;B is their first
client.
</P>
<P>
   The bold, brightly colored posters, promoting weekly specials on
beer and liquor brands, sought to appeal to potential customers,
particularly men 21 to 25, with wry humor that mocked traditional
spirits ads and humble production values meant to underscore their
homemade origins.
</P>
<P>
   One poster, for instance, pitched Dempsey's Extra Stout, brewed
in Monroe, Wis., with handwritten comparisons between the state and
Ireland in categories like ``obsessions,'' ``drinking habits'' and
``differences between respective weddings and funerals.''
</P>
<P>
   A Thompson executive visiting Madison as part of research into
finding ways to reverse a decades-long plunge in J&AMP;B sales by
increasing its appeal to drinkers younger than retirement age saw
the posters _ and the appreciative crowds gathered to peer at them
through the store windows. He was impressed enough to buy a
disposable camera and take pictures to share with colleagues back
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``My radar was up to anything I thought was speaking to the
target in a voice that didn't feel like an advertiser talking to a
consumer,'' said the executive, Michael Hart, senior partner and
group creative director at the flagship New York office of
Thompson, part of the WPP Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``This business is changing so rapidly,'' he added. ``I will do
anything and everything to find a voice that's heard by this new
generation.'' At a meeting, Hart and other Thompson executives
presented several of their own ideas along with a campaign based on
the Badger posters. The client chose the Anders-Streed work, which
became the basis for the test campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scotch has gone through such a long-term decline that we knew
we needed to do something radically different,'' said Michael
Stoner, vice president and scotch product group director at
Schieffelin &AMP; Somerset in New York, a joint venture of Diageo,
which owns J&AMP;B, and LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ads still talked in `scotch language,' always relating the
country club rules,'' he added, referring to conventional elements
like brand heritage and drinking etiquette. ``Rick and Anders'
stuff looks so different, so fresh, and is so true to this
audience, the mid-20-something beer-drinking guy, that we
immediately embraced it.''
</P>
<P>
   When research showed that other liquor brands, like Captain
Morgan's rum and Jim Beam bourbon, had made inroads into that
market by encouraging mixing with cola, the print ads by Carlson
and Streed _ initially 10, now more than 10 times that _ were
focused on drinking J&AMP;B in such a manner, which would horrify
scotch purists.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are brands conquering this demographic,'' Kramer said,
``so we accepted that we had to break out of the scotch box.''
</P>
<P>
   ``J&AMP;B is a great old brand with a rich history,'' he added,
``but the concept Rick and Anders came up with is in the voice of
the consumer, like the responsible-drinking message that says,
`Drinking in moderation beats vomiting in excess.'''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign was initially tested in Colorado and Wisconsin,
appearing in publications like The Onion, a satirical weekly
newspaper to which Streed has contributed. Thompson copywriters are
creating radio commercials to accompany the print ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sales are up about 14 percent,'' Stoner said, ``which, for a
brand that has been declining for 22 years, is astonishing and
wonderful for us.'' The test has been expanded to San Diego and
Providence, R.I., he added, where it ``is going quite well.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't talk about what's going to happen,'' Stoner said,
``but it's very likely it'll be expanded.''
</P>
<P>
   About three months ago, Kramer recalled, he began discussing
with Carlson and Streed the possibility of opening an agency ``that
would be a problem solver, an independent creative voice.'' The
collaboration is made much easier by a sensibility the three share:
an appreciation of what Carlson describes approvingly as anything
``old school.''
</P>
<P>
   That can range from the work shirt worn by Kramer bearing a
Miller Lite logo and the style of play of the University of
Wisconsin basketball team to the Old Gold Filter Kings smoked by
Carlson and the Huber beer sold at Badger Liquor, a local brand
that comes in cartons still festooned with a character resembling a
brewmaster version of Peanut.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Carlson and Streed said they used some of the money they
earned from Thompson to repair the 1940's neon sign over the Badger
Liquor entrance, which reads ``Badger Liquor Shop Ice Cubes'' and
depicts a tilted bottle pouring drops of liquid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about how can we do something bigger,'' Streed said,
``creative work that would appeal to anyone as long as we keep it
honest.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he and Carlson are taking the advice of those
old-school comedians, Bob and Ray, by not quitting their day jobs.
Both still work at Badger Liquor and still make window posters.
</P>
<P>
   Carlson's most recent, peddling ``Carlo Rossi wine-esque wine,''
presents make-believe ``celebrity summer plans'' of stars like
Christina Aguilera, Tim Allen and Ricky Martin. The poster
resembles the Hayseed House ads for J&AMP;B but is somewhat different.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Kramer said, laughing, the font for the ad
headlines, developed by Carlson, was bought by Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   Carlson acknowledged that in a tone of voice half amused, half
amazed: ``They own my handwriting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
