<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-KENNEDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COLUMN GLADLY NEVER WRITTEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BUD KENNEDY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is the column I prayed I would never have to write.
</P>
<P>
   When I was 5, I saw a tornado swoop down from the clouds and
peel shingles from the roof of the Lena Pope children's home in
west Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   I know tornadoes can strike Fort Worth. I've seen it happen.
</P>
<P>
   I prayed I would never see another.
</P>
<P>
   I've met some survivors of the previous major tornado to strike
Fort Worth, a 1995 twister that tossed cars and demolished
apartment buildings near Texas Christian University in southwest
Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   That storm wasn't even the day's biggest headline. It came the
night of April 19, the night of the Oklahoma City bombing.
</P>
<P>
   That tornado left only survivors.
</P>
<P>
   This tornado, for the first time in recorded Fort Worth history,
brought death.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know how many people really bought into the American
Indian legend that a tornado would never strike where river forks
come together. But it was as good a way as any to explain Fort
Worth's 150 years of grace.
</P>
<P>
   In the past 50 years alone, Dallas County suffered 17 fatalities
in eight tornadoes, according to federal records kept by the
Vermont-based Tornado Project.
</P>
<P>
   That includes 10 deaths in this area's ``Big One'': the 1957
tornado that wiped out much of the Oak Cliff neighborhood southwest
of downtown Dallas and then danced along the Trinity River bottoms
past downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, the tornado did not turn along the river.
</P>
<P>
   It did not strike the Indians' 1840s campground across the river
north of downtown.
</P>
<P>
   It climbed the bluff and came through downtown.
</P>
<P>
   An 1875 tornado supposedly followed the same path west of
downtown, according to a 1981 Fort Worth history. But a newspaper
then reported that ``When the wind struck the high bluffs. ... It
was dissipated.''
</P>
<P>
   The bluff may have weakened this tornado from the force that
plowed up West Seventh Street and wiped out a half-block across the
west side.
</P>
<P>
   It kept enough strength to topple the Calvary Chapel tower and
break windows and topple walls across downtown.
</P>
<P>
   The 1995 tornado rated an F2 on the Fujita scale used to rank
the force of storms. The worst tornado to hit Tarrant County in the
past half-century, at least on the Fujita rating scale, was an F3
tornado that injured nine people May 4, 1960.
</P>
<P>
   That tornado struck the Casino Beach recreation area on Lake
Worth and cut across what was then rural northwest Tarrant County,
destroying homes and businesses on Jacksboro Highway and in Sansom
Park.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, we've been lucky. In our lifetimes, families and
entire neighborhoods have been wiped out by tornadoes in nearby
Wichita Falls, Waco, Lancaster, Lubbock, and recently, near Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Among American cities, we have been singularly spared for 150
years, says meteorologist Harold Brooks, a severe storms expert.
</P>
<P>
   Until last night.
</P>
<P>
   (Bud Kennedy is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Contact him at (817) 390-7538 or budk(at)star-telegram.com. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
